<HEADLINE>
PHILANTROPIC RED SOX GIVE AWAY LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Carl Everett may play at one speed, but he loses
at another, which accounts for the long, measured walk he made from
center field after Sunday's 6-5, 12-inning loss to the Philadelphia
Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Jordan's winning ground-rule double off reliever Rheal
Cormier long since had sailed over Everett's head and cleared the
fence on one carom off the Veterans Stadium carpet when the
outfielder finally made it to the visitor's dugout, with only
pigeons for company.
</P>
<P>
   He ate slowly, he showered slowly, he dressed slowly. And by the
time he finished writing out a check for the clubhouse attendant
and turned away from his cubicle, he was facing an
all-but-abandoned clubhouse. Lose five games in a row, as the Red
Sox have, including three straight here to a team whose record
suggests it's the worst in the National League, and no one is
inclined to stick around.
</P>
<P>
   Except for those charged with asking where it all went wrong.
They already had an inkling, of course. Try the eighth inning, when
Everett fell down on a line drive by Phillies rookie Pat Burrell,
who was credited with a double on the play and came around to score
the tying run on Desi Relaford's smash off the glove of second
baseman Jeff Frye.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be only one question you're waiting around to ask
me,'' said Everett. ``I just missed the ball. Game over.''
</P>
<P>
   The game, of course, had not yet lurched to its conclusion, 4
hours 3 minutes after it began. That wouldn't come until the 12th,
when Ron Gant led off by blooping a single off the end of his bat,
took second on a wild pitch by Cormier, and came across with the
winning run when Jordan launched his hit over Everett's head.
</P>
<P>
   But what had been a 5-0 Red Sox lead after their third at-bat,
one in which Everett climaxed a five-run uprising off Phillies ace
Curt Schilling with a three-run home run, his 19th of the season
and fifth in six games, disappeared with Everett face-down on the
rug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I froze on it,'' Everett said of Burrell's line drive,
neglecting to add that when he finally did react, he turned the
wrong way at first. ``My feet got tangled up, and I missed it. I
should have made that play.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lowe was on the mound when Everett took his tumble. He was
the third of five Sox pitchers on an afternoon in which the
Phillies used seven and held the Sox scoreless on three singles
over the last nine innings. Lowe retired the next two batters,
Everett's strong arm keeping Burrell on third after Mickey
Morandini's flyout, but he wound up with a blown save when Frye's
dive wasn't enough to come up cleanly with Relaford's smash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been crazy,'' said Lowe, who has blown just two saves in
12 chances. ``I was one pitch away from getting out of that inning,
but I threw a 1-and-2 curveball to Relaford that didn't do much. It
hung over the middle of the plate, he hits it, and they score a
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team in general, we're obviously struggling. A team funk.
We've just got to go out there and get one win, but obviously one
win has been hard to come by lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Lefthander Jeff Fassero thought he'd be claiming one, after the
Sox staked him to that five-run lead. Instead, the Sox, who blew an
8-2 lead to Kansas City on Wednesday, failed to protect another big
edge while losing for the 10th time in their last 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping to put an end to it today,'' Fassero said.
``We're not playing good baseball right now. It keeps going, and
we've got to get a win here somewhere. We've just got to get all
the bad stuff out of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero, who had given up just three home runs in his first 10
starts, gave up three in three innings Sunday. Gant and Mike
Lieberthal, who hit two home runs on Saturday, hit solo homers in
the third. Burrell, a player Phillies fans view with the same
expectations of greatness they once had for a young Mike Schmidt,
made it a 5-4 game with a two-run homer in the fifth, his first in
front of the home crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero didn't beat himself up over the homers by Gant and
Burrell. Both hit pitches that were down and away. ``National
League baseball,'' Fassero said. ``I don't think they try to pull
balls as much in this league. I can live with those pitches. They
try to pull, and I've got two ground balls to short. Give them
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberthal hit what Fassero called a ``get-it-over slider'' on a
3-and-2 count, not a good pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies were back in it. The Sox, who hit just .175 over
the weekend while losing twice in extra innings sandwiched around a
9-3 blowout, never got another runner to third base. Phillies
center fielder Doug Glanville ran down six line drives, and made a
difficult backhand catch of Brian Daubach's deep slice with Frye
aboard on a walk in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Sox' last three hits were pinch singles by Nomar
Garciaparra and Mike Stanley. Garciaparra, after playing seven
games in a row after coming off the DL, was given the day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't matter,'' Garciaparra said about sitting out. ``We
should have won, regardless.''
</P>
<P>
   So now it's on to Florida, and a three-night set with the
Marlins, another supposed NL bottom-feeder. The Phillies had been
swept five times this spring. They hadn't swept anyone until this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to win every game,'' Everett said. ``But they have a
team over there that can hit. A lot of people underestimate those
guys because of their record. But I played against them. Those guys
can hit. They're never out of a game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
