<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO PREVAIL, BRIGHTEST STARS MUST COME OUT 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Stars are old, and they're beginning to look it,
and in lieu of a plastic surgeon nipping here and tucking there,
Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock has little left in his makeover kit but
to hurry a hobbled Jamie Langenbrunner into the lineup Monday night
for Game 4 of the Stanley Cup Finals at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' said the affable Hitchcock, ``things change
significantly now.''
</P>
<P>
   The unstated qualifier there is that Hitchcock hopes things
change significantly now.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have his Stars on the run. Perhaps better stated, the
Devils have the defending Cup champs too often standing still and
looking to score from the outside. New Jersey moved to a 2-1 lead
in the best-of-seven series Saturday night with a 2-1 win because,
for the most part, too many of the Stars' big players looked like
they wanted to score with their reputations rather than their hard
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``For offensive chances,'' Hitchcock bluntly added, ``(the
Devils) make you pay a healthy price to get in those areas to
score. At the end of the day, you are going to have to decide
whether the Cup and the accolades that go with it (are) worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Late-night hockey fans might remember where Brett Hull was when
he scored the triple-overtime Cup winner against the Sabres last
spring. Buffalo fans still tiptoe through insomnia each night with
Hull's image flashing in a haunting red scroll across their bedroom
ceilings. One of the game's great snipers, known for his blistering
slappers, Hull knocked in the winner with one of his toes in the
crease. He sensed the moment, risked getting clobbered, and
delivered the biggest goal of his life with one of his smallest
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time for Hull and Cup brothers Joe Nieuwendyk and Mike
Modano to get reacquainted with the ugly, sometimes grotesque art
of the inside game. If they don't, they'll be headed outside
following Game 4. They now know for certain that they're not going
to will their way to a win.
</P>
<P>
   Going to the front of the net isn't any fun against the Devils,
but frankly, it's easier than fighting through the Stars' back
line. Devils defensemen Scott Stevens and Ken Daneyko like to
bounce bodies _ you might remember Stevens's smackdown on Eric
Lindros a little over a week ago _ but the likes of Richard
Matvichuk, Darryl Sydor, Derian Hatcher, and Dave Manson deliver
even more of a wallop.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Arnott snaked his way through on a defensive lapse to
score first for the Devils in Game 1, but for the most part, the
Stars don't allow much inside heat on goalie Eddie Belfour. The
Stars were able to gain the zone with offensive rushes, but too
often didn't land a shot on net, or muscled up some weak imitation
of a scoring chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have spent some good time in the offensive zone,'' said
Stars forward Scott Thornton, cousin of Bruin Joe Thornton. ``We
just really haven't created a lot of good scoring chances in front
of the net.''
</P>
<P>
   The key player to change that approach is Nieuwendyk, last
year's Conn Smythe winner as the postseason MVP. Modano and Hull
always will be considered skill players, able to change a game's
momentum with their crafty touch and clever shots. But the
33-year-old Nieuwendyk essentially is the fullback in the Stars'
attack, the guy who relies on creating havoc down low with his
speed and size, crashing and banging.
</P>
<P>
   The Modano-Hull-Jere Lehtinen combination often ignites the
Dallas offense, but a truly effective Stars attack has Nieuwendyk's
line (likely with Langenbrunner and Thornton Monday night)
continuing the first-line momentum and following up with good
scoring chances. For the first three games of this series, it just
hasn't been there. And for the record, the Stars didn't make any of
their big-name players, including Hull, Modano, and Nieuwendyk,
available Sunday to the media. It gave the appearance that they
were being shielded from the media's scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, meanwhile, deftly worked the room. He was asked how
he felt about suggestions in the press that his team is worn out.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Hitchcock, whose appearance and delivery make him a
modern-day Captain Kangaroo, ``(the local media) are probably tired
of covering us. They want to get on with the Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   A noted Civil War buff, Hitchcock was asked if he felt he was
now defending Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean, is it burning?'' he said with a chuckle. ``I prefer
to think we are on the march to Savannah.''
</P>
<P>
   Do they march? Do they run? Do they stand resolute? To think
that they could lose Monday night and still recover to win three
straight is virtually unimaginable. If the Stars have a last stand,
they have to make it Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The body becomes irrelevant,'' said Hitchcock, talking of the
sacrifice he now must see from his tired, aging bunch of champions.
``Our players know that feeling and we feel like we can go to that
(mind-set). It is an awful hard way to have to play. But there
isn't much time left in the season . . . this opposition is as
strong as anybody we have ever seen in our lives _ and we are going
to have to go there now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
