<HEADLINE>
STUCK ON STORIES OF RUBIN, DE LOS RIOS 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Rossana De Los Rios's wonderful ride melted away
drearily Sunday as she came unstuck in the grayness of a twilight
drizzle. Chanda Rubin wonders if she can find ``the glue'' to hold
her in the saddle and keep riding.
</P>
<P>
   A few more points would have done it for De Los Rios, the
racket-packin' mama who has seemed to materialize from some
mysterious kingdom (hello, Paraguay) as the unlikeliest of French
Open combatants. A few more points would have made a minimum
$40,000 difference for this young matron whose husband is out of
work, and whose cramping legs would not work in the closing minutes
of her gutsy bid for the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   She would have been only the second qualifier to go so far.
Instead, a strong 17-year-old Spaniard, Marta Marrero, gained that
honor by cutting through De Los Rios's serve in the concluding game
to win, 4-6, 6-0, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dream to be back here,'' said De Los Rios in Spanish.
Shrugging, she shook her head, wiggling the bleached ponytail that
stretches down her back. ``I tried everything to win. I broke her
in the next-to-last game, but I did not have enough. But I was back
here. I can still play. I will play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, the lone Paraguayan female tennis player ever
to appear on the international scene, De Los Rios won the French
junior title. ``Then I got tired of it. I married, had the child,
didn't play for five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, at 24, she chipped away the deep layoff rust,
polished the weaponry, and beat the bushes for enough computer
points to pry her way into the qualifying tourney. Then came seven
matches in 10 days. The last one was too much.
</P>
<P>
   Plugging away in a white dress and with the soulful face of a
madonna, De Los Rios fought every inch of the way, fending off the
inevitable with a sturdy forehand _ and, most of all, corrazon.
``Si,'' she said as she tapped her chest and smiled, ``Si.
Corrazon.'' Heart.
</P>
<P>
   While she played, her 3-year-old daughter, Anna Paola, armed
with an ample supply of lollipops, played with daddy in the damp,
chilly grandstand of Court 1. Sometimes Anna Paola watched working
mama at toil she did not understand. Baby, of course, would need
new pairs of shoes, and mama's $40,000 check would help for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   Another 24-year-old, Rubin, out of Carencro, La., also knows
what it's like to be away from the game, and worry that she never
would regain her touch. She is better known, and far more affluent
than De Los Rios, having won more than $2 million in her career to
De Los Rios's $145,000. Rubin made the semis of the Australian Open
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Low woman in the US triumvirate taking up space in the
quarterfinals, No. 25 Rubin beat Natasha Zvereva, 6-4, 7-5. That
was a follow-up on her elimination of No. 7 Nathalie Tauziat. Her
compatriots: No. 3 Monica Seles, 7-5, 6-3, over Amelie Mauresmo;
No. 4 Venus Williams, 7-6 (7-4), 6-2, over Anke Huber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Chanda's finding the glue,'' said her easygoing coach,
Benny Sims. Under his guidance for the last two years, she appears
to be divining the path back to the Top 10, where she resided (No.
6) for a while four years ago. ``What I mean by glue is structure,
discipline on big points, knowing how to construct the points. It's
what everybody else calls focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurrah, a word to replace tired, overworked ``focus.'' A welcome
contribution from Sims, who did a decade as teaching pro at the
Sportsmen's Tennis Club in Dorchester and Longwood Cricket Club in
Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chanda needs to have that glue all the time. She's coming
close, but she's also found out about fear. You see, here is a
woman who had been No. 1 in her age groups since she was 11, when I
first saw her in a kids tournament. She did nothing wrong. When I
saw her I was excited. Right away I phoned my friend, Arthur Ashe,
and said, `You won't believe it but I've seen a little black girl
from Louisiana who can do it all.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Arthur was very encouraging. He followed her career from afar.
So did Venus and Serena (Williams). They were kids watching her on
TV. When they moved up there were three blacks in the top 20. Never
happened before.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then the fear came in, Chanda's first injury. A sort of
loss of innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said, ``I was misdiagnosed as having tendinitis of my
right wrist. It was eventually found to be a broken bone in the
hand, a small stress fracture that required surgery. That removed
me from the Olympic team. When I thought I was recovered, I wasn't
hitting my forehand _ my best shot _ the same way. I was
frustrated, lost my confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   It got so bad that she went down to the bush league to try to
straighten herself out, get a few wins. She couldn't hit a ball
over the net. ``I was seeded No. 1 at Midland (Mich.), and lost in
the first round, 6-0, 6-3, to somebody I can't even remember
(Alexandra Olsza).
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   She was so pitiful that a local sportswriter accused her of
tanking the match.
</P>
<P>
   She got a break when she and her family, who had known Sims for
a long time, phoned for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been with me since Berlin in the spring of '98,'' Rubin
said. ``Benny's a walking encyclopedia. He knows everything about
the game. I've learned so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims said, ``I think I provide a comfort zone. I knew how she
had played and I think I've helped restore her concepts of the
game. She reminds me so much of Arthur, very placid and controlled
outwardly, but a fiery competitor within. You never forget the
fear, the worry that your game has gone. But you do learn to deal
with it. Glue helps.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' said Rubin, ``I've got the chance I've wanted. It's
been four years since I've gotten this far in a major, and I get to
play Martina Hingis. That's opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   De Los Rios found hers again in Paris. Even greater opportunity
beckons Rubin _ if she sticks to Hingis with the glue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
