<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BRISBY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRISBY HOPES IT'S CATCHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Time has passed quickly for Patriots wide
receiver Vincent Brisby, who is entering his eighth year in the
National Football League. He's ninth all-time on the team's
receptions list with 217 _ for 3,142 yards (a 14.5 average) _ and
he has 14 touchdown catches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy, I feel fortunate, and I look forward to doing
it again,'' said the 6-foot-3-inch, 193-pounder who had 18 catches
for 266 yards last season after being inactive four of the first
five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't seem like seven years, going on eight,
though,'' he said. ``I'm a tough competitor and I'll continue to do
the thing that got me here. It's still amazing, I could have had a
lot more catches with all the injuries I've had. Hopefully, my
number of catches will move higher in the next couple of seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Brisby, who earns approximately $2 million a year in a contract
that concludes after the 2001 season, wasn't happy with his playing
time last season. One of his best games came against Buffalo (4
catches for 45 yards).
</P>
<P>
   He also hopes the fact that he had no touchdown grabs last
season was an aberration. ``I don't think about it. Last year is
over as far as I'm concerned,'' he said. ``I'm just concerned about
this season.''
</P>
<P>
   So, with the team now coached by Bill Belichick, Brisby is
working as hard as he can, including at this week's minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get in the best shape of my career and trying to
help us win games,'' said Brisby, who attended Northeast Louisiana.
``We have a whole different coaching staff and the opportunities
are going to be a lot better for me this year. I'm going to try to
capitalize on them and get back to playing the way I can and
contribute at the level I should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Brisby likes what Belichick brings. ``He's a great guy; he's
definitely the type of coach we need around here,'' the receiver
said. ``He's a straight-up guy. There's no guesswork concerning
him; you pretty much know where you are. He gives you an
opportunity, telling you where you are, and he lets you go from
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The double sessions we're going through are always tough. He's
trying to get us better each day and I'm trying to separate myself
from the other guys out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brisby tries to catch every ball thrown to him, in games and
practices. ``I get upset anytime, even if I don't get open,'' he
said. ``Anytime something goes wrong with me doing something, I get
upset. I'm a competitor in all phases.''
</P>
<P>
   Concentration is the key, said Brisby.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just need to concentrate on it, by doing a lot of drills,
by catching a lot of balls, but the main thing is to watch the ball
come in and not look up,'' he said. ``You have to keep your eyes on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The salary cap is a factor for the Patriots, and Brisby's $2
million could solve some problems if he is jettisoned. But the
receiver doesn't think in those terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get ready to play, that's the only thing I can
do,'' he said. ``All the other stuff is going to take care of
itself. That's not what I'm here for.''
</P>
<P>
   Possibly being cut ``is just part of the game,'' he said. ``If
that's the problem, it's not in my control. The only thing I can do
is what I do on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Brisby has made it a point to attend most of the offseason
workouts. ``I've been here 95 percent of the time, just getting
ready and looking to be a vital part of the starting lineup and
playing very well on any given Sunday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brisby believes his nagging injuries haven't allowed him to be
more of a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say what I have to say when I have to,'' he said. ``My role
is more on the field, though. I've never really been a vocal guy.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as Brisby keeps catching passes, that will do the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
