<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS NOT YEST IN EXCELLENT POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ ``Look around, position by position,'' a pro
scout said early last week. ``Is there excellence at every
position? If there is, the team has a great chance of going deep
into the playoffs. If not, it's likely to be a mediocre year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' the scout added, ``there's always the St. Louis
Rams. At this time last year, if you went around their team you
wouldn't have seen too many areas of excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   Excellence is a subjective term.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who recently completed a mandatory minicamp, do
have excellence at some positions _ quarterback and linebacker _
and are good at some positions, such as wide receiver and defensive
back. But there are positions riddled with questions, mainly the
offensive and defensive lines, where games are won and lost.
</P>
<P>
   As new coach Bill Belichick often says in the days before
training camp, ``If we had to line up and play, we could.'' Those
aren't exactly reassuring words. And Belichick said Saturday it was
too early to tell whether his offensive line has made any progress.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is hard to tell whether Max Lane, Adrian Klemm, or
Grant Williams can replace Bruce Armstrong, who played very well
the first half of last season before his knee problems became a
factor. A strong left tackle is crucial to the health and
well-being of franchise quarterback Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots still have Lane and Todd Rucci (right guard), who
played in the Super Bowl, and a potential building block in Damien
Woody, who had a strong rookie season at center.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, there's Williams, who had problems handling the
rush in Seattle last year; guard-center Lance Scott, a free agent
from the New York Giants who is recovering from knee surgery;
Derrick Fletcher, a 6-foot-6-inch 350-pounder who is being tested
at left guard but is unproven; backup center/guard Jason Andersen;
and right tackle Ed Ellis, who must prove he's serious about
football after his NFL Europe debacle. There's also Greg
Robinson-Randall, a fourth-round pick out of Michigan State who may
become a factor as a tackle and push Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   The line is unsettled except for Woody and Rucci. Rucci could be
a salary cap dump, but that is unlikely. Lane could wind up at left
tackle or back at guard.
</P>
<P>
   Could it all come together? Certainly more far-fetched things
have happened. Could it also be uglier than last year, when the
team allowed 58 sacks? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Belichick is switching to a 3-4 alignment.
</P>
<P>
   Willie McGinest has played all over the field, from a
pass-rushing defensive end to a cover linebacker, and he will run
the gamut in Belichick's schemes.
</P>
<P>
   The linemen are Chad Eaton, Brandon Mitchell, Henry Thomas, Jeff
Marriott, Jon Harris, Dave Nugent, and Greg Spires.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is firmly entrenched in Belichick's doghouse for skipping
the voluntary portion of minicamp. As it turned out, Belichick had
only a two-day mandatory camp, canceling Sunday's activity because
of personal business.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas never has played Belichick's two-gap style and has said
he doesn't care for it. Eaton has been all business and has been
challenged by the coach to return to his form of two years ago. He
has gotten into tremendous shape.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, at 6-7, is a physical specimen who was slowed during
minicamp by a hamstring problem. A former No. 1 pick of the
Philadelphia Eagles out of Virginia, he never has lived up to that
promise. But he is a strong man who has refocused on conditioning
and this will be a make-or-break season.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have patiently waited for great things from
Mitchell, who likely will line up on the outside. So far, he's
shown flashes of brilliance, but has been more inconsistent than
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Spires always has had to prove his size (6-1, 260) does not hurt
his effectiveness in the NFL. For him to stick, he'll have to be an
exceptional pass rusher and improve in stopping the run.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick rarely answers a question directly, even one as simple
as whether he believes there are specific areas on the field he
thinks need improvement.
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious the lines are such places, and as the free agency
period continues, the Patriots may seek help.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there is no telling what type of a team Belichick
will have in September. But it appears there will be an exhaustive
search for ``excellence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
