<HEADLINE>
WRIGHT DOES NOT WRONG IN REVOLUTION DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ After four-plus years of searching for a
viable identity, the Revolution appear to be finally making
progress. The debut of Mauricio Wright during a 2-0 victory over
Miami Saturday displayed the possibilities of a team that could,
for the first time, have an effective blend of style and substance,
experience and youth.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution games will feature fighting spirit and hard tackles,
but also backheels and fantasy, a composed passing game, plus
athleticism and speed. The game should become less chaotic, appear
more effortless. And the Revolution should be versatile enough to
survive a kick-fest, which could occur as early as Saturday, when
they host San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the first half against Miami, Wright captured the
imagination of the 16,139 spectators at Foxboro Stadium with a
backheel pass to avoid the pressure of Brazilian striker Welton.
This was a rare feat for a Revolution player, especially a
defender, and it symbolized the team's renewed confidence.
</P>
<P>
   There were too many spaces in the Revolution defense in the
first half, and they will continue to appear while Wright and his
teammates become acquainted. But the Revolution seem capable of
compensating for their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wright isn't afraid to play the ball with his feet,''
goalkeeper Jeff Causey said. ``He's a playmaker on the back line,
plus he's another big guy (6 feet 2 inches), and that helps on set
pieces. He can hold the ball a little more, so we don't panic and
just boot it away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our confidence is high and we are on a roll. If we do go down
a goal we don't panic and hang our heads like last year. We know we
can get a goal back.''
</P>
<P>
   Said midfielder Ted Chronopoulos, who scored the first goal in
the 72d minute: ``Wright is not afraid to come out of the back with
the ball, so you have to be ready to cover for him. This game was
more fluid than in the past because we were playing through
Mauricio Ramos and Leonel Alvarez. You know (Ramos) is going to get
you the ball, it's a matter of finishing. If we put shots on net we
are going to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright made a symbiotic link with midfielders Alvarez and Ramos,
who play a similar style and are at the heart of coach Fernando
Clavijo's transformation of the Revolution. They will have to find
a way to differentiate between the two Mauricios, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wright adds another dimension,'' striker Wolde Harris said.
``We have been working on possession a lot in practice. You have to
be able to keep the ball or guys will be on you right away. The way
we want to play, guys have to be confident on the ball and have fun
with the game. And to play that way, you have to be confident of
the people behind you and not be worried they are going to cuss you
out or not cover for you if you make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Republic of Ireland team, which tied Mexico, 2-2, in Dallas
Sunday and will play against the US at Foxboro Stadium Tuesday, is
a young group. Fulham defender Terry Phelan and Sunderland striker
Niall Quinn are the only holdovers from the starting lineup that
played to a 1-1 tie with the US before a crowd of more than 51,000
June 9, 1991, at Foxboro Stadium. ``It is a team in transition with
some very good young players,'' said Aidan Cochran, a Football
Association of Ireland executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
