<HEADER>
A4532 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TONY-AWARDS-2TAKES-NY     06-05 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-AWARDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH TONY AWARDS FOR DIRECTING GO TO MICHAEL BLAKESMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a first for a director, Michael Blakemore won a
doubleheader on Sunday night, capturing Tony Awards as the best
director of both a play and a musical at the 54th annual ceremony
honoring the best of Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Blakemore won for the revival of Cole Porter's musical ``Kiss
Me, Kate'' and for Michael Frayn's play ``Copenhagen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago the British director was also nominated twice,
although he won neither for the musical ``City of Angels'' nor for
the play ``Lettice and Lovage'' that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is, `Thank you, America,''' Blakemore said on
Sunday night in one of his acceptance speeches during the awards at
Radio City Music Hall. ``And of course by America I mean New York,
and by New York I mean Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the triumph of Blakemore's two productions, ``Kiss Me,
Kate'' won the Tony for best musical revival and ``Copenhagen'' won
for best play. ``Copenhagen,'' which deals with nuclear physics,
was a striking venture for a Broadway increasingly known for
playing it safe with splashy musicals.
</P>
<P>
   Also significant was the choice of ``Contact'' as best musical
of the season, marking a dramatic shift in the definition of the
American musical. A dance show performed to recorded music with no
original score or live singing and little dialogue, ``Contact'' had
generated considerable controversy in the last few weeks over
whether it should qualify as a musical.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Goldstein, the executive director of the Theater
Development Fund, which runs TKTS and theater support programs,
resigned from the Tony nominating committee to protest the show's
eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   The musicians' union, Local 802, also objected on the grounds
that no music had been created for the production and no newly
created musical performance occurs in the production.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gersten, the executive producer of the Lincoln Center
Theater, which produced ``Contact,'' has dismissed such critics as
``forces of darkness.'' But in his acceptance speech on Sunday
night, Gersten simply paid tribute to the cast of ``Contact,''
calling the dancers ``the true acrobats of the gods.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Stroman won for best choreography for ``Contact.'' She
found herself competing against herself for best choreography and
best direction of a musical, since she did both for ``Contact'' and
for ``The Music Man.''
</P>
<P>
   In accepting the choreography award, she honored her husband,
the director Mike Ockrent, who died of cancer in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance has lifts and dips and unexpected turns, just as real
life does,'' she said. ``Had I not fallen in love with Mike
Ockrent, I could not have written `Contact.'''
</P>
<P>
   The cast of ``Contact'' also fared well at the awards. Boyd
Gaines, saying that ``the Tonys have been very good to me,''
accepted the third Tony Award of his career for his performance as
a depressed ad executive who finds redemption through dance.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ziemba, competing against fellow cast member Deborah
Yates, won for her portrayal of a repressed housewife in another
segment of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Stoppard's ``The Real Thing'' had a big night, beating out
``A Moon for the Misbegotten,'' ``The Price'' and ``Amadeus'' for
best revival. Among the producers on stage to accept the Tony was
Harvey Weinstein of Miramax Films; ``The Real Thing'' marked the
first time the movie company had helped back a Broadway show.
</P>
<P>
   A star of the play, Jennifer Ehle, won for best performance by a
leading actress in a play, beating out her mother, Rosemary Harris,
who was nominated for her performance in Noel Coward's ``Waiting in
the Wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehle's co-star, Stephen Dillane, also won the Tony, in a
competitive category that included Gabriel Byrne of ``Moon for the
Misbegotten,'' David Suchet of ``Amadeus'' and the two actors who
alternate roles in ``True West,'' Philip Seymour Hoffman and John
C. Reilly. The producers of ``True West'' unsuccessfully tried to
get the two actors in the Sam Shepard play to be considered jointly
so that they would not compete against each other or cancel each
other out.
</P>
<P>
   The award for best original score went to Elton John for
``Aida.'' The award was something of a consolation prize, given
that the Disney show was not nominated for best musical. In what
may have been a response to this slight, John did not attend the
awards ceremony. Nor did the lyricist, Tim Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Headley, the star of ``Aida,'' won the Tony for best
performance by a leading actress in a musical. In her speech,
Headley thanked Disney, which had previously chosen her to play
Nala in ``The Lion King.'' ``I love you so much,'' she said. ``And
I'll work for you for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aida,'' with its contemporary renditions of ancient Egypt,
also won for best scenic design (Bob Crowley) and for lighting
design (Natasha Katz).
</P>
<P>
   In presenting the award for best costume design, Dame Edna
Everage planted two big kisses on Martin Pakledinaz, who won for
``Kiss Me, Kate.'' Pakledinaz tried to keep a straight face _
despite its lipstick marks _ during his acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiss Me, Kate'' also won for orchestrations (Don Sebesky). And
Brian Stokes Mitchell won the Tony for his performance as the male
lead in the show.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For his performance as a curmudgeonly farmer father in the
revival of Eugene O'Neill's ``A Moon for the Misbegotten,'' Roy
Dotrice won the Tony for best performance by a featured actor in a
play.
</P>
<P>
   Blair Brown won for her performance in ``Copenhagen.'' Like the
director, Blakemore, Brown thanked the producers for their bravery
in producing a play with such complex subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dead'' won the award for best book of a musical for
Richard Nelson. The award was bittersweet given that the show _
unable to survive a drop in ticket sales _ has already closed on
Broadway, although it will be produced at the Ahmanson Theater in
Los Angeles in July and then tour the country.
</P>
<P>
   Among this year's presenters were Kelsey Grammer, Susan Lucci,
Kathie Lee Gifford, Jack Wagner and Carol Burnett, all television
stars who appeared on Broadway this season or are about to _
Grammer is to open in ``Macbeth'' on June 15.
</P>
<P>
   Al Pacino, Matthew Broderick and Bebe Neuwirth also presented
awards, as did Patrick Stewart, who is currently starring in ``The
Ride Down Mount Morgan'' by Arthur Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The Tony producers were clearly relieved to have Rosie O'Donnell
back as host _ along with the comedic talents of Nathan Lane as
``special guest star'' _given that ratings dropped without the
popular talk show host last year.
</P>
<P>
   This year's nominees, announced on May 8, were selected by a
24-member committee. The 705 Tony voters, comprising theater
professionals and journalists, cast ballots in 21 categories.
</P>
<P>
   The Tonys are presented by the American Theater Wing, which
founded the Tonys in 1947 and runs theater education programs, and
the League of American Theaters and Producers, which represents
Broadway producers.
</P>
<P>
   The first hour of the ceremony, broadcast on PBS, included a
special Tony Award for regional theater, a grant of $25,000, which
went to the nonprofit Utah Shakespearean Festival of Cedar City.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining two hours of the presentation were shown on CBS
and featured the presentation of 12 awards.
</P>
<P>
   A special Tony Award for lifetime achievement in the theater was
given to the producer T. Edward Hambleton, founder of the Phoenix
Theater. Another special award was given to ``Dame Edna: The Royal
Tour,'' Barry Humphries's one-man/one-woman show at the Booth
Theater. After greeting the crowd with her trademark ``Hello,
Possums'' in presenting the award for best costume design, Dame
Edna said, ``I'm the only Broadway show to be closing
voluntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Tony honors for excellence in the theater were
given to the actress Eileen Heckart, who has been nominated for two
Tony Awards in the past and recently starred in ``The Waverly
Gallery'' Off Broadway; Sylvia Herscher, a theatrical agent and
manager; and ``Encores!,'' the seven-year-old series at City
Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
