<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ BURIES NEMESIS, DELIVERS CRUCIAL MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After winning Game 3 of what will rank as one of
the more memorable Western Conference finals, Los Angeles Lakers
coach Phil Jackson declared that with another loss the Portland
Trail Blazers would ``be at death's door.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that Jackson, along with a lot of us media hacks, was
wrong. But his forecast did bring attention to the concept of
death's door _ a place that was visited by both sides Sunday in
Game 7 at Staples Center so often that the NBA could have begun a
frequent-flier program.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half, the Lakers were mostly dead.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the third, the Blazers died.
</P>
<P>
   In the same period, it was the Lakers who had a big coronary.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the fourth quarter, the Blazers gave up the death
rattle _ one of the more spectacular, untimely and grievous swoons
in recent sports history.
</P>
<P>
   Squandering a 15-point fourth-quarter lead, they became the
Frail Blazers, and the Lakers came from apparently sincere deadness
to the Western championship.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA Finals against Indiana won't begin until Wednesday,
which is good because after the improbable 89-84 result, it will
take a while to digest just how the Lakers are in it and the
Blazers are not.
</P>
<P>
   For seven of the final eight quarters of this stirring series,
the Blazers confounded the Lakers at every turn. They won Game 6
Friday in Portland by smothering the game's most valuable player,
Shaquille O'Neal, and Sunday were winning Game 7 in the same
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   They wiped out the Lakers' crowd with an 18-2 run in a
third-quarter burst of brilliant, balanced offense, just as they
had Friday in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Then without warning, the Blazers turned leaden as the Northwest
winter sky. Rasheed Wallace missed six shots in a row. Scottie
Pippen disappeared. Arvydas Sabonis fouled out.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if they realized they were wiping out the best team in
the NBA on national TV, and suddenly grew dizzy from the height.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have gotten better shots,'' said an aggrieved
Portland coach, Mike Dunleavy. ``Maybe they wore us down. Maybe we
were tired down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Tired? The team with the deepest bench in the league? The team
with everyone mostly healthy? The team that had already done the
heavy lifting, coming back from a 1-3 deficit to force this
decider?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, they were tired. Tempting as it is to attribute
everything to a pressure-induced choke (and there was some of
that), they were as tired as were the Lilliputians from strapping
down Gulliver.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Neal, making eye contact with Kobe Bryant driving the
lane inside the final minute, took his lob almost at the top of the
backboard and thrust it through the shivering iron, the
difference-maker delivered the explanation on the slim difference
between the Lakers and Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   As former Huskies and Cougars coach Marv Harshman used to say,
when everyone else is tired in the fourth quarter, the big fella is
still seven feet.
</P>
<P>
   And this particular big fella, thwarted though he was for the
last two games, had a passion lit in him. If it still burns in this
next fortnight, the Pacers might want to consult their insurance
brokers about paid-up premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, former Lakers great and part-owner Magic
Johnson was holding forth for a group of reporters. He works out
occasionally with O'Neal and was describing things the center would
tell only another man of his playing stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he wants it,'' Johnson said. ``He wants it bad. He
wants that loser label off his back.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, as Michael Jordan before him, was often derided as a
great scorer who couldn't deliver a championship. Despite his
immensity and skills, he had brought his team to the Finals only
once before, in 1994, when the Orlando Magic was swept by Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In four years in L.A., his teams never came close. The loser
label was starting to become as permanent as his Superman tattoo.
</P>
<P>
   The brand was fairly glowing in the fourth quarter until the
Lakers clamped down on the withering Blazers and started finding
ways to beat the irritating double-teams.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a shooter, reserve Brian Shaw, stepped up to take some
pressure off by hitting three treys in the final 16 minutes. The
Blazers' strategy to slough off at power forward and shooting guard
and onto O'Neal was coming apart.
</P>
<P>
   During a timeout as the gap closed and the frenzy built, Jackson
exhorted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil said, `We've come too far to blow it. Let's fight, let's
claw, let's hit shots.' I said I'm going to kick it out so make me
look good,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   After his epic dunk for an 85-79 lead, O'Neal ran down the court
almost childlike, eyes wide and index fingers thrust toward the
vibrating masses.
</P>
<P>
   He hadn't yet won his ring, but he had won a game nearly as
large as him, in a fashion almost as stupendous.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had beaten a splendid nemesis in a way almost
inexplicable.
</P>
<P>
   Inexplicable, except for him.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 0032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
