<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4544 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-TRAILBLAZERS-LAKE     06-05 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TRAILBLAZERS-LAKERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS SAVE THEIR BEST FOR LAST TO ELIMINATE TRAIL BLAZERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)  By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant were moments from
suffering the most devastating playoff loss of their careers, a
defeat so agonizing for the young stars that it would take only a
National Basketball Association title to live it down.
</P>
<P>
   But something miraculous happened at the Staples Center on
Sunday night, something neither their fed-up legions nor the
Portland Trail Blazers expected.
</P>
<P>
   In the crucible of the Western Conference finals, they grew up
and played like champions.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, Bryant and the Los Angeles Lakers came back from a
16-point deficit and beat the Blazers, 89-84, before nearly 19,000
people in yellow T-shirts who watched in stunned disbelief as the
final buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   The end came so suddenly for Portland, which did not score a
basket during a 7-minute-30-second stretch in the fourth quarter
and failed to become the seventh team in league history to rebound
from a 3-1 series deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you live for,'' said Bryant, whose 25 points, 11
rebounds, 7 assists and 4 blocked shots led the Lakers. ``These are
the backyard-type of situations you dream about when you're young.
Two minutes to go. Game on the line. Tie score.''
</P>
<P>
   With O'Neal unable to get free inside for most of the evening,
Bryant had the defining game of his career. With the game tied at
79-79, Bryant made two free throws with 1 minute 34 seconds left
and then sank a 16-footer from the left wing with 1:09 remaining to
push the lead to 4.
</P>
<P>
   After Rasheed Wallace missed two free throws with 1:25 left,
Bryant drove the middle of the lane and at the last possible second
lofted an alley-oop pass for his 7-foot-1-inch, 330-pound teammate.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who scored 9 of his 18 points in the final period,
caught the ball with his right hand, cocked it back and dunked it
maliciously _ a basket that made the score 85-79 with 41.3 seconds
left and turned the arena into a state of extended delirium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like Shaq dropped out of the roof when he threw that
down,'' said Rick Fox, the Laker forward. ``Just devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   That dunk officially sent the Lakers into the NBA finals, where
they will play host to Indiana in Game 1 on Wednesday. But how
close they came to vacationing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brian Shaw made it possible. The reserve guard hit two pivotal
3-pointers during 15-0 run in the quarter, including one from the
left wing with 4:02 remaining that severely damaged Portland's
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   That shot tied the game at 75-75 and sent the building into a
tizzy. Shaw, traded by the Blazers to Houston as a minor piece in
the deal for Scottie Pippen last summer, was picked up by the
Lakers after the Rockets released him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ironic, huh?'' he said in the post-game locker room, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   He had some inspiration. O'Neal pulled some of his teammates
aside after Coach Phil Jackson spoke to the team between the third
and fourth quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `We've come too far to let this thing just end
like this,''' he said. ``I said: `Let's fight, let's scratch, let's
claw and let's play. Let's play.' That was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. He also mentioned that the Blazers were not going
to let him shoot, so he was going to have to rely on his teammates
more by distributing the ball to open shooters when he was double-
and triple-teamed near the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Brian Shaw looked at me and said, `Yeah, just like
Orlando.' When he said, `Just like Orlando,' I knew his shot was
going to be on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers trailed by 75-59, mostly because Wallace, who led the
Blazers with 30 points, and Steve Smith could not miss from the
perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal picked up his third foul with 6:18 left in the second
quarter, swinging his elbows as he tried to create space for
himself around Arvydas Sabonis. Rather than frustrate him, though,
it made him focus and play more effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant played 48 minutes on a sprained right foot in Game 6 on
Friday. If he was sore, the Lakers were hurting worse. Struggling
badly, the Lakers needed Bryant to be superhuman. He was not, but
his 12 points, defense (3 blocks) and rebounding (6) were enough to
keep the Lakers in the game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the pressure was on any one player, it was on O'Neal to
deliver in only the second Game 7 he has ever played.
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson, who directed the Lakers to their last title in
1988 and now serves as a team vice president and part owner, sensed
the feeling building. ``He needs this so people don't look at him
as a loser,'' Johnson said. ``This is his time. Everyone knows
it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal came late to that realization. He finally dived for a
loose ball with less than nine minutes left in the third quarter,
tumbling into the second row as the Superman theme was played over
the public-address system.
</P>
<P>
   Among his litany of self-proclaimed nicknames _ the Big
Aristotle being the most recent _ O'Neal earlier this season called
himself Shaq Kent. But there are no phone booths inside the Staples
Center. Only fallible human beings who play basketball for a
living. And against a remarkably resilient team from Portland, they
were just enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how,'' Bryant said, ``but we just found a way to
wear them down. It's kind of wild to think we won this game, isn't
it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
