<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S DEFENSE DOES IT ALL IN 6-4 WIN OVER PADRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If you didn't see it, don't worry, you will. This one
will run on TV more often than Andy Griffith reruns.
</P>
<P>
   In a game loaded with fielding gems, right fielder Stan Javier
made a catch so astounding Sunday that it not only helped the
Mariners hold onto a 6-4 victory over the San Diego Padres, the
replays could account for 20 percent of ESPN's summer programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be on the highlights for about a year and a
half,'' said left fielder Rickey Henderson, who added he doesn't
remember seeing a catch like it in his 22 big-league seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be played (over and over), and I think it
should be,'' catcher Tom Lampkin said. ``Our defense made so many
big plays today. The catch that Mike Cameron made, the play that
Rickey Henderson made ...''
</P>
<P>
   Hold on, we'll get to those soon enough. First, Javier's catch.
Just in case it isn't being replayed on TV this very minute, here's
what happened.
</P>
<P>
   With Seattle leading 5-1 in the seventh inning, two out and a
runner on base, San Diego's Phil Nevin slammed a pitch off reliever
Arthur Rhodes that had two-run homer written on it in flashing
neon.
</P>
<P>
   Javier raced back to the warning track, leaped and reached his
glove over the fence. The ball appeared to strike the glove's
pocket about an arm-length beyond the fence but Javier couldn't
hold onto it. Yet when he pulled the glove back, he also flipped
the ball back onto the field side of the fence. As Javier fell to
the ground, he looked up, saw the ball dropping toward him, reached
out his glove and became the leading candidate for Catch of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
   No, they don't practice this before games.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I got lucky,'' Javier said. ``I can't explain it
or anything. It was just a lucky catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but as Branch Rickey said, luck is the residue of
design.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has to be in the top five catches for me,'' said winning
pitcher Paul Abbott, who allowed one run in 51/3 innings. ``He went
back and took a home run away, and then he had the presence of mind
to look for the ball and catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everytime you take a home run away from anyone, you have to
smile,'' said Javier, who had a grin on his face when he saw the
ball in his glove. ``When you make a play like that, instead of
5-3, it's still 5-1.''
</P>
<P>
   Javier's catch was the second in a trifecta from Seattle
outfielders. You Know Who may be in Cincinnati, but the Mariners
outfielders still cover more Seattle real estate than a January
rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson made a fine running catch in left field in the first
inning and Cameron robbed Tony Gwynn of extra bases with a crucial
fence-rattling catch in center during a three-run San Diego rally
in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something you take pride in,'' Cameron said. ``Every
year, I keep saying I'll win a gold glove this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as (Gwynn) hit it, I thought I had a pretty good bead
on it. I just wanted to hold onto it, I was going full tilt. That
was a very big hit I took away from Tony Gwynn.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was just the outfield. John Olerud, Alex Rodriguez and
Jose Paniaqua turned a nifty bases-loaded 3-6-1 double play that
saved another run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good plays, bad plays, mediocre plays, they're all
contagious,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got guys who can catch the ball,'' Abbott said. ``Good
defense wins game. That, and throwing strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego did neither.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle had only five hits but squeezed out six runs thanks to
seven walks and San Diego left fielder Al Martin's error in the
third inning. Martin dropped Lampkin's two-out fly ball, allowing
two runs to score and extend Seattle's lead to five runs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the game got interesting at the end _ ``A little
exciting,'' manager Lou Piniella said _ when San Diego scored three
runs off Frankie Rodriguez and Kazu Sasaki.
</P>
<P>
   And it could have been worse. Sasaki allowed a home run to
Martin, the first batter he faced, Gwynn's flyout to Cameron, and
then walked the next two batters before striking out Bret Boone to
end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Accurately estimating the runs saved by Seattle's defense and
the runs allowed by San Diego's would be a bit like calculating the
city's annual caffeine consumption, but it's safe to say the
Mariners would have lost the game had it not been for their gloves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a game we won with our defense,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
