<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-DRAFT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON'S POWER ATTRACTS ATTENTION FROM SCOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It started with a call from interested scouts and pro
coaches: How would you, Tripper Johnson, like to work out in Safeco
Field?
</P>
<P>
   Two homers (one account says they were ``mammoth'') to left and
a dozen or so shots to all fields with Lou Piniella looking on and
suddenly the Newport High School (Bellevue) senior was on his way
to the biggest jump up the list for Monday's major league amateur
baseball draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they like that I can hit and that I play hard,'' said
the unassuming 6-foot-2, 190-pound third baseman. ``Those are the
two main reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the growing legend around Johnson, who started
the season with a homer in Yakima that broke the window of a Ford
Bronco and ended it with an inside-the-park romp against Issaquah.
</P>
<P>
   At 18, Johnson now is considered by Baseball America as one of
the top three high school power hitters this year. Team One
Baseball, part of the Rivals.com network, said Johnson ``looks to
be a sure thing to be the first prospect taken out of the region''
and is one of the ``most improved prospects in the country,
especially over the past two months.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's projected to be Washington's only potential
first-round pick, with a 54 score (out of a 20-80 scale) as the
highest-ranked state player by the Major League Scouting Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Other Northwest players received early attention, especially
outfielder Skyler Fulton of Capital High in Olympia, and
left-handed pitcher Fraser Dizard of Meadowdale in Lynnwood.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson quietly put together an impressive senior season for
the Knights, hitting .519 with nine homers, 37 RBIs, 14 doubles and
42 runs scored in 24 games. He also stole 16 bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the year that I thought he would have,'' said Newport
coach Brian Fischer. ``Scouts at first didn't get a chance to look
at him all that much. But when they started to come to every game,
they realized how good an athlete he really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Already committed to play baseball at the University of
Washington, Johnson is taking the draft in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything is going to fall into place. I feel
right,'' he said. ``Even if I don't want to sign, the time will
come. Whether I go to college or sign, it will work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson believes the Huskies' incoming recruiting class is
top-notch and he has a great respect for UW hitting coach Joe Ross.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the program has really improved over the last five
years and that's why I really wanted to go there,'' he said. ``If I
feel uncomfortable signing, then I'll just go to college.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's also long dreamed of playing pro baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a standout football player, began playing baseball in
Little League mostly because his father signed him up to play. His
devotion to the game was all his own from then on.
</P>
<P>
   ``From there, once he got me started, it was pretty much my
decision what I wanted to do,'' he said. ``I've been with it ever
since.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Fischer, Johnson has hit well since he joined the
Newport program as a freshman. The Dodgers' Todd Hollandsworth also
played at Newport, but Fischer said Johnson is as good or better at
this stage in his baseball development.
</P>
<P>
   ``His best asset has been that he can hit, and that's what's
gotten him up into the real high rounds. But he has of the other
stuff: His defense, his running speed and his sheer athletic
ability,'' Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   To work on his pro potential, Johnson has been using a wood bat
in batting practice all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably what made him a better hitter,'' Fischer said.
``He certainly deserves it and he's worked at it over the last four
years. It's just now paying off for him.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's full name is Nelson Johnson III, hence the nickname
``Tripper,'' which derives from being the third Nelson in the
family. It started out as ``Triple.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, he's also had the triple-treat baseball experience of
his life, visiting not only Safeco Field but Dodger Stadium and
Coors Field in workouts for scouts and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   But those two shots into the 390-foot left field power alley at
Safeco were Johnson's way of saying that he's ready for bigger
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I'll always remember because there aren't many
kids who get a chance to hit in Safeco,'' he said when asked about
the homers. ``I was just lucky to get a phone call and invited
down. ... Yeah, I got two out.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Angelo Bruscas can be reached at 206-448-8010
</P>
<P>
   or angelobruscas &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
