<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4549 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     06-05 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR MARINERS TO FASHION A HOT STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A wrist-twisting, home-run-robbing, once-in-a-lifetime
catch by Stan Javier spiced things up at the ballyard Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   So did Mike Cameron's face-busting, up-against-the-wall steal of
a Tony Gwynn double.
</P>
<P>
   The late-inning defensive jewels by the right and center
fielders to preserve a 6-4 Mariners victory over San Diego were
welcome occurrences in this murky netherworld called
``interleague'' that the M's, Padres and all of baseball are
wallowing in.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that the tedious sound of the word
``interleague'' has doomed baseball's 4-year-old novelty act to
such a state of listlessness?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, which is why someone better order the Mets or the Reds
to come to Safeco Field before we have to see the Padres again.
Baseball is allegedly at work on this stagnant aspect of its
entertainment product.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, in the absence of meaningful games against
other .500 AL West opponents or more entertaining rivals such as
the Yankees, Red Sox or the fellas from Cleveland, the M's got busy
attempting to give the home crowd something to cheer about.
</P>
<P>
   The big highlight came in the top of the seventh when Javier
jumped up and deflected San Diego third baseman Phil Nevin's
almost-a-homer just as it arced over the right-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   Then, falling backward to the warning track, Javier reached out
and caught the ball as it tumbled back into the not-so-comfy
confines of Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling in the dirt, Javier held on, saving two runs and ending
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Even for a franchise that spent 11 years being treated to
spectacular, wall-climbing, pull-back homer rob jobs, this one was
for the video archives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' Javier said. ``But to be honest, I just got
lucky. It was a lucky catch. It was our day. We made some good
defensive plays.''
</P>
<P>
   This is nothing new for the 2000 Mariners. In fact, with the
second-best fielding percentage in the American League, the
Mariners have unearthed more than their fair share of leathery gems
so far this season.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, even Rickey Henderson tracked down a long fly ball off the
bat of Gwynn Sunday, giving the Mariners outfield a nice little
trifecta of effort and execution.
</P>
<P>
   What has not happened for the M's, however, is a hot streak _ a
topic that seems to be catching a little fire lately. With May now
having rolled definitely into a so-far toasty June, it is time for
the M's to consider ways of heating up.
</P>
<P>
   Javier, like everyone, has hardly failed to notice that the AL
West lead continues to bob and weave among its four parity-minded
contestants.
</P>
<P>
   No team has been able to establish itself as the clear leader,
although the idea had been that the division was the M's to
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always look at the (standings) so you see what's going on.
We've just got to get hot. We need to get a streak going,'' Javier
said.
</P>
<P>
   With today's game against the Rockies, another mushy and largely
uninspiring interleague spot in the schedule, the Mariners will
have completed one-third of the season.
</P>
<P>
   They have endured the absence of No. 1 starter Jamie Moyer until
his return last Friday and they will continue to wait on Freddy
Garcia, who is on schedule to be back in about a month.
</P>
<P>
   But with Paul Abbott stepping into a starter's spot, John Halama
racing to a 6-1 start and Aaron Sele delivering workmanlike starts,
the M's have not been pinched as badly as one might have suspected.
</P>
<P>
   As for the bullpen, the M's have even endured the road disasters
by closer Kazuhiro Sasaki and the continuing bewildering inability
of Jose Mesa to use the breaking ball.
</P>
<P>
   No, just when the M's look as if they are dodging bullets and
taking advantage of the versatility this revamped roster gives
them, something else goes out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   These days, what seems to be most effectively dampening the
Mariners' ability to get on a roll is the lack of rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Edgar Martinez was a one-man wrecking crew for the
Mariners in May, with a .441 batting average, 10 homers and 32
RBIs. But the promise of small-ball hit-and-runs, rallies and
manufacturing offense has failed to flourish.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 51 innings, it has been noted that the Mariners have
failed to get more than three hits in any one inning. The other
day, despite coaxing 11 walks, the Mariners still lost, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   The M's are stranding more people than the S.S. Minnow.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, defense was again the bright spot. Javier and Cameron
embraced in center field after Cameron's outstanding catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you make a good defensive play it is the most
satisfying,'' Javier said. ``He and I didn't get a hit (Sunday) but
we were glad to help out in other ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the defense has been a sight to behold on many occasions
during the first third of this season. Now it's time for a little
something extra.
</P>
<P>
   Does a six-game winning streak sound good? How about 8 of 10?
Or, heaven forbid, why not just go for 10 in a row?
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
