<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4550 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-TRAILBLAZERS-NYT &LR;      06-05 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TRAILBLAZERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAIL BLAZERS FOLLOW PLAN TO THE BITTER END 
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Until the waning moments, the Portland Trail
Blazers never wavered from their plan. Intent on stopping Shaquille
O'Neal from the start of the Western Conference finals, the Trail
Blazers again stymied the National Basketball Association's most
valuable player at every important juncture of Game 7 on Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Until the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal scored 9 of his 18 points in the final period, lifting
his team into the NBA finals against the Indiana Pacers as the
Lakers defeated the Trail Blazers, 89-84, at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers had built a 13-point lead at the beginning of
the fourth quarter, and sent O'Neal and the Lakers in search of a
dramatic rally, which came as Portland went scoreless for almost
six minutes of the quarter. That allowed the Lakers to tie the
score at 75-75.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, it appeared Portland's plan would work. On
offense, the Trail Blazers spread the court and lured O'Neal away
from the basket.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy gave Rasheed Wallace more room to work in the lane
and he delivered 10 points in the third quarter. Steve Smith kept
the Lakers confused from the outside and hit 4 of 5 shots for 10
points in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, the Trail Blazers banged and flew at O'Neal from all
angles. As they fought to maintain their lead, the threat of
intentionally fouling O'Neal _Portland Coach Mike Dunleavy's
hack-a-Shaq philosophy from Game 1 _ loomed prominently.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's what it comes down to, that's what we'll do,''
Dunleavy said before Game 7. ``We're not going to change something
like that at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Portland tying the series at 3-3 on Friday, guard
Bonzi Wells said there was no secret to what the Trail Blazers
wanted to do against O'Neal and the Lakers' other star, Kobe
Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of different guys and matchups we can throw at
them,'' Wells said. ``We've got to key on two of their guys. With
us, they've got to try and stop five guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle in the middle became a bump-and-grind ballet as the
Trail Blazers tried to put O'Neal in foul trouble. They succeeded
to some extent, as O'Neal was whistled for his third foul with 6
minutes 18 seconds left in the second quarter and the Lakers
trailing by 35-25. At that point, he had yet to make a field goal
and was spending more time making passes to teammates than looking
for ways to crash the basket.
</P>
<P>
   That third foul seemed to awaken O'Neal like a slap in the face.
He muscled inside for two quick baskets and finished the first half
with 9 points on 2-of-4 shooting and 5-of-8 free-throw shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Lakers star center had three fouls. O'Neal was also
coming off two games in which he was not much of a force in the
second half, especially the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal totaled only three shots in the fourth quarter of the
Lakers' losses in Games 5 and 6. When his team needed him most was
when the Trail Blazers' defense against him was best.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fourth quarter, when we're behind, we start to rush
ourselves and take quick jump shots,'' Derek Fisher said before
Game 7. ``We need to realize that we still have time to go to Shaq.
It's our responsibility to give him the opportunity to be the
bigger factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Trail Blazers led by 23-16 through the first
quarter, they fell behind early in the war of attrition against
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   He took only two shots, missing both, and made 2 of 4 free
throws, but whoever tried to guard him set off a chorus of
whistles.
</P>
<P>
   Arvydas Sabonis, who later fouled out, was called for two fouls
and went to the bench with 3:37 to play in the quarter. Brian Grant
fared worse, picking up two fouls in one minute and being replaced
by Jermaine O'Neal with 2:37 left.
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine O'Neal earned his second foul with 9:15 left in the
second quarter. Still, the Trail Blazers persisted with their
strategy of attacking O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out fast and physical, a style that kept the Lakers off
balance in Portland's victories in Games 5 and 6, also helped with
the defense of O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't anticipate a fast start,'' said Trail Blazers Coach
Mike Dunleavy. ``Like the other games, we know it's going to be 48
minutes. All year long, we haven't had anything handed to us.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
