<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4552 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKESIDE3-PIPPEN-     06-05 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKESIDE3-PIPPEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPPEN PARALYZED IN FOURTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the race for the seventh ring reaches the
homestretch, Phil Jackson moves ahead of Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt Pippen wanted to prove he could win an NBA
championship without Michael Jordan or the man who coached him in
Chicago. He still might one day, but not before Jackson (and former
teammate Ron Harper) get first crack at the title.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Pippen played Sunday's Game 7 with intensity, likely
motivated by what was at stake. Still playing with two bad fingers,
he took charges in the paint, grabbed a team-high 10 rebounds,
assisted in triple-teaming Shaquille O'Neal and encouraged from the
bench when he wasn't on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   When he made a 3-pointer near the Lakers bench with 18 seconds
remaining in the third period, he glared at Jackson as if he were
Reggie Miller mocking Spike Lee.
</P>
<P>
   But he also disappeared in the fourth quarter, along with the
rest of his teammates. When no one could buy a basket for 7
minutes, Pippen was no different (he didn't attempt a shot and
committed a turnover).
</P>
<P>
   When he fouled out with 25.4 seconds to play, Pippen finished 3
for 10 from the field (2 of 6 from 3-point land) and scored 10
points, five below his series average.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to swallow, and it will be all summer,'' he
somberly said. ``I know that as just one of the players on the
team, we are very disappointed. I realized that we sort of made
cowards of ourselves in the fourth quarter. We played like we were
fatigued, and they gained momentum that they needed to pull this
game out.''
</P>
<P>
   So that leaves one piece of unfinished business: the
Pippen-Jackson feud. Is it over? Are they friends again now that
their Western Conference Final series has been decided?
</P>
<P>
   The NBC cameras wanted to capture the moment but didn't get the
chance. As Pippen slowly walked off the court, stopping to hug
Harper and other Lakers, Jackson was seen walking into the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen never got a chance to talk to Jackson, at least not where
anyone could witness it. Jackson didn't address the issue in his
postgame media session.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen and Harper talked plenty, however. They often guarded
each other, always trying to one-up the other.
</P>
<P>
   Then came their postgame embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pip is real class,'' Harper said. ``First thing I said to him
was that he had great games. Man, he was carrying his team. He did
everything he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, 'I'll see you in the off-season.' I got love for him,
and he's got love for me. I'm sad to see him go, but I'm happy to
see him go.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, while saying less, was complimentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wished him good luck and told him to go win a
championship,'' Pippen said. ``We tried to test them and push them
to the limit, and they responded. Let's see if they can be crowned
champions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
