<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-NBA-WEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS WIN THE WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Whether the Los Angeles Lakers are adept enough to
win the NBA championship this season still is of intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   Those wondering about their maturity level, however, need only
look at the accelerated course taken Sunday in Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles took the more experienced Portland Trail Blazers to
school down the stretch of the Western Conference finals and won
Game 7, 89-84, to advance to the NBA Finals for the first time
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   For the Lakers, the culmination of a hard-fought, best-of-seven
series basically took on the equivalence of going from kindergarten
to college in a day. The same youth and raw talent that contributed
to a 15-point deficit early in the fourth quarter are what
propelled an astonishing comeback.
</P>
<P>
   It took a 31-13 run in the fourth quarter for the Lakers to
graduate to a date with the East champion Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until this point, this has been the ultimate test,'' Lakers
guard Kobe Bryant said after scoring a team-high 25 points. ``They
pushed us to the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles beat Portland, 4-3, to avoid becoming the seventh
team in NBA history to blow a 3-1 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers never conceded anything in this series until that
decisive final frame.
</P>
<P>
   Portland led 75-60 when the Lakers used a 15-0 run the tie the
score with 3:56 left. While the Lakers grew more and more energized
with every possession, the Blazers grew weary.
</P>
<P>
   Their shots either fell short or rattled out of the rim.
Portland was allowed just one attempt each trip down during the
stretch. The result was 13 consecutive misses that fed the Lakers'
frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Tied 79-79, Bryant made two free throws to put the Lakers in
front for good. After another Bryant basket put the Lakers ahead,
83-79, he threw a lob pass to Shaquille O'Neal for a dunk that
punctuated the rally.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's basket over Rasheed Wallace's outstretched arm put the
Lakers ahead by six points with 41 seconds left in the game. Los
Angeles put on a free throw clinic in the final minute to preserve
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers missed 15 of 21 shots in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically what happened is they beat us,'' Portland coach Mike
Dunleavy said. ``They beat us. Maybe our legs. Maybe we were a
little tired. We had some wide open looks that we didn't make. But
they made some big shots with a hand in their face. They're an
excellent team. They deserve all the credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland had won two consecutive games at Staples to extend the
series. In a way, the Lakers were determined not to be embarrassed
at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew my teammates were going to step up for me,'' said
O'Neal, who was held to 18 points and nine rebounds. ``I kept
telling them that this is do-or-die. Let's just forget about
everything, play hard and win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Blazers forward Scottie Pippen said his team showed heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't bring that (fourth) quarter back,'' Pippen said. ``We
knew we didn't complete this game. We lost this (series) in one
quarter. But we have a lot more to be proud of than to be down
about. This series could have been over a week ago if we had
believed everything that was said about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland nearly reversed Lakers coach Phil Jackson's comment
after Game 3 when he said the Blazers were at ``death's door.'' But
just as they did to even the series, the Blazers put up a steel
door with their defense to control the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very interesting game,'' Jackson said. ``I've never
seen one quite like that before. ... My condolences to Portland and
also my congratulations on a great season, and a very well-fought
series.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers led 71-58 heading into the final frame after a
pivotal and powerful third quarter that figured to complete the
Lakers' collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy inserted a taller Bonzi Wells for 5-foot-10 Damon
Stoudamire. The move put Pippen at point guard with Arvydas
Sabonis, Rasheed Wallace and Steve Smith on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   That group, much like it did in Game 6 at Portland, dominated
the Lakers. With 6:22 left in the third, the Blazers used an 18-2
run to seize a 68-53 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   During that stretch, Smith scored seven consecutive points with
shots off the dribble. Wallace's monster dunk capped the offensive
onslaught. Meanwhile, the Lakers' offense shifted into neutral with
little movement and poor shot selection.
</P>
<P>
   Containing O'Neal allowed the Blazers to manufacture a pair of
10-point leads in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we played as hard as we could play,'' Wallace said.
``We can walk around with our heads up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, though, walk on with the conference crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what Game 7 is all about,'' Lakers guard Glen Rice
said. ``You go out there and leave it all on the line and the
better team won. We were the better team today.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
