r a BC-CENSUS-AZR &LR;      06-05 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTER MIGRANT CENSUS
 WANTED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY PETER ORTIZ 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Sitting at the end of a narrow dirt path that snakes
more than a mile along a Queen Creek grape field is the migrant
camp that Domingo Martinez calls home.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away, the sweet scent of oranges permeates the air
as Jose Gamboa-Ayon crouches beneath a tree in the middle of the
grove where he both works and sleeps.
</P>
<P>
   These men mirror the faces of a vital but often invisible
workforce that fuels Arizona's $6.3-billion agricul tural economy.
Their lives are often hidden in the massive citrus groves and
fields where they toil, and they too often go uncounted in the U.S.
census.
</P>
<P>
   Farm workers are responsible for helping to make Arizona second
only to California in turning out lettuce, cauliflower, broccoli,
cantaloupes and lemons, yet no one knows how many live here.
</P>
<P>
   And counting them thoroughly is critical to their long-term
well-being.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is how much of the $182 billion in federal funds will
go toward health, education and hous ing services in communities
where farm workers have been under counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a decadelong process,'' said Ken Evans, president of the
Arizona Farm Bureau Federation, which rep resents 9,000 farmers.
``What they miss right now will hurt us for the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona officials estimate that about 65,000 seasonal and
migrant farm workers live in the state, while the 1990 census gave
a count of 30,387.
</P>
<P>
   Gamboa-Ayon is among those who are easy to miss.
</P>
<P>
   His weathered face speaks of his 30 years working the field. The
59-year-old farm worker has a trailer, but spends much of his time
deep in a Queen Creek citrus grove, where he sleeps on two
mattresses propped on milk crates beneath a tree.
</P>
<P>
   A few feet from his bed, Gamboa-A yon has a metal shelf where he
stores condiments and cooking utensils. He uses cilantro and green
onions from a garden he planted to prepare meals over an open
flame.
</P>
<P>
   Gamboa-Ayon said more farm work ers live in the grove, which has
empty jugs of water and blankets scattered about.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials acknowledge that migrant and seasonal farm
workers were not properly represented during the last count a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Interagency Farm Workers Coalition was created in
1995 to make sure that doesn't happen this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to serve the farm worker, we need to know how
many we have and where they are,'' said Maria Chavez, who heads the
coali tion of 60 advocacy and government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition compiled a list of places where farm workers live
or congregate, and then turned them over to local census offices.
Those offices then sought out local resi dents to be census takers
in their communities.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials also hired a major advertising firm and spent
$167 million to help communities promote the census through radio,
television and print media.
</P>
<P>
   Census workers will have until Aug. 9 to finish their count.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from a faulty census is a serious concern with
Arizona's De partment of Economic Security, which turns to census
data to help plan for farm worker job opportuni ties.
</P>
<P>
   And in Queen Creek, a faulty census count has hurt farm workers
who get limited medical care from a local clinic. Local farm worker
agencies that apply for federal grants often use census numbers in
trying to show the need in their community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The census is our most important national data source, what
every body turns to first,'' said Alice Larson, a social welfare
researcher in Washington state. ``You can't advo cate funds unless
you know how many people you are talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Illene J. Jacobs, who was appointed to the 2000 Census Advisory
Com mittee in 1995, hopes that this year's effort can fix the
problems of 1990. She directs the California Rural Legal Assistance
program, which found a 40 percent undercount of the farm worker
population in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that not only were they missing farm workers, but the
profile of the farm worker population was skewed,'' Jacobs said.
``The farm workers that were enumerated tended to be higher income,
and better educated than many of the migrant and seasonal farm
workers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1997-98 farm worker survey by the U.S. Department
of Labor, the average farm worker is a single, 31-year-old man. A
majority, 77 percent, were born in Mexico, and 60 percent lived
below the poverty line, with a median income of $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, 38, like many farm work ers in Arizona, still has
family in Mexico that he gets to visit two or three months out of
the year. He spends most of the year in Arizona and plans his life
around the harvest ing schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no choice,'' said Jesse Aguilar, a farm laborer
contractor who hired Martinez and 500 other farm workers throughout
the year. ``The crop won't wait for us.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5 a.m., Martinez slings a canvas bag around his chest and
works his way up and down a 14-foot orange tree with the help of a
ladder. He speedily picks off the oranges, stop ping every four
minutes to empty his bag into a huge bin.
</P>
<P>
   It will take 16 trips before he fills an entire bin and earns
$17. By the end of his workday at 1 p.m. he will fill five to six
bins. He'll send home $200 to $300 a week to a wife and four
children, keeping the rest for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had heard about the census effort on television and
thought it was a good idea, but has yet to meet a census taker.
</P>
<P>
   Many farm workers like Martinez have only a post office box and
won't receive a form by mail because they don't have a permanent
address or they live in another household.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez understands the fear that some farm workers have about
their census forms being turned over to immigration officials. But
census commercials convinced him of the need for an accurate count.
</P>
<P>
   Aguilar supports the census effort and said his farm workers are
aware of the campaign. But he is concerned that Martinez and many
of his men are being missed. He said he and other contractors he
knows were never contacted by census officials. He hopes to see
census takers during the summer, when he expects 1,500 to 2,000
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Silva saw how the last census had hurt her Queen Creek
commu nity from the farm workers who sought help at a local health
clinic. Silva is project coordinator with the Family Resource
Center, which serves migrant and seasonal farm worker families in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transportation, for one, is not here,'' Silva said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
