<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ'S FINGERPRINTS ALL OVER THIS COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You're the uniformed agent at the gate of the NBA
Finals, entrusted with rubber-stamping the Lakers' entry papers
Sunday after they unapologetically pushed ahead of Scottie Pippen
and the rest of the Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal is the first to get validated. His fingerprints
were all over the late surge that moved the Lakers to the front of
the line via an 89-84 victory over Portland in the series-deciding
Game 7 of the Wes tern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-foot-1 center had a resplendent season, earning league MVP
honors for the first time in his eight-year NBA career. His
scoring, rebounding and shot-blocking numbers, however gaudy,
wouldn't have meant anything if he hadn't steered the Lakers into
position to win a championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   For 36 minutes Sunday, O'Neal was lending credence to his
critics who questioned whether or not he had the iron will to go
with his muscles of s teel. He had 24 touches in the first half and
two measly baskets to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal picked up his third foul before he had put up his third
shot and had nine points after 36 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In the same situation last year, O'Neal would have dissolved
like an antacid tablet dropped into water. This time, with the
Lakers down by 13 points with 12 minutes remaining and the pressure
approaching the ear-popp ing point, he was so poised he gave his
primary defender, Aryvdas Saboni s, heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal made all four shots he tried in the fourth and final
quarter and was so aggressive Sabonis fouled out of the game trying
to thwart him. H e also was 3-for-4 from the free-throw line, no
insignificant statistic given that O'Neal's foul shooting had been
so shaky for most of the regu lar season he was benched in the
final seconds of a home game against P ortland in January so he
wouldn't wind up at the foul line with the ball and the game in his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   That indignity seemed but a distant memory when O'Neal stepped
up to the free-throw line with 2:44 remaining and swooshed two
throws to draw the Lakers even with the Trail Blazers, at 77-77.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, O'Neal's final basket came on a resounding dunk on a
feed fro m Kobe Bryant with 41.9 seconds left. It was an
exclamation point for O' Neal, who finished with 18 points, five
assists, one blocked shot and no more knocks against him.
</P>
<P>
   You give O'Neal your stamp of approval and signal to the next
player in line.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant bounds up to your booth.
</P>
<P>
   Time was when Bryant never would have fallen in line behind
O'Neal, much less have his back. Last year the Lakers' two most
prominent players jockeyed for marquee billing and ended up
bringing down the whole producti on.
</P>
<P>
   This year they melded their games and their goals so they were
complemen tary, not contradictory. Bryant contributed a team-high
25 points and co llected 11 defensive rebounds. Without his hard
work and extra effort un der Portland's basket, the Lakers would
have been hopelessly out of posi tion to mount a furious
fourth-quarter comeback.
</P>
<P>
   In another era, this month would have found the 21-year-old
Bryant colle cting a college diploma. He no longer has to justify
his decision to lea p straight from high school to the pros.
</P>
<P>
   You give Bryant a stamp of approval and signal to the next in
line.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant you are face-to-face with the team's first-year
coach Phil Jackson. Lured out of retirement by the challenge of
turning the Lakers into something more precious than their
individual parts, Jackson succe eded where a lot of people believed
he was doomed to fail.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of leading O'Neal, Bryant and Co. to the NBA
Finals, he p roved his care and feeding of hulking, hungry egos
was, in retrospect, n o small contribution to the Chicago Bulls'
six NBA championships.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's bearing buttressed his troops in the anxious hours
between the Lakers' ugly 10-point loss to Portland in Game 6 and
the start of Game 7. He oozed confidence and that's the scent that
engulfed the senses of people who visited the Lakers' practice on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It overrided any whiff of fear.
</P>
<P>
   You gladly give Jackson your stamp of approval and send him on
his way.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Shaw is the next to greet you. The Lakers signed Shaw, 36,
to give them a warm body when Bryant was sidelined at the beginning
of the year with a wrist injury.
</P>
<P>
   If Bryant doesn't get hurt, Shaw isn't a Laker. It's that
simple.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Shaw survived his shaky status to see all the hours he
spent la st summer at the UCLA gym working on his shooting stroke
pay huge divide nds. He made three 3-pointers in the final 12:04 to
bring the Lakers back from the brink of extinction.
</P>
<P>
   You give Shaw your stamp of approval and wave up the next player
in line .
</P>
<P>
   It is point guard Ron Harper, who most everybody but Jackson
considered too old and decrepit to lead the Lakers' offense.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that he is a 35-year-old warrior with the knees of
someone 73 , Harper emerged as the team's designated superego. It
was his job to re ign in all the ids.
</P>
<P>
   And sure enough, Harper was seen whispering into Bryant's ear
more than once Sunday, same as he has done all season, telling him
to play smart ball, not street ball.
</P>
<P>
   Harper took six shots and four of them went in. He also dished
out six a ssists, including one to O'Neal with a little over two
minutes to play t hat produced the basket that gave the Lakers
their first lead (at 79-77) since the middle of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   You wink at the player Bryant affectionately calls ``Old Head''
and give him your stamp of approval.
</P>
<P>
   One after the other you give your stamp of approval to forward
Rick Fox, who settled for less money to play for an NBA title
contender. And Glen Rice, who subjugated his own ego and much of
his offense for a chance a t a championship ring. And Robert Horry,
whose shot wasn't falling but w hose defense never faltered.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, all that remains is Los Angeles. The city that ushered
in the new year with a whimper rang out the Western Conference
finals with a bang. You give your stamp of approval to 18,997 fans
who made the Staples C enter a den of din and smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
