<HEADER>
A4556 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE2-BLAZER     06-05 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE2-BLAZERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS LEFT TO WONDER WHAT WENT WRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bonzi Wells didn't need to speak in order to
communicate the feelings of disappointment, despair and downright
disgust that filled the Portland locker room Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Wells slumbered out of the showers, covered his face with both
hands as he reached his cubicle and eventually began rubbing the
top of his stubbled head, likely trying to conjure up some answers
to the million-dollar question: How could this happen?
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have all summer to think about it,'' Portland forward
Brian Grant said minutes after the Trail Blazers had their season
end in agony with a Game 7 loss to the Lakers in the Western
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers, one solid quarter away from their first trip
to the NBA Finals since 1992, can now take solace only in their
strong regular season and the fact that they pushed the Lakers to
the edge of elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the team, I'm proud of everybody, but we just
came up a little short,'' said guard Steve Smith, who scored 18
points. ``We felt that we played better minutes than they did in
the series, but the minutes that we didn't play (well), they took
advantage of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Players denied that visions of the NBA Finals entered their
minds, even when Portland took a 15-point lead early in the fourth
quarter. But hosting Indiana in Game 1 couldn't, and shouldn't,
have been too far from the Trail Blazers' minds.
</P>
<P>
   This was a team built to win a Game 7, a team whose players
averaged more than 40 playoff games per man and a team led by a
player, Scottie Pippen, who was acquired in large part to provide
playoff leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers put themselves in position to achieve their
goal after battling back from a 3-1 series deficit, but that only
made Sunday's loss more difficult to accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think they would be able to score 31 points against
us (in the fourth quarter),'' Greg Anthony said. ``Our guys played
hard, and we made the plays we wanted to offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we didn't give it our all, because we did. We
had our opportunities, and that's what makes it even more
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Portland players were just as quick to praise the
Lakers, particularly Shaquille O'Neal and Brian Shaw, for their
clutch fourth-quarter efforts, but stopped short of declaring the
Lakers the favorites against the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Indiana has) one of the deadliest shooters to play in the
NBA, Reggie Miller, and they've got a big man in Rik (Smits), so it
ought to be a good (series),'' forward Rasheed Wallace said. ``I'll
watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   As time expired, Pippen and Lakers guard Ron Harper, former
teammates with the Chicago Bulls, embraced following an
often-contentious series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wished him good luck and told him to go win a
championship,'' Pippen said. ``We tried to push them to the limit
and they responded. Now we'll see if they will be champions.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen and the rest of the Trail Blazers will take the summer to
contemplate what might have been had they not missed 13 consecutive
shots in the fourth quarter, and wonder how many of the same faces
will return next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it to semifinals, why wouldn't we be back?'' said
Smith, alluding to rumors in Portland that the team might be broken
up. ``We still want to win a championship together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
