defying the order of another Alabama judge that he remove the Ten
Commandments from the wall behind his bench and stop opening court
sessions with a prayer. Today, proudly unrepentant, Moore of the
Circuit Court in Gallant is trading on his renown to run for chief
justice of the Alabama Supreme Court, the top judicial post in the
state. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-MONEY-ADS (Washington) _ Two and a half months ago, flush
with victory in the primaries and eager to be seen as taking the
high road, Vice President Al Gore sent an e-mail message to Gov.
George W. Bush, proposing a ban on ``issue ads'' paid for with
unregulated soft money. Bush, who raised a staggering $70 million
in his primary campaign, dismissed the challenge as a ploy. But
now, with the Democrats dropping hints that they may soon begin a
television advertising campaign on behalf of Gore, Republicans are
eager to hoist the vice president on his own petard. Asserting that
Mr. Gore's message amounted to a solemn promise not to use soft
money, the Republicans are trying to paint Gore as a hypocrite even
before the Democrats' first commercial hits the airwaves. By Peter
Marks.
