<HEADER>
A4559 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN--HERSKOWITZ-HNS &LR;      06-05 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--HERSKOWITZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Bat Day only a hit for fans, White Sox
<TEXT>
<P>
   By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Easy like Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The first three hits were home runs, two by Chicago, and each
leading off an inning. The Astros' last base knock of the day
occurred in the fourth inning, a two-run dinger by Daryle Ward, as
White Sox pitchers retired 16 of the last 18 batters they faced,
eight on strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   So the Astros' offense retired early and the club went on to
lose the rubber game of this interleague series 7-3, and we are
trying to think of how many ways to describe how poorly the home
team played.
</P>
<P>
   In a goodwill gesture entirely unrelated to the outcome of the
game, the Astros gave away 3,000 Louisville Sluggers to kids
wearing their youth league uniforms. As luck would have it, the
varsity kept for itself the bats that had only five hits in them.
</P>
<P>
   The souvenirs were not miniatures, but full-sized bats, the kind
that come in handy if you're making a movie about the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   You reflect that every day is Bat Day at Enron Field, or so it
seems, with the visiting club usually taking the honors. Sunday's
game was tied until Octavio Dotel actually delivered his first
pitch, which Ray ``Bull'' Durham pounced on and drove over the wall
in left-center.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were behind to stay as lefty Mike Sirotka, a Houston
resident and LSU graduate, handcuffed them most of this dull,
one-sided day. Chris Singleton led off the second inning with a
rocket shot into the seats in right-center to give the Sox a 2-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the inning, Richard Hidalgo appeared to
surprise himself by hitting a ball with less than his best rip, but
his high fly kept going until it cleared the fence in left-center,
his 18th homer of the season. The ball traveled 355 feet, and
Hidalgo was laughing out loud when he took his seat in the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Some would argue home runs are not just cheap at Enron.
Sometimes, like butterflies, they are free.
</P>
<P>
   The Pale Hose, as they are known in the mercantile world, put
away the game with a three-run burst in the third on four straight
hits, collecting two of them on Paul Konerko's double. Konerko
started in place of the menacing Frank Thomas, a move that must
have made Houston hearts leap like a fawn before the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Konerko broke out of a 1-for-26 slump with three hits,
including two doubles, as Dotel wobbled all day, leaving with two
out in the fifth and all seven runs charged to his account. The
loss was the fourth in five decisions for the young Dominican.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker has a policy, applauded by many, of
letting his starters try to work their way out of a bad situation.
The policy worked swell in the spacious Astrodome, but at Enron the
pitchers seem to create bad situations so they can make the best of
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had mounted their last threat in the bottom of the
fourth, when Ward connected with Lance Berkman on base for the runs
that cut the score to 5-3. The inning would have been bigger if
Hidalgo had not been thrown out at third base trying to stretch a
hit into the left-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't get out of the box well,'' Dierker said. ``That
happens to a lot of hitters here. He didn't think the ball was hit
well, and all of a sudden it's off the wall. You start trying to
turn it on, and take that extra base.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Astros were unable to put together two solid
games in a row, failing to tie their longest winning streak of the
season. You can criticize the pitching, the hitting and the
baserunning, but the defense wasn't flawless either. Tony Eusebio
dropped a throw at the plate, allowing Konerko to score in a
two-run fifth inning. The bobble wasted a perfect throw from
Berkman.
</P>
<P>
   In the category of
shutting-the-barn-door-after-the-cow-has-fled, four Astros relief
pitchers threw shutout ball the rest of the day, with Doug Henry
striking out five in two innings and working out of a bases-loaded,
one-out jam in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros can't sink much lower. They are already last in their
division and competing for the worst record in all of baseball. The
White Sox pounded them for 13 hits, including two homers and four
doubles. Durham's first-pitch homer was an omen of the total misery
that loomed ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Sirotka pitched seven strong innings, and the Astros won't win
often when Craig Biggio, Jeff Bagwell and Ken Caminiti are a
combined 0-for-10. Caminiti expressed his frustration by getting
the thumb in the eighth, after being called out on strikes.
</P>
<P>
   His temper provided the first excitement in two hours for
another sellout crowd of 41,117. The fans are still adjusting to
the park, too, cheering every ball hit in the air, including
infield pops, figuring the ball has a chance to go out.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
