<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4560 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKESIDE4-BANKSHO     06-05 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKESIDE4-BANKSHOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK SHOT LEADS TO BLAZERS' TANK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Control started slipping away ever so innocently,
but when it went, it went quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst was Brian Shaw's desperation 3-pointer at the end
of the third quarter that missed so badly it banked in, cutting
Portland's 16- point lead to 13 heading into the fourth quarter of
the Lakers' 89-84 victory in Game 7 of the Western Conference
finals Sunday at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's fortunate clank did more than breathe life into the
Lakers, it staggered the Blazers. All of a sudden they looked tired
and confused. Their confident play up to that point became
tentative, unsure.
</P>
<P>
   Shots that were falling earlier bounced off the rim into the
hands of the Lakers. Calls that went Portland's way started going
to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers looked vulnerable, and L.A. sensed it.
</P>
<P>
   So did Portland, which missed 13 straight shots during one
stretch of the fourth to relinquish momentum, the game and the
series to the very appreciative Lakers, who responded with a 21-4
run to take a 79-77 lead with 2:12 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   After climbing out of a three-games-to-one hole and taking a
16-point lead on the road in Game 7, the Blazers handed it all back
to the Lakers in one miserable quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With it went their chance to play for the NBA championship and,
perhaps, a little bit of pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we sort of made cowards of ourselves in the fourth
quarter,'' Scottie Pippen said. ``We played like we were fatigued,
and they gained the momentum they needed to pull this game out.''
</P>
<P>
   How it happened is open to debate, although the Lakers' defense
was an obvious factor.
</P>
<P>
   Portland was shooting 46 percent from the field through three
quarters, then got harassed into 21.7-percent shooting (5 of 23) in
the final period to allow L.A. to swipe away control.
</P>
<P>
   The misses became contagious, spreading from one player to the
next. The Blazers not only misfired with hands in their faces but
also easy, open looks in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came down to the fourth quarter, and we just did not make
shots,'' Portland coach Mike Dunleavey said. ``I thought that our
execution was pretty good. We didn't turn the ball over, we got
some pretty good looks. They just didn't fall for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen was 0 for 3 in the quarter before fouling out with 32
seconds left. Rasheed Wallace, who had 30 points, was 3 of 9. Steve
Smith, Brian Grant and Bonzi Wells were a combined 1 of 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed some shots down the stretch, can't do nothing about
that,'' Wallace said. ``And it's all said and done with now.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland's offensive collapse energized the Lakers, who clamped
down even harder defensively and found a rhythm on offense,
shooting 60 percent (9 of 15) for the period.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw connected on two 3-pointers, the second one tying the game
75-75 with four minutes left, by taking advantage of Shaquille
O'Neal's kickouts off double teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shots were just falling tonight,'' Shaw said. ``They were
doubling the ball, and we were swinging it, and we were open. We
were trying to take what the defense gave us.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the Blazers gave away a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing not to come away with the win,
especially when you feel like you had it in your grasp,'' Greg
Anthony said. ``We just played a really poor fourth quarter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
