<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4563 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-05 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM A MOMENT, MEMORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The stars of the moment are Shaquille O'Neal and
Kobe Bryant. So why am I thinking about Kirk Gibson?
</P>
<P>
   The burning, lasting image is a lob pass and a dunk. So why am I
picturing a back-door slider and a miracle home run?
</P>
<P>
   The result is an NBA championship that is not yet secured but
seems now to be destiny. So why am I recalling a long-ago World
Series?
</P>
<P>
   Because the only way to do justice to the Kobe-to-Shaq lob with
42 seconds left in Sunday's playoff game, to the Lakers comeback it
capped and to the hysteria it launched, is to compare the moment to
Gibson, the Dodgers and October 1988.
</P>
<P>
   You have to be a fan of a certain age to remember the last time
it felt this good to be at an L.A. sports event.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years. The wait just might have been worth it.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers go on, as will be expected, to win the NBA Finals
over the Indiana Pacers, then their 89-85 victory in Game 7 of the
Western Conference finals against the Portland Trail Blazers will
go down as one of the signature moments in L.A. sports history.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest since Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were down by 16 late in the third quarter and by 15
with 10 minutes left in the game. The Trail Blazers had outplayed
them from afternoon to evening and were on their way to completing
a momentous comeback of their own - winning the series after
trailing 3 games to 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't look good,'' Lakers guard Brian Shaw said in the
locker room afterward. ``We had to remind ourselves we had a lot of
time to chip away at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The comeback started innocently enough with an O'Neal hook shot
to make it 75-62. Then Bryant spiked a Bonzi Wells shot, and Shaw
canned a 3-pointer from the left corner. Portland called time out
with 9:36 to play, and they were going crazy in the Staples Center,
19,000 fans in giveaway gold T-shirts putting life in the
first-year arena.
</P>
<P>
   But the best, the loudest, the most golden was yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry's 3-pointer, Bryant's floating jumper, Shaw's
3-pointer to tie the score at 75 with four minutes to play, Horry's
dive and scramble to come up with a critical rebound, O'Neal's bank
shot to give the Lakers their first lead since 5-4. ...
</P>
<P>
   And then ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq falling out of the rafters (to grab) that alley-oop,'' as
Lakers forward Rick Fox described the play.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were up 83-79 by this point. The clock was under 50
seconds. Bryant had the ball at the top of the key. He shook
Scottie Pippen with a crossover dribble, drove to the free-throw
line and threw a pass to the middle of the backboard.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Kirk Gibson reached down and away for a Dodgers
championship.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, Shaquille O'Neal reached up and ... up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was, like, `Damn! He closed it off!' '' Bryant said of
O'Neal's catch and dunk.
</P>
<P>
   That put the Lakers ahead by six - and in command.
</P>
<P>
   They were going crazier in the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just seemed to be a capper,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were a lot of plays (that made up the
comeback),'' backup center John Salley said. ``But that one kind of
summed up the way we played. Kobe threw it up high, and Shaq was
just determined to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   All night, the Blazers tried to hold O'Neal down, and mostly
they did, limiting him to 18 points, eight of those on free throws.
</P>
<P>
   And then, look who was coming up ... and up.
</P>
<P>
   It was a where-were-you-when? kind of moment.
</P>
<P>
   You - you in the gold - were lucky to be there.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, I was so sure the Dodgers were cooked in Game
1 of that World Series against the Oakland A's, I watched the
bottom of the ninth on a TV outside the clubhouse doors, wanting to
waste no time gathering the losers' quotes.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, I was so sure the Lakers were done, I was writing down
lines for a column on how they got beat by a better team. (Possible
lead: ``The best team money can buy, indeed!'')
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if it's the Lakers or the Blazers who were the
better team the past two weeks. I don't know if that was the Lakers
stealing Game 7 or the Blazers giving it away.
</P>
<P>
   I do know there was something magical about it, something we'd
have missed if the Lakers had won in five games as they were
supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   And I do know that all of the emptiness L.A. fans have felt
since the city's last great sports moment ... she is gone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 0122EDT &QL; 
