<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4567 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE1-SHAW-L     06-05 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE1-SHAW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE SHAW A HAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Kobe Bryant hadn't broken his hand last fall,
it's doubtful Brian Shaw would have had such a large hand in
Sunday's memorable comeback victory over Portland.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Shaw promised he would be elsewhere if the Lakers had
not signed him as an emergency measure when Bryant went on the
injured list last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be in Oakland up in the Bay Area on a fishing boat,''
Shaw said. ``Six-seven months ago, I didn't know where I would be
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's four victories from an NBA title, after hitting two
critical 3-pointers that helped the Lakers overcome a 15-point
fourth-quarter deficit and defeat the Trail Blazers 89-84 in Game 7
of the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw was nothing short of the Lakers' savior, scoring 11 points
and hitting three 3-pointers overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian Shaw carried us,'' Lakers forward Robert Horry said.
``He made some big shots and got us pumped.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of Shaw's 3-pointers was significant.
</P>
<P>
   --With 4.4 seconds left in the third quarter, Shaw banked in a
26-footer that gave the Lakers a glimmer of hope by cutting a
16-point Portland lead to 13 71-58 entering the final period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just glad that it went in. I wasn't trying to bank it,
and it went in,'' Shaw said. ``Somebody helped guide it in.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Lakers guard Ron Harper: ``I don't how he made that
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the shot didn't seem terribly important, but even
Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy singled it out after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big momentum play,'' Dunleavy said. ``It got them
to where they were in striking distance.''
</P>
<P>
   --After Portland rebuilt its lead to 75-60, Shaw helped stop the
Blazers' momentum again with a 24-foot jumper with 9:36 remaining
that brought the Lakers within 10 points (75-65).
</P>
<P>
   --Then came the shot he'll always remember. With the Lakers
trailing 75-72, Shaw saw an opening in the Blazers' defense and
nailed a 25-footer to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wasn't aware what the score was,'' Shaw said. ``I was
just happy the basketball went in. I guess the stars were in
alignment. I've been in a pretty good groove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to take what the defense gave me. I was one
of those guys (Portland) didn't count on.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also a player the Blazers didn't want. Or couldn't keep.
They traded him to Houston last year in the deal that brought
Scottie Pippen to Portland. But a modest Shaw wasn't about to gloat
or admit any extra satisfaction over knocking a former team out of
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very ironic the way it worked out, to play the team I
was on last year,'' Shaw said. ``I'm grateful to their organization
for giving me an opportunity. I didn't consider myself a castoff in
Portland. It just didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets didn't want Shaw either, and he only became a Laker
after being scouted in some local pick-up games when Bryant went
down prior to the season. He's another of Lakers coach Phil
Jackson's old-timers, along with Harper and John Salley.
</P>
<P>
   From Bryant's fateful injury came Sunday's heroics. Shaw was
quick to rank his final 3-pointer that tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, right now, it's the biggest moment of my career,''
Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Now all he needs is an NBA ring. He was teammates with Shaquille
O'Neal in Orlando when they took the Magic to the NBA Finals in
1995, only to be swept by Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still haven't achieved the ultimate goal,'' Shaw said. ``We
didn't taste victory (in '95). Shaquille and I, we're calling this
the 'ShawShaq Redemption.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
