<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4569 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-05 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Pippen: Plop, plop, fizz, fizz
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This never happened when Michael Jordan was
around.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen never had to lean on the old crutch about bad
officiating, because he could always lean on Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen never had to make big excuses, because he had Michael to
make the big shots.
</P>
<P>
   At long last, a reason for his own high-profile line of
basketball shoes _ Air Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   For the way the wind came out of the Blazers' sails. For the way
the air burst from their tires as if they had run over a bed of
nails at 80 mph. For the way Pippen stood by and let them blow it.
</P>
<P>
   The best team money could buy _ with a $74 million payroll _
turned up counterfeit in the biggest quarter of the season, and
Pippen in his vaunted role as leader looked as phony as a $3 bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Titanic was bigger, but the Blazers went down faster.
Vesuvius erupted without notice and buried Pompeii, but at least
the citizens could see the lava coming.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen and the Blazers went up like the Hindenburg, in a roaring
ball of flames.
</P>
<P>
   Their 89-84 victory in Game 7 of the NBA Western Conference
finals wasn't so much an ascendancy for the Lakers as it was a
complete and devastating Portland collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Think free fall.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-point Blazers lead went over the edge in just a little more
than 10 minutes and so did Pippen's false hopes of being the man
who could carry the banner.
</P>
<P>
   Some guys are born to be the Lone Ranger and others are simply
born to be Tonto.
</P>
<P>
   So while Pippen watched helplessly as the Blazers came unwound,
it was no real surprise to anyone who has followed his career of
riding Jordan's coattails.
</P>
<P>
   Not if you remember the Game 7 migraine against the Pistons. Not
if you remember the final 1.8 seconds against the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Some horses pull the wagon and others are tied to a rope and
follow it.
</P>
<P>
   On his long-awaited day in the spotlight, Pippen melted like a
wax figure at Madame Tussaud's with just 12 points on 3-for-10
shooting. And when the heat was turned up most in the fourth
quarter, he evaporated faster than a drop of water in a microwave,
taking only three shots and missing every one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very disappointed,'' Pippen said. ``We realize we sort
of made cowards of ourselves in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's yellow streak was bigger than Pippen's as the veteran
of six NBA championships with the Bulls never stepped up.
</P>
<P>
   This was the night Pippen finally was going to step out of
Jordan's shadow and instead he was swallowed up by it.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan never would have allowed his team to miss 13 straight
shots and fail to score on nine consecutive possessions in the
fourth quarter. Pippen did.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan never would have been content hanging around the
perimeter and dumping passes inside to Rasheed Wallace or standing
off to the side for clear-outs by Steve Smith. Pippen did.
</P>
<P>
   With the turnabout from a 3-1 deficit nearly complete and the
final game firmly in his hands, it was Pippen who ran the Portland
offense that sputtered and coughed and eventually broke down like a
Chevy Corvair in the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   It is a game the LA fans will celebrate for the way the Lakers
got up off the floor and never quit running at Portland. It was a
performance that will go down as the biggest fourth-quarter
comeback in any seventh game of any playoff series in NBA history.
It was a moment that will live on for years just on the image of
Kobe Bryant blowing past Pippen, tossing that lob pass up there
toward the moon and Shaquille O'Neal going almost into orbit to
grab the ball and slam it home.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that will propel the Lakers into the Finals as the
favorites against the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a game mostly the Blazers couldn't finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be aggressive and keep taking the ball to the
basket,'' Pippen said. ``But there was a momentum shift and once
that happens, then the officiating tends to shift and it's hard to
stop things then. We were no longer getting the calls we had been
getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq was allowed to camp out in the lane. It became an uphill
battle for us.''
</P>
<P>
   An uphill battle? With a 15-point lead?
</P>
<P>
   What Pippen had to do was what he had preached to everyone he
was doing all season and all through the series _ lead. What Pippen
had to do was show his untested teammates how to stay calm and to
keep functioning when the game was in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   What Pippen had to do was show the Blazers how to go in for the
kill. What he did was watch it all slowly slip away. With Shaq
limited to only nine shots and 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   It was more painful to watch than medieval torture. Pippen
didn't attack the basket. He didn't create shots for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Michael always rowed the boat ashore. Pippen couldn't get an oar
into the water.
</P>
<P>
   This never happened when Jordan was around. It's also why Tonto
never got his own show.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 0139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
