<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4571 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-LA     06-05 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZING RALLY LIFTS LAKERS TO FINALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The greatest season in recent history nearly
became history until the Los Angeles Lakers at last made history,
with the greatest comeback anyone could have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   And made one gigantic, fantastic, heart-stopping leap to the NBA
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are Western Conference champions and bound for the
Finals for the first time in nine years, because for one 12-minute
span Sunday, they assumed the identity of a championship team.
</P>
<P>
   Down to their last game of the series, down to their last
quarter, down 15 points to the Portland Trail Blazers, the Lakers
did not wilt.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't flinch. Didn't panic. Or even momentarily consider their
time had passed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they mounted a spectacular comeback filled with Robert
Horry's tough defense and Brian Shaw's clutch 3-point swishes, Kobe
Bryant's steady playmaking, and one gargantuan,
Oh-my-God-we're-going-to-the-Finals slam dunk by Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   The championship banners hanging in the Staples Center rafters
shook, the Blazers fell, and the Lakers pulled out an 89-84 victory
to send 18,997 fans into delirious bliss, and send this franchise
to the championship round for the first time in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   The Finals begin Wednesday against the Indiana Pacers at Staples
Center. As soon as they can clean up all the sweat and confetti
that rained here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took everything we had,'' Glen Rice said. ``Guys had to dig
down deep. It was one of those situations where you had to lay it
all on the line, and that's what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, it was the biggest comeback in a Western Conference
finals Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficially, it was the biggest game Los Angeles has seen in
over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Killer instinct, no?'' Bryant said with a wide smile.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be questioned again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've showed a lot of comeback efforts during the course of
the year, and I thought they had that part of it in them,'' said
coach Phil Jackson, who took just one season to deliver the Lakers
to the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great win for the fans, a great win for this
franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   No one but the Lakers saw it coming. They trailed continuously
for most of three quarters in a game that looked very much like the
last two - both losses.
</P>
<P>
   Rasheed Wallace was scoring at will, Steve Smith was shooting
with precision, and a swarming defense had all but shut down
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   So Jackson, in an early fourth-quarter timeout, gave in.
``Forget about Shaq,'' he told his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we forced the ball into him, we were creating
turnovers, either for Shaq or for us,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Lakers worked the ball around and created their own
opportunities. But Rick Fox hit O'Neal for a bucket to cut the
deficit to 75-62 early in the fourth. Then Brian Shaw hit a
3-pointer. Then Robert Horry grabbed an offensive rebound and hit a
3-pointer, and the deficit was cut to five points with 7:06 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Comeback was on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heart and effort,'' Bryant said. ``They outworked us pretty
good the last couple games, and we didn't want it to happen in the
seventh game, particularly on our home floor. So we just brought a
lot of heart and a lot of effort and a lot of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   A Kobe jumper. A Kobe 3-point miss, a Jackson look of
exasperation on the bench. Then a Shaw 3-pointer, and with 4
minutes left, the Lakers had used a 15-0 run to forge the tie,
75-all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't panic,'' Fox said. ``No one panicked. We just
continued to recognize the situation we were in. In the third
quarter we recognized, hey, if we were not going to win this game,
we were gonna not win it by fighting, and really giving it a
wholehearted effort. We did things defensively first, and then we
knocked down some shots. Pressure shifted toward them, those shots
didn't fall, and it was a matter of us making big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Horry kept fronting Wallace, who despite scoring a game-high 30
points, kept missing in the fourth. The Blazers missed 13
consecutive shots. And the Lakers kept coming.
</P>
<P>
   Free throws by Bryant and O'Neal gave them the lead, a Bryant
jumper over Scottie Pippen made it a 4-point game. And then came
the crushing blow.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant crossed up Pippen at the top of the key, lofted a perfect
lob to the right side of the hoop, and O'Neal - bottled up for the
last two games - unleashed every last ounce of frustration with a
right-handed jam and a bellowing victory yell.
</P>
<P>
   It was 85-79, with 41.3 seconds left, and the Blazers were done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard for me to get any shots all night,'' O'Neal said.
``We caught eye contact, and he just threw it up. And I just went
up and got it. That was an opportunity for me to get an easy
bucket, because I really didn't get any easy shots all game.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland had used a 21-4 run to take control in the third
quarter building a 16-point lead Jackson called ``daunting'' - but
the Blazers had nothing left for the fourth, which the Lakers won
31-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing not to come away with the win,
especially when you feel like you had it in your grasp. We just
played a really poor fourth quarter,'' said the Blazers' Greg
Anthony. ``For whatever reason, our best just wasn't good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers survived a mere 18-point night by O'Neal. They were
carried by Bryant's 25 points, Horry's 12 and 11 each from Rice and
Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been playing hard all game long,'' Bryant said, ``and in
this type of situation, all you can ask for yourself is just to
play hard. We felt like we could play hard for 48 minutes, and we
finally were able to wear them down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
