<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE FINISHES STRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Not a sore right foot, a hyperactive Damon
Stoudamire, a hot-shooting Steve Smith or a wily Scottie Pippen
could rattle Kobe Bryant on Sunday, in the biggest game of his
young career.
</P>
<P>
   As the Los Angeles Lakers closed out the Western Conference
finals with an 89-84 Game 7 victory over Portland, Bryant took
turns closing down the Trail Blazers' main weapons. Stoudamire went
silent (5 points), while Bryant turned in key runs against the
other two.
</P>
<P>
   Although he collected four fouls, Bryant played without foul
trouble for most of the game, a luxury he hasn't had most of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought his defense was really good,'' coach Phil Jackson
said. ``He was allowed to play defense, which is important because
he was aggressive, he was physical, he was active and he did a good
job on everybody we put him on today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's most obvious numbers were the 25 points and seven
assists he posted on offense. But he had 11 defensive rebounds and
blocked four shots - including a Bonzi Wells attempt early in the
fourth quarter, as the Lakers began a comeback from 15 points down.
</P>
<P>
   The right foot Bryant sprained in Game 5 never appeared to be a
factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just took it as a personal challenge,'' he said, ``because I
felt like all series long, they've kind of been going at me, trying
to expose me, trying to get me in foul trouble, and it got to a
point where it really started to get under my skin. I just took it
as a personal challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing's free: The Lakers' worst foul shooter Sunday was not
Shaquille O'Neal, who made 8 of 12, and 3 of 4 in the fourth
quarter. The foul-line liability turned out to be the usually
reliable Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant made just 6 of 12 from the line and missed three key free
throws in the fourth - one at the start of the comeback from 15
points down, and two near the end.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were up 86-82 with 25.4 seconds left when Bryant got
Scottie Pippen to foul out. But Bryant missed both free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Horry also went 3 for 6 from the line as the Lakers made
just 10 of 18 in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq shooting free throws well down the stretch, that's
something you couldn't depend upon, he did it,'' Jackson said.
``The rest of the guys not shooting free throws well at important
parts, that was a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, a career 81 percent foul shooter, isn't concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just nip it in the bud for the final series,'' he said. ``Just
forget about it, work on them and just knock them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Advantage: A lack of noise and crowd energy at times this season
made everyone wonder whether Staples Center could provide a
home-court advantage. Jackson himself had called it into question,
but not after Sunday's win.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has to go to the hometown fans,'' he said. ``I think that
game is one that you have to count on as a home-court advantage
because of the energy that our fans gave us in that fourth
quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Brian Shaw, who fired up the masses with two big 3-pointers
in the fourth, ``It was pretty special today. Everybody in the
crowd stayed until the very end. That is what home-court advantage
is all about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
