<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4574 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-SHAQ-LA     06-05 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-SHAQ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISER, MATURE SHAQ SHOWS HE'S SUPER IN CLUTCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ That was some trick, making someone 7 feet 1 and
335 pounds disappear before a watching nation. Either Houdini had
slipped into a Trail Blazers uniform, or Shaquille O'Neal had
slipped out of the building.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal is supposed to be basketball's most unstoppable force,
but the Portland Trail Blazers had somehow managed to reduce him to
Elden Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   This was the biggest game of O'Neal's Laker life, the game where
he was supposed to prove he really was the MVP, really had cause
for that ``S'' emblazoned all over everything he owns.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for three quarters Sunday, O'Neal had made exactly two field
goals. He had taken but six shots and pulled down five rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Portland hadn't given anything this much attention since Mount
St. Helens.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh game of the Western Conference finals, with a
trip to the Finals awaiting the winner, the Los Angeles Lakers
trailed 71-58, and O'Neal was looking at a long summer of
explaining.
</P>
<P>
   And then the strangest thing happened.
</P>
<P>
   Portland was up by 15 early in the fourth quarter, when for one
of the few times on the night, O'Neal got the ball inside and
connected on a layup. It seemed innocent enough, but it started
perhaps the greatest comeback in Lakers history.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers went on a 15-0 run to catch the Blazers. O'Neal had
emerged from the phone booth. After Portland center Arvydas Sabonis
fouled out with 2:44 to play, O'Neal capped what was an overall
25-4 run when he electrified the crowd by skying to reach a Kobe
Bryant pass above the basket and slamming it through the net.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had a stunning 85-79 lead with 41.9 seconds to play,
and ready or not, were going to The Finals.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had nine points, four rebounds and an assist in the
fourth- quarter comeback. And something added to his reputation,
instead of subtracted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got the guys together and said, `Let's ----ing go.
We've been here before. We've got to do it,''' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   `` `We've come too far now to let it all slip away. Let's fight
and scratch. Let's crawl. Let's hit shots. Let's do it. They're not
going to let me shoot anyway, so just throw it down. I'm going to
let them come scramble and then kick it out. Make me look good.'''
</P>
<P>
   This was the wiser, more mature O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Portland has played him better in this series than any team he
had faced in his Lakers career. They had a big body in the 7-3
Sabonis to matchup against him, and were quick to double- and
triple-team him with 6-11 Rasheed Wallace and the long-armed
Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers could seldom work the ball inside, and when they did,
the Blazers often fouled so quickly, O'Neal didn't have time to get
off a shot.
</P>
<P>
   As the Lakers fell further behind, his frustration grew, but he
kept it hidden. The Big Man was not being given a chance by the
Blazers to have a big game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little frustrated, but I just hung in there and never
really gave up,'' O'Neal said. ``I could tell early that my guys
were going to hit their shots. I knew my guys were focused and
ready, so I was just trying to do all the little things.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he was doing too little when the Lakers fell behind by as
many as 16 at the close of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was frustrated, but maybe that's because I know him
pretty well,'' Laker Brian Shaw said. ``But he never really let
anybody else see him like that. He kept his head up, kept his wits
about him, and continued to do what he needed to do and not let us
see him down. And I think that was very important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw - O'Neal's former teammate in Orlando - hit three
3-pointers in the second half to help spark the comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why this is a team game,'' said Laker Robert Horry, who
had six points in the final quarter. ``We always count on him for
90 percent of our offense, but we've got to be a team. It's just up
to us to help him out. We can't always depend on him.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was back in the building, and the Lakers back in the
Finals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 0205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
