<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4575 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-TRAILBLAZE     06-05 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-TRAILBLAZERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL, LAKERS GO 4TH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The best team that money supposedly could buy came
up looking like Confederate currency when it came time to be
counted. For that, the Lakers are going to the NBA Finals. That
huge exhale you heard was from the executives over at NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, down by 13 after three and by 15 with 10:28 to play,
took advantage of a monumental Portland meltdown in the fourth
quarter and won Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's dramatic Game 7, 89-84, before a
yellow-clad sellout at Staples Center. They will face Indiana in
the Finals, which begin here Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers, a $73 million ensemble of All-Stars and Olympians,
looked like your basic Biddy Ball team when it came time to close
the deal. ``We realize we were sort of made cowards,'' said Scottie
Pippen, the six-time champion brought in to prevent such
happenings. The Blazers were outscored, 31-13, in the quarter. They
shot 5 for 23. They went 7:30 without a point and 8:11 without a
basket, missing 14 straight shots over that span.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very disappointed,'' said Pippen, who was 3 for 10 and
finished with 12 points, none in the fourth. ``We lost this game in
one quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   How true. The Lakers are lucky to be where they are this
morning. They were hardly overwhelming, more like the long-lost
beneficiary of a will. But it was impossible for them not to
benefit from such largesse. They were down by 15 with 10:28 left.
They were tied with 4:00 to play. They missed 17 free throws in the
game, lost the turnover battle, and still won.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen one quite like this,'' said LA coach Phil
Jackson, who has seen just about everything.
</P>
<P>
   Portland led, 75-60, when a second-chance layup by Shaquille
O'Neal got the rally rolling. Kobe Bryant (11 rebounds, 7 assists,
4 blocks) then swatted away a Bonzi Wells drive and the Lakers were
on their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a statement to them,'' Bryant said of the block.
``That was a statement to them that we were not going to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Shaw then hit the first of his two treys and the lead
quickly was 10. A Blazer timeout did nothing. Kobe (a free throw)
and Shaq (a free throw) cut it to 8 and then Robert Horry, who has
been bricking treys all series, knocked one down to make it 75-70.
Rasheed Wallace (30 points, but 3 for 9 in the fourth) then missed
and Bryant converted from the lane. Shaw then tied the game with
his second trey of the run and third of the game. His first was a
biggie at the end of the third quarter, cutting the lead from 16 to
13.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just went at it, little by little,'' said Shaw, who, along
with O'Neal will be making his second visit to the NBA Finals. Both
were on the 1995 Orlando team that was swept by Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazer drought ended with a Wallace finger roll with 2:58 to
play. That made it 77-75 and was Portland's last lead of the game.
There would be two more ties, the final one with 1:50 left (at 79)
after a Shaq goaltend.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bryant drove to the basket and got fouled by Wallace.
Bryant was a bit shaky at the line all night _ 6 for 12 _ but he
knocked these two down. Wallace then had the same opportunity nine
seconds later. He missed them both. Kobe (a jumper) and Shaq (a
high alley-oop from Bryant) blew the lead out to 6 and that was
that.
</P>
<P>
   Portland coach Mike Dunleavy sounded afterward as if he had
missed the entire quarter. He talked about how he was proud his
team had played 48 minutes _ he was off by 12 _ and how the Blazers
got good looks but simply didn't put the ball in the basket. The
last time we checked, that's how points are scored and games are
won.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave it a great run,'' he said of his team. ``A lot of
people wrote us off, during the season and during the series.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad it had to end in such calamitous fashion for
Portland. No one will remember the way the Blazers took the crowd
out of the game with a 13-0 first-quarter run. Or how they hung in
there despite early foul trouble to Arvydas Sabonis and Brian
Grant. Or how they shackled Shaq, who was a mere 5 for 9 from the
field. Or how they put on a clinic in the third quarter, going on
an 18-2 run and getting the lead to 16 with 20.6 seconds left in
the third.
</P>
<P>
   No one will remember any of that except the loyalists at the
Blazers Boosters Club. This one came down to winnin' time, a
familiar phrase here in the 1980s. The new Lakers may not be as
good or as successful as their predecessors, but they, like them,
know what to do when the game is on the line. They went out and won
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
