<HEADER>
A4613 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i PM-CLINTON-MISSILES05-CO     06-05 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 PM-CLINTON-MISSILES05-COX &HT;    CLINTON PITCHES MISSILE DEFENSE TO RUSSIAN PARLIAMENT
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Clinton took his case for a new U.S. missile
defense system directly to the Russian people and their elected
representatives Monday, telling them the proposed shield poses no
threat to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In nationally televised remarks before the Russian parliament,
Clinton said it was ``inconceivable'' that the United States would
deploy such a system without working closely with Moscow to keep
from renewing an arms race between the world's two largest nuclear
powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find any future apart from cooperation with you in the
nuclear area inconceivable,'' he said. ``The real question is a
debate over what the impact of this will be, because of the
capacity of the technology involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks capped a three-day visit to Moscow centered on tough
talks with President Vladimir Putin over missile defense and
nuclear weapons reductions.
</P>
<P>
   The first American president ever to address Russia's
parliament, Clinton left Moscow afterwards and flew to Kiev for an
afternoon of meetings with President Leonid Kuchma of the Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to return to Washington late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   In about eight hours of face-to-face summitry in Moscow, Clinton
was unable to overcome Putin's objections to a national missile
defense system to defend the United States from a missile attack by
a rogue state or terrorist group. The president is to decide this
fall whether to proceed with development of the system, which is
now being tested by the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   He made a pitch for Russian acceptance of the system in a joint
speech before the 450-member Duma, the key legislative body, and
the 178-member Federation Council. Not all members were in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The system is aimed at protecting the United States from the
threat that a rogue state or terrorist group might one day try to
attack the country with a nuclear missile.
</P>
<P>
   Putin told Clinton the risk of such attack was being exaggerated
by advocates of the system, and that deploying it could cause more
harm than good by upsetting the balance of power between the United
States and Russia. Together, the two nations possess more than 80
percent of the world's nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pleaded with Russians to think carefully about how
quickly global security is being changed by the wide availability
of new technology and information that will soon make it possible
for many new actors to acquire advanced weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be realistic,'' said Clinton. ``Despite our best
efforts, the possibility exists that nuclear and other deadly
weapons will fall into dangerous hands, into hands that could
threaten us both.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton, ``the technology required to launch missiles
capable of delivering them over long distances, unfortunately, is
still spreading across the world. The question is, what is the best
way to deal with it?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made his comments during a 45-minute speech meant to be
a grand survey of U.S.-Russian relations at a time of historic
turmoil inside the former superpower.
</P>
<P>
   He urged the Russian people to continue their difficult journey
from communist autocracy to free-market democracy and stressed the
need to build the elements of a civil society based on the rule of
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Above all,'' said Clinton, ``a strong state should use its
strength to reinforce the rule of law, protect the powerless
against the powerful, defend democratic freedoms, including freedom
of expression, religion and the press, and do whatever is possible
to give everyone a chance to develop his or her innate abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's message ran into heavy weather, though, in the form of
parliament member Vladimir Zhirinovsky, the ultra-nationalist who
has built a political career by decrying the collapse of the former
Soviet Union and the subsequent decline of living standards across
the Russian motherland.
</P>
<P>
   Seated 14 rows away from Clinton, Zhirinovsky grumbled loudly
when the president was introduced. As applause filled the chamber
at the end of the speech, he hollered out to his colleagues, ``Why
are you applauding for him? He destroyed our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhirinovsky led several dozen protesters _ some chanting
``Yankee go home,'' and ``U.S. out of Serbia _ outside of the Duma
building, while others waved red Soviet-era flags bearing the
hammer and sickle symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has poured money into Russia, and after
eight years, what has happened? It has brought to power a KGB
colonel, those whom the United States was fighting against on the
dollars of U.S. taxpayers,'' said parliament member Alexei
Mitrofanov, the number two man in Zhirinovsky's ultranationalist
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is worse for most Russians after ten years of reform,''
Mitrofanov told American reporters immediately after Clinton's
speech. ``Clinton understands nothing of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
