<HEADER>
A4615 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN07-COX     06-05 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Elian affair shows flaws in Cuban policy
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Elian goes home _ and it now seems all but certain that he
will _ perhaps he will leave us with something useful: a new
appreciation of just how goofy our Cuban policy has become.
</P>
<P>
   The boy should have been out of here six months ago, as soon as
he had recovered from his traumatic rescue and as quickly as
arrangements could be made for his father to pick him up.
</P>
<P>
   Instead _ famously, flamboyantly _ he became one of those
wildfire cause celebres that take over a whole era of news cycles,
only to wind up within a few years as a puzzling footnote, if even
that, to the real history of its time.
</P>
<P>
   The Castro-addled Miami Cuban community went ritually bananas
over his prospective return, claiming stronger stewardship resided
with cousins umpteen times removed than with the boy's dad. (A
claim based mainly on the finders-keepers taunt.) A whole
jurisprudence was jerry-built around the boy, like a mining camp
thrown up overnight after gold is struck.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential politics was sucked in, as Democratic nominee-to-be
Al Gore hurried to the TV cameras to pander for votes that just
might tip Florida his way. (GOP rival George W. Bush was
pre-pandered.)
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration dithered for weeks, a wet finger to
the political winds, until finally deciding, oh, what the heck,
let's just follow the law.
</P>
<P>
   All of this because U.S. policy continues to be swung by that
tiny but hugely noisy electoral fraction at the tip of Florida,
allied elsewhere, especially in Congress, to a scatteration of
vestigial Cold Warriors with precious little war left to wage.
</P>
<P>
   Look, Fidel Castro is an enemy of his people's freedom. He is,
if not exactly a dictator, unilateral, pre-emptive and arbitrary.
His persistence in a failed command economy has reduced his nation
and its people to a shabby poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to love or endorse the aging autocrat to
recognize that the generation-old U.S. effort to isolate and
undermine his regime 1) doesn't and can't work and 2) has outlived
whatever usefulness it once had.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. economic boycott of Cuba and grant of extraordinary
refuge to Cubans were meant to parry Castro's ability to play the
willing cat's paw for Soviet mischief in the hemisphere. That
ability ended when communism flopped in Russia and the Kremlin
stopped sending checks. All that remains of Cuba's revolutionary
fervor are a few wan and feeble gestures at pro forma rallies.
</P>
<P>
   The current U.S. interest lies in repairing relations in a way
that prepares for Castro's inevitable slump from power. That means
re-establishing commerce as a counterweight to Cuban economic
slide. Do we really want Haiti II just offshore? And it means
establishing a working political relationship that can prevent
further nonsense like the Elian affair.
</P>
<P>
   We just cut a permanent trade deal with China, for goodness
sakes, the mother of communist populations. It's time to develop a
Cuban policy. For years, we've only had a Castro policy.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He writes from
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
