<HEADER>
A4702 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-HAITI-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-05 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-HAITI-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
T WO ELECTIONS ON AN ISLAND. SO CLOSE, SO FAR APART 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (The Week in Review) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ Wilda Severe carried the future in her
mind and body as she waited to cast her ballot last month in
Haiti's legislative elections. Though five months pregnant, she
stood for hours on a slowly moving line, hoping that her vote would
usher in a better life for her baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the conditions of the country to change,'' she said.
``The conditions are not good for anybody right now. People suffer
and there is no work. And there is insecurity. The country is still
not at peace.''
</P>
<P>
   More than five years after a U.S.-led military occupation
restored democratic rule in Haiti, the civil serenity that she and
many Haitians hoped for remains elusive. In the weeks before the
elections, politically motivated violence had left 15 people dead,
and in the slums the sense of poverty only deepened.
</P>
<P>
   When the last U.S. troops left Haiti this year, some policy
makers saw it as the end of a successful mission to restore
democracy. But the fact that the elections (in which former
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide's party did well) found so many
Haitians still pining for peace and progress belies any boast. It
raises questions about why Haiti seems to stagger from crisis to
crisis as it tries to embark on the path to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Part of an answer lies just a short flight away in the Dominican
Republic _ a nation that shares not just the island of Hispaniola
with Haiti, but also a history of dictatorship, violence and U.S.
intervention. It too has had an election in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   But there, just over the border, the economy is expanding
rapidly. New roads, modernized government agencies and investment
have transformed the capital. Though many of the poorest Dominicans
felt excluded from the boom times, they peacefully voiced their
dissatisfaction at the polls, where a near majority elected
Hipolito Mejia president on May 16. And then the ruling party
abandoned its quest for a runoff and conceded defeat for the good
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Like the border that separates the two countries _ where the
lush green landscape of the Dominican Republic gives way to the
barren, deforested soil of Haiti _ the contrast in political and
social fortunes is sharp. Considering that Haiti was once the more
prosperous and cosmopolitan of the two countries, and that the
violence of Gen. Rafael Trujillo's dictatorship in the Dominican
Republic 35 years ago ago rivaled if not exceeded that of the
Duvalier family here, why do the two nations seem headed in
opposite directions?
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of the answer can be summed up in two words: 30
years,'' said Michele Wucker, author of ``Why The Cocks Fight,'' a
book exploring the relationship between the two nations. ``Haiti is
now where the Dominican Republic was not too long after the United
States invasion in 1965.''
</P>
<P>
   Even within the shared experience of military intervention,
however, there are differences. After the 1965 intervention, when
Joaquin Balaguer came to power and ushered in years of repressive
rule, the United States essentially kept a hands-off policy in the
Dominican Republic, Ms. Wucker said. In Haiti, the United States
restored Aristide to power in 1994, but placed narrow constraints
on the exercise of his power. Wucker said that the United States
also contradicted itself, pressing for elections while cutting aid
to help finance them. ``They talk in pretty terms about
democracy,'' said. ``But deep down they are reluctant to let Haiti
muddle its own way in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of dictatorship also played out differently. While
some Dominicans still bear scars _ physical and psychological _
from Balaguer's early years, just as many recall benefiting from
jobs, homes and other favors. So strong are those memories that
nearly a quarter of the votes went to Balaguer, even though he is
93, blind and infirm.
</P>
<P>
   In Haiti, the experience of a former president running again is
relatively rare, since most have gone into exile after enriching
themselves. ``They had Balaguer, we had Duvalier, but the histories
are very different,'' said Raoul Denis, a record store owner in
Port-au-Prince. ``On our side, Duvalier destroyed the institutions
and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Those institutions, like the courts and the police, still
struggle to maintain a semblance of law and order in Haiti. At the
same time, other forces that could help bring pressure to bear lack
sufficient experience to prove effective. In the Dominican
Republic, public-interest advocates have played an important role
in calling for clean elections and good government. Business
owners, aware that tourists and factory jobs can flee unless there
is social and political stability, also had a stake in the future
and supported it with investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem is we in Haiti do not have an authentic
bourgeoisie that has invested in Haiti,'' said Patrick
Pierre-Louis, a law school professor. ``All their money goes to the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominican business leaders were a major force for their
country's stability, said a diplomat who has worked there and in
Haiti. When the United States worried about elections in the
mid-1990s, such leaders were vulnerable to friendly pressure, since
business owners wanted trade parity with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Haiti there isn't much tourism,'' said the diplomat, who
spoke on condition of anonymity. ``The assembly sector is still not
large. They weathered the embargo and other bad situations. I'm not
sure the levers we had in the Dominican Republic could work here.''
</P>
<P>
   While Haiti's elections are the first step toward achieving a
normal government, bigger obstacles remain in a country where
winner-take-all has been a rule applied literally by victorious
candidates. Haiti's political leaders have yet to understand that
the power of the vote extends beyond election day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dominican interests are the interests of their country,'' said
Georges Sassine, a factory owner active in civic groups. ``Here,
you have people who come here, get rich and leave. We are still a
colony of ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
