<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4710 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-ROGUE-DEMOCRACIES-R     06-05 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ROGUE-DEMOCRACIES-REVIEW-1,150(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN DEMOCRACY RUNS OFF THE RAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (The Week in Review) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ For years the United States has classified some
countries, like Iraq and North Korea, as ``rogue states.'' Now, as
the world becomes more democratic _ more than 60 percent of
countries have elected leaders _ something more complicated enters
the political lexicon. Call them ``rogue democracies.''
</P>
<P>
   These are democratic governments that go off the rails, either
in aggressiveness toward neighbors, cruelty to citizens or
backtracking on the promise that democracy will foster liberty and
equality.
</P>
<P>
   How to deal with this new type of rogue, or to know when to
recognize one, is not easy for established democracies. It is,
after all, tempting to assume that when other nations choose to
freely elect their leaders, good things automatically follow.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Peru is the latest example: an elected president,
Alberto Fujimori, has rewritten the constitution, cut the power of
his congress and chipped away at political liberties, all in the
name of social order. Now he is claiming a third term after an
election so riddled with irregularities that the opposition
boycotted it and the Organization of American States won't approve
it.
</P>
<P>
   What's the world to do? Shun Peru? Impose sanctions? When
Austria's voters put the xenophobe Jorg Haider near the seat of
power, Europe got together and forced his ostracism. But in Peru a
similar outcome seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   It has been obvious for some time that democracy no longer has
one universally accepted definition, and so it is hard to say when
a country ceases to be one. Consider the variety of forms in Peru,
Russia, India, Zimbabwe, the United States, Austria and Japan.
There is also a growing understanding that elections don't
guarantee free expression or fair treatment of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a nation's ability to call itself a democracy often buys it
sympathy among voters in the West and among human-rights advocates
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Elected leaders on almost every continent have, indeed, long
used the forms of democracy as political wool to pull over the eyes
of those abroad who would judge their legitimacy to rule.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Latin America, constitutions are routinely amended or
rewritten to expand the terms and power of presidents.
</P>
<P>
   In Zimbabwe, where parliamentary elections are now less than
three weeks away, President Robert Mugabe has systematically
attacked the opposition under the guise of a violent campaign to
seize land from white farmers.
</P>
<P>
   In Iran, lame-duck conservatives tried to block the newly
elected reformist parliament; it was seated only with the suffrance
of the Islamic republic's ``supreme religious leader,'' who can
veto such earthly procedures as elections.
</P>
<P>
   In Singapore, and now Malaysia, elected Asian governments
dominated by intolerant leaders have fashioned the most
sophisticated, perfectly legal methods of destroying political
opponents through the courts. The slow-moving prosecution on sex
charges of Anwar Ibrahim, Malaysia's once-fast-rising deputy prime
minister, is a prime example.
</P>
<P>
   As for the component parts of the former Soviet Union, tidy
definitions of democracy are surely confounded by the
criminalization of the economy and, to some extent, political life,
not to mention the tenacity of Communist-era and Communist-style
political bosses who see elections pretty much as nuisances.
</P>
<P>
   There have always been imperfect democracies; the very messiness
of the political form invites imperfection. The United States has
had segregation, the internment of Japanese-Americans and repeated
episodes of local police brutality. Europeans differ on the limits
of free expression and how to treat minorities. But those can be
seen as shortcomings in realizing democracy's ideals, not a
negation of them. A more fundamental problem arises when
institutions are too weak to provide eventual remedies to the
shortcomings _ a role often played by elected legislatures and, in
America, the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, a democracy strays into rogue territory when a country
cannot muster any checks on the power plays of an elected leader
who chooses not to step aside and rewrites the rules accordingly. A
corollary is almost always oppression of some kind, often beginning
with the political opposition. And the mix becomes lethal, as it
did in Yugoslavia, if race, ethnicity or religion are then used to
inflame political passions.
</P>
<P>
   Lorne Craner, president of the International Republican
Institute, which is supported by the Republican Party, said that in
some dodgy democracies, ``a lot of people have figured out you can
have a bad election and get away with it.'' So his organization and
its opposite number in Washington, the National Democratic
Institute, have been thinking for years that it might be better to
concentrate more on what happens between elections. European
democracy groups and the Organization of African Unity are making a
similar shift, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating when there's no other reason why
countries that have poor human rights and democracy records don't
get sanctioned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Kaufman Purcell, president of the Americas Society in New
York, classifies the governments of Hugo Chavez in Venezuela and
Fujimori in Peru as ``imperfect democracies'' _ adding that often
``it is a hard call where to draw the line between imperfect
democracies and fake democracies.'' A democracy, she says, ``at the
very least must have some basic defining characteristics, the most
important being the ability to vote an incumbent out of power
through the use of a functioning electoral process that allows
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Bengt Save-Soderbergh, who runs a new intergovernmental
organization in Stockholm called the International Institute for
Democracy and Electoral Assistance, says even free and fair
elections don't define democracy: ``Deep down it's a culture, with
values and also respect, tolerance _ all these things.''
</P>
<P>
   At Emory University in Atlanta, Robert Pastor, an expert on
Latin America who served in the Carter administration and who has
advised and monitored elections as far afield as China, draws a
line at downgrading the essential role of national elections. There
are those who say, for example, that building in voting experience
from the village up, as China and Pakistan say they are doing (and
as Americans did before 1789), may be more useful than imposing
periodic national elections on an inexperienced people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been an argument that says democracy is more than
elections,'' Pastor said. ``I agree with that, but not when one
takes the next step and says that elections are not that important
for democracy. On that I completely disagree. Democracy should be
more than free elections, but it can't be less.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the problem of a different kind of rogue: The
electoral democracy whose human rights record or foreign policies
fall short of international standards but don't raise eyebrows. The
contrast between attitudes in America toward India and Pakistan is
instructive, one that human rights organizations often point to.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's annual international human rights survey
is very critical of India for its treatment of women, minorities
and people declared ``untouchable'' by the Hindu majority. In the
disputed territory of Kashmir, which is under Indian military
occupation, the report found significant abuses of the local Muslim
population. Moreover, American officials say that India has only
narrowly escaped being placed on the list of terrorist nations for
its backing of unrest in neighboring nations, including bombings
and perhaps assassinations in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   But at Human Rights Watch in New York, Kenneth Roth, the
executive director, said that Americans often overlook the record
because most of India's governments have been freely elected, while
neighboring Pakistan gets much closer scrutiny, having lurched in
and out of military rule. ``India has many attributes of a
democracy,'' said Roth. ``But it's too facile to embrace India as a
democracy without recognizing the flawed nature of its political
system when it comes to marginal populations or perceived security
threats.''
</P>
<P>
   Ram Narayan Kumar, an Indian human rights leader, worries about
the precedent. ``Around India,'' he said, ``the lesson other
countries there will learn is that you just have to appear to be
democratic.''
</P>
<P>
   Examples matter everywhere, said John Hirsch, a former U.S.
ambassador to Sierra Leone who is vice president of the
International Peace Academy, a research organization with close
ties to the United Nations. In Africa, he said, the two countries
in which to hope for continued success are Nigeria and South
Africa, both of which held open elections last year.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Joseph Smith, a political science professor at the
University of Virginia, said that strong democracies ``haven't
given enough thought to maintenance and sustaining of democracy.''
In the case of Peru, he added, the United States could have given
stronger support to the Organization of American States. Instead,
the Clinton administration first endorsed, then backed away from,
an unusually bold OAS judgment that the election was flawed. Smith
and Craner said that was a bad message to send to Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to mobilize the multilateral organizations to a far
greater extent,'' Smith said. ``Democracy needs constant
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
