<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3222 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-DETERRENCE-REVIEW-N     06-05 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-DETERRENCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLING THE WATERS OF NUCLEAR DETERRENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (The Week in Review) 
 By MICHAEL ORESKES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For nearly half a century the Cold War world's
tense stability was built on a simple bit of political philosophy.
Nicknamed, appropriately, MAD, for Mutual Assured Destruction, it
held that the leader of a country advanced enough to build nuclear
weapons would never actually use them if he was assured his nation
would also be obliterated by his enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Why call this a political philosophy? Because at its core, as at
the core of every political philosophy from Plato to Marx, is an
appraisal of human nature. MAD's view of human nature was,
paradoxically, surprisingly sunny. It held that a leader, no matter
how ambitious, ideological or even nutty, would never be so far
gone (or allowed to be so far gone by his cohorts) as to risk the
annihilation of his own people.
</P>
<P>
   That was the heart of deterrence: America's belief that the
Russians were rational and their belief that Americans were, too.
</P>
<P>
   As nuclear technology proliferates, however, the nuclear
equation is becoming more complicated, and a new view of deterrence
is taking hold in the United States. That view was summed up by a
bipartisan report last fall from a federal advisory commission
studying national security in the 21st century: Threats to U.S.
security will be more diffuse, harder to anticipate and more
difficult to neutralize than ever before. Deterrence will not work
as it once did; in many cases, it may not work at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because in the post-Cold War world, the new thinking goes,
there are some countries and leaders who simply cannot be trusted
to be rational about nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The old line in the sand was between two ideologies, each held
by people the other believed to be capable of acting sensibly. The
new line is between people who can be counted on to behave like us
and people who can't. Under the old thinking, the best defense was
the threat of an overwhelming offense. But in the new world, the
new theorists suggest, the best defense in some cases is actually a
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee, embraced this view in a speech recently calling for a
robust missile defense of the United States. And President Clinton
is in Moscow this weekend to discuss the new thinking, and his own
less expansive missile defense plans, with Russian President
Vladimir Putin, who holds a treaty barring the United States (or
Russia) from deploying a National Missile Defense (NMD).
</P>
<P>
   On his way to Moscow, Clinton gave a glimpse of the new
strategic view. The world, Clinton suggested during a stop in
Lisbon, can be divided between ``civilized nations,'' and
``irresponsible new nuclear powers and their possible alliances
with terrorists and other groups.'' Rest assured, Clinton said,
America would share with the civilized the technology to defend
against the irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   Who belongs in this second group? Clinton named neither the
civilized nations nor the irresponsible ones, although there was a
hint he was prepared to include Russia in the civilized category
because the very phrase was one Boris Yeltsin had once used to
describe a world protected by missile defenses.
</P>
<P>
   But what of China, which is on the verge of modernizing and
expanding its nuclear force and openly views a system defending the
continental United States as a threat to that force?
</P>
<P>
   The Americans say it's not China they're worried about, either,
but what the Clinton administration calls ``rogue states.'' North
Korea, for example, would fall into this category. But why is Kim
Jong-il of North Korea not likely to be deterred by the threat of
national devastation, if he struck at America?
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, North Korea is an isolated place, the last Stalinist
state and so economically troubled that people flee to China for a
better life. When Kim went on a secret state visit to Beijing last
week pictures released afterward showed him wearing a Mao jacket,
while China's president, Jiang Zemin, was attired in suit and tie.
Certainly he is behind the fashion curve. But does that mean he
would risk extinction?
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of the Cold War there has been only one real-world
test of deterrence against a so-called rogue state, and it supports
those who say it remains effective. It came on the eve of the Gulf
War. In a variety of ways, including a direct meeting with Tariq
Aziz, the Iraqi foreign minister, the U.S. secretary of state,
James Baker, warned Saddam Hussein that the use of chemical or
biological weapons against allied forces would be met by ``the most
severe consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis did not use these weapons and later said they
understood the American warning to mean a nuclear response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam Hussein may have been ruthlessly expansionist, but he
did not act irrationally,'' writes Robert S. Litwak, a former
member of the national security council staff at the White House,
in his book, `` Rogue States and U.S. Foreign Policy'' (Woodrow
Wilson Center Press, 2000).
</P>
<P>
   Critics of America's emerging new strategic thinking, which is
to say most of the rest of the world, seem to think that the new
theories of deterrence have more to do with the mind of America
than the mind of Saddam Hussein or of Kim Jong-il.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have always seen themselves as self- reliant, and they
have placed great faith in technology. Replacing MAD with NMD
relieves you of a dependence on the rationality of your fellow man,
in favor of an independence granted by your homegrown radar,
computers and missiles. America's allies are not convinced that is
an improvement, but Americans seem to be.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that they do not know much about it, nearly
60 percent of Americans said in a survey last month that they favor
trying to build a missile defense system against nuclear attack.
Told that $60 billion had already been spent, opinion remained in
favor. One American in four wants to try to build the system
despite the cost, even if scientists conclude it probably won't
work, according to the survey, conducted by The New York Times and
CBS News.
</P>
<P>
   What most Americans have not begun to consider is that an
anti-missile system would represent a fundamental shift in how the
nation thinks about nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   In 1945, the first year of the nuclear age, Albert Einstein
described atomic energy as a ``menace'' and added: ``Perhaps it is
well that it should be. It may intimidate the human race into
bringing order into its international affairs, which, without the
pressure of fear, it would not do.''
</P>
<P>
   For a half century that is what happened, more or less. What
frightens some analysts is that a shield against nuclear attack on
the United States would make Americans believe they are safe and
thus help lift from their leaders the pressure of fear, which helps
motivate the world's one superpower to work for continued order and
safety in the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
