<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To Be or Not to Be, Texas Style, and Bush-Lessness &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has the distinction of presiding
over more executions (131) than any governor in the country. So, on
Thursday, when he granted his first 30-day reprieve to a death-row
inmate, the political world took note: was it an instance of a man
running as a compassionate conservative trying to advertise his
charitable nature?
</P>
<P>
   Matters of life and death can become embroiled in the theater of
politics. Eight years ago, a presidential candidate who also
happened to be a governor made a special trip back to his home
state of Arkansas to be on hand for an execution, an act viewed in
political circles as a demonstration of a moderate Democrat's
tough-on-crime credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides insisted there was nothing political about their
candidate's decision, which paved the way for DNA tests to be
administered to try to clarify the condemned man's guilt or
innocence in a case of rape and murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an opportunity to get more information now from that
test,'' said Karen P. Hughes, a spokesman for Bush. ``So he feels
it's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   With the candidates' daily rollout of positions on all sorts of
pressing issues _ last week Bush and Vice President Al Gore offered
their takes on, among other things, mental health care, cancer
treatment and land conservation _ voters can be forgiven for
forgetting that the politicians still hold important day jobs that
can change lives.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the ceremonial aspects of their offices meld with the
oratorical requirements of their campaigns, as they did for Gore on
Monday, when he addressed a Memorial Day commemoration in
Pennsylvania. Noting his own military service, which included a
five-month stint in Vietnam as an Army reporter, Gore said, ``I
know that my service doesn't in any way match that of the heroes we
honor on this day.'' One of the more unusual aspects of the speech,
delivered in a week in which polls showed the presidential contest
to be neck-and-neck: not a single mention of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   The Physicist and the Wrapper &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like poets who find inspiration on the kitchen table or back
porch, physicists are rediscovering the world they can see with the
unaided eye. The trend began at least a decade ago when they began
pondering why Brazil nuts, the largest and heaviest nuggets in a
can of mixed nuts, always end up on top after being jostled during
shipping.
</P>
<P>
   The movement may have found its Ferlinghetti in Dr. Eric Kramer,
a physicist at Simon's Rock College in Massachusetts, who presented
experiments to explain that plague upon opera, theater and serious
music: the maddening, inescapable crackling of candy wrappers.
</P>
<P>
   After analyzing the sound, Kramer and a colleague discovered
that it was not a continuous rustle but a series of brief,
unpredictable bursts just thousandths of a second long. As
theatergoers may already suspect, opening a wrapper slowly does not
quiet those bursts but only slows down the rate at which they go
off. Each snap, Kramer found, is the product of a tiny
rearrangement of one of the creases in the wrapper.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamics of those innumerable little rearrangements is
complex enough to keep any physicist happy. But like the Brazil nut
phenomenon, which was found to be caused by a subtle circulation in
the can, the candy wrapper research may be most interesting as
another step in the journey of physicists back from the minuscule
scale of the atom and the gigantic scale of the cosmos. Like
Ferlinghetti, they are rediscovering the mysteries of the here and
now.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES GLANZ
</P>
<P>
   Arrests in Slaying of Five At a Fast-Food Restaurant  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As families buried the dead, two men were arrested and charged
with the killings of five people who were herded into the basement
of a Wendy's restaurant in New York City. . Two others were
wounded. A prosecutor described how the victims were bound, gagged
and blindfolded with duct tape, their heads covered with plastic
bags, and shot one by one as they knelt in a freezer room. The
suspects, John B. Taylor, 36, and Craig Godineaux, 30, could face
the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JANE FRITSCH
</P>
<P>
   Closer to Going Home  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a decision that caused several people in Miami's Little
Havana to sink to their knees in despair, a federal appellate panel
upheld the right of immigration officials to deny 6-year-old Elian
Gonzalez a political asylum hearing. It was one more hurdle, but
not the last, in Juan Miguel Gonzalez's legal fight to return his
son to Cuba. Lawyers for Elian's Miami relatives are expected to
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICK BRAGG
</P>
<P>
   A Cheap, Long-Distance Call  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Resolving years of wrangling between the nation's largest
telephone companies, the federal government reached agreement on a
new rate structure that will sharply reduce bills for the poorest
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with the Federal Communications Commission, the
largest rate reduction in the agency's history, also cuts access
charges that the long distance companies pay local Bell companies;
the savings, if passed on to consumers, should help lower bills.
The changes could lead to a flat rate for long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEPHEN LABATON
</P>
<P>
   A Statement, Not Fashion
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of 2 of the 11 women legislators at the opening of
Iran's new Parliament, the first dominated by reformers since the
1979 Islamic revolution, signaled a change. Elaheh Koulai from
Tehran and Tahreh Rezazadeh from Shiraz chose not to wear the
chador, the head-to-toe black covering that has been an Iranian
symbol for two decades. More reformist chic than radical, they wore
long shapeless coats and pinned their black scarves tightly under
their chins so no hair showed, which the law requires.
</P>
<P>
   The reformers' plans include increasing press freedom and
creating a more prosperous economy for an overwhelmingly young
population. The women's dress, though, stirred hope that the new
Parliament may indeed ease religious restrictions that have
dominated social life for a generation.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NAZILA FATHI
</P>
<P>
   Spy and Entrepreneur  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said he did nothing to betray the country he adopted decades
ago, but Cuban-born Mariano Faget, a high-ranking supervisor in the
Miami office of the Immigration and Naturalization Service, is
facing five years in prison after being convicted on espionage
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Faget was found guilty of disclosing classified information,
converting it for his own gain, lying to the Federal Bureau of
Investigation and failing to reveal foreign business contacts on
federal documents. He is involved in a company planning to do
business in Cuba when the U.S. embargo is lifted.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICK BRAGG
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   House Arrest  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He can only communicate in his childhood language of Javanese.
He can only comprehend short sentences. And when he speaks, he
sometimes strays from the subject at hand. This, according to his
lawyers, is the mental state of former President Suharto of
Indonesia after a series of strokes.
</P>
<P>
   But, they say, he was alert enough for one more indignity: the
government placed him under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SETH MYDANS
</P>
<P>
   A Question of $70,000  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A psychiatrist discharged from the Air Force after announcing
that he was gay filed a lawsuit challenging a demand that he
reimburse the government for the cost of his education: more than
$70,000. Dr. John Hensala said he did not know he was homosexual in
1986 when he joined a Pentagon program that paid for a medical
degree from Northwestern University. In return, he was to serve
four years in the Air Force. But seven months before he was to
begin active duty, Hensala told the Defense Department that he was
gay. The Air Force said he did so to avoid serving.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JANE FRITSCH
</P>
<P>
   An End to Privacy
</P>
<P>
   For more than 2,000 adoptees in Oregon who have applied to see
their original birth certificates, the long wait is about to end.
U.S. Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor refused a request by
a group of birth mothers to block a law passed by the state's
voters in 1998 granting any adopted adult access to the birth
records. The birth mothers had argued that the nation's first such
voter-approved law was an unconscionable privacy violation, but
adoptees said they have an even more basic right to try to discover
where they came from _ and what their biological parents' medical
histories might be.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK
</P>
<P>
   Record Outs  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Randy Velarde, the Oakland Athletics' second baseman, became the
11th player in major league baseball history to turn in an
unassisted triple play. With none out and runners on first and
second, the Athletics' opponents, the Yankees, tried a double
steal. Velarde went to cover second base. Shane Spencer hit a line
drive up the middle right to Velarde, who tagged out Jorge Posada
as he ran from first and then stepped on second base to force out
Tino Martinez. Three outs in less than three seconds. ``You have a
better chance of getting struck by lightning,'' Velarde said
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALAN SCHWARZ
</P>
<P>
   Women's Vulnerability  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pervasive abuse of women is compounding AIDS in some of the
poorest countries of southern Africa and South Asia, a Unicef
survey reported. The study suggests that between a fifth and a half
of women and girls around the world may suffer abuse during their
lives, from their birth to battering later in life. Unable to
resist sexual advances by family members, girls and women become
vulnerable to disease, including AIDS, which is now infecting more
women than men in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3224 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-ROGUE-DEMOCRACIES-R     06-05 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ROGUE-DEMOCRACIES-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating) 
 UNITED NATIONS: be less.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the problem of a different kind of rogue: The
electoral democracy whose human rights record or foreign policies
fall short of international standards but don't raise eyebrows. The
contrast between attitudes in America toward India and Pakistan is
instructive, one that human rights organizations often point to.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's annual international human rights survey
is very critical of India for its treatment of women, minorities
and people declared ``untouchable'' by the Hindu majority. In the
disputed territory of Kashmir, which is under Indian military
occupation, the report found significant abuses of the local Muslim
population. Moreover, American officials say that India has only
narrowly escaped being placed on the list of terrorist nations for
its backing of unrest in neighboring nations, including bombings
and perhaps assassinations in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   But at Human Rights Watch in New York, Kenneth Roth, the
executive director, said that Americans often overlook the record
because most of India's governments have been freely elected, while
neighboring Pakistan gets much closer scrutiny, having lurched in
and out of military rule. ``India has many attributes of a
democracy,'' said Roth. ``But it's too facile to embrace India as a
democracy without recognizing the flawed nature of its political
system when it comes to marginal populations or perceived security
threats.''
</P>
<P>
   Ram Narayan Kumar, an Indian human rights leader, worries about
the precedent. ``Around India,'' he said, ``the lesson other
countries there will learn is that you just have to appear to be
democratic.''
</P>
<P>
   Examples matter everywhere, said John Hirsch, a former U.S.
ambassador to Sierra Leone who is vice president of the
International Peace Academy, a research organization with close
ties to the United Nations. In Africa, he said, the two countries
in which to hope for continued success are Nigeria and South
Africa, both of which held open elections last year.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Joseph Smith, a political science professor at the
University of Virginia, said that strong democracies ``haven't
given enough thought to maintenance and sustaining of democracy.''
In the case of Peru, he added, the United States could have given
stronger support to the Organization of American States. Instead,
the Clinton administration first endorsed, then backed away from,
an unusually bold OAS judgment that the election was flawed. Smith
and Craner said that was a bad message to send to Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to mobilize the multilateral organizations to a far
greater extent,'' Smith said. ``Democracy needs constant
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
