<HEADER>
A4725 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-PRIVACY-ISSUE-REVIE     06-05 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-PRIVACY-ISSUE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HIDDEN ISSUE EMERGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating) (The Week in Review) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A hot new issue is lurking just below the political
radar, ready to explode onto the American electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tests off the charts!'' said Neil Newhouse, a Republican
pollster.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Penn, President Clinton's pollster, said, ``Everybody's
seen it in their surveys _ it's pretty hard to miss. It's a pretty
powerful groundswell.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., who held three hearings on the
subject last week, gushed, ``Boy, you prompt it with just a couple
words and you're going to get a torrent of responses from people.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is privacy. It encompasses far more than peeping toms,
or even hackers invading Web sites or intercepting cell phone
conversations. Not only are people frightened that information
about their personal peccadillos could turn up in hostile hands,
but also that thieves could cash in on their financial data.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, people confess to pollsters, they are suspicious
of companies that have access to their financial and health care
records, and are frightened that the information will be used
against them. They are no less wary of what the government could do
with such data.
</P>
<P>
   To many voters, that their movements and activities are being
tracked on the Internet _ perhaps even by their bosses _ may not
pose a direct danger. But the very idea of it is, well, creepy.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting an opportunity, Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George
W. Bush have begun speaking out about protecting the dissemination
of private information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, there is greater protection for your video rental
receipts than for your most intimate medical information,'' Gore
said in a speech at New York University two weeks ago. ``I've seen
cases where people's prescription drug histories are sold freely to
direct mail companies without their permission; where hundreds of
employees at an HMO have access to patients' records.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bush offered a nod, telling Business Week recently, ``I'm a
privacy-rights person. The marketplace can function without
sacrificing the privacy of individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, privacy seems like a sure-fire political issue: it
touches day-to-day anxieties triggered when people are asked to
divulge their credit card number over the telephone or when they
retrieve cash from an ATM machine. It is always a draw for press
coverage. And as Internet use burgeons, so will fears.
</P>
<P>
   But politicians face a challenge to convert privacy from being a
subliminal worry to something that will actually affect how people
vote. Complicating that challenge is that privacy is not, at first
glance, a matter that would drive voters to one party or another.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have been the most aggressive in vying for the privacy
niche. They are framing it as a tension between civil libertarians
and consumers on one side and big business on the other. Already,
in the House, Democrats have zeroed in on a vote taken last July,
in which most Republicans opposed instituting rigorous privacy
protection for customers' medical and financial records.
</P>
<P>
   Although privacy comes up less in political discourse among
Republicans, they argue that it would not be out of character for
them to seize the issue. After all, libertarians have always been
big on privacy. And Republicans were the most outspoken in
condemning the Census Bureau's long form, asserting that it was an
infringement on privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a hill that nobody holds, and either party could seize
the ground,'' said Mark Mellman, a Democratic pollster who for
months has been using flip charts to persuade his clients that
privacy ``is a huge issue waiting'' for someone to grab. ``The
issue of privacy is very much in the place that health care was a
decade or so ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that either party could potentially become
identified with privacy, Newhouse said the competition will be over
who ``can be there first and strongest and be the noisiest on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a Gallup poll in March asked who would better handle
protecting ordinary Americans against invasions of privacy. Gore
drew 41 percent; Bush, 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy may be so potentially hot that some candidates did not
want to publicly admit that they were husbanding the issue for
their fall arsenals. Who wants to tip off a rival to a fresh line
of attack?
</P>
<P>
   ``My campaigns are reluctant about showing leg early on this,''
said Jim Jordan, political director of the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But candidates who face primary opponents do not have the luxury
of holding off. Last week, former Rep. Maria Cantwell, who is
running for the Democratic Senate nomination from Washington state,
began broadcasting a television commercial on privacy. Cantwell,
who lost her seat after one term in the Gingrich revolution of
1994, went on to make between $25 million and $50 million in the
Internet business.
</P>
<P>
   Peering into the camera, Cantwell says in the 30-second spot:
``What you do on your own computer should be your business and
nobody else's. I want to make sure no child is left behind and that
the Internet remains a tool for learning, not another way for
government, banks or insurance companies to invade your privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of another Democrat, Mike Ciresi, a trial lawyer
who is seeking the Senate nomination from Minnesota, last week
swamped potential supporters with thousands of glossy brochures
featuring the headline, ``Mike Ciresi Will Protect Your Privacy!''
'
</P>
<P>
   When voters are asked what concerns them most, they seldom cite
privacy right off the bat. Yet pollsters find that when voters are
probed about issues that affect their lives, privacy shoots to the
top _ or close to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``God gave me a couple of ears _ I just listen to people,'' said
Brian Schweitzer, a peppermint farmer and soil scientist from
Whitefish, Mont., who is running for the U.S. Senate. ``Everywhere
I go in Montana people want to protect their privacy. It's huge!''
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer, a Democrat who hopes to oust Sen. Conrad Burns,
accused the Republican incumbent of co-sponsoring a bill that
``would force the individual consumer to contact corporate America
and beg them not to collate and sell your personal information.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Burns insisted that Schweitzer ``mischaracterized
the legislation'' and was simply ``trying to get his name in the
paper.'' He is just as committed, he said, to guarding people's
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows whether this issue will truly rouse voters in the
fall of 2000 to the same extent as health care and education. After
all, even after the tax revolt of 1978 in California, it took years
for cutting taxes to become a winning issue nationally. And despite
stirrings about smog and dirty water in the 1970s, the environment
did not emerge as a top-of-the-mind concern of American voters
until years later.
</P>
<P>
   The other challenge facing both sides is that there are no easy
remedies for protecting privacy. Even if consumers clamor about
their rights, no politician wants to be seen taking steps that
could hobble the new economy _ or provoke the Internet industry,
which has become increasingly generous in doling out contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates should also be mindful that there can be unintended
consequences when they try to capitalize on a new issue.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists for Rep. Debbie Stabenow, D-Mich., said that in
their drive to topple the incumbent Republican, Sen. Spencer
Abraham, they plan to castigate him as siding with big business _
and against consumers _ on privacy matters.
</P>
<P>
   But Abraham shot back that he intends to play up that his
campaign has an ``Internet privacy policy on our Web site _ and she
doesn't even have one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be interesting for Congresswoman Stabenow to make
that an issue,'' he said. ``We're explicit. We will protect the
privacy of people who log on to our Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
