<SLUG> BC-R-BESTSELLERS-PAPER-S-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, June 11)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending May 27 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. HANNIBAL, by Thomas Harris. (Dell, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Seven years after his escape, the fiendish
</P>
<P>
   psychiatrist Hannibal Lecter is still at large.
</P>
<P>
   2. RIVER'S END, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a glamorous Hollywood couple
</P>
<P>
   must cope with her family's horrifying past.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE BLUEST EYE, by Toni Morrison. (Plume, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of an 11-year-old black girl _ pregnant by
</P>
<P>
   her father _ who prays for blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE SAVING GRACES, by Patricia Gaffney. (HarperTorch,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) The close friendship that binds four women is
</P>
<P>
   put to the test.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE KILLING GAME, by Iris Johansen. (Bantam,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) A forensic sculptor hopes to find her
</P>
<P>
   murdered daughter's remains.
</P>
<P>
   6. WE'LL MEET AGAIN, by Mary Higgins Clark. (Pocket,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A woman tries to free herself of people's
</P>
<P>
   suspicion that she murdered her husband.
</P>
<P>
   7. WHILE I WAS GONE, by Sue Miller. (Ballantine, $12.95.)
</P>
<P>
   A small-town veterinarian, the wife of a minister, begins
</P>
<P>
   a flirtation with an old friend from her bohemian past.
</P>
<P>
   8. WHERE THE HEART IS, by Billie Letts. (Warner, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A pregnant teen-ager finds help and caring in a small
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma town.
</P>
<P>
   9. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE, by J.K.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling. (Scholastic, $5.99.) A British boy, neglected
</P>
<P>
   by his relatives, finds his fortune attending a school
</P>
<P>
   for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   10. LAKE NEWS, by Barbara Delinsky. (Pocket Star, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   To escape a scandal in the big city, a singer flees to
</P>
<P>
   her seemingly idyllic hometown.
</P>
<P>
   11. BLACK FRIDAY, by James Patterson. (Warner
</P>
<P>
   Vision, $6.99.) A secret militia lays siege
</P>
<P>
   to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) THE TESTAMENT, by John Grisham. (Island, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A reclusive billionaire, a burned-out lawyer and
</P>
<P>
   a missionary are brought together by a startling
</P>
<P>
   secret.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE RIGHT HAND OF EVIL, by John Saul. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) When a family moves into its ancestral home,
</P>
<P>
   terrible secrets begin to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   14. THE GIRLS' GUIDE TO HUNTING AND FISHING, by
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Bank. (Penguin, $12.95.) The progress of
</P>
<P>
   a young New York woman through the terrain of
</P>
<P>
   sex and love.
</P>
<P>
   15. SERPENT, by Clive Cussler with Paul Kemprecos.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $7.99.) The Andrea Doria's remains yield
</P>
<P>
   treasures that point to a deadly conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.) The
</P>
<P>
   story of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a single
</P>
<P>
   crew.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. GIRL, INTERRUPTED, by Susanna Kaysen. (Vintage, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A memoir of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   4. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography of a man
</P>
<P>
   who survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   5.(x) ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer recalls his
</P>
<P>
   childhood amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE LEXUS AND THE OLIVE TREE, by Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   (Anchor, $15.) A journalist explains the instant
</P>
<P>
   electronic global economy.
</P>
<P>
   7.(x) THE ELEGANT UNIVERSE, by Brian Greene. (Vintage,
</P>
<P>
   $15.) A presentation of superstring theory, which
</P>
<P>
   is an attempt to mediate between quantum mechanics and
</P>
<P>
   general relativity.
</P>
<P>
   8.(x) THE LOST BOY, by Dave Pelzer. (Health
</P>
<P>
   Communications, $10.95.) The author of ``A Child
</P>
<P>
   Called `It''' recalls his life in foster homes. (b)
</P>
<P>
   9.(x) BELLA TUSCANY, by Frances Mayes. (Broadway, $15.)
</P>
<P>
   An American remembers a spring and summer spent in the
</P>
<P>
   romantic sections of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   10. RAISING CAIN, by Dan Kindlon and Michael Thompson
</P>
<P>
   with Teresa Barker. (Living Planet/Ballantine, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   The emotional life of boys.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) EVERY MAN A TIGER, by Tom Clancy with Chuck Horner.
</P>
<P>
   (Berkley, $16.95.) The novelist and a retired Air Force
</P>
<P>
   general examine the Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) ENCORE PROVENCE, by Peter Mayle. (Vintage, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   Further adventures in the south of France.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance
</P>
<P>
   to geographical advantages. (b)
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   Hiking the Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $13.) How a murderer helped James
</P>
<P>
   Murray compile the Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) THE FIRST WORLD WAR, by John Keegan. (Vintage, $16.)
</P>
<P>
   A historian recounts the 1914-18 conflict from the viewpoint
</P>
<P>
   of the strategists and the men in the trenches.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE TEENAGE SOUL III, compiled by
</P>
<P>
   Jack Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen and Kimberly Kirberger.
</P>
<P>
   (Health Communications, $12.95.) Inspirational stories. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. THE WORST-CASE SCENARIO SURVIVAL HANDBOOK, by Joshua
</P>
<P>
   Piven and David Borgenicht. (Chronicle, $14.95.) Coping with
</P>
<P>
   life's nasty surprises, from quicksand to killer bees.
</P>
<P>
   3. RICH DAD, POOR DAD, by Robert T. Kiyosaki with Sharon
</P>
<P>
   L. Lechter. (Warner, $15.95.) Teaching one's children
</P>
<P>
   how to get rich and stay rich.
</P>
<P>
   4. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by Robert C. Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   (Avon, $14 and $6.99.) A physician recommends ways
</P>
<P>
   to lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
</TEXT>
