<HEADLINE>
DAZZLE DAD WITH GIFTS THAT DON'T GROW ON TIE RACKS
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 ART ADV: An illustration of a father fleeing from ties is available
by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By MARY LOFTUS 
 c.2000 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, I'll be brief. To the point. No frills.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 things to get dad for Father's Day that aren't
sappy, silly or sentimental. Because, when you get past the
hand-drawn card or the goofy tie, dads want stuff that's practical.
</P>
<P>
   They want presents that, just like good children, work hard,
don't cost much and do what they're supposed to do. And after the
ambiguity of parenthood, it might be nice to have something with a
lifetime guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   1. The Sapphire Lifetime Light ($20, Herrington, 800-903-2878).
A tiny but brilliant LED flashlight that clips to key ring, coat or
briefcase, and gives a full 180 degrees of illumination instead of
a narrow slice of light. The beam projects up to a mile, lasts for
more than 100,000 hours of use and comes with a lifetime guarantee.
It is shockproof and waterproof, and comes in burgundy, blue,
black, silver, gold, violet or green. You can gold-plate it for $10
more.
</P>
<P>
   2. The Timex Expedition pocket watch ($17, campmor.com,
888-226-7667). A water-resistant pocket watch with caribiner clip
that can attach to backpack, golf bag or belt. Can be used while
jogging, hiking, beach-combing or during sports. Hands are
luminescent, and it has large, easy-to-read numbers.
</P>
<P>
   3. An all-inclusive gift certificate with a theme: a weekend at
a beach condo wrapped in a deluxe beach towel with sunscreen,
baseball cap and Beach Boys CD; a car detailing inside a leather
map holder with a key chain and a dual cigarette power adapter; a
golfing day on the greens with new balls, shirt and tees.
</P>
<P>
   4. The Sony SkyMap GPS 2000 navigational system ($199, Best
Buy). Plug it into your laptop and the car's cigarette lighter, and
you can find your way around anywhere. Comes with a free year of
live traffic reports, for dads who hate traffic jams and asking for
directions.
</P>
<P>
   5. Simmons full-sized binoculars ($77, www.netique.com) feature
focus-free viewing, with a 367-foot field of view at 1,000 yards.
Fully coated lenses and leatherette fanny pack included. Great for
bird-watching while hiking, or seeing Cirque du Soleil from the
back rows.
</P>
<P>
   6. An online gift certificate from Barnes &AMP; Noble
(www.barnesandnoble.com) or Amazon.com (www.amazon.com). You can
send, browse and spend online, and your dad can pick the book he
wants, although you could give him some tips: ``Dave Barry Turns
50'' by Dave Barry himself ($15); ``Big Fish: A Novel of Mythic
Proportions,'' by Daniel Wallace ($18); ``Messages from My
Father,'' by Calvin Trillin ($8); ``Fathers and Sons: An
Anthology,'' by Alberto Manguel ($13); ``The Complete Illustrated
Guide to Everything Sold at Hardware Stores,'' by Steve Ettlinger
($15); ``The Fred Book,'' by Fred Imus ($11.)
</P>
<P>
   7. A Skil rechargeable, cordless screwdriver ($19, The Home
Depot). Handy for home repairs and shop projects. Does all the work
without stripping the screw. Comes with a plug-in recharger and
changeable bits, for Phillips or flathead.
</P>
<P>
   8. A subscription to a magazine, from the trendy Men's Journal
($10/10 issues, MensJournal.com) to Men's Health ($25 per year,
www.menshealth.com) to the digital Wired ($15 per year,
www.wired.com), to the top weekly news mags, Newsweek ($41 per
year, 1-800-631-1040) and Time ($67 per year, 1-800-843-TIME). Or
he may enjoy browsing Smithsonian magazine ($26 per year,
www.smithsonianmag.si.edu).
</P>
<P>
   9. Handyman for a day. Find a reputable fix-it-all tradesman in
your area and make up a short list of home improvements that dad
has been putting off all year. Pay by the job, and tell him to get
as far as he can in a day. Give him a bonus if dad wants to help.
</P>
<P>
   10. OK, this is a little bit sentimental: eBay auctions
(www.ebay.com) has a feature where you can plug in key words and
they'll let you know when related items become available, from a
picture postcard of the town where your dad grew up to a souvenir
ticket stub from the World Series. Just plug in key words then bid.
You'll be sure to get a few personalized items that are a custom
fit.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary Loftus writes for the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
