<SLUG> BC-LIGHTHOUSE-ROMANCE-LIFEBEAT-1500&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERNIGHT STAY AT A LIGHTHOUSE IS ANYTHING BUT ROCKY
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 ART ADV: Photo of East Brother Lighthouse available in JPEG format
by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355. 
 By KEN MCALPINE 
 c. 2000 Ken McAlpine. 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<TEXT>
<P>
   We stand, my wife Kathy and I, by the white picket fence marking
the rocky edge of East Brother Island. Close at hand, ghostly sea
gulls glide silently and a foghorn moans. Thirteen miles away, the
lights of San Francisco flicker. A light breeze carrying the scent
of tide, brings just enough damp to force Kathy to press into me,
and for this I am grateful. Above us, from atop the main house
where we have just finished a gourmet dinner, East Brother Light
Station swings its beam over a dark carpet of night-still water.
</P>
<P>
   Lighthouses lend themselves to many things. One of them is a
silence in which you might hear your wife's innermost desires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm wondering,'' says Kathy. ``Maybe I should have asked for
the recipe for the fudge cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Good news is you can stay at the East Brother Light Station, and
assorted other lighthouses scattered about the country, indulging
in the romance you imagine.
</P>
<P>
   The days of the lightkeepers have receded into the past. At the
turn of the century there were about 1,000 lighthouses in the
United States manned by hardy folk unafraid of solitude and foul
weather. Of the 600-some lighthouses still operating today, only
one manned station remains (Boston Harbor Light _ the rest are
automated). But at a select few windswept locales, the keepers'
homes have been refurbished and reinvented to elevate solitude,
foul weather (if you're lucky) and languorous idyll to romantic
art.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight guests arrive at East Brother Island just past 4 p.m.
and depart at 11 the next morning. To people whose credo is ``seize
the day,'' it might seem wantonly indulgent to spend hours occupied
with nothing but eating, reading and gazing out at wind-beaten
waters. Nevermind. Letting the rest of the world seize the day
while we stepped off and into each other's arms sounded great to
us.
</P>
<P>
   And it sounded smarter still when Captain Gary met us that
afternoon at the San Pablo Yacht Harbor dock to whisk us, four
couples in all, by small outboard, the 10 minutes to East Brother
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Before we set foot in the boat, he made our responsibilities
clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three rules on the island,'' he said. ``Don't make the
cook mad, don't make the captain mad, and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   I liked Captain Gary. He and his wife Ann are the innkeepers at
East Brother Light. During our overnight stay, Ann would wield
spices and seasonings to fashion miracles, including broccoli
George Bush would weep for. For his part, Captain Gary displayed a
vast knowledge of lighthouses, wore numerous jaunty caps and
sported a mischievous manner that led me to believe he'd ignored a
few rules of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, we had more responsibilities than Captain Gary
outlined. Arriving at East Brother Island, we were greeted by Ann,
shown to our rooms, and presented with a tidy one-page schedule
indicating that in short order we were expected in the upstairs
parlor of the main house for champagne and French brie.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy and I were in the separate Fog Signal Building, in a small
room tucked just off from a maze of pipes and machinery which we
would soon see was in fine working order. (Four larger rooms are
located in the main house, which is topped by the light station).
Our room was just big enough for a sink, brass bed and well-stocked
bookshelf. But it was ship-cabin cozy, with white linens, the sweet
smell of wood and windows that looked out to the water and the
skyline of San Francisco turning pink-hued in the falling dark.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as we were alone, Kathy scanned our itinerary, quickly
assessing what was required of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd better not fill up on hors d'oeuvres. They're serving
Cornish game hen and chocolate fudge cake for dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   There would be little opportunity to walk any of this off.
Plunked at the juncture of the San Pablo and San Francisco bays,
East Brother Island is a but three-quarters of an acre of rock.
This provides just enough terra firma for two small, low-slung
buildings (our Fog Signal Building and Gary and Ann's
flower-fronted quarters), and, at the island's center, a concrete
hummock that marks the cistern. (The island's water supply comes
solely from gathered rain, so showers aren't allowed for guests who
stay just one night.)
</P>
<P>
   Rising above this, painstakingly resurrected from the mists of
the past, is the main house, a stately, four-story Victorian
mansion, beige with white gingerbread trim, capped with the light
tower that first winked to life over 100 years earlier. Island and
structures are all ringed by a hand-cut white picket fence,
overhung by wheeling gulls, and scoured by salt breezes. It's as if
someone touched a wand to nautical nostalgia and brought it to
life.
</P>
<P>
   In the upstairs parlor of the main house we shared hors
d'oeuvres with the four other couples staying the night. They were
friendly, in their early thirties to mid-fifties, mostly from
California _ computer programmers, business owners, educators and
engineers _ looking to celebrate something special or nothing at
all. Judging from a guest book I browsed through later, ours was a
representative group, though other guests have endured more.
(``It's day three,'' wrote one visitor, marooned on the island by a
storm, ``and we're almost out of wine!'').
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on soft couches and gleaming dark wood chairs,
wood-stove warmed and fortified with red-pepper-and-green-olive
hummus, we listened as Captain Gary explained some of the history
of East Brother Light. The house we sat in, he told us, was nearly
identical to the one a string of lightkeepers called home going
back to March 1, 1874, the day the station shot its first warning
beacon over the water.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, the buildings were abandoned by the Coast Guard, then
for 10 years gnawed by the elements to near extinction. However,
the weather-beaten structures were rescued by a non-profit
citizen's group and restored, several hundred volunteers working
for 18 months to re-create each building down to the finest detail.
East Brother Light opened as a bed and breakfast in November, 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The main house we were sitting in, Gary told us, was a bit more
luxurious than the original version the lightkeepers stayed in, but
not much.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know why the house was so nice back then?'' Gary asked.
``They had to entice people to take the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, reading through an interesting history of the Island, I
discovered why. Husbands and wives did live together on East
Brother Island, and now and then they might have found time for
each other. But for the most part they were occupied with danger
(fires and shipwrecks), hardship (on foggy nights they slept _ or
tried to _ 50 yards from a foghorn loud enough to jump start a
hairline on a cue ball) and daily ennui _ repairs, sanding,
painting, record keeping and repairs on those repairs
</P>
<P>
   Looking to capture something beyond workaday life, one couple
cultivated a garden. Another husband and wife, Earl and Lillian
Snodgrass, planted a stand of young trees.
</P>
<P>
   In short, their lives together were a lot like ours.
</P>
<P>
   Before dinner, Gary provided us a brief glimpse of their lives.
We all trooped into the Fog Signal Building, where Gary fired up a
1939 Caterpillar Diesel engine you could eat off of, then moved
quickly about, turning handles and pulling levers to release the
required burst of air.
</P>
<P>
   The diaphone fog signal was no longer used to sound warnings,
but Gary set it off so guests might get a memorable feel for
fog-shrouded nights past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fog signal, is, shall we say, loud,'' said Gary, ushering
us quickly outside so that we might enjoy its full resonance. ``You
can hear it from 23 miles away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What about your neighbors?'' asked Pam Chupka, a young woman
from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``What neighbors?''
</P>
<P>
   There was a short wail, sounding plaintive, lovely and mournful.
This came from the small foghorn that still peeps regularly at
30-second intervals from the other side of the island. What
followed might be approximated if you handed Godzilla a tuba, then
stomped on his foot.
</P>
<P>
   The blast left my ears, but continued to reverberate in my chest
and kneecaps.
</P>
<P>
   Gary smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this was a working diaphone, it sounded every 20 seconds
for as long as it was foggy. That's why the exterior walls of the
house were mortar-lined brick. For insulation. Still, the keepers
didn't get much sleep in the foggy season.''
</P>
<P>
   In short order, our nerves were calmed by a magical four-course
meal accompanied by good conversation, sweet zinfandels and
tinkling silver. Post-dinner, our responsibilities consisted of
holding each other, backdropped by a lullaby of wind and water,
then waking early enough to get at Ann's hot popovers.
</P>
<P>
   That night the diaphone was silent, but still I woke in the
middle of the night, easing out of bed, leaving my softly breathing
wife. Outside the air was warm. I stood beside a row of eucalyptus
trees, watching the dark, swirling currents, happy to be alone
because I knew I wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Earl and Lillian Snodgrass are gone, but the trees they planted
together are tall and sweet-smelling now, tribute to a shared life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIND A LIGHTHOUSE NEAR YOU &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In recent years a handful of lighthouses in North America have
been converted into places where landlubbers might stay,
accommodations ranging from youth hostels, to family bungalows to
romantic, upscale bed and breakfasts. Some shoreline offerings?
</P>
<P>
   _ East Brother Light Station Point Richmond, Calif. 510-233-2385
www.ebls.org
</P>
<P>
   Multi-course gourmet meals, bedrooms with views of the San
Francisco Bay from tiny East Brother Island. Four rooms in the main
house and a small room in the Fog Signal building. Available
Thursday through Sunday. Adults only. $290-$390 per night,
including dinner and breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Keeper's House Isle Au Haut, Maine 207-367-2261
www.keepershouse.com
</P>
<P>
   Guests arrive on this 12-square mile island on Penobscot Bay by
mail boat. Half the island is wilderness area, Acadia National
Park. No phones, no electricity, lighting is by gas light and
kerosene lanterns. Adults only. $280-$319 per night, including all
meals and use of the inn's bikes.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Lighthouse Inn, West Dennis, Mass. 508-398-2244
www.lighthouseinn.com
</P>
<P>
   On Nantucket Sound, accommodations include rooms in the main
house, cottages with fireplaces and Cape Cod-style houses with
guest rooms. Swimming pool, tennis court, kids programs. $98-$172
per night.
</P>
<P>
   _ Big Bay Point Lighthouse, Big Bay Mich. 906-345-9957
www.lighthousebandb.com
</P>
<P>
   This 18-room inn with seven guest rooms and a sauna in the light
tower is in the foothills of the Huron Mountains, offering great
hiking, biking and ski trails. Adults only. $95-$175 per night,
including breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pigeon Point Lighthouse and AYH-Hostel, Pescadero, Calif.
650-879-0633
</P>
<P>
   Fifty miles south of San Francisco, four bungalows by the
cliffside lighthouse provide lodging for up to 50 hostellers.
Bungalows have three male or three female bunk rooms. Separate bunk
rooms may be reserved for families and couples. Shared bathrooms
with hot showers and fully equipped kitchens. $13 (AYH members) to
$16 (non-members) per person, per night (children $6.50).
</P>
<P>
   _ Rose Island Lighthouse, Newport, Rhode Island 401-847-4242
www.roseislandlighthouse.org
</P>
<P>
   This restored turn-of-the-century lighthouse on Rose Island in
Narragansett Bay has two first-floor bedrooms and second floor
keeper's apartment. Families welcome. Neat twist _ guests learn
what it was like to be a lighthouse keeper by doing an hour's worth
of chores a day. You'll raise the flag, record the weather, then
get on to painting, sanding, brass polishing, grass cutting, etc.,
depending on needs and the season.
</P>
<P>
   The keeper's apartment is available Sunday to Sunday. Weekly
rates, $650-$1,200, depending on the season.
</P>
<P>
   For general lighthouse information and more listings, send a
SASE to the United States Lighthouse Society, 244 Kearny St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94108. Or check out www.lighthousedigest.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken McAlpine is a freelance writer based in Ventura, Calif.)
</P>
