<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANHATTAN-RESTAURANTS-LIFEBEAT-390&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATRICAL AND CHIC, 2 RESTAURANTS OFFER A REAL MANHATTAN
EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 ART ADV: Photos of restaurants available in JPEG format by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By CRAIG KELLOGG 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philip Johnson's Brasserie was a chic haunt for late-night
regulars like Andy Warhol and Halston during its heyday in the '60s
and '70s. But by 1995, when it was damaged by fire, the hangout had
become famously tattered. Enter architects Elizabeth Diller and
Ricardo Scofidio _ a pair of professors currently sharing a 1999
MacArthur Foundation ``genius'' award _ for the makeover.
</P>
<P>
   The two began to rethink the room as a slick new East Side
restaurant with white upholstered Saarinen chairs and translucent
green resin tabletops.
</P>
<P>
   Today the streamlined Brasserie resembles nothing so much as the
first-class departure lounge at tomorrow's airport. Under a new
wraparound pearwood ceiling, the barstools wear clear plastic seat
pads filled with yellow medical gel. For the men's and women's rest
rooms, a single trough sink passes coyly through a slot cut in the
common wall, simultaneously serving both sexes. And a row of
flat-screen video monitors above the bar shows live surveillance
snapshots of patrons coming through the front door _ exactly what
you'd expect from a pair of architectural theorists who are
fascinated with the politics of watching and of being watched.
</P>
<P>
   With Manhattan's Brasserie having opened on January 11, 2000,
British lifestyle merchant Sir Terence Conran was not about to be
outdone. Just blocks away, Conran, together with partner Joel
Kissin, has inaugurated the nineteenth in his global portfolio of
signature restaurants (already a collection that includes London's
Bibendum and Bluebird). His new Guastavino's is actually a duo of
eateries, offering formal dining at Club Guastavino upstairs and a
less expensive bar and brasserie below.
</P>
<P>
   Finally redeveloped after decades of tortured planning, the
vaulted space _ built of fireproof tiles in 1914 by the architect
Rafael Guastavino y Esposito _ once arched over a farmers' market
under New York's Queensboro Bridge. Hometown architect Hardy
Holzman Pfeiffer specified repairs to the creamy tile shell and the
floor was paved with matching shades of marble.
</P>
<P>
   Conran's own designers installed a mezzanine that greatly
increases the capacity of the space. Extending under the rustic
granite arch of the bridge foundation, the upper level also
provides two private dining areas with gritty views out to the
roadway's underbelly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING THERE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guastavino and Club Guastavino are located at 409 E. 59th St.
between First and York Avenues in Manhattan. Guastavino is open for
lunch from Monday through Friday, 11:30 a.m. to 2:30 p.m., and for
Saturday and Sunday brunch, from 11:30 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. Dinner is
served from 5:30 pm. For reservations, call (212)980-2455. Club
Guastavino is open for lunch from Tuesday through Saturday, 11:30
a.m. to 2:30 p.m., and for dinner Tuesday through Saturday, from
5:30 p.m. A special brunch menu is served on Saturdays and Sundays.
Call (212)421-6644 for reservations.
</P>
<P>
   The Brasserie is located at 100 E. 53rd St. between Park and
Lexington Avenues. From Monday through Saturday, it's open from 7
a.m. to 1 a.m. (except for a half-hour hiatus between 11 a.m. and
11:30 a.m. during which the restaurant is closed). The Brasserie
serves breakfast, lunch and dinner, and what it calls ``apres
midi'' _ a light, afternoon menu. Sundays, the Brasserie is open
from 7 a.m. to 10 p.m. All menu items are a la carte. Dinner
entrees range in price between $15 and $29. For reservations, call
(212) 751-4840.
</P>
<P>
   (Craig Kellogg writes for ``House Beautiful'' magazine.)
</P>
