<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4767 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-KENYA-TOURISM-CHAOS-C     06-05 2845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENYA-TOURISM-CHAOS-CENTERPIECE-ADV04-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV04 
 THE LAST SAFARI IN KENYA
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Sunday, June 4, or thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following article from The New York Times
Magazine is for use by clients of the ``Centerpiece'' package.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 ART ADV: Photos are available from Lookat Photos agency by
contacting Ashley Woods or Nicole Aeby in Zurich, Switzerland, at
411-291-0470; fax 411-291-0474, or e-mail: mail(at)lookat.ch. 
 By BLAINE HARDEN  
 c.2000 Blaine Harden  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carjackers forced Peter Behr to strip to his underpants. One
kicked him in the face. Another shoved a pistol in his mouth. A
third put a hunting knife to the throat of his 15-year-old son.
After commandeering his Mazda outside a shopping complex in
Nairobi, the carjackers became annoyed. Their hearts had been set
on a Toyota. When they discovered their mistake, they drove it and
its occupants to the outskirts of Kenya's capital and
pistol-whipped Behr and his son, Glen. The robbers then walked
away, leaving the car keys.
</P>
<P>
   The Behrs drove straight to a police station. When the Kenyan
police found out that the Mazda had not been stolen and that its
owner and his son were neither dead nor dying, they said, in
effect, no harm, no foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want to know,'' whispered Behr, 47, a
third-generation Kenyan who retired as a white hunter when going
after big game was banned 23 years ago and is now a safari guide.
``I have been jumped by a leopard, but nothing was as scary as that
day.''
</P>
<P>
   He whispered his hijack story as we were sitting together in his
Land Rover in the middle of a herd of about 60 elephants grazing in
the Masai Mara game reserve. It was dawn. The only noise they made
was when they wrapped their trunks around clumps of dew-drenched
grass, ripping them from the earth. This was background music to
the white hunter's sotto voce story about his adventures with the
Nairobi criminals four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When I visited Peter Behr and his wife, Louise, at Masai Mara
early this year, it seemed as if the animals had come together on
the mile-high equatorial plain and decided to throw a party. Soft
rains had delayed the coming of the dry season. Gazelles chased
each other on the plain. Fat lions slept in the wondrously green
grass. The reserve, just a half hour by air from Nairobi, was all
dressed up for what should have been prime time in the tourist
season. But there was hardly a human around.
</P>
<P>
   During the two nights I spent at Behr's small but splendid camp
beside the Mara River, called Olonana, there were just two tourists
_ and they were there by sheer chance. A tour operator had sent
them to there after their walking safari in another Kenyan game
reserve had been canceled for lack of people.
</P>
<P>
   There is a link, of course, between the lack of paying customers
in paradise and the carjacking that haunts Behr. It's a
canary-in-the-coal-mine connection. The decline of tourism tracks
the decline of nearly everything in Kenya. Kenya was once a
celebrated exception to the rule of misrule in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   When I lived in Nairobi and traveled across the continent as a
reporter in the second half of the 1980s, it was always a relief to
come home. Kenya simply worked better than the rest of black-ruled
Africa. When I returned to Kenya this year after an 11-year
absence, the change was staggering. Roads were in ruins, telephones
barely worked during business hours and the school system was on
the verge of collapse. As a result, Western governments and
investors had turned their backs on the country.
</P>
<P>
   After years of daily flights, Lufthansa and Air France had
halted passenger service. In the 1990s foreign investment fell to a
fifth of previous levels. Major donors, including the United
States, had all but ended aid to the government. The coffee and tea
industries were in decline because of corrupt management that
allowed the state to bleed profits from farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, earnings from tourism, a cornerstone of the
economy and a key source of foreign currency, had slid nearly 40
percent in five years. Half the country's tourist beds had gone
empty since 1997. Kenya lost its dominance in the African safari
trade, according to American travel agents, as many travelers opted
for game-drive vacations in Botswana, South Africa and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? It is one of Africa's most familiar _ and saddest
_ stories since self-rule spread across the continent in the 1960s.
A one-man regime ruined the country to preserve itself. President
Daniel arap Moi, who is in his mid-70s and has been in office for
22 years, ran his country into the ground so that he might have a
few more years in power.
</P>
<P>
   Kenya's fall is especially disturbing because it could easily
have been averted. Moi's government strangled an economy that was
vibrantly alive. It fomented ethnic violence where there was none,
triggering tribal bloodshed during election years. Displaced
Kenyans didn't vote, and Moi won disputed elections in 1992 and
1997. In the process, he crippled a tourist industry that thrived
on the passion of travelers who were enchanted by Kenya and who
went home to spread the word about an African paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Crime, which has been scaring off foreign tourists for years,
has reached a level that alarms many Kenyans. The Standard, a
Kenyan daily, wrote in an editorial this year that residents of
Nairobi ``yearn for the days when they only dreaded nightfall.
These days women are raped in broad daylight, muggings pass
unnoticed, murders are committed with relative impunity, while
carjackings are now the rule rather than the exception.''
</P>
<P>
   When I read that editorial, it struck me as a bit over the top.
But when I walked across Nairobi on a Saturday morning to pick up
an airplane ticket, I wandered into a shootout. That afternoon,
students at the University of Nairobi rioted for the third day
running. What got them started was an attack by ruling-party thugs
on opposition members of Parliament. Kenyan policemen had stood by
and allowed the thugs to beat up the opposition lawmakers. Then the
policemen arrested the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent students from busting up the Norfolk Hotel, which
abuts the university and is the oldest tourist establishment in
Nairobi, security guards with clubs took up positions in front of
the hotel's Lord Delamere Veranda. White tourists retreated to the
hotel bar, where some of them drank tea and tried to concentrate on
books about a gracious Kenya that used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Their preferred diversion was ``Out of Africa,'' Karen Blixen's
memoir of a coffee farm she owned in the 1920s at the foot of the
Ngong Hills. When I moved to Nairobi in 1985, the film version of
``Out of Africa,'' which starred Meryl Streep and won the Oscar for
best movie, had just been shot on location in Kenya. When I
returned this year, another big-budget movie, ``I Dreamed of
Africa,'' starring Kim Basinger, had also just been filmed. It,
too, was based on a memoir about living on a farm in Kenya. But for
security reasons it could not be shot inside the country.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers, most of them white and many with money to burn, have
been part of the economic backbone of Kenya since the turn of the
century. The Swahili word ``safari'' entered popular American usage
after Theodore Roosevelt arrived in 1909 and hired 500 porters to
follow him into the bush with everything from collapsible bathtubs
to cases of Champagne. Soon thereafter, socialites, plutocrats,
maharajas, royalty and movie stars began to parade across Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to understand why. ``You emerged into thousands of
acres of rolling English parkland, a haze of blue lawn rising and
falling to the horizon, untouched by the plow and apparently
uninhabited,'' wrote James Fox in ``White Mischief,'' an account of
upper-class British shenanigans in highland Kenya in the 1920s and
'30s.
</P>
<P>
   In one highland enclave called Happy Valley, not far from
Nairobi, more than a few white settlers succumbed to what became
known as ``the three A's'' _ altitude, alcohol and adultery. By the
1980s, Kenyan entrepreneurs had perfected the high-end safari. They
were helped along by ``Out of Africa,'' which transformed the
upper-crust safari into a booming business that, at its height in
the late '80s and early '90s, brought in about a third of Kenya's
hard-currency earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The ``product,'' as tourist operators call Kenya's natural
offerings, had become an expensive fantasy that was part Happy
Valley, part Hollywood and part Ralph Lauren: balloon rides at dawn
over the wildebeest migration, followed by a Champagne breakfast,
followed by a nap in a tent with a hot shower and flush toilet.
Bush boutiques selling crisp cotton outfits of the sort that Meryl
Streep/Karen Blixen wore when she had a farm in Africa. Nouvelle
cuisine dinners served in candlelit mess tents by Masai waiters
with impossibly high cheekbones. The smell of wood smoke, the
perfume of frangipani and somewhere in the near distance _ the
chance of white mischief.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of fantasy that Peter and Louise Behr were
selling _ or trying to sell _ when I visited them at their camp.
Even though the place was nearly empty, they maintained five-star
standards in the bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is your shampoo, your conditioner and your shower gel,''
said Maurice Tissah, the steward who showed me to my tent on a high
bank above the Mara River. The tent was the size of a pricey hotel
suite in Paris and was done up 1920s style, with new but
old-looking steamer trunks, brass lanterns, a pasha-style pull rope
that turned on the lights and diaphanous folds of mosquito netting
encircling two king-size beds. After I showered with hot water
(using the gel), I sat out on the porch of my tent, watching hippos
gambol in the river.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, during our game drive, Behr told me that the
safari trade was unlikely to survive. He said insecurity had taken
too firm a hold in Kenya for tourism to recover.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when state-sponsored, election-year tribal violence
exploded along the Kenyan coast, the International Monetary Fund
got fed up with Moi. Citing corruption and poor governance, the IMF
suspended its $220 million aid program. Nearly all donor money to
the government has since dried up. Without aid or tourism, Kenya's
economy went dead in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to get the money flowing again, Moi appointed a sworn
enemy, Richard E. Leakey, the famous paleoanthropologist and
conservationist, to head the civil service and clean up corruption
in Kenya. Five years ago, Moi accused Leakey of being a racist, a
colonialist and a foreigner. (Leakey is a third-generation Kenyan.)
Thugs from Moi's ruling party attacked and flogged Leakey, who had
founded an opposition party and was considering a run for the
presidency. And yet last July Moi made Leakey the second most
powerful man in the country. If nothing else, Moi's choice of
Leakey as a corruption-buster was a masterstroke of public
relations.
</P>
<P>
   It intrigued donors, giving Moi's government more credibility
than it has had in a decade. Western diplomats regarded Leakey as
the Kenyan least likely to be played by Moi for a fool. And since
he took over the civil service, there have been impressive
improvements in the way the government keeps track of money and in
the quality of people appointed to run key government agencies,
like the port of Mombasa. Moi also got serious as never before
about luring back tourists.
</P>
<P>
   He named his closest adviser and longtime business associate,
Nicholas Biwott, as minister of tourism, trade and industry. Biwott
is no Leakey. He is tainted by allegations of corruption and has
been accused of involvement in the murder of a rival who, at the
time of his death, happened to be Kenya's foreign minister.
Biwott's appointment suggests that while Moi is more interested
than ever before in reviving tourism, he is not all that keen on
fundamental change in the way his regime does business.
</P>
<P>
   When I arrived in Nairobi, I asked to see Biwott and was ushered
into his office less than 12 hours later. This was a shock. When I
was writing critical stories about Kenya in the late '80s, Biwott
stood on the floor of Parliament and denounced me by name as ``the
well-known girlfriend'' of South African spies. When I telephoned
him then to explain that I was a man, he paused for a long time,
chuckled and said we must get together soon, but refused ever to
see me _ until tourism took a nose dive and Moi told him to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   During more than two hours of conversation, Biwott, a short,
gray, gimlet-eyed man in a bright blue suit, was invariably polite,
even a bit wistful. I didn't have the heart to bring up the
business about the South African spies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we squandered quite a bit,'' he said, referring to
Kenya's lost reputation. ``We need to work with the international
press. It is that negative publicity that has killed us. That is
why I am very, very pleased to receive you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Biwott is the best minister of tourism in 25 years,'' says
Mahmud Jan Mohamed, chairman of the Kenya Tourism Federation and
managing director of Serena Hotels, the largest chain of safari
lodges in East Africa. Still, Biwott has an international
reputation as one of Kenya's most corrupt ministers.
</P>
<P>
   During his 10 years as minister of energy, Biwott was linked in
the Kenyan press with a number of kickback schemes and
noncompetitive contracts awarded to companies in which he had an
interest. Even worse, he became a prime suspect in the 1990 murder
of the Kenyan foreign minister, Robert Ouko. As a result, Moi fired
Biwott and later ordered him arrested. But after a short stint in
jail and a slightly longer stay in the political doghouse, Biwott
returned to the good graces of the president, a fellow member of
the Kalenjin tribe. The murder remains unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   To help Moi win re-election in 1992, Biwott paid Kalenjin youths
to start ethnic clashes with rival tribes, according to testimony
given at a parliamentary inquiry into the violence. The violence
has continued off and on ever since and is a major reason why
tourists have been scared away from Kenya. As Biwott smiled wanly,
I asked him about the charges of corruption, murder and fomenting
violence that terrified tourists. Who was he, I asked, to put a
welcoming face on Kenya?
</P>
<P>
   ``All these perceptions are false,'' he said, without raising
his voice or seeming annoyed. ``I am neither powerful nor corrupt.
I do my work diligently, according to rules and procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked about the apparent conflict of interest involved in his
being in charge of tourism. He owns Air Kenya, an airline that with
the collapse of the road system has become the lifeline of the
safari industry. He also has major interests in a number of tourist
hotels and lodges. ``When we are in government, we don't get
involved in private business,'' he said, his smile tightening.
</P>
<P>
   Although numbers are down, wealthy tourists continue to travel
to Masai Mara. Almost none of them, though, go by car. They fly out
from Nairobi, usually on Biwott's Air Kenya planes, skipping six
spine-crunching hours on bad roads. But they also miss a journey I
regard as one of the marvels of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   From Nairobi, the road climbs 2,000 feet up the Kikuyu
escarpment to where the air has the bracing purity of the Scottish
highlands. The rolling hills are covered with the unearthly Day-Glo
green of ripening tea. Then, quite suddenly, the road comes to what
seems to be the edge of the earth _ the eastern wall of the Great
Rift Valley. Far below, down through the heat rising from the floor
of the valley, dormant volcanoes march off into an impossibly
distant horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Having been away from Kenya for so long, I had forgotten the
country's capacity to inspire wonder. During the long, dusty drive,
I found myself making plans to return to Kenya for a vacation. I
wanted to believe that Biwott and Moi and maybe even Leakey could
somehow work together to reverse Kenya's decline, revive living
standards and make the country safe for tourists. When I got out of
the sun, I got over it.
</P>
<P>
   (Blaine Harden, a reporter for The New York Times, is the author
of ``Africa: Dispatches From a Fragile Continent.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
