<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4769 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-LINDY-BOGGS-VATICAN-C     06-05 2653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINDY-BOGGS-VATICAN-CENTERPIECE-ADV04-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV04 
 LINDY BOGGS IS HAVING HER SAY AT THE SEE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Sunday, June 4, or thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following article from The New York Times
Magazine is for use by clients of the ``Centerpiece'' package.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By MICHAEL LEWIS  
 c.2000 Michael Lewis  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a man with a gift for charming others meets a woman with a
gift for making others feel charming, there is no telling how it
will end. Sometime around Easter of 1997, Bill Clinton called Lindy
Boggs, whom he had known since he was a college student, and asked
her, somewhat improbably, to become his ambassador to the Holy See.
(She ``is maybe the only person on the earth who could convince the
pope that I am worth dealing with,'' Clinton has joked to his
friends.)
</P>
<P>
   Lindy told Clinton she would think about it, but she was only
being polite. Almost as soon as he had made the offer, she had made
up her mind to decline it. She was 82 years old, spoke no Italian
and knew no one in Rome. She intended to end her days as she had
begun them, in private life, in New Orleans. Then she changed her
mind.
</P>
<P>
   As she tells it, she was standing one Sunday morning at the back
of St. Louis Cathedral (which is just down the street from her
home) in front of the chapel dedicated to Our Lady of Prompt
Succor. Our Lady of Prompt Succor is the saint to whom the local
Ursuline nuns prayed on behalf of Andrew Jackson before the Battle
of New Orleans. (After the battle, Jackson went immediately to the
nuns to thank them for the saint's intercession.) Standing before
Our Lady of Prompt Succor, Lindy recalls: ``I thought: Lindy Boggs,
you are a big sissy. If the president asks you to do a job, you
could at least give it a try.''
</P>
<P>
   In Rome these days, you hear so many anecdotes about Boggs that
you have to remind yourself how little time she has had to generate
them. The morning after she arrived to take up the ambassador's
post, she was informed that she was to be seated that night at a
table filled with nothing but cardinals; she mulled that over, then
said, ``I think I'll wear red.''
</P>
<P>
   There was the time Lindy exchanged three phone calls in one day
with an Italian archbishop on some minor piece of Vatican
diplomacy. Picking up the receiver the last time, she said,
``Dahlin', does this mean we're going steady?''
</P>
<P>
   And there was the trip to the hospital after Lindy had fallen in
her driveway and broken her knee. As she was wheeled in, her eyes
lit on a tall, dark Italian surgeon. ``Tell me, doctor,'' she said,
``is it a prerequisite in Italy that all doctors have to be
handsome?''
</P>
<P>
   The woman who passed along this last anecdote happened to work
at the American Embassy at the Holy See. She suggested that if I
wanted to hear more of this sort of thing, I had come to the right
place. Whatever else our ambassador had absorbed in her two and a
half years on the job, she had clearly learned that a woman in her
mid-80s surrounded by men in dresses sworn to vows of celibacy can
say whatever she pleases. ``Is it true that she calls the pope
'Dahlin''?'' I asked. ``You'll have to ask the ambassador that.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time I had seen Lindy Boggs, she was making a
less-than-convincing attempt to leave politics. Her career as an
elected official had just ended, as it began, with a death in her
family. She was elected to Congress in 1973 _ to the seat left
vacant when her husband, Hale Boggs, was lost in a plane crash in
Alaska _ and decided to get out in 1990 to help one of her
daughters, Barbara Sigmund, who was then mayor of Princeton, N.J.,
fight cancer. (Lindy has two other well-known children: Cokie
Roberts, the Washington journalist, and Tommy Boggs, the Washington
lobbyist.)
</P>
<P>
   After the cancer won, Lindy moved back home to the French
Quarter of New Orleans, claimed to be retired, then promptly joined
the boards of just about 600 local charities. At the time, I was
living just around the corner from her on Bourbon Street and
stopped in a few times. One of these visits came the same evening
that a presidential candidate named Bill Clinton was scheduled to
pay Lindy a call. As it happened, it was also the same time the
Gennifer Flowers story was breaking.
</P>
<P>
   The party that night at Lindy's house was a fund-raiser dressed
up as an intimate gathering for a few old friends who might like to
meet an attractive young politician. The decorous hum of a handful
of New Orleans Democrats milling about Lindy's upstairs living room
was punctuated by a riot in the downstairs hallway.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had burst into the house in a blaze of television lights
and a crush of reporters, all of whom wanted to confirm the precise
details of his extramarital sex life. The reporters bayed for
graphic details; Clinton, huge and pink, tried to shove past them
to the party. The situation had spun out of control, when Lindy
appeared at Clinton's side and took him by the arm.
</P>
<P>
   The mob went quiet: it takes some nerve to holler ``oral sex''
in the presence of a septuagenarian. Then Lindy did her usual
trick. She told the reporters how happy she was that they had come
to see her. She offered them refreshments. Refreshments! She might
as well have tried to distract a pack of hounds with a cheese dip _
or so I thought. But suddenly, and inexplicably, the mood in that
hallway changed. The hounds lost the scent, the baying ceased, the
fox grinned and strolled on by.
</P>
<P>
   She is one of those people who seem to have been put on this
earth to undermine attempts to generalize about politicians. During
her two decades as a member of Congress, she was the one person in
Washington it was against the rules not to like and who seemed, for
her part, incapable of disliking others. Richard Nixon and George
McGovern: both dear friends. She adored Jack Kennedy, and he, of
course, adored her. She also adored Lyndon Johnson, and he, of
course, adored her.
</P>
<P>
   When she ceased to be a congressional wife and became a
congresswoman, she said there was only one thing that bothered her
about the new job: she would be forced to vote. How could you vote
without voting against something? In most people, this approach to
public life would seem spineless. In Lindy, it came across like a
glimpse of an alternative, enchanted universe. And as political
strategy it was just plain shrewd.
</P>
<P>
   The Lindy effect seems to be working in Rome, too. For instance,
this year Pope John Paul II has beatified one New Orleanean, the
Rev. Francis Xavier Seelos, and will canonize another, Mother
Katharine Drexel. Up until now, outside of its professional
football team, New Orleans has not been long on saints. In nearly
300 years it has manufactured exactly one.
</P>
<P>
   In this jubilee year, the pope will miraculously increase the
number of sacred people for Lindy's former constituents to pray to.
Perhaps not entirely by coincidence, Lindy, for many years, was on
a church committee in New Orleans that was trying to persuade the
Vatican to beatify Seelos. But when I asked her if her presence had
anything to do with his beatification, she just said: ``Oh,
dahlin', the Vatican makes all those decisions in private. And
Father Seelos was such an easy choice.''
</P>
<P>
   When she said this, we were sitting in her office at the
American Embassy at the Holy See, with its view of the Palatine
Hill. She had spent nearly two hours avoiding an explanation of her
job. It is a strange fact about Lindy Boggs that the two things she
spends most of her time on _ politics and praying _ are the two
things she least cares to discuss. (``Lindy's really from the old
school that has pious faith,'' says the Rev. Christopher Nalty, a
young priest studying at the Vatican who often appears on the
ambassador's arm. ``You didn't really question it, or talk about
it. You just had it.'')
</P>
<P>
   Still, I couldn't help wondering, What does an ambassador to the
Vatican do all day? Actually, that was the wrong question. What
Lindy did with most of her days in Rome had already become clear.
She went to the endless parties and meetings of cardinals and
archbishops and the other ambassadors and invited all the same
people to her own parties and meetings. Wherever she went, five
Italian policemen with machine guns followed.
</P>
<P>
   Her schedule was as merciless as a New Orleans debutante's. Each
day between 10 in the morning and midnight she seemed to pause only
once, briefly, to send a cable or two back to the State Department
in Washington, where it was read by a foreign-service officer whom
Lindy had never met. But how did she fill up all those cables? It
was this that she did not care to discuss. And there is not an
intrusive question in the world for which Lindy Boggs does not have
a charming anecdote with which to defuse it.
</P>
<P>
   Ask her, say, about the jockeying among cardinals to see who
gets to be the next pope, and she'll reply with a funny story of a
lunch she had with Ronald Reagan. ``My mother is uncharmingly
discreet,'' Cokie Roberts says. ``All those years I was a reporter
on Capitol Hill, and she never told me a damn thing.''
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, after a few hours of listening to delightful and
charming stories about former heads of state, it dawned on me.
``The whole point of your job here,'' I said, ``is to avoid
controversy.'' ``Which I have been doing my whole life!''
</P>
<P>
   The Embassy at the Holy See, which Reagan established in 1983,
would seem at first glance to be a textbook case of the Pointless
Embassy. There is almost nothing the United States can do to shape
Vatican policy. Vatican theology, on which much Vatican policy
rests, is officially off limits to the U.S. ambassador. Moreover,
the Vatican may be the least concerned of all nations about what
the United States wants it to do.
</P>
<P>
   When the pope decides to air his opinion that cancer can be
caused by ``certain sexual behavior,'' as he did last year, the
United States does not even bother to try to stop him. To do so
would be worse than pointless. It would risk incurring the wrath of
the one man outside the United States who, with a flick of his
wrist, could wreak havoc with U.S. public opinion. As a result,
much of what constitutes Vatican diplomacy is actually appeasement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the job,'' admits one official at the United States
Embassy at the Vatican, ``is to put the best possible face on the
inevitable.'' But there is something else, too, and it is peculiar
to the Embassy at the Holy See. The information that flows into the
Vatican from missionaries and churches _ perhaps the world's most
elaborate news-gathering network _ is information the State
Department would like to possess. In the darkest days of the
Bosnian war, for example, the Vatican had an intimate view of
affairs in the Balkans. Now it has perhaps the closest thing
available outside Congo and East Timor to the ear-to-the-ground
story on the conflicts inside.
</P>
<P>
   And so the question for the American ambassador becomes: How do
you get people inside the Vatican to tell you things? ``The Vatican
operates much like the U.S. government did right after World War
II,'' Lindy says. ``The difference is that you can't override the
pope's veto.'' What she means by this is that in both places the
protocol is so arcane as to constitute a subject unto itself.
</P>
<P>
   Protocol is the Esperanto of Vatican social life. It operates as
a substitute to local custom and tends to be more elaborate in
places where people have the least culturally in common. Vatican
protocol is by itself of little interest. What is interesting is
the way it is used to mask Vatican politics or, rather, to keep
people out who don't belong. As one well-placed monsignor put it to
me: ``How you communicate here is as important as what you
communicate. Ambassador Boggs seems to know this instinctively.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't until you stop thinking of Lindy as an emissary and
start thinking of her as a seeker of Vatican secrets that you can
see the sense in her social life. Perhaps coincidentally, perhaps
not, she has befriended not merely the upper echelon of Vatican
officials but also other ambassadors. One of her new dear friends
is the Spanish ambassador, who, as the representative of the oldest
embassy at the Vatican, enjoys a privileged access; another is the
German ambassador, who, as it happens, is also privy to a lot of
Vatican gossip.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most surprising fact about Lindy Boggs is that she
can't sleep at night. She spends all day sincerely looking for
little ways to make the world a better place and then spends all
night staring at her ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she was in Congress, she was always tired,'' recalls her
former legislative aide, Jan Schoonmaker. ``I used to schedule
downtime for her because I knew she hadn't slept the night before.
I'd ask her why, and she'd say that she was worrying. Or some
constituent had called at 2 a.m. to ask why he hadn't got his
Social Security check. I'd say, 'Lindy, you need an unlisted phone
number.' And she'd say, 'But dahlin', then people wouldn't know how
to find me at night.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a habit with her still. Our last meeting in Rome coincided
with one of her many dinner parties. The last archbishop had gone,
and she was running a fever, yet she insisted that I hang around.
She had something to show me.
</P>
<P>
   She's worried _ though, of course, she does not come right out
and say it _ that I'm going to depict her as a sweet old lady who
makes a lot of people happy but doesn't really serve any greater
purpose. She handed me a yellow Post-It on which she had scribbled
what she called ``my political interests.'' The list read:
Preservation, National Archives, Holocaust museum, Smithsonian,
Children and Families, NASA. It may be the least controversial list
of political interests ever created, offering only the tiniest
sliver of her view of the world. I asked her about her long record
of voting against abortion rights. ``Oh,'' she said, ``I've always
been for life. But I never would have raised it as a political
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   She still had an expectant air about her; the list wasn't the
thing that she wanted to show me. She grabbed me by the arm and led
me out to the bottom of her marble staircase. There on the banister
rested a plain manila folder. She had placed it there before the
dinner so that it would be at hand afterward. She opened it and
extracted a stack of photographs. The pictures of her first meeting
with the pope, when she presented him with her credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are with the Holy Father,'' she said, as she paged
through them, lovingly, ``you feel you are in the presence of
something. He's just pure ... goodness.'' It was an extraordinarily
detailed sequence. Every move seemed to have been documented.
</P>
<P>
   As I paged through the photographs, Lindy described the ritual
leading up to the papal encounter. When she finished, I realized
she had once again spoken at great length, and had told me
everything but what I wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Lindy,'' I asked, ``what did you and the pope talk
about?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dahlin', that's private!''
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Lewis is a contributing writer for The New York Times
Magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
