<P>
   SEC-KRAMER _ SEC commissioner Roy Kramer turns 71 in October and
shows no signs of slowing down. Since he become commish in 1990,
the SEC has evolved into the most powerful conference in the
nation, routinely competing for national titles. But his biggest
impact is on the bottom line: The schools were dividing $10 million
per year in '90, now they are divvying up $68.5 million. And he has
been a driving force behidn the BCS series to determine the
national football titleist. How much longer can he keep on? It's
time for the SEC to begin taking a look at who will replace him.
(Barnhart, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
