<HEADER>
A4783 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0606-COX     06-05 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: We have been looking
<TEXT>
for a Golden Book titled ``My Snuggly Bunny.'' This was my mother's
favorite book as a little girl. I was hoping to surprise her with
it this Christmas.
<P>
   _ Wendy G.
</P>
<P>
   A: Golden Books, 888 Seventh Ave., New York 10106, has no plans
to reissue this selection. I found a copy online ($18). Check out
www.alibris.com. One of the writers/illustrators of ``My Snuggly
Bunny'' was Patsy Scarry, wife of Richard Scarry. The best-selling
Golden Book? ``Pokey Little Puppy,'' which is also the best-selling
children's hardback book. The Smithsonian even has a copy in its
permanent collection.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our wedding rehearsal dinner was an outdoor affair _
Texas-style. Fun, but many out-of-town guests were covered with
chigger bites the next day. What are chiggers? What works to stop
the itching and encourage healing? Why are some bothered and others
not at all?
</P>
<P>
   _ Muriel B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Chiggers have four stages, reports John Jackman of A&AMP;M's
entomology department: egg, larva, nymph and adult. The larva, a
six-legged critter, is the blood-sucking mite causing the itching.
No one knows why some are chigger magnets while others are not.
Chiggers seem to be attracted by odors, says allergist Dr. Russell
Roby. Vitamin B's odor often repels chiggers and fleas. The most
effective way to avoid them? Cover as much skin as possible
(special attention to areas covered with elastic), avoid fields and
brush, and use insect repellent. Try sulfur in your socks and shoes
or Avon's Skin-so-Soft. Shower after exposure or bathe in water
laced with a tablespoon of bleach. Antihistamines and anesthetics
provide quick temporary relief as does Fels Naptha soap.
Hydrocortisone cream is slow-acting, but longer lasting. For more
information, contact the Allergy Center (338-4336) at
www.allergy-center.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A guest inadvertently put a gold-rimmed dinner plate in the
microwave. The microwave set off sparks from the plate, and the
gold rim was damaged.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa F.
</P>
<P>
   A: You can touch up the paint, but the plate is then only good
for decorative purposes. A plate is fired after it is made, so the
new paint would not last.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My husband works in the manufacturing section of a high-tech
company. Sometimes when they run out of parts and are unable to
work, employees are forced to use vacation time or take the time
off without pay. Is this legal? It seems unfair that the employees
should suffer because somebody did not order enough parts. Also, we
can never plan a vacation because we never know how much time he
will have left due to the company's inefficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   _ M.P.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, this is legal. Texas is an employment at will state.
Generally, vacation and leave policies are matters of negotiation
between employer and employee, remarks Larry Jones of the Texas
Workforce Commission. Texas employers may place conditions on the
use of accrued vacation leave, such as requiring employees to take
it during temporary shutdowns. Why unpaid leave? Under the Federal
Fair Labor Standards Act, an employer is under no obligation to pay
an hourly employee for time not actually worked. By imposing such
conditions, an employer risks employees filing unemployment
insurance benefits claims because of having been laid off for lack
of work.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have several hundred pre-recorded cassettes, 30-45 minutes
per side, most in plastic cases. Is there a nonprofit group that
can use them? I hate to just throw them out.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cindi W.
</P>
<P>
   A: Then don't, because some of my readers would love to have
them. Sounds like a bird's nest on the ground for some lucky group.
Call Wallace at (512) 250-9284.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do so many roads bleed black rivulets _ an eyesore? They
seem to be a recent phenomenon. Has technology recessed?
</P>
<P>
   _ Rasika H.
</P>
<P>
   A: Blame it on the weather and the traffic. When the roadway
surface becomes thin from an overabundance of vehicles, it begins
to bleed, or shell, causing cracks that must be patched. The seal
coat is a thin layer of asphalt, which not only eliminates
shelling, but also prevents water from getting into small roadway
cracks and freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We were on a trip the week CBS presented the miniseries
``Jesus.'' Could you help me get a copy of either the whole series
or the second part?
</P>
<P>
   _ J. Schulz
</P>
<P>
   A: CBS is selling this video, but it is currently back ordered
for four to six weeks. Apparently ``Jesus'' sells faster than Round
Rock doughnuts. Call (888) 227-8881 to order ($29.98 plus shipping
and handling).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a round plastic card holder to fan out
playing cards. It is especially good for games that you play with a
lot of cards, like double deck pinochle (20 cards).
</P>
<P>
   _ Joanne M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Ecologically conscious? Order a plastic one made from
recycled detergent containers from O.N.E. at (530)396-2327 or
online at www.recyclestore.com. Only $2 each, but you must purchase
a minimum of 10 disks.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Every time I tell someone where I live (Shepherd Mountain),
my brother says ``it is really just a hill; there are no mountains
in Texas.'' I say they would call it Shepherd Hill if that were
true. Are these true mountains? How can you tell?
</P>
<P>
   _ H.N.A.
</P>
<P>
   A: Texas is not a mountainless state. Ever heard of West Texas'
Guadalupe Mountains? Guadalupe Peak has the highest elevation in
Texas at 8,751 feet. According to the American Geological
Institute's ``Glossary of Geology,'' generally a mountain will
project at least 1,000 feet above the surrounding land or 2,000
feet above sea level, reports Sigrid Clift of UT's Bureau of
Economic Geology. If a mountain has a distinctive feature that
rises above the surrounding land area with steep sides and a
restricted summit, the moniker fits.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have an old wooden crank telephone (Western Electric, 317P)
inherited from my grandfather. It has all the original equipment,
including the wiring diagram. How can I find out its age and the
best way to care for it? I was thinking of having the case
refinished, but don't want to harm it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cherry K.
</P>
<P>
   A: If the phone is in good condition, use Johnson's Paste Wax to
protect the wood (if you restain, attend to the underside of the
bells). Hard to date it without more data. One, two or three boxes?
Cathedral top or no? You probably have a peaked top from the
1910-1930 period, says Phone Wizard's Bruce Patterson. Contact him
at (504) 822-4730 or phonewizard(at)juno.com about working on the
phone. Patterson can even modernize it without devaluing the piece.
An appraisal? Send photos of the phone to Museum of Independent
Telephony, 412 S. Campbell, Abilene, Kan. 67410. You will be
charged a small fee for research.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We saw a John Wayne movie called ``The Cowboys.'' Was this
the only movie where he died?
</P>
<P>
   _ L.E.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: No, the Duke's character died in eight films, reports the
Birthplace of John Wayne, a museum in Iowa: ``The Shootist,'' ``The
Cowboys,'' ``The Alamo,'' ``Sands of Iwo Jima,'' ``Wake of the Red
Witch,'' ``The Fighting Seabees,'' ``Reap the Wild Wind'' and
``Central Airport.'' Pay attention! This is a list you expect to
see on ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX, 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
