<HEADER>
A4785 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0606-COX     06-05 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: We have been looking
<TEXT>
for a Golden Book titled ``My Snuggly Bunny.'' This was my mother's
favorite book as a little girl. I was hoping to surprise her with
it this Christmas.
<P>
   _ Wendy G.
</P>
<P>
   A: Golden Books, 888 Seventh Ave., New York 10106, has no plans
to reissue this selection. I found a copy online ($18). Check out
www.alibris.com. One of the writers/illustrators of ``My Snuggly
Bunny'' was Patsy Scarry, wife of Richard Scarry. The best-selling
Golden Book? ``Pokey Little Puppy,'' which is also the best-selling
children's hardback book. The Smithsonian even has a copy in its
permanent collection.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our wedding rehearsal dinner was an outdoor affair _
Texas-style. Fun, but many out-of-town guests were covered with
chigger bites the next day. What are chiggers? What works to stop
the itching and encourage healing? Why are some bothered and others
not at all?
</P>
<P>
   _ Muriel B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Chiggers have four stages, reports John Jackman of A&AMP;M's
entomology department: egg, larva, nymph and adult. The larva, a
six-legged critter, is the blood-sucking mite causing the itching.
No one knows why some are chigger magnets while others are not.
Chiggers seem to be attracted by odors, says allergist Dr. Russell
Roby. Vitamin B's odor often repels chiggers and fleas. The most
effective way to avoid them? Cover as much skin as possible
(special attention to areas covered with elastic), avoid fields and
brush, and use insect repellent. Try sulfur in your socks and shoes
or Avon's Skin-so-Soft. Shower after exposure or bathe in water
laced with a tablespoon of bleach. Antihistamines and anesthetics
provide quick temporary relief as does Fels Naptha soap.
Hydrocortisone cream is slow-acting, but longer lasting. For more
information, contact the Allergy Center (338-4336) at
www.allergy-center.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A guest inadvertently put a gold-rimmed dinner plate in the
microwave. The microwave set off sparks from the plate, and the
gold rim was damaged.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa F.
</P>
<P>
   A: You can touch up the paint, but the plate is then only good
for decorative purposes. A plate is fired after it is made, so the
new paint would not last.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My husband works in the manufacturing section of a high-tech
company. Sometimes when they run out of parts and are unable to
work, employees are forced to use vacation time or take the time
off without pay. Is this legal? It seems unfair that the employees
should suffer because somebody did not order enough parts. Also, we
can never plan a vacation because we never know how much time he
will have left due to the company's inefficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   _ M.P.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, this is legal. Texas is an employment at will state.
Generally, vacation and leave policies are matters of negotiation
between employer and employee, remarks Larry Jones of the Texas
Workforce Commission. Texas employers may place conditions on the
use of accrued vacation leave, such as requiring employees to take
it during temporary shutdowns. Why unpaid leave? Under the Federal
Fair Labor Standards Act, an employer is under no obligation to pay
an hourly employee for time not actually worked. By imposing such
conditions, an employer risks employees filing unemployment
insurance benefits claims because of having been laid off for lack
of work.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have several hundred pre-recorded cassettes, 30-45 minutes
per side, most in plastic cases. Is there a nonprofit group that
can use them? I hate to just throw them out.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cindi W.
</P>
<P>
   A: Then don't, because some of my readers would love to have
them. Sounds like a bird's nest on the ground for some lucky group.
Call Wallace at (512) 250-9284.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do so many roads bleed black rivulets _ an eyesore? They
