<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4786 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-CYBERSCENE0606-COX     06-05 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some free stuff offered on the Internet is actually free
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The world is full of free offers. There's the classic
advertising ploy called _ in the trade _ BOGOF (buy one, get one
free). If you leaf through almost any newspaper or magazine you'll
find offers for free subscriptions, free catalogs, free
installation of car stereos _the list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   The magic word ``free'' is also a big deal on the Internet. As
you'd expect, there are dozens of Web sites devoted to bringing you
the opportunity to sign up for almost any kind of free offer you
can imagine. So today, at absolutely no cost to you, we'll look at
some of the sites that guide you to free offers.
</P>
<P>
   Just keep in mind that there is no true free lunch and that many
of these offers may end up charging shipping costs, or be
contingent on you buying something. So let the non-buyer beware.
</P>
<P>
   The first site is called The Original Totally Free Stuff and can
be found at www.totallyfreestuff.com/. The free offers here are
conveniently lumped into categories such as books, clothing,
coupons, audio, educational, e-mail accounts and hardware. One nice
feature of the site is a listing _ always found on the opening page
_ of free offers that have recently been added.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, on a recent visit, there were new offers for a
free mouse pad, a six-month magazine subscription and the seemingly
incredible offer of $75 free. But if you follow the link to sign up
for the free money, you'll learn that, to get it, you have to agree
to sign up for a telephone service and an Internet service. Which
just goes to show that not everything is free, even on a site
called Totally Free.
</P>
<P>
   Volition.com calls itself ``the oldest free stuff site'' on the
Net. It can be found, logically enough, at
www.volition.com/free.html. Just as was true with our first site,
you'll find free offers listed by category. Some of the categories
include home furnishings, credit cards, toys, pet supplies and
family fun.
</P>
<P>
   Just as was true with the first site, not all the free offers
offer free stuff. For instance, here's an offer you'll find at the
site:
</P>
<P>
   ``Receive a free $25 SuperCertificate from GiftCertificates .com
when you are approved for a Discover Platinum Card.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's not enough, you can also sign up for a free online
chat with a psychic.
</P>
<P>
   Next let's stop in at a site called Get-it-for-Free at
www.get-it-for-free.com/. You'll find the now-familiar free
mousepad offer there, too. Among other offers, you can get a free
rubber stamp (you'll pay $2.39 in shipping and handling costs to
get your free stamp); coupons that are said to be worth $100; and
an offer for a free Neopet (you'll have to travel to the site to
find out what a Neopet is).
</P>
<P>
   TheFreeSite.com at www.thefreesite.com/ calls itself ``the best
place to find freebies, freeware, free stuff, samples, games'' and
it does seem _ on casual observation _ to be one of the best of the
bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the offers here include services that offer free e-mail
and free Internet service, free postcards, free games and free MP3
computer audio files.
</P>
<P>
   You may find more legitimately free offers here than on the
other sites. Even so, don't expect to get a free BMW or trip to
Hawaii. But the allure of the free offer _ to those caught in its
trance _ may be more important than the product.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
