<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wireless age to bring new freedoms ... and burdens
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Deb Spicer Tompkins lives in the blur.
</P>
<P>
   There is a blur, she will tell you, where there used to be a
line separating professional and family, private life and public.
But with her cellular phone, pager and wireless digital assistant,
Tompkins often finds herself where there is no line at all.
</P>
<P>
   As managing director of the technology practice at Hill and
Knowlton, a public relations firm, she gets e-mail from clients,
pages from her children, phone calls from co-workers, all the time,
everywhere. ``If you're not careful, it puts you in a perpetual
reactive mode,'' she said. ``Sometimes instead of reducing
information overload, it contributes to information overload.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, the human relationship with technology has always been
two-way. And now, in the wireless revolution, we have combined the
mobility of cars, the reach of phones and the power of computers.
``This is huge,'' said Steve Jones, professor and head of
communication at the University of Illinois at Chicago. ``Wireless
Internet access represents as much of a revolution as the
introduction of the Internet itself.''
</P>
<P>
   To those who grew up in the pre-Net era, the prospects can sound
like an episode of ``The Jetsons.'' Say you're driving to the
theater. The car knows where you are going, sees the time, does a
quick calculation and realizes you are not going to make it on
time. The car calls the theater, then sells the tickets to someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Prial, marketing director for IBM's pervasive computing
unit, says it is hardly a stretch from what can be done now to that
scenario. ``You get to the theater and sure enough, you say, `Darn,
we're late.' And the car says, `No problem. I sold the tickets.'''
</P>
<P>
   The upside of the technology seems clear enough: Employees can
hit the beach without ducking a critical conference call, children
can reach parents from a party gone sour, stranded motorists can
summon a tow truck. The near future is even more alluring: paying
for items before you get to the store, turning on the oven when you
are miles from home, checking in to a flight while still on the way
to the airport _ something Swissair already does in Zurich.
</P>
<P>
   ``And tomorrow, you'll have your electronic boarding pass on
your phone,'' Prial said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many burdens of wireless technology are also hard
to miss. The relentless flood of e-mail and voice mail. The ease
with which a colleague or boss can intrude on your free time. The
annoyance of hearing strangers blithely discussing private business
in public places on their cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Yet work and bad manners are not new, even if we have witnessed
a spate of new technologies. How much of a difference does it make
that we can communicate without wires?
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Net power in the palm of your hand _ for
transactions, for information, for communication _ will be the
difference, said Steve Jones, professor and head of communication
at the University of Illinois at Chicago. ``People will become more
spur of the moment. It makes the Internet more a part of everyday
life.''
</P>
<P>
   As voice recognition software improves, users will ask their
hand-held devices for movie information, the nearest four-star
Italian restaurant and maybe even to translate what a stranger
says. ``We can get terribly Star Trek about it, but it's
possible,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he is not happy about what technology has done so far. Flip
answers to critics _ ``well, just turn it off!'' _ ring hollow, he
said. ``People are realizing that even as they turn cell phones off
and don't check e-mail, it doesn't stop coming.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTENDS WORK WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Wireless extends the work week and may also add a layer of
stress, said Deborah Borisoff, professor in the department of
culture and communication at New York University. ``E-mail ups the
ante for responding. People call you and say, `I sent you threkd.
``Whatever the advantages, efficiencies, conveniences and
portability, these are devices for imposing private life on public
life. These devices surround people with a kind of shell in which
they become inaccessible and unaware of the world around them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not just discourteous, Carey said. ``Democracy is a form
of public life that depends ultimately on people being aware of
strangers and being able to converse with them. There have been
many incursions and erosions of that. This is a kind of wholesale
assault.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet to IBM's Prial, that blending of public and private is only
for the better.
</P>
<P>
   If someone on an airplane recommends a book, now you may write
the name on a napkin, shove it in your pocket and forget it. But
soon, you will tap out the book title on your wireless, press a
button that says, ``buy this book'' and it will be waiting for you
at your hotel or when you get home.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless evangelicals expect the home to be networked as well.
Put a ``Web cam'' in the refrigerator that you can view from work,
so you know if you are low on milk. Better yet, install an
automatic ``replenishment'' sensor that calls you, he said. ``You
are driving home from work and you get a message that says, `Pick
up milk.' That improves your life.''
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY AN ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   Some scoff at the IBM version of the wireless world-to-come.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just silly,'' said Alan L. Marcus, professor of history
at Iowa State University. ``That's Pollyanna stuff, although I can
understand in a world where one is selling things that this would
be attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Take one example _ the availability of a patient's medical
information, he said. ``Think about an insurance company having
your test results and, all of a sudden, you are not insurable. The
one thing that everybody wants is privacy, and this means that
privacy is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   But wireless is really part of a much larger picture, said
Marcus, author of ``Technology in America: A Brief History.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans love technology, especially the kind that gives them
personal control _ or at least seems to. Look at cars,
videocassette players, cable television _ the culture is deep-fried
in individualism, Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it does change relationships, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless encourages bosses to reach out and touch employees at
odd moments _ undermining the ``I wasn't home to get the phone
call'' alibi. And increasingly personalized work schedules raise
another barrier to unions, which often rely on a shared work
experience. But Marcus doesn't blame the wireless wave on muscular
marketing efforts to sell wireless service to one and all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic forces only work if people buy stuff,'' Marcus said.
``There has to be a reason why you spend your money that way.
Talking about economic forces reverses how we think. We think about
`them' doing it to us, but we do it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Marcus went to a wedding and wondered: Should he turn
off his cell phone and risk missing an emergency call from his
children or risk disrupting the wedding? Obviously, he should have
found out the number at the wedding's location and left that with
the kids. Instead, he switched off his phone, later marveling at
his own narrow-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I had a cell phone, it never occurred to me how to
operate without a cell phone.''
</P>
<P>
   GOOD FOR GROWTH
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget money.
</P>
<P>
   While wireless may appeal to our need for autonomy and
productivity, it is also a potentially dramatic economic
fertilizer. Leaps forward in communications and transportation have
spurred business expansion by lowering costs, raising efficiency
and making possible transactions that were simply not feasible
before.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless does the same.
</P>
<P>
   The service has grown much cheaper even as it becomes a more
powerful tool. Business-to-business electronic commerce _ something
increasingly possible via wireless _ will make companies more
efficient. Wireless also lets employees work away from the office _
in cars, airports, hotels and at home. Meanwhile, consumers find
them
</P>
</TEXT>
