<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's Martha, minus the attitude
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Believe it or not, there may be one thing you can
probably do better than Martha Stewart, the undisputed goddess of
gracious living.
</P>
<P>
   Martha, as you may know, has become legend for baking 240
chocolate chip cookies to decorate her Christmas tree, making her
own garden compost and creating picture frames from twigs found on
her Connecticut estate.
</P>
<P>
   But you know, when it comes to the Internet, Martha still seems
a little lost, which is odd, considering her Web site is one of the
best of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   In between pruning peonies and making Polish delicacies with her
mother on her syndicated TV show, Martha will occasionally sit down
at the computer and attempt to show us how to surf the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The only time I've seen Martha get really excited about the Web
was during a demonstration she did about how to order seed catalogs
online. Here she was clearly in her element. Look! A catalog of
rare hybrids from Holland. Look! A British seed catalog brimming
with things you could never find in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That time, Martha herself was at the terminal, and she was
having a ball. Finding things online that genuinely interest you
that you didn't even know about before you logged on is one of the
main reasons people get so excited about the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But moments like that are rare. Last week, Martha had on her
show Jay Walker, co-chairman and founder of Priceline.com, the
name-your-own-price Web site best known for arranging discount
airfares to almost anywhere. He sat down at the computer, neatly
located in the computer storage hutch Martha built on an earlier
episode, and proceeded to show Martha how to buy airline tickets
online.
</P>
<P>
   During the demonstration, Martha sat quietly beside Walker while
he walked her through the nuances of the pull-down menu and other
computer basics while explaining how the service works. For people
who know how to surf the Web, and especially for people who've
always wondered how you can get plane tickets to Paris for a song,
it was a great segment.
</P>
<P>
   NOT IN HER ELEMENT
</P>
<P>
   But watching the show, I got the distinct feeling that Martha
Stewart has never logged on to Priceline.com and probably never
will. When she gets out the flour and butter and makes a
three-tiered wedding cake to die for, her enthusiasm and her
dedication to perfection is clear _ and is part of what makes her
the woman you love to hate. But when she takes a nod at the Net,
with the exception of the seed catalog extravaganza or passing
references to the wonders of eBay, you can just tell her heart
isn't in it.
</P>
<P>
   Martha should know people don't watch Martha Stewart Living to
find out how to get a cheap flight to Paris (or Buffalo, which was
the destination Martha selected for the demonstration). The people
who watch her show and read her magazine are as interested in the
Internet as they are in making the perfect flower arrangement, and
she knows she has to talk about the Internet whether she likes it
or not.
</P>
<P>
   What Martha can't seem to do is bring her trademark perfection
to the fine art of Web surfing. The legions of Martha devotees want
to know what sites she surfs, not just for seeds but for cooking
supplies, gardening tools and directions for making that yummy
dessert she whipped up last week.
</P>
<P>
   Although Martha _ the person _ is still learning to love the
Web, Martha Stewart the company has already claimed its own corner
of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Martha is a shrewd enough businesswoman to know she needs a Web
site, and www.marthastewart.com is a great site with a slightly
different attitude from the person, TV show and magazine of the
same name.
</P>
<P>
   Martha never pretends to be a Web geek, and I love her for that.
So whether she knows it or not, MarthaStewart.com is an excellent
example of multichannel media delivery.
</P>
<P>
   The people behind the Martha Stewart Living juggernaut know that
they are not in the magazine business, the TV business or even the
Internet business.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Stewart Living is all about attaining a certain lifestyle
and makes use of any and every media outlet, including the
Internet, to give people the information that has made Martha
Stewart a billion-dollar media company.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Stewart.com is beautifully organized, easy to use and
jam-packed with practical information you can actually use, such as
how to get all the wrinkles out of a linen tablecloth or select the
right type of homeowner's insurance.
</P>
<P>
   MarthaStewart.com also has an extensive e-commerce section,
where the truly devoted can purchase some of the items used to
create various projects demonstrated in the magazine and on TV. It
may be a little heavy on the e-commerce links, but this is the only
place to get the actual items Martha uses and recommends, and her
company is smart enough to go for it.
</P>
<P>
   The Web version of Martha Stewart is useful and interesting.
Although Martha has final say, the tone is a little easier to take
than the stern taskmaster of print and video. The information on
the Web site is written a crisp, clear, no-nonsense manner, but
Martha's schoolmarmish tone is nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who wishes they could cook, garden or craft like
Martha without actually having to put up with Martha, the Web site
is a refreshing, highly recommended alternative.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a while before Martha Stewart the person understands
what her viewers want her to do with the Web, but Martha Stewart
the businesswoman understands how to use the Web to her very best
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
