<HEADER>
A4806 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECHNOBUDDY0606-COX     06-05 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Medium-priced computers could be the best vintageBy Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I am not exactly an international sophisticate. So _
when I took a corporate job during a break from newspapering _ my
boss, a veteran of really wicked expense account wars, tried to
help and explained his theory of ordering wine in a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get the most expensive wines,'' he said. ``Restaurants
just put them there as window dressing; they don't expect to sell
many bottles. And don't get the cheapest ones, they're overpriced
for what they are and not very good. Look in the middle prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when I came to work after a long holiday weekend, I
started thinking about that 15-year-old advice. There were four or
five e-mails from readers asking what to look for in a new
computer. I realized computers and wine have a lot in common. The
ones in the middle price ranges are usually the best choice. That's
not universal advice, but those who need a really powerful computer
usually are advanced users who don't need my advice.
</P>
<P>
   Near as I can figure, the middle ground for computers right now
is a 500 megahertz PC. It seems so strange, typing that. Just a few
years ago, computer magazines were writing with awe about 350
megahertz machines.
</P>
<P>
   Newer faster PCs keep coming along and _ if you really want to
stay at the top of the heap _ you can buy PCs in the 1 gigahertz
range now.
</P>
<P>
   And there still is the high tech equivalent of an arms race. As
processors get faster, software gets more demanding, so you almost
have to upgrade just to run the latest programs. That trend is
still around, but it seems to have slowed some. You can do nicely
now and probably for the next couple of years, as far as running
your favorite programs, on a 500 megahertz machine.
</P>
<P>
   The next decision is memory. Even ordinary home PC users should
consider getting 128 megabytes or even more of RAM. Memory does
make a difference. A good video card and a fat hard disk are nice
too.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the neat thing. As I glance through the ads for PCs in
the 500 megahertz range, it's easy to see that every one of them
comes loaded with almost everything you need. So, for ordinary
folks, there aren't too many difficult choices to make anymore. My
guess is that the machine you find at the store will be more than
adequate without changing a thing.
</P>
<P>
   But there are decisions to make.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays there are two choices when it comes to who makes the
processor chip (and that's the real brains of your computer).
There's Intel, the safe choice, and AMD, a relative newcomer but a
respected one. I prefer Intel chips, but you're really fine with
either one. And the AMD advocates make a good case: AMD chips
usually test out just as fast or faster than the Intel chip. I go
with Intel simply because it's an old habit _ mostly a brand
preference.
</P>
<P>
   The next big choice is between a brand name PC _ one made by a
company like Dell or Gateway _ or a no-name machine, usually
assembled by what is called a ``screwdriver shop'' in the trade.
The no-name machines, logically enough, cost much less because the
manufacturer isn't saddled with a lot of advertising and marketing
costs.
</P>
<P>
   You might think that there would be a large and consistent
quality difference between, say, a Dell and some PC with a name
such as Sunshine Computing Co. on the case. Life would be easier if
that was the case. Then the decision would be to pop the extra
bucks for the brand name machine. But the truth is that some of the
screwdriver shop PCs are great, others are jokes.
</P>
<P>
   So what you get (and what you ought to buy if you're a novice)
is consistent dependability from the big brand name manufacturers.
You also get more reliable and professional customer support if
things go wrong. What you can get (if you know computers or have a
trusted friend who does) from the screwdriver shops is a real
bargain. So if you have a spirit of adventure and enough know-how
to evaluate the machine, you can save some money.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
