<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4816 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN0606-COX     06-05 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bored public left with the Senate
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I have not succeeded in making myself
follow the presidential elections. In this, I suspect I am not so
different from most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   When you have two candidates racing to out-moderate each other,
they tend to blur together in people's minds. Both Vice President
Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush are pursuing reasonableness
to an unreasonable degree.
</P>
<P>
   That's why people who enjoy following politics as though poll
results were sports-page box scores have turned to U.S. Senate
races as the biggest game in town.
</P>
<P>
   This has had an odd effect. People who have lived their whole
lives in cities where waitresses ask you if you want grits or home
fries with the breakfast special suddenly are fonts of opinion on
New York state politics.
</P>
<P>
   They talk knowingly about the up-state vote. They had decided
views on when and whether Mayor Rudolph Giuliani would be in or out
of the race. And once he was out, whether that young Lazio guy, who
lives on an island somewhere, is dead in the water or a sure bet
against Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Political junkies across the country have been seized with New
York Envy. They, at least, have a real race. One with scandal,
sudden reversals, surprises and outrageous fortune!
</P>
<P>
   It all makes speculating about vice presidential candidates too
boring to mention and not worth handicapping.
</P>
<P>
   Even Florida's Senate race is more engaging than the national
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is seeing something that's not supposed to happen here:
a duke-it-out Senate primary among Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   For generations, the traditional Florida Senate race has been a
pile-on in the Democratic primary with ballots as long as your arm.
The winner would face the sole designated Republican.
</P>
<P>
   No more. Now Florida is a genuine two-party state, and
Republicans really and truly are fighting for nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Two Republicans want to succeed Connie Mack in the Senate _
Education Commissioner Tom Gallagher and U.S. Rep. Bill
</P>
<P>
   McCollum. (Actually three, Ray Sessman, a teacher from Fort
Lauderdale whom nobody has heard of, also will be on the ballot.)
</P>
<P>
   McCollum, a 10-term congressman with a familiar '90s style
guns-and-impeachment record, is trying to soften his image.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher, a former state insurance commissioner and candidate
for governor, is running as a Real Florida Guy opposing a
Washington Insider.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Insider is to political advertising what the
Bargain Brand is to detergent ads. As a black-suited wrestling
opponent, he is second only to the Tax-and-Spend Liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, when Gallagher ran an ad suggesting an unnamed
McCollum is a Washington Insider. McCollum responded instantly. He
ran an ad saying Gallagher is a Tax-and-Spend Liberal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's slick. He's sly. And he tried to raise your taxes,'' the
ad said.
</P>
<P>
   This slogan may not be as great a masterpiece as ``Hey Buddy,
You're a Liberal,'' the slogan that made Mack a senator, but expect
to hear it again.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, it might be put to music. Maybe with tune like ``You're A
Mean One, Mr. Grinch.'' He's-s-s s-s-s-lick. He's-s-s s-s-s-lyyy
... He's a mean one . . . .
</P>
<P>
   The tax increase in question was a move in 1994 for Floridians
to vote on raising the sales tax to pay for more prisons. Fear of
crime and early release of prisoners made this a momentarily
popular issue. It was the Vanilla Ice of constitutional
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher told reporters the ad was, well, ``typical Washington
insider stuff.'' Neither candidate, it appears, is going to stray
much from the basics this summer.
</P>
<P>
   And when it's over, the winner will face the Democrat, Insurance
Commission Bill Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   The primary winner then will call him a Tax-and-Spend Liberal.
And a Tallahassee Insider.
</P>
<P>
   If the home-grown variety of insider doesn't sound as scary as
Washington's, don't worry. With the right camera effects and a
couple million dollars worth of repetition after Labor Day, this
creature could look every bit as ugly
</P>
<P>
   By Halloween, they may be selling masks.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
