<HEADER>
A4818 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-FEATURE-TURTLES06     06-05 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-TURTLES0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Man-made lights confuse baby sea turtles _ and lead many to
their deaths
 &HT;    By Cathy Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They crawl from the sea in the dark of night. They are
big. They are quiet. They are determined.
</P>
<P>
   What are they? Mother sea turtles looking for a safe place to
lay their eggs!
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe that sea turtles existed before the
dinosaurs. But without human help, sea turtles could become
extinct, too.
</P>
<P>
   All six of the sea turtle species that swim in the waters around
the United States are on an endangered- or threatened-species list.
That makes it against the law to disturb them or their eggs.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to know that if you spend part of your summer
vacation on the coast of Florida, Georgia or any other Southern
state, because you might be sharing beach space with sea turtles or
their eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Turtle specialists tell us that beginning in mid-May each year,
females come out of the ocean several times to lay nests of about
120 eggs.
</P>
<P>
   The turtles work hard to dig a deep hole with their back
flippers. After laying the eggs, they kick sand over the nest and
leave, going back to the ocean until it's time to lay more.
</P>
<P>
   About two months later _ if people, animals or high tides don't
bother the eggs _ baby turtles hatch and make a fast dash to the
sea.
</P>
<P>
   People's love of the beach creates problems for sea turtles,
according to Martha Maglothin, a turtle researcher employed by the
Apalachicola National Estuarine Research Center in Florida.
Building and other activity on beaches means there's less room for
turtle nests.
</P>
<P>
   Baby turtles can get confused by man-made lights. When they come
out of their eggs, baby turtles want to crawl as fast as they can
toward the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Their brains are programmed to find the water by looking for the
brightest thing on the horizon, which used to be the ocean before
so many people came along.
</P>
<P>
   Now baby turtles get confused by the lights on houses and
hotels, and even by flashlights and bonfires, Maglothin said.
</P>
<P>
   They often run away from the sea and end up dying in the sand.
Unattended bonfires can burn the baby turtles, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists used to think that about one in 1,000 hatchlings made
it to adulthood. Now it is believed that the number is closer to
one in 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is the main place in the United States where sea turtles
come to lay eggs, and people there are trying to protect the
turtles, according to Barbara Eells, a teacher and turtle volunteer
in Port St. Joe, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Power Corp. has developed a ``Lights Out for Sea
Turtles'' program to urge people to help keep beaches dark at night
when it's May through October.
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp boats, once a big threat to sea turtles, now are
outfitted with special devices to prevent turtles from getting
caught in nets and then drowning.
</P>
<P>
   Also, students and grownups are learning about the dangers of
letting garbage get into the sea. Turtles sometimes eat plastic
bags and bottles, which can kill them.
</P>
<P>
   Baby sea turtles still have many animal predators _ such as
raccoons, dogs, cats and ghost crabs _ that raid nests for food.
</P>
<P>
   But human beings are starting to get the message about saving
sea turtles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an uphill battle, but I think we're finally starting
to make a difference,'' Maglothin said.
</P>
<P>
   DID YOU KNOW?
</P>
<P>
   Sea turtles are large air-breathing reptiles. They move slowly
on land but swim quickly and gracefully in the sea. When they are
active, sea turtles must swim to the ocean surface to breathe every
few minutes. When they are resting, they can remain underwater for
as long as two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sea turtles live in all but the coldest of the world's oceans,
but they nest only on warm beaches. Sea turtles lay 40,000 to
70,000 nests in Florida each year, making Florida the most
important nesting area in the United States. The sea turtles most
commonly found in Florida are loggerheads, green turtles and
leatherbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe that many sea turtles return to the place
where they were hatched when they decide to make their nests. Some
sea turtles swim thousands of miles to nest.
</P>
<P>
   A sea turtle may live 40 to 60 years or more. But the vast
majority of baby turtles that hatch never make it to adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   Much about sea turtles is still a mystery, including where they
live for the first year or two of their lives. Scientists call this
period the ``lost years'' because turtles of this age group are
rarely seen by people.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
