<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elian a step closer to Cuba
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Elian Gonzalez's father won a major victory last week
toward taking his son home to Cuba. The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, which is in Atlanta, ruled that it was OK for the U.S.
government not to grant Elian an asylum hearing. At an asylum
hearing, a person can ask the U.S. government to protect him and
not force him to return to his home country.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba is a Communist nation about 90 miles south of Florida.
Cubans often try to come to the United States because they think
they'll have a better life here. Elian's mother died at sea while
trying to bring Elian to America. Elian's father wants the boy to
return to Cuba with him.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives have two weeks to fight the decision in
court.
</P>
<P>
   BEWARE OF THE BEARS!
</P>
<P>
   More houses are being built in Atlanta where there used to be
forests and fields. And sometimes bears still live there.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a young black bear stole food near some townhouses.
Last month, a family of bears moved into a subdivision and another
bear was spotted on a golf course _ but wasn't playing well at all.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife rangers tranquilized the bear near the townhouses and
released it in the North Georgia mountains. One of the subdivision
bears was captured and released into woodlands. But the other bears
are still at large.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to come face to snout with a bear, rangers
say, keep your trash cans covered and keep pet food inside.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
