<HEADER>
A4820 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0606-CO     06-05 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New kid on the block
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The weather's been good _ some rain, some
sun. The corn is just about as tall as it should be this time of
year, and nobody died last night _ which means there's not a whole
lot to grumble about this morning. The cafe's kind of quiet _ until
Gene walks in _ then it's time to pick on the new
</P>
<P>
   guy.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Gene decided it was time to retire to the
country so he sold his radio station in Sandusky, bought 10 acres
just outside of our village, built a house and a barn, got himself
a horse and a tractor, and put in a row of tomato plants. Now he's
a farmer _ at least that's what he calls himself. My coffee
buddies, most all retired farmers, like to tease him. Fortunately,
Gene gives as good as he gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Gene!'' Amos hails him as he comes through the door.
``That new tractor of yours still running?'' Gene grins, says it
runs great, and that he's even thinking about buying a sidecar for
it so Amos can ride with him when he plows, just to make sure he's
doing it right.
</P>
<P>
   Amos (340 acres _ retired) is ready for him. He jabs his gnarled
index finger on the table top right next to the cup Gene just set
down and says real loud so everybody can hear, ``If it don't have
yellow wheels, I don't ride on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cal (260 acres _ retired), not wanting to miss any of the fun,
jumps in. ``We told you that if you wanted to be a real farmer like
the rest of us you had to buy the tractor that ``runs like a
Deere'' so's folks'd take you seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene reminds them, ``I'm almost 70 and my wife is in great
health. So what if I died and became an angel? First thing you
know, I'd fly in to check out the farm and there'd be my widow's
new husband riding around on my John Deere tractor. That'd make me
so mad I'd do something un-angel-like and wind up down
</P>
<P>
   below.
</P>
<P>
   Amos says that's where all Brand-X tractor owners end up anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Not too many new folks move to our village so when a stranger
shows up in the cafe three or four mornings in a row, the regulars
who've lived here all their lives and know everybody and who they
married, are curious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's the guy at the counter?'' someone will ask in a stage
whisper. If no one knows for sure, the process of elimination
begins. ``Maybe it's Harold Specht's cousin from Michigan. He looks
a little like them Spechts, don't you think?'' Or, ``That could be
one of those Burkhausen boys that moved away when he
</P>
<P>
   was still a kid. Any of them left out there on the homeplace?''
Usually, when the genealogy trail cools, they lose interest and
forget about the stranger, but that didn't happen with Gene _ he
didn't give them a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why he just come over and sat right down and started talking
to us,'' Amos says, ``kind of like you did Lizzie when you first
moved to town. How long ago was that?''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years, I tell him, since I sat down to my first cup of
coffee with them _ we've shared a lot of history across these
scarred tabletops. ``When I met all of you I was still renovating
my house; remember all the questions I used to ask about plaster
and plumbing?'' Cal says he recalls telling me that farmers don't
do inside stuff _ that's why they have wives.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years we've been through college (mine) and
grandchildren (theirs), retirements, a couple of heart attacks,
three bypasses, and some prostate problems (also theirs). We've
lost a couple of our regulars. Mr. Brown almost made it to 90.
</P>
<P>
   Gene finishes his decaf and stands up. ``Gotta' go,'' he says.
``Got a lot to do today.'' Amos asks what's so all-fired important.
</P>
<P>
   A big grin spread's across Gene's face. ``Gonna' paint my
tractor wheels yellow so I can be like you big guys,'' he says and
heads for the door. Everybody cracks up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what?'' Amos asks, chuckling so hard he can hardly
get out the words. ``He's one of us regular guys,'' then he turns
to me and adds, ``just like you, Lizzie.''
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty high praise in my book.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
