<SLUG> BC-TECH-WEEWEB0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Check out the Adventures of GreatKid
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   www.greatkids.com _ Read stories about extraordinary kids who
are inventors, volunteers, sports stars and musicians. There's
12-year-old Daniel in Santa Cruz, Calif., who invented a
``decrinkler'' for dollar bills, an idea inspired by finicky
bill-changing machines at video arcades. Meet Craig, also 12, from
near Toronto, who with 20 friends started a non-profit group called
Free the Children that encourages world leaders to pass laws to
protect children from employers who exploit them. There are now
Free the Children chapters in seven countries. They credit a new
child labor law in Canada to their work. If you know a kid who
should be recognized, the operators of this site would like to hear
from you.
</P>
<P>
   www.fun4children.com _ This is a site of jokes, riddles and
rhymes for kids, by kids. Here's one from Becky of Palm Coast (no
state listed): How do you catch a blue elephant? Answer: With a
blue elephant gun. Question: How do you catch a pink elephant?
Answer: Hold the nose of the pink elephant until he turns blue and
use the blue elephant gun. Other features to the site include
animation of the day, the birthday page, and crafts and activities,
with instructions on how to make such goodies as paper butterflies,
pencil holders and personalized bookmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4822 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WIRELESS0606-COX     06-05 2303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wireless age to bring new freedoms ... and burdens
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Deb Spicer Tompkins lives in the blur.
</P>
<P>
   There is a blur, she will tell you, where there used to be a
line separating professional and family, private life and public.
But with her cellular phone, pager and wireless digital assistant,
Tompkins often finds herself where there is no line at all.
</P>
<P>
   As managing director of the technology practice at Hill and
Knowlton, a public relations firm, she gets e-mail from clients,
pages from her children, phone calls from co-workers, all the time,
everywhere. ``If you're not careful, it puts you in a perpetual
reactive mode,'' she said. ``Sometimes instead of reducing
information overload, it contributes to information overload.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, the human relationship with technology has always been
two-way. And now, in the wireless revolution, we have combined the
mobility of cars, the reach of phones and the power of computers.
``This is huge,'' said Steve Jones, professor and head of
communication at the University of Illinois at Chicago. ``Wireless
Internet access represents as much of a revolution as the
introduction of the Internet itself.''
</P>
<P>
   To those who grew up in the pre-Net era, the prospects can sound
like an episode of ``The Jetsons.'' Say you're driving to the
theater. The car knows where you are going, sees the time, does a
quick calculation and realizes you are not going to make it on
time. The car calls the theater, then sells the tickets to someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Prial, marketing director for IBM's pervasive computing
unit, says it is hardly a stretch from what can be done now to that
scenario. ``You get to the theater and sure enough, you say, `Darn,
we're late.' And the car says, `No problem. I sold the tickets.'''
</P>
<P>
   The upside of the technology seems clear enough: Employees can
hit the beach without ducking a critical conference call, children
can reach parents from a party gone sour, stranded motorists can
summon a tow truck. The near future is even more alluring: paying
for items before you get to the store, turning on the oven when you
are miles from home, checking in to a flight while still on the way
to the airport _ something Swissair already does in Zurich.
</P>
<P>
   ``And tomorrow, you'll have your electronic boarding pass on
your phone,'' Prial said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many burdens of wireless technology are also hard
to miss. The relentless flood of e-mail and voice mail. The ease
with which a colleague or boss can intrude on your free time. The
annoyance of hearing strangers blithely discussing private business
in public places on their cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Yet work and bad manners are not new, even if we have witnessed
a spate of new technologies. How much of a difference does it make
that we can communicate without wires?
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Net power in the palm of your hand _ for
transactions, for information, for communication _ will be the
difference, said Steve Jones, professor and head of communication
at the University of Illinois at Chicago. ``People will become more
spur of the moment. It makes the Internet more a part of everyday
life.''
</P>
<P>
   As voice recognition software improves, users will ask their
hand-held devices for movie information, the nearest four-star
Italian restaurant and maybe even to translate what a stranger
says. ``We can get terribly Star Trek about it, but it's
possible,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he is not happy about what technology has done so far. Flip
answers to critics _ ``well, just turn it off!'' _ ring hollow, he
said. ``People are realizing that even as they turn cell phones off
and don't check e-mail, it doesn't stop coming.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTENDS WORK WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Wireless extends the work week and may also add a layer of
stress, said Deborah Borisoff, professor in the department of
culture and communication at New York University. ``E-mail ups the
ante for responding. People call you and say, `I sent you three
e-mails. Why haven't you answered?'''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, despite the advantage of mobility, erosion of
personal life is becoming ``the norm,'' she said. ``We know the
comparison with the way it was, but what about the new
generation?''
</P>
<P>
   Borisoff ran into resistance when she demanded that graduate
students switch off phones and pagers in class. ``People tell me,
`I would lose my job if I turned off my beeper.'''
</P>
<P>
   James W. Carey, author of ``Communication as Culture'' and
professor at Columbia University, recounted standing behind a woman
in a Baskin-Robbins ice cream shop who was taking orders via
wireless phone from the people at home, apparently oblivious to the
people behind her in line.
</P>
<P>
   When the key division between home and public disappears, people
act rudely and don't even know it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Martin, who writes the syndicated Miss Manners column,
said new technology takes getting used to. ``Some people think they
are in an etiquette-free zone. Still, I think that everyone will
calm down when we get used to cell phones.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not technology that makes people rude, she said. ``It is
amazing how technology improves but people don't.''
</P>
<P>
   But Carey said he believes technology does shape expectations.
Television, he believes, has convinced some people that those being
watched can't watch back. One student who sat in the front row
constantly talked during class and was astonished that he
complained, Carey said. ``She said, `You mean you noticed? I didn't
think it would bother you.'''
</P>
<P>
   POWERFUL MEDIUM
</P>
<P>
   Many people still think the technology is just for talking.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as the Europeans know and as Americans are finding out,
wireless is reaching new realms. When the phone's souped-up
software connects to sophisticated networks, the phone becomes a
map, a wallet and a window on the Web. With a tiny screen, phones
won't replace computer surfing, but Net sites are being configured
to be usable _ if not exciting _ via the phone.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Atlanta-based Hotpalm.com has software that will
let users trade stocks by phone. Moreover, Hotpalm technology can
let a shopper in a store connect to a search engine that will sweep
the Web to find the best price for the item you are looking at,
said Chandan Seernmani, chairman, chief executive officer and
co-founder of Hotpalm.com. ``Then you can take that to the service
desk and say, `Would you care to match this price or should I push
the button and buy this?'''
</P>
<P>
   Phones fitted with global positioning software can tell you
where the nearest Home Depot is _ and how to get there. Connected
to the Net, an emergency medical technician might read a patient's
medical history as she is lifted into the ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will change the way that people live and the way they do
things,'' Seernmani said. ``This is the wave we are getting ready
to ride.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW GATED COMMUNITY
</P>
<P>
   It started with the Walkman _ the first technology to create a
kind of ``gated community in the street,'' Carey said.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the man on the sidewalk talking on the phone, the woman
in the coffee line speaking loudly into her hand and ignoring those
around her, he said. ``Whatever the advantages, efficiencies,
conveniences and portability, these are devices for imposing
private life on public life. These devices surround people with a
kind of shell in which they become inaccessible and unaware of the
world around them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not just discourteous, Carey said. ``Democracy is a form
of public life that depends ultimately on people being aware of
strangers and being able to converse with them. There have been
many incursions and erosions of that. This is a kind of wholesale
assault.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet to IBM's Prial, that blending of public and private is only
for the better.
</P>
<P>
   If someone on an airplane recommends a book, now you may write
the name on a napkin, shove it in your pocket and forget it. But
soon, you will tap out the book title on your wireless, press a
button that says, ``buy this book'' and it will be waiting for you
at your hotel or when you get home.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless evangelicals expect the home to be networked as well.
Put a ``Web cam'' in the refrigerator that you can view from work,
so you know if you are low on milk. Better yet, install an
automatic ``replenishment'' sensor that calls you, he said. ``You
are driving home from work and you get a message that says, `Pick
up milk.' That improves your life.''
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY AN ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   Some scoff at the IBM version of the wireless world-to-come.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just silly,'' said Alan L. Marcus, professor of history
at Iowa State University. ``That's Pollyanna stuff, although I can
understand in a world where one is selling things that this would
be attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Take one example _ the availability of a patient's medical
information, he said. ``Think about an insurance company having
your test results and, all of a sudden, you are not insurable. The
one thing that everybody wants is privacy, and this means that
privacy is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   But wireless is really part of a much larger picture, said
Marcus, author of ``Technology in America: A Brief History.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans love technology, especially the kind that gives them
personal control _ or at least seems to. Look at cars,
videocassette players, cable television _ the culture is deep-fried
in individualism, Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it does change relationships, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless encourages bosses to reach out and touch employees at
odd moments _ undermining the ``I wasn't home to get the phone
call'' alibi. And increasingly personalized work schedules raise
another barrier to unions, which often rely on a shared work
experience. But Marcus doesn't blame the wireless wave on muscular
marketing efforts to sell wireless service to one and all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic forces only work if people buy stuff,'' Marcus said.
``There has to be a reason why you spend your money that way.
Talking about economic forces reverses how we think. We think about
`them' doing it to us, but we do it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Marcus went to a wedding and wondered: Should he turn
off his cell phone and risk missing an emergency call from his
children or risk disrupting the wedding? Obviously, he should have
found out the number at the wedding's location and left that with
the kids. Instead, he switched off his phone, later marveling at
his own narrow-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I had a cell phone, it never occurred to me how to
operate without a cell phone.''
</P>
<P>
   GOOD FOR GROWTH
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget money.
</P>
<P>
   While wireless may appeal to our need for autonomy and
productivity, it is also a potentially dramatic economic
fertilizer. Leaps forward in communications and transportation have
spurred business expansion by lowering costs, raising efficiency
and making possible transactions that were simply not feasible
before.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless does the same.
</P>
<P>
   The service has grown much cheaper even as it becomes a more
powerful tool. Business-to-business electronic commerce _ something
increasingly possible via wireless _ will make companies more
efficient. Wireless also lets employees work away from the office _
in cars, airports, hotels and at home. Meanwhile, consumers find
themselves using wireless more as its costs fall. And new versions
of wireless will let them do more business _ whether it's buying
stocks, books or clothes.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, technology is an economic driver and wireless is a
key technology, said Charles Mahla, senior economist for Econ One,
a California-based consulting group. ``Ultimately that's going to
result in greater profits, greater incomes, greater demand for
consumer products. All this propels the economy forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Wireless also holds the promise of evening out economic
inequities. Development, technology and wealth are concentrated in
a relatively few places. But when new technology changes costs, the
possibilities shift, too, said Linda Garcia, associate director of
the Georgetown University Program in Communication, Culture and
Technology. ``From my point of view, the special thing about
wireless is that it has a very different cost structure. Wireless
doesn't have a high fixed cost. You can recover your capital
faster. This is exciting for, say, rural India.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the rural United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think cooperatives, rural telephone companies, have been
more likely to deploy technology more rapidly than the regional
Bell companies (like BellSouth). They have to make a capital
investment, but they don't have to make a profit. I'm just afraid
that it won't continue to happen. Other people can come and eat
their lunch _ these are great takeover companies.''
</P>
<P>
   For its advantages, many wonder if technology liberates us or
ties us further down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to think about whether this is freedom or an
illusion,'' said NYU's Borisoff. ``What do we mean by freedom? And
freedom from what?''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Seagraves, executive director of the American Civil
Liberties Union in Georgia, uses her phone frequently _ but often
leaves it switched off. ``I don't find it to be an intrusion
because, if I don't want to talk, I turn it off. We sometimes give
technology a control that it doesn't have to have. And maybe we are
blaming technology for our own inability to set boundaries and make
our own choices.''
</P>
<P>
   But those choices are not easy for us, said Ralph Keyes, social
critic and author of ``We, the Lonely People.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans constantly tussle with technology, hoping it is a tool
to improve lives, even as it sometimes forces a trade-off. ``Every
day I ask myself, is my life better because I have all this
technology? I don't have a clear answer to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
