<HEADER>
A4832 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-NEW-AMERICA-PARENTS-O     06-05 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-PARENTS-OF-BIRHMINGHAM-BOMB-VICTIMS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS OF BIRMINGHAM BOMB VICTIMS TELL STORY OF BLACK SURVIVAL IN
AMERICA  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By VERNON JARRETT  
 &HT;    Every time I chat with Mrs. Alpha Robertson, I am reminded by
her voice and overall demeanor that I am in the presence of an
ignored chapter in American social history. She is the embodiment
of the historic travail of black parents who lived during the era
of lynch rule in the South.
 &HT;    In the South there was once a truism among blacks stating that
regardless of what parents did for their children, they always was
the albatross of the lynch mob.
 &HT;    Mrs. Robertson, 81, is the mother of Carole Robertson, one of
the four teenage girls murdered when racists bombed Birmingham's
black 16th Street Baptist church in 1963. I've maintained a great
friendship with Mrs. Robertson since I first interviewed her in
Chicago over 15 years ago.
 &HT;    Recently, I spoke by phone with Mrs. Robertson following the
announcement by the State of Alabama that two alleged Klu Klux
Klansmen had been indicted for the murder of her child. The nature
of the conversation required me to consider my words carefully.
There could be no lightweight reporters' banter: ``Will you be glad
if the two alleged Klansmen are sentenced to the chair?''
 &HT;    Yet, the temptation to dwell on the superficial was offered. One
of the indicted reportedly had said that his ``only regret's that
the black church was not filled'' when the bomb exploded.
 &HT;    This heartless statement represents an age-old, pervasive,
antihuman attitude that black parents once had to endure whenever
their children left their doorsteps. It also represents the
mentality that once gave lynch mobs a degree of acceptability
throughout the land _ not just in the South.
 &HT;    Despite over 4,742 lynchings from 1909 through 1968, as recorded
by the NAACP, the U.S. Congress remained silent for decades, even
though 1,297 of the hanging victims had been white. Congress
refused to pass any antilynching legislation until after World War
II, when the annual statistics for lynchings had dropped to single
digits.
 &HT;    But don't confuse the lynching of blacks with the hanging of
whites. A black lynching usually expressed a ritualized worship of
racial supremacy. Frequently lynchers dressed in their Sunday best
or wore old army attire from the Spanish American War or World War
I. The lynchers and attendant mob carried the Confederate war flag,
as though brutalizing blacks was an act of patriotism.
 &HT;    Some of the mob even fought for charred souvenirs such as toes,
fingers, and in some instances, burnt genitals for display at
country stores and barbershops.
 &HT;    The tolerance of lynching represented a national and regional
sickness. This sickness can be witnessed today in those who
advocate Confederate flags flying over state capitol grounds.
 &HT;    Mrs. Robertson and I strongly favor justice finally prevailing
in solutions to old murders, but we are also largely concerned
about changes in old attitudes. We detect a modicum of hope in the
singular fact that the State of Alabama is trying to correct at
least one of its sins of the past.
 &HT;    As we talked, I recalled a conversation we had one evening over
20 years ago when I was visiting Montgomery, Ala. The phone rang
and an unannounced voice spoke as though it was old friend. ``Hey,
Vernon, how you doin', fella,'' the voice said. ``Your friend Alvin
(black Alabama Rep. Alvin Holmes), told me you were in town ... Any
thing you need?''
 &HT;    I couldn't detect the drawl until the man said ``This is George,
you know me, the governor. I jess wanted to know if everything was
all right.''
 &HT;    Gov. Wallace went on to talk about how he had changed, and how
``we all had to change, no doubt about it.'' Wallace said ``we know
we didn't treat colored people right, and so does everybody.''
 &HT;    I turned down Gov. Wallace's offer of transportation to the
airport, but I conceded to myself that times had changed at some
level in the South. I couldn't resist remembering that in 1963
Wallace stood at the entrance of the University of Alabama and
drawled, ``I say segregation now, segregation tomorrow and
segregation forever.''
 &HT;    Nor could I clear from memory the spiritual climate of 1963 when
those four girls were slain and two black boys were killed the same
day _ one shot by a cop in Birmingham. I also recalled a white
civil rights marcher named William L. Moore of Baltimore who was
shot to death near Attalla, Ala., and that in Jackson, Miss.,
Medgar Evers was assassinated for trying to register blacks to
vote.
 TAKING DOWN THE CONFEDERATE FLAG  
 &HT;    Mrs. Robertson and I recognize the significance of this singular
initiative coming from the State of Alabama. Indeed, it should
proceed with serious intent. A sector of Alabama, like Gov.
Wallace, has become clearly aware of the power of the black ballot.
Martyrs such as Martin Luther King Jr., Evers and so many others
did not die in vain.
 &HT;    However, delayed indictments of old culprits will never truly
compensate noble souls like retired school teacher Alpha Robertson
or the ghost of her late educator husband Alvin Robertson Sr. whose
biggest sin was sending their pretty little child ``all dressed
up'' to die in Sunday School.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Vernon Jarrett is an active member of the national advisory
board of the Rosa and Raymond Parks Pathways to Freedom Program for
Youths. In 1991 he received a Lifetime Achievement Award from the
National Association of Black Journalists.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Vernon Jarrett 
