<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-LOOKING-TO-FUTURE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING WHAT'S AHEAD  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By NAT IRVIN II  
 &HT;    What if the United States and the rest of the world were at the
beginning of a period of change _ an economic expansion driven by
technological progress that would literally dwarf the magnitude of
the Industrial Revolution? If this were true, what would the
implications be for African-Americans?
 &HT;    One way to understand the future is by learning to make up
stories about the future through scenarios. Scenarios are a way of
organizing what we already know (what we've learned from the past),
while encouraging different perspectives on what the future might
hold.
 &HT;    Gerald Harris, of Global Business Network, a San Francisco-based
planning organization, uses scenarios. Harris says that telling
stories about the future can be a very important tool for the
African-American community as a way of seeing the future now, not
later.
 &HT;    ``We can't win the race by looking to see who is coming up from
behind and who is running beside us. We must also see who is in
front of us,'' Harris says.
 &HT;    Futurist thinking is not about predicting the future, but it is
a way of thinking intelligently about how the future might play
out, and making decisions and adjustments today _ in anticipation.
 &HT;    It is also a way of learning from, and interacting with, events
and trends as they unfold and making adjustments when new things
are learned. For example, using scenarios, you can fast-forward to
the year 2025 and then reframe the present by looking backward and
imagining how people in the future might look back on the world
today.
 &HT;    For example, let's ``look back'' from the year 2025. You would
see the American landscape being reshaped by information and
communication technology. It would be a world where the rapid
spread of technology, combined with a world movement toward
capitalistic economic systems, formed an irresistible force of
change and growth.
 &HT;    Looking back, you'd see a world where telecommunications,
biotechnology, nanotechnology and alternative sources of energy had
come together in an era of globalization. It had all come together
to create a long boom of economic expansion with new jobs and new
opportunities.
 &HT;    It was a world in which our ability to communicate with the rest
of the world increased _ faster and broader as the power of the
networked society evolved through communications networks adopted
by nearly one-third of the globe's teen-agers.
 &HT;    This was a world of the networked society where work is varied,
including new work arrangements with employers. There were more
independent contractors used, and there was a big increase in the
speed and scope of transactions and interactions.
 &HT;    It was a world in which AOL gobbled up Time Warner to form a new
company with a market value of about $300 billion. That merger of a
new Internet company and an old media powerhouse brought forth a
new era and was the first of many megamergers of necessity. The
Internet needed content in order to survive, and media companies
wanted to capture a larger audience through personal computers.
 &HT;    It was a world in which identifying and using genetic
information doubled every one or two years, transforming
agriculture, nutrition and health care to create new products in an
emerging life-sciences industry.
 &HT;    In this long-boom scenario of the future, periods of slow
worldwide economic growth are very short and transitional, with no
recessions and no depressions. As to who wins in the long economic
boom to the networked economy, some nations do and some don't.
 &HT;    Every nation that matters _ not just China but Namibia, Ghana,
Nigeria, India, Trinidad and Tobago _ must determine to get on
board this economic train or be left behind in a quickly advancing
game, where being behind can be fatal.
 &HT;    OK, come back to today, April 2000. Ask yourself what are the
implications for the United States in the long-boom scenario? What
are the implications for the African-American community in the
long-boom scenario? What does this mean to you?
 &HT;    The answer, in part, is for African-Americans to take advantage
of the future we envision by reframing the present.
 &HT;    The next generation of African-Americans, according to Harris,
will need to reposition ``the center point of our American
experience beyond the slavery/racist nexus of our past.
 &HT;    ``Black Americans are a diverse group. But as a community, there
will be advantages to forward looking _ a more open vision of
ourselves and our place in America,'' Harris explains. ``What we
are talking about is adding a major plank to our cultural sense of
self.''
 &HT;    We are going to have to change the way we see ourselves, and we
need a tool that allows us to learn to do this. Utilizing the
technique of scenario planning and thinking can help.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Nat Irvin II is a contributing columnist to Emerge magazine.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Emerge magazine 
