<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-KOREAN-PITCHERS-GO-MAJOR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREAN PITCHERS ARE TURNING UP RED  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By ED ODEVEN  
 &HT;    Sang-Hoon Lee stands out in more ways than one. The 29-year-old
pitcher from Seoul is on the verge of becoming the first man in
history to play in the elite levels of professional baseball in
Korea, Japan and the United States. Lee signed a two-year contract
with the Boston Red Sox in January and at press time appeared to be
slated as the No. 2 lefty in the Red Sox bullpen behind veteran
Rheal Cormier.
 &HT;    Oh, and then there's his famous shoulder-length, bushy
reddish-brown hair that has earned him the nickname ``Samson'' _ a
reference to the Biblical warrior with impressive physical prowess.
 &HT;    Lee has also accomplished what few pitchers have done: excel as
a starter and closer. In 1995, he had a 20-5 record as a starter
and earned the Korean Most Valuable Player honors. Two years later,
Lee saved 37 games, and was chosen as the relief pitcher of the
year.
 &HT;    Last season, he had a 6-5 record and a 2.83 earned run average
(ERA) while pitching for the Chunichi Dragons in Japan. In 95.1
innings, Lee struck out 65 batters and walked 30 in 36 appearances.
 &HT;    These numbers and past accolades, however, don't mean much to
Lee nowadays.
 &HT;    ``I don't want to put too much meaning in them,'' Lee said
through interpreter Seung-hyun Park before a recent exhibition game
against the visiting Minnesota Twins at Wilbur ``Billy'' Smith
Field in Fort Myers, Fla. ``I just want to do my best and not think
about the past.''
 &HT;    Lee adds his main goal for this season is to earn a spot on
Boston's 25-man roster and stick around to contribute all season.
 &HT;    Joining Lee at the Red Sox training camp are fellow Koreans Jin
Ho Cho and Sun-Woo Kim. Cho split last season with Boston's
Triple-A Pawtucket team (9-3 with a 3.45 ERA and 80 strikeouts in
109.2 innings), and also appeared in nine games with the Red Sox,
posting a 2-3 record in 39.1 innings of work.
 &HT;    Kim, a 22-year-old from Inchon, was 9-8 with a 4.89 ERA in 26
games last season all starts for Double-A Trenton. The
hard-throwing right-hander fanned 130 batters and yielded just 44
base on balls in 149 innings.
 &HT;    According to Lee, the duos' presence in Ft. Myers has made his
transition to America easier.
 &HT;    ``It's been very beneficial to have Jin Ho Cho and Sun Kim
here.''
 &HT;    During his brief stay in the United States, Lee says the Red Sox
coaches haven't asked him to alter his pitching style. So, what
should baseball fans expect from Lee this season?
 &HT;    ``He's somebody we are looking for to get out left-handers in
key situations,'' teammate Mike Stanley says.
 &HT;    Certainly that's an important role for a team yearning to
overtake the lefty-loaded New York Yankees as the American League
East's premier ballclub this season. Wendell Kim, Boston's third
base coach, says in limited playing time Lee has made a favorable
impression with the organization.
 &HT;    ``It looks like he can handle himself. He might be able to get
you out with his pitches' change of speeds,'' he says.
 &HT;    After a respectable stint in the big leagues last summer, Cho
appears ready to crack the starting rotation on a full-time basis
as well.
 &HT;    ``He's obviously battling for that number five spot,'' Stanley
says. ``He gave us some good quality innings last year coming up.
He's got pretty good experience and knows what it takes to compete
and win at this level.''
 &HT;    Minnesota Twins manager Tom Kelly believes Cho is progressing as
a productive hurler.
 &HT;    ``He seems like a guy that's sort of learning and making the
transition. I'm sure it's a challenge for him to come over here and
pitch, especially at this level,'' says Kelly, who guided the Twins
to thrilling seven-game World Series triumphs in 1987 and 1991.
 &HT;    ``I think he's handled it well. He seems to be pretty composed
on the mound and I'm sure it s quite a learning experience. You've
got to admire that and take your hat off to the young man for
trying.''
 &HT;    While observing the 20-plus pitchers during spring training,
Wendell Kim notices Sun Kim has the necessary skills to succeed.
 &HT;    ``He's around the plate. He's got a good presence on the mound.
He looks poised. Nothing seems to rattle him,'' Wendell Kim
reports.
 &HT;    Gary Gaetti, who broke into the majors with the Twins in 1982
and is currently fighting for a spot on the Red Sox roster, says
Lee, Cho and Kim have become welcome additions during the
Grapefruit League season.
 &HT;    ``They are very pleasant human beings,'' the easy-going Gaetti
says. ``Now there are a lot more Latin players and a lot more Asian
players. And I guess that's good because we are trying to get
global with baseball.''
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Ed Odeven is a contributor to KoreAm Journal.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 KOREAM Journal 
