<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4871 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN07-CO     06-05 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Those green things on our dinner plates
 &HT;    For release June 7, 2000.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON - It is a situation in which I often find myself. No
visit to London can be complete without a swing through that
leviathan of a department store, Harrod's. Particularly to the book
department as that is contiguous to the sewing and needlepoint
department to which my wife is devoutly drawn despite the fact that
the inventory there hasn't changed in a dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   And so here I am again. Having worked my way through British
History, World Travel, Mysteries, Biographies and some seamy
magazines I encounter my wife in Cooking, to which she drifted
after finally realizing that, indeed, Harrod's sewing and
needlepoint department has been trapped in a time bubble.
</P>
<P>
   As my wife pages through multiple cooking books, my otherwise
bored gaze drifts to one of the shelves that displays a book
entitled, simply, ``Parsley.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would anyone write a book about parsley? I asked myself --
curiously reaching for the book itself. It is thin and buttressed
by myriad pictures of the same old thing, parsley, on different
types of dinner dishes.
</P>
<P>
   It regenerated my own reaction to parsley on my plate: I toss it
onto my wife's plate, or onto the table itself; gently but with
contempt.
</P>
<P>
   To me, parsley is what broccoli is to George Bush, the
courageous former president who dared go public with his eating
enmity. ``I do not like broccoli and I haven't liked it since I was
a little kid and my mother made me eat it and I'm president of the
United States and I'm not going to eat any more broccoli,'' he
whined after it was served him aboard Air Force One in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   He will be remembered more by me for that than for his
victorious Gulf War coalition or even his disastrous ``read my
lips'' utterance.
</P>
<P>
   He said what he felt, that he hated broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   And while I like broccoli, I detest parsley. Seemingly, it's
everywhere -- clumped as sprigs atop the meal or sprinkled around
the plate in tiny fragments for those growing numbers who labor
under the impression that a plate of food is an artistic
expression.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants don't even have to be chic to be part of the parsley
coterie; plain, old eating joints do it. If they don't have
parsley, then it's watercress, or chicory, or some other bitter
green.
</P>
<P>
   It is my contention that grub of this type merely are roadside
grasses mowed up from highway medians and tossed onto our plates.
Some diners look at parsley and the like as nourishment, others see
it just as coloring to an otherwise drab plate of food.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, I don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   In agreement was the late poet Ogden Nash, who summed it all up
in three succinct words: ``Parsley is gharsley.''
</P>
<P>
   I flipped through the pages of the book on parsley in search of
justification for its presence atop my restaurant meals but I
really found none. I did, however, find a little history:
</P>
<P>
   During the Isthmian Games of ancient Greece, winners were
crowned with wreaths of parsley. They wore it, they didn't eat it,
they didn't scatter it on their food!
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in this book, as I waited, waited, waited for my wife,
I read that parsley often was laid at the tombs of the dead - which
speaks wonders to its use today. And, yes, the Greeks also used it
for a spice but heaven knows why.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, I am offending many who love parsley, who grow
parsley, who serve parsley and, particularly, who sell parsley.
Realize, however, that I am just a sprig of grievance, a lonely
voice against a preponderance of people who regularly use and enjoy
parsley as either a vegetable, herb, decoration or graveside
remembrance.
</P>
<P>
   To those I have offended, I apologize. Which is more than Bush
did for the broccoli lovers. But then again, he didn't get
re-elected; I presume because of it. It's something George W. might
think about as the campaign gets more involved in issues.
</P>
<P>
   As you can imagine, I did not purchase the book; it's still
there for other Harrod's roamers to ponder. Come out of Magazines,
turn right to Cooking, look down to the corner, bottom shelf; it's
right next to Parsnip.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox News Service. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
