NYT-06-05-00 1146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4872 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LEWIS-DEAL-COX     06-05 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-DEAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL star pleads guilty to misdemeanor
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- NFL star Ray Lewis pleaded guilty today to a
misdemeanor charge that will allow him to stay out of prison and
escape murder charges in the Buckhead stabbing deaths of two
Decatur men.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 25, is now a witness for the prosecution and will testify
against his former co-defendants, Reginald Oakley and Joseph
Sweeting.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Garland, Lewis' lead lawyer, also said the linebacker will
give testimony ``that affects more than the people here on trial.''
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, testimony was given implicating two other men
who were passengers in Lewis' stretch limousine Jan. 31. During a
street brawl after a night of post-Super Bowl partying, Jacinth
Baker, 21, and Richard Lollar, 24, died of stab wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an innocent man, wrongly accused, and who's been
through an awful ordeal,'' Garland said in a hastily called news
conference. ``Today, he has been exonerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland said his client is expected to take the witness stand
Tuesday and that it has been ``arranged'' that Lewis will return
and play this upcoming season for the Baltimore Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief plea hearing before Superior Court Judge Alice D.
Bonner, Lewis answered questions with ``yes'' and ``no,'' except to
say ``guilty'' to a misdemeanor charge of obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The obstruction charge is for giving incomplete statements to
police and demanding that those in his limousine keep quiet about
the fatal fight.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Clint Rucker said he will drop the
murder, felony murder and aggravated assault charges against the
All-Pro player.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis will testify that he did not see anyone stab a victim
during the fight, Garland said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray saw no knife being used, but Ray will say what he saw
during the fight and let the jury make those determinations,''
Garland said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner accepted the deal that Lewis serve a one-year sentence on
probation.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis agreed to pay one-third of the court costs to Fulton
County for the prosecution of his case. That sum has yet to be
determined, Bonner said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis pleaded guilty under the First Offender Act, which means
if he stays out of trouble during the term of his probation, the
misdemeanor charge will be expunged from his record.
</P>
<P>
   After the plea agreement was approved this morning, Charita
Lollar, cousin to Richard Lollar, told a reporter, ``money talks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if you were part of a crime in Georgia, you were
held guilty,'' she said. ``But in Atlanta if you have money...
you'll walk out of here and play football.''
</P>
<P>
   She then shook her head.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Harvey, a lawyer for Oakley, said the prosecutors had just
proved Lewis was a ``liar'' and now they want him to be their
witness. ``I plan to cross-examine the (expletive) out of him,''
the lawyer promised.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sadow, a lawyer for Sweeting, predicted that, regardless
of Lewis' testimony, his client will be exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner adjourned court until Tuesday, although Sadow said he
wanted to continue the proceedings today and even hear Lewis'
direct testimony. Postponing the case another day ``gives the state
a little more time to get its case together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey and Sadow received tapes of the statement Lewis gave
prosecutors Sunday in their preparation to attack Lewis on
cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   The case, by nearly all accounts, has gone badly for the
prosecution, with flip-flopping witnesses and scant evidence that
Lewis had attacked anyone. In fact, no witness so far has
testtified to seeing anyone stabbing a victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very interested in what (Lewis) will say; I bet he doesn't
even know right now,'' Harvey said. ``It'll hurt Sweeting a hell of
a lot more than Oakley. But Sweeting's his friend.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, prosecutors brought a Baltimore man, Sherman
Street, who came to testify that the day before Oakley turned
himself in, Street had warned Oakley that he would be ``the fall
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray Lewis has all the money and the resources,'' Street had
told Oakley, who then agreed with that statement.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner refused to allow that statement to be admitted. Harvey
wanted to use that to show Oakley's ``state of mind'' before
turning himself in. The judge ruled that would be prejudicial
evidence of one defendant (Oakley) testifying against another
defendant (Lewis).
</P>
<P>
   Now, that statement should be admitted and Harvey said his hands
won't be tied. ``Now we can try this (expletive) case,'' Harvey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Garland said that early Sunday, District Attorney Paul Howard
called him and came to his Buckhead home to broach a deal. The two
men met, with Howard deciding to drop the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This became a political issue; people moved quickly and
without study,'' said Garland. Prosecutors ``got caught up in the
media swirl. They rushed into this and didn't study.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland said the plea and Lewis' testimony will put to rest
``any lingering idea that the lawyers got him off or the DA fumbled
the ball. That's not the case here. Here the DA came forward and
said `He's not guilty.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
