<P>
   Steve Sadow, a lawyer for Sweeting, predicted that, regardless
of Lewis' testimony, his client will be exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner adjourned court until Tuesday, although Sadow said he
wanted to continue the proceedings today and even hear Lewis'
direct testimony. Postponing the case another day ``gives the state
a little more time to get its case together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey and Sadow received tapes of the statement Lewis gave
prosecutors Sunday in their preparation to attack Lewis on
cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   The case, by nearly all accounts, has gone badly for the
prosecution, with flip-flopping witnesses and scant evidence that
Lewis had attacked anyone. In fact, no witness so far has
testtified to seeing anyone stabbing a victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very interested in what (Lewis) will say; I bet he doesn't
even know right now,'' Harvey said. ``It'll hurt Sweeting a hell of
a lot more than Oakley. But Sweeting's his friend.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, prosecutors brought a Baltimore man, Sherman
Street, who came to testify that the day before Oakley turned
himself in, Street had warned Oakley that he would be ``the fall
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray Lewis has all the money and the resources,'' Street had
told Oakley, who then agreed with that statement.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner refused to allow that statement to be admitted. Harvey
wanted to use that to show Oakley's ``state of mind'' before
turning himself in. The judge ruled that would be prejudicial
evidence of one defendant (Oakley) testifying against another
defendant (Lewis).
</P>
<P>
   Now, that statement should be admitted and Harvey said his hands
won't be tied. ``Now we can try this (expletive) case,'' Harvey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Garland said that early Sunday, District Attorney Paul Howard
called him and came to his Buckhead home to broach a deal. The two
men met, with Howard deciding to drop the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This became a political issue; people moved quickly and
without study,'' said Garland. Prosecutors ``got caught up in the
media swirl. They rushed into this and didn't study.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland said the plea and Lewis' testimony will put to rest
``any lingering idea that the lawyers got him off or the DA fumbled
the ball. That's not the case here. Here the DA came forward and
said `He's not guilty.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
