<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDWAY-ANNIVERSARY (San Francisco) _ This year, for the first
time, the U.S. Navy is treating the Battle of Midway as one of its
two most important historical dates (after Oct. 13, 1775 _ the day
the Navy was born). Around the world, the event was remembered
Sunday. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   FOSSILS-LEGEND (San Francisco) _ Fossil-hunting scientists are
raving over evidence that some ancient legends of monsters are
based on pre-Christian nomads' discovery of dinosaur bones in
central Asia, hundreds of years before the time of Jesus. By KEAY
DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   WAR-BRIDE (San Francisco) _ She faced centuries of rigid
tradition; he, the mighty bureaucracy of the U.S. occupation
forces. But in the end, Kazue Nagai _ resplendent in a silk kimono
_ married young Air Force cryptographer Frederick H. Katz in 1946
in Tokyo. She is said to be the first war bride of a GI in occupied
Japan. Mrs. Katz, a longtime resident of San Francisco, died of a
stroke last week at the age of 80. By ANNIE NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXPENSE-ACCOUNTS (San Francisco) _ The guy who expensed his
Chicago hotel room for $2,788 after a kielbasa sausage dinner
caught on fire and nearly burned the place down almost won. And the
Texas auditor reimbursed for the rental of an elephant almost took
the grand prize too. But the winning entry in the country's
funniest expense report contest came from the Lake Oswego, Ore.,
marketing manager who wrote off two voodoo dolls: He had bought
them to curse an industry analyst who frequently bashed his
company. By MARSHA GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-TEST (Undated) _ All of you who are patiently waiting for
the Chrysler PT Cruiser you ordered are going to love this: The
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration paid a premium to
buy two at a dealership in East Aurora, N.Y. This week, these two
cars will be smashed beyond repair as part of the government's
consumer crash-testing program. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-PASSAT (Undated) _ Make no mistake about it: Volkswagen is
back. The brand is not quite on top again, but it is pushing hard
to get there, thanks in part to the huge success of its New Beetle,
introduced just two years ago as a thoroughly modern car with a
retro look, and the hot-selling midsize Passat sedan, which has
topped the lists of best midsize cars in several recent consumer
automotive publications. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-LEXUS (Austin, Texas) _ When it comes to luxury sedans,
Lexus leaves most of its competitors scrambling to catch up. But
there has been something missing in the Lexus lineup: a true
driver's car that would appeal to younger buyers. Now there is a
Lexus that looks and feels like a sporty BMW 3-series car _ the IS
300, and it goes on sale at North American Lexus dealerships June
23. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   JAVA-CONFAB (San Francisco) _ Moscone Center will be jammed to
the rafters this week, crowded with over 20,000 Java enthusiasts in
town for the fifth annual JavaOne Conference, sponsored by Sun
Microsystems Inc. As usual, the show will launch with a keynote
address from Sun Micro's chairman, chief executive and spiritual
leader Scott McNealy Tuesday morning. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   EXCITE-AT-HOME (San Francisco) _ ExciteAtHome has certainly been
living up to its name in recent months. The broadband Internet
company's bucolic Redwood City, Calif., campus has become an
exciting home, indeed, since George Bell ascended to the position
of chief executive officer in January. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MARINES-BOOK (Undated) _ More than half a century ago, Gerry
West and Bob Addison took part in seven critical, bloody battles
under the canopied rain forests of the Solomon Islands. West and
Addison were Marines, members of the battalion known as Edson's
Raiders, more recently part of the publication of a history of
their battalion, the 345-page hardcover book ``Edson's Raiders.''
</P>
<P>
   By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO-BOOKS (Undated) _ ``As Nature Made Him: The Boy Who Was
Raised As A Girl,'' by John Colapinto, is a thoroughly researched
and skillfully told profile of David Reimer, the victim of a
botched circumcision in 1967. Colapinto received the National
Magazine Award for his abbreviated version of Reimer's saga, which
appeared in Rolling Stone. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-TIEMPOS (Undated) _ While most salsa/Caribbean music is
known for its spicy rhythms and danceable grooves, the music on
Ruben Blades' recent CD ``Tiempos'' is meant for the mind. The
Panamanian singer/songwriter says ``Tiempos'' is a mix of sounds
and influences, an ``effort to integrate different sounds from
Latin America to serve as a background for stories related to our
everyday life.'' By RAMIRO BURR.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ICE-CREAM (Undated) _ Today's electric ice-cream makers come in
a variety of sizes that are much smaller than early crank bucket
models. Some of the new space-saving devices can also be left out
on the counter, next to the toaster and breadmaking machine. By
FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The lake was glass, the oars
leaving little swirls with each stroke, and so quiet you could
almost hear the flowers bloom. Just then, 10 feet off the shore of
a small, nearby island, a raucous splash and squawk on the surface
snapped me to attention. I turned and spotted a washtub-sized swirl
on the lake surface, apparently from a giant bass, leaving a
five-foot ring, which then expanded across the surface like
dissipating sound waves. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The other morning the traffic
reporter for KCBS radio looked down on Highway 101 south of San
Francisco and reported that traffic was at a standstill. ``There's
no accident,'' he said. ``There are just too many cars.'' By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Judging Sister Jeannine: What
would Jesus say? Sister Gramick, while expressing her love for the
Catholic Church, simply refused to express any assent whatsoever to
the teaching of the Church on homosexuality. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   WEN-HO-LEE (San Francisco) _ The harsh treatment of Wen Ho Lee
has awakened and energized many Asian Americans who will no longer
be silent. For the past six months, Dr. Lee has been held in
solitary confinement, a target of a FBI investigation that to date
has produced no accusations of espionage. By THEODORE HSIEN WANG.
</P>
