<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LEXUS GOES AFTER YOUNGER MARKET WITH SPORTY MODEL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Lexus finally has built a BMW.
</P>
<P>
   Well, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Lexus, the luxury brand of Japan's largest automaker, Toyota,
entered the U.S. market in 1990 and soon set the benchmark for
luxury cars worldwide, leaving European stalwarts Mercedes-Benz,
BMW, Audi and Jaguar wringing their hands with worry.
</P>
<P>
   The LS 400 sedan, Lexus' flagship, soon led the luxury pack with
top overall quality ratings from J.D. Power &AMP; Associates, and both
the European and Japanese competitors were scrambling to catch up.
The U.S. luxury brands, meanwhile, weren't even in the running.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I say is that almost overnight, we went from a question
mark to a benchmark,'' said Mike Watson, a longtime U.S. Toyota
executive who has been involved with Lexus from the start.
</P>
<P>
   But Watson, Lexus' service and technical training manager, is
among those at Lexus who are the first to acknowledge that, at
least for some consumers, there has been something missing in the
Lexus lineup: a true driver's car that would appeal to younger,
more sport-oriented buyers. Buyers, they say, who would opt for a
bright-yellow BMW 328i, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time ever, there is a bright yellow Lexus,
and it looks and feels like a sporty BMW 3-series car.
</P>
<P>
   It's called the IS 300, and it goes on sale at North American
Lexus dealerships June 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 10 years, we've built our reputation by introducing quiet,
sophisticated luxurious cars,'' Lexus Marketing Manager Greg
Kitzens said during the recent national media launch of the IS 300
at the Barton Creek Resort in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, like Mercedes, our current lineup doesn't bring in many
customers under 40 years old,'' he said. ``So we recognize it's
time for Lexus to broaden its appeal an attract younger buyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome, then, the IS 300, with rear-wheel drive, an inline
six-cylinder engine (both longtime BMW attributes) and an
affordable price tag: $30,995, well-equipped.
</P>
<P>
   That puts the car in the same ballpark with the BMW 328i and
Audi A4, both of which are seen by younger consumers as truly fun
drivers' cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have six distinct model lines that accounted for
sales of nearly 186,000 units last year,'' Kitzens said.
</P>
<P>
   But to broaden Lexus' appeal, he said, ``We knew we needed a
sporty, stylish, performance-oriented car. We broke ground in this
area with the ($46,000) 1998 GS 400, which is the dream car of many
young people. But we wanted to introduce a performance Lexus that
the younger crowd could afford without resigning themselves to
eating 99-cent chalupas at Taco Bell every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Introduced more than a year ago in Europe as the IS 200, with a
smaller engine, the car already has become a hit overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lexus rolls out the IS 300 for the U.S. market, sporting
bold looks similar to a German sports sedan and carrying a
3.0-liter six-cylinder engine that cranks out 215 horsepower and
218 foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   That's more power than found in either the BMW 328i, with 193
horsepower and 206 foot-pounds of torque, or the A4, with 190
horsepower and 207 foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   The IS 300 beats both of those competitors in zero to 60 mph
performance. The Lexus reaches 60 mph in 7.1 seconds, compared with
7.2 seconds for the BMW and 8.4 seconds for the A4. There is a
sportier version of the A4, called the S4, but it costs $37,000 and
comes with a turbocharged 2.7-liter engine.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the IS 300 will be offered only with a five-speed
automatic transmission, but a five-speed manual is scheduled for
sometime next year for those who want even sportier performance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the automatic has a clutchless manual-shift option
similar to Audi's Tiptronic transmission that lets the driver
choose when to move to another gear.
</P>
<P>
   As Lexus' first offering in the entry-level sporty sedan
segment, the IS 300 has no loyal owner base to draw from, Kitzens
said. Lexus is breaking new ground here.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we might attract a few current Lexus owners looking for
something new, for the most part the IS 300 customer will be
someone who's never entered our dealerships before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He or she is someone who sped right past a Lexus store driving
a BMW or (Acura) Integra, maybe glancing to see if their dad had
dropped off his LS 400 for service. But now, it's our job to lure
this buyer in.''
</P>
<P>
   The target IS 300 buyer, Kitzens said, generally will be male,
35-40 years old, married, highly educated, with a median household
income of $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This person likes to drive,'' he said. ``He or she has an
active lifestyle, participates in sports, and is techno-savvy, but
is perhaps looking for an alternative to a typical yuppiemobile.''
</P>
<P>
   Lexus plans an entirely separate marketing campaign focusing on
the IS 300, integrating traditional media such as newspapers,
magazines and television with an increased presence on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the company launched its IS 300 ad campaign via its
www.lexus.com Web site, offering Web surfers the opportunity to win
an IS 300 by designing their own TV commercial for the car.
</P>
<P>
   On June 29, the winning commercial will be shown during ``Who
Wants to be a Millionaire.'' Both the person who wrote the ad, as
well as someone who voted in the contest, will win new IS 300s, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet ads kicked off the IS 300 campaign theme:
``sufficiently radical.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The scenarios in our national and dealer ads depict people who
live life on the edge and are about to go over the top,'' Kitzens
said. ``The IS 300 is shown as a vehicle that provides sufficient
stimulation in one's life, avoiding the need to resort to drastic
behavior. We think these ads will position the car as daring and
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, he said, the IS 300 offers ``flashy styling and
amenities such as the in-dash, six-disc CD stereo system. Add in
the competitive price as well as Lexus' reputation for quality, and
this car is poised for success.''
</P>
<P>
   Lexus already has proved that it can cut into the sales of
German luxury cars, but it remains to be seen whether the brand can
make inroads where BMW and Audi clearly have held the edge _ in
lower-end, sporty performance cars that appeal to youthful buyers.
</P>
<P>
   If Lexus predictions are accurate, the company will sell 25,000
of the IS 300 in North America annually. And probably, many of
those will be the bright yellow one, Lexus officials said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
