<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-PASSAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WITH SPIFFY PASSAT, VW IS ON A ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A $31,000 Volkswagen?
</P>
<P>
   That's 15 times what I paid for my first Volkswagen, back in the
days when you could buy a brand-new Beetle for about $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   But, then, Volkswagen has come a long way from its humble U.S.
beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, during VW's heyday in the 1960s, the Beetle was
quite a fad, and Volkswagen dealers were among the snootiest people
around. I remember that the VW dealership where I grew up was so
independent that the management wouldn't let customers anywhere
near the service department.
</P>
<P>
   You dropped your car off out in front of the dealership, and a
white-uniformed attendant took it away into the secret complex in
the rear, where, presumably, other white-uniformed people performed
magic on it to get it running well again.
</P>
<P>
   With the huge influx of Japanese imports in the '70s, consumers
suddenly got spoiled. The Japanese cars didn't have to go back to
the dealership every few weeks (or days) for service; they actually
held up for a long, long time with very little maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   People weary of all the maintenance headaches with their little
German VWs turned to the Japanese cars, and the rest, as they say,
is history. VW dealerships fell onto hard times, and many went out
of business. The Beetle fad was over.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the best-selling cars in the United States are Japanese
models _ the Toyota Camry and Honda Accord.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake about it: Volkswagen is back. The brand is
not quite on top again, but it is pushing hard to get there, thanks
in part to the huge success of its New Beetle, introduced just two
years ago as a thoroughly modern car with a retro look.
</P>
<P>
   The New Beetle isn't the only reason VW is enjoying a new era of
popularity with U.S. consumers, however. One key to that success is
the hot-selling midsize Passat sedan, which has topped the lists of
best midsize cars in several recent consumer automotive
publications _ not the least of which is Consumer Reports.
</P>
<P>
   I generally don't put a lot of stock into what Consumer Reports
has to say about cars, but at least on this point I am pretty much
in agreement: The Passat is an outstanding family sedan, and most
definitely one of the finest midsize cars on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I'm not sure I'm ready to pay $31,000 for a Passat, which
was the price tag on our test car: the 2000 Passat GLX 4Motion
sedan with all-wheel drive. Thankfully, you really don't have to
pay $31,000 to get a nice Passat; prices for the base GLS four-door
begin at just over $21,000.
</P>
<P>
   But if you have an extra few bucks to spend, and you want a car
that rivals similarly priced luxury models from VW's sister, Audi,
as well as BMW, Volvo, Saab and Mercedes-Benz, then perhaps this
vehicle is the one for you.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, luxury models. This Passat is nothing like any Volkswagen
of the past. Forget the cheap, affordable ``people's car'' image of
VW, and think high-end, premium-quality motorcar.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath, of course, the Passat shares basic components with
the premium Audi A4, including engines and transmissions. There are
differences, however. The Audi is a bit shorter and somewhat more
compact, but the Passat is truly a midsize sedan with room for five
adults.
</P>
<P>
   And it is certainly well equipped. Air conditioning, which was
virtually unheard of on the Beetle and other early VW products, is
standard here, of course, and it's not just a basic manual system.
This is automatic climate control.
</P>
<P>
   Also included are power windows and door locks (never in a
Beetle!), power mirrors with an anti-fog system, a tilt and
telescopic steering wheel, and for $1,075 extra (included on our
test car), the five-speed Tiptronic automatic transmission like the
one used in Porsches. This transmission allows the driver to shift
manually (without a clutch), or it will do the shifting on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Other amenities that would have been foreign to the original
Beetle, but which are standard on the Passat GLX (accounting for
much of the price difference from the GLS model), include leather
interior, genuine wood interior trim, cruise control, front and
side air bags for the front occupants, four-wheel disc anti-lock
brakes, the great-sounding Monsoon audio system with eight
speakers, a power glass moon roof, multifunction trip computer, and
heated seats and windshield-washer nozzles.
</P>
<P>
   The only options on our test car were the automatic transmission
and the 4Motion full-time all-wheel-drive system ($1,650), which is
offered on the Passat for the first time this year. This is the
same system found on the Audi.
</P>
<P>
   The base Passat comes with a 1.8-liter, 20-valve turbocharged
four-cylinder engine, similar to the one offered in the New Beetle,
rated at 150 horsepower and 155 foot-pounds of torque. But the GLX
comes only with the 2.8-liter, 30-valve V-6, which turns out 190
horsepower and 206 foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   This is a smooth engine with plenty of power for quick starting
and freeway merging. But even the base engine, with one of the most
unobtrusive turbochargers I've experienced, offers plenty of zip,
with much better fuel economy as a plus (up to 23 miles per gallon
in the city and 32 on the highway).
</P>
<P>
   Road handling is one of the great features of this vehicle,
particularly the all-wheel-drive model. The car is extremely
sure-footed in tight turns, and there is no wheel slippage on
acceleration. No, it's not a sports car, but sometimes it feels
like it's as close to one as you can get with a sedan.
</P>
<P>
   The Passat's ride is very smooth, and the cabin is very quiet,
even at freeway speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Other standard features on the GLX include power rack-and-pinion
steering, an anti-theft system for the vehicle and the audio
system, anti-intrusion side-door beams, integrated front fog lamps,
comfort seats with height and lumbar adjustments up front,
rain-sensing automatic wiper speed-control, and child safety
rear-door locks.
</P>
<P>
   Total sticker for our test car was $30,905, including $525
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings for the V-6 engine with automatic
transmission are 17 miles per gallon in the city and 24 mpg on the
highway. The tank holds 16.4 gallons of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
