<HEADER>
A4903 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CRASH-TEST-HNS &LR;      06-05 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-TEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAFETY AGENCY PAYS PREMIUM TO BUY POPULAR CHRYSLER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All of you who are patiently waiting for the Chrysler PT Cruiser
you ordered, which the dealer said will take four to six months to
receive, are going to love this:
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, an arm of
the federal government, went out shopping for a couple of PT
Cruisers last month and, after looking east and west, north and
south, came up with not one, but two, at a dealership in East
Aurora, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA's shopper bought both of them _ at a premium of about
$10,000 over the manufacturer's sticker price for each one.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect to see any happy bureaucrats cruising around in
these Cruisers with U.S. government license plates on them.
</P>
<P>
   These two Cruisers are destined for the scrap heap.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday and Thursday, these two cars will be smashed beyond
repair as part of the government's consumer crash-testing program,
agency spokesman Rae Tyson said in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The first, for which the government paid $28,900, will undergo a
side-impact test in which the testing lab simulates the impact of
another car T-boning the Cruiser at 38.5 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   This particular PT Cruiser comes with the optional side air bags
for the front occupants, so NHTSA can gauge how well those work in
protecting the driver and front passenger.
</P>
<P>
   In the second test, a Cruiser that the government paid $27,500
for will be crashed head-on into a concrete barrier at 35 mph to
test how occupants would fare in such an accident.
</P>
<P>
   The government will rate the PT Cruiser on front and side
impacts on a scale of one to five stars, with five being the best.
Tyson said the results will be posted on NHTSA's consumer Web site
at www.nhtsa.gov probably no later than July 1.
</P>
<P>
   If you are planning to buy one of the PT Cruisers, you might
want to wait to see how well it fares in the crash tests, Tyson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The dealer who sold the cars to the government said he had one
of them in stock and had been using it as a demonstrator, and the
second one was on order when the NHTSA shopper came in looking for
two of the Cruisers.
</P>
<P>
   The government doesn't buy cars from the manufacturer for crash
testing; it goes out and buys them from dealers just like retail
customers would, Tyson said. ``That way we know the vehicles are
representative of what consumers are buying.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, the dealership _ Delia Car Co. _ wasn't told up
front who the buyer would be or what would become of the cars, but
he knew before the sale was completed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I knew before I gave them the cars what they were going
to do, and it really doesn't bother me,'' said the dealership's
manager, August Delia. ``We still have one of them here; they
haven't picked it up yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Delia acknowledged that the cars are in short supply and that
customers are clamoring for them, but he said he felt that the
crash tests were a worthy cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lots of people waiting for the Cruisers, and we've
told them to expect to wait about six months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government appreciates Delia's gesture in selling the cars
for the crash tests, Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he did us a favor,'' Tyson said. ``We made the
decision to get the crash tests done as soon as possible, even
knowing that availability was going to be a problem. We looked out
West and down South and found there would be a long wait. But we
felt timeliness was important.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's hard to see two perfectly good, brand-new,
hot-selling cars totaled on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The government won't have to take the cars very far to have the
tests done, Tyson said. East Aurora is a suburb of Buffalo, N.Y.,
home of the independent laboratory that NHTSA uses for such tests.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   FORD DELAYS NEW SUV MODELS
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. said this week it will delay introduction of the
larger, redesigned four-door Explorer sport utility vehicle from
this fall until early next year. Manufacture of the new models will
not begin until late this year, and the vehicles will go on sale in
late winter or early spring as 2002 models.
</P>
<P>
   The redesigned vehicles, which replace the current generation
Explorer and its upscale clone, the Mercury Mountaineer, originally
were to have gone on sale later this year as 2001 models.
</P>
<P>
   Ford blamed the delay on quality issues concerning ``fit and
finish'' of the trucks, which have been the nation's best-selling
passenger vehicles since shortly after their introduction in 1990.
</P>
