<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAVA-CONFAB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JAVA CONFERENCE BEGINS IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Some 20,000 Java enthusiasts will be in San
Francisco this week for the fifth JavaOne Conference, sponsored by
Sun Microsystems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Java has nothing to do with coffee. It is a computer programming
language, developed by Sun Microsystems in the mid-1990s as a
building tool for Internet-based applications.
</P>
<P>
   Although developed by Sun, the language's building blocks have
been distributed freely over the years in an effort to develop
software programmers who use it.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has worked. Java-based applications rule the Internet,
and the language is favored by hand-held device programmers, as
well, fueling application for 3Com's popular Palm Pilots and other
personal digital assistants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use it almost continuously,'' said Bill Rowe, a 40-year-old
Java programmer from Westborough, Mass. ``I started about five
years ago and now it's essential to the way I operate.''
</P>
<P>
   It has also become essential for software and Internet companies
to keep a stable of Java programmers on call, or better yet, in
house.
</P>
<P>
   That demand has resulted in huge increase in programmers'
salaries. A recent survey conducted by the Java Pro Web site, in
concert with the Wilson Research firm, showed the average
compensation for Java professionals worldwide was $73,000 a year,
and $86,400 in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Java programming community is growing very rapidly,'' said
Mike Kaul, the chief executive of HotDispatch, a Mountain
View-based Java start-up that offers programmers a forum for
exchanging tips and solutions to programming problems on line.
``They're in high demand and are paid very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies like HotDispatch consider JavaOne the event of the
year. ``It makes all kinds of sense to be there. Everyone who's
everybody in the Java universe will be there,'' Kaul said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bill Gee, vice president of marketing for Sun's
software products and platforms, ``We have over 300 companies
exhibiting on the floor, which is also way up from last year. We
sold out about six weeks ago and have a waiting list.''
</P>
<P>
   On premise will be a nine-hole mini-golf course, pingpong
tables, air hockey and twice-nightly live performances of the
television show ``Win Ben Stein's Money.'' The entertainment side
of things will peak on Thursday night, with a performance from rock
band Blues Traveler at the San Francisco Exhibition Concourse.
</P>
<P>
   Sun chairman and chief executive Scott McNealy will address the
convention Tuesday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
