<HEADER>
A4927 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EXPENSE-ACCOUNTS-HNS &LR;      06-05 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPENSE-ACCOUNTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CREATIVE EXPENSE REPORT WINS `DILBERT'-LIKE PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The guy who expensed his Chicago hotel room for
$2,788 after a kielbasa sausage dinner caught on fire and nearly
burned the place down almost won. And the Texas auditor reimbursed
for the rental of an elephant almost took the grand prize too.
</P>
<P>
   But the winning entry in the funniest expense report contest
came from the Lake Oswego, Ore., marketing manager who wrote off
two voodoo dolls: He had bought them to curse an industry analyst
who frequently bashed his company.
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the competition, ``Dilbert'' cartoonist Scott
Adams, called the voodoo doll story submitted by Dan Wolff ``a
wonderful blend of inappropriate spending and malicious intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect Dan Wolff to go far in management,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff wiped more than 100 other competitors off the expense
account books in a national Internet contest called ``Laughing at
Your Expense,'' the results of which were published Monday. Entries
were submitted to Freeworks.com, a Mountain View-based Internet
company that specializes in streamlining administrative tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Contestants were asked to write essays of up to 150 words
describing their most creative business expense reports, and give
voice to the ``cubicle-constrained workers of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner, said Adams, had to make him laugh and to demonstrate
an appropriate amount of chutzpah.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to be trying to get away with something,'' Adams
said. ``And the more bizarre, the better. If it was something cruel
and unusual, even better yet.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Wolff was working in the Portland branch of a San
Rafael, Calif.-based software company when he and a vice president
were sent to a conference in New Orleans. While strolling by the
Rev. Zombie's House of Voodoo, Wolff was grumbling about the
industry analyst when he got a brilliant idea:
</P>
<P>
   Buy a voodoo doll and curse the wickedly unfair critic, whom he
humorously recalled as ``the embodiment of evil analysts whom we
lived in fear of and hated.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolff's vice president was delighted with the concept. He picked
out a doll and handed it to Wolff with this blessing: ``Expense
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolff spent $70 for two dolls, and another $1 for two sets of
coffin nails. He would use the one doll, and just for good measure,
send the other to the poor public relations chief who had to deal
with the dreaded analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, whose popular cartoon strip lambastes management and
lampoons the idiosyncrasies of the work world, said deciding on a
winner was tough, considering the competition. Among the other
competitors:
</P>
<P>
   _ Kathryn Scott, an internal auditor from Amarillo, Texas, who
submitted a $2,500 expense for renting an elephant, which she used
to pull heavy machinery out of the mud.
</P>
<P>
   _ A technology consultant whose colleague expensed $200 in beer
while on a business trip in Germany. This expense was approved,
although a $7 movie rental was turned down because it was against
company policy to reimburse for such entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This went all the way up to the chief financial officer,''
said Ann Garcia, the consultant from San Carlos, Calif. ``We're
talking about $7 for an expense and a bunch of people who are
making a couple of hundred grand a year.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A police officer was reimbursed for condoms, which he said
were for use on duty. The department's bomb squad uses water-filled
condoms to disrupt the internal circuits of a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Freeworks is giving Wolff and his wife, Suzy, a weekend in San
Francisco and dinner with Adams at Stacey's Cafe, a restaurant that
Adams co-owns.
</P>
<P>
   After Wolff was reimbursed for the voodoo dolls, he chickened
out when it came time to do the curse. The analyst is alive and
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of mine from New Orleans wouldn't even touch it,''
Wolff said. ``He told me, `We don't mess around with voodoo.' It
sort of made us feel odd about using it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
