<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICELINE FOR GROCERIES SAVES MONEY, SQUANDERS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Like so many bargain opportunities these days, Priceline.com's
new online bid-for-groceries service forces users to decide which
is more important: time or money.
</P>
<P>
   The service offers real savings over supermarket prices on
brand-name items, but requires users to spend more time shopping
and in the checkout lane.
</P>
<P>
   In short, there's a tradeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Deena Ferguson of Greenfield, Mass., put it well: ``I have found
it to be both a colossal pain in the neck and a great way to save
money.''
</P>
<P>
   The savings are what draw you in and keep you coming back.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline WebHouse Club, a private affiliate of Priceline.com,
started doing business in the Boston area in mid-March. It already
has 25,000 members here and plans to expand nationally later this
year. The company says the average customer saves about $15 per
shopping trip.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works. After signing up and giving Priceline your
credit-card information, you start shopping. The first 90 days are
free; after that, you pay $3 a month for months in which you use
the service.
</P>
<P>
   Say you want yogurt. Priceline gives you one size (8-ounce
containers) and three brands to choose from (Dannon, Colombo, and
Breyers). You have to choose at least two brands, but the odds of
having your bid accepted go up if you are willing to accept any of
the three.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline says the typical price for yogurt is 79 cents to 83
cents per container. It lets you choose whether you want to pay 65
cents (odds for success are put at 90 percent), 59 cents (75
percent), 50 cents (65 percent), 45 cents (50 percent), or submit
your own bid.
</P>
<P>
   I tried 50 cents and 45 cents with no success. You have to wait
24 hours before submitting a new bid. My 59-cent bid for three
containers was accepted, and the winning brand was Colombo. My
credit card was immediately charged, and I was given 90 days to
pick up my purchase at a participating Stop &AMP; Shop, Star Market,
Big Y, or A&AMP;P supermarket. Shaw's is expected to join soon.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline issues each customer a debit card. When you go through
the supermarket checkout, the groceries are scanned in the usual
way, and you use the debit card, which matches the groceries
scanned to what you've already paid for through Priceline.
</P>
<P>
   With Colombo selling for 75 cents a container last week at the
Stop &AMP; Shop in Quincy, Mass., I saved 16 cents per container by
shopping on Priceline. My biggest savings was $4.30 on a jumbo
package of Pampers diapers.
</P>
<P>
   For items that don't have multiple brands (milk, vegetables,
many meats), Priceline requires you to use half-price tokens. The
tokens, which also can be used on other items, guarantee bidding
success and substantial price savings.
</P>
<P>
   A gallon of milk, for example, cost $1.47 with one token. Perdue
boneless, skinless chicken breasts cost $2.13 a pound with two
tokens, instead of $4.99 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   There is even some price protection with Priceline. If your
local supermarket has an item on sale for less than what you paid
with Priceline, Priceline says it will make up the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline also currently honors all manufacturer's coupons and
swallows bottle and can deposits, but those benefits aren't likely
to last. Priceline spokesman Robert Padgett says coupon acceptance
will be phased out over the next two weeks, and the deposit
benefit's days are numbered.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem most consumers have with Priceline is that
it takes a lot of work to get the savings and, if you're not
careful, the whole process can end up being more trouble than it's
worth.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, a Priceline customer shops twice _ once online and
again at the store. You even have to check out twice at the store,
once with your Priceline items and a second time with any items you
decide to buy in the store that you didn't purchase through
Priceline.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Prybot of Gloucester says it takes an extra 15 to 20
minutes for her to shop online with Priceline. Daniel Smith of
Norwood says he gets dirty looks from the customers behind him in
line while he pays for his Priceline groceries and then repeats the
process for his other items.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with Priceline can get complicated. Gerald McCullough of
Westborough says it took him more than six weeks to extract credits
out of Priceline for coupons he had used. He also was charged sales
tax on items that are exempt from sales tax in Massachusetts, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Others have complained about how Priceline handles sales of
taxable items. The company collects sales tax on what Priceline
says is the prevailing price for the item in Massachusetts, not
what the customer actually pays for it or even what the supermarket
charges. The Massachusetts Revenue Department, which disagrees with
that approach, is currently investigating.
</P>
<P>
   While the savings with Priceline are respectable, several
consumers wondered how big they really are.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Nelson, for example, bought a box of Trix recently on
Priceline for $2.87. That represented a substantial savings over
the regular Stop &AMP; Shop price of $3.19, but it didn't look so good
when compared to the Shaw's price of $2.50.
</P>
<P>
   In my yogurt example above, I paid 59 cents for an 8-ounce
container of Colombo yogurt, a savings of 16 cents over the regular
Stop &AMP; Shop price. I could have bought the Stop &AMP; Shop brand of
yogurt for 50 cents and saved even more money. On every item I
purchased, in fact, a generic version could be purchased for less
than my winning bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that Priceline is for people who buy name
brands at full retail price. For those who look for sales or buy
store brands or make a trip to Wal-Mart for toiletries or
detergents, Priceline is not going to do you a lot of good,'' says
Rich Griggs of Taunton.
</P>
<P>
   The half-price tokens are another source of frustration. They
offer great savings, but many consumers see them as annoying
teases. You get six tokens for free when you start. To get more,
you have to buy them (six for $12.95), refer potential new members
(two tokens for four e-mail addresses), or sign on with a Priceline
partner. (Priceline is able to offer lower token prices because its
partners put up the money.) By buying a $25 subscription to Star
magazine, for example, you can get 12 tokens.
</P>
<P>
   By far the biggest complaint I hear from consumers is that you
have to take the brand and size Priceline gives you. While the
restriction is understandable, and for many people and many items
no big deal, it still can be annoying.
</P>
<P>
   As Susan White of West Yarmouth says: ``For many items, there is
only one brand that is acceptable to both me and the kids. My
9-year-old son can pick out the only spaghetti sauce he's willing
to eat in a blind taste test.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Mohl is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached at
617-474-2510, by e-mail at mohl(at) globe.com, or at The Boston
Globe, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
