<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4944 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-AUDIO-BOOKS-HNS &LR;      06-05 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `NATURE' TAPE MAKES THE BOOK ALL THE MORE COMPELLING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``As Nature Made Him: The Boy Who Was Raised As A Girl'' by John
Colapinto; read by Howard McGillin; abridged, approximately 5
hours; Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio; $24.
</P>
<P>
   This thoroughly researched and skillfully told profile of David
Reimer deserves to be an early candidate for best nonfiction book
of the year. Colapinto received the National Magazine Award for his
abbreviated version of Reimer's saga, which he detailed in Rolling
Stone a couple of years ago. ``As Nature Made Him'' is the rest of
that compelling story, including actual names and additional
horrifying details.
</P>
<P>
   Reimer, an identical twin, was the victim of a botched
circumcision in 1967. His parents, just older than teen-agers
themselves, followed the advice of medical experts and agreed to a
radical treatment, surgically altering their son to live as a girl.
</P>
<P>
   It was hailed as a landmark case by the physician championing
Reimer's sexual reassignment, Dr. John Money at Johns Hopkins
University, as well as by feminists eager to tout nurture over
nature. But Reimer was never in the least comfortable being female,
which Dr. Money refused to admit, and late in adolescence went
through an excruciating series of operations (including a double
mastectomy) to have his gender reversed once again.
</P>
<P>
   Few abridged audio books make me want to pick up the text in its
entirety. William Least Heat Moon's travelogue ``River Horse,'' is
the only other recent book on tape I can think of that is so
riveting and well done that any modification of the original seems
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Squandering Aimlessly: My Adventures in the American
Marketplace'' by David Brancaccio; read by the author; abridged,
approximately 3 hours; Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio; $18
</P>
<P>
   I like the National Public Radio weekday business program
``Marketplace,'' which David Brancaccio hosts. And I enjoy
Brancaccio on that eclectic, often informative, award-winning show.
</P>
<P>
   But I have had a difficult time listening to ``Marketplace''
ever since I popped Brancaccio's first book into the car stereo.
This purports to be the author's financial pilgrimage, a
cross-country trip that details how we Americans spend, invest and
save our money.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: It doesn't work, perhaps because this is a heavily
edited version of the author's book, perhaps because the author
badly needed an editor he didn't have. Brancaccio's travels, from
Minnesota's Mall of America to Wall Street, could better be titled
``Wandering Aimlessly.'' While he regularly deploys routines used
during ``Marketplace,'' such as ``Let's take a look at the
numbers,'' he also goes off on tangents during different segments,
leaving the listener wondering what happened to the storyline.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay It Forward'' by Catherine Ryan Hyde; read by Debra Monk,
with Leland Gantt, Enid Graham, Michael McGlone, Liam Norton, Anne
Pitoniak, Sharon Quinn and Gordon Weiss; abridged, approximately 4
hours; Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio; $23
</P>
<P>
   This simple story, about a 12-year-old boy who innocently hopes
he can change the world by doing good deeds and manages to have far
more impact than anyone could possibly have guessed, is in the
process of being made into a movie starring Kevin Spacey, Helen
Hunt and Angie Dickinson. That blockbuster cast almost assures it
of a lot of attention, possibly more than it merits.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Pay It Forward'' is not quite as simple as it sounds:
Choose three people for whom you want to do a favor, and when they
ask to pay you back, tell them to ``pay it forward'' instead, to
find three people who they can help. It's a pyramid scheme of sorts
designed to generate goodwill in all directions.
</P>
<P>
   I won't give away the ending of this inspirational tale, which
has surprisingly well developed minor characters, but let me give
two words of advice to folks planning to see ``Pay It Forward'' in
the theaters: Take Kleenex.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
