<HEADER>
A4945 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-LANGSIDE-AZR &LR;      06-05 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGSIDE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SLUG-LANGSIDE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    INTERNET LANGUAGE CREATES HYBRID OF SPEECH, WRITING(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: SIDEBAR to LANGUAGE. Moving in ``A'' and
``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BARBARA YOST(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Susan Herring, associate professor of linguistics at the
University of Texas-Arlington, has been studying correspondence
from the Internet since before it was the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The computer network was initially called the ARPANET. Estimated
date of birth: 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Herring acquired transcripts of ARPANET
discussion groups from the 1970s and began to study them to see how
e-mail has influenced language.
</P>
<P>
   With that research, she launched the field of computer discourse
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Herring was looking at several factors in network and e-mail
language: etiquette, formality/informality, grammatical complexity,
errors.
</P>
<P>
   Her findings include:
</P>
<P>
   Sentence structure is simple but has not devolved into
fragments.
</P>
<P>
   Slang has become more prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discourse markers'' usually found only in the spoken word are
common: ``oh,'' ``hey.''
</P>
<P>
   Errors decreased slightly over time.
</P>
<P>
   Herring found distinctions between the writing used in chat-room
discussions and that in e-mail. The former is less formal and
contains more typographical errors, abbreviations and simple
sentences as people type quickly to keep up with real-time
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail writers take more time to review their messages and clean
up errors. Formality depends on the recipient and purpose of the
message.
</P>
<P>
   In general, correspondence over the computer is a hybrid of
traditional writing and the spoken word. Chat rooms fall closer to
speech, while e-mail is more like writing.
</P>
<P>
   New words are being invented rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer technology is the biggest supplier of (new)
vocabulary,'' Herring says.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains to be seen how many of those words seep into
common usage. Some have already come and gone - ARPANET, ``FTP''
(file transfer protocol) and gopher. The latter two are file
retrieval terms that predate the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Another trend Herring has noted is the evolution of spelling as
words fall into common usage. Upper case is abandoned, hyphens drop
out. In many circles, Internet is no longer capitalized. E-mail is
often spelled ``email.''
</P>
<P>
   Old words take on new meaning. ``Spam'' once referred only to
the Hormel processed meat product. Now it denotes unwanted,
``junk'' e-mail and is both noun and verb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flame'' once referred to actual fire or was a slang term for
flamboyant homosexuality. In computer talk, it now means a message
sent with hostile content. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4946 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS &LR;      06-05 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL YOU NEED IS LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   StockGift.com makes perfect sense. But it feels all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   This is a generational problem. Anyone who remembers the Beatles
live on the Ed Sullivan show is probably going to have trouble with
an online wedding gift registry set up to give the happy couple
shares of Microsoft. Or Lycos. Or AT&AMP;T. Or whatever makes their
portfolio sing.
</P>
<P>
   The service, started in February by Gino Heilizer out of
Washington, D.C., is similar to a department store gift registry,
except that instead of toasters, glassware, and china patterns, it
lists stocks and mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of selecting an item, gift givers pledge money that goes
into an account the bride and groom will use to buy their
investments. If someone wants to transfer shares of stock from an
outside brokerage account, that can be arranged, too.
</P>
<P>
   Click, click, click and the deals are done, complete with an
electronic gift card. Also available for christenings, bar
mitzvahs, birthdays, and anniversaries. Cost to the recipients is
$19.95 per stock or fund, and they can choose up to four. Cost to
the giver is a 2.95 percent transaction fee on credit cards and
nothing for checks.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's not to like? This is a new millennium, practicality
is king, and Ed Sullivan is dead.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that some of us are unreconstituted romantics who
mist up over the wrapping paper in the Hallmark store. We spring
for the bows with the tacky bells attached and have invested
heavily in crystal over the years because, as our grandmothers used
to say, ``It means something.''
</P>
<P>
   Heilizer's sigh is as heavy as Waterford. ``People are very busy
and don't have time to buy gifts,'' says the 31-year-old
entrepreneur, who got his idea while planning his wedding two years
ago. He and his wife didn't need anything, but set up a traditional
gift registry as a convenience for friends and relatives. When his
wife put a cheese grater on their list just to fill the space,
Heilizer hit the wall and decided to change the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those defining moments in life,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But what's wrong with a cheese grater, Gino? Not in the same
class with crystal, certainly, but a nice grater with a wooden
handle and different settings for strings, shreds, and chunks could
be pretty darn swell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asking people to spend money to come to my wedding and
also to waste money on gadgets we didn't need,'' explains Heilizer,
a man on a mission, who has 250 people registered on his site.
``I'm frugal. I drive a 10-year-old car.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Magee, 30, and Malachy Beare, 32, a Boston couple who
registered with StockGift.com for their August wedding, ply an
antiquated mind-set with more logic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have a lot of the items couples traditionally
request on bridal registries, since we've been living on our own
and together for some time,'' notes Magee, who has a wedding Web
page with a link to StockGift.com. The StockGift site also features
a page on the couple, as it does for all registrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking people to contribute to our future and our
children's future,'' says Beare.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't it a little cold asking people for money?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some stocks are very hot,'' quips Beare, whose registry lists
Microsoft, Cisco, and Motorola. ``And if you have a gift registry
at a department store, you're asking people for money.''
</P>
<P>
   Heilizer tries to put it in reassuring baby boomer terms:
``Think of it as a US Savings Bond, only better.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, well, maybe. But where is the joy of surprise? Where is
the spontaneity in the housewares department? What about intriguing
packages arriving in the mail? And does this mean nobody will laugh
for years to come at Uncle Charlie's taste?
</P>
<P>
   OK, an attic can have too much Uncle Charlie in it. But even a
hideous candy dish has a unique memory and some humanity clinging
to it.
</P>
<P>
   Can a stock certificate ever feel the same? That probably
depends on the eye of the investor _ or maybe it's the ear.
</P>
<P>
   I don't care too much for money
</P>
<P>
   Money can't buy me love
</P>
<P>
   Can't buy me love. Everybody tells me so.
</P>
<P>
   Can't buy me love. No, no, no no!
</P>
<P>
   Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4947 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-LANGSIDE-AZR &LR;      06-05 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGSIDE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SLUG-LANGSIDE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    INTERNET LANGUAGE CREATES HYBRID OF SPEECH, WRITING(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: SIDEBAR to LANGUAGE. Moving in ``A'' and
``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BARBARA YOST(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Susan Herring, associate professor of linguistics at the
University of Texas-Arlington, has been studying correspondence
from the Internet since before it was the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The computer network was initially called the ARPANET. Estimated
date of birth: 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Herring acquired transcripts of ARPANET
discussion groups from the 1970s and began to study them to see how
e-mail has influenced language.
</P>
<P>
   With that research, she launched the field of computer discourse
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Herring was looking at several factors in network and e-mail
language: etiquette, formality/informality, grammatical complexity,
errors.
</P>
<P>
   Her findings include:
</P>
<P>
   Sentence structure is simple but has not devolved into
fragments.
</P>
<P>
   Slang has become more prevalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discourse markers'' usually found only in the spoken word are
common: ``oh,'' ``hey.''
</P>
<P>
   Errors decreased slightly over time.
</P>
<P>
   Herring found distinctions between the writing used in chat-room
discussions and that in e-mail. The former is less formal and
contains more typographical errors, abbreviations and simple
sentences as people type quickly to keep up with real-time
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail writers take more time to review their messages and clean
up errors. Formality depends on the recipient and purpose of the
message.
</P>
<P>
   In general, correspondence over the computer is a hybrid of
traditional writing and the spoken word. Chat rooms fall closer to
speech, while e-mail is more like writing.
</P>
<P>
   New words are being invented rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer technology is the biggest supplier of (new)
vocabulary,'' Herring says.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains to be seen how many of those words seep into
common usage. Some have already come and gone - ARPANET, ``FTP''
(file transfer protocol) and gopher. The latter two are file
retrieval terms that predate the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Another trend Herring has noted is the evolution of spelling as
words fall into common usage. Upper case is abandoned, hyphens drop
out. In many circles, Internet is no longer capitalized. E-mail is
often spelled ``email.''
</P>
<P>
   Old words take on new meaning. ``Spam'' once referred only to
the Hormel processed meat product. Now it denotes unwanted,
``junk'' e-mail and is both noun and verb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flame'' once referred to actual fire or was a slang term for
flamboyant homosexuality. In computer talk, it now means a message
sent with hostile content. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
