 &HT;    NEW &AMP; NOTABLE(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING in ``E'' and ``L'' categories) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By ANNE STEPHENSON(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your story goes here.
</P>
<P>
   ``WALL''
</P>
<P>
   By Andy Goldsworthy
</P>
<P>
   (Abrams, $35)
</P>
<P>
   The work of British artist Andy Goldsworthy is a wonderful
collaboration between man and nature, based in a vision that takes
eccentric liberties with ordinary things - leaves, rocks, thorns,
icicles, even raindrops. Goldsworthy has written other books, but
none more appealing than this one about a sculpture he created at
New York's Storm King Art Center during 1997 and 1998. Called Wall
that went for a walk, (CORRECT: Wall that went for a walk) it is a
2,278-foot stone wall that swirls voluptuously around trees and
juts across fields, plunging, at one point, into a lake and
reemerging on its far shore. At places on the wall, Goldsworthy has
set huge boulders in the stone - they seem to levitate, odd gems in
unlikely settings. Also here are photos of the many ``ephemeral''
artworks (the shelf life is brief, when you're working with wet
leaves) Goldsworthy created as the wall progressed. If you've never
seen his work, go to a bookstore and look at this, then take a
walk. You'll never see nature in quite the same way again.
</P>
<P>
   ``ME TALK PRETTY ONE DAY''
</P>
<P>
   By David Sedaris
</P>
<P>
   (Little, Brown, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   At New &AMP; Notable, we pride ourselves on our decorum, so we blush
to tell you that we started chuckling on Page 6, and were howling
and weeping by Page 24. This admission will come back to haunt us,
of course, but there you have it. We'll even say straight out that
David Sedaris is one of the funniest writers working today. It's
true that the pieces in this book are not as edgy (his critics
would say ``profane'' or ``vicious'') as those in his previous
collections, ``Naked'' and ``Barrel Fever.'' Some of his fans will
be disappointed by that, but we were not, nor were we put off by
the fact that Sedaris writes almost exclusively about himself - his
droll, often beleaguered persona is the ticket to the biggest
laughs. Best of all, Sedaris is a writer, not a comedian. He tells
stories, and you'd be hard pressed to pull one-liners from them
because there is humor in every word. If you read this book and
don't think it's funny, we do not want to hear about it. Now excuse
us while we reread page 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``REFLECTIONS IN BLACK''
</P>
<P>
   By Deborah Willis
</P>
<P>
   (Norton, $50)
</P>
<P>
   ``Our history,'' Richard Wright said, ``is far stranger than you
suspect, and we are not what we seem.'' His words take on meaning
when you see the early images in this handsome volume, a history of
Black photographers from 1840 to the present. African-Americans
produced photographs in the earliest days of the daguerreotype
process, creating an important ``counterimage'' to the exaggerated
features and demeaning situations often seen in depictions of Black
people. Black photographers were entrepreneurs, and many of their
clients were accomplished Black citizens and families. This volume
moves from the portraits of the 1800s and early 1900s to the
photojournalism of the 1930s and '40s, the social and artistic
movements of the 1950s and '60s and finally the social and cultural
content of contemporary photography. Willis is curator at the
Center for African American History and Culture in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``IT'S NOT ABOUT THE BIKE''
</P>
<P>
   By Lance Armstrong
</P>
<P>
   (Putnam, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong does things in a big way. Other people write
books about the long road back from cancer, or the physical and
emotional trauma of infertility, or the experience of growing up
without a father, or the determination it takes to win the most
important bicycle race in the world. Armstrong lays claim to ALL of
it, and the result is a pretty terrific book. Its appeal is due
largely to Armstrong's candor and tough, no-nonsense voice - there
will be no doubt in your mind why he won the 1999 Tour de France.
He's willing to let us wonder - because he wonders himself - why he
lived through the testicular cancer that spread to his lungs and
brain and left him with almost no chance of survival. Armstrong's
book is both inspiring and entertaining. He doesn't whine, doesn't
sugar-coat the tough parts and doesn't forget to thank the good
people who helped him most along the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
