<HEADER>
A4957 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR &LR;      06-05 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-SLUG-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    WEB&AMP;MAGS(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING IN ``E'' and ``L'' categoreis.) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER and DAN KINCAID(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are reviews of a website and some current magazines.
</P>
<P>
   WEBSITE
</P>
<P>
   DINOBASE
</P>
<P>
   http://palaeo.gly.bris.ac.uk/dinobase/dinopage.html
</P>
<P>
   OK, here's a chance to impress your kids - maybe - while talking
dinosaurs are heavy on their minds. This site contains a treasury
of serious information about those beloved monsters that should
quickly acquaint you with some of the lore and lingo.
</P>
<P>
   On site, a big carnosaur (read: meat eater) welcomes you with
gaping jaws. Dinobase is packed with technical information, such as
names of species and genera. One unusual feature is a list of
dinosaur finds by year from the 1700s to 2000 {ndash} now you can
brag about what dino was found in the year you were born, if it
helps.
</P>
<P>
   One link includes ``101 Crazy Theories about Dinosaur
Extinctions,'' capsule summaries of about every possible
explanation that's been put out to explain the demise of the dinos,
ranging from mammals brunching on their eggs to slipped disks to
constipation to increasing stupidity due to a shrinking brains -
the ultimate in dumb and dumber.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the catastrophic explanations that are the
current favorites: meteorite impact and world-class volcanism. This
kind of end seems apt for the great beasts - and is a bonus for the
moviemakers. The site is put together by the University of Bristol
in England.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINES
</P>
<P>
   ``FORBES''
</P>
<P>
   Cover story coaches millionaires on how to avoid raising spoiled
children. Upshot seems to be like, ``Hey, don't give them
everything they want without making them do a lick of work.'' But
(beginitalic)Forbes (enditalic)makes it sound better than that. And
longer. Waaay longer. The story is part of
(beginitalic)Forbes'(enditalic) huge ``Annual Investment Guide,''
which could come in pretty handy, especially if you're dabbling in
the stock market these days. One story talks about tax-smart
investing, while another warns how expensive divorce is becoming
these days. In the boring old British television section of the
magazine, two leading investment experts debate the market's
direction. This is basically the same tired bout: the value-based
old economy vs. the Internet-crazed new economy, which as you
recall, drew slightly less than Tyson-Holyfield on pay-per-view the
last time out. Another piece examines the scores of companies that
are lining up to host Web sites these days. Trouble is, their
profits might end up at www.pieinthesky.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``SMITHSONIAN''
</P>
<P>
   Magazine calls the repopulation of the bighorn sheep in the West
a ``conservation success story,'' noting that the population has
rebounded to 70,000 from a low of 23,000 around 1960. Article notes
that bighorn have benefited from ``better science, better
conservation and management practices'' and financial support. So
maybe they'll stop bonking their heads together in frustration.
Another article informs us that the mustard seed is the world's
most heavily traded spice. We'll tuck that away for that day we
finally make it on to (beginitalic)Jeopardy(enditalic)! ``No doubt
about it, mustard's on a roll in America,'' the article cracks.
Ouch. There's another piece that profiles Seattle's new Experience
Music Project, a 140,000-square-foot, $100 million museum and
general tribute to rocking out. In a wise move, they're calling it
EMP for short. As you might imagine, they've got a lot of guitars
there, including a fragment of one owned by Jimi Hendrix that was
smashed and burned at the 1967 Monterey festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``PSYCHOLOGY TODAY''
</P>
<P>
   Includes pretty interesting Q&AMP;A with Park Dietz, a top forensic
psychiatrist who has interviewed many of America's most infamous
criminals, including Ted Kaczynski (the Unabomber) and serial
killer, necrophiliac and cannibal Jeffrey Dahmer. Dietz, who
consults for movies and the television show (beginitalic)Law &AMP;
Order(enditalic), said of Dahmer, ``I really liked him. He's one of
the few killers I've met who seemed to genuinely want to understand
himself.'' Yecch. Dietz also subscribes to the theory that, ``With
rare exceptions, people are responsible for what they do.''
Magazine also includes a story about the latest buzz diagnosis for
people who find themselves in pain all the time - fibromyalgia,
which has no known cause, no simple diagnostic test and no easy
treatment or cure. Hmm. Could be trouble. And in something we've
always suspected, a short Q&AMP;A says the stomach is the body's
``second brain.'' Hence the intense craving for a brat.
</P>
<P>
   ``SPIN''
</P>
<P>
   This magazine always gives the uninitiated the feeling that
they've walked in about halfway through the movie. For the most
part, if you don't know what the stories are about, you won't know
much more when you've finished. To wit, from a story about Moby, a
former DJ turned pop star: ``After (beginitalic)Go(enditalic), his
(beginitalic)Twin Peaks(enditalic)-sampling kick-drum anthem, was a
U.K. Top 10 hit in the rave blowup of 1991, he gradually morphed
into an agitprop, Jesus-thanking, disco-punk pariah with a penchant
for flinging off his shirt.'' Oh thanks. That clears everything
right up. There is an equally turgid piece on Trance, a new form of
rave dance music sweeping the world and involving all things
fluorescent. When we say our music's pretty, we mean it's pretty
loud. They also catch up with Hanson, the boy band who drove
everyone nuts with their big hit, ``MMMBop.'' Apparently, Ike, Zac
and Tay are growing up. Tay?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4958 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-RELIGION-PERCEPTIONS-     06-05 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-PERCEPTIONS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-RELIGION-PERCEPTIONS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    CAN THE WORLD'S METHODS SPREAD THE GOOD WORD?CAPS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By MAUREEN JENKINS(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine you're in business to sell a product. But before you can
sell it, you need to find out whether people want it. If it meets
their needs and fits their lives.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, any smart marketer needs to know how to find the
folks who might want what he or she's selling.
</P>
<P>
   Should the church really be any different?
</P>
<P>
   Percept Group, Inc., is a Costa Mesa, Calif.-based firm that
provides demographic-based data to churches, regional
denominational groups and religious organizations. And no, says
president and co-founder Mike Regele, the company isn't mixing God
and mammon. Rather, using tangible research, it helps churches get
a handle on esoteric matters like the soul and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The goal? To get mainline Christian denominations {ndash} whose
membership losses are well documented these days {ndash} moving and
growing.
</P>
<P>
   The method? Finding out the values, mores and religious
attitudes of people in pre-defined geographical spaces and selling
this data to religious bodies hungry for ways to reach the
unchurched.
</P>
<P>
   ``In times past,'' said Regele, ``when you knew your neighbor
and your community, you knew who those people were. So what
demographics do is give you a first-order picture of the people
among who you live.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church's role in North American culture has shifted from
the center to the fringes. As the churches begin to face that, they
realize their vulnerability is very real,'' and they must either
adapt or die.
</P>
<P>
   Some folks criticize these modern marketing methods, believing
the Church survived and thrived for centuries using old-fashioned
ways of spreading the Word. Regele, a Presbyterian minister and
congregational mission planner, begs to differ. Despite running the
numbers and studying sociological data, Regele says that
ultimately, Percept's 170 clients' success depends on the personal
touch. His company's research, he says, simply points the way.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream Protestants {ndash} United Methodists, Episcopalians,
Presbyterians and Lutherans {ndash} are Percept's bread and butter.
But these days, even some Southern Baptist churches, Catholic
dioceses and non-denominational groups are using the firm's data to
retain and grow memberships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really rooted in a theological conviction,'' said Regele,
48, ``that the church is the sign and foretaste and instrument of
the mission of God in the world. Our whole evaluation is that the
church needs to be for others, not itself.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what prompted First United Methodist Church of Tempe,
housed on the main drag of Arizona State University, to check
Percept out. The 100-year-old church was stagnant, its pews filled
with 55- to 60-year-olds and very few of the college kids who
stroll past its doors each day.
</P>
<P>
   The church needed to know ``what kind of worship service the
community was looking for, and what we were providing,'' says the
Rev. David McPherson, senior pastor. ``We also know we're not
visible enough, so we're trying to find out what we can do with our
facilities to make us more visible.''
</P>
<P>
   So after investing $700 in Percept's survey of its own members
and a five-mile radius surrounding it, First United launched an 11
a.m. contemporary service a few years back.
</P>
<P>
   It features video clips from popular movies. Slide shows using
Microsoft PowerPoint, displayed on a big screen in front. Lively
bands jamming gospel tunes. And occasional skits that share the
Word with in-your-face style.
</P>
<P>
   McPherson admits that at first, all his older members weren't
with the program, but ``they do see that it's worth giving it a
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It [helped] people get more focused on what Christ wants us to
do, rather than what (beginitalic)I (enditalic)want to do,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true at St. Luke's at the Mountain, a small
Episcopal mission church near Phoenix's South Mountain. The
surrounding area was becoming largely Hispanic, although none
belonged to the congregation. Following a Percept survey, the
Episcopal Diocese of Arizona's Hispanic missioner, the Rev. Modesto
Mursuli, went knocking on doors, inviting residents to the church's
brand-new Spanish worship on Sunday evenings. Attendance now
averages about 60.
</P>
<P>
   `` I just looked at it as another way of spreading the gospel,''
Episcopal Archdeacon Bill Greeley said. ``You can no longer take
for granted people are coming. Out here, the Church has got to be
asking the questions the people are asking. `What's the meaning of
life? How can I make it to the next paycheck? How do I live in a
troubled marriage?'''
</P>
<P>
   Using two years' worth of Percept data, the Episcopal Diocese
hopes to plant three new churches in Phoenix, two in Tucson, and
one in Payson over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   And hopefully, help aging ones like St. Peter's in Litchfield
Park revitalize themselves as they reached out to new members and
searched for a new pastor.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them to go into the next millennium,'' Greeley said,
``they needed to reach out to young families with children. They
had to call someone who had that passion, because the face of the
congregation would change.''
</P>
<P>
   So, St. Peter's is upgrading its buildings, adding
family-friendly amenities to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do Percept customers learn about the community around
them, but also rediscovering some truths about their own
congregations in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day,'' Regele says, ``the church is about a
story, has been telling that story for 2,000 years, and that's the
core of what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Maureen.Jenkins(a)Arizona
</P>
<P>
   Republic.com or (602) 444-8307.
</P>
