<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4961 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-05 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POMP AMID SPECIAL CIRCUMSTANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Normally, the best show on the bill at a federal
courthouse is not a trial but a ceremony welcoming new American
citizens. For inspiration, renewal of an old idea, and sheer drama,
you can't top it.
</P>
<P>
   But in Boston this Friday evening, you can. The place to be is
the US courthouse for the commencement exercises of the Urban
College, possibly the most unheralded &UR;  &LR; successful experiment in
higher education today.
</P>
<P>
   The college still doesn't have its own building, much less a
nickname or a football team, but the 76 adults getting associate
degrees in human services management, early-childhood education,
and general studies are arguably more important to this country's
future than any 76 graduates of Harvard, and I have more than a
suspicion that they have more on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Most are parents working low-wage jobs under heroic
circumstances and have spent years earning their degrees a course
or two at a time. Most are over 30, half haven't been near a school
for 10 years, and nearly half have been on welfare at some point.
Every one of them understands the value of his achievement against
all odds.
</P>
<P>
   Urban College has been around for seven years, but this year's
commencement is a special occasion for two reasons that represent
the official validation of its special niche in an educational and
political universe that is comically slow to recognize innovation.
The college is a place that stands all conventional wisdom about
``credentials'' on its myopic head.
</P>
<P>
   The first reason is the receipt last month of a federal grant
that will enable the college to expand its all-important services
to its unique student body. To most big-shot schools, $925,000 is
chump change, but tutorials, an information lab, links to available
social services, and the like are everything for an adult trying
like crazy to juggle kids, poverty, and school. Dr. Lee Hines, the
school's president, told me that the grant is a ``pivotal move,''
which strikes me as an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, more than 70 percent of those who enter Urban College
graduate, a retention rate that most places with mostly low-income
student bodies would die for. Motivation and curiosity, the most
important raw material for a good education, are a given there; but
the right blend of services can make its success even greater. It
should come as no surprise that the politician who cajoled his
fellow pols, harassed the federal bureaucracy to help nail down the
dough, and had the vision to get involved in the first place was US
Senator Edward M. Kennedy. For somebody used to dealing in
billions, there is no better example of the impact he has on
poverty fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The second reason this Friday is special involves another key
higher education center for the people who count most in
Massachusetts _ Lesley College, a go-to place for those lucky
enough to be interested in child care and education. Last month
Lesley and Urban College became partners, and Lesley will recognize
its partner's courses for full credit. That means that those with
the guts to enter the associate degree program can look at a clear
path to a college degree if they stick with it. And Lesley will
take them in as juniors.
</P>
<P>
   For the 76 graduates _ indeed, for all 500 students at Urban
College _ this is life itself. All of the differences between
low-wage jobs and life above the median can be attributed to
education and training. A year or two of something after high
school makes a difference; a college degree makes all the
difference. The lessons Urban College's students teach the rest of
us are that for the roughly 7.5 million Americans working full time
in poverty, a return to school (along with a living wage) can work
wonders and that it is never too late.
</P>
<P>
   Urban College exists because of Action for Boston Community
Development's longtime head, Bob Coard. Unlike nearly every
population center in America, community action, the core of the
original War on Poverty, still exists in Boston because Coard has
kept it young and innovative. ABCD had always had an adult high
school program, and Coard first expanded it by feeding people into
participating colleges in the area.
</P>
<P>
   It was Coard who shepherded it through the long tunnels of the
higher education and State House systems, stole Dr. Hines from
Chicago and kept the focus on low-income, older adults. As always,
the very nature of ABCD's operation _ built on outreach, aimed at
those most in need, and using its existing programs like adult high
school and welfare-to-work, makes that possible. As Coard told me
last week, the ideal Urban College recruit is someone who under
normal circumstances would not even have a shot at community
college.
</P>
<P>
   This Friday, however, is about accomplishment, not obstacles.
With a lease on life and overdue recognition, the next challenge
for Urban College is to get its own building. And name it after Bob
Coard.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
