<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4.4 PERCENT SAVINGS RATE WON'T PRODUCE POSH RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  I am contributing $166 a month to my Roth IRA. Do my
investments sound like good ones to you? I do not have an
employer-sponsored pension plan. How much will I need to save per
year to have a comfortable retirement?
</P>
<P>
   A.P., El Cajon, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  The short, unpleasant answer is: a whole lot more than you
are saving now.
</P>
<P>
   If you continue fully funding your IRA and achieve 10 percent
average annual investment gains for 29 years, you would amass
$868,734. But if inflation averages 3.5 percent, that pool would
have the buying power of about $320,000 in today's money; the buck
of 2029 would have the buying power of 37 cents of today's money.
</P>
<P>
   Let's approach it from another angle. Many people figure they
can live in retirement on about two thirds of what they need during
their working years. Thus if you retire at age 65, you would need
the 2029 equivalent of $30,000, basing the calculation on the
midpoint of your salary range. When you adjust that number for 3.5
percent inflation, the unhappy result is $81,356. You would then
need about $1.25 million to support withdrawals at that level
without depleting the principal.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's take a third tack on the problem. Your current
savings rate, again using the midpoint of your earnings estimate,
represents a 4.44 percent savings rate. That might be acceptable if
you were also earning a pension, but that's not your situation. I
think you should adopt a strategy of saving 10 percent of your
earnings. If you were to save $375 a month, the pool would be
$1,292,627 at the end of 29 years.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, since your income is likely to increase more or less
in line with the rate of inflation _ and ideally, faster than
inflation _ if you maintain the 10 percent discipline rather than
the $375 monthly payment you would have a considerably greater
amount saved. That would be a good thing, given that you will want
to have both a savings pool to provide an income stream and another
savings pool that can be left in growth investments to protect you
against post-retirement inflation.
</P>
<P>
   I did not factor Social Security into any of these calculations;
the time you are retiring is about the time, based on many
calculations, that pessimists say the Social Security system will
begin breaking down if nothing is done to shore it up. Some form of
Social Security is likely to survive. I just wouldn't want to base
my retirement security on the bet that it will.
</P>
<P>
   I have no problem at all with your choice of investments. The
one change I would suggest is that you concentrate your most
aggressive investments, such as the T. Rowe Price Science and
Technology holding, in your tax-deferred accounts, and your most
conservative (and those least likely to make major distributions)
in the taxable accounts. Since index funds tend to meet those
characteristics, the position in Vanguard Index Growth is
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   You probably won't want to move your current position in the
Price fund, given that there are probably adverse tax consequences,
but you should follow the idea of putting your most aggressive
investments in tax-deferred accounts when you are making further
investments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  I am divorced and debt-free and plan to retire in 10 years.
I need to have an income of at least $2,000 a month after retiring.
How can I more productively invest my money for retirement? Am I on
target to meet my monthly income needs after retirement? How much
should I be saving each month?
</P>
<P>
   S.M., Sherwood, Ore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  It seems to me you can afford very little risk, so I would
suggest nothing more aggressive than seeking a higher return from a
government-insured savings instrument. The nation's best rate on a
five-year CD entering last week was 8.11 percent. If you invested
your $27,000 at such a rate for 10 years, you would have $60,580
upon retirement (although there would be no assurance you would
enjoy the same rate after the first five years ends).
</P>
<P>
   The chief bugbear that faces you is inflation. Although it would
seem the interest from the CD would take you nicely above $2,000 a
month in 10 years, that picture is illusory. If inflation averages
3.5 percent for the next decade, you will need $2,821 to buy what
$2,000 buys today. Thus, you would be 21 percent shy of the
equivalent of $2,000 in today's buying power.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to suggest how much to save, given your fairly
limited income stream. If your projection that you would need
$2,000 a month for living expenses in retirement is based on the
fact that you are spending $2,000 a month now, this would mean you
currently have the ability to save $800 a month. If that is the
case, you would be in pretty good shape. Such a savings program
could build an account of $147,245 after 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But since the effects of inflation would be steadily mounting as
those years elapsed, you probably could not maintain that savings
rate and hold your current standard of living. So my suggestion is
simply to save as much as you can.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  I believe that the existing law involving IRAs requires
minimum withdrawals within six months after reaching age 70 1/2. My
intent is to continue working past that age. I believe I read
somewhere that if one is still actively employed after reaching 70
1/2, that person is not required to make withdrawals and can make
contributions. Is this indeed a viable option?
</P>
<P>
   T.F., Santa Ana, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  I'm sorry, but there is no way around the rules for
mandatory withdrawals from a traditional IRA after age 70. The
withdrawal schedule is a little more complicated than what you
outline. The first withdrawal must be made by April 1 of the year
following the year in which you reach age 70 1/2. Thus, you could
delay your first withdrawal until April 1, 2003.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a snag. If you waited until that date, the first
withdrawal would be for 2002 but would appear on your tax return
for 2003. Then you would also, during calendar 2003, be required to
take a withdrawal for the year 2003; effectively, you would face
two withdrawals on one tax return. For that reason, most people in
your situation would take their first withdrawal in late 2002 and
the second in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   As for contributions to a traditional IRA after age 70 1/2, the
answer is no _ it simply can't be done. But there are two wrinkles.
First, if you are married and your spouse is not yet 70 1/2, you
can contribute to an IRA in her name, provided you meet the earned
income requirements. Second, you can contribute to a Roth IRA after
age 70 1/2, provided you earn enough to qualify for the
contribution and don't earn too much to qualify for a Roth IRA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  I have about $100,000 in a 401(k) plan that I want to
transfer to a rollover IRA. I realize my proposed allocation is a
fairly aggressive portfolio, but I am willing to incur some risk as
I do not plan to touch this money for at least 20 years. What do
you think?
</P>
<P>
   L.C., North Andover, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  I would suggest only one small change. Although the
Vanguard Total Stock Market Index holds 3,362 stocks, the portfolio
is market weighted, meaning the holdings are in proportion to the
market capitalization of the stocks in question. The effect of this
is that it is dominated by the large-cap domestic stocks _
substantially duplicating the position in Index 500.
</P>
<P>
   Since you would already have exposure to the small- and mid-cap
markets, why not boost the Index 500 position to 35 percent, and
put 10 percent in either Vanguard European Stock Index fund or
Vanguard Total International Stock Index?
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4964 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-INVESTING-DOGS-     06-05 1948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-INVESTING-DOGS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 CRITICS SAY CONTRARIAN BET ON THE DOW'S LAGGARDS IS DOOMED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While surfing Web investing sites a couple of years ago, Stephen
Lepley came across some investing strategies promising to beat the
Dow Jones industrial average, with the offbeat names Dogs of the
Dow and the Foolish Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were starting to hear things on the Internet about the
Dogs of the Dow. I researched it a little bit. You knew you weren't
going to go broke if you're doing this,'' said Lepley, 43, of
Greenfield, Mass., who monitors investing sites from his home
computer and posts his own investing Web page.
</P>
<P>
   So, like hundreds of thousands _ if not millions _ of other
investors, Lepley jumped on board, attracted by the chance to beat
the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   These contrarian strategies invest in the most beat-up stocks of
the 30 big-name companies that make up the Dow, with the
expectation that they'll turn around within a year and outperform
the index as a whole. The Dogs invest in the 10 stocks with the
highest dividend yields, often the lowest priced of the 30. The
Foolish Four chooses four stocks using a yield and price ratio.
</P>
<P>
   But the popular Dogs of the Dow severely lagged the index the
last two years, and isn't showing much more life this year.
Meanwhile, the related Foolish Four slightly trailed the Dow two
out of the last three years and is in its third revision since it
was first described several years ago by the Motley Fool in books
and on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dogs and the Foolish Four _ it was a fad. And there are
other fads today,'' said Lepley, who works for ISO New England, the
region's independent electrical system operator. Although his
Foolish Four account made a double-digit profit the year he was in
it, it lagged the index, so he stopped following the strategy last
year. He now has his low-six-figure portfolio only in mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Waters, 32, of Newton, Mass., almost bought into the Dogs of
the Dow himself last year after receiving a ``very slick marketing
piece'' from Charles Schwab about its new offering following the
strategy. But when he sought advice on an online discussion board
at Morningstar.com, ``the responses I got from people were kind of
pessimistic,'' said Waters, a salesman for an Internet start-up.
``For a long time now, it's been kind of underperforming.''
</P>
<P>
   Are the Dogs permanently in the dog house, and are the Foolish
Four little more than fool's gold? Some critics say the Dow Dogs
are too popular a strategy for their own good or are doomed at the
bottom of the heap because they're old-economy stocks. Others say
the Foolish Four are nothing more than a statistical trick known as
data mining.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of these strategies say the Dogs will have their
day again. The stakes are high, with billions of dollars invested
in these and other Dow dividend-based strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding and tapping into the interest:
</P>
<P>
   --Big financial services companies including Merrill Lynch,
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, and Charles Schwab, which now offer
ways to invest in the Dogs of the Dow strategy through so-called
unit investment trusts and individual stock brokerage accounts.
</P>
<P>
   --The Motley Fool, which touts the Foolish Four on its Web site
and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   --Popular books that highlight some form of a Dow dividend
strategy, with such titles as ``Beating the Dow,'' ``How to Retire
Rich,'' and ``Investing Secrets of the Masters.''
</P>
<P>
   --Mutual fund companies, which sell products with names such as
the Leveraged Dogs fund.
</P>
<P>
   --Web sites with such addresses as www.dogsofthedow.com and
www.topthedow.com.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy began with the book ``Beating the Dow,'' first
published a decade ago by Michael B. O'Higgins and John Downes. In
it, money manager O'Higgins and financial writer Downes describe a
beat-the-market method of identifying the 10 Dow stocks with the
highest dividend yields, and then buying equal dollar amounts of
the five lowest-priced of those 10. Hold them for a year and repeat
the process.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale behind the strategy, also known as a contrarian or
value-oriented approach: By investing in the highest-yielding,
lowest-priced Dow stocks, you're buying out-of-favor big-name
companies in the hopes they'll come back into favor during the year
in which you hold the portfolio. (Since the yield is a result of
dividing a stock's cash dividend into the stock price, a high yield
suggests a beaten-up stock price.)
</P>
<P>
   The ``Beating the Dow'' strategy became so well known among
investing circles that Barron's financial weekly newspaper
popularized the phrase ``Dogs of the Dow'' to describe it and
regularly updates readers on the strategy's performance. Although
O'Higgins and Downes focused on buying the five lowest-priced of
the 10 highest-yielding Dow stocks, most followers of the strategy
buy the 10 highest-yielding stocks.
</P>
<P>
   O'Higgins, a Miami-based money manager, now thinks the Dogs
don't have any legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became too popular,'' he said, plus the strategy currently
features what he calls ``some real dogs,'' such as International
Paper and DuPont, each down more than 20 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, O'Higgins has a new strategy, described in his latest
book, ``Beating the Dow with Bonds.'' The new strategy's indicators
have led him to put his O'Higgins fund 100 percent into long-term
Treasury zero-coupon bonds. His fund is up around 11 percent so far
this year while the Dow is down about 8 percent. (Last year, the
fund was down more than 20 percent, he said, while the Dow was up
more than 20 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Also critical of the Dogs of the Dow, but for other reasons, is
the co-author of another new book, ``Investing Secrets of the
Masters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The argument that's raised against the Dogs of the Dow these
days: The universe of stocks on the Dow has a lower yield than in
the past,'' said William Donovan, a Massachusetts-based financial
journalist who co-authored the book with money manager Charles
Babin. ``The argument is the yield has shrunk because of the
turnover of companies in the Dow. I think that's a valid
argument.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the relatively high-yielding stocks recently booted out of
the Dow: Sears, Chevron, and Goodyear. Replacing them were
low-yielding Home Depot and Intel, and no-dividend Microsoft. Since
the Dogs of the Dow strategy is based on buying high yields, some
critics say these changes in the Dow have caused the Dogs' recent
dismal performance.
</P>
<P>
   In their book and on the Web site topthedow.com, Donovan and
Babin describe another Dow dividend-based approach they say isn't
affected by such changes, and which they say has historically
outperformed both the Dogs and the Dow. The ``Total Return
Portfolio'' approach uses both growth in dividend payments and
yield to come up with the 15 Dow stocks to own.
</P>
<P>
   There's no shortage of critics of these investing approaches.
But there are still plenty of others who continue to carry the
banner.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Mahoney, chief investment officer for Merrill Lynch's
Defined Asset Funds, which include the Select Ten unit investment
trust that holds the Dogs of the Dow, said ``Select Ten is a valid
and good strategy'' that can be an important part of a diverse
portfolio, representing the value investing style.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early part of the year, certainly you'd say value
stocks had not done very well. In 1999, growth outperformed value.
But look at it now,'' he said, explaining that the Nasdaq is off
more than 30 percent from its high. Now, ``value has been
outperforming growth,'' in the sense that value stocks are down
less than growth stocks since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch is the main sponsor of Select Ten, but other
companies including Salomon Smith Barney and PaineWebber also offer
it. The minimum investment is $250. Fees amount to 2.75 percent.
Select Ten now has about $9 billion in assets, down from $12
billion the end of last year, largely as a result of redemptions,
according to Mahoney.
</P>
<P>
   Another diehard Dogs fan: Pete Grosz, founder of the
dogsofthedow.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a value investment strategy. I think a portion of your
investment would do well by it. It's good for diversification,''
said Grosz, a California-based online publisher who has personally
invested using the strategy since the early 1990s and launched the
Web site in 1995. The free site has grown to more than 20,000
subscribers, and Grosz just launched another investing site,
chartoftheday.com.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Dogs' recent poor performance, Grosz said: ``As we
say on the Web site, there will be some years that the Dogs will
underperform. Right now, with the market's attention turned toward
tech stocks, it's flowing away from value stocks. But we wouldn't
expect that would last forever. So that's why we stay put, and the
value stocks have just become a greater value relative to the tech
stocks and high-growth stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Once just a slight variation of the five high-yielding,
low-priced Dow stocks strategy, the Foolish Four now uses a ratio
that takes into account low price and high yield, by dividing the
yield by the square root of the price.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Coleman, portfolio manager for the Foolish Four, said the
four stocks selected using this formula are ``beating the market
right now, minus 1 percent vs. minus 3 percent,'' as of late May.
While that's ``not really something to write home about,'' she
added, the historical data going back to the 1960s show the stocks
fitting this formula each year do substantially better on average
than the overall Dow, the original Foolish Four, and the Dogs of
the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   But in a 1999 article in the Financial Analysts Journal entitled
``Mining Fool's Gold,'' and in an article this year in the American
Association of Individual Investors journal, Brigham Young
University associate professors Grant R. McQueen and Steven R.
Thorley criticized the Foolish Four for being nothing more than a
statistical trick known as data mining.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sort by yield, then by price, take the four lowest, then
throw out the second highest, and when the moon is full and you tap
three times on your chin. . . . If you look hard enough, you'll
find it,'' said McQueen in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just for fun, we played that game,'' he said. ``We created
what we called the Fractured Four. The Foolish Four (an earlier
version) outdid the Dow on odd years, not even years. So tongue in
cheek, we tweaked the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   The result: The Fractured Four trounced the overall Dow, the
Dogs of the Dow, and an earlier version of the Foolish Four, up by
34.82 percent on average between 1973 and 1996. ``Obviously, it's
absurd,'' McQueen said. He also said he was suspicious about the
way the Foolish Four has been redefined three times.
</P>
<P>
   Portfolio manager Coleman defended the latest Four, saying it is
not a result of data mining but a refinement in response to the
historical data.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the changes were a result of more data, better data to
look at,'' said Coleman, who has been a journalist, technical
writer, and Motley Fool publications and customer service manager.
He also studied finance for a year.
</P>
<P>
   McQueen remains unconvinced. Whether it's the Foolish Four or
some other variation of a Dow dividend approach focusing on five,
10, or 15 stocks, ``my common-sense advice is watch out, they're
not very diverse, they force you to trade a lot, and they don't
always manage your taxes very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
