<HEADLINE>
MT. SHASTA'S POWERFUL MYSTIQUE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Free to clients of Way to Go!) 
 (FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES) 
 BY ANN K. LUDWIG  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Blanketed with snow until midsummer, Mount Shasta's Upper
Panther Meadow was warm early last September and bright with Indian
paintbrush, yarrow and cliff penstimon.
 &HT;    From the trailhead at around 7,600 feet, my husband, Karl, and I
had walked gently uphill along a grassy creek to the source spring
considered sacred by Indians, who still conduct ceremonies there.
It is a small sandy pool rimmed by flowers and rocks, with lovely
cold water bubbling out.
 &HT;    After tasting the spring water we joined several others who sat
nearby meditating. Then we climbed a bit higher for another view of
the snowy slopes rising above us.
 &HT;    At 14,162 feet, Mount Shasta towers above the surrounding hills
and dominates the Northern California landscape for hundreds of
miles. It has long exerted an almost mystical pull on climbers,
philosophers and naturalists.
 &HT;    On his first view of it, the naturalist John Muir wrote, ``my
blood turned to wine,'' and in 1888 he proposed preserving the
region as a national park. It was an idea whose time never came,
although a fraction of the originally proposed acreage was finally
added to the National Wilderness Preservation System in 1983.
 &HT;    By the time of the Wilderness designation, the pristine rivers
that burst from mountain springs in the area and still make it a
prime fishing destination had long been harnessed by Shasta Dam
about 50 miles to the south near Redding, Calif.
 &HT;    Completed in 1945, the dam created Shasta Lake, whose placid
waters and 365 miles of shoreline offer tamer alternatives to
fishing and boating enthusiasts as well as providing water and
hydroelectric power for an area stretching 500 miles south,
including Sacramento.
 &HT;    Fortunately for preservation, the mountain itself is far from a
large urban area, though the region is served by a major
north-south highway, Interstate 5.
 &HT;    In all of surrounding Siskiyou County there are fewer than
50,000 people; the City of Mount Shasta has only about 3,600
inhabitants. The other small towns that skirt the mountain, Weed,
McCloud, and Dunsmuir, also offer dramatic views of the dual-cone
peak and the curious lens-shaped cloud formations that gather above
it.
 &HT;    All four towns, which grew out of the region's early lumber and
railroad-based economy, now enjoy clear air and clean water; they
also assume the risks of living beneath a volcano that is currently
dormant but fully capable of erupting again.
 &HT;    Although Mount Shasta's last reported eruption was around 200
years ago, bubbling sulfurous springs near the summit are a
reminder of the mountain's turbulent inner life. Historically,
eruptions have occurred on average every 600 years, but today
careful seismic monitoring of the peak offers the prospect of early
warning.
 &HT;    Unfazed, or perhaps attracted, by the risks, thousands of
climbers annually attempt the ascent. However, fewer than a third
of them reach the summit, according to the United States Forest
Service, often because they've failed to train and acclimate or to
inform themselves about route and weather conditions.
 &HT;    A few years ago my husband, Karl, and I spent several days near
the City of Mount Shasta while he prepared to climb the mountain.
(He succeeded.) Charmed by the area, we returned early last
September for a more leisurely four-day stay.
 &HT;    After savoring Mount Shasta's presence from the other historic
and picturesque towns, we paid a brief visit to Lake Shasta where
we toured ancient Shasta Caverns and Shasta Dam, whose completion
transformed the region.
 &HT;    This mountain is extraordinarily buoyant and powerful. Not
surprisingly, many Indians view it as a spiritual center, and
traditionally considered it the Great Spirit's teepee or the
gateway to the inner earth.
 &HT;    The magic of the setting has also attracted strange myths that
have the mountain inhabited by ancient civilizations or UFO-flying
aliens.
 &HT;    After checking in at the popular Strawberry Valley Inn on the
main street of the City of Mount Shasta _ challenging because the
reservation system was as quaint as the setting _ we walked to
Village Books nearby.
 &HT;    Over an espresso we scanned books about the mysterious races
said to live within the mountain, the Lemurians and Yaktayvians,
and recalled that in August 1987, the mountain was one of the
gathering sites for the Harmonic Convergence, a worldwide event
marking a particular planetary alignment. In the store, notices of
services and events were evidence of the metaphysical and
alternative-healing community drawn to the mountain.
 &HT;    After breakfast at the inn, based in a 1920s stone house that
has a lovely terrace with a mountain view, we were off to City Park
to see the spring that supplies the headwaters of the Sacramento
River.
 &HT;    A man was balancing on the mossy rocks filling plastic water
bottles with the freshest of water, which flows in a gushing stream
out of the hillside and tumbles down an incline past picnic tables
and sports fields.
 &HT;    Our next destination was a contemporary war memorial outside the
nearby town of Weed, and apparently one of its chief attractions.
To reach the Living Memorial Sculpture Garden, we drove a dozen
miles northeast of Weed on Highway 97 alongside desolate black
mesas of lava flow.
 &HT;    The sculptor and Vietnam veteran Dennis Smith has dedicated to
all veterans his 10 works in metal (he is finishing the 11th),
groups of larger-than-life human figures with vaguely alien
features, including ``The Refugees,'' ``POW-MIA'' and ``Coming
Home.'' They stand in an austere but pleasingly laid-out garden of
Ponderosa pine, manzanita and chaparral with an exhilarating view
of the glacier-covered north side of Mount Shasta. No one else was
there.
 &HT;    Later that afternoon, back in the City of Mount Shasta, we drove
up the mountain's Everitt Memorial Highway about 14 miles to the
Upper Panther Meadow trailhead to visit the sacred spring. At
around 7,600 feet, it is just half a mile from the highest point
accessible by car.
 &HT;    The next day we turned our attention from the natural world to
humans' impact on it. The Mount Shasta Fish Hatchery stocks many of
the streams and lakes of Northern California with catchable trout.
One of the oldest operating fish hatcheries west of the
Mississippi, it began production in 1888.
 &HT;    An original hatchery building now houses the Sisson Museum, the
local history and ecology museum named for the town founder, Justin
Sisson. Photographs and artifacts chronicle the early climbing
history of Mount Shasta, and working models reflect the importance
of the Southern Pacific Railroad that was an essential lifeline
from San Francisco to the north.
 &HT;    The nearby historic lumber mill town of McCloud was our
destination for the night. Founded more than 100 years ago, it
ceased being a company town in 1965, and the Champion International
Mill closed in 1979.
 &HT;    However, the McCloud Railway Company and the McCloud Hotel have
been rejuvenated to take advantage of its picturesque setting and
its proximity to fine fishing and winter sports. Layoffs at the
remaining mill, P&AMP;M Cedar Mill, which processes cedar for pencils,
had just been announced, a reminder of the lumber economy's
fragility.
 &HT;    The McCloud Hotel is a handsome three-story building, yellow
trimmed in forest green. From its front porch bordered with pansies
and garlanded with wisteria, we could see Mount Shasta. Our
attractive and comfortable standard room combined two original
rooms and provided an up-to-date bathroom.
 &HT;    Though our schedule didn't permit it, many hotel guests cross
the street to board either an open-air excursion train or the
Shasta Sunset Dinner Train.
 &HT;    Before moving on the next day, we drove about seven miles east
of town to see McCloud Falls. Accessible by car, the three-stage
falls and river provide inviting swimming and fishing holes, but in
September we saw only a few other people.
 &HT;    On a hike from the lower to the middle falls we saw a fisherman
catch a nice trout, lending credence to the McCloud River's
reputation. Back in town we made a short stop at the Heritage
Junction Museum, whose eclectic, well cared for collection of
community artifacts, displayed in one large room, includes logging
equipment, sporting goods and household items.
 &HT;    Back on Interstate 5, it is only five miles south to Dunsmuir, a
town built in the 1880s to serve the Central Pacific Railroad.
Originally called Pusher, it was named for the helper engines that
boosted trains over daunting grades along the Sacramento River
Canyon.
 &HT;    The small, old-fashioned downtown, listed on the National
Register of Historic Places, retains much of the 1920s architecture
of its heyday, and the trains (mostly freight) still roll through
the railyard almost hourly.
 &HT;    Just off the main street, Dunsmuir Avenue, are the visitors
center and the Enchanted Forest Porcelain Doll Factory. Here the
proprietor, Marian Anderson, produces collector-quality dolls with
some 650 faces and various ethnicities. Her not-for-children dolls
range in price from $169 to $2,000.
 &HT;    In the spirit of this historic railroad town, we spent the night
in a converted caboose. One exit south of Dunsmuir is the Railroad
Park Resort, where we checked into the Caboose Motel, where 22
cabooses and one boxcar, each an individual room, encircle a pool
and hot tub. We climbed aboard attractively decorated No. 17,
``Southern Pacific'' emblazoned on its side.
 &HT;    Our brass king-sized bed just left passage to the bathroom and
cupola, to which we climbed to enjoy our view of the towering
granite formations in nearby Castle Crags State Park.
 &HT;    After a smooth night on board our caboose, we headed to Lake
Shasta, about 35 miles south. The wild forested canyon and rushing
Sacramento River give way to the serene lake which forms arms and
fingers stretching into the neighboring hills.
 &HT;    Our first destination, Shasta Caverns, required a short boat
ride across the lake and a bus ride uphill. Even in September the
cool damp interior of the cave was a welcome relief from
temperatures in the '90s. We had to earn it on the tour, however,
by climbing up and down stairs, a total of 650 steps.
 &HT;    I'm not much of a spelunker, so I was happy that lighting was
good and stairs and paths well maintained. The limestone cave, long
known to Wintu Indians, was first explored by a white man, James
Richardson, with a Wintu guide, Charles Morton, in 1878 and opened
to the public in 1964.
 &HT;    Our hourlong tour refreshed our memories of stalactites and
stalagmites and unloosed our imaginations. Surrounding us were
dreamlike formations resembling popcorn and broccoli, or graceful
drapery and columns, and, directed by the guide's flashlight, a
tiger, pipe organ and castle.
 &HT;    Continuing on about 15 miles to 55-year-old Shasta Dam, the
second largest dam in mass in the United States, we parked right on
top. Down the 487-foot high spillway, three times the height of
Niagara Falls and the largest manmade waterfall in the world, only
a trickle of water flowed. Our guide explained that the lake was
down about 43 feet; in spring, with the winter rains and runoff, it
would probably be around eight feet from the crest.
 &HT;    He described construction of the dam from 1938 to 1945, a story
that is astonishing, both statistically and in human terms. For
instance, first a diversion tunnel 1,821 feet long had to be built
for the main line track of the Southern Pacific Railroad; then
workers labored for five and a half years pouring concrete 24 hours
a day to create the wall of the dam.
 &HT;    The tour included an echo chamber, the old railway tunnel that
later served to divert the river, and a view of osprey nests on a
power plant tower. A good tour, perhaps even, as the guide
maintained, ``the best dam tour in the USA.''
 &HT;    Leaving the area, we stopped at the vista point about a mile
from the dam, where we could see three Shastas: the dam and the
lake in the foreground and gleaming regal Mount Shasta in the
distance. While the dam was a powerful example of man's ability to
transform nature for better or worse, we were thankful for Mount
Shasta's mighty and humbling presence.
 &HT;    -----
 SIDEBAR: THE MOUNTAIN, THE TOWN AND THE LAKE  
 INFORMATION  
 &HT;    In the Mount Shasta area, for information about activities and
lodging, contact the Siskiyou County Visitors Bureau, Post Office
Box 1138, Mount Shasta, Calif. 96067; (877) 747-5496;
www.visitsiskiyou.org.
 &HT;    Similar information on the Lake Shasta area is available from
the Redding Convention and Visitors Bureau, 777 Auditorium Drive,
Redding, Calif. 96001, (800) 874-7562; www.ci.redding.ca.us.
 &HT;    Information about conditions on Mount Shasta is available at
www.r5.fs.fed.us/shastatrinity.
 WEATHER  
 &HT;    At Mount Shasta, mornings and evenings are typically crisp in
July and August, with afternoon highs in the 80s, occasionally the
90s, though humidity is low.
 &HT;    In the hotter Lake Shasta area, summer highs are in the 90s to
low 100s, and evenings are also warm. September brings cooler
weather to the whole region.
 GETTING THERE  
 &HT;    From the San Francisco Bay Area, Redding is 220 miles north via
Interstate 5, about a four-hour drive. The City of Mount Shasta is
about an hour beyond Redding. United Express has flights between
San Francisco and Redding, where rental cars are available.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    The Strawberry Valley Inn, 1142 South Mount Shasta Blvd., in the
City of Mount Shasta, 96067, (530) 926-2052, fax (530) 926-0842,
has 15 comfortable guest rooms flanking a garden and an old stone
house that serves as office and lounge. Doubles $63 to $87 ($50 to
$56 for 10 smaller rooms in an annex, the Court).
 &HT;    The 17-room McCloud Hotel, 408 Main St., McCloud, Calif. 96057,
(800) 964-2823, fax (530) 964-2844, was built in 1915 and restored
as a bed-and-breakfast in 1995. Some rooms and suites have
four-poster beds, and four suites have large whirlpool baths.
Doubles $74 to $119; suites $124 to $167.
 &HT;    In Dunsmuir, accommodations at the Caboose Motel in the Railroad
Park Resort, 100 Railroad Park Road, Dunsmuir, Calif. 96025; (530)
235-4440, fax (530) 235-4470, include 22 attractively refurbished
cabooses, one deluxe boxcar and four cabins. Most have brass beds.
Doubles, $70 to $75.
 &HT;    The hospitable O'Brien Mountain Inn, Post Office Box 27,
O'Brien, Calif. 96070, (530) 238-8026, fax (530) 238-2027, near
Lake Shasta, has four rooms decorated with musical themes: world
beat, folk, jazz or classical. Three rooms have private patios.
Doubles, $97 to $147. (A treehouse suite with a bluegrass theme is
being built; $197.)
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    In a neat white house behind a white picket fence in the City of
Mount Shasta, homey Lilys, 1013 South Mount Shasta Blvd., (530)
926-3372, has an international menu with lots of vegetarian
options. Pastas, Asian and Mexican dishes, fish and meat entrees
are served at dinner; entree prices, from $11.95 to $22.95, include
soup or salad. Wines start around $14 a bottle. Breakfast, lunch
and dinner daily.
 &HT;    Also in the City of Mount Shasta, ambitious fare is served at
another converted residence, Trinity Cafe, 622 North Mount Shasta
Blvd., (530) 926-6200. In simple, stylish dining rooms, a changing
a la carte menu is served.
 &HT;    A typical selection included appetizers such as baby corn
fritters with lime mayonnaise and entrees such as grilled Alaskan
halibut on a bed of red chard. Three-course dinner for two with a
bottle of wine, $65. Dinner Wednesday through Sunday. Reservations
recommended.
 &HT;    In Dunsmuir, across the street from the rail yard, at Cafe
Maddalena, 5801 Sacramento Ave., (530) 235-2725, the decor and
lovingly prepared food are Italian and Mediterranean. Pastas
include homemade ravioli with a filling of fish, ricotta,
vegetables and herbs. Three-course dinner for two with wine, around
$65. Dinner only May through November, Thursday through Sunday.
Reservations recommended.
 &HT;    On Lake Shasta, Tail o' the Whale, at Bridge Bay Resort on
Bridge Bay Road, (530) 275-3021, serves steaks and seafood in a
nautical atmosphere with a view of the lake and bridge. Dinner for
two with wine, around $55. Breakfast, lunch and dinner daily.
 ATTRACTIONS  
 &HT;    Living Memorial Sculpture Garden, Highway 97, 13 miles north of
Weed, (530) 938-2218 or (530) 842-2477. Open daily. Free.
 &HT;    Mount Shasta Hatchery, 3 North Old Stage Road, City of Mount
Shasta; (530) 926-2215. Grounds open to visitors daily, 8 a.m. to 4
p.m. Free.
 &HT;    Sisson Museum, 1 North Old Stage Road, City of Mount Shasta;
(530) 926-5508. Open daily except major holidays. June through
September open from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.; in April, May, October,
November and December, 1 to 4 p.m. Closed January through March.
Free.
 &HT;    Heritage Junction Museum, 320 Main St., McCloud; (530) 964-2604.
Open May 1 through Oct. 31, Monday through Saturday from 11 a.m. to
3 p.m. and on Sunday from 1 to 3 p.m., or by appointment, (530)
964-2626. Free.
 &HT;    Shasta Sunset Dinner Train and McCloud Excursion Train, Main
Street, McCloud; (800) 733-2141 or (530) 964-2142; www.mctrain.com.
One-hour diesel excursions run at 4 p.m. on Fridays and Saturdays
in June and Thursdays, Fridays and Saturdays July through
September. Adults $10, children under 12, $5.
 &HT;    Steam excursions run several times a year. Dinner trains ($75 a
person without tax or tip) run from 6 to 9 p.m. on Saturdays from
January through April, November and December; Fridays and Saturdays
in May, June and October, and Thursdays, Fridays and Saturdays July
through September.
 &HT;    Enchanted Forest Porcelain Doll Factory, 4100 Pine St.,
Dunsmuir; (530) 235-0441. Open Tuesday through Saturday, 10 a.m. to
4 p.m.
 &HT;    Lake Shasta Caverns, Shasta Caverns Road exit of Interstate 5 in
O'Brien; (800) 795-2283. Open all year. From Memorial Day to Labor
Day tours depart every half hour, 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. In April, May
and September, tours are on the hour from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m.; Oct. 1
through March 31, 10 a.m., noon and 2 p.m. Adults $15, children 4
to 12, $7.
 &HT;    Shasta Dam, Shasta Dam Boulevard Exit of Interstate 5; (530)
275-4463 or (530) 275-1554. From Memorial Day through September,
tours are hourly from 9 a.m. to 4 p.m.; the rest of the year the
tour schedule is the same on weekends, but weekday tours are at 10
a.m., 11 a.m., 1 p.m. and 3 p.m. Free.
 GUIDES  
 &HT;    Shasta Mountain Guides, (530) 926-3117; Sierra Wilderness
Seminars, (888) 797-6867, and Alpine Skills International, (530)
426-9108, lead climbs on Mount Shasta. 
 &HT;    -----
