<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SHOPPING-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: WEEKEND DEALS IN AMERICAN CITIES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Let's hear it for the big-city weekend trip. Maybe the agenda is
to sleep late and breakfast in the room. Or spend the day wandering
through museums and shops before working out in the hotel health
club. Or dine well and see a show. But whether it's San Francisco,
Chicago or New York (or Atlanta, Minneapolis or Boston), the
two-nighter in the big city is a time-tested formula for
stimulation and restoration.
 &HT;    Weekend city deals are often a good buy because business
travelers are a Sunday-to-Thursday phenomenon. Come Friday and
Saturday, those giant Hyatts and Hiltons have rooms to spare. But
shop around to make sure that a big-city weekend doesn't add up to
credit-card shock a month later.
 &HT;    Thanks to the Internet, hotels have the ability to calculate
occupancy and sell rooms much faster and more efficiently than ever
before. This means that there are many room rates floating around
out there.
 &HT;    Sure, a low rate may sound good, but the extras can be painful.
The $20-a-day parking fee, the $15 continental breakfast and the
$8-per-person fee to use the health club are how hotels derive a
significant amount of their revenue. So try to get a low rate and
as many perks as possible up front.
 &HT;    The first step: Do your research. This is crucial for first-time
visitors to a city, but since hotels open, close and get renovated
all the time, it's essential for returning visitors to do as well.
A good city guidebook from Fodor's or TimeOut is fine, as are
Internet city guides such Digital City (www.digitalcities.com) and
Citysearch.com (www.citysearch.com).
 &HT;    Hotel brokers can be a good way to find affordable big-city
lodging. The best, nationally known ones, such as Quikbook (381
Park Ave. South, New York, N.Y. 10016; 800-789-9887;
www.quikbook.com) and Hotel Reservations Network (8140 Walnut Hill
Lane, Suite 800, Dallas, Texas 75231; 800-96-HOTEL;
www.180096hotel.com), offer discounts from 15 percent to 40 percent
off the so-called ``rack'' or published room rates in dozens of
cities around the country.
 &HT;    Other brokers, such as Express Reservations (3825 Iris Ave.,
Boulder, Colo. 80301; 800-356-1123; www.express-res.com), work only
with New York and Los Angeles, while companies such as Washington
D.C. Accommodations (2201 Wisconsin Ave. N.W., Suite C-110,
Washington, D.C. 20007; 800-554-2220; www.dcaccommodations.com)
specialize in a single city _ in this case our nation's capital.
 &HT;    The advantages to working with a hotel broker are
straightforward. They promise to save a traveler money. Period.
Hotels are grouped by price range, and there's no charge for their
services. But not every hotel is available through a hotel broker,
and smart travelers call a property directly to check the price.
Because room inventory fluctuates, hotels sometimes have a lower
price rate than discounters in order to sell off empty beds.
 &HT;    Another good source for weekend deals are the major lodging
chains, which frequently have lots of empty rooms on weekends.
Again, smart travelers call a property directly, call the chain's
toll-free number, visit the chain's Web site and see if the
property is available through a hotel broker. That may sound
time-consuming, and even overkill, but the room rates can vary
widely for the same room at the same property.
 &HT;    Some rates may include breakfast or parking privileges, while
others may be cheap, bare-bones room prices that can jump
dramatically once extras such as parking and breakfast are added
on.
 &HT;    Some hotel Web sites, like Marriott International
(www.marriott.com), require consumers to go through a
trial-and-error process for the best rates. Others are easier to
navigate and advertise their deals. Hilton Hotels (www.hilton.com)
has ``Hilton Value Rates'' for its properties _ rates that can also
be e-mailed to travelers every week.
 &HT;    Both Westin Hotels &AMP; Resorts (www.westin.com) and Sheraton
Hotels &AMP; Resorts (www.sheraton.com) have ``Hot Rates'' _
Internet-only specials that provide up to 20 percent discounts on
weekends.
 &HT;    Hyatt Hotels and Resorts' Web site (www.hyatt.com) features
``Special Offers,'' with rates for ``Value,'' ``Getaway Next
Weekend'' and ``Packages.'' For a given property, the prices and
perks can greatly differ.
 &HT;    The two on-line giants, Travelocity.com (www.travelocity.com)
and Expedia.com (www.expedia.com), are also sources for weekend
deals. The latter recently purchased Travelscape.com, which gives
it a base of thousands of hotel rooms around the country. They also
send out periodic discount hotel e-mailings.
 &HT;    For those who are flying, yet another source of weekend hotel
deals are offered by the airlines. Although the number of cities is
limited in nature, virtually all of the major carriers offer such
deals, often through their Web sites, including Delta
(www.delta-air.com), American (www.aa.com) and Continental
(www.continental.coml).
 &HT;    Delta Vacations, for example, has Standard, Preferred and
Ultimate air/hotel/transfers-inclusive vacations, based on hotel
categories. The cost obviously depends on the city chosen. But
because of the highly changeable nature of airfares between major
American cities, this convenient way of booking a city weekend may
not yield the best price.
 &HT;    For those who are flying, free spirits can let their trip be
dictated by the e-fares that the airlines post every week and which
Smarter Living.com (www.smarterliving.com) collates and sends out.
Just remember that most of these last-minute fares are only good
from Saturday to Monday or Tuesday. 
 ---- 
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
<TEXT>
