<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSE SENSE PREVAILS IN THIS MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any day now I may be faced with the choice of buying food for
the horses or groceries for Michael and me. I suppose we can aways
forage for food. I need to lose weight, so it might even be a good
thing. And I'm already getting some practice foraging because
Michael has me combing the neighborhood for dandelion greens, for
the horses.
</P>
<P>
   At first I was a little reluctant to pitch in and help. What
would the neighbors think? But Michael assured me the neighbors
would be glad to get rid of the dandelions. Most people think of
dandelions as weeds, although they cost $1.49 a bunch at Bread &AMP;
Circus. Those are the organic ones, unsullied by pesticides. The
horses like the $1.49 greens, but they like the foraged variety
too. They don't seem to notice the difference, not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The other day we were picking dandelions in the park and I heard
myself say, ``Oh, there's a big one over there,'' and I realized
that once again I'd been sucked into the vortex of Michael's horse
madness. Not that I needed to be reminded.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago Michael started spending time on the backside of
Suffolk Downs, working for the trainer Carlos Figueroa, mucking out
stalls, hot-walking the horses, doing whatever needed to be done.
It was strictly volunteer work. Michael wanted to learn the
business from the ground up, and Figueroa agreed to teach him.
``You are a student at Figueroa University,'' he told Michael,
``and you are on scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael's original plan was to write a book. I happen to know
that he has accumulated enough notes to write something roughly the
size of the Oxford English Dictionary, but the book is never quite
finished. There's always another story on the backside. And the
stories are like horses: One inevitably leads to another.
</P>
<P>
   The first horse was Fly McGrew. Michael and some friends bought
Fly and invested more than $11,000 in his training and upkeep. Not
long after Fly returned from a vacation _ six weeks of aqua
aerobics at a New Hampshire training center _ it became clear that
the horse simply didn't want to run. These days he has a new career
as a show horse, and is doing nicely, winning ribbons right and
left.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Michael's investors understandably dropped out. The
faithful few invested in another horse, Invigorate, then another,
Summer Attraction. Luis Arzola, Figueroa's nephew, trains the
horses. Michael is in charge of pampering them. He buys 100 pounds
of carrots a week and cuts them into dainty pieces. He picks
dandelion greens for them, with some help from me. Last week, he
brought home their dirty laundry.
</P>
<P>
   There are feed bills, vet bills, farrier bills, trainer bills.
The horses get regular rubdowns from Gina Smythe, their massage
therapist. At one point there was talk of consulting a horse
psychic, but that hasn't come to pass, not yet. All these things
cost lots of money. Both horses have been doing well. They're
supporting themselves, more or less, for the moment. But in racing,
you can't be sure of anything, except more bills.
</P>
<P>
   When we met, Michael had yet to become interested in horses.
When we married it was for better or for worse. I don't recall
anything being said about horses. Occasionally I remind him that
one of my aunts was married to a trainer, for a while. My ex-uncle
is a lovely man. I never understood why she left him, until now. In
those old Westerns, when a man has to choose between a horse and a
woman, the horse always wins. I used to think that was a joke. It's
not. But you know, dandelion greens don't taste all that bad in a
salad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-JOHNSON-BOS &LR;      06-05 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-JOHNSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLASH OF CULTURES AND COUPLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AMY GRAVES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Le Mariage &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Diane Johnson. Dutton. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   322 pp. $23.95. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Le Mariage'' is the story of a marriage about to commence in
France, and another that is headed for the skids. But its main
attractions are social satire and a string of wonderfully
interconnected crime capers, and only in a roundabout way is this
novel about marriage itself.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Diane Johnson's last novel, ``Le Divorce,'' a funny,
first-person story of the thrills of Paris through the wide eyes of
a college-age California woman who has just arrived there, ``Le
Mariage'' takes a while to warm to. In fact ``Le Mariage'' is a
delight and a frustration to read _ delightful for its amusing
insights on the clash of French and American cultures, frustrating,
at least for the first 100 or so pages, for its jaded outlook.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, mostly cagey veterans of Parisian life, are
self-centered and naive, the French narrow and class-conscious. The
women eye one other as rivals, alliances among the men are far from
easy, and no one's motives are the least bit noble.
</P>
<P>
   About halfway through, though, the story picks up steam with the
arrest of Clara, an American and former film actress who lives in a
Paris suburb with her filmmaker husband, Serge Cray. She faces the
trumped-up charge of destroying a historic monument, i.e.,
remodeling her house, though the real beef against her and her
husband is that they won't allow hunting on their property.
</P>
<P>
   As Clara languishes in jail, a national scandal in the French
tradition ensues. Though their neighbors are incensed at being
barred from land they've hunted for years, French sentiment in
general is against hunting. It is the charges connected with their
house that finally make the Crays unpopular. Newspapers on the
right and left weigh in, and television commentators ponder the
American erosion of French traditions. Much of the book's humor and
misunderstandings are generated by this clash of cultures; the
Americans often wind up on the losing end for trying to live in a
country they cannot fully understand.
</P>
<P>
   As the characters' lives unexpectedly collide, the book achieves
a lively balance between their actions and their inner reflections.
Johnson inhabits each one through fine stream-of-consciousness in
which a character's voice comes through as the focus shifts.
</P>
<P>
   She starts with Clara, whose perfect life seems in jeopardy well
before she lands in jail. Her beauty and distress attract a young
American journalist, Tim, who becomes a highly-paid aide to the
Crays. Their French neighbor, Antoine de Persand (who made his
first appearance in ``Le Divorce'' as the brother of a runaway
husband), also falls in love with Clara and offers to intercede on
her behalf in the battle over hunting.
</P>
<P>
   There are some obvious ironies _ Tim's attraction to Clara, for
example, grows as his wedding to the very French, somewhat snobbish
antiques dealer Anne-Sophie looms. But the book also offers
surprises. One of the funniest scenes happens just after one of the
scariest. Clara, who's become a pariah over the hunting question,
is harassed by a bunch of local Frenchmen. Her unintentional
revenge comes as she flees them: ``The hunters, half laughing, half
angry, crowded the car but made no effort to impede them as they
started up. Then Clara shifted into the wrong gear, first instead
of reverse. As it lurched forward into the crowd of men, she
slammed on the brakes and killed the motor. The men pulled back
from this dangerous display of inept driving, except for one who
screamed, `Mon pied, mon pied! Madame!' She had stopped on his
foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has a gift for comedy and surprise. We're led to think
that an American tourist, Delia, whose desires seem commonplace,
wants to go to the Louvre to see the art; later she's suspected of
going there to have a liaison with her lover, Gabriel, who's on the
lam in connection with a stolen manuscript. The real reason for
Delia's Louvre trips is one of the book's many comic twists.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson exploits the naivete of American characters who would
never describe themselves that way, especially Tim, who thinks he
knows the score because he is clever enough to write for both a
left-leaning publication and one on the right, while simultaneously
tracking down the stolen manuscript for a police friend and trying
to arrange for Serge to buy it. The French characters _ for
instance Anne-Sophie, who is about to marry an American without any
understanding of American life _ are skewered mainly for their
ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the plot that makes for eager reading: Will Clara be
found guilty, finally, and sentenced for the crime? Will
Anne-Sophie and Tim make up before they venture down the aisle?
Will Serge find out about the attraction between Antoine and Clara?
</P>
<P>
   If ``Le Divorce'' looked at what can happen when a couple splits
up and the families start squabbling, ``Le Mariage'' gives us what
happens when people's lives converge. The joke is that many of the
same things happen _ people fall in love, betray each other, or
cause some other kind of catastrophe _ around both occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Graves is a member of the Globe staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
