<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4980 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-SUMMER-BOS &LR;      06-05 1826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SUMMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SEASON OF ADVENTURE FOR THE ARMCHAIR TRAVELER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hedgehog was abject. Having stumbled into the bookstore
without his reading glasses, he saw only miles of shelves before
him _ titles he could barely ascertain, colors of vivid but
indistinguishable promise, seas of text that offered the mysteries
of the deep but no map by which to navigate. ``Whatever shall I
do?'' he asked the wise old owl, who, having singular vision, had
already taken up a familiar perch in the corner and was immersed in
E. O. Wilson's ``The Ants.'' ``I have misplaced my glasses and
neglected to make a reading list,'' said the hedgehog, wretchedly.
``What shall I read? How shall I choose?''
</P>
<P>
   The owl, accustomed to plaintive inquiries from creatures great
and small, paused only for effect. ``That all depends, my dear
fellow,'' he told the hedgehog, ``on where you want to go. Or,
perhaps more to the point, who it is you want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Diligent readers of this writer may recall the little hedgehog
from summers past, as he only emerges from his long hibernation
(much of it spent reading Goethe) to comment upon fair-weather
reading. But the old owl's point is well-taken. All of us read, at
some subliminal level, in order to venture to another realm, be it
the icy tundras of 19th-century Russia or the hot prospects of
Silicon Valley. Stupefied by commutes and commitments and the daily
tedia of modern life, we gravitate toward a biography of Mozart or
Lincoln _ and, for a few hours or days, see before us the streets
of Paris or feel the moral weight of American battlefields.
Literature provides an infinite itinerary that nonreaders may
respect but cannot fully appreciate; we can go anywhere, at any
time, for as long as we like _ without having to pack or worry
about the traffic. Like Tanglewood for the classical music buff or
London's West End for the theater maven, reading affords us flights
of fancy that elevate the senses, however fleetingly, to a higher
plane. There the world is richer and simpler both; there, the
prison of self that dictates much of real-time experience is, for a
little while, exchanged for a day pass to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that we gaze upon this year's vacation fare as vistas
of possibility, offering transport to foreign lands, and even
temporary foreign identities, for the armchair traveler. The genre
that may accomplish this fastest is that of adventure or expedition
literature _ what Brookline Booksmith has wonderfully titled its
``Oh No!'' section. Soon enough George Clooney will be starring as
Sebastian Junger's ``The Perfect Storm'' reaches the screen, taking
that last great wave on the Andrea Gail; a newer maritime entry in
Oh-No lit is Nathaniel Philbrick's ``In the Heart of the Sea: The
Tragedy of the Whaleship Essex,'' the story of the 1820 Nantucket
whaler calamity that inspired ``Moby-Dick.'' Kevin Patterson
describes a less eventful but more literary voyage in his account
of sailing to Tahiti, ``The Water in Between: A Journey at Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   If hypothermia is your thing, you'll appreciate the
calorie-by-calorie horror of this year's Everest bounty, the best
of which are probably ``The Lost Explorer: Finding Mallory on Mount
Everest'' by Conrad Anker and David Roberts, and ``Lost on Everest:
The Search for Mallory &AMP; Irvine'' by Peter Firstbrook. John Balzar
went the distance at lower altitudes, though scarcely less arduous,
in his thousand-mile sled-dog run across the Canadian Yukon;
``Yukon Alone'' isn't always true to its title (there were other
madmen and women on the Quest race), but his account is pleasurably
grueling to read, and you don't have to don his 13-pound bunny
boots to feel the victory _ or the cold.
</P>
<P>
   On to even harder climes. Those of us who appreciate war stories
do so for myriad reasons, but the most universal (or so I like to
believe) is that godly ascent of the senses afforded by the darkest
of conflicts. This summer's ``Cold Mountain'' wannabe is Howard
Bahr's ``The Year of Jubilo,'' about a Civil War soldier returning
home. Other recent fiction has approached the subject sideways:
Chang-Rae Lee's ``A Gesture Life,'' about an elderly
Japanese-American man living in upstate New York, has the Second
World War buried somewhere in its dark heart, while Michael
Ondaatje's ``Anil's Ghost'' encompasses the civil war in Sri Lanka
by relaying its individual losses. Colum McCann's brief but
iridescent ``Everything in This Country Must'' casts glances at the
Troubles in Northern Ireland through the sad specificities of its
characters.
</P>
<P>
   But the turf battles fought in American fiction this year have
been mostly over the groves of academe and the virtual premises of
cyberspace. Saul Bellow's roman a clef, ``Ravelstein,'' concerns a
brilliant, dyspeptic political philosopher whose name isn't Allan
Bloom, but might as well be; gossip connoisseurs will flock to his
tale, though Bellow purists will be disappointed. Philip Roth has
given his Zuckerman the role of tragic satirist in ``The Human
Stain,'' an oxymoronic narrative job that only Roth could envision
and achieve. Francine Prose's ``Blue Angel'' hits a lighter note;
its sendup of dour academicians will amuse everyone but its
targets, who will be too busy reading Lacan to notice.
</P>
<P>
   And bitheads may be too busy writing code to care, but the rest
of us, straddling worlds between the Web and old-fashioned text,
have been given a bridge to the other side in Richard Powers's
``Plowing the Dark'' _ a round-trip ticket to virtual reality, and
never mind that it's all pixels and mirrors. Caroline Preston is
less dazzled in ``Lucy Crocker 2.0,'' which trades in its graphics
cards and scanners for the canoes and lakes of backwoods Wisconsin
and finds romance in real life. If you must have the real unreal
thing, go to Michael Lewis's nonfiction spellbinder, ``The New New
Thing: A Silicon Valley Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking the geographical cure is what some readers require, and
this year's fictional road map will get you far indeed. Zadie
Smith, pyrotechnic newcomer to the stars, has delivered a big,
multicultural Londontown in ``White Teeth,'' which spans more than
a century and shows off a zeitgeist talent. Anchee Min, who gave us
``Red Azalea,'' takes poetic license with the story of Mao Zedong's
widow in ``Becoming Madame Mao.'' Our own Diva of Ideas, Susan
Sontag, fictionalized the life of Polish actress Maryna Zalezowska
for the historical fiction of ``In America''; Joyce Carol Oates,
who knows a good Gothic subject when she sees it, went to Marilyn
Monroe for the protagonist of ``Blonde.''
</P>
<P>
   Less action-packed but more word-by-word sensual is the rural
Ireland Edna O'Brien rewardingly delivers in ``Wild Decembers.'' In
``The Barbarians Are Coming,'' David Wong Louie takes a decidedly
American theme _ immigrants and their efforts for their children _
and makes it vividly, hilariously, his own, moving between the
sting of Connecticut WASPs and the pain of Chinese-American
immigration in mid-century. Charles Baxter stayed home in Michigan
for ``The Feast of Love,'' giving us the lyrical essence of ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream'' in his reimagining of a realm of love and
community. Sometimes time travel can take you further: Scottish
writer A. L. Kennedy has her protagonist in ``So I Am Glad''
falling in love with Cyrano de Bergerac. If the melodies and dirges
of ``Hamlet'' still fill your soul, you can return there by way of
John Updike's fiercely imagined ``Gertrude and Claudius.''
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps you prefer to strut and fret upon someone else's
stage for a while: Memoir and biography can accomplish that task
nicely and still get you home in time for dinner. The most
exhilarating contribution to memoir to appear in ages is Dave
Eggers's hardly hyperbolic ``A Heartbreaking Work of Staggering
Genius,'' which tap-dances across the conventions of the genre and
leaves you breathless. More conventional (and providing a tug of
the literary past) are Martin Amis's self-portrait and ode to his
father, Kingsley, in ``Experience: A Memoir,'' and Shirley
Hazzard's fond remembrance of Graham Greene in ``Greene on Capri: A
Memoir.'' National Public Radio cultists are already queueing up
for David Sedaris's just-released autobiographical essays, ``Me
Talk Pretty One Day.'' In the subgenre of Fabulous People You
Wouldn't Want to Be: Judith Thurman's ``Secrets of the Flesh: A
Life of Colette,'' which goes far in explaining why posterity loves
the French writer more than her children could ever manage. A
different kind of tragedy unfolds in British writer Hermione Lee's
``Virginia Woolf,'' which begins with a famous defining quote from
the great novelist's diary: ``I meant to write about death, only
life came breaking in as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick, on to happiness! Most of us read domestic dramas _
a.k.a., Gee, I Thought My Family Was Nuts _ for the literary
schadenfreude they provide: Nice to know that other people's
nuclear-unit meltdowns can translate into Art. Well, you still
can't do better than ``Anna Karenina.'' But this year has seen a
charmingly creepy story of a psycho marriage in Margot Livesey's
``The Missing World.'' Alice Elliott Dark's stories, ``In the
Gloaming,'' are mannered and elegant; George Saunders, in
``Pastoralia,'' sought the opposite effect by going dark and
allegorical. Two substantial recent novels from beloved
practitioners of the form are Rosellen Brown's ``Half a Heart'' and
Jayne Anne Phillips's ``MotherKind.'' For the latest nonfiction
popular treatise on Everybody's Miseries, including your own, go to
neurologist Frank T. Vertosick Jr.'s cringingly satisfying ``Why We
Hurt: The Natural History of Pain.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, if being somebody else _ Count Vronski, Ophelia,
Colette _ seems too ephemeral or transient a notion, there's always
the journey of becoming someone else. Jay Gatsby tried this, as did
a host of other half-tortured protagonists, and it didn't work, so
you'll be given no false encouragement here. But a true sojourn
into consciousness itself awaits readers of neurologist Antonio R.
Damasio's ``The Feeling of What Happens: Body and Emotion in the
Making of Consciousness,'' which will help tell you who you are and
how you got that way. In which case, a next obvious step might be
Accepting Who You Are: See David Brooks's ``Bobos in Paradise,''
and hold on to those stock options.
</P>
<P>
   The last word must go to our presbyopic hedgehog, who has been
patiently burrowing and foraging through piles of books since we
began, arriving at this rough list for his own reading pleasures:
Marc D. Hauser's ``Wild Minds: What Animals Really Think,''
Elizabeth Marshall Thomas's ``The Social Lives of Dogs,'' and _
even hedgehogs love a good horse race _ Jane Smiley's triumphant
novel, ``Horse Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone to the starting gate!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
