<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S HOT ON THE JUST-PUBLISHED LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bobos in Paradise'' by David Brooks (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25).
Brooks has identified a new social offshoot, a combination of
bohemian thinking and bourgeois living that is rising in importance
and wielding new clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare's Language'' by Frank Kermode (Farrar, Straus and
Giroux, $30). This thoughtful and readable treatise on the Bard's
magic returns to examining the language itself to explain his
continuing power.
</P>
<P>
   ``MotherKind'' by Jayne Anne Phillips (Knopf, $24). This
thoughtful novel is a crash course in the essential mysteries of a
child's birth, a mother's death, and a woman's plight as she
negotiates between the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red Mafiya'' by Robert I. Friedman (Little Brown, $25.95). An
investigative reporter doggedly documents how the Russian mob
landed on America's shores and is expanding its influence at a
rapid clip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pastoralia'' by George Saunders (Riverhead, $22.95). A second
striking collection finds personal stories, and occasional grace,
in the schlocky sprawl of the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Human Stain'' by Philip Roth (Houghton Mifflin, $26). An
eloquently imagined American tragedy, with a good man undone by his
desire to be ``just on his own and free.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At End of Day'' by George V. Higgins (Harcourt, $24). Artful
and uncompromising, as always, this final novel by the vernacular
master tells a story right out of the crime-news headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anil's Ghost'' by Michael Ondaatje (Knopf, $25). The author of
``The English Patient'' sets up another collision of history and
imagination, in his native Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   ``White Teeth'' by Zadie Smith (Random House, $24.95).
Incandescently inventive, insouciantly multicultural, this debut
novel shows off the new English.
</P>
<P>
   Selected from books recently reviewed in the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
