<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4983 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-MUSIC-TIEMPOS-HNS &LR;      06-05 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TIEMPOS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BLADES SAYS `TIEMPOS' IS MEANT FOR THE MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAMIRO BURR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While most salsa/Caribbean music is known for its spicy rhythms
and danceable grooves, the music on Ruben Blades' recent CD
``Tiempos'' is meant for the mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The instrumentation is different. There's no emphasis on
strident horn sections or fiery percussion solos,'' Blades said in
a recent interview. ``The lyrics seek to provoke thought and this
means to confront issues. Generally, salsa music serves as a way to
escape reality through dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiempos'' was nominated for a Grammy this year but it went to
Tito Puente's ``Mambo Birdland.'' Blades is a three-time Grammy
winner, most recently for ``La Rosa De Los Vientos'' (1996).
</P>
<P>
   The Panamanian singer/songwriter said ``Tiempos'' is a mix of
sounds and influences.
</P>
<P>
   ```Tiempos' is an effort to integrate different sounds from
Latin America to serve as a background for stories related to our
everyday life. The songs were written by me and another Panamanian
singer-songwriter named Romulo Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three instrumental songs by Costa Rican composers _
Walter Flores, Fidel Gamboa and Carlos Vargas. The range of themes
goes from the coldness of hired killers (`Sicarios') to the hope
for a better future (`Encrucijada').''
</P>
<P>
   The 14-track CD is contemplative, thoughtful and enchanting.
Blades is in his familiar stance _ decrying social decay in
``Hipocresia,'' then questioning personal faith in ``Creencia'' and
aching for a lost love in ``Dia a Dia.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bladesalso lightens up, kicking in fiery dance rhythms in
``Mar del Sur'' and the saxophone-driven R&AMP;B/funk grooves on the
title track. And he also offers optimism, as in the
acoustic-leaning ``Encrucijada,'' where he offers a hopeful message
of deliverance in a corrupt world.
</P>
<P>
   All 14 tracks were written by Blades in the style he long ago
called ``music journalism.'' And he supplements the traditional
salsa instruments of percussion and horns with violins, violas and
cellos to produce new textures. He's been called a salsa singer,
but a more apt description of his music, especially on this CD, is
political and philosophical folk/salsa ballads.
</P>
<P>
   But he dislikes labels and formats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the songs on `Tiempos' are descriptive of everyday
realities, some of which are difficult to confront by society as in
`Sicarios.' I refuse to be labeled because it locks you into a
specific category and prevents growth.''
</P>
<P>
   His music is reflective of his varied earliest musical
influences.
</P>
<P>
   ``My generation began to participate in music through rock 'n'
roll. It was young, different and exciting. Frankie Lymon and the
Teenagers, Orquesta Aragon and Frank Sinatra were early influences,
as diverse as they are. ... My first concert was when my father
took me to see Ismael Rivera and Cortijo y su Combo when I was
about 12 years old, in Panama.''
</P>
<P>
   Blades eventually obtained his law degree. He teamed up with
Hector Lavoe and later Colon, with whom he collaborated on the
landmark album ``Siembra,'' which produced Blade's biggest hit,
``Pedro Navaja.'' In 1984, Blades released ``Buscando America,''
another influential album whose title track focused on search for
truth and understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Blades also worked in movies, most notably ``Crossover Dreams''
and in 1988, ``The Milagro Beanfield War.'' More recent roles
include the famed muralist Diego Rivera in the 1999 film ``Cradle
Will Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1994, Blades expanded his interests to the political field,
declaring his candidacy for the president of Panama. And despite
losing, he felt he accomplished his goal of spotlighting the
growing social and democratic movement in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   ``My desire was always to serve my country. Politics is,
ideally, the way to do so under a democracy. In the future it is
very possible that once again I'll participate in the process. The
biggest lesson learned was that in order to be effective in the
political arena I must be residing in Panama full time, 24 hours a
day, 365 days a year. My absences hurt my credibility there. Only
when I can move permanently to Panama can it work.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Ramiro Burr by e-mail at rburr(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4985 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-NEWENGLAND-BOS &LR;      06-05 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEWENGLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LAST, FROM THE US, A SEAFARING SAGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For New Englanders, the problem with the Hornblower saga and the
Aubrey-Maturin novels is that their legendary sea warriors are
Brits. C. S. Forester did write one book with an American hero _
``The Captain from Connecticut,'' which some buffs consider better
than all the Hornblowers _ but that aside, the naval adventure is a
genre dominated by British writers and British captains.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the balance is being reversed, the seas swept
clear, with the arrival of ``All the Brave Fellows,'' the fifth in
James L. Nelson's ``Revolution at Sea'' series, featuring Captain
Issac Biddlecomb of the struggling Continental Navy (Pocket Books,
$25.95). Biddlecomb is a New Englander, as is his creator: Nelson
lives in Harpswell, Maine, and writes with the authority of a
former director of education aboard the sail training vessel HMS
Rose, a replica of a British frigate from the time of the American
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   In ``All the Brave Fellows,'' Biddlecomb runs his overmatched
brig aground on the Jersey shore to prevent its capture by the
British, with his wife on board tending to the wounded (she takes
part in the fighting in earlier books). Then he runs the British
blockade of Philadelphia to take command of a new Continental
frigate. The Biddlecomb stories are closer in spirit to Forester
than to Patrick O'Brian _ more action and less wit, and definitely
no chamber music _ which makes for spirited adventure and great
reading.
</P>
<P>
   Among other new books with New England settings by New England
authors, there is adventure of a happier sort in ``Logs of the Dead
Pirates Society'' by Russell S. Peffer (Sheridan House, $23.95).
It's a charming account of a summer's cruising in Buzzards Bay on a
marine research schooner crewed by high school students. Peffer,
their captain, teaches literature at Phillips Academy in Andover
and fills out the days' adventures with nicely integrated lessons
in history and science.
</P>
<P>
   But the youngsters are the heroes. A squall hits on a final
day's run into Marion, with a teenage girl at the helm. ``You need
me on deck?'' calls Peffer from below, where he is monitoring the
radar. ``No!'' she replies. ``We got this covered.'' And after a
moment's consideration, Peffer shouts back, ``It's your boat. Stir
it up!'' (Regrettably _ and inexcusably, at the price _ the book
lacks photographs or a nautical chart of Buzzards Bay.)
</P>
<P>
   Local history provides a point of entry for an impressive study
of broader historical issues in ``Suffering Soldiers: Revolutionary
War Veterans, Moral Sentiment and Political Culture in the Early
Republic'' (University of Massachusetts Press, $40). The author,
John Resch, teaches history at the University of New Hampshire,
lives in Peterborough, and draws on the men from that town who
served in the Continental Army for his case study. In the immediate
postwar years, the ``citizen-soldiers'' of the Colonial militias
were regarded as the true heroes of a ``people's war,'' to the
detriment of the ``professional soldiers'' of the Continental Army
who had generally served longer _ and often far from home.
</P>
<P>
   The professionals' postwar readjustment was difficult, promised
pensions were not forthcoming, and by the early 1800s many were
seeking relief. Public attitudes changed in response to the image
of these ``suffering soldiers'' and passage of a pension bill in
1818, Resch writes, ``honored them as virtuous republican
warriors'' and ``became a catalyst for legitimizing the Continental
Army as a republican institution.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``High-Minded and Low-Down'' (University of Massachusetts
Press, $20 paperback), Nicholas E. Tawa explores the role music
played in American life in the first half of the 19th century. His
interest, writes Tawa, professor emeritus of music at the
University of Massachusetts at Boston, ``is what people have to say
about themselves and their relation to music,'' seeing in their
comments a way to understand the period when American culture was
being formed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men and women,'' Tawa writes, ``stated repeatedly that to make
themselves better and to profit by the sentiments of the soul, they
turned to music. Clarifying this predilection further, they said
that they prized music because it was the native tongue of the
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   A chapter on music at parties and ``frolics'' provides a
delightful collection of anecdotes. A frequent destination during
rural winters was a tavern, where there would be supper and ``a
local fiddler . . . able and willing to supply the music for
dancing and singing.'' In Wiscasset, Maine, Pardon Bowers's Tavern
was a popular destination until he decided to charge admission.
``The sleighing parties refused to continue going there'' and a
local farmer made his living room available _ ``but suggested that
they bring their own fiddler.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to fiction with a New England setting: Rarely does a
town meeting produce so fine a short story as ``What Counts in Bogs
Harbor'' by Elizabeth Elder. The story appears in ``Watching a
River Freeze,'' a collection of stories, nonfiction pieces, and a
novella (Puddingstone Publishing, $21). The reader can guess that
some story Elder covered for The Coastal Journal, a weekly
newspaper in Bath was the genesis for this tale. Tyler C. Tyler had
been town clerk for so long that ``most people had the courtesy not
to mention his being late for town meeting'' _ and in
development-pressured mid-coast Maine, he owns a farm that's no
longer worked. His childhood friend, Lem Clemsey, no longer walks
into town by the shore road, ``not since the north shore property
had been developed and the new houses started to go up. `Them
cliffs wasn't never meant for houses,' Lem would snarl if anyone
asked his opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge in the early 1980s is the locale and inspiration for
Anne Whitney Pierce's ``Rain Line'' (Hardscrabble/University Press
of New England, $24.95). A drunken Harvard hockey star drives his
car off a bridge and into the Charles River. He dies but his
girlfriend, a violin student, survives _ not yet aware she is
pregnant with his child. He is working-class Irish, she is poor but
genteel old family, and Pierce has a fine eye and ear for the two
societies. The opening line _ ``To this day, I wonder if Danny knew
he was going to die'' _ suggests that there is guilt and coping
aplenty here, but it is firmly handled.
</P>
<P>
   Author J. P. Polidoro reports that ``Rapid Descent: Disaster in
Boston Harbor'' (Longtail Publishing, $16.95) is selling well at
local airports _ to people who have already landed, one hopes.
Suffice to say that in this thriller, anything that could possibly
go wrong with a commuter flight out of Logan Airport _ over the
harbor, in the harbor, even under the harbor _ does.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kenney is a member of the Globe staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
