<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CHANG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING INDIVIDUALS OF SIAMESE TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
CHANG AND ENG 
By Darin Strauss 
Dutton, 323 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a January morning in 1874, Eng Bunker awoke to find himself
alone for the first time in his life.
</P>
<P>
   In the stillness of dawn, his twin brother, Chang, lay dead
beside him _ meaning Eng's own death was imminent, as close as his
next breath. Wrapping his arms around his brother, Eng says, ``This
is the end I have feared since we were a child.''
</P>
<P>
   With this beguiling, mysterious line, Darin Strauss begins his
sublime historical novel, ``Chang and Eng,'' based on the lives of
the men for whom the term ``Siamese twins'' was coined. Born in
Thailand in 1811, the brothers Bunker (a name adapted after they
moved to America) lived their 63 years conjoined at the chest, and
became famous as a caged sideshow attraction for such showmen as P.
T. Barnum. They would eventually marry two sisters, settle as
farmers in North Carolina, and father 21 children.
</P>
<P>
   While many people are at least vaguely familiar with the famous
photograph of the brothers that adorns the book's dust jacket, time
has eroded their deeper lives, reducing them to little more than
freakish oddities. Yet in this ambitious, assured first novel,
Strauss imagines these men in full. They are given voice, their
fears, hopes, and dreams made vital; most important, Strauss
establishes for each man a vivid, poignant personality.
</P>
<P>
   Narrated in deathbed flashbacks by Eng, the story ping-pongs
between the various periods in the brothers' lives. Born on the
Mekong River, they are first believed by their parents to be twin
boys. It is not until a midwife tries to bathe them that the truth
is revealed. Their father screams, and the horrified midwife drops
them to the floor. Even though each child has a full, distinct
body, all that is noted is the ligament binding them at the
breastbone _ ``not two children, but one curse on the family,'' Eng
says. Only their mother first approaches her children without
trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother, knowing my brother and me for more than one child,
kept her calm,'' Eng says. ``The glimmer of two thousand years of
Siamese superstition left her dark eyes in an instant. She cooed
into my face and patted our cheeks.'' News of the ``double-child''
spread quickly, bringing curiosity-seekers and any number of
medicine men suggesting various methods of separation. None would
work, though that's fine with Chang, who is content fastened to his
brother.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for Eng, who craves a life alone. The contrast is
particularly sharp when as boys they first encounter other
children. Chang sees the boys as ``half-formed,'' while his brother
views them as ``lovely'' and ``liberated.'' And it's not the only
difference between the brothers. Chang is more fun-loving,
gregarious, and freely enjoys _ perhaps too much _ alcohol. Eng, on
the other hand, is reserved and scholarly; as for alcohol, he won't
touch it, although he feels its ill effects whenever his brother
indulges.
</P>
<P>
   At its simplest, ``Chang and Eng'' is a tale of siblings living
under most uncommon circumstances. But Strauss understands all of
this story's angles and curves, uses them as an exploration of
prejudice _ whether in Siam, where the king, fearing the the
``double-boy'' represents a bad omen, wants them executed; or in
pre-Civil War America. And then there is their exploitation by
various hucksters eager to get rich from what one newsman calls
``the unholy, double-freak show.''
</P>
<P>
   As a novel, ``Chang and Eng'' is never a freak show, and
Strauss's elegant prose soars in the chapters where the brothers
meet Sarah and Adelaine Yates, two sisters who are first fascinated
by Chang and Eng, then fall in love with them. Chang is instantly
smitten, but Eng is more reticent. ``Rather than a flood of
passion, love came to me as a curious and distant spectacle,'' Eng
says. ``But I shared my brother's resolve to marry like ordinary
human beings, to experience the matrimonial joy less deserving men
relished.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Strauss writes about the brothers' intimate lives with
their wives, but he does so with restraint, even beauty. How the
brothers respect each other's privacy becomes an almost-spiritual
undertaking, as when Chang spends his first night with Adelaine,
and Eng passes ``into the highest loftiness of trance, trying to
raise my spirit out of our bodies, like a mist to circle the world
and vapor toward Siam.''
</P>
<P>
   Because there is no definitive record of Chang and Eng's lives,
their history, Strauss writes, has largely comprised ``a confusion
of legend, sideshow hyperbole, and editorial invention.'' This, of
course, works to the author's advantage, since he is not shackled
by niggling facts and details. Still, Strauss neither plays fast
and loose with this freedom, nor uses the opportunity only to
conjure answers to our most puerile questions. He memorably
accomplishes through fiction something that history has long denied
to Chang and Eng. He takes these so-called freaks and again makes
them men.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
