<HEADER>
A4988 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-GRENOBLE-ART-B     06-05 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-GRENOBLE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 SIXTH-GRADER'S WORDS BUILD MYTHIC WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENFIELD, Mass. _ Nicky Grenoble, 12 and intrepid, is cruising
the virtual world she has created on the Internet. ``That's my
house,'' she says, as a large unfinished white edifice swims into
view. She points to two red cars parked in the garage and says
proudly, ``That's my friend's car and that's mine.'' Then she zooms
down a blacktop highway and a small black-and-white cow pops into
view.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the cow I named after a kid in my class. Idon't like
him,'' Nicky says. ``That's why he's in the middle of the road as a
cow.''
</P>
<P>
   Move over J. K. Rowling, author of the best-selling Harry Potter
series. Out in the bucolic hinterland of Western Massachusetts,
right down the road from Butynsky's Farm Stand, lives a
freckle-faced sixth-grader who is so adept at putting the fruits of
a gifted imagination into words that she recently won a national
writing contest for young authors. Like Rowling, she weaves
material from real life into tales of mythical places peopled by
wizards, dragons, and sprites. But in a 21st-century twist, Nicky
also populates her stories with futuristic creatures she has
gleaned from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write about stuff I'm thinking about and I can insult people
as much I want to do without them
</P>
<P>
   knowing it,'' Nicky says. ``But I don't like real life much. I
like science fiction and fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Timekeeper,'' the short story she submitted to the Trumpet
Book Club Young Authors of America contest, is about a wizard who
looks through a mirror (yes, ``Alice's Adventures in Wonderland''
is one of Nicky's favorite tales) and decides to lure a 12-year-old
girl named Tory into his mystical kingdom. The Tory Nicky describes
in her story looks a lot like her, with ``red-gold hair,'' a
``spray of light freckles'' across her nose, and eyes that ``change
color with her mood.'' The judges for Scholastic Inc., which
sponsored the contest, honored Nicky's entry as one of 20 selected
from 1,500 entries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of the entries this year was really good, so this
is a real kudo,'' says Betsy Howie, manager of contests and
promotions for Scholastic. ``The judges were impressed with the way
she combined a 12-year-old kid and a Merlin-like timekeeper. Her
story was a sophisticated blend of the ultramodern and the ancient
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicky (short for Nicole) lives with her younger sister, Monique,
a precocious 6 1/2-year-old whose book of the moment is Roald
Dahl's ``Matilda,'' and her parents in a modest Cape house on the
rural outskirts of Greenfield. She takes a yellow school bus every
day to a public elementary school, practices her piano, and rides
bicycles with her next-door neighbor, Erik. She bites her
fingernails, and leaves them painted blue long after the polish has
chipped. She wears denim capri pants and tames her bouncy auburn
hair with a green scarf.
</P>
<P>
   She has no time for Britney Spears or the Backstreet Boys
(``Their songs all sound the same''), but jumps to sing lyrics
(``C'mon, c'mon, come tell me'') by her favorite group, Smash
Mouth. Her mind is a castle of fanciful ideas, plucked from hours
of reading and roaming the Internet on the computer in her bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Nicky's ``absolute favorite'' book is ``The Golden Cat'' by
Gabriel King. ``He's a genius, you know,'' she says. She has two
pet cats, Shawnee and Angel, and her room is filled with fluffy
white stuffed cats, bronze cat figurines, and, behind her bed, a
poster of five angelic-looking white cats and one mischievous
charcoal cat with red horns. ``I think cats have more free will
than dogs,'' she says. ``They don't come when you call them. I
think that's really cool.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was Nicky's passion for felines and the Net that
combined to inspire her first foray into fiction. A devoted fan of
``Cats,'' the Broadway musical, Nicky had already discovered the
fan fiction on the ``Cats'' Web site when her sixth-grade teacher
assigned the class to write a story using their spelling words.
``Fan fiction,'' Nicky explains, ``is where people take the
characters of one story and make up other characters to go with
that story, or make up other stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicky's story, now posted on the ``Cats'' Web site under the
pseudonym Aria, is ``about these two girls and they saw one of
their cats leave the house and they followed it and it ended up in
a junkyard based on the Jellico cats' junkyard, and the two girls
saw their teacher in a cage and the cats bared their teeth and
started to chase them and they ran back to their house,'' she says.
``And one of the cats had a human voice and a human Cheshire-like
smile and when the girl woke the next day, she thought it was all a
dream, but then she saw one of her cats smiling at her with human
lips.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at the kitchen table, eating a lunch of instant noodle
soup, Nicky says she is angry at Andrew Lloyd Webber, the producer
of ``Cats,'' because he's shutting down the longest-running musical
in Broadway's history. ``I forced all the kids in my class to sign
a petition,'' she says. ``They had no idea what they were
signing.'' She giggles. ``It could have been a contract to make
them my slaves.''
</P>
<P>
   The cell phone on the table rings and Nicky grabs it. ``Hi,''
she says. ``I'm kinda busy right now. Go away!'' She hangs up.
``That was Erik,'' she says. ``If I answer the phone and say `go
away' you know it's Erik. He wanted to go for a bike ride in the
rain. He's going to get himself kidnapped.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicky explains that she likes to ``torture'' Erik. ``I just have
this reputation for not being right in the head. I had a contest
once to get strange looks from people. I think I got about 200
strange looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicky's mother, Suzanne, who is also sitting at the table,
smiles at her daughter. ``Nicky is just irreverent,'' she says.
``She's got my twisted sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   And her mother's love of words. Suzanne Grenoble is a former
literature teacher who now stays home with the children while her
husband, Robert, works as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Grenoble is writing a novel aimed at the young adult
market, but it looks like her elder daughter will be published
before she is. Scholastic is planning to include Nicky's winning
short story in a special anthology, due out in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe I won,'' Nicky says. ``I never thought it
would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The telephone rings again. Nicky disappears. In a minute she is
back. ``Can Emily come over, puhleeze?'' she cajoles her mother.
The answer is yes and Nicky is gone for good this time, to gab on
the phone with her friend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
