<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5015 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-MARINES-BOOK-HNS &LR;      06-05 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINES-BOOK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOOK STRUGGLE PAYS OFF FOR WORLD WAR II RAIDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than half a century ago, Gerry West and Bob Addison took
part in seven critical, bloody battles under the canopied rain
forests of the Solomon Islands.
</P>
<P>
   West and Addison were Marines, members of the battalion known as
Edson's Raiders in honor of their commander, Merritt A. ``Red
Mike'' Edson. They were part of the United States' first offensive
at Guadalcanal Island in the Pacific war, and their brigade took on
legendary status within the Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   They epitomized valor in the jungle's killing fields.
Twenty-four Raiders, mostly enlisted Marines and Navy corpsmen,
fought with such noteworthy bravery that they had U.S. Navy ships
named in their honor, all but one posthumously.
</P>
<P>
   West, a former corporal who lives in Fort Edward, N.Y., and
Addison, retired athletic director at Adirondack Community College
in Queensbury, N.Y., had for years worried that the heroic saga of
their unit would be relegated to a footnote in the annals of World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Edson's Raiders have met annually since 1948 in
Quantico, Va., at Marine Corps headquarters. A decade ago, West and
Addison were instrumental in the formation of a book committee in
the Edson's Raiders Association. The goal was to get their story
into print.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different kind of battle altogether for the ex-Marines,
but it required the same determination and self-reliance that
helped them survive two long years in the South Pacific. Striking
gold with the fourth writer, the committee worked to detail the
account of their battalion, and the 345-page hardcover book
``Edson's Raiders'' came off the presses earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   They hired Joseph Alexander, a retired Marine Corps colonel and
the author of five books, who is probably best known as a
celebrity-host on cable television's the History Channel, to
research and tell the story of their battles. His fee: $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders really took matters into their own hands once
Alexander was finished. They published the book themselves, under
the imprimatur Edson's Raiders Assoc. Inc., in a limited edition of
just more than 3,000 copies. That cost $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you, we're really proud to have this book in
print,'' said West, 80. ``It was a real effort. We wanted to have
it in our hands before too many more of our guys passed on.''
</P>
<P>
   They are primarily selling the book (listed at $32) themselves
and by classified ads placed in Leatherneck magazine, a monthly
publication of the Marine Corps. West and Addison as of last week
had sold 1,115 copies at $19.95, which, after all of their
expenses, gives them a $6 profit per book. Copies are also being
sold at the Marine Corps headquarters for $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, nearly 2,000 copies of ``Edson's Raiders'' are in
boxes in a storage facility or piled high in West's home. They may
eventually sell the majority of them at cost to a national
bookstore chain, because their goal all along was to break even
with this project.
</P>
<P>
   By convincing Alexander to write the story of Edson's Raiders,
the association was able to separate itself from the pack of
self-published books. Alexander, historian and author of the 1997
book, ``The Battle History of the U.S. Marines: A Fellowship of
Valor'' (Naval Institute Press), brought instant credibility to
their project.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who has copyright ownership of the book ``Edson's
Raiders,'' is working with the Naval Institute Press to publish an
edited version of the book later this year. This was the first book
Alexander was commissioned to write.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rough for any veteran to write about his own memoirs,''
said Alexander, who retired from the Marines in 1989 after 29
years. ``Even if you are a first-rate writer, what you lack with
self-publishing is the national-level marketing and distribution
systems. Taking care of the sales can be a full-time job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can market a book yourself, but the key is to get it on
Amazon and get someone to review it there,'' he added. ``Then I
think you have a chance to break even.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Edson's Raiders'' has yet to appear on the electronic catalog
at Amazon.com. That's because Edson's Raiders Association, the
book's publisher, is also the book's primary seller.
</P>
<P>
   West says he and Addison believe that most of the surviving 300
or so members of Edson's Raiders (of the 2,800 Marines, Navy
medical personnel and chaplains who served with the 1st Marine
Raider Battalion between Feb. 16, 1942, and Feb. 1, 1944) are aware
of the book and have had a chance to purchase copies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   PLETHORA OF MILITARY BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   ``Edson's Raiders'' may then join the shelves teeming with
self-published military memoirs and accounts of particular
campaigns. At a time when only a minimal investment is required to
publish a relatively high-quality book, the number of new books of
military history grows by quantum leaps seemingly every day.
</P>
<P>
   These are books that are well outside the radar of best-seller
lists, unlike the recently released ``Flags of Our Fathers''
(Bantam) by James Bradley with Ron Powers, or NBC anchor Tom
Brokaw's megaselling tributes to the World War II generation. These
are books with neither aspirations nor dreams of being a financial
success.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Keene, managing editor at Leatherneck magazine, says his
office is constantly receiving unsolicited self-published stories,
which he describes as vanity press books.
</P>
<P>
   Explained Keene: ``We get so many books we can't even mention
them all. Some former lance corporal who was alive in World War II
will decide he wants to write about himself, and he pays a lot of
money to get it published.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can read some of them and tell it's a terrible book, and
some aren't very accurate,'' Keene said. ``Every once in a while
there's a diamond in the rough. But a majority of the ones that
come through these vanity presses aren't that good. I think the
majority are done with good intentions, but most aren't well
researched or well-edited or well-written.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To purchase a copy of ``Edson's Raiders, send a check (made out
to Edson's Raiders Association) for $19.95 to Gerald V. West, 65
County Rte. 42, Fort Edward, NY 12828.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
