<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSACTION-1ST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT UNDER SIEGE BY LAW SUITS 
</HEADLINE>
 LEDE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (REVISES AND CORRECTS)  
 By JON KAMMAN  
   
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - While fighting to
</P>
<P>
   keep from being split in two by the federal government,
Microsoft Corp. is also suddenly under siege by about 150 lawsuits
demanding refunds for millions of buyers of its Windows software.
</P>
<P>
   Class-action attorneys have beaten paths to courthouses
nationwide since a federal judge declared on Nov. 5 that the
world's largest software company was using monopolistic power to
crush competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also gouged consumers in pricing Windows and its
entwined Internet Explorer browser, according to the onslaught of
private lawsuits. The company denies overcharging for any of its
products.
</P>
<P>
   Because the federal antitrust action won by the Justice
Department and 20 states did not seek monetary damages from
Microsoft, private consumers, including five in Arizona, have been
filing lawsuits at the rate of more than one every weekday in the
past six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are simply a bunch of attorneys trying to make money,''
Microsoft spokesman Jim Cullinan said at the company's headquarters
in Redmond, Wash. ``This is not for the benefit of consumers in any
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Four lawsuits filed since December by Phoenix law firms are
seeking class-action status, several in conjunction with nationally
recognized firms that have represented consumers in
multimillion-dollar cases involving tobacco, breast implants, the
fen-phen diet drug and numerous other pandemics.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs are a Phoenix law firm, a Scottsdale employment
agency that bought 13 computers loaded with Windows, two individual
Phoenix residents described as ``typical'' computer users and a
bowling-alley owner in Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   If the lawsuits are successful, virtually anyone in Arizona who
bought one or another type of Windows could qualify to collect
damages.
</P>
<P>
   The awards could be three times the amount Microsoft is judged
to have overcharged for Windows _ minus substantial lawyers' fees
and other costs of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the lawsuits are the findings of fact issued in
November by U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson in the
government's antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said a Microsoft study showed that the company could
have charged $49 instead of $89 for an upgrade to Windows 98, and
``there is no reason to believe that the $49 price would have been
unprofitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words gave attorneys visions of winning as much as $120,
or three times the $40 price differential cited by the judge, for
every unit of Windows bought by millions of individuals and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, claims could total in the ``tens of billions of
dollars,'' according to the Consumer Federation of America. In
fiscal 1999 alone, Windows sales totaled $8.5 billion, accounting
for more than 40 percent of Microsoft's total revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of Microsoft's vulnerability and wealth has
attracted many of the biggest names in class-action litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's literally coast to coast,'' said Michael Flannery, an
attorney in the San Diego of the nation's largest firm specializing
in class actions. The Milberg Weiss firm is no stranger to Arizona,
having won $240 million for investors bilked by the collapse of
Charles H Keating Jr.'s American Continental Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Flannery said the firm is handling at least a dozen lawsuits
against Microsoft, including two in conjunction with the Phoenix
firm of Bonnett Fairbourn Friedman &AMP; Balint.
</P>
<P>
   Another Arizona lawsuit was filed by the Phoenix office of a
Minneapolis firm associated with the Cincinnati practice in which
class-action icon Stanley Chesley is a nameplate member. That firm
also is handling at least 12 Microsoft lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the lawsuits are baseless,'' Microsoft's Cullinan said.
``There was nothing in . . . the Department of Justice case that
ever suggested that Microsoft was overcharging customers. In
actuality, the government found the exact opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Cullinan said the $89 vs. $49 cost cited in Jackson's findings
of fact was based only on Microsoft's marketing survey of what
consumers thought Windows 98 might be worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most consumers considered $89 a fair price and have shown so
since,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation that a $49 price could have produced an adequate
profit is ``kind of weird,'' Cullinan said, because the cost of
developing an operating system ``is hundreds of millions, if not
billions, of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that's just an erroneous finding from the court,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   All four Arizona lawsuits started in Maricopa County Superior
Court because the state's antitrust and consumer protection
statutes are seen as hospitable to such actions. But two were
transferred to U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   In federal court, nearly identical Microsoft lawsuits from
around the country are likely to be merged into one, and ``cases
tend to go on forever,'' said Marty Harper, an attorney at the
Goodwin Raup firm in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the Phoenix cases moved to federal court was sent
to Maryland for likely consolidation, prompting the plaintiff's law
firm to start over in state court by filing a slightly different
action on behalf of a new plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   Harper said the lawsuit his firm filed was carefully crafted to
be ``unremovable'' from state court.
</P>
<P>
   Class-action lawyers deny they are motivated by greed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say they are basically a private attorney general'' for
consumers' interests, attorney Flannery said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bring to justice large corporate wrongdoers with large
amounts of wealth who might otherwise escape that justice because
individual consumers who are hurt can't take them on by
themselves,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
