<P>
   &UR; GHOST OF GRAHAM GREENE HAUNTS SIERRA LEONE CAPITAL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANGLOPHILE-FREETOWN-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FREETOWN _ Unnoticed amid the turmoil of events in Freetown,
Sierra Leone's capital, the world has lost one of its most
supremely seedy literary landmarks. As the pride of the British
fleet sailed into view of Graham Greene's ``world of tin roofs, of
vultures clanging down,'' the cockroaches of The Bedford Hotel _
immortalized in his book ``The Heart of the Matter'' _ were frying
inside. The seedy hotel, with its $3.50 room price, was a reminder
of the Freetown that Greene knew when he served here as a Colonial
Officer in the early 1940s....By Alex Duval Smith, The Independent
of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (875 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOILET-TO-TAP WATER SCHEME RAISES A STINK IN CALIFORNIA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `TOILET-TO-TAP'-CALIF-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's a scare going around the San Fernando
Valley in Los Angeles. In this tract of suburban communities laid
out between the mountains and the desert, the authorities are so
short of water that they are seriously considering recycling human
excrement and plunging it straight back into the drinking supply.
The ``toilet-to-tap'' scheme has raised quite a stink among
residents worried about their property values, not to mention
health....By Andrew Gumbel, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: California) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GENTRIFICATION AWAITS PARIS' LAST WORKING-CLASS AREA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `REAL'-PARIS-ADIEU?-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Canal Saint-Martin is a time machine. If you walk
the three miles of the canal, you abandon the wealthy, homogenized,
well-scrubbed grandeur of 21st-century Paris. You infiltrate a
meaner, tougher, more picturesque, almost vanished city: the Paris
of B&AMP;W movies and the Inspector Maigret novels. But not for much
longer, perhaps. The Paris city council is considering an ambitious
$95 million plan to revive the neglected canal system _ a plan
which residents fear will plunge a dagger of gentrification into
the heart of one of the last remaining, pleasant, working-class
areas of Paris....By John Lichfield, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
