<P>
   (375 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALL'S QUIET ON THE LEBANESE FRONT _ FOR NOW, AT LEAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEBANON-LIMBO-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KFAR KILA, LEBANON _ As a procession of helicopters swept in to
land, loudspeakers blasted Wagner's ``Ride of the Valkyries'' over
the hillsides southern Lebanon. The U.N. peacekeepers' noisy
display was a deliberate reference to the Vietnam War, as depicted
in the film ``Apocalypse Now.'' Pundits had predicted an apocalypse
in Lebanon if Israel made good its promise to withdraw from the
country's southern fringes even without a peace deal with Syria.
But the Israeli-Lebanese border has remained remarkably quiet since
Israel's army retreated to its side on May 24, ending a 22-year
occupation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (925 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA: WHERE ECOLOGIST IS A DIRTY WORD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA-BLUE-`GREENS'-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Even in the democratic heyday of post-communism, Russia
was a tough place for greens. Where the right laws existed, they
were hard to enforce. A combination of abundant natural wealth,
plenty of space and careless habits meant that few Russians took
environmental housekeeping seriously. Now, a mix of business
interests, criminal activity and government paranoia threatens to
make matters far worse. On top of all this, the new government of
Vladimir Putin announced ambitious plans on May 25 to build 40 new
fast-breeder nuclear-power station in Russia over the next 30
years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT'S TO BE DONE ABOUT PERU'S SHAM ELECTION? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STINKER-FUJIMORI-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIMA _ ``Democracy is dead,'' declared President Alberto
Fujimori's defeated challenger, Alejandro Toledo, to 50,000
supporters in Lima after the polls had closed in Peru's May 28
presidential run-off. ``Fujimori, murderer,'' chanted the crowd.
Much of Latin America tacitly agreed, So too, loudly, did the
United States. But what were they all to do about the result? And
more importantly, perhaps, how will Fujimori reckon with the new
political activism that his electoral shenanigans have unleashed? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; E-COMMERCE RESTORES TRUCKING'S GLORY DAYS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CYBER-TRUCKERS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RICHMOND, VA. _ Once, America's trucking industry was a cozy,
regulated semi-cartel, with a few big companies dominating most
regions. CB radio and the call of the open road made every boy
dream of one day driving his own 18-wheel rig. But when
deregulation hit in the 1980s, the business quickly lost its charm.
Yet a radical transformation of the trucking industry is now under
way, thanks to e-business. CB radio has given way to e-mail, GPS
tracking and wired hubs. Who knows? As e-commerce restores
trucking's glory days, a new generation of kids might even dream of
being truckers again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Virginia) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,100 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOREOVER &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IS SOCCER OUT OF SYNC WITH THE AMERICAN SPIRIT? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOCCER-STARS'N'STRIPES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ As the Euro 2000 championship looms and the
continent again becomes football-crazy, an old question is being
asked once more: will Americans ever learn to love ``the other''
football _ European football, that is _ or are the rhythms of the
world's most popular game somehow out of sync with the American
spirit? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW SOFTWARE GOT ITS NAME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; VICTORIAN-`SOFTWARE'-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ An etymology researcher has discovered that the
ubiquitous computer term ``software'' was coined way ahead of its
time _ though in a quite different context. Back in 1850,
``soft-ware'' and ``hard-ware'' were terms used by trash-can
scavengers to distinguish compost from non-biodegradable matter. So
a Victorian would have been baffled by the modern use of the
term.... Garbage in, garbage out, as computer programmers like to
say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
