<P>
   &UR; HOW TO STOP DIAMONDS FROM FINANCING NASTY AFRICAN WARS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIAMOND-WARMONGERS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ De Beer's nightmare has shifted from a flood of
diamonds to blood on diamonds. At least three wars in Africa are
``fuelled'' by diamonds. In two of them, rebel movements control
mines and sell diamonds to buy weapons. The United Nations wants to
cut off their source of cash: so-called `conflict diamonds.' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIJI: STOP MAKING CONCESSIONS TO GEORGE SPEIGHT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIJI-TERRORISM-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ George Speight is known as a ``failed businessman.''
But since May 19, when Speight and other rebels took the Fijian
government hostage, he has been proving to be a successful
terrorist. Enough is enough, however; a line must be drawn, and
Speight expelled from Fiji. In the longer term, a solution is
needed for the underlying dispute between Fijians and Indians,
which is over land. Whatever happens, Speight must not be
rewarded. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AVENGING DUKAKIS: WHY GORE MIGHT YET TRIUMPH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GORE-DUKAKIS-REVENGE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What can Al Gore do to lift himself out of his
current doldrums? Change from earth tones to black leather, to up
the ante on last October's Alpha-male makeover? Replace Naomi Wolf
with Tina Brown? Appear on Oprah Winfrey? A more modest strategy
would be to sit back and reflect on the campaign of the last
Democrat to lose. Michael Dukakis's 1988 defeat at the hands of
George Bush senior provides a perfect playbook of how to destroy
George junior. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE REMAKING OF A PRESIDENT: GEORGE W. GETS A MAKEOVER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSH-REINVENTED-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The only way that George W. Bush's presidential
campaign could go any better these days would be for Al Gore to
announce that, as well as smoking a little dope as a student, he
also joined the Communist Party. Whatever the outcome of the race,
one of the lasting ironies of the 2000 campaign may prove to be
that the ``lightweight'' Bush grabbed the intellectual edge from
the ``heavyweight'' Gore. &QL;
</P>
