<HEADER>
A5053 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-BUSH-REINVENTED-ECONO     06-05 1785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-REINVENTED-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REMAKING OF A PRESIDENT: GEORGE W. GETS A MAKEOVER  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (NOTE: Two trims, totaling 525; 1,600 words uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The only way that George W. Bush's presidential
campaign could go any better these days would be for Al Gore to
announce that, as well as smoking a little dope as a student, he
also joined the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   The election is being fought on Democratic issues (education,
health care and welfare) at a time of extraordinary prosperity. Yet
Bush is dominating the policy debate, sounding exciting Republican
variations on familiar Democratic themes.
</P>
<P>
   The latest opinion polls show Bush ahead by between six and ten
percentage points. He is ahead among almost every important
demographic group _ men and women, Catholics and Northeasterners,
married couples and independent voters and, in all probability,
among married swingers as well.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Gore's constituency seems to be shrinking to what
might be unkindly described as geezers and losers: the over-65s and
people earning $20,000-40,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   There are still good reasons for thinking that the vice
president is a much more powerful candidate than he currently
appears. But, at the very least, Bush has justified some of the
hopes that the Republican establishment invested in him.
</P>
<P>
   He has not only made far better use of the two months following
the major primaries than Gore; he has also outperformed him on what
ought to be Gore's strongest ground, policy wonkery.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Gore is being deafened by criticisms from his fellow
Democrats, while Bush basks in the praise of the Republican
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   The public face of Bush's makeover has been a series of
well-choreographed press conferences. More interesting has been
what has gone on behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has established a friendly relationship with the press
corps, a group that he initially tried to micromanage and
spoon-feed.
</P>
<P>
   Within his own party, he has cleverly used his struggle with
Senator John McCain to silence the right-wingers who have often
seen the Bushes as unsound Rockefeller Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   And he has proved a master of using the full range of his
party's resources _ from policy intellectuals such as Steve
Goldsmith and Larry Lindsey to clean-scrubbed young activists. A
party that threatened to fall apart during the McCain insurgency is
now pulling in the same direction.
</P>
<P>
   The main aim of all this activity has been to eliminate Bush's
two big negatives. The most obvious is the fear that he is a
prisoner of the far right. This is always a risk if you are
governor of a state that executes more people than most countries
do.
</P>
<P>
   But the risk became a serious political liability when Bush
aligned himself with Ralph Reed, the former head of the Christian
Coalition, and Bob Jones III, the head of a university that banned
interracial dating, in order to crush McCain in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since then Bush has tried to rebrand himself as ``a
different kind of Republican.'' He regularly boasts that he won the
support of 50 percent of Hispanic voters and 25 percent of blacks
in his last election as governor.
</P>
<P>
   He has perfected an aggressive new form of affirmative action
relating to photo opportunities: he is always surrounded by
minorities, even when he is in the whitest of suburbs. And he has
also belatedly made friends with the Log Cabin Republicans, a gay
pressure group.
</P>
<P>
   This might look like gesture politics. Gore's aides talk about
Bush going on a ``Bob Jones Redemption Tour.'' But the tour is
currently selling out most of the arenas.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush has been busy burnishing his ideology as well as his
image.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not only marched happily into Democratic territory such
as schools, housing and, in the next few weeks, family policy. He
has borrowed a clutch of bright ideas from Bill Clinton's favorite
think-tank, the Democratic Leadership Council, and endorsed
Medicare reforms suggested by one of the Democratic Party's
brightest luminaries, Louisiana's John Breaux.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to dismiss somebody as a right-wing nut if they spend
more time talking about education than anything else _ and if they
steal many of their best ideas from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Whittman, a political analyst at the Heritage
Foundation, a conservative think-tank, points out that this policy
offensive is also eroding Bush's second big negative: his
reputation as a lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will never entirely escape from his frat-boy image _ indeed
his very likeability may be one of his strongest weapons against
the cold Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But the flurry of policy initiatives is meant to suggest that
young George sometimes kept a copy of the latest Brookings policy
paper concealed inside his Playboy, and that he also knew who to
call when the homework assignment was due.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps not surprising that Bush has closed the gravitas
gap on issues such as education. But he has also notched up more
unexpected victories. One such is foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was a leading architect of the Clinton administration's
Russian policy. Bush, by contrast, was until recently best known
for referring to Greeks as ``Grecians'' and having trouble naming
the leaders of large countries. Yet Bush's team has been working
hard to close this gap. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 150 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 850) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, the China-trade bill, which the House of
Representatives passed last week, was something of a gift for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore, conscious of his union supporters, held back a
little in his support for permanent trading relations with China,
Bush, who comes from the free-trading, pro-immigration side of his
party, was more effusive about globalization.
</P>
<P>
   He also seized on the opportunities to appear both bipartisan
and statesmanlike _ praising Bill Clinton as well as the House
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Missile defense, by contrast, is one of Gore's specialities. Yet
on May 23, Bush put forward the case for substantially reducing
America's stockpile of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The speech was a little vague on details, but Bush surrounded
himself with some of the mightiest members of his party's
foreign-policy establishment _ Henry Kissinger, Brent Scowcroft,
General Colin Powell and George Shultz. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Excited talk about both Colin Powell and John McCain finding
their way into a Bush cabinet is also helping to close the gravitas
gap.
</P>
<P>
   Put all these things together and it is clear that over the past
two months Bush's team has done more than just downplay negatives.
They have begun to substantiate Bush's often-repeated claim to be a
``leader.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes leadership to suggest radical reform of the
Social-Security system, something that even a retiring politician
like Clinton is loth to do. Indeed, the Bushites have thoroughly
colonized a territory that Gore has bizarrely decided to leave
empty: that of intelligent social reformer.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Bush has begun to put more flesh on the bones of
``compassionate conservatism,'' positioning it as more cautious
than Gingrichism but more pro-market than his father's Country Club
Republicanism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 375 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 1,150) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   On education, he offers a mild form of school choice and teacher
accountability. (Pupils who are trapped in persistently dismal
schools will be given vouchers to leave.)
</P>
<P>
   On Social Security, he wants younger workers to be able to
invest a small portion of their payroll taxes on their own.
</P>
<P>
   On welfare, he supports a bigger role for voluntary
organizations, particularly those that try to change people's
character, not just tide them over from day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   All this has forced Gore onto the defensive. The vice president
seems forever to be objecting to ``risky schemes'' but never
advancing any interesting ideas of his own. (``If Al Gore would
have been around in Philadelphia when they were signing the
Declaration of Independence,'' Tom Ridge, the governor of
Pennsylvania and a possible Bush vice president has quipped, ``he
would have refused to sign it because it was a risky document.'')
</P>
<P>
   Gore seems increasingly allied with the most stick-in-the-mud
elements in the Democratic coalition _ the people who think that
New Deal liberalism is too perfect to need redesigning. And he is
alienating the brighter elements in his Party.
</P>
<P>
   New Democrats such as Bob Kerry, the senator for Nebraska, and
Will Marshall, the head of the Progressive Policy Institute, worry
that Gore's liberal fundamentalism will condemn their party to
defending entitlement programs (particularly for the old) that eat
up an ever-greater share of federal spending.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan has used the pages of the New
York Times to argue the case for retirement saving accounts. Brian
Lunde, a sometime executive director of the Democratic National
Committee, has even announced that he is supporting Bush.
</P>
<P>
   All this suggests that, if he is elected in November, Bush will
be able to form working links with the New Democratic Coalition _ a
group of 65 pro-business Democrats in Congress who regularly
champion high-tech issues and who broke with their party last week
to secure the passage of the trade deal with China.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, a Gore administration might squander one of the
greatest opportunities in modern politics: the chance to redesign
the welfare state at leisure, while the coffers are full, rather
than being forced to redesign it by a crisis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,600) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Polls can change. But the battle for ideas is usually a
slower-moving process. Whatever the result, one of the lasting
ironies of the 2000 campaign may prove to be that the
``lightweight'' Bush grabbed the intellectual edge from the
``heavyweight'' Gore.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any such thing as a ``vital center,'' it now belongs
to the Republicans rather than the Democrats. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
