<HEADER>
A5073 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     06-05 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBLEM IS, `M.Y.O.B.' DOESN'T MIND ITS OWN BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``M.Y.O.B'' spends so much time talking about other television
shows that it seems to have forgotten it has its own characters to
contend with. And that's just one of the problems to doom an
otherwise promising premise that places adoption and the search for
identity at the heart of its comedic possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Riley Veatch (Katharine Towne) is a 16-year-old whose search for
her birth mother has landed her on the doorstep of her aunt, a
conservative, uptight high school principal (Lauren Graham).
</P>
<P>
   But locating her biological mother quickly takes a back seat to
Riley's limitless supply of snappy comebacks, pop culture
references and verbal assaults, all of which are designed to make
her seem hip, cool and edgy for bucking authority, yet merely make
her seem like a bitter, unhappy malcontent.
</P>
<P>
   It's actually unclear whether Aunt Opal's sister is the birth
mother, particularly after Opal and Riley receive a fax from her
(she joined a cult and moved to Finland) that simply says, ``I've
never been pregnant. You're being had.''
</P>
<P>
   Opal, whose life is tied up in the school and a girlfriend who
phones her every evening, lets Riley stick around anyway, enrolling
her in school and slowly easing her into the small town's life,
which includes a nightly dose of ``Law &AMP; Order'' (must be the
reruns on A&AMP;E).
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship is cemented in Tuesday's premiere when Riley
uses her skills of manipulation (''lead with the breasts,'' is her
advice) to first get Opal the promotion she was in line for and, in
next week's episode, to save her from the horrible ordeal of firing
her one and only friend for romancing a student.
</P>
<P>
   ``M.Y.O.B,'' which means mind your own business, comes from Don
Roos (''The Opposite of Sex''), who uses the single-camera format
that gives Fox's ``Malcolm in the Middle'' its unsitcom look. But
that's about the extent of the positives coming out of the first
two episodes. The real issue is that even for a sitcom that wants
to derive some of its comedy from the drama of an adopted teen-ager
searching for her biological family, the humor is tired and the
drama that could fuel it is acknowledged only in passing.
</P>
<P>
   But most annoying is how ``M.Y.O.B'' is full of TV references,
with most of them being supplied by Riley's voiceover.
</P>
<P>
   On the town: ``I was hoping for `Melrose Place.' But it was more
like `Green Acres.'''
</P>
<P>
   On Opal's surprisingly short skirts: ``Look at those skirts. Who
dresses her _ Ally?''
</P>
<P>
   On gays: ``I don't have a problem with gays. I watch `Frasier'
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``M.Y.O.B'' even thinks it's being clever by allowing its star
to address her own show, describing it as ``the whole
fish-out-of-water, odd couple, unrequited-love combo platter you
get most every night on every channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, she's about right.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
