<SLUG> BC-THOMSON-PRIMARK-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMSON TO BUY PRIMARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (Stock quote in last graf does not reflect close)  
 By CAROLYN KOO   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Canadian publisher Thomson said Monday that it will buy Primark
(PMK:NYSE), a provider of financial, economic, and market research
information, for about $842 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes as Thomson, a traditional print publisher,
focuses more on providing information online and through CD-roms
and computer software.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, Toronto-based Thomson will pay
$38 for each share of Primark stock, a 31 percent premium over
Primark's closing price Friday. The transaction is expected to be
completed in the second half of the year. Thomson will also assume
$235 million in Primark debt.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Kasputys, chairman and chief executive of Primark, will
become the chairman of Thomson Financial, the company's financial
publishing arm.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Thomson recorded $5.8 billion in revenue and Thomson
Financial recorded $1.44 billion. The majority of the company's
revenue is derived from specialized legal, financial and medical
information, as well as textbooks. Thomson also has substantial
North American newspaper assets, which it plans to sell, though it
won't sell Toronto's The Globe and Mail.
</P>
<P>
   Primark, based in Waltham, Mass., posted $495 million. The
company offers information in print, online and other electronic
media.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday midday trading, shares of Primark neared Thomson's
offer price, soaring 29 percent, or 8 5/16, to 37 5/16, after
reaching a 52-week high of 37 1/2. Meanwhile, shares of Thomson
fell 60 Canadian cents, or 1 percent, to C$50.40 on the Toronto
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
