<HEADER>
A5087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-(TRIMS     06-05 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ASSURES RUSSIANS OF U.S. GOOD WILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON with ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In the first appearance by a Western leader before
Russia's parliament, President Clinton on Monday sought to assure
its deputies that the United States wants Russia to become a strong
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Russians still suspect that America does not wish you
well,'' Clinton said. ``The United States wants a strong Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   While he is only the second world leader to address the
parliament _ Alexander Lukashenko, the autocratic president of
Belarus, was the first _ Clinton received only a polite and muted
reception. Some deputies skipped the session, partly because they
were confused about when it was supposed to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a full hall,'' said Nikolai Kharitonov, the leader
of an agrarian faction that generally supports the Russian
president, Vladimir Putin. ``But it was not a bad speech. Let's
hope it is realized constructively.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Clinton's task was a difficult one. NATO expansion,
the Western alliance's war with Yugoslavia and, more recently, the
Clinton administration's plans to build a limited missile defense
have created the impression here that Washington revels in its role
as the world's only superpower and is determined to thwart the
emergence of new powers, including Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton struggled, with limited success, to put those suspicions
to rest. The parliament he addressed is no longer a
Communist-dominated legislature, reflexively opposed to U.S.
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   It is a varied and sometimes fractious body, which is broadly
supportive of Putin but that also includes tycoons, a small cluster
of reform-minded democrats and nationalists as well as a stubborn
left-wing opposition.
</P>
<P>
   It is also an institution that will vote on Putin's plans for
economic reform, regulatory issues of interest to U.S. business and
future arms control treaties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of the Red parliament, Clinton goes to the Duma that
is loyal to the Kremlin,'' the newspaper Sevodnya observed. ``But
like the previous parliament it is not that friendly to the U.S.
president.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   U.S. security agents and White House sound engineers prowled the
parliament building, part of which served as the old State Planning
Agency during Soviet times. Their presence produced resentment from
some of the deputies, who complained that the event was being
turned into a White House production.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Standing at the lectern, Clinton declared that ``Russia's future
is very important to others because it is among the most important
journeys the world will witness in my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   On security issues, Clinton insisted that his administration's
plan for limited missile defense was not a drive for military
superiority. And he underscored that he wanted to preserve the
principles of nuclear deterrence.
</P>
<P>
   On the economy, Clinton backed Russia's bid to join the World
Trade Organization, a bid that requires Moscow to change some of
its economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia should not be the only major industrialized country
standing outside this global trading system,'' Clinton said. ``We
will support you, but you must know the decision to join the WTO
requires difficult choices that only you can make.''
</P>
<P>
   On the political front, he criticized the prosecution of
Russia's war in Chechnya, insisting that he was speaking more in
sorrow than in anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``My question on Chechnya was an honest one, the question of a
friend,'' he said. ``And that is whether any war can be won that
requires large numbers of civilian casualties and has no political
component bringing about a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton then launched into a discussion about how he sought to
negotiate peace in Northern Ireland as a kind of model for Russian
efforts in the North Caucasus. More generally, however, Clinton
insisted that he had not come to Moscow to preach to the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have to overcome the temptation to think that we
have all the answers,'' Clinton said. ``You will choose what your
interests clearly demand and what your people democratically
embrace.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's approach impressed some Russian politicians, even
those who underscored that the U.S. president's term was coming to
an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a clever lecture,'' said Andrei Kokoshin, a deputy in
the Fatherland-All Russia party and a former national security
adviser to President Yeltsin. ``I think Clinton is still
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Boris Gryzlov, the leader of the Unity Party, which supports
Putin, objected to Clinton's discussion of Chechnya but said that
the Clinton administration's arms control position indicated that
it has listened to Moscow's concerns about the importance of the
anti-ballistic missile treaty signed by Russia and the United
States in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The communists and nationalists, the old masters of the
parliament, however, were sharply critical of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should not come here and tell us that Russia should be part
of Europe,'' said Alexander Kuvayev, one of the leading Communists
in the parliament. ``Russia can decide itself which way to go. And
what he said about Chechnya is none of his business.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The nationalist leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky created a row,
screaming ``Shame! Shame!'' as Clinton spoke. Zhirinovsky plays the
part of an ardent nationalist, but many Russians see him as a kind
of clown on the political fringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whom is he teaching how to live?'' Zhirinovsky yelled. ``It's
profane! We are not going to do what America commands!''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After visiting the parliament, Clinton received the warmer
welcome he was more accustomed to during his previous four trips to
Russia as president. He visited Boris Yeltsin, the former Russian
president, at his residence outside Moscow before boarding a plane
for Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Yeltsin had a sense of comradeship clearly lacking
in the president's business-like meetings with Putin. And Clinton
seemed to look back on the old meetings wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all just had a nice visit, just like old days,'' Clinton
said. ``He's got a beautiful place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
