<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5094 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-AFRICA-INVEST-ART-BOS     06-05 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-INVEST-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICA'S STRIFE COOLS INVESTORS' ARDOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Tom Boardman had a frustrating trip. As head of
an influential South African financial house, he had gone to
Britain and the United States in mid-May seeking investors. But
every meeting started the same way _ with concerns about
instability in Zimbabwe, where a land grab has marred an election
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appetite for buying into South Africa has been tempered by
Zimbabwe,'' said Boardman, chief executive of the Cape Town-based
Board of Executors, a banking and asset-management group. ``They
all asked the same question: What makes you think South Africa
won't go the same way?''
</P>
<P>
   Western pessimism about Africa is nothing new, but more and more
people across the continent find it hard to take. Sure, they
concede, Africa has serious troubles. But writing it off as
``hopeless,'' as one influential British magazine did recently, is
too much of a generalization.
</P>
<P>
   From Ghana to Botswana, politicians, intellectuals, and
corporate captains assert that their continent has passed into a
new era, where good governance and economics are gradually becoming
the norm.
</P>
<P>
   At the root of this ``African renaissance'' lies a fundamental
change in the way Africans see themselves _ less as helpless
recipients, more as capable partners. After a century of foreign
exploitation and homespun mischief, Africans are knocking at the
doors of richer nations with briefcases rather than beggars' bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most essential factor of an African renaissance is our
perception of ourselves in relation to the global community,'' said
Malegapuru Makgoba, a prominent South African academic. ``Before
you can drive human rights, before you can drive economic
development, you have to be conscious of who you are and what you
want to be. We are becoming conscious of our own dignity and
self-respect.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the year, Africans heralded what they
enthusiastically called ``the African century,'' the dawn of an era
in which Africa would emerge as a vibrant marketplace in the global
village, rather than its festering ghetto. Gone were colonialism,
the Cold War, apartheid, and dictatorial Zaire. For the first time,
democratic governments ruled South Africa and Nigeria, the
continent's two most important hubs, at the same time. Africa, it
seemed, captured the millennium's spirit of new beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   But things fell apart, again. The government of Zimbabwe,
challenged by a surging opposition movement after two decades of
uninterrupted rule, let loose ax-wielding thugs against its rivals.
Mobs invaded white-owned farms under the pretext of land reform,
but then turned the occupied lands into ``re-education camps,''
beating black farm workers into allegiance to the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   Floods devastated Mozambique. Rwanda and Uganda, two allies in
the multinational war in Congo, turned their guns on each other.
Famine struck arid Ethiopia, which then attacked its seaside
neighbor, Eritrea. And a ragtag rebel movement of boy-soldiers that
terrorized Sierra Leona a year ago by hacking the limbs off
children with machetes took 500 international peacekeepers hostage,
violating a peace accord that made its leader vice president of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The crises tapped a deep well of ink as the international media
cried for a hopeless continent. ``Brutality, despotism, and
corruption exist everywhere,'' the Economist magazine stated two
weeks ago, ``but African societies, for reasons buried in their
cultures, seem especially susceptible to them.''
</P>
<P>
   African intellectuals find such condemnations sweeping and
wrong, but not surprising. As late as 1987, Margaret Thatcher, then
prime minister of Britain, declared that ``anyone who thinks that
the ANC is going to run the government of South Africa is living in
Cloud Cuckooland.'' Just seven years later, African National
Congress leader Nelson Mandela was sworn in as state president.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, said Mandela's successor, Thabo Mbeki, who spent
the latter part of May urging political and business leaders in
Britain and the United States to help developing nations combat
poverty, is that Africa's Western critics fail to distinguish one
African country from another. No one has said, Mbeki noted during a
recent fireside chat with a few foreign journalists, that the
Balkan crises of the past decade proved all Europe was culturally
barbaric. Yet, Africa is repeatedly seen as one entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result of which, of course, is that when war erupts
between Eritrea and Ethiopia, it's Africa; when Foday Sankoh,'' the
rebel leader of Sierra Leone, ``and his people kidnap UN
peacekeepers, that's Africa; instability around Zimbabwe around the
land question, that's Africa,'' Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela signaled two years ago that Africans wanted a new set of
rules. Standing alongside President Clinton at a news conference in
Cape Town, he chided the West for questioning his choice of
friends. Libya's Moammar Khadafy and Syria's Hafez Assad may be
international pariahs, Mandela said, but they supported black
liberation struggles.
</P>
<P>
   That tone may sound arrogant, said Mandela's longtime friend,
Mac Maharaj, but it derives from the decades of struggle against
oppression, and it still applies as Africans demand a new place at
the world's table.
</P>
<P>
   As the country that epitomizes Africa's positive shift, South
Africa is the moral and intellectual midwife of the renaissance
ideal. But the call for renewal resonates across the continent.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a decade, Strive Masiyiwa, arguably Zimbabwe's most
successful businessman, has battled official corruption. As the
generation that fought against colonialism fades, he said, Africans
are rapidly shifting their view.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great challenges . . . revolves around this very
issue that, `Let's not wash our dirty linen in public.' That
mind-set has led to a lot of our greatest minds turning a blind eye
to a rising demagoguery in our society. That's what we have to
break. Comradeship must not be a refuge for lies and intellectual
dishonesty,'' Masiyiwa said.
</P>
<P>
   Makgoba said he sees a kind of second flowering of black
consciousness. In the 1970s, a dynamic young South African named
Stephen Biko argued that blacks needed to find their own self-worth
before they could find peace with their white oppressors. That same
ideal, Makgoba said, shapes Africa's emerging assertiveness. ``What
we are trying to say is, `Don't dictate to us.' That's an important
development,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologist Themba Sono said fellow Africans shouldn't get
carried away with a renaissance ideal, particularly when children
are forced into soldiering, people sold into slavery, and
governments brutalize their people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a new man, prove it,'' said Sono, of the University
of Pretoria. ``Our priority should be to correct what's wrong, to
see that the thugs are brought to book and find humanity for
African people.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, Mbeki said, is to build a more constructive
partnership between Africa and the West. Africa is rebuilding, he
said. South Africa is helping its neighbors to build aluminum
smelters and regional natural-gas pipelines. Nigeria has offered to
send election monitors to Zimbabwe. More and more leaders are
pressing their peers to adhere to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we looked at some detail at what is happening in Africa, it
is possible to isolate the bad things that are happening,'' Mbeki
said. ``What then do we do about Africa, not to deny the bad things
that are happening, but also not then to allow that those bad
things overshadow the very important work that is being done? I
would like us to have a look at this question.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
