<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KYLE-MACLACHLAN-IN-SEX-AND-THE-CITY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 KYLE MacLACHLAN: THE JOY OF `SEX AND THE CITY'  
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Kyle MacLachlan with Kristin Davis in a
scene from ``Sex and the City.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    It takes a tough guy to play a sexy hunk on HBO's ``Sex and the
City.''
 &HT;    The 41-year-old actor Kyle MacLachlan is spending every morning
lifting weights and running his buns off. He doesn't dare take even
a single day off, because he knows the stakes are high.
 &HT;    ``In a few days, I shoot my first love scene,'' MacLachlan says
by telephone from his New York apartment, still breathing hard from
an early-morning workout. ``I don't want there to be any love
handles or flab on my body.''
 &HT;    Image matters. Just ask Chris Noth, who plays Mr. Big, the
object of Sarah Jessica Parker's affections on the hit series.
 &HT;    ``My heart goes out to Kyle,'' Noth says. ``You truly do feel
like one of the girls before those love scenes. You look in the
mirror and think, `Gosh, my butt does look a little big.'''
 &HT;    MacLachlan admits to jitters as he approaches his ``Sex and the
City'' debut.
 &HT;    ``What if one of the women on the show says, `Kyle, did you have
to eat garlic for lunch?''' MacLachlan says. ``I can imagine doing
a bedroom scene on the show and Kristin Davis turning to me and
saying, `Um, buddy, have you ever heard of Altoid mints?'''
 &HT;    MacLachlan is the new guy in the big city this year, joining the
story of four single women living and loving in Manhattan. He plays
a surgeon who gets involved with the uptight, sexually naive art
dealer Charlotte, played by Davis.
 &HT;    ``We meet in a dramatic fashion on the street,'' MacLachlan
says, breaking a key ``Sex and the City'' rule: Don't talk about
upcoming plots. ``Her character almost gets hit by a cab, and I
come to her rescue.
 &HT;    ``It's a very Prince Charming moment,'' he says. ``In fact, the
rest of the girlfriends come in and immediately give me the
thumbs-up.''
 &HT;    But on this series, happiness in relationships is always
short-lived.
 &HT;    ``Just when everything seems perfect, they are going to throw in
some serious monkey wrenches,'' MacLachlan says. ``I can't tell you
what, because they write the scripts as we go. I am just told what
I need to know.''
 &HT;    You can count on seeing plenty of love scenes, however, which
doesn't faze the actor, who has appeared in such risque feature
films as ``Blue Velvet'' (1986) and ``Showgirls'' (1995).
 &HT;    ``You know, love scenes are weird to do, because you don't
really know the other person well,'' he says. ``It's actually so
difficult to act scenes of intimacy. It's almost like a one-night
stand, but filmed. You're just jumping into bed with a stranger.
 &HT;    ``The good thing is that people in this business are usually
pretty cool,'' he adds. ``Everyone is in the same boat. Everyone is
nervous.''
 &HT;    MacLachlan has been in that business for nearly two decades,
starring in films from ``Dune'' (1984) to ``One Night Stand''
(1997). He is best known, however, as FBI Special Agent Dale Cooper
in David Lynch's television series ``Twin Peaks'' (1990-1991),
which is now enjoying a successful second run on the Bravo and FX
cable networks.
 &HT;    To this day, MacLachlan gravitates to the weird and the
unpredictable. His most recent film was Mike Figgis' ``Time Code''
(2000), in an improvised role.
 &HT;    ``It was a whole different kind of challenge,'' the actor
recalls. ``I basically improvised for 90 minutes and he filmed it.
I really enjoyed the process.''
 &HT;    The just-wrapped ``Perfume,'' a movie set in the fashion world,
offered a similar challenge.
 &HT;    ``It was all improvisation again,'' MacLachlan says. ``I worked
with Paul Sorvino _ we're fashion designers. Jeff Goldblum is also
involved in our scenes. Basically, I did the movie as a favor. It's
four short stories blended into one tale. It was shot on a low
budget.''
 &HT;    Also shot on a shoestring budget is the new film ``Hamlet,'' an
updated version of the Shakespeare classic that's set in modern-day
New York. MacLachlan plays the evil Claudius, opposite Ethan Hawke
as Hamlet and Bill Murray as Polonius.
 &HT;    ``I was thrilled to get the role, because I had never done
`Hamlet,''' MacLachlan says. ``Initially I thought that someone
called me for the wrong role _ Claudius traditionally is played by
an older actor. But the idea this time was to make him younger and
more of a threat to the Ethan Hawke Hamlet character.''
 &HT;    MacLachlan plays Claudius as a young CEO who has Hamlet's mother
on his expensively suited arm.
 &HT;    ``He's very evil, but with this cool detachment,'' he says. ``My
Claudius also has this look in his eyes that screams he will stab
you in the back at a moment's notice. But he's more than just the
bad guy _ he's tormented about what he has done.
 &HT;    ``He isn't a man but an image,'' the actor adds, ``which leaves
him feeling completely empty. Even though he seems at ease, I saw
him as a man who is not secure in his skin when you peel the layers
away.''
 &HT;    A long career of steady work, if never A-list stardom, has left
MacLachlan financially secure enough to choose his projects as he
sees fit.
 &HT;    ``It's never been about money for me,'' he says, ``so I can
happily say that this one was pretty low. The entire movie cost
less than a million dollars. But I think it's just so creative.
 &HT;    ``We filmed in New York and took advantage of what the city has
to offer,'' the actor says. ``It was so rich and risky _ most of
the scenes you see of me walking outside in a crowd were the result
of running outside and catching the moment.''
 &HT;    MacLachlan grew up in Yakima, Wash., as the eldest of three
brothers. He found acting as a student at the University of
Washington in Seattle, then hit the pavement in both New York and
Los Angeles, where early rejection nearly made him quit the
business.
 &HT;    ``I remember being turned down for the Charlie Sheen role in
`Platoon' (1986), and it was quite devastating,'' MacLachlan says.
 &HT;    It was director David Lynch who finally gave him his ticket to
success, first casting him in ``Dune'' and following that with
``Blue Velvet,'' which made the actor a star.
 &HT;    It was also Lynch who made MacLachlan into an offbeat sex symbol
by casting him as Special Agent Cooper in ``Twin Peaks.''
 &HT;    ``All of a sudden, people began staring at me in the street with
this quizzical look on their faces,'' MacLachlan says. ``What's
great is that a whole new generation of people are now discovering
`Twin Peaks.' We did the series a little over 10 years ago, but it
seems to still intrigue people.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, he denies persistent rumors of a new ``Twin Peaks''
movie.
 &HT;    ``From what I understand,'' he says, ``any thoughts of reviving
the project are impractical. There were so many people involved,
who own a portion of `Twin Peaks,' and to make them all agree on
something is impossible.
 &HT;    ``It's pretty much done forever.''
 &HT;    But the memories live on. Remember, Special Agent Cooper loved
``cherry pie and a damn fine cup of coffee.''
 &HT;    ``I'm still identified with that catch phrase,'' MacLachlan
says, laughing. ``It's funny, because when I go into a diner I
always get sent a complimentary piece of pie and a big cup of java.
 &HT;    ``I love the coffee _ but, to tell you the truth, I never liked
cherry pie!''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
