<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TIRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD TIRE FACTORY STOKES A NEW ENGINE IN RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   YAROSLAVL, Russia _ This could be what hell looks like.
</P>
<P>
   Gaunt, sweating men heft massive metal and rubber objects onto
huge metal hooks, while others struggle with steaming, hissing
machines in 120-degree heat. The roar of machinery drowns out all
other noise; the infernal green steam blots out all sight.
</P>
<P>
   These are the first impressions created by a visit to the old
production line at the Yaroslavl Tire Factory, where they still
make tires the way they did when the place was built in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   But first impressions in Russia are often misleading. This is
not hell. Nor is it another example of Russia's descent into
post-Soviet industrial blight.
</P>
<P>
   If the long lines of job-seekers that form outside Yaroslavl
Tire are any indication, this is one of the most desirable
workplaces in this city of 600,000 on the Volga River, 120 miles
northeast of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Yaroslavl Tire, which employs 8,000 workers, is also a prime
example of how Russia's crumbling, old smokestack industries,
neglected under years of socialist stagnation and post-Soviet
blight, could be on the verge of revival.
</P>
<P>
   A chat with the company's youthful general director, Nikolai
Tonkov, provides an intriguing look at the mixture that makes for
success in Russia's still-developing market economy. Agile
management, new ideas, and good timing are no doubt important. But
it helps quite a bit to have the financial backing of one of
Russia's oligarchic superconglomerates, in Yaroslavl Tire's case
the natural gas monopoly Gazprom. And the support of political
heavyweights is absolutely necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a good relationship with the authorities, you can
work,'' said Tonkov, who enjoys close ties with Yaroslavl's
Governor Anatoly Lisitsyn, and who served as a representative in
Yaroslavl for the recent election campaign of President Vladimir V.
Putin. ``I'll always try to be with the party that runs the
country. I'll never be in the opposition, because I realize that is
useless in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonkov, 33, received a reporter in Yaroslavl Tire's tastefully
remodeled front offices, which provide a first impression more in
line with the company's recent successes.
</P>
<P>
   A former tire salesman who had expanded his retail network to
100 stores across Russia before taking the top job at Yaroslavl
Tire two years ago, Tonkov has doubled company sales to $12 million
to $14 million per month. Workers, who used to receive their pay
several months late, and in tires that they had to resell, now get
paid on time and in cash. In a country where many companies have
been threatened with layoffs, Tonkov is expanding his operation.
</P>
<P>
   Under Tonkov's leadership, Yaroslavl Tire has changed its
mentality from a Soviet-style behemoth that mass-produced huge
amounts of unwanted tires to a smart player that is aiming for
Russia's growing market of motorists driving imported cars and
trucks. Gradually, the factory has begun replacing the 1930s-era
technology with new, automated machinery that pumps out the
steel-belted radials consumers want with a fraction of the labor
needed to produce the older lines.
</P>
<P>
   This leap into modernity has brought new challenges. Convincing
workers to embrace the new technology has not been easy. Stanislav
Pismarev, during a tour of the old production line, the roof of
which is still scarred by Nazi bombs from World War II, said
workers prefer the more familiar 1932 line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to teach people new skills,'' Tonkov said. ``The old
habits die hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge has been financing new equipment. No Russian
factory produces the latest machinery, so the company had to look
for expensive alternatives abroad. To afford them in an economic
environment where there is little interest in long-term investment,
Yaroslavl Tire had to tighten spending and cut corners on the heavy
tax burden placed on Russian enterprises, which Tonkov said totals
87 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This is one area where the relationship with Lisitsyn, the
governor, comes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to help with taxes,'' Lisitsyn said in an interview. He
said large employers like Yaroslavl Tire do not pay rent for their
premises. Lisitsyn caused a small uproar recently when he reduced
local taxes for manufacturers, then made up for the money by
introducing a trade tax paid by consumers. This is technically
illegal _ governors do not have the right in Russia to introduce
taxes _ but Lisitsyn defends his moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still forming the market in Russia, and we have to
protect our own producers,'' he said. ``Some day there will be
equal rules for everyone and governors here will have a reduced
role, like governors in the United States, but for now Russia has
89 regions with 89 different economies . . . we have to lobby the
interests of our manufacturers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisitsyn's lobbying has brought Yaroslavl Tire and another
rubber-products factory Tonkov recently acquired purchase orders
from government agencies for such equipment as tents for refugees,
medical supplies, and components for naval and military equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Russian governors like Lisitsyn will be able to retain
such powers is one of the questions raised by Putin's recent
attempts to tighten federal control over the regions.
</P>
<P>
   The political pact with Lisitsyn also came in handy last year,
when Yaroslavl Tire was up for sale. Tonkov was able to fend off
buyers who were hostile to the idea of him staying on as general
director, and with the governor acting as an intermediary, was able
to come to an agreement with Siburo, the Gazprom subsidiary that
eventually bought the factory.
</P>
<P>
   Close relationships between businessmen and politicians are
nothing new in Russia. But generally these ties have been exploited
in ways that benefit individual bureaucrats and factory managers,
not the public. A group of directors earned personal fortunes by
privatizing factories at ridiculously low prices, often through the
banks run by politically connected insiders. Then the best assets
were gradually siphoned away to offshore accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Tonkov says he tries to explain to American businessmen _ and
potential investors _ that ``in Russia, there is not only
corruption, but also the development of competitive business.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no easy task, and Tonkov knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows that there are directors who can't earn profits
by manufacturing, so instead they incur millions of dollars of
losses while making a fortune in bribes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dishonesty at the workplace had a trickle-down effect in Soviet
factories that has been hard to overcome. One of Tonkov's reforms
was to hire a 700-member security detail for the industrial complex
to help crack down on rampant theft that had been crippling the
factory. (``We catch all the thieves,'' Tonkov said.)
</P>
<P>
   Tonkov is not hoping to make Yaroslavl Tire the next Michelin
anytime soon. A more realistic target is Matador, a Slovak tire
manufacturer that has made inroads in European markets after
overcoming decades of industrial stagnation.
</P>
<P>
   Even that seemed an ambitious goal two years ago, when Tonkov
was invited by Yaroslavl Tire's owners to take on the job of
commercial director, with the understanding that he would
eventually take over as general director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that the whole place was a mess,'' he said. ``They were
making one size of tire, no one bought them, no one knew how to buy
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonkov replaced the old management with people from his tire
sales company, VVSh, and began restructuring Yaroslavl Tire.
</P>
<P>
   He was inadvertently helped by the August 1998 crash of the
Russian currency, the ruble, which actually helped Yaroslavl Tire
by temporarily making imports far too expensive for Russians to
buy. Tonkov's response included using a new, patriotic-sounding
slogan, ``Russian Tires for Russian Roads.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the Russian economy is stuck in the 1970s,'' he said.
``I hope the president looks at the successful companies, the ones
that have changed, and says, that's the way we should do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
