<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5102 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-THE-YEAR-IN-TELEVISIO     06-05 1574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-YEAR-IN-TELEVISION-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM MADNESS: THE GOOD, THE BAD AND THE UGLY OF TELEVISION
1999/2000 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Frankie Muniz, Erik Per Sullivan, Jane
Kaczmarek, Christopher Kennedy Masterson, Bryan Cranston and Justin
Berfield in a scene from ``Malcolm in the Middle.'') 
 By the staff of TV GUIDE CANADA  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before June 19. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Who could have predicted the just-completed television season?
 &HT;    If you'd told any television critic last summer that the year's
biggest hit would be a prime-time game show _ hosted by the
unctuous Regis Philbin, no less _ they'd have laughed in your face.
 &HT;    And things were just as strange further down the ratings ladder.
Here's a look back at some of the highlights and lowlights. 
 -0- 
 THE GOOD  
 &HT;    + ``The West Wing.''
 &HT;    NBC's weekly Oval Office drama is perhaps the best-written
ensemble drama ever to have graced network television, courtesy of
creators Aaron Sorkin and John Wells.
 &HT;    Of course, it helped tremendously to have an A-list cast, headed
by Martin Sheen as the definitive television president and backed
by the likes of Rob Lowe, John Spencer and Alison Janney.
 &HT;    It's rare that a television show measures up to its prelaunch
hype, but ``The West Wing'' was even better than we expected.
 &HT;    + ``Popular.''
 &HT;    After an inauspicious beginning as yet another zits-'n'-cliques
teen drama, WB's ``Popular'' somehow morphed into the quirkiest,
best-written teen show on television.
 &HT;    Delta Burke as multibillionaire mom Cherry Cherry, a slew of
wacky guest stars from 1980s television and consistently knowing
scripts ensure that adult viewers are more than entertained.
 &HT;    ``After School Specials'' were never this cool. Or this crazed.
 &HT;    + ``Futurama.''
 &HT;    With ``The Simpsons'' stuck in a creative rut _ how many times
can we see Homer fail while the more interesting Springfield
secondary characters cry out for story lines? _ viewers are finding
solace in Fox's ``Futurama.''
 &HT;    Like ``The Simpsons,'' ``Futurama'' was immediately subversive
in its cast: The star of the series, Frye (voice of Billy Fox), is
a certified slacker whose best pal is Bender, a drunken,
malfunctioning robot. Big points for originality.
 &HT;    + ``Sex and the City.''
 &HT;    The second season of HBO's ``Sex and the City'' actually
improved on the first, as it matured into a well-rounded ensemble
dramedy, with the relationships between the girls and their men
providing some substance for the weekly sexfest.
 &HT;    Carrie's torturous relationship with Mr. Big and Miranda's
touching affair with the sweet-but-unsuitable Steve tugged at
heartstrings, even while our funnybones were being lasciviously
stroked.
 &HT;    + ``Malcolm in the Middle.''
 &HT;    A family sitcom about an average family without a last name _
just two oddball parents and four misbehaving sons.
 &HT;    It doesn't sound like much on paper, but on screen Fox's
``Malcolm in the Middle'' blossomed into an affectionately wry and
genuinely hilarious sitcom, winning huge ratings along the way.
 &HT;    Creator Linwood Boomer's nostalgia for his own early life shines
through in the show's trademark mix of delirious desperation and
the joys of a sweetly dysfunctional home.
 &HT;    + David Letterman's bypass.
 &HT;    Who'd have thought that a health scare could turn a crotchety
old talk-show host, one whom many thought had had his day, into a
national darling?
 &HT;    Indeed, that Letterman even had a heart was startling to some.
 &HT;    His return to his CBS desk after five weeks away broke ratings
records for ``The Late Show,'' and permitted him to beat Jay Leno's
``Tonight Show'' for the first time in years.
 &HT;    + ``Who Wants To Be A Millionaire.''
 &HT;    What's wrong with this picture: A slow-paced game show, hosted
by Kathie Lee's smarmy sidekick, beating ``ER'' in the ratings?
 &HT;    It's a mystery. Yet ABC's ``Millionaire'' has turned into a
ratings juggernaut that leaves all other programs foundering in its
wake.
 &HT;    The celebrity series was an improvement on the show's usually
glacial pace _ especially Tea Leoni's answer to husband David
Duchovny's phone-a-friend question. When the question stumped her,
she told him, ``Oh, honey, you're so screwed!''
 &HT;    + ``Freaks &AMP; Geeks.''
 &HT;    NBC's ``Freaks &AMP; Geeks'' is proof that being both a critics'
darling and a grassroots cult hit can't save a well-written show
from an early death.
 &HT;    So, like ``My So-Called Life'' before it, ``Freaks &AMP; Geeks''
bloomed only for a single season, and will live most fondly in the
memories of those who loved it.
 &HT;    Also like ``My So-Called Life,'' look for ``Freaks &AMP; Geeks'' to
be the springboard for some major talent, most notably Linda
Cardellini.
 &HT;    + Nurse Hathaway's departure on ``ER.''
 &HT;    When George Clooney turned up on ``ER'' to settle Carol
Hathaway's doubting heart, it took many fans by surprise. Where was
the big network ballyhoo over Clooney's return?
 &HT;    Clooney did the role for $596 _ as well as for the fans and for
the legacy of his character. The beautiful, sweet cameo tied up a
favorite story line perfectly, without any unnecessary hype.
 &HT;    The fact that Julianna Margulies, who played Nurse Hathaway,
turned down an astounding $27 million offer from NBC to stick with
the show somehow made the farewell even fonder. 
 -0- 
 THE BAD  
 &HT;    + ``God, The Devil &AMP; Bob.''
 &HT;    The animated ``God, The Devil &AMP; Bob'' never even sounded like a
good idea.
 &HT;    The protests from conservative religious groups were also
predictable, but for once the controversy failed to translate into
high ratings.
 &HT;    Then came the lawsuit from Jerry Garcia's estate, alleging that
the God character resembled the dead Head Deadhead, and NBC finally
banished the show to the television afterworld.
 &HT;    + ``The Tenth Kingdom.''
 &HT;    Besides being a waste of videotape and viewers' time, ``The
Tenth Kingdom'' was an interminable, bad-effects-strewn fairy tale.
 &HT;    Offbeat casting _ Camryn Mannheim as Snow White? _ and a
promising premise were not enough to turn NBC's poisoned apple into
a glass slipper.
 &HT;    + Post-haircut ``Felicity.''
 &HT;    Never before have the creators and producers of a show dared to
blame a ratings slide on their star's haircut. But when
``Felicity'' star Keri Russell's long, curly locks fell to the
floor, the WB show's ratings followed suit.
 &HT;    Rather than a season of continuous ``Ben or Noel?'' dilemmas and
uninspired writing, Felicity's follicular folly was named as the
culprit.
 &HT;    Guys, if that's the case, may we suggest a wig?
 &HT;    + ``Dawson's Creek,'' post-Kevin Williamson.
 &HT;    After a whip-smart two seasons under the watchful eye of
pop-culture auteur Kevin ``Scream'' Williamson, WB's ``Dawson's
Creek'' fell victim to Williamson's expanding empire when he left
to work on the mercifully brief run of ``Wasteland.''
 &HT;    Without Williamson, our favorite tortured-teen foursome found
themselves up the ``Creek'' without a paddle, as story lines veered
from dull to flat-out stupid.
 &HT;    A late-season reinvigoration suggests that the ``Creek'' may not
yet have run dry. 
 -0- 
 THE UGLY  
 &HT;    + ``Who Wants to Marry A Multimillionaire.''
 &HT;    When Fox was denied permission to stage a disaster special _
they wanted to crash an empty passenger plane into the desert _
they retaliated by staging a disaster of another kind: ``Who Wants
To Marry A Multimillionaire.''
 &HT;    In it, an allegedly wealthy bachelor (Rick Rockwell) was
actually wed to a nurse, Darva Conger, on live television _ a
concept that somehow managed simultaneously to degrade the
contestants, the audience and the institution of marriage.
 &HT;    Note to the newlyweds: After an annulment, you're supposed to
disappear. Instead Rockwell is trying to use the hype to revive his
standup-comedy career, while Conger is appearing nude in Playboy.
 &HT;    + JonBenet Ramsey TV movies.
 &HT;    As if it weren't horrible enough to live through the media
circus surrounding the grisly murder of JonBenet Ramsey, both Fox
and CBS felt that it was necessary to bring the still-unsolved
murder to the screen.
 &HT;    Neither adaptation offered any enlightenment, since the truth is
not yet known, and neither showed a shred of respect for the little
girl whose life and murder they sensationalized.
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
