<SLUG> BC-HEATHER-DONAHUE-IN-BOYS-AND-GIRLS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE WAKE OF THE BLAIR WITCH, HEATHER DONAHUE GOES FOR LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Heather Donahue in a scene from ``Boys
and Girls.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    ``The Blair Witch Project'' scared audiences silly last summer,
but the hit horror film's success proved even more terrifying for
Heather Donahue.
 &HT;    Donahue starred as Heather, one of three documentarians stalked
by strange forces in the eerie Maryland woods. The unheralded film
took off, and the actress was catapulted from unknown to overnight
sensation.
 &HT;    ``It sort of opened my eyes and made me reconsider what I really
wanted,'' Donahue says. ``All of a sudden I was in the public eye,
and that was frightening to me.
 &HT;    ``It didn't have anything to do with the work aspect of what I
do, which is what I love,'' she hastens to add. ``I was dealing
with this whole other full-time job that was just not what I had in
mind.''
 &HT;    After the fact, and in the midst of the ``Blair Witch'' hoopla,
Donahue looked hard in the mirror, picked the brains of family and
friends, and conferred with her agents. After having spent her
career perfectly happy performing in regional stage productions and
independent features, she wanted to take control of her suddenly
blossoming options.
 &HT;    ``I want to work on stuff I like,'' the refreshingly
straightforward actress says by telephone from the Los Angeles home
she shares with her longtime boyfriend, writer/photographer Gregor
Hrynisdak. ``I don't want to limit myself because something's not a
big-budget production, and I don't want to do something crappy
because it will make a lot of money. I don't want that to become my
criteria for choosing a project.
 &HT;    ``It's all very complicated,'' Donahue says. ``It was good for
me to remember what my values were and what my goals were, and then
to see how they could fit into the bigger picture that my agents
helped me to see.
 &HT;    ``I'm still figuring it out,'' she admits. ``Everybody has his
or her own path, and sometimes that's not always immediately clear.
I think if you stay true to yourself you have a better chance of
staying on the correct path that will be satisfying to you in the
long run.''
 &HT;    Donahue's post-``Blair Witch'' path is a perfect example of her
attempt to hang onto her past while looking to her future. Making
two films simultaneously, she accepted a supporting role in the
high-profile feature ``Boys and Girls,'' which will open nationwide
on June 16, while co-starring in the indie feature ``Seven and a
Match,'' which is currently seeking a distributor.
 &HT;    ``My character in `Boys and Girls' is a slightly off-kilter
woman who's a combination of Betty Crocker and an electrical
engineer,'' Donahue says. ``She's completely obsessed with Ryan,
who is Freddie Prinze Jr.'s character.
 &HT;    ``She's quite awkward, but very confident in her awkwardness,''
Donahue adds. ``Megan ultimately snags Ryan when his friend
Jennifer, Claire Forlani's character, puts him up to it. And our
relationship continues until the big surprise.''
 &HT;    ``Boys and Girls'' is only one of several recent hormone-driven,
high-school- or college-based romantic comedies, however, and
Donahue is hard-pressed to say what will distinguish it from
``She's All That'' (1999), ``Down to You'' (2000) and ``Road Trip''
(2000). Asked to do so, the actress turns silent, then dissolves
into laughter, and finally stammers.
 &HT;    ``What will set it apart?'' she asks. ``OK, hang on. Give me a
second. Aaaaah. Hmmm. Well. It's got a great supporting cast. It's
a lot of fun. It's about how you can't hide from your own fate, as
much as you try.
 &HT;    ``How's that? Not bad under pressure.''
 &HT;    Donahue's role in the film may be a glorified cameo, but she
relished the experience, both for the chance to play a lighter role
and for the perks that come with big-budget filmmaking.
 &HT;    ``It was such a great opportunity to do something that had
nothing in common with `The Blair Witch Project' or my `Blair
Witch' character,'' she says. ``It was cute and light and fun, and
we shot it in San Francisco. And there's nothing like San Francisco
with a per-diem.
 &HT;    ``For everybody else on the set it was sort of a low-budget
studio movie,'' she adds, ``but for me it was big-time. At lunch
there were four different salads to choose from on the
craft-service table. I was like, `All right. This I can do.'
 &HT;    ``In my journal it is actually written in capital letters and
underlined: `I HAVE A TRAILER!''' the actress says, laughing. ``It
was so nice to have my own space, to have a VCR and a radio and my
own bathroom. I especially felt that way because I was going back
and forth between San Francisco and Fishers Island, off the coast
of Connecticut, where I was shooting `Seven and a Match,' which was
a low-budget, indie film where we were doubling up in dressing
rooms.''
 &HT;    Whit, Donahue's character in ``Seven and a Match,'' represents
another departure. She's a wunderkind at W, a top-drawer fashion
magazine for women.
 &HT;    ``Whit is short for Whitney, and she's a character removed from
me in so many ways,'' Donahue says happily. ``She's incredibly
stylish and witty and quick and sort of closed off. She's sexual,
but chilly at the same time.
 &HT;    ``The movie is basically an ensemble `dramedy,' as it were,
about friends from college,'' the actress says. ``They meet up a
few years after graduation, and try to find their place with each
other again.''
 &HT;    Donahue's current good fortune is a direct result of ``The Blair
Witch Project,'' which she ``never in a million years'' expected to
take off. She appreciates everything the film has done for her
career, but can't deny a lingering frustration at the fact that she
and her two co-stars received no share of the film's box-office
windfall.
 &HT;    ``It's never beneficial to look back,'' the actress says as the
conversation draws to a close. ``I think any financial issue that
has to do with `Blair Witch' is also something that, like
everything else, required adaptation and an understanding of the
business.
 &HT;    ``I obviously have a better understanding of the business now
than when I was just an eager little beaver,'' Donahue says.
``There are lessons to be learned from everything. And I learned a
lot of very valuable, important lessons _ artistically and
business-wise _ from being a part of `Blair Witch.'''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
