<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5105 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-SAMANTHA-MORTON-IN-JE     06-05 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAMANTHA-MORTON-IN-JESUS-SON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE OSCARS, SAMANTHA MORTON RETURNS TO THE DARK SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Samantha Morton with Billy Crudup in a
scene from ``Jesus' Son.'') 
 By SHEP MORGAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    She may be British, but Samantha Morton didn't have any trouble
coming up with an American accent for Woody Allen's Jazz Age
comedy, ``Sweet and Lowdown'' (1999).
 &HT;    She didn't need one _ her character was mute. But her
performance was compelling enough to earn an Academy Award
nomination as Best Supporting Actress.
 &HT;    Now she needs that accent, however, for her latest role, as a
heroin addict in ``Jesus' Son,'' based on Denis Johnson's cult
collection of drug-culture short stories. The powerful, often
darkly comic drama is set in 1970s middle America, and Morton
admits to having fretted over how she'd sound in the role.
 &HT;    ``When I auditioned, I think my accent was terrible,'' Morton
says with a laugh, ``but I believed I could make it work. I went
through some intensive dialect training with the same voice coach
who worked with Kenneth Branagh on `Celebrity' (1998), but I
couldn't bring myself to try to sound American off the set.
 &HT;    ``I got into a taxi in New York and started speaking with my
Yank accent,'' she recalls, ``and I felt like a total fraud. I
realized I had to be hiding behind a character, and then I could go
to town with it.''
 &HT;    In ``Jesus' Son,'' Morton plays Michelle, a junkie drawn into a
self-destructive love affair with a wayward druggie (Billy Crudup).
There are several scenes in which her character mainlines heroin.
 &HT;    ``They hired an ex-drug addict to work with me,'' she says,
``but at the beginning I was the most pathetic drug user
imaginable. I would sit in my hotel room every night, practicing
with all the paraphernalia and hoping I wouldn't drop something.
When I got on the set, I just crossed my fingers and went for it.
 &HT;    ``When it came to simulating a heroin high, I didn't do much
research,'' she adds. ``Denis Johnson has the most amazing
descriptions of what it's like in his book. You read those and it
doesn't take much imagination to understand why Lou Reed, in his
song `Heroin,' has the lyric `I feel just like Jesus' son.'
 &HT;    ``That's what was in my mind when I was doing the drug scenes.''
 &HT;    The result is a wrenching portrait of the druggie subculture,
directed by New Zealander Alison Maclean _ best known for ``Crush''
(1993) _ with echoes of Gus Van Sant's ``Drugstore Cowboy'' (1989)
and ``My Own Private Idaho'' (1991).
 &HT;    ``Actually, I think it's more character-driven than either of
those films,'' Morton says. ``It may have some of the same
bleakness, but we certainly didn't have Gus on our minds when we
did `Jesus' Son.'''
 &HT;    Michelle's world is a couple of decades and a continent away
from Morton's own teen years in working-class England, but the
22-year-old actress says that nonetheless she identified with her
character.
 &HT;    ``It was the '70s and she was in the middle of nowhere,'' Morton
says. ``What sort of freedom do you have, and what kind of life do
you have to look forward to? It must have been incredibly
frustrating, and she was searching for something more. In that kind
of situation, drugs become a release.
 &HT;    ``But Michelle also sees the danger in it, and she finally makes
a clear decision to try to stop.
 &HT;    ``I think I was the only actress that auditioned who really
understood Michelle,'' she continues reflectively. ``I was the only
person who really knew her _ I can't tell you why.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes that happens to me,'' she says. ``I'm a girl, but
when I read `Catcher in the Rye' I totally understood Holden
Caulfield, and I could play him. Michelle was clear to me in the
same way.''
 &HT;    Though she has played her share of period roles _ most notably
in two television movies, in the title role of the BBC's ``Jane
Eyre'' (1997) and as Harriet Smith in ``Emma'' (1997) _ Morton has
done her best work in darker contemporary stories. She first caught
the public eye as a teen-age prostitute in the television
miniseries ``Band of Gold'' (1995), and made her American debut as
Iris, a girl who immerses herself in promiscuous sex as a defense
against loneliness and loss, in ``Under the Skin'' (1998).
 &HT;    ``I do seem more comfortable with tormented characters who go to
dark places,'' she says. ``I find it much harder to do happy
things. Maybe that's why people seem to remember the roles I've
played as women who weren't exactly ordinary _ but they're not me.
 &HT;    ``You can't put too much of your own life in a role or it
becomes therapy,'' she says. ``You'd be going crazy every time you
made a film. I leave those characters behind on the set. There's no
point in acting all the time _ I love my job, but I have to be
careful that I don't take it home. You could drive your family and
friends mad.''
 &HT;    Offscreen, in fact, Morton is in particularly good spirits
lately. She recently had a baby daughter _ the father is British
actor Charles Creed-Miles _ and seems delighted by motherhood.
 &HT;    ``It's wonderful to think of yourself as just a mother,'' she
says. ``I quite like it.
 &HT;    ``Actually, I've already felt that being a mom might influence
my choice of roles,'' she adds. ``I got a script the other day that
was pure trash, and I thought of my daughter when I turned it down.
Obviously, I want her to be proud of me, to look at my work when
she grows up and know I did it for the right reasons.
 &HT;    ``I dread the thought of playing another character like Iris or
Michelle,'' she admits. ``It's so daunting. I don't know whether
I'm ready for it again, at least not yet.''
 &HT;    Morton reports that, so far, her Oscar nod hasn't led to
anything approaching Hollywood stardom.
 &HT;    ``But I'm not driven by that,'' she adds. ``I'd rather be known
for my roles than what I wore to a premiere. I'd hate to be
remembered for the dress I had on. Right now, I can get on a bus
and come home from town without even being recognized _ I would
never like to have that taken from me.''
 &HT;    Her lifestyle isn't very compatible with the Hollywood party
circuit, anyway.
 &HT;    ``I like going walking,'' she says. ``I like the sunshine, which
we haven't had much of in Britain lately. I have a lovely garden,
and I like to sit and listen to the breeze play my wind chimes.
 &HT;    ``I just like the peaceful life.''
 &HT;    All in all, she concludes, she's happy with her career as it is.
 &HT;    ``I was watching the telly tonight,'' she recalls, ``and `Scent
of a Woman' (1992) was on. There was a scene where Philip Seymour
Hoffman is waddling along behind Chris O'Donnell _ he was just one
more actor in that film. Isn't that strange? Now he's a huge star,
and people revel in his work.
 &HT;    ``I've been a bit like that,'' Morton says. ``I've been sort of
staggering along, and things have worked out great for me. I think
if you set out to be a big star, you can really mess up your head.
 &HT;    ``I just think you should live life fully and don't regret
anything,'' she concludes. ``Just keep moving forward. I think you
get what you're meant to have in life. I always knew I'd get what
was meant for me.''
 c.2000 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Shep Morgan is a Hollywood-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Jesus' Son,'' consult the
Lions Gate Films Web site at www.lionsgatefilms.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
