<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, June
6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GRAND-CANYON (Grand Canyon) _ The mysteries of Grand
Canyon's formation continue to amaze geologists. This week more
than 80 of them will gather in Grand Canyon Village to compare
notes and work toward a unified theory of how and when the canyon
formed. The last time a similar group of experts met to discuss the
evolution of the Colorado River was in August 1964, before modern
theories of plate tectonics revolutionized geophysics with the
notion that continents could drift, slam into one another and alter
entire landscapes the size of the American Southwest. Not
surprisingly, the favorite theories from the previous era are now
on the table for serious revision. By Sandra Blakeslee. (2100
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3, and a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-THERAPY (Denver) _ Gene therapy burst into the news
like a bolt of lightning last fall, when a teenager from Tuscon
died in an experiment at the University of Pennsylvania. But while
politicians and the press have spent the year focusing on
allegations of lax government oversight and shoddily-run clinical
trials, the science of gene therapy has been making quiet, steady
progress. Little by little, researchers say, they are finding new
and better ways to deliver genes to their target cells. By Sheryl
Gay Stolberg. (1780 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CORN-BUTTERFLIES (Undted) _ The first field study of corn
genetically engineered to produce pesticides finds that the pollen
does not have adverse effects on black swallowtail butterflies.
However, the results do not bear directly on monarch butterflies,
which were found in an earlier laboratory study to be harmed by
such pollen. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SOLAR-HILLS (Undated) _ As predicted by theoreticians, the
Sun's surface is pockmarked by a grid of short hills that are
similar to long-lived, slow-moving bumps that travel across the
Earth's oceans, scientists have shown. By Kenneth Chang. (715
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BLACK-HOLES (Undated) _ By the latest count, astronomers
have detected massive black holes at the centers of more than 30
galaxies. The numbers are now sufficient, scientists say, to
recognize patterns and understand where, when and how the most
powerful black holes typically develop. The discoveries of several
are being announced this week. By John Noble Wilford. (775 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FLAT-SPACE (Undated) _ Nothing in the entire course of human
history would have been noticeably different if the universe were
not flat. Yet precisely for this reason there is poetry in the
recent discoveries that are worth celebrating, even if one is not a
cosmologist. They represent on the one hand a triumph of the human
imagination, and on the other a valuable reminder that science can
never be purely cerebral. An essay by Lawrence M. Krauss. (1575
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on gas
beneath the floor of the mid-Atlantic, the lack of fossils of
butterflies and insects and lingering insecticides. By Henry
Fountain. (680 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOCTORS-TESTS (Undated) _ Doctors' experiences can often
lead them to the wrong conclusion and cause problems in the end. A
vivid example of why controlled double-blind testing in the end
makes for better science. (800 words) By Abigail Zuger, M.D.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PERON-HEALTH (Undated) _ New discoveries about the life of
Eva Peron show that she was never told about her cancer, that a top
New York surgeon was flown in to treat her without her knowledge
and that she never knew the seriousness of her cancer. Like many
others of that era, her illness was hidden from her. And as still
occurs today, the illnesses of public officials can still be hidden
from the public. By Lawrence K. Altman. (1340 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: Morning
sickness may be troublesome, but science shows that it has many
health benefits, including protection the fetus and the mother. By
Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ORBACH-DIANNA (Undated) _ Conversation with Susie Orbach,
the psychotherapist who treated the Princess of Wales. By Claudia
Dreifus. (1320 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SAILING-YOUTH (Undated) _ Sailing is used as therapy to help
troubled youths learn discipline and teamwork. By Alison Hendrie.
(650 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT2.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and
fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Considering how hard it is for many people to remember what
they did even the day before, it is remarkable that so many
childhood memories remain intact. But now a new study shows that
many of those memories may be, at best, suspect. (265 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A new study, however, suggests that one sign of the future
cocaine addict is if he plunges headlong into cocaine use from the
very beginning. (290 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers say they have been able to measure brain changes
in dyslexic children who have been taught to read with a newly
developed technique. (290 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ An article in The Annals of Internal Medicine suggests there
may be merit to an alternative form of medicine known as distance
healing. This can include anything from therapeutic touch _ in
which a practitioner, without touching the patient, tries to alter
his energy field _ to simply praying for someone who is ill. But
there's no explanation. (260 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DYING (Undated) _ Short update on the work sheet used to
determine what end-of-life treatment people may prefer. By Denise
Grady. (150 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: Whatever
happened to seeding clouds to make it rain? By C. Claiborne Ray.
(300 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-ART (London) _ A Critic's Notebook: To be in London these
days is to be endlessly entertained by art, by the museums that
show it, the multiplying galleries that sell it and the masses who
have become weirdly fascinated by it. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   TV-TRAVIATA (Paris) _ On filming a television broadcast of La
