<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5127 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-GRANDPARENTS-N     06-05 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GRANDPARENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT RULES AGAINST GRANDPARENTS IN VISITING RIGHTS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a case of keen interest to grandparents across
the United States, the Supreme Court on Monday struck down a
Washington state law that had allowed not only grandparents but
also non-relatives to petition for the right to visit children.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 decision overturned the Washington law as
``breathtakingly broad.'' But the justices left open the
possibility that less extreme laws upholding the rights of
grandparents might withstand their scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   All 50 states have adopted grandparents' rights law, permitting
grandparents and sometimes others to seek court-ordered visiting
rights under various circumstances. The high court recognized the
importance of those rights Monday as it acknowledged the role that
many grandparents play in the lives of children.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1998, approximately 4 million children _ or 5.6 percent of
all children under age 18 _ lived in the household of their
grandparents,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote for the court.
</P>
<P>
   The case decided Monday, Troxel vs. Grandville, No. 99-138, drew
briefs from the 30-million member AARP, an advocacy group for
middle-aged and older Americans, as well as dozens of organizations
interested in the definition of family, from gay groups that
recognize same-sex unions to fundamentalist Christians with a
Norman Rockwell-like vision of home and hearth.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor noted that ``the demographic changes of the past
century make it difficult to speak of an average American family.''
But the ruling Monday was sufficiently nuanced, and the underlying
issues are so broad that Monday's action in this area of law was
almost surely not the last.
</P>
<P>
   The case produced six different opinions from the nine members.
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg
and Stephen G. Breyer joined O'Connor, while Justices David H.
Souter and Clarence Thomas wrote concurring opinions that took
somewhat different tacks.
</P>
<P>
   Justices John Paul Stevens, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M.
Kennedy each wrote dissenting opinions.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 plurality upheld the Washington state Supreme Court,
which declared in 1998 that the state law violated a parent's
constitutional right to rear his or her children without state
interference. The nation's high court on Monday cited not only that
overriding principle but the individual circumstances of the case
before them.
</P>
<P>
   The grandparents in this case are Gary and Jenifer Troxel, whose
son Brad fathered two daughters with his girlfriend, Tommie
Granville. Brad Troxel and Granville separated, and Brad Troxel
went to live with his parents before committing suicide in 1993.
Granville married a man who adopted her two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Gary and Jenifer Troxel wanted to see their granddaughters more
often than Granville and her new husband would allow, so the
grandparents brought suit and initially won a court visitation
order.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor placed considerable importance on the fact that no
court has ever found _ and the grandparents have never alleged _
that Granville was an unfit parent. Moreover, the justice noted,
Granville never sought to cut off visitation entirely; the mother
and her husband simply wanted to allow less of it than the
grandparents wanted.
</P>
<P>
   In his dissent, Stevens said the high court need not have
reviewed the Washington law but might better have left it to the
state legislature to revamp. He noted, too, that a parent's rights
regarding his or her child have ``never been regarded as
absolute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
