<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5138 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-FOSSILS-LEGEND-HNS &LR;      06-05 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSSILS-LEGEND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LEGENDS ABOUT EARTHLY `GIANTS' NOW SEEN AS EARLY SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Fossil-hunting scientists are raving over
evidence that some ancient legends about monsters are based on
discoveries of dinosaur bones made by nomads hundreds of years
before the time of Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   The myth of the griffin, a winged lion with a birdlike beak, was
apparently inspired by the nomads' discoveries of fossilized bones
of the protoceratops, an animal that existed more than 65 million
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Also, according to ``The First Fossil Hunters: Paleontology in
Greek and Roman Times'' by Adrienne Mayor, folk tales about a
vanished race of giant humans stemmed from ancient discoveries of
huge fossil thigh bones.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, paleontologists trace those same thigh bones _ some of
them 3 to 4 feet long _ to prehistoric elephants and other large
mammals, not to Goliath-sized humans.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor's 344-page book has drawn enthusiastic reviews.
</P>
<P>
   In the May 19 issue of Science magazine, Mott T. Greene, a
leading American historian of science, praises the book as ``a
historical and scientific detective story of the first rank . . .
(a) rich, spirited, and eminently readable book.''
</P>
<P>
   The book has thrilled paleontologists, researchers who study
fossils, by showing that their science dates from ancient times,
much older than previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   Most historical accounts of paleontology begin a few centuries
ago, when scientists puzzled over fossilized fish and seashells
found on mountains, some of them thousands of feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   As Mayor shows in her book, ancient Greek and Roman researchers
thousands of years ago collected numerous fossils of large extinct
mammals, measured their size and displayed them in temples and
museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``There they identified fossils as the relics of giants, heroes
and monsters of myth,'' the classical folklorist said in a
telephone interview from her home in Princeton, N.J. Some ancient
writers argued that the enormity of the supposed ``human'' remains
proved the human race had become smaller and weaker.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor ``has uncovered a barely noticed source for many of the
myths of the Old World, and for the first time has assembled in an
orderly way the evidence for early man's discovery of and
explanations for fossil remains,'' said Sir John Boardman, a
classical art historian at Oxford University in England. Because of
Mayor's analysis, he said, many ancient ``texts, sites, and
pictures will never seem quite the same again.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest impact of the ancient bones was on popular culture.
For example, many ancient Greek vases of the seventh through fifth
centuries B.C. depict griffins.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor said she would never forget the moment when she began to
suspect that the ancient images of griffins were based on reports
of the discovery of protoceratops bones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the Greek island of Samos, not too far from the coast
of Turkey. I was visiting the archaeological museum there, where I
saw hundreds of bronze griffins that had been excavated from the
temple on Samos,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earliest depictions of griffins looked really gnarly and
brutish. It looked as if the artist were trying to portray
something real rather than mythological,'' she said. ``And then in
a flash, I realized that they looked like modern reconstructions of
dinosaurs in a museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Protoceratops, which lived in the twilight of the dinosaur age
more than 65 million years ago, had a beak like a bird. At
maturity, it was typically 8 feet long, about the size of a lion.
It also had a bony frill at the back of the neck that the ancients
could have mistaken for the roots of wings, she said.
</P>
<P>
   What came next was 10 years of research into modern
paleontological records and ancient writings such as those archived
at the American School of Classical Studies in Athens. She not only
found strong evidence that the ancients were aware of prehistoric
fossils, but that they depicted them artistically. She also found
archaeological evidence of fossil collecting in antiquity.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``all ancient philosophers ignored these big bones. If
they had not, they might have come up with the idea of evolution
long before Darwin,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Were the ancient images of griffins based on dinosaur bones from
the island of Samos? That was not possible, she realized, because
geological forces did not form the island until long after the
dinosaurs became extinct.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she learned, the Greeks heard about the bones from
illiterate Scythian nomads who prospected for gold in the
westernmost regions of the Gobi Desert (in present-day China). They
found the bones in that area, specifically in deserts below the
foothills of the Altai Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That same region was visited by a noted American explorer of the
1920s, Roy Chapman Andrews, the author of the engaging book ``On
the Trail of Ancient Man,'' which described his adventures in the
exotic desert lands of China and Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
   One of Andrews' most celebrated finds was a complete
protoceratops skeleton. ``I was paging through the book and found a
photo of the skull of a protoceratops, partly embedded in the
ground. It looks just like a griffin,'' Mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   To learn what the Greeks knew about prehistoric fossils in their
own lands, she analyzed numerous historical narratives from more
than 30 different ancient authors, ranging from the historian
Herodotus of the fifth century B.C. to Augustine in the fifth
century A.D.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, classical scholars assumed that ancient accounts
of the bones of giants and monsters were ``just fantasy or
travelers' tales or superstition,'' she said. But Mayor's work
indicates that ancient reports of giant fossils contained grains of
truth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
