<HEADER>
A5142 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV11-NY     06-05 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW-TECH WORDS FIND HIGH-TECH MEANINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 11)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great American counterspook, Paul Redmond, left a word-news
tip in the dead drop that is my answering machine: ``Check out
 &UR; bundling &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Old-timers remember that word fondly from their spooning days.
`` &UR; Bundling &LR;  was originally courting in bed,'' noted an 1874
British slang dictionary, ``the lovers being tied or bundled up to
prevent undue familiarities. The practice still obtains in Wales.''
</P>
<P>
   This 1781 term for an early form of what is now called ``safe
sex,'' apparently pioneered by the prudent Welsh, was derived from
the Old English  &UR; bindan &LR; , ``to bind together,'' and was later
applied to ``men and women sleeping together, where the divisions
of the house will not permit of better or more decent
accommodation, with all their clothes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to the Arizona Legislature in 1956, which
prohibited `` &UR; bundling &LR;  or combining various limited benefit
insurance policies.'' The pejorative connotation grew when the
Justice Department in 1975 accused IBM of charging anti-competitive
prices for  &UR; bundling &LR;  hardware and software services.
</P>
<P>
   The European Community repeated the complaint in 1981, when John
Tagliabue defined the word in The New York Times: ``the practice of
what is called  &UR; bundling &LR;  _ selling the elements of a computer
system as a package to prevent competitors from supplying them at
perhaps better conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Today the term obtains, to use the archaic verb, in the
Microsoft case, as a federal judge ruled that the company illegally
 &UR; bundled &LR;  its Web browser with its Windows software. In my
legal-etymological interpretation, the company is appealing on the
grounds that separate divisions wrapped up in bed together, fully
clothed, are not making love.
</P>
<P>
   Thus do old terms find new uses in the brave new wide Web world.
The trade name  &UR; Spam &LR; , for example _ which was created in 1937 by
Hormel Foods out of the first and last letters of ``spiced ham'' _
has, when uncapitalized, come to mean ``junk e-mail,'' with a
second sense of ``the random posting of advertisements on computer
bulletin boards.''
</P>
<P>
   A fanciful speculation about the metaphoric reason for the
adoption of  &UR; spamming &LR;  by the computer world can be found in the
excellent Newton's Telecom Dictionary, 16th edition: ``The term is
derived from a brand of pink, canned meat that splatters messily
when hurled.'' (A spokesman for Hormel vociferously denies this,
and tests run at the Safire Semantic Kitchens confirm that uncanned
Spam, when hurled against a wall at a normal speed, bounces rather
than splatters.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cache &LR; , pronounced ``cash,'' from the French verb  &UR; cacher &LR; ,
``to hide,'' came to mean ``a hiding place for valuables''; it was
especially applied to holes dug to conceal provisions and
ammunition. (One reason given by the Pentagon for the U.S.
incursion into Cambodia in 1969 was to capture buried arms, causing
the Nixon aide Len Garment to ask, ``Can you check a  &UR; cache &LR; ?'')
</P>
<P>
   In usage by the new lingo, information is  &UR; cached &LR;  when it is
placed closer to the user to make it more accessible, which also
places less strain on limited computer and network resources. The
meaning has changed from the sinister ``hiding place'' to a more
positive ``nearby holding place.''
</P>
<P>
   A  &UR; cookie &LR;  originated as a small Dutch cake and became the term
for a baked morsel to be passed around after the canapes have been
devoured. The metaphoric origin of  &UR; cookie &LR;  in computerese is
obscure (send speculation to onlanguage(at)nytimes.com), but its
meaning is ``a text file placed on a computer's hard disk by an
Internet server to track the client's habits and tastes.''
</P>
<P>
   Marketers say it provides convenience and unexpected choices to
clients; privacy guardians warn that a  &UR; cookie &LR;  can follow a
customer's movements around the Web to create an invasive profile.
</P>
<P>
   A  &UR; cookie-pusher &LR;  was a term coined in World War II to be a
derogation of diplomats who attended too many receptions; now it is
an exponent of ``targeted marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Attendant &LR;  began as ``one who waits upon or accompanies,'' as
in Milton's ``Lest sin Surprise thee, and her black  &UR; attendant &LR; ,
Death.'' After adoption by airlines of ``flight  &UR; attendant &LR; '' when
 &UR; stewardess &LR;  was taken as sexist, the word was snapped up by
technologists and now has two meanings. The first is ``an
inexpensive computer that leans heavily on its connection to more
sophisticated computers.''
</P>
<P>
   The second meaning bothers me. ``An  &UR; attendant &LR;  is an operator
of a phone system console,'' lexicographer Harry Newton tells me.
``Typically, it's the first person in a company to answer an
incoming call. That person  &UR; attends &LR;  the phone system; when the
company's phone is answered by a machine, that's an  &UR; automated
attendant &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   What's the matter with  &UR; operator &LR; ? My mother was a telephone
 &UR; operator &LR;  and proud of it. An  &UR; operator &LR;  suggests an active,
purposeful, hands-on person engaging with a device or system; an
 &UR; attendant &LR;  is more passive, sometimes just hanging around ``in
waiting.'' The machine, or system, that is  &UR; operated &LR;  is secondary
to the human in charge, but the phone system that is merely
 &UR; attended &LR;  is the master.
</P>
<P>
   Hello, Central?
</P>
<P>
   OF WIMPS AND MUSH
</P>
<P>
   In an aside (watch out for those asides) in an article last
month, I recalled a 1980 headline over an editorial in The Boston
Globe that read ``Mush From the Wimp,'' which I presumed a
prankster substituted for the cliche ``All Must Share the Burden.''
I am now informed by David Greenway, who retired last month as
editor of The Globe's editorial page, that it was not sabotage but
a self-inflicted wound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the late Kirk Scharfenberg, editorial writer and later
editor of the page,'' writes Greenway, ``who wrote `Mush From the
Wimp' over his editorial on President Carter's economic plan. He
wrote it as a joke, never thinking that the headline would ever see
print.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, the copy editors write the headlines,'' continues
my colleague Greenway, ``but in this case the copy editors let it
through. The night editor caught it in midrun, and the headline was
hastily changed to the cliched `All Must Share the Burden' as a
last-minute sub for the rest of the run.''
</P>
<P>
   Many years later, when Greenway became editor of The Globe's
editorial page, the paper criticized animal rights advocates who
wanted to close down dog-sled racing in Alaska. The headline chosen
for its historic resonance: ``More Wimps for the Mush.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
