<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTION AND ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Whatever happened to seeding clouds to make it rain?
</P>
<P>
   A. Cloud-seeding experiments and government programs continue,
but in this country at least, they are not regarded as a panacea
for drought. The programs are usually subject to strict controls.
The Weather Modification Association, a clearinghouse for research
and information on all kinds of approaches to changing the weather,
says 32 states have enacted laws regulating who can practice cloud
seeding.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud seeding dates from experiments in 1946 at the General
Electric Laboratories in Schenectady, N.Y., and usually relies on
silver iodide as a seeding agent, providing nuclei for the rapid
formation of ice crystals that may eventually produce raindrops.
</P>
<P>
   There are some unknowns about effectiveness and safety. For
example, seeding at the wrong time and in the wrong place may
actually decrease rainfall. Some skeptics worry that there is a
possibility of creating severe weather like hail or floods or of
increasing rainfall in one region at the expense of another. Other
scientists say the possibilities of creating hail are remote and
that seeding can be suspended if there is danger of flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud seeding has been used for more than 25 years in parts of
West Texas and has been an important arm of water policy in Utah,
one of the driest states, since 1973. There have been recent major
programs in Florida, Thailand and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by mail to Question,
Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd St., New York,
N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to question(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1557EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5145 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-SAILING-YOUTH-ART     06-05 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SAILING-YOUTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAILING USED AS THERAPY FOR TROUBLED YOUTHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times)  
 By ALISON HENDRIE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although he spent the first 17 years of his life on the shores
of the Chesapeake Bay, Carl Immel had never set foot in its water.
After being jailed on assault and theft charges two years ago,
however, the court assigned Immel to Baltimore's Fresh Start
Program, which uses sailing as a therapeutic tool for troubled
teen-agers. Soon he was racing a 23-foot Rainbow sail boat in
Baltimore Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know a jib from a main sheet,'' said Immel, now 19,
who has since graduated from the program and gotten a job. ``But I
loved it the first time I raced, especially being out there away
from everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in poor urban neighborhoods is hardly the traditional
pedigree for sunset sails, but sailing is now being used to help
youths facing abuse, violence and crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids come from tough backgrounds where they have a world
of issues and are products of their environment,'' said Parker
Rockefeller, director of development for Living Classrooms, a
nonprofit educational organization in Maryland that runs the Fresh
Start program, a learn-by-doing program for students who have
trouble with the law. ``When they come off the boats, they have an
incredible sense of accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sailing is a sport of independence, responsibility, control and
direction, the very qualities that are often lacking among youth
who have been in trouble, said Carol Miller, a child psychologist
and member of Sea Sisters, a Maryland group of women who sail. ``I
have seen teens,'' she said, ``in whose homes there was no control,
no consistency, and no one to trust.
</P>
<P>
   Sailing, she said, tackles these issues head on by getting the
teen-agers off the therapy couch and in control of a boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thrill, excitement and high you get from heeling over in a
high wind is very attractive to these children who often have a
high threshold for stimulation and engage in life-threatening
activities on the streets,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   It is this thrill that Dawn Riley, captain of America True, a
U.S. entry in the America's Cup race last year, wanted to share. In
1995, she began a nationwide youth sailing program, True Youth,
which pairs boat owners with at-risk children, like first-time
offenders or victims of abuse. Having spent much of her childhood
on the family sailboat, Riley, who is from Detroit, appreciates the
connection sailing makes with the young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a big clique mentality, but out on the boat, the
playing field is level,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a tremendous amount of responsibility because of
strong winds and tides and cold water,'' said Paul Sidorenko, vice
commodore of Golden Gate Yacht Club in San Francisco, who runs the
club's youth sailing program. ``If you don't focus, you can die.''
</P>
<P>
   At Fresh Start, the young people run the entire ship, a schooner
called The Lady Maryland, with staff members there simply to help
out. ``Fifteen kids are lined up on the starboard side pulling up
this huge, heavy canvas mainsail,'' Rockefeller said. ``You can't
do that without working together.''
</P>
<P>
   The same self-esteem and competence sailing sometimes imparts to
troubled youths from the city can work for the suburban ones, too.
A 10-year-old from Arnold, Md., who asked that her name not be
used, struggled through her parents' divorce and sought counseling
with the Strong Girls program at the YMCA, which included sailing
with the local Women Aboard club. She said that while on the boat,
the tension she felt at home began to slip away.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother noticed the change: ``There was a light I hadn't seen
in her eyes for quite a while. The sailing seemed to blow things
away and I was just grateful to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1558EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
