<HEADER>
A5151 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      06-05 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Belching Sea
</P>
<P>
   The sea floor off the mid-Atlantic coast has a bad case of
indigestion. Scientists have discovered that there are large
amounts of gas trapped beneath it, and there are signs that the gas
occasionally bursts through in a kind of suboceanic belch.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the gas was confirmed last month during a
research cruise by scientists from the Woods Hole Oceanographic
Institution and several universities. The scientists were studying
the structure of the continental shelf, particularly the presence
of what appeared to be large cracks that could someday cause
underwater landslides, leading to tsunamis.
</P>
<P>
   They suspected that rising gas could be at least partly
responsible for the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Seismic data gathered by the researchers showed the presence of
gas beneath the top layers of sediment. But the scientists also
realized that the cracks were not really cracks at all, but rather
a series of large depressions, up to about three square miles in
size, that appeared to be the result of gas eruptions.
</P>
<P>
   What happens, the scientists suggested, is that gas builds up
under the sediments, which are relatively impermeable, until
something occurs _ the researchers do not know just what _ to cause
it to break through. The violence of the eruption essentially blows
a hole in the sea floor, leaving behind the depression.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists say this phenomenon could weaken the shelf and
contribute to the possibility of landslides. While the risk is
slight, underwater landslides are not unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Respect for Aged Insects
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to fossils, moths and butterflies get far less
press than, say, dinosaurs. The lack of attention is partly due to
a lack of specimens: only about 700 moth and butterfly fossils
exist.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are not sure whether the lack of fossils means that
these insects were not abundant millions of years ago, or that they
just do not preserve well.
</P>
<P>
   A new discovery, however, indicates that poor preservation is
the problem. In one fell swoop, a European scientist has more than
doubled the number of these fossils in existence. The researcher,
from the University of Goettingen in Germany, reports in Nature the
finding of some 1,700 moth specimens in 55-million-year-old
sediments in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   More than a thousand of the specimens are of one species, and
they were often found close together. Since the area in which they
were found was once part of the ancient North Sea, the finding
indicates that the moths undertook mass migrations over the sea, as
some species still do. And mass migration means that there must
have been masses of these insects around.
</P>
<P>
   Loitering Insecticide
</P>
<P>
   The insecticide chlordane was banned in the United States in
1988, but like other pesticides in the family known as
organochlorines, it is known to loiter in the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Just how long it loiters, and what kind of trouble it gets into,
is the subject of a study by scientists at the Connecticut
Agricultural Experiment Station in New Haven. They have shown that
even decades after use, chlordane is taken up by many common garden
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers grew test crops on a patch of land that used to
be a lawn and had been treated with chlordane in 1960. They found
that root crops like carrots, beets and potatoes had among the
highest concentrations of chlordane, which might be expected given
that it is taken up by the roots. But the pesticide was also found
in the edible parts of vegetables like spinach, lettuce and
zucchini. It was not found in the edible parts of tomatoes, corn or
peppers, however.
</P>
<P>
   Chlordane accumulates in animal tissue, and can lead to
disorders of the digestive and nervous systems. The researchers
noted, however, that the amounts in the test crops were very small.
Washing the vegetables in water will help reduce the chances of
consuming the pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1603EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
