<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5170 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-RACE-MILITARY-ABRIDGE     06-05 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-MILITARY-ABRIDGED-ART-$ADV07-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
FORT KNOX, Ky.: four times.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Ruth, a Puerto Rican, suspected that his
academic deficiencies were behind his stagnation. He had never
taken any college courses in the Army, even though he had had the
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But as they watched other sergeants move up _ mainly white ones,
whose credentials were no better than his _ the Williamses also
began to suspect race. ``It makes you wonder,'' Ruth Williams said.
``Is he being passed over because he's a black male?''
</P>
<P>
   TINKERER FROM SHEBOYGAN
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved working with my hands,'' Feyer said. ``I
guess I got that from my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, Gerrit, was a Dutch immigrant, a wood carver who
helped make molds for machine parts. Harry was the youngest of
seven children whom Gerrit and Cornelia Feyer reared in Sheboygan.
</P>
<P>
   The Feyers had moved there for the work and for their faith.
Sheboygan offered a school run by the Christian Reformed Church, an
offshoot of the Dutch Reformed Church, and the Feyers wanted their
children educated in the Reformed tradition. Sheboygan was a safe
setting in which to raise children, but it was isolated.
</P>
<P>
   There were few blacks in Sheboygan. A local joke has it that if
you see a black man on the street, he must play for the Green Bay
Packers. Feyer remembers knowing one black family. The father was a
police officer, the son a thief.
</P>
<P>
   While Earnest Williams was a football hero in high school, Harry
Feyer faded into the crowd at his school. He didn't play sports, he
didn't participate in extracurricular activities, he didn't do well
in his studies.
</P>
<P>
   Where he usually got lost was under the hood of a car. He would
spend hours in a neighbor's garage, breaking down and rebuilding
engines. Mechanical tasks absorbed him, just as they would in the
Army, to the point where they distracted from what else was going
on in his life.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing school, he married his high school sweetheart,
Laurel Cluk. He got a job in a wall-paneling factory but soon
concluded that it was a dead end. He decided to enlist.
</P>
<P>
   In the Army he gained recognition as a first-rate mechanic and
was given the job maintaining Cobra helicopters. He wound up doing
little more than that; it took him almost eight years to become a
sergeant. In part he blames a supervisor, in part himself.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1991, and the Army was phasing out the Cobra, so
promotions for people who worked on it were becoming rare. He was
supposed to be notified of a special program permitting Cobra
mechanics to switch to other specialties. But he was a good
mechanic and his supervisor didn't want to lose him, so, Feyer
said, the supervisor hid the notification papers.
</P>
<P>
   PROMOTION BLUES
</P>
<P>
   One day in 1994, the Army told Feyer that it was kicking him
out. It had been three years since his supervisor had sandbagged
him into remaining a Cobra mechanic, and he had still not made
sergeant. The Army was pruning itself of dead wood, and he, stuck
at corporal, was on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Laurel Feyer was pregnant at the time, and the couple had a
5-year-old son; they needed the Army's medical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Fear galvanized him. He pleaded with the Army not to discharge
him, so he volunteered to work in nuclear, biological and chemical
warfare. Few soldiers choose that specialty. Most are scared off by
it, imagining themselves in stifling chemical-warfare suits, never
mind the poisons. But promotion possibilities there are wide open.
</P>
<P>
   He made sergeant a few months later.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion brought another surprise. Attending mandatory
classes for noncommissioned officers, he graduated with honors.
Buoyed by his success, he then earned an associate's degree at a
community college in Colorado Springs, where the family was living.
In short order he became staff sergeant, then drill sergeant,
finishing near the top of his class. Now, at Fort Knox, he had a
chance for platoon sergeant, and he wasn't going to be denied by a
group of blacks just because he wasn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The company's executive officer, Lt. Paul Bergson, a white,
advised Feyer that before raising a stink, he should determine
whether the blacks promoted to platoon sergeant had more seniority.
He checked, and they had.
</P>
<P>
   But the black sergeants got wind that whites were questioning
the platoon leadership's racial makeup and resented it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never want to see a black man get ahead,'' Reed said.
Williams agreed. As soon as whites feel even a little threatened,
he said, ``they all stick together.''
</P>
<P>
   A TRUCE, OR MAYBE NOT
</P>
<P>
   By autumn 1999 Williams and Feyer had reached a kind of
accommodation. It may have had something to do with Williams'
promotion; in September he received word that, on his fifth try, he
was being made sergeant first class.
</P>
<P>
   Feyer began trying to work more effectively with Williams. He
tried to anticipate what was be wanted of him. He felt Williams
tried to talk with him more. ``We're clicking now,'' he said. ``We
don't even have to say anything. We each know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams had a different view: his partner still wasn't pulling
his weight. ``He wants his own platoon,'' Williams said. ``I feel
he should get it and then fall on his face. The reason he doesn't
fall on his face now is because I don't let him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams soon had something else on his mind. Near the end
of the fall cycle, he was told that he was being transferred to
Echo Company, across the parade ground.
</P>
<P>
   The orders outraged him. He had achieved a position of power in
Bravo Company. The transfer would mean he would have to start over
again.
</P>
<P>
   Why the transfer? Williams saw the reason as racial: the
battalion's white hierarchy could not tolerate one of its four
companies' being run by black sergeants. One had to go.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before the December graduation, Feyer and Williams sat
brooding in their office. Williams was angry about his impending
transfer. Feyer was still upset about having been denied the drill
sergeant's award. He was speculating about who may or may not have
voted for him. Williams, who had voted against his partner, sat in
silence.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after the graduation ceremony, Williams moved his
gear over to Echo. He had met his new battle buddy, Mordecial Hale,
who is black. Williams was asked whether it would be better having
a brother as a partner. ``Without a doubt,'' he replied.
</P>
</TEXT>
