<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-GRANDPARENTS (Washington) _ Wading into the complexities
of modern American families, the Supreme Court rules that parents
have the sole right to decide whom their children may visit. The
ruling covers time spent with grandparents and other relatives. In
a 6-3 decision, the court struck down a Washington state law that
allowed ``any person,'' including non-relatives as well as
grandparents, to seek visitation rights with children. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NEW-YORK-SENATE (Washington) _ Independent pollster John Zogby
says first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton may face a tougher race
against Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., for the U.S. Senate than she faced
against New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. Zogby says despite
his latest poll showing Clinton edging Lazio, 46 percent to 44
percent, Lazio beats Clinton in key battlegrounds, including
upstate and the New York City suburbs, as well as among Catholic
voters. By STEWART M. POWELL
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DEMOCRATS (Austin, Texas) _ For all the ground they have
lost to the Republicans in recent years, Texas Democrats might be
forgiven for wanting to cry as they head into their upcoming state
party convention. But Democratic officials are optimistic, even in
a year when some party faithful might vote for a favorite son
presidential candidate, Republican Gov. George W. Bush. Regaining
power is ``a mixture of getting the right people to come back into
politics, and I don't think we're there yet,'' says Laredo mayor
Betty Flores. By PEGGY FIKAC.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   D-DAY-MUSEUM (New Orleans) _ When the doors open Tuesday, the
National D-Day Museum will honor a generation of men and women
whose courage secured an Allied victory in World War II. Some of
those veterans will take part in the grand-opening ceremonies in
New Orleans. By JULIE COOPER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ When the Supreme Court allowed a New
York photographer to take a public group shot of 152 naked models
lying in a street this weekend, it reinforced our First Amendment
rights to freedom of expression. It also encouraged a trend toward
nudity, particularly female toplessness. British matrons posed nude
for a best-selling calendar. A female Ohio rugby team took off the
bras for a bare-breasted photo shoot. Women have sued for the right
to go topless in public places. Is this good fun or an alarming
decline in moral standards? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
