<HEADER>
A5172 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTERNET-FILM06-COX     06-05 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FILM06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOLLYWOOD MOVIE TO GET FIRST ALL-DIGITAL SCREENING
 &HT;    Moving in the (f) financial and (e) entertainment categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The new Hollywood movie ``Titan A.E.'' is being
beamed to Atlanta on Tuesday over the Internet _ an event being
likened to first telegram, sent from Washington to Baltimore in
1844.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an absolute first,'' said Larry Lang, vice president of
service provider marketing at Cisco Systems, which is supplying the
digital plumbing for the historic four-hour Internet transfer of
the 42-gigabyte file.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that when people publish the milestones of digital
cinema, that one of those milestones definitely will be in Atlanta
tomorrow as the first movie ever delivered down the network to a
theater,'' Lang said Monday in a telephone interview from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   With its hundreds of billions of digital ``bits'' of data, Titan
A.E. (as in, ``After Earth'') overwhelms ``What hath God wrought,''
the message contained in Samuel Morse's inaugural telegram.
</P>
<P>
   The film will stream across a secure private network from 20th
Century Fox studios in Hollywood to the Woodruff Arts Center. It
will travel by way of a Cisco-equipped Qwest Communications data
center in Burbank, Calif., and a comparable BellSouth site in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The animated film features the voices of Matt Damon, Drew
Barrymore, Bill Pullman, Janeane Garofalo, Nathan Lane, and John
Leguizamo.
</P>
<P>
   It is due to open in theaters nationwide June 16 after its
premiere at the Woodruff Center to a Supercomm 2000 trade show
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Lang said only about 25 U.S. theaters, out of some 38,000
domestic movie screens, currently have the equipment needed for a
full digital-to-digital movie transfer. ``But the number,'' he
added, ``will rise quite rapidly after some thorny economic issues
are finally resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Movie house owners have been hesitant to pay costs of about
$100,000 per projector, when most of the initial savings will go to
the Hollywood studios, which will be freed from the burden of
making thousands of film prints and shipping them around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Lang said, however, that ``it would quite a while'' before such
Internet downloads can enter home theater market. Few homes, he
noted, are equipped with the necessary fiber optic cables.
Moreover, he noted, the projection equipment, even in a more
simplified form, is still too costly for all but the richest
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The elaborate security formula adopted by Cisco, which includes
coding of the film's data, multiple protective ``firewalls'' and
secure routers, is aimed at reducing widespread fears in Hollywood
that films will become subject to the same sort of piracy concerns
that have recently plagued the music industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``In principle, we're doing more or less the same thing as what
happens whenever people deal with their bank or broker through
their Internet browser,'' Lang said.
</P>
<P>
   Digital projectors have been used in the last year to exhibit a
few films, such as Disney's ``Dinosaur,'' in a few theaters around
the country. Video images also regularly stream across the
Internet, but often with poor quality and in postage-stamp size.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: filmforce.ign.com/titan(underscore)ae/
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
