<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT URGES JUDGE TO DENY MICROSOFT'S REQUEST FOR MORE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL BRICK   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Department of Justice urged a federal judge Monday to reject
a request by Microsoft (MSFT:Nasdaq) for more time to plan how it
would comply with an expected order to break up the software
company.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors submitted the third draft of their proposed breakup,
incorporating a few of Microsoft's numerous suggestions. They
agreed to several minor and cosmetic changes, but argued against
the company's most significant protest, a request for 12 months to
come up with a divestiture plan instead of the four months the
Justice Department had proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no justification for the proposed extension of time
in which Microsoft is to file a report on the steps it has taken to
comply,'' prosecutors wrote in their response to Microsoft's
comments on their revised proposal. ``Microsoft's request confuses
the actual planning and implementation of the divestiture with the
requirement of this provision, which is simply to report to the
Court.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redmond, Wash.-based company has until noon EDT Wednesday to
respond in writing ``if it so chooses,'' according to a court
order. Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson , who is overseeing the case,
is expected shortly thereafter to order the company split into two
parts.
</P>
<P>
   But the company immediately criticized the latest revisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government's latest effort, the version 3.0 of its plan,
would still damage consumers in the high-tech industry, and even
the slightest cosmetic changes do not change the fact that their
plan remains excessive, unprecedented and harmful to consumers,''
said Jim Cullinan, a spokesman for Microsoft. He added that the
company had not been given a fair chance to argue against the
proposed remedies and that prosecutors had not presented sufficient
evidence to support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly no testimony or evidence to support the
assertions made by their declarations,'' Cullinan said.
</P>
<P>
   A two-way split, the crux of the government proposal, would
place the ubiquitous Windows operating system in one company and
create a second business for everything else, including software
applications, the Internet Explorer Web browser and the Microsoft
Network Internet service provider and network of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   A final ruling seems imminent this week, though it was widely
expected last week as well, before the company surprised the court
with a long list of proposed changes. Microsoft has said repeatedly
that it will appeal all aspects of the ruling, from the findings of
fact to the remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Jackson ordered this additional round of briefs in the
case on Thursday, one day after Microsoft, in what was to have been
the final brief in the case, called the prosecutors' proposal
vague, defective and unlikely to withstand appeal. The company,
which had been given an opportunity to comment on the form of the
proposal, instead made those comments on its substance. It also
offered new witnesses from an array of business sectors to testify
that a breakup would harm the economy and said it would need 12
months to devise a breakup plan, not the four months prosecutors
had offered.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing Wednesday , Microsoft argued that ``the timetable
proposed for the divestiture is unrealistic.'' It said that federal
regulators, both foreign and domestic and including the U.S.
Securities and Exchange Commission, would examine a breakup plan.
</P>
<P>
   On May 24, Jackson abruptly closed the proceedings in the case,
refusing Microsoft's repeated requests for more time. The company's
lawyers filed an offer of proof just before Judge Jackson ended the
hearing, which also included a list of such new potential witnesses
as William H. Gates, Microsoft's chairman, and Steve Ballmer, the
company's chief executive, and described the testimony they could
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Jackson has ruled that Microsoft employed illegal business
practices to extend a monopoly on computer operating systems to
other markets. His recent attempts to wrap up the case, which
attempts to apply antitrust law to the rapidly changing technology
of a seemingly Internet-bound marketplace, must seek to both avoid
obsolescence and the inadvertant creation of appellate grounds. The
company has already written that it was denied due process because
its attorneys expected the May 24 hearing to be the beginning, not
the end, of the remedies phase.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Judge Jackson's attempts to pick up the pace in the
antitrust case, partly in an effort to allow appeals to begin, the
time required for those appeals is unknown. Provisions specific to
antitrust law give the U.S. solicitor general, and not the Justice
Department, 15 days to request that the Supreme Court immediately
review the company's appeal. That would allow the government to
leapfrog the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia, which reversed Judge Jackson in an earlier ruling adverse
to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Within 90 days of a ruling, the behavioral remedies outlined by
17 states and the Justice Department would take effect. These
remedies include publishing the so-called source code used by
programmers to design software applications for Windows. Other
proposed behavioral remedies would regulate Microsoft's relations
with computer makers and software companies.
</P>
<P>
   The company could ask an appeals court to stay a portion of the
remedies; Judge Jackson himself could stay portions of his
remedies.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
