<HEADER>
A5176 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-SOLAR-HILLS-NYT &LR;      06-05 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SOLAR-HILLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLAR WAVES OFFER HINT TO WHAT'S INSIDE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By KENNETH CHANG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   How is the Sun like the ocean? As predicted by theoreticians,
the Sun's surface is pockmarked by a grid of short hills that are
similar to long-lived, slow-moving bumps that travel across the
Earth's oceans.
</P>
<P>
   The observation of the tiny solar bulges, each just about 100
yards tall and separated from the next by about 50,000 miles, could
provide solar physicists a new tool for examining the inside of the
Sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we see is, Everywhere on the edge of the Sun are bumps
that are carried by solar rotation,'' said Dr. Jeffrey Kuhn of the
University of Hawaii's Institute for Astronomy, lead author of a
paper describing the solar hills in the current issue of the
journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   The Solar and Heliospheric Observatory, from its round-the-clock
Sun-watching position between the Sun and Earth, traces the outline
of the Sun every 12 minutes. The hills, known as Rossby waves, are
too small to be seen in any single outline, but statistical
patterns of undulations emerged as Kuhn's team studied almost three
years of data.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is an impressive feat, what they've done,'' said
Dr. Charles Wolff, a scientist at Goddard Space Flight Center in
Greenbelt, Md., who has worked out theoretical calculations of
Rossby waves on the Sun. ``It's the equivalent of standing in New
York and detecting the thickness of a nickel in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Wolff said, there have been only indirect and
inconclusive evidence for Rossby waves through sunspot
observations.
</P>
<P>
   The hill patterns linger, despite other more violent roilings on
the Sun like coronal mass ejections and solar flares.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to live for years,'' Kuhn said. ``We see the
features persist even as the pattern of sunspots comes and goes.''
</P>
<P>
   What creates the hills is the Sun's spin, the same phenomenon
that causes Northern Hemisphere hurricanes, ocean currents or any
other fluid on a spinning sphere to rotate in a clockwise
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an alternating series of high and low pressure
systems covering the whole surface of the Sun like a
checkerboard,'' Wolff said. ``That entire pattern drifts slowly
westward.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-pressure regions bulge outward slightly, producing the
hills. Oceanographers have detected similar patterns in
ocean-height measurements by the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's Topex/Poseidon satellite. The watery version of
Rossby waves are only a few inches high and are separated from each
other by about 1,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take something like 15 to 20 years to propagate from San
Francisco to Tokyo,'' said Dr. Dudley Chelton, professor of
oceanography at Oregon State University and a co-author of a 1996
article in the journal Science that first discussed the Rossby
waves in the Topex/Poseidon images.
</P>
<P>
   However, in midlatitude regions, the slow pace of the ocean
Rossby waves is still twice as fast as what was predicted by the
equations of the meteorologist Carl-Gustaf Arvid Rossby, who
devised them in the 1930s to describe swirling weather patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Roland De Szoeke, a colleague of Chelton at Oregon State,
has been tweaking the equations to explain the faster-than-expected
Rossby waves. The speed of the waves depends on the density of the
fluid, De Szoeke said, and at the midlatitudes, the thermocline _
the boundary between the warm surface waters and the cold, denser
waters below _ runs deeper than in the tropics. In turn, Rossby
waves alter the water temperature and density, pushing the
thermocline downward by several hundred feet.
</P>
<P>
   For oceanographers, the Rossby waves don't tell them anything
new about ocean conditions. They can directly measure temperature
and density directly by dropping probes into the water. Solar
scientists who do not have that luxury may be able to use Rossby
waves to deduce something about what is going on inside the Sun.
Why are the hills 100 yards tall? Why are they 50,000 miles apart?
</P>
<P>
   ``The first puzzle is what determines those numbers,'' Kuhn
said, ``and that is undoubtedly going to be determined by the
interior conditions of the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
