<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DOCTORS-TESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS' CASES: IT CAN PAY TO IGNORE EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER, M.D.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is easy to become irritated with the plodding pace of
clinical medical science. Studies churn on for years, comparing
Drug A with Drug B, Drug C with placebo, finally spitting out a few
cautious conclusions that invariably end with a call for yet more
research on more minutiae of the same old questions.
</P>
<P>
   Even doctors become impatient with it all. Sometimes, especially
as they get older, they just begin to pay the studies less mind,
and concentrate instead on what they have seen with their own eyes.
At conferences they tend to lean their aging bones back in the
chair and say to the young ones, ``I know all about those studies
of A, B and C, and in my experience things are a little
different.''
</P>
<P>
   The wisdom of medical experience can be delicious to accumulate
and display. Unfortunately, it can also be quite dangerous _ as a
recent case of hepatitis in a patient of mine clearly shows.
</P>
<P>
   My patient's hepatitis was entirely routine. He was sick for a
week with the usual warning signs _ fatigue, achiness, a sudden
dislike of strong odors. For another 10 days he was in bed
nauseated, with a throbbing ache in the right side of his abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   His diagnosis was easy enough to make: his liver enzymes on a
blood test were off the charts, fifty times as high as normal. His
care was not particularly challenging either: with bed rest and
fluids, he was better in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a month later, he is still a little shaky but back at work.
It will take another blood test to determine which hepatitis virus
made him sick.
</P>
<P>
   The instructive parts of his case are actually not its medical
details at all, but a few casual sentences the patient and I had
exchanged before his hepatitis started. We were discussing whether
he should start taking medications for his infection with HIV, the
virus that causes AIDS. His stage of infection was advanced enough
that he probably should, but the decision of when to begin them was
entirely up to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' he said, cheerful and efficient. ``I'm ready. I will
start them tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   I shrugged. It was a Friday. ``You might as well give yourself
the weekend off.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is exactly what he did. He took the weekend off, and by
Monday morning he was not feeling very well at all. He dragged
himself through the rest of the week, new pill bottles unopened,
and by the time he stumbled to the lab for the blood tests that
diagnosed his hepatitis, even thinking about the medications made
him queasy. The bottles are still unopened.
</P>
<P>
   But suppose he had decided to start those pills on that Saturday
after all?
</P>
<P>
   If he had, he would still have developed a whopping case of
hepatitis, of course: it had begun to incubate well before our
conversation took place. But he would have developed it just a few
days after he started a set of new pills.
</P>
<P>
   It would have played out as a crystal-clear case of cause and
effect, precisely timed and far too obvious to question. In big
studies, none of the medications he was to start caused liver
problems like his. Even so, I would have been hard- pressed to
avoid blaming the drugs. Even if I had thought to consider a virus,
I would probably have assumed that the drugs had activated the
virus. How else to explain the course of events?
</P>
<P>
   My patient would have had a variety of tests, possibly even a
liver biopsy. When he recovered I would have given him a different
set of drugs, and warned him never to take any of the first again.
</P>
<P>
   I would also have started worrying about using those drugs in
other patients, especially those with liver problems. I would have
known, of course, that studies show hepatitis from those drugs is
mild and rare. But I would have been wary of trusting the studies
against my own experience.
</P>
<P>
   I would have mentioned my patient's case to colleagues all over
the country, implying that they might want to think twice about
those medications in their own patients. ``In my experience,'' I
would have said, settling my aging bones in the chair, ``you can
get into trouble with those.''
</P>
<P>
   And it would all have been utterly misguided, a mistake from
beginning to end, misinformed by a fluke of personal experience.
</P>
<P>
   Only the tortuously slow studies designed to examine drug
effects in thousands of people can begin to sort out this kind of
coincidence from true cause and effect. Their glacial pace shows
how difficult it is in medicine to dissect the powerful role of
happenstance out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   And as for single startling cases of self-evident cause and
effect: often their moral is simply how deceptive single startling
cases of anything can be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
