<HEADER>
A5183 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BLACK-HOLES-NYT &LR;      06-05 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BLACK-HOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WHEN AND HOW OF BLACK HOLES EMERGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the latest count, which rose with fresh announcements Monday,
astronomers have detected massive black holes at the centers of
more than 30 galaxies. The numbers are now sufficient, scientists
say, to recognize patterns and understand where, when and how the
most powerful black holes typically develop.
</P>
<P>
   New observations by the Hubble Space Telescope support the
theory that black holes did not precede a galaxy's birth but
evolved along with the galaxy. They were fed by the same inward
collapse of gas that caused the creation of stars in the galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger the galaxy, the findings show, the bigger its central
black hole, the extremely dense mass with a gravitational pull so
powerful that it sucks in everything nearby and allows nothing to
escape, not even light. One of the more intriguing surprises is
that the typical black hole, large or relatively small, invariably
has a mass that is two-tenths of one percent of the mass of the
high-density central region, or bulge, of the galaxy. Why such a
proportion pertains to so many examples is still a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Another pattern to emerge from the observations is that the more
massive black holes _ ones with compressed masses more than one
billion times that of the Sun _ appear to develop only in
elliptically shaped galaxies with dense central bulges of stars.
Pure disk-shaped galaxies, like the neighboring Messier 33, have no
observable black holes. And galaxies with only small bulges, like
the Milky Way, Earth's home galaxy, have relatively small black
holes of a few million solar masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, we can put strong constraints on the
relationship between galaxy formation and black hole formation and
growth,'' said Dr. John Kormendy of the University of Texas at
Austin, a member of an international team of astronomers that
reported the new findings Monday at a meeting in Rochester of the
American Astronomical Society.
</P>
<P>
   The team announced the discovery of eight more supermassive
black holes in galactic centers, based on observations by the
Hubble telescope's newly installed spectrograph. Although the
objects themselves cannot be detected because no radiation escapes
their gravity, their presence can be inferred by measuring the
velocities of disks of gas trapped in the clutches of black holes,
like water swirling around a drain. At least 33 such objects have
now been observed.
</P>
<P>
   Kormendy and colleagues, Dr. Karl Gebhardt of the University of
California at Santa Cruz and Dr. Douglas Richstone of the
University of Michigan, said that the correlations between galaxy
structures and black hole masses were important clues to how the
galaxies formed and the source of energy to make quasars shine.
Quasars, the brightest lights in the distant universe, are the
radiating signatures of matter plunging into the black hole and
feeding its growth at the center of a young galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main events that made a galaxy and the ones that made its
black hole shine as a quasar are the same events,'' Kormendy said.
</P>
<P>
   Such behavior, the scientists explained, appears to be most
violent in galaxies and most productive of black holes where
primordial hydrogen gas collapses into a dense central bulge around
a small compact core of matter, a ``seed'' black hole. The
observations so far have yielded no clues to how the seed black
holes originated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team will try to solve this mystery in the coming year by
looking for the smallest nuclear black holes that we can find with
Hubble,'' Richstone said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing the new findings, scientists have identified two other
ways in which galaxy evolution possibly affects black hole
development. Even though regular disk galaxies do not appear to
harbor massive black holes, if two disk galaxies with small black
holes collide, the merger would produce an elliptical galaxy with
conditions feeding the appetites of growing black holes. Also, in
some cases, gas flowing to the center of a disk galaxy could
gradually create a ``pseudo bulge,'' as opposed to a primordial
bulge, where a black hole could accumulate mass.
</P>
<P>
   Gebhardt notes that the more massive black holes dwell in
galaxies where the stars move especially fast, even the ones far
beyond the gravitational influence of the black hole. He said this
was strong evidence that the host galaxy underwent a tremendous
collapse in its earliest stages. So the mass of a black hole may
tell a lot about its history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
