<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HOTEL-SHOPPING-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTELS GO RETAIL (NEED A BED?) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 11)  
 By TERRY TRUCCO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long ago, guests had to leave their hotel rooms and venture
into stores to shop. But these days, some of the finest hotels
offer guests the chance to shop without getting out of bed. If you
can't live without the pillow-top mattress you slept on last night,
or the ice bucket, or the big black desk chair _ they're all for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   For years, hotels have sold small items like monogrammed
bathrobes and towels to guests who wanted to take home more than
memories. Such sales were largely defensive. ``Anything with a
little pizazz would disappear unless there was a sign attached that
said it was for sale,'' said James Eyster, a professor emeritus at
the Cornell University School of Hotel Management.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, hotels have become retailers on a grander scale.
It's no longer unusual to find a price list on the bedside table.
The polite prevention of theft is a big reason for the trend,
particularly at boutique hotels stocked with stylish toys. At the
Mondrian in Los Angeles, a card states that amenities are to be
enjoyed ``during your stay'' and includes a price list should the
trash can ($16) or the alarm clock ($32) prove irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   But old-fashioned marketing is behind the newest wave of hotel
retailing. No one has taken the concept further than the
two-year-old W hotel chain, which publishes a catalog of more than
25 room items, from a $55 chenille throw pillow to an $18
silver-plated yo-yo.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Fatino, vice president of brand design and development,
said she selected amenities for the hotels' high-style rooms with
two goals in mind. ``We wanted to create an entire environment in
each hotel and to make the guest think how great it would be to
have the hotel experience at home.'' A former buyer for Pottery
Barn, Fatino recalled how she and her retailing colleagues often
picked up ideas for merchandise at boutique hotels in Europe and
Asia. ``At W, we're doing the reverse and selling the items
ourselves,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   So far, catalog sales have been solid but unspectacular; for the
first quarter of the year, W sold $20,000 worth of bedding products
from the catalog. But of course the objects also help publicize the
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Large-scale hotel retailing began quietly with mattresses and
bedding. Last year 2,000 guests at Four Seasons hotels asked to buy
the custom Sealy mattresses the hotels use. The New York Palace has
shipped its Sealy mattresses as far away as Singapore. By marketing
its new Simmons mattress, pillows and sheets aggressively with
cards and an 800 number, the Westin hotel group sells three beds a
day on average.
</P>
<P>
   Large chains are in an excellent position to become retailers,
Eyster said. ``When you're buying something at a good volume, it's
not a problem to tag an order on and sell to the public.'' Volume
buying can make the price agreeable. This fall Wyndham Hotels and
Resorts plans to sell the Herman Miller Aeron desk chairs used in
their refurbished rooms for less than the suggested retail price.
</P>
<P>
   Staying in a hotel that sells furnishings allows guests to live
with items before they buy them. ``What better way to test a
mattress than to sleep on it for a night in a hotel?'' said Eyster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
