<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, June 6. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   UKRAINE-ECON (Kharkiv, Ukraine) _ Nearly a decade after
independence, Ukraine's decision to go along with the United States
and break a deal with Russia over an Iranian power station is
emblematic of a lament frequently expressed in this city: that
Ukraine's agenda for growth and economic development in the
post-Soviet era never seems to be as important as the strategic
objectives of the United States and its Western allies. By Patrick
E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EUROPE (Moscow) _ President Clinton addressed Russia's
Parliament Monday, urging its elected deputies to choose wisely in
determining their country's future _ both at home and in its
relationships with the rest of the world. In a 45-minute long
speech in the vast, austere Parliament building, Clinton struggled
to navigate a difficult course. He encouraged Russia to make the
political and economic reforms necessary to become what he called a
``modern, strong, democratic nation,'' but tried not to sound
bossy. By Elaine Sciolino and Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EUROPE-UKRAINE (Kiev) _ President Leonid Kuchma of
Ukraine used the occasion of a brief visit by President Clinton
Monday to announce that the Chernobyl nuclear power station will be
closed by Dec. 15. Following Kuchma's announcement to close the
plant, the site of the world's worst the worst radiation accident
in history, Clinton pledged $78 million in American aid to help
Ukraine pay for the construction of a $750 million ``sarcophagus
project'' that will reconstruct and stabilize the structure that
covers the ruined reactor. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ITALY (Rome) _ Russian President Vladimir Putin called on
the European Union and NATO Monday to join forces with Moscow and
set up a joint anti-missile shield, after talks here Monday with
Italian Prime Minister Giuliano Amato. ``This will avoid creating
problems linked to a imbalance in the equilibrium of forces and
ensure 100 percent the security of all European countries, with the
obvious involvement of our American partners,'' Putin told a press
conference. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-GRANDPARENTS (Washington) _ Declaring that parents have a
``fundamental right to make decisions concerning the care, custody,
and control'' of their children, the Supreme Court ruled Monday
that a Washington state law went too far in permitting a judge to
order visiting rights for grandparents over a mother's objection.
Without a rationale that could command a majority, the court
stepped cautiously and appeared intent on avoiding a
one-size-fits-all constitutional prescription for a world of
rapidly changing family dynamics. Consequently, the court stopped
short of declaring unconstitutional the Washington law _ one of the
broadest of the so-called ``grandparents' rights'' laws in terms of
permitting judicial intervention into family affairs _ and also of
giving concrete guidance for judging the constitutionality of the
variants that exist in the 49 other states. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-MEDIAONE (Washington) _ Clearing the final significant
regulatory obstacle to a corporate merger that will create the
nation's largest cable television, telephone and high speed
Internet company, the Federal Communications Commission on Monday
approved AT&AMP;T's acquisition of MediaOne after the companies agreed
to the sale of some of their assets. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-WOMEN (Undated) _ A federal agency has determined that
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. systematically discriminated
against women working in one of its divisions, opening the door for
lawsuits, and possibly a class action, against the firm. By Patrick
McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GRAND-CANYON (Undated) _ This summer more than one million
tourists will venture to the rim of the Grand Canyon and are likely
to feel their jaws drop as they gaze upon the world famous
spectacle: a vast wilderness of rocks, deep gorges and a mighty
river lost below cliffs, buttes and pinnacles festooned in pastel
shades of purple, orange, pink and green. Inevitably, some of these
visitors will turn to a park ranger and ask: ``How did the Grand
Canyon get formed? Why did this happen here and nowhere else?'' The
honest answer is that nobody knows. By Sandra Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3, and a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-THERAPY (Denver) _ Gene therapy burst into the news
last fall, when a teenager from Tucson died in an experiment at the
University of Pennsylvania. But while politicians and the press
have spent the year focusing on accusations of lax government
oversight and shoddily run clinical trials, the science of gene
therapy has been making quiet, steady progress. Little by little,
researchers say, they are finding new and better ways to deliver
genes to their target cells. Clinical trials of gene-based
treatments for hemophilia are showing promise, and certain cancer
patients appear to respond to gene therapy. And the field got a big
ego boost this spring when French scientists reported they had used
gene therapy successfully to treat babies born with defective
immune systems. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-ART (London) _ The British are nuts about their artists,
and by nuts I mean they are out of their minds. The condition shows
no sign of easing _ the reverse in fact, thanks to the Tate Modern,
a huge new engine of national self-congratulation spurring many
ancillary goings-on. Fresh galleries are suddenly open, including
another branch of the American dealer Larry Gagosian's empire.
American colonization betrays growing trans-Atlantic regard, a sure
sign of change. To be in London these days is to be endlessly
entertained by art, by the museums that show it, the multiplying
galleries that sell it and the masses who have become weirdly
fascinated by it. A journal by Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-LEWIS-TRIAL (Undated) _ Baltimore Rams linebacker Ray Lewis
pleads guilty to a misdemeanor count of obstructing justice and, in
exchange, murder charges are dropped against the player. The plea
agreement came as Lewis was standing trial for murder in Atlanta in
the stabbing deaths of two players outside a Super Bowl party last
January. Under the deal, Lewis was sentenced Monday to a year of
probation. What now has to be resolved is what penalties he will
face from the National Football League. By Thomas George.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT5,6.
</P>
