<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ADOPTION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NATURAL DRAMA OF ADOPTION FITS TV'S DESIGNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Near the end of the premiere episode of ``Time of Your Life,''
Sarah, the young, wide-eyed protagonist played by Jennifer Love
Hewitt, experienced something of an epiphany. On a Manhattan
subway, no less.
</P>
<P>
   Broke, homeless and totally alone in this city of 8 million
people, she couldn't think of a better moment to wipe clean her
slate and start a life makeover. Having come to New York to find
her birth father, and failed miserably, she figured she couldn't
rely on anyone but herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's my lifeline?'' she asked. ``Where do I make the
connection?''
</P>
<P>
   Creators of the series, which aired on Fox, used such questions
as a kind of metaphor for Sarah's ongoing search for self, and for
her severed family ties.
</P>
<P>
   Adoption has long proved a powerful dramatic lure, but never has
the subject turned up such fertile ground for narrative
storytelling as witnessed recently on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicity,'' ``Moesha,'' ``Oh Grow Up,'' ``The Smart Guy'' and
``ER,'' where viewers this past season learned that Dr. Kerry
Weaver (Laura Innes) is adopted, are only a few of the series that
have recently introduced plot lines involving adoption in some
form.
</P>
<P>
   Shows dealing with the hardships of adoption were rare just a
few years ago and unthinkable a generation ago. But adoption has
become a contentious, controversial issue recently _ and television
has used it to ratchet up its dramatic quotient and lure viewers.
For one thing, adoption, for years a closed process clouded by
stigmas and misconceptions, isn't nearly as secretive as it once
was. Now it's an infinitely more transparent experience supported
by various state laws prohibiting sealed adoption records. The
changes have allowed adoptees greater control over information that
affects their lives, while diminishing privacy rights of birth
parents and others involved in the process _ all of which has led
to heated public and legal debate on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   That has led to a spurt of television projects in which adoption
is a central theme. Beginning Tuesday, NBC launches ``M.Y.O.B.,'' a
single-camera sitcom focusing on 16-year-old Riley, who slipped
through the cracks of the foster-care system and onto the doorstep
of a high school principal named Opal, who may be the girl's birth
mother's sister.
</P>
<P>
   Such premises are tailor-made for hourlong drama, but they've
also shown up on sitcoms, where they've muted the lightheartedness,
providing an easily relatable way to show high drama and intense
emotions. On ``Moesha,'' for example, one character's nephew turned
out to be his son. Ray J. plays a street-wise teen-ager who learns
by mistake that his mother is really his aunt. He was the product
of an affair, and his father gave him up to the father's sister to
raise.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout has dramatically shifted the dynamics of this
comedy, making it one of the more tense sitcoms on the schedule,
and the season ended with no resolution.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Felicity,'' writers gave the character Julie (Amy Jo
Johnson) a complicated soap-opera scenario. She learns after
searching for and reuniting with her birth mother that her mom not
only married her birth father but also had two other children. In
the season finale, viewers are left hanging about whether Julie
will give a kidney to the dying birth father she's never met.
</P>
<P>
   J.J. Abrams, the co-creator of the series and writer of that
episode, said they never thought twice about delving deeply into
the schisms of adoption and exploring how abandonment issues
re-surface with adult adoptees. To make sure they were getting it
right, he says, they consulted adoption experts who read scripts
for emotional authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always knew that a story line involving self-discovery was
one we wanted to pursue since, in many ways, it parallels adoption
and being a college student away from home for the first time,''
says Abrams. ``Both can feel disoriented and alienated.''
</P>
<P>
   That parallel was never more evident than in an episode in which
Julie first sees her birth mother and is virtually paralyzed. Her
difficulty in revealing herself alternated with scenes of Keri
Russell's Felicity revisiting her artistic passion, but it was
Julie's story line that clearly carried more punch. To her credit,
Johnson has managed to play the scenes with a sense of excitement,
fear and bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that the psychological importance of being
adopted doesn't just stop when you grow up,'' says Johnson, who is
not adopted. ``It kind of lies waiting to take center stage at
various times. In my own research for that particular story line, I
found that one who is not grounded in his factual history won't
feel substantial, and talk of feeling bewildered and powerless and
without a firm sense of self. I just hope we're being true.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, television's portrayal of adoption has been spotty, and
has often been untrue to the real emotional dynamics at play in
families. Adoptee characters on TV are usually angry, cynical,
volatile people showing up unexpectedly at the doorstep of birth
parents who either didn't know about them or weren't all that
interested in seeing them in the first place. Adoptive parents are,
for the most part, nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   That happened in ``Oh Grow Up'' and ``M.Y.O.B.'' In the new NBC
series, Katharine Towne plays the adopted Riley as a know-it-all
who masks her emotional vulnerabilities by verbally abusing
everyone she comes in contact with, including her aunt and other
teachers and students at the school.
</P>
<P>
   During her final episodes on ``Party of Five,'' Hewitt's Sarah
would learn that her disenchantment with life and mild depression
were a result of her feeling, as she put it, ``exposed, abandoned,
rejected and unwanted,'' as a child of adoption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children who are adopted certainly have predictable and often
unspoken concerns about themselves and how they feel
disconnected,'' says Marietta Spencer, the former head of the Post
Adoption Department at Children's Home Society of Minnesota. ``So
seeing (that portrayed on TV) is hardly a crime. But if there are
errors committed by television, it's the way it makes all adoptees
seem like these lost souls who will never feel whole until they're
reunited with their birth parents. It's simply not true for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The language of adoption alone can be damaging, says Spencer. TV
has, for the most part, picked up words and phrases that show a
lack of understanding of adoption's intent. In the ``ER'' episode
when Dr. Weaver hires a private detective to find her birth mother,
references were constantly made about her ``real'' parents (as
opposed to ``birth'' parents) and that she ``was given away'' as
opposed to placed for adoption.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in a lot of ways, how can you fault something like
television?'' Spencer adds. ``Even in worldly cities, people still
say callous things to adoptive families. But the fact that these
shows are on the air and talking about it can only be better for
how people see and understand the adoption process, though that it
may become a trend to be exploited concerns me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817)390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
