<HEADLINE>
INMATE WEB SITES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies INMATES-INTERNET) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hundreds of inmates now have Web pages on which they ask for pen
pals, romance and, in some cases, money. If you plan to become a
pen pal with an inmate, here are some tips:
</P>
<P>
   1. Don't provide your home address or telephone number, at least
until you become acquainted with the inmate to whom you're writing.
</P>
<P>
   2. Contact the inmate's prison unit before you send anything
other than a letter. Different prison units have different rules.
Inmates typically cannot receive cash, anything metal, or
photographs that are sexually explicit or suggestive.
</P>
<P>
   3. Before you agree to send money to an inmate's legal defense
fund, check the court file to verify the information he or she
provided to you.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Here are some inmate Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   meet-an-inmate.com
</P>
<P>
   cyberspace-inmates.com
</P>
<P>
   outlawsonline.com
</P>
<P>
   lampofhope.org
</P>
<P>
   pennpals.org
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
