<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEMOCRATS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS GO TO CONVENTION TRYING TO REBUILD TEXAS PARTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It is just past noon in the back parlor at
Threadgill's, the Austin restaurant where former Texas Agriculture
Commissioner Jim Hightower broadcasts red-hot populism over the
airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of restaurant patrons, munching on corn bread, seem
not to notice that one of the last liberal Democrats to have held
statewide office in Texas is speaking into a microphone on a small
stage near the window.
</P>
<P>
   The headphone-wearing host of the ``Chat and Chew'' radio show
takes a call from a disillusioned former Democrat. Hightower
advises her to vote as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't stand for us, why do we stand for them?'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   The short answer to that question, in Texas anyway, is that
people are not standing up for Democrats at the polling place much
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   As the party of Lyndon Johnson prepares to conduct its state
convention in Fort Worth this week, no one argues that the
Democrats' grip on power in Texas is the weakest it has been since
Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The top Democratic statewide candidate is U.S. Senate hopeful
Gene Kelly, a perennial ballot box loser riding the popularity of
the late dancer whose name he shares. Kelly was not initially
offered a speaking role at the convention, and then declined a late
offer to address the crowd in Fort Worth. He has raised little
money for his race against Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   And after being wiped out in elections two years ago, Democrats
occupy no statewide office. Only the House of Representatives, with
four seats to spare, is controlled by Democrats and led by a
Democratic officeholder, House speaker Pete Laney of Hale Center.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats call it a ``rebuilding year'' in which they will focus
exclusively on legislative and congressional races at a time when
the state offices of governor down to land commissioner are not up
for grabs. The legislative contests are seen as crucial because
redistricting adjustments in 2001 could determine the partisan
balance of power for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic consultant Ed Martin said it makes sense to ignore
the statewide contests this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking at Kay Hutchison, who has already got enough
special interest money to make it difficult to beat her, so the
question is: Do you want to throw good money after bad?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the party is betting that the climate will
improve for Democrats statewide by 2002, when George W. Bush will
not be on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   But other Democrats complain that the party's woes have less to
do with what the Republicans are doing and more with their
self-inflicted wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many of our statewide candidates quit being Democrats,''
Hightower said. ``The result is that people who are naturally
inclined to vote for a party that stands for working families ...
that stands for old folks and children and family farmers, didn't
see the party flag flying for them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   THE `BATTLEGROUND PLAN': Democratic fortunes in statewide races
hit bottom in 1998, but some successes in the Legislature and
congressional races in recent years have bucked the trend.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democrats outnumber Republicans in the U.S. House, 17-13,
hold a four-seat advantage in the Texas House and have battled back
to being one seat shy of a majority in the Texas Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Behind those successes is the so-called ``Battleground Plan,''
which, according to one internal Democratic document ``is the sole
reason the Texas House of Representatives still has a Democratic
majority after the 1998 elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the program is to fund combined media campaigns and
get-out-the-vote efforts in ``battleground'' districts _ those that
are competitive. Without any heavyweight Democratic contenders
statewide this year, the battleground plan is the party's exclusive
focus.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan, or the nearly exclusive focus on it, is not
without critics.
</P>
<P>
   Though successful in protecting Democrats in swing districts,
such as U.S. Reps. Martin Frost of Dallas and Charles Stenholm of
Stamford, along with about two dozen state representatives and
senators around Texas, some complain that party leaders
aggressively ignore everything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're busy off trying to protect some moderate to conservative
Democrat somewhere from being beat by a Republican and spending no
time or effort in a huge part of Texas that is naturally
Democratic,'' said Ed Wendler, a longtime party operative and
Austin lobbyist. ``You can't win statewide if you don't run.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
