<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5203 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-TV-MYOB-SPI &LR;      06-05 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MYOB-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW COMEDY JUST A SEASONAL BURNOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The worst thing about ``M.Y.O.B.'' is that, at one point in the
hugely misanthropic proceedings, the main character has to explain
to us dullards what ``M.Y.O.B.'' means. Like most of the
alternative weeklies and trendoid magazines out there, it assumes
each of us has the IQ of a tuber and needs to be reminded regularly
that we're too unhip to walk the talk.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the worst thing about ``M.Y.O.B.'' might be that
Lauren Graham, who will someday find a show that makes her a big
star, is once again placed in a rickety vehicle that will soon
sputter into oblivion with other series like ``Conrad Bloom,''
``Townies'' and ``Good Company.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Graham, NBC knows ``M.Y.O.B.'' is a turkey and is
merely burning off the six episodes it ordered under the guise of
giving viewers fresh, new fare in the summertime. (Graham, a good
actress with the sort of expressive face made for TV, will reappear
this fall in ``Gilmore Girls,'' a new family friendly drama on The
WB.)
</P>
<P>
   In ``M.Y.O.B,'' she plays Opal Brown, a high school
administrator who we know is uptight because her clothes are. This
wouldn't be of any significance in the world of TV comedy, except
that the show itself bothers to mention it. When Opal kneels down
to administer CPR to the school's stricken principal, the main
character, a teen runaway named Riley Veatch, exclaims in just one
of her many too-precious voiceovers: ``Look at those skirts! Who
dresses her? Ally?''
</P>
<P>
   This sarcastic, TV-savvy patter is a large part of what Riley
(Katharine Towne) has to impart as she moves in with Opal, her
aunt, and expounds on all the foibles of the uptight world. The
rest is cynical, self-referential hoo-hah that's supposed to render
Riley the coolest thing since Skechers but insidiously works to
make her the most unsympathetic character this side of Dr. Evil.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one plank in Riley's manipulative platform of personal
philosophy: ``There's only one thing better than getting what you
want: getting what you want and pissing somebody off at the same
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about ``M.Y.O.B'' is that it offers helpful
hints, such as this one from Riley: ``I bet you were hoping this
wasn't going to be the typical TV show. But I mean, come on, it's
the whole fish-out-of-water, odd-couple, unrequited-love combo
platter you get most every night on every channel. So you don't
want to watch? Hey, that's OK. `Law &AMP; Order' is bound to be on
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank NBC for small favors.
</P>
<P>
   Odds 'n' ends
</P>
<P>
   The half-hour Hollywood satire, ``Action,'' which Fox gave up on
way too soon, returns this month on FX cable. FX will broadcast all
13 episodes, including five that never aired on Fox, starting June
20 at 10:30 p.m. ... ``Freaks and Geeks'' reportedly has found a
home at MTV, but, as is the case with ``Action,'' it's not likely
any new episodes will be filmed. ... Fans of the canceled ``Now &AMP;
Again'' are using Tuesday, the anniversary of D-day, as a rallying
point to send postcards en masse to CBS Entertainment president
Leslie Moonves, hoping he'll grant a reprieve. That CBS address,
once again, is 7800 Beverly Blvd., Los Angeles, CA 90036-2165. ...
KCTS/9 starts the 13th season of ``P.O.V.'' one of the best things
about summertime on PBS, Wednesday at 9 p.m. with ``Well-Founded
Fear,'' a documentary about seeking political asylum in the United
States and how the Immigration and Naturalization Service handles
these cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
