<HEADLINE>
BUSH DOES `DUTY,' PASSES HAT OUT WEST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Heading west last week, George W. Bush
continued to call for a reduction in nuclear arms. The Cold War is
over, he reminded folks.
</P>
<P>
   The political war, however, is very much alive, and Bush made it
abundantly clear that there would be no unilateral cutback in the
arms race between him and Vice President Al Gore, his likely
Democratic presidential opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor dragged the money sack with him through four
Western states, raising _ between issue-oriented events _ a
targeted $1.8 million for his campaign, the Republican National
Committee (to spend boosting his campaign) and state Republican
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Couples paid as much as $20,000 to meet and exchange small talk
with Bush at some of the receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush and Gore both have talked about the need for new
restrictions on campaign-finance activities, don't expect that to
be a priority issue for either candidate. The only goal they really
have at this point is to be elected president, and money is an
essential commodity in &QL; 
reaching it.
</P>
<P>
   At the rate they _ and President Clinton _ are going, every
political donor in the country may be picked clean before Election
Day.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year, Bush has raised more than $80 million, a
record, for his presidential race. The national Republican Party
also has raised at least that much in so-called ``soft money'' that
can be used to help elect Bush and other GOP candidates. And the
Democratic Party has raised $76 million, according to the most
recent reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure the campaign and local victory committees
prepare to conduct one of the most extensive grass-roots campaigns
in the history of American politics,'' Bush told reporters in
Denver, where he kicked off his western swing.
</P>
<P>
   As the presumptive head of the Republican ticket, he has an
obligation to his supporters and the GOP faithful to keep the
engine fueled, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet I'm doing my duty to make sure that those who are
willing to campaign by my side and campaign for me have got the
resources necessary to wage an effective battle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The West is important to Bush's presidential bid, and not only
as a source of campaign dollars. The region, he hopes, also will
help provide the electoral votes necessary for a Republican
recovery from Democrat Bill Clinton's back-to-back presidential
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton carried several Western states, including California,
the biggest electoral prize, in both 1992 and 1996. And California,
where Bush ended the week at a meeting of the Border Governors
Conference, will probably remain a huge obstacle for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush intends to actively compete there and in the region's
less populous states as well. And he did his best last week to make
Western voters feel at home with him. More than once, he pointed
out that Midland, his hometown, is in West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from the West,'' he said. ``People understand that I come
from a part of the world where individual initiative and individual
responsibility are part of the credo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize there's a role for government, but there's also a
healthy disrespect for what government can do,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of anti-big government message that has served
the governor so well in Texas, which, like the West, has a can-do,
up-by-the-bootstraps reputation with roots in the rough-and-tumble
frontier era.
</P>
<P>
   It also reflects a historical reality that has seen Texas lag
behind most other states in expenditures on education, health care
and social services important to people who don't even have boots,
much less the straps. It is a legacy that is bemoaned by many
Texans and has cost the governor some negative national publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Texas _ partly because of Bush and partly because of state
legislators from both parties _ is improving its record, and Bush
is quick to point that out in Texas, in the West and everywhere
else he campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's message, overall, is conservative, light on
governmental involvement and heavy on personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a philosophy that one has when you've been raised out in
the West,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also is betting it is a philosophy that, like his
fund-raising prowess, is not confined by geography.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
