<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5213 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-TEXAS-DEMOCRATS-2ndTa     06-05 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEMOCRATS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
AUSTIN, Texas: don't run.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1998, Wendler said he and a top aide to former Democratic
Comptroller John Sharp tried to persuade party leaders and
fund-raisers to fund an outreach program in traditionally
Democratic areas in South Texas and the inner cities _ to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp, who lost the lieutenant governor's race to Rick Perry by
68,000 votes of 3.7 million cast, said he directed several hundred
thousand dollars to drumming up support in nonbattleground areas _
but nobody else did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we had had more money to produce our vote, if we
had had an Hispanic on the ticket (maybe we'd be better off).
There's a lot of `ifs' on the thing, and it really doesn't do any
good to point fingers,'' Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   THE BUSH FACTOR: Although the politicians and their consultants
dream of what might have been, others suggest that Democrats are
losing elections because they either do not have a compelling
message or they have not been trying to aggressively sell one to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats have been basically messageless,'' said Ben
Barnes, a former lieutenant governor and still a loyal Democrat.
``If you've just got the governor selling and everybody else being
quiet, well, obviously the sentiment is not going to be there, the
pressure is not going to build.''
</P>
<P>
   Liz Chadderdon, a former spokeswoman for the Texas Democratic
Party, was more blunt. She said the party's legislators passed up
numerous opportunities to showcase their issues during the 1999
legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   She said Democrats allowed Bush to take credit for issues he
fought them on, including the Children's Health Insurance Program,
which the governor initially wanted to fund at a lower level than
Democrats did.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't another state in the country where Democrats would
have handed their issues to a Republican governor,'' Chadderdon
said. ``If they lose, they have no one to blame but themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Chadderdon's former boss, party Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm,
said Democrats are improving on the public relations front.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're encouraging our folks to do is go out and take
credit for what really did happen, and all you've got to do is look
at the record,'' she said. ``They're beginning to realize that
they've got to start talking about their accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   THE FUTURE: The drubbing Democrats took in 1998 has led many to
despair, but party operatives are optimistic not only about their
chances in the 2000 legislative and congressional races, but also
statewide races two years from now.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are quick to note that Bush beat their nominee, Garry
Mauro, by 1.4 million votes in 1998, but the races farther down the
ballot were squeakers by comparison. In other words, without Bush
on the ticket, they believe that it will be a more hospitable
climate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the question of how Democrats should position themselves
produces a predictable split along ideological lines.
</P>
<P>
   Liberals such as Hightower say the party should get back to its
populist roots, motivate ``working stiffs'' to vote and quit trying
to ``fish in the 20 percent pool _ the 20 percent who are doing
well, because that's who makes the campaign contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sharp, the former comptroller and a moderate who might run
again for lieutenant governor, said the road to victory is right
down the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This state is not a bunch of right-wing crazies any more than
it's a bunch of left-wing crazies,'' he said. ``The Democrats could
make a mistake, they could nominate a candidate on the left fringes
that would not be able to get money and not be able to get money
from the business community. ... There's got to be somebody the
business community feels comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Root is Austin bureau chief for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (512) 476-4294, or e-mail:
jroot(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
