<HEADLINE>
CHERNOBYL NUCLEAR POWER PLANT WILL CLOSE BY DEC. 15 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine _ President Leonid Kuchma of Ukraine used the
occasion of a brief visit by President Clinton on Monday to
announce that the Chernobyl nuclear power station will be closed by
Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   After Kuchma announced the closing of the Chernobyl plant, the
site of the world's worst radiation accident, Clinton pledged $78
million in U.S. aid to help Ukraine pay for the construction of a
$750 million project that will reconstruct and stabilize the
structure now covering the ruined reactor.
</P>
<P>
   The United States will also pay an unspecified amount for what
it calls a business incubator or economic development plan in
neighboring Slavutych, the city of 28,000 built in the 1980s to
house Chernobyl's corps of engineers. The aid will help offset the
dramatic economic impact the shut down of the plant is expected to
have on the local population.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the United States will give Ukraine an additional $2
million to improve safety at its four other nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine is the third-largest recipient of U.S. aid after Israel
and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aim of this decision is to reduce nuclear risks in the
world,'' Kuchma said after talking with Clinton. The decision, he
added, ``was not easy to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuchma made his announcement to reporters after the two leaders
met in the white-and-gilt splendor of the Mariinsky presidential
palace. Calling the decision historic, Clinton said, ``This is a
hopeful moment. It is also a moment when we remember those who
suffered as a result of the accident there.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The 1986 explosion and fire at Chernobyl, just 80 miles from
Kiev, killed 28 people outright with high radiation doses and
covered much of Europe with a radioactive cloud, causing untold
deaths and illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The sarcophagus, a hastily built concrete and steel structure
that encases the shattered reactor hall containing nearly 200 tons
of radioactive fuel, is now riddled with leaks and threatening to
crack open.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Ukrainians depend on the plant for jobs and
power, but even now, before Chernobyl is closed, Ukraine faces an
acute energy crisis.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kuchma had promised the group of leading industrialized nations
known as the Group of Eight that Ukraine would shut down the
plant's sole remaining working reactor by the end of the year if
they provided financial help. But until Monday he repeatedly
delayed setting a firm date, saying that Ukraine has not received
aid promised by the developing countries to finish two new nuclear
power plant reactors that were under construction in western
Ukraine before the Soviet Union collapsed. They are expected to
cost about $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration official who briefed reporters said
that Monday's announcement represented a significant shift in
Ukraine's position.
</P>
<P>
   In his announcement Monday, Kuchma said that Clinton had agreed
to solicit the other Group of Eight countries for help in
shouldering the costs. But with just eight months left in office,
it is not clear what Clinton can achieve.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to meeting with Kuchma, Clinton also delivered a
speech to tens of thousands of Ukrainians during his six-hour
stopover on the final leg of his last scheduled trip to Europe as
U.S. president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the oppressors are gone,'' Clinton said. ``Stalin is
gone. The Nazis are gone. But you, the people of Ukraine, you are
still here, stronger than ever!''
</P>
<P>
   ``You must build a free and prosperous Ukraine,'' he added. ``Do
not give up. Keep on fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the president's speech, administration officials
said, was to show concrete support for Ukraine's independence,
which came with the collapse of communism nine years ago after
three centuries of rule by Moscow.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The visit to Ukraine was also a brilliant photo opportunity that
Clinton seized to the fullest. He stood atop an outdoor dais and
waved to the crowd, turning to the north, south, east and west. The
gold-domed, wedgwood-blue St. Sophia Cathedral and the central
square decked with huge U.S. and Ukrainian flags served as a
picture-perfect backdrop on a picture-perfect day. The cathedral
was destroyed by the communists in the 1930s and its reconstruction
is still unfinished. It was blessed and inaugurated last week, just
in time for Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at a news briefing why Clinton did not mention the closing
of the Chernobyl plant in his speech, an administration official
said: ``It's Ukraine's reactor. There's a lot of emotional
sensitivity'' attached to the subject.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
