<HEADER>
A5234 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SPOLETO-S.C.-NYT &LR;      06-05 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOLETO-S.C.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: SALUTING FLEXIBILITY, IF NOT THE FLAG, AT
SPOLETO 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES R. OESTREICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Bill T. Jones is not dancing, but Nigel
Redden is. It has been that kind of year here at Spoleto Festival
USA.
</P>
<P>
   Redden, the festival's general director, has become quicker on
his feet since 1998, when he took over the Lincoln Center Festival,
too, only to become mired in an international flap over the Chinese
opera ``The Peony Pavilion'' when its troupe was detained in
Shanghai. It took him a year to snatch triumph from the jaws of
defeat there by presenting the opera with a newly assembled
company.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a star-crossed season at Spoleto, and Redden is
hopping. The first crisis was the growing controversy in recent
months over the Confederate battle flag that flies above the state
Capitol in Columbia. Several performers withdrew from the festival
in protest, including the Bill T. Jones/Arnie Zane Dance Company,
and would-be festivalgoers have boycotted in unknowable numbers.
Ticket sales, which were 17 percent ahead of last year in February,
are now 10 percent behind.
</P>
<P>
   But that figure reflects other factors as well, including a
second crisis: a severe spinal injury to the director of another
company, Antoine Rigot of the French circus troupe Les Colporteurs.
(A tightrope performer, he was injured off the job, while
swimming.) Redden acted quickly, bringing in David Dimitri, a
French performer known to the troupe. Nine of the 14 scheduled
performances will be lost, it appears, obviously affecting ticket
sales, but most of the troupe's planned run at the Lincoln Center
Festival next month is expected to take place.
</P>
<P>
   Redden's approach to the flag issue was necessarily subtler and
more multifaceted. Some of the boycotting performers were replaced.
And three thematic events were added, including an outdoor concert
on Friday and addresses and readings by Southern writers on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many, the flag controversy is behind us,'' Redden said,
``for better or for worse.'' The State Legislature has decided to
remove the flag on July 1 to a Confederate soldiers' monument on
the Capitol grounds, where a monument to black slaves is also to be
installed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the writers' session, in the Riviera at Charleston Place,
was impassioned. Kendra Hamilton, a black writer from Charleston,
tied together the recurring themes, challenging the familiar
argument that what is being upheld by the flag and similar symbols
is heritage rather than hate. ``Heritage slides very easily into
hate,'' Hamilton said. She advocated instead a shift from heritage
to history given a cold, hard look.
</P>
<P>
   The concert, in a lovely setting at the Cistern on the College
of Charleston campus, offered an inspiriting set of gospel songs by
the Brotherhood, a septet from nearby Mount Pleasant, S.C., and a
performance of Copland's ``Lincoln Portrait'' by Steven Sloane and
the festival orchestra, narrated by State Senator McKinley
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At least two of the scheduled musical events also spoke to the
notion of a changing epoch, whether or not tied to a dawning
century or millennium. The official festival concert, on Thursday,
offered the American premiere of ``Surrogate Cities,'' a sonic boom
of a symphony from 1994 by Heiner Goebbels, a pathbreaking German
composer. This work, everywhere amplified, draws much of its
driving energy from rock. It turns the symphony orchestra on its
head, so that percussion dominates; the brasses fill out the sound,
and strings and woodwinds often provide little more than local
color.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer exhilarating sonic assault, heavy with sampling and
with vocal effects that could pass for it (or for percussion), is
barely suggested in a new recording from ECM (which of course also
forgoes the visual assault of spotlights repeatedly searching the
stage and the audience). It gave one listener a first sense of what
it must have been like to hear a big Mahler symphony a century ago,
with the whole notion of sonic possibility expanded at a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   This basic texture made all the more striking the isolated
moments of conventional beauty, like the old recording of a
haunting cantorial song, gently lifted, as it were, out of the
rubble. Or rubble it seemed. Literary meaning is elusive in this
work, with inspiration from Kafka and dimly scrutable texts by Paul
Auster and others, and the program book afforded little help.
</P>
<P>
   That sense of finding jewels amid rubble was enhanced by the
setting, the Memminger Auditorium, an old building abandoned after
Hurricane Hugo blew its roof off in 1989 and partly restored for
the purpose. Here was an opportunity for Charleston, so immersed in
its ancient history (not to say heritage), to reconnect with its
more recent history as well. The performance by Sloane and the
festival orchestra was a knockout, at times almost literally, and
David Moss supplied most of those remarkable vocal effects.
</P>
<P>
   The other work that conveyed a sense of epochal change was far
more modest: Bright Sheng's opera ``Silver River,'' which had its
premiere in 1997 at the Santa Fe Chamber Music Festival. Sheng uses
an ancient Chinese folk myth ``of a perfect `heavenly love' that
can exist even between different species,'' in his words, as a
metaphor for a sort of ultimate Wagnerian Gesamtkunstwerk, unifying
theater with opera, both Western and Chinese. David Henry Hwang's
deft libretto turns precious at times. The music seldom does. Sheng
proves remarkably successful at juxtaposing Asian and Western
idioms in more or less ``pure'' forms. With due respect to several
wonderful performances on Friday evening, especially those of Karen
Kandel as the Golden Buffalo and Jamie Gwan as the Jade Emperor, it
was wondrous to hear the romance between David Fedele's flute and
Wu Man's pipa.
</P>
<P>
   Notable among other events attended was Moshe Leiser and Patrice
Caurier's production of Gluck's ``Iphigenie en Tauride'': notable
on Saturday, it turned out, mainly for its dreariness, in its
strained gestures of stock pity, terror or dementia, and in the
often mistuned playing of the orchestra, again with Sloane
conducting. In fairness, there were vocal consolations, especially
the ringing Pylade of Tracey Welborn, and the rest of the audience
seemed content.
</P>
<P>
   The festival runs until Sunday, when Redden can begin training
for his next dance, at Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
