<HEADLINE>
FCC APPROVES AT&AMP;T'S ACQUISITION OF MEDIAONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Communications Commission on Monday
approved AT&AMP;T's acquisition of MediaOne, clearing the way for a
corporate merger that will create the nation's largest cable
television, telephone and high speed Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   In eliminating the final significant regulatory obstacle to the
merger, the commission gave the companies a choice of which
programming and cable assets they would need to sell to come within
the regulation that forbids any corporation from having interests
in more than 30 percent of the nation's cable market. The
commission had estimated that the combined companies, without any
divestitures, would control more than 40 percent of the industry.
The companies have agreed to sell some assets.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger was valued at $58 billion when it was
announced a year ago during a wave of consolidation in the
telecommunications and high-speed Internet markets. Those deals
have posed a particular challenge for antitrust regulators because
of the complex interlocking ownership interests between cable
operators, programmers and high-speed Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Both Time Warner, which will now become the nation's
second-largest cable operator, and AT&AMP;T have shared interests in
the same high-speed Internet and programming companies.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago the Justice Department's antitrust division
approved the merger after the companies agreed to sell each of
their interests in Road Runner, the nation's second-largest cable
Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC went further Monday, ordering another round of
divestitures to bring the merged company into compliance with a law
that says only mergers found to be in the public interest will be
approved.
</P>
<P>
   The commission decided to give AT&AMP;T and MediaOne a year to
choose from three options to meet the 30 percent limit. They could
sell their interest in the Liberty Media Group, a programming
company that AT&AMP;T acquired an interest in when it bought
Tele-Communications Inc. last year. They could sell MediaOne's 25
percent interest in Time Warner Entertainment, a programming and
cable operating company. Or they could sell enough individual cable
systems around the nation to bring down their share of the market
to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives have not said how they would comply with the
order. They have said they hope to close the deal later this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups were critical of Monday's decision, saying that
it did not go far enough in preventing AT&AMP;T from controlling the
rapidly growing cable marketplace. They said the commission
appeared to have caved in to special interests and that the
regulators should have used the deal to force the companies to open
their Internet network to competing service providers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
