<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET YIELDS MAJOR JOB GAINS FOR U.S. FIRMS
 &HT;    430&AMP;add. Moving in the (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The sizzling Internet economy, on track to top $850
billion in revenue this year, is beginning to yield major
productivity gains for the nation's employers, University of Texas
researchers found in a study released Tuesday (cq).
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to productivity, digital companies are leading
the nation's economic performance,'' Andrew Whinston, director of
the Center for Research on Electronic Commerce at the university's
Graduate School of Business, said in an interview here.
</P>
<P>
   The 82-page report, the latest semi-annual survey on the overall
state of Internet commerce was co-authored by Anitesh Barua, the
center's associate director.
</P>
<P>
   It found that revenue per employee, a key measure of
productivity, rose by 19 percent from 1998
</P>
</TEXT>
