<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5248 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-GEORGIA-0606-C     06-05 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GEORGIA-0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GEORGIA, UTAH COPS GET LOOK AT THE HOLY, AND HIGH-SECURITY, LAND
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ They took in the history of the walled Old City, but
from a police overlook and through the monitors of surveillance
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen Georgia and Utah law enforcement officials visited
Jerusalem Monday as part of a two week Georgia State University
exchange program to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Featuring discussions on counter-terrorism, bomb disposal, drug
interdiction and common police practices, the program offers the
Utah officials a hand in preparing for the 2002 Winter Olympics in
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   They saw the command center where Israeli police watch monitors
from the more than 200 surveillance cameras that keep an eye on the
Old City. The Old City, predominantly Arab but also with Israeli
Jews and Armenians, is a tangle of tiny bazaar-filled streets and
some of the holiest sites in Islam, Judaism and Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   The group visited the Western Wall, sacred to Jews. But, they
descended to it from a police station where paramilitary Israeli
police overlook both the wall and the Dome of the Rock mosque,
sacred to Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   For the visitors, Israel's constant state of high security was
clear. While public surveillance and spot searches might put off
Americans, Israelis have learned to live with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Israel take security seriously because they depend
on it for their existence,'' said Tommy Tomlinson, a Georgia State
Patrol commander from Milledgeville. ``In the states, we often take
it for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson was on duty at Atlanta's Centennial Park in 1996 when
it was the scene of the Olympics bombing.
</P>
<P>
   This is the eighth annual trip through the university's
Department of Criminal Justice. The program was started by
department chairman Robert Friedmann(cq), who grew up in Israel.
Several groups of Israelis have also come to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Dearden, Utah commissioner of public safety, said many of
the techniques used by the Israelis were in use during the Atlanta
Olympics. But, he said the trip gives him a chance to see them in
different environments and with time-tested improvements.
</P>
<P>
   For example, motion-detecting fences were activated too
frequently in Atlanta, sending police scurrying on false alarms.
But the Israelis have meshed them with camera networks that can be
used to see if the alarms are real.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli bomb disposal experts discussed the threats they face
from bomb-making instructions now on the Internet. The U.S.
delegation also saw an Israeli-made computer program for
coordinating law enforcement during a large-scale crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The trip is primarily paid for by Georgia Power Company and
Dante's Down the Hatch jazz club in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kaplow can be contacted at LarryK(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   On the web, see the Georgia State University Department of
Criminal Justice web site at www.cjgsu.net
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
