<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, June 6, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A cool rain will fall over most of the Northeast on Tuesday as
low pressure moves off the Middle Atlantic coast. The heaviest rain
in the day is expected near the east slopes of the central
Appalachians where moist winds ascend the sloping terrain. Rain
amounts of more than an inch will be common in the interior
Northeast by early Wednesday. Farther west, rain will gradually end
from the eastern Ohio Valley and Great Lakes to the west slopes of
the Appalachians, but clouds will linger most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Drier air will spread over the Southeast in the wake of a cold
front. Despite plentiful sunshine, afternoon temperatures will stay
several degrees below seasonal levels. In the humid air ahead of
the front, scattered thunderstorms will bring needed rain to
drought-plagued areas of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Plains will be warmer than recent days as breezes from the
south develop. Sunshine and heat will persist in the interior West.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: MODERN CHILL
</P>
<P>
   Record-low temperatures for June 5 were reached at several
places across the upper Midwest early Monday. In Duluth, Minn.,
where record-keeping began in 1870, mercury in the official
thermometer plunged to 32 degrees, tying the daily record. Monday's
chill is made more impressive when it is considered that to set
record minimums, modern air masses generally must be colder than
their 19th-century counterparts records because of the local
heating effects caused by urban growth. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
