<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5256 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-05 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ALL GRIDLOCK, ALL THE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The other morning a radio traffic reporter
looked down on Highway 101 south of San Francisco and reported that
traffic was at a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no accident,'' he said. ``There are just too many
cars.''
</P>
<P>
   The economy is booming, so there are more jobs paying more money
to buy more cars.
</P>
<P>
   Every townhouse built in the suburbs means two more cars on the
road. Every family that can afford to live in San Francisco can
afford their two cars, too. I once saw a whole family of newcomers
proudly drive out of San Francisco Honda with their own fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Cars are a symbol of being American, so why not? As a car-lover
since my father bought his brand-new '49 Ford, I can't condemn
cars, despite the traffic misery and pedestrian deaths and injuries
they have caused.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, contrary to that traffic reporter, I think there aren't
enough cars and the traffic jams aren't long enough.
</P>
<P>
   The count of vehicles registered in San Francisco increased from
445,691 in 1998 to 453,905 in 1999. Not counting the cars of
commuters, that's 8,000 new vehicles on the streets in just one
year. That's not enough.
</P>
<P>
   People think they can actually get somewhere in these things.
And they must be constantly trying to get somewhere, because in San
Francisco there are three cars for every two parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   If there were many more cars, people would at least give up
circling the block looking for that mythical space.
</P>
<P>
   If there were many more cars and traffic jams, nothing would
move except for walkers, bicyclists and the public transit that
would have to be expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, I'm not some goody-two shoes, NPR-listening hater of
internal combustion engines. I'm a driver and a motorcycle
aficionado (who wised up), but I'm also a bicyclist and a walker.
</P>
<P>
   The internal combustion I worry about is the kind I feel when I
drive, when I think I can actually get somewhere, and a little
faster than the next guy. A lot of drivers feel that way.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic, the parking and the madness aren't bad enough yet.
Everything will have to come to a complete stop before people turn
road rage into a demand for rational transportation planning.
</P>
<P>
   If we must have a Manhattanized downtown, let's have
Manhattanized transportation. You can still get across San
Francisco much faster by car than you can by public transit, even
if there's nowhere to park when you get there.
</P>
<P>
   The driving is just frustrating enough, though, that it pushes
people to speed, run red lights and ignore crosswalks. They're
killing and injuring pedestrians at a record rate.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the driving is not frustrating enough to bring
the cars to a complete halt.
</P>
<P>
   You hear a lot of baloney about San Francisco being a
``world-class city.'' Come on.
</P>
<P>
   There is no world-class city in the world where anyone expects
to get anywhere by car. They all have world-class mass transit.
They're all world-class walking cities.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco used to be one of the best walking cities in the
world, but now it's a city where walkers are in a free-fire zone
every time they step off a curb.
</P>
<P>
   When I moved here 25 years ago, you could put a foot into a
crosswalk without looking and the cars would screech to a stop. No
horns, no obscene gestures, just smiles from the drivers.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? The number of people stayed the same, and the
number of cars almost doubled. Rents and the pace of life went New
York on us.
</P>
<P>
   Last week two children were hit and injured while crossing a
street with their Montessori school teacher and classmates. The
director of the school, Roger Satterfield, described the current
mental state of the city as ``the adrenaline-panicked life.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a great phrase. Adrenaline panic drives us at work, and we
drive to and from work in adrenaline panic. The adrenal glands
drive us to fight or flight, and we're flying and fighting all at
once on the roads.
</P>
<P>
   The right turn on red has become part of the downfall of San
Francisco's civilization. It's now performed at full speed right
through pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   I say abolish the right turn on red entirely. That's just one
little thing San Francisco could do to restore civility in the
streets. That would slow traffic down, especially at crosswalks.
</P>
<P>
   The slower the better. A standstill, the best.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
