<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 11) 
 By JOSEPH SIANO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Diamond Hunt
</P>
<P>
   Q. A few years back, I was watching a TV show about gems that
mentioned a state park in the South that was open to the public for
diamond hunting. Do you know where it is? _ Patti Winston, Savage,
Minn.
</P>
<P>
   A. Your fortune may await you at Crater of Diamonds State Park,
on Route 27 near Murfreesboro in southwestern Arkansas. It is 120
miles from Little Rock (not a very encouraging name for a diamond
hunter _ but, on a more positive note, not too far from a place
called Hope). Open daily except Thanksgiving, Christmas and New
Year's. Hours are 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. most days, and to 8 p.m. May 26
to Sept. 3; (870) 285-3113, fax (870) 285-4169.
</P>
<P>
   The diamond-search area is a 36.5-acre field of diamond-bearing
soil called lamporite. Weather permitting, the soil is plowed
routinely to make it easier to sift through. Tickets to search for
diamonds are $4.50, $2 ages 6 to 12, and can be bought at the
visitor center; they are good only on the day of purchase, unless
bought after 6 p.m. Park officials say you can sometimes find
diamonds on the surface, so tools aren't required. But you can
bring digging tools (nothing with a motor on it), buy a small
trowel or cultivator for $1.37 each at the park, or rent larger
shovels and soil-sifting screens.
</P>
<P>
   There are 60 campsites in the park, all with water and
electrical hookups, and they cost $13.50 a night. Two bathhouses
contain hot showers and modern restrooms. Except for holiday
weekends, the park says, reservations usually aren't necessary.
</P>
<P>
   What are your chances of walking out of the park looking as if
you're ready for the Oscar presentations? The first diamonds were
found on the property in 1906, a 3-carat white diamond and
1.5-carat yellow diamond. Soon after, the owner sold the land for
$36,000 and a diamond rush quickly followed. From 1907 to the late
1930's, several commercial mining operations were tried on the
80-acre deposit, and all failed. Since 1949, the site has been
operated as a tourist attraction, with the state taking over in
1972.
</P>
<P>
   The largest stone ever found at the site was the Uncle Sam
diamond, mined commercially in 1924. The white diamond weighed
40.23 carats rough and was cut into an emerald-shaped stone of
12.42 carats. The largest one found since it became a state park
was 16.37-carat rough white diamond, cut into a marquise of 7.54
carats. In 1998, a 7.28-carat white diamond was found by a woman
searching the surface of the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Point and Click
</P>
<P>
   Q. In the fall, my wife and I plan to visit five Asian
countries, including Japan. I usually try to brush up on the local
language, but not this time. I have heard of a little pocket-size
folder with pictures on it that you can point to in order to be
understood. Is it polite to use these? And if so, where can I get
them? _ Joel Peck, Morganville, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. Although we've been taught it's not polite to point, Japan is
a country where many restaurants keep plastic models of various
dishes on display so customers can point to what they want. So keep
that index finger limber.
</P>
<P>
   Langenscheidt Publishers sells foreign-language phrase cards.
Each one packs about 200 phrases on a pocket-size laminated card.
They come in several languages, including Japanese and Filipino,
and cost $1.99 each from Hagstrom Map and Travel Center, 57 West
43rd Street, New York, N.Y. 10036; (212) 398-1222 or (800)
432-6277.
</P>
<P>
   The Hagstrom store also sells two folding guides with
pictographs for $5.95 each. One, by Langenscheidt, is in a small
book form. The other is a laminated folding card.
</P>
<P>
   And the Japan National Tourist Organization, (212) 757-5640,
offers two free aids. ``Tourist Language Handbook'' has 17 pages
with phrases in English and Japanese; ``Hello, Japan'' contains 100
pages of pictograms, travel tips and points of etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Jazz
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be returning to Kansas City, Mo., this summer for my
50th high school reunion. While there, I want to hear live jazz. Do
you know of any clubs I can go to? _ Jerome Evans, South Lake
Tahoe, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. John Niccum, the music editor of Pitch Weekly, a free
newspaper in Kansas City with extensive arts listings, says that on
most nights, there are about a dozen clubs and restaurants in the
city with live jazz. He suggested four clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Club Mardi Gras, at 19th and Vine, (816) 842-8463, is in the
10th and Vine Historic District. The original jazz club at that
site, also called the Mardi Gras, opened in 1929, and various jazz
clubs have operated there on and off ever since. There's music on
Friday and Saturday nights from 9 p.m. to 1 a.m. with  $3 cover
and no minimum. Fridays are usually reserved for traditional Kansas
City jazz, with Saturday given over to the blues. Groups are
usually four to seven pieces. One wall is decorated with the
original 1929 mural depicting a Mardi Gras parade. Louisiana-style
food is served.
</P>
<P>
   Two blocks from the convention center, the Majestic Steakhouse,
931 Broadway, (816) 471-8484, is in the basement of a restaurant.
Live jazz is presented nightly, with swing and bebop the
specialties. Music starts 6:30 weeknights, 7 p.m. Friday and
Saturday and 5 p.m. Sunday, and usually stops at 10:30 to 11 p.m.
There is no cover or minimum. The building, dating from 1910, is on
the National Register of Historic Places, and it has tile floors
and tin ceilings. You can eat at the restaurant upstairs or in the
jazz club, and a cigar club occupies the third floor.
</P>
<P>
   For a more intimate setting, try the Phoenix Piano Bar and
Grill, 302 West Eighth St., (816) 472-0001. Swing jazz and blues
are the preferred forms here, with four- to five-piece groups the
norm. Music is offered Monday to Saturday, usually until 1 a.m.,
but if you want a seat, the owners suggest you get there by 6 p.m.
Besides table seating (pasta, steak and seafood are on the menu),
you can sit at the bar or around the piano. There is no cover
charge or minimum.
</P>
<P>
   The Club at Plaza 3, 4749 Pennsylvania Ave., (816) 753-0000, is
in the Country Club Plaza. This is a steakhouse, with the music
presented on the lower level Wednesday through Saturday.
Performances start at about 7 p.m. Wednesday and Thursday and 8:30
p.m. Friday and Saturday and last about four hours. Weeknights
typically feature three-piece groups with larger groups (up to 11
musicians) on weekends. Dinner is available, and there is
cocktail-table seating, too. The $5 cover charge is waived if you
order dinner; there's no minimum.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
