<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5261 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FRUITWORKS-AD-COLUMN-     06-05 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRUITWORKS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: PEPSI TAKES LOW-KEY APPROACH TO MARKETING FRUITWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Blockbuster TV commercials. Glitzy news conferences.
Celebrity endorsers. The Pepsi-Cola Co. is practically synonymous
with this kind of big-league national marketing tactics.
</P>
<P>
   So it's somewhat odd that Pepsi's FruitWorks, a juice-based
noncarbonated drink that will compete with brands like Triarc
Beverage Group's Snapple and Coca-Cola Co.'s Fruitopia, is being
introduced nationally this month with comparatively little fanfare.
And it's deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   The soft drink giant has decided the best way to ingratiate
FruitWorks with the ever-fickle youth market is through grass-roots
marketing programs that it hopes will create a word of mouth allure
and hip personality for the new brand. While grass-roots marketing
has always been a part of selling brands at Pepsi, this time it is
the marketing plan, explained Robin Kaminsky, Pepsi's director of
alternative beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi is going this route after its vast research _ this is the
company that invented the Pepsi generation _ indicated that not
mass marketing, but very specific promotions and TV commercials
made especially for young people is the best way to establish
awareness for its new brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to talk to our target is not through mass
marketing, but through the kinds of one-on-one marketing that our
plan is about: linking with our target and talking to them the way
they want,'' said Kaminsky.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy to reach teen-agers 15 to 24, but as young as 12,
relies on an entertainment-oriented Web site, a sampling program
and a national promotion starting in July with MTV's ``Total
Request Live,'' a popular hit-countdown show.
</P>
<P>
   Central to its strategy of reaching computer-savvy kids is its
Web site, created by DDB Digital, a unit of Omnicom Group. Steven
Marrs, DDB Digital's chief operating officer, said the agency knows
from its experience as the creator and manager of pepsiworld.com
that today's youth are almost hard-wired to reject direct pitches
that dictate what is or is not cool. Instead, he said, the
challenge was to offer a Web site in which young people help to
create ``the personality and tonality of the brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've learned is that these kids are not like everyone
else, they are not ones to be marketed to and they have a desire to
go out and create their own space in world,'' said Marrs. ``So we
work with them to build the brand, and give expression of who they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site features a ``music maker,'' where kids can make
their own sounds and a place to create your own cartoon
frame-by-frame including word bubbles. Both can then be sent as an
e-mail message to friends _ which is a way for Pepsi to spread the
word about FruitWorks. The site began Feb. 8 and through May 22 had
102,000 different visitors, according to DDB Digital research.
</P>
<P>
   ``In talking to this market, it's important to be cool, but you
can't just say `we're cool,' explained Steve Hicks, DDB Digital's
creative director. ``We actually created a space where kids can go
and express themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The FruitWorks promotion with MTV is also an un-commercial.
FruitWorks simply tries to be hip by association. For example, two
spots that will air only on MTV are about TRL's fanatical fans who
line up daily outside MTV's Times Square studios in New York where
the program is broadcast live. FruitWorks is sponsoring the
program's first home video release, and is running a national
consumer sweepstakes where the grand prize is a visit to MTV
studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made sense in a big way to tap into the Zeitgeist of TRL,
and not so literally be a commercial,'' said John Shea, MTV's
senior vice president of strategic programming.
</P>
<P>
   That the promotion was created by MTV's in-house commercial
division is unusual in itself. Big corporations typically assign an
ad agency of record before advertising on a brand begins. But Pepsi
decided from the start to do this differently, and so far there
hasn't been a need for a classic ad agency relationship. Still,
Pepsi's longtime agency, BBDO Worldwide, is working on media
planning and buying, Kaminsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi expects FruitWorks to be a top 5 brand in its first year
on the market, and that so far sales are 50 percent above its
projections, said Kaminsky.
</P>
<P>
   FruitWorks is late to market. Fruit beverages sold in
single-serve bottles had its fastest growth in the early 1990s with
the proliferation of so-called new-age beverages, led by the
phenomenal early success of Snapple iced teas and fruit drinks,
said Gary Hemphill, vice president of information services at
Beverage Marketing Corp., a New York-based research firm. Coke
introduced Fruitopia, in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The market has since slowed, and last year grew about 7 percent
to $2.2 billion, Hemphill said. He said Snapple is still the
leader, with a 12.4 percent share, but Fruitopia is fast-growing,
with 8.5 percent of the market. In comparison, the carbonated
beverage market was flat at about $40 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company's lack of big advertising dollars behind
the brand has not been lost on its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are taking a low-key approach and it's just a
product that some of their bottlers need to fill up some accounts
to try to compete with new-age beverages,'' said Mike Weinstein,
Triarc's CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Snapple has become known for its grass-roots marketing and wacky
``best stuff on earth'' advertising, first with salesclerk Wendy as
spokeswoman and more recently with national TV commercials that
feature fruit come to life (which are actually actors in costumes
as bananas and peaches) to underscore that Snapple is all natural.
The newest campaign created by Deutsch, New York, shows Snapple
fruits at a health spa where they get in shape with gym equipment
and are ``randomly'' tested for preservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But with Pepsi's powerful distribution system FruitWorks'
potential cannot be underestimated. Hemphill said he believes Pepsi
aims to do in the juice-based category what it did in the iced tea
market. Snapple created that category with its all-natural iced
teas back in the 1980s, but it was overtaken by Lipton several
years ago. Lipton Iced Tea is marketed by the Pepsi-Lipton Tea
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Pepsi, it's really about their distribution system _ that
sets them apart from the competition,'' said Hemphill. ``I think
this gives FruitWorks an excellent opportunity to be successful.
You'll see it almost everywhere you see Pepsi-cola products.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
