<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5265 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     06-05 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADVxx-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING HIS HAND AT SPAM HAIKUS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because I work at home with no adult supervision, I spend a good
part of the day browsing the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of worthwhile, educational things on the Internet
and it took me some time to learn how to avoid those and find the
stuff I was really interested in, such as trash, smut and other
things of no practical value.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, you don't have to search too long to find this
stuff. The Internet is many things to many people, but at its core
it's a haven for lonely guys with far too much time on their hands.
Why Al Gore wanted to claim invention of this thing is beyond me.
</P>
<P>
   I realize that some of you may be intimidated or bewildered by
things having to do with computers and that is certainly
understandable. The media has done a poor job explaining the new
technology, possibly because they don't understand it themselves. I
followed the Microsoft antitrust case for months and I'm still not
entirely clear what it was all about. Something having to do with
``browser,'' who I thought was the guy from Sha Na Na with the
really deep voice.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality is that while computers themselves are
complicated and expensive and more unreliable than a Chevy Corvair
(If someone runs into the back of your personal computer, the gas
tank may explode. I'm kidding. I think.), computer content is often
refreshingly loony and pointless.
</P>
<P>
   Like a sharpened pork-product dagger to the heart, this
observation was driven home recently with the discovery of an
utterly useless, and therefore fascinating, Web site called Spam-Ku
Archive (http://pemtropics.mit.edu/jcho/spam/archive.html(NUMBER
SIGN)select). The purpose, if one could call it that, is to create
a haiku (three unrhymed lines of 5, 7 and 5 syllables respectively)
dealing with America's favorite canned luncheon-meat-like product,
SPAM.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some examples:
</P>
<P>
   Winter trailer home:
</P>
<P>
   Bills unpaid _ no heat inside.
</P>
<P>
   Raw SPAM for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   A half-eaten slice.
</P>
<P>
   Ants swarm the cold, greasy plate.
</P>
<P>
   A suicide note.
</P>
<P>
   Opening old can:
</P>
<P>
   Insert tab in key and turn.
</P>
<P>
   If strip breaks, you're screwed.
</P>
<P>
   Conquering GIs
</P>
<P>
   Gave SPAM to Japanese then
</P>
<P>
   Watched them jump off cliffs
</P>
<P>
   Spock scans the pink meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's life, Jim,'' he tells Kirk, ``but...
</P>
<P>
   not as we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ John M. Debevec
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere a black hole
</P>
<P>
   Consumes everything in sight;
</P>
<P>
   A blue can sails by.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Mitchell
</P>
<P>
   Stroll to the SPAM aisle
</P>
<P>
   Past the condoms and tampons.
</P>
<P>
   No one is watching.
</P>
<P>
   _ Junkyard God
</P>
<P>
   I stare, it stares back.
</P>
<P>
   I long to know its feelings.
</P>
<P>
   It demurs. Lunch, then.
</P>
<P>
   _ Drew Scott
</P>
<P>
   In the can of SPAM
</P>
<P>
   A severed human finger.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant texture change.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tom Elliott
</P>
<P>
   SPAM smells so sexy.
</P>
<P>
   A little behind the ears,
</P>
<P>
   And I can date cops.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Mitchell
</P>
<P>
   Mother's rough finger
</P>
<P>
   Stirs water into the Tang
</P>
<P>
   And glazes the SPAM.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Mitchell
</P>
<P>
   Trailer park wedding
</P>
<P>
   A piata, Schlitz, and SPAM
</P>
<P>
   Vegas honeymoon
</P>
<P>
   _ LisaSteveDougJulie
</P>
<P>
   Try it yourself. It's fun. Here are a few I came up with:
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA shuts SPAM plant
</P>
<P>
   Hear the giant sucking sound!
</P>
<P>
   Ross Perot was right.
</P>
<P>
   Southern SPAM better
</P>
<P>
   Keep your head, don't forget what
</P>
<P>
   The heart doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   Pink, jellied texture
</P>
<P>
   Not a problem for Buster;
</P>
<P>
   Pugs eat anything.
</P>
<P>
   Flashlight dead? Try this:
</P>
<P>
   SPAM on stick makes a great torch
</P>
<P>
   That will burn for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Martha Stewart!
</P>
<P>
   Want to share a can of SPAM?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, no. Ladies first.
</P>
<P>
   Cafeteria
</P>
<P>
   Food by any other name
</P>
<P>
   Tastes as sweet as SPAM
</P>
<P>
   What if newspapers
</P>
<P>
   Came with a free can of SPAM?
</P>
<P>
   Would you love us less?
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5272 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-MYOB-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-05 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MYOB-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MYOB': SHOW VEERS BETWEEN `ANTI-SITCOM' AND WARM AND FUZZY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``MYOB,'' which begins Tuesday on NBC, is electroplated with
attitude. That coating scratches easily, though, revealing the
sentimentality underneath.
</P>
<P>
   The sitcom, from a concept by Don Roos, writer and director of
the film ``The Opposite of Sex,'' strikes a subversive pose, as if
it were the opposite of network television. Much of its humor is
directed at the medium's dumb conventions. But the darts it throws
have rubber tips; they hit the target without inflicting damage.
</P>
<P>
   From the first lines of narration from a 16-year-old girl named
Riley (Katherine Towne), you can hear the show straining to be
cool. When first encountered, Riley, a tough-talking little blonde
in tight clothes, has just flown into San Francisco. She accepts a
cab ride from a giggling ninny with a lecherous look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' Riley tells you. ``Nothing bad happens to me.
This isn't a TV movie where, I like, end up murdered and my mom has
to pose as a hooker to help track down the murderer.'' True to her
word, Riley out-foxes the guy after she gets a free meal in his
hotel room, meanwhile sprinkling her narration with wry remarks
about television in general and other NBC series in particular.
</P>
<P>
   But speaking of her mom, it turns out that's who she's looking
for. See, Riley was adopted as a baby, but when she was 4 her
adoptive mother died in a post office shootout _ ``She was the
idiot with the gun.'' How Riley got from then to now isn't
specified.
</P>
<P>
   Riley has a copy of what might be her birth certificate, hacked
from a government computer, which leads her to a woman she thinks
is her birth mother's sister Opal (Lauren Graham), an earnest
assistant principal in a Northern California high school. Opal's
sister, Pearl _ yes, some of this is funny _ who moved to Finland
with her guru 14 years ago, says by e-mail that she never had a
baby. But even Opal allows that crazy Pearl might not remember.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, the love-starved Opal must cope with the arrival
of someone claiming to be her kin, the sudden death of the school's
principal and his quick replacement by Opal's crumb of an
ex-boyfriend, Mitch (Paul Fitzgerald), whom Opal still loves even
though he dumped her long ago and has now stolen the job she
deserved. Whew!
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Opal takes Riley home. They start bonding. Riley tells
her, ``Maybe you're worth more than you think.'' Then Riley
blackmails the school superintendent, who turns out to be the creep
who picked Riley up at the airport, into making Opal principal
after all.
</P>
<P>
   Next week Riley plays little miss fix-it again when Opal has a
falling-out with her best friend.
</P>
<P>
   So which is it? Subversive anti-sitcom or warm and fuzzy?
``MYOB'' _ that stands of course for ``mind your own business,''
which Riley cannot do _ tries to split the difference. And despite
its ironic veneer, the show just doesn't have enough difference to
split.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of Tuesday's episode, which Roos wrote, Riley throws
down a challenge: ``So you don't wanna watch? Hey, that's OK `Law
and Order' is bound to be on somewhere.'' Great. Where?
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MYOB  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   9:30 p.m. ET Tuesday on NBC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don Roos and Ann Donahue, executive producers; David Codron,
consulting producer; Mimi Friedman and Jeanette Collins,
co-executive producers; Amy Engelberg, Wendy Engelberg, Jack
Clements, Jimmy Aleck and Jim Kelly, producers; directed by Bryan
Gordon. An NBC Studios Production.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Katharine Towne (Riley Veatch), Lauren Graham (Opal), Paul
Fitzgerald (Mitch Levitt), Colin Mortensen (A.J.) and Amanda Detmer
(Lisa Overbeck). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
