u i BC-CLINTON-0606-COX     06-05 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON PLEDGES AID TO SHUT DOWN CHERNOBYL NUCLEAR PLANT
 &HT;    With sidebar slugged CLINTON-MISSILES
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine _ With a vote of confidence in Ukrainian democracy
and aid to help shut down the world's most infamous nuclear power
plant, President Clinton wound up a week of overseas travel here
Monday and headed home to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   On the last leg of a trip that earlier took him to Portugal,
Germany and Russia, Clinton stopped off in Kiev, the 1,500-year-old
capital of Ukraine, where President Leonid Kuchma promised to shut
down the Chernobyl nuclear power plant by Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing an estimated 70,000 people jammed into a broad,
brick-paved square, Clinton praised Ukraine's first decade of
democracy and urged the country to press forward with its march
away from Communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly part of the Soviet Union, Ukraine became an independent
state in August, 1991, following the Soviet break up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communism has lost in Ukraine, but a full commitment to free
market democracy has not yet won,'' said Clinton, speaking from
atop a temporary dais erected in the historic square.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your children are to live their dreams, it must win,'' said
Clinton. ``Do not give up. Keep on fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also suggested that Ukraine is a candidate for admission
into the economic and security structures that stood down Soviet
Communism. While he didn't mention either the European Union or
NATO by name, he made clear that Ukraine is no longer within
Moscow's sphere of influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``America believes Ukraine has a right to a place among the
nations of Europe. No one must take that right away from you,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reject the idea that the eastern border of Europe is the
western border of Ukraine,'' said Clinton. ``We can, and we will,
keep the door to the transatlantic community of democracies open to
Ukraine.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton promised Ukraine $80 million in U.S. aid to help shut
down Chernobyl and entomb the reactor that exploded in 1986 in the
worst accident in the history of the nuclear power industry.
</P>
<P>
   A 1991 fire in another of the plant's four reactors cemented
Chernobyl's reputation as the most dangerous nuclear plant in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The 1986 disaster killed at least 31 people immediately, forced
the evacuation of 135,000 more and released airborne radiation that
swept across much of central Europe. Thousands have died since then
of maladies attributed to radiation received as a result of the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Closing Chernobyl has been a goal of the United States and its
partners in the Group of Seven industrialized democracies for
years. The G-7 has already given Ukraine some $3 billion _ $200
million of it is from the United States _ over the past decade to
improve safety at the plant and to build new plants to help replace
the electric power production lost by the closing of Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton pledged $25 million to boost the
development of small and medium sized businesses in Ukraine, in
part to help offset the economic losses associated with closing the
plant.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's larger mission here was to praise the Ukrainian spirit
and encourage this country of 50 million in its struggle to build a
modern democratic state after a century of war, repression and
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, Soviet dictator Joseph Stalin waged terror
campaigns against Ukrainian intellectuals and imposed policies that
created famines that left more than 3 million dead. The next
decade, Nazi invaders killed 1 million Ukrainian Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the oppressors are gone. Stalin is gone. The Nazis are
gone. The Soviet Union is gone,'' said Clinton . ``But you, the
people of Ukraine, you are still here, stronger than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to return to Washington late Monday night,
with a busy week of diplomacy and more travel ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   He meets Tuesday with King Abdullah II of Jordan. Close to the
Palestinian community, Abdullah is seen as a key player in
Clinton's efforts to broker a Mideast peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton flies to Tokyo. He will spend only a few
hours there, to attend memorial services for the late Japanese
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, before returning to Washington
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton hosts Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo for a
meeting at the White House, then travels that night to Minneapolis,
where he is to deliver the commencement address at Carleton
College.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans can be e-mailed at: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
