<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     06-05 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SHOULD CREATE MORE NATIONAL MONUMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has written about public lands issues
for over a decade and is respected for his insight into these
issues. His e-mail address is levendos(at)trib.com.)  
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four more national monuments are coming America's way soon. And
there is a strong likelihood that President Clinton will designate
several more monuments before he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   There will be the usual clamor in Congress claiming the
president has abused his power _ a power given to the presidency by
Congress when it passed the Antiquities Act in 1906.
</P>
<P>
   On May 31, Secretary of the Interior Bruce Babbitt sent the
president a recommendation that four unique landscapes be protected
under the Antiquities Act. The proposed national monuments are
located on federal public lands in Arizona, Colorado, Oregon and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Antiquities Act authorizes the president to create national
monuments on federal land to protect areas of special cultural,
scientific, archeological and ecological interest.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton doesn't have to act on Babbitt's
recommendation, the president has shown a strong inclination to use
the Antiquities Act to protect special landscapes that are in
jeopardy from urban sprawl, development or exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office, Clinton has designated five new national
monuments and expanded an already existing one, the Pinnacles
National Monument in California. The most recent designation, the
Giant Sequoia National Monument in California, was announced on
April 15.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt proposes that the president designate the Ironwood
Forest National Monument in Arizona, Canyons of the Ancients
National Monument in Colorado, Cascade-Siskiyou National Monument
in Oregon and Hanford Reach National Monument in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Ironwood Forest National Monument is located 25
miles northwest of Tucson and encompasses approximately 135,000
acres of public land managed by the Bureau of Land Management in
the Sonoran Desert. The area supports one of the highest densities
of ironwood trees in the Sonoran Desert. An ironwood tree can live
as long as 800 years.
</P>
<P>
   The ironwood landscape is also critical habitat for the desert
Bighorn sheep. Unfortunately, this unique area is threatened by
numerous golf courses and housing developments.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Pima County Board of Supervisors sent a unanimous
resolution to Babbitt seeking national monument status for this
area, which is within their county.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Canyons of the Ancients National Monument is
located in the Four Corners region of southwest Colorado, about 45
miles west of Durango. The BLM manages the 164,000 acres that would
be included in the proposed monument. The area contains the highest
known density of archeological sites in the nation _ more than
20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The archeological finds include great kivas, cliff dwellings,
shrines, sacred springs, petroglyphs, sweat lodges and villages.
</P>
<P>
   The integrity of these archeological sites is threatened by the
growth of population in the area, with tourism and increasing
vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., introduced a
bill to protect the landscape and sites as a National Conservation
Area. He suspended all action on the bill in late March due to
local controversies over the NCA designation.
</P>
<P>
   National monument status is the only quick solution to
protecting the area.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Cascade-Siskiyou National Monument is located 25
miles southeast of Medford, along the Oregon-California border. It
includes the biologically significant Soda Mountain _ significant
because of its geological age, soil types and transitional climate
zones.
</P>
<P>
   The 52,000-acre area of BLM land is situated where the Klamath
and Cascade mountains converge, creating a rich ecology that
supports a wide variety of rare plants and animals.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Hanford Reach National Monument contains 200,000
acres of public land located in south-central Washington, along the
Columbia River. The area is within the Department of Energy's
Hanford Nuclear Reservation, but outside the radioactive hot spots
and would become a buffer zone around the nuclear reservation.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would give the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service the
responsibility of managing the monument.
</P>
<P>
   The Hanford Reach is the last free-flowing, non-tidal stretch of
the Columbia River, where nearly 80 percent of fall chinook salmon
spawn.
</P>
<P>
   The area also contains American Indian cultural artifacts that
span more than 10,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a great deal of political pressure to convert
portions of the area to agricultural uses. Such uses could
jeopardize salmon habitat and threaten other historic objects
within the area of the proposed monument.
</P>
<P>
   If the president designates these sites as national monuments,
he will have created or expanded 10 monuments during his
administration _ setting aside more than 3.8 million acres for
greater protection.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the public agrees with the administration's goal to
ensure greater protection of unique public lands. And the public
can expect Clinton to designate other sites as national monuments
before he leaves office _ the Missouri Breaks area in central
Montana and Steens Mountain in southeastern Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   And the president may expand the Great Sand Dunes National
Monument in Colorado and Craters of the Moon National Monument in
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   The move to put these lands out of the reach of oil and mining
interests, developers and those who would plunder natural and
archeological resources for private gain is the right move at the
right time.
</P>
<P>
   With an increasing and mobile population, let us ensure that
future generations have the opportunity to enjoy their special
heritage in nature. The president should adopt Babbitt's
recommendations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1809EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
