<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5294 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-HNS &LR;      06-05 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLLSTER SEES TOUGHER ROAD FOR MRS. CLINTON IN SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, enjoying a slight lead in a
new poll in New York state, faces a tougher battle against Rep.
Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., for a U.S. Senate seat than she did against
feisty New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a pollster said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   John Zogby, president of Utica, N.Y.-based Zogby International,
said a statewide survey of 704 likely voters completed Sunday
showed the first lady leading Lazio 46 percent to 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Zogby said he found ``anti-Hillary'' sentiment deeply
embedded among parts of the electorate as well as problem areas
looming for her.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, a fourth-term congressman from Long Island, matches or
exceeds Giuliani's margin over Clinton among upstate voters,
suburban voters, male voters and Roman Catholics, Zogby said. Lazio
also cuts into Clinton's edge over Giuliani among blacks and
Hispanics, even though the first lady holds a sizable lead.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Giuliani from the race boosted Clinton's edge
in New York City, among women and among Jewish voters, Zogby's
survey found.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton held a slight edge over Giuliani in the last survey
conducted before the mayor's withdrawal, 42 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio entered the race against Clinton to fill the seat of
retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., after Giuliani
withdrew, citing the need to seek treatment for prostate cancer and
the breakup of his 16-year marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio is ``her worst nightmare,'' Zogby told reporters. Clinton
cannot paint Lazio as a right-wing acolyte of former House Speaker
Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., because the congressman has voted to support
President Clinton's policies almost as often as he has supported
the GOP agenda, Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio ``kind of comes right down in the middle which is pretty
much where New York Republicans are,'' Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby said Clinton's dogged efforts to court New Yorkers,
including constant visits to the state and the purchase of a home
in Chappaqua, N.Y., have failed to boost her margin of support
which remains ``frozen at about 45 percent or 46 percent'' of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The ability of the little-known Long Island congressman to
achieve parity with Clinton in the Senate race within two weeks of
entering the race underscores the depth of residual anti-Clinton
sentiment, Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's showing of 44 percent represents a solid anti-Clinton
vote, Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   Voters ``needed to know that Lazio was neither a serial killer
or a pedophile and that was enough to meet the lowest threshold''
of winning their support over Clinton, Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby added: ``The issue then becomes who can get up to 48
percent or 49 percent which really is what it is going to take to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Zogby said that repeated polls show roughly 45 percent of the
New York electorate remains staunchly ``anti-Clinton'' regardless
of what the first lady does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary is the polarizing character,'' Zogby said of a high
profile Senate contest that is expected to cost candidates and
their parties a total of more than $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Rudy was in (the race) the best that each (candidate) had
going was each other,'' Zogby said. ``And now all of a sudden, Rudy
is out and I think that at least for the time being, Hillary's
people are scrambling because Lazio just sort of defies what the
strategy had been.''
</P>
<P>
   Zogby said Clinton cannot hope to benefit from Vice President Al
Gore's 14 percentage point lead in New York state over presumptive
GOP nominee George W. Bush because voters will cast ballots in the
presidential race and the Senate race without regard to the
parallel contest.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is such a ``giant in the race'' that people ``will come
out to either vote for or against Hillary,'' Zogby said. Gore's
expected victory in New York ``will not have an impact'' on
Clinton's political fortunes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby said Clinton is running a ``very good campaign,'' by
staging repeated visits to upstate cities froim Albany to Buffallo
where she wins coverage in media markets that reach pockets of
Democrats, white working women and union households.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lazio has scored gains as well among loyal Clinton
constituencies. African-Americans were ``energized'' to repudiate
Giuliani at the polls to retaliate for the mayor's unapologetic
support for police in a series of shootings of unarmed blacks,
Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio cuts into this base, drawing 8 percent of the
African-American vote _ a sizeable jump from the 2 percent or less
that Giuliani reaped in some earlier polls.
</P>
<P>
   With Giuliani in the race, ``Hillary was going to mop up'' with
a large turnout among African Americans that could have generated
an extra 80,000 or 90,000 votes for Clinton, Zogby said. ``But that
is missing now,'' Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
