<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VETERANS GROUP OPPOSES SITE, DESIGN OF WWII MEMORIAL
 &HT;    With photo.
 &HT;    By MIRIAM A. GARCIA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A group of World War II veterans said Monday they
oppose building a WWII memorial between the Washington Monument and
the Lincoln Memorial, saying it will ``destroy'' the National Mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veterans to Save the Mall'' and other groups launched a
campaign to relocate the proposed memorial or modify its large,
elaborate design.
</P>
<P>
   ``Destroying our National Mall should not be our legacy,'' said
John Graves, a decorated WWII veteran who fought with the 63rd
Infantry Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to honor all who served in World War II, but in a way
that respects our history and the heritage of the National Mall,''
Graves said in a statement. He is also featured in an advertisement
opposing the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argue that the memorial's 56 square pillars and two
arches will be an intrusive presence on the Mall.
</P>
<P>
   The monument's design, featuring a 237-by-338 foot lowered plaza
located at the east end of the Reflecting Pool in front of the
Lincoln Memorial, has received preliminary approval from the
National Park Service, the Commission of Fine Arts, and the
National Capital Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The National WWII Memorial campaign has raised nearly $90
million from veterans groups, private citizens and corporations to
build the $100 million project, said Mike Conley, associate
director of the project.
</P>
<P>
   WWII was ``clearly the most significant event of the 20th
century, and the victory belongs in the company of the Washington
and Lincoln memorials,'' Conley said.
</P>
<P>
   Preserving vierws of the two monuments was the main criterion
for the design, Conley said. In addition, ``the route of visitors
from Washington to Lincoln is virtually unchanged,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After objections were raised to the original design, Conley
said, the structure was redesigned to allow a wider central vista.
Curved ramps were also added to make it easier for pedestrians to
get around the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Another opponent, W. Kent Cooper, said the WWII memorial would
appear to be ``stacked on top'' of the Lincoln memorial. In
contrast, when ``the Vietnam Veterans Memorial was built on the
same grounds, it didn't destroy anything, it added to it,'' said
Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who led the design team for the Korean War Veterans
Memorial, is a trustee for the Committee of 100 on the Federal
City, a local organization that opposes the memorial site.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has recommended alternative sites for the
memorial, including the Constitutions Gardens area north of the
Reflecting Pool.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign to place the monument in the disputed location,
however, is nearing its final stages. Backers expect final approval
this summer and to break ground on Veteran's Day in November,
Conley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get it built before there aren't any more WWII
veterans to see it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.savethemall.com, www.wwiimemorial.com
</P>
<P>
   Miriam A. Garcia's e-mail address is miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
