<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5296 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-05 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NUDITY BECOMES A FASHION STATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The way clothing codes are going, actress Sarah
Jessica Parker was overdressed when she appeared at last Saturday's
MTV Movie Awards ceremony wearing nothing but a casually draped
towel.
</P>
<P>
   Early the next morning, Spencer Tunick, a publicity-conscious
Manhattan photographer, snapped 152 naked models stretched out on a
deserted street. He called it art. And he had permission from no
less than the U.S. Supreme Court, which sided with his First
Amendment right to freedom of expression over the city's
objections.
</P>
<P>
   The high bench looked on this case with more bemused tolerance
than it has displayed in its handling of most past nudity issues.
</P>
<P>
   A New York state ordinance forbids public exposure of private
body areas except when part of a play, exhibition, show or
entertainment. The city claimed it would be ``irreparably harmed''
by the photo shoot because it would invade the privacy of residents
living nearby who ``might object to seeing nude bodies early on a
Sunday morning.''
</P>
<P>
   The court didn't buy the notion that the presumed shock to the
sensibilities of local citizens was of such great moment as to
overcome the First Amendment protection of an artistic photograph.
But the photographer was required to complete the picture-taking a
half hour and he promised that everyone would be nude for only 90
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The idea seems to be that going briefly buck-naked is not in bad
taste if the exposure has a benign purpose and is not prolonged or
sensationalized.
</P>
<P>
   Tunick himself said, ``I don't think I could do this in the
middle of the day in front of Macy's.''
</P>
<P>
   When a women's rugby team from Ohio State posed topless in
November for a photo in front of the Lincoln Memorial, however, the
official response was not similarly kind. It wasn't illegal, and
the women said they meant to market a tee-shirt emblazoned with the
picture to raise money for the team. But the university failed to
see the merit of this project, and the team was suspended for the
rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Similar female exhibitionism is spreading, perhaps stimulated by
sexy poses in magazines and the skimpy outfits on television. When
the fashion industry's recent preoccupation with showing off belly
buttons grew boring, designer emphasis shifted to an excess of
cleavage, which inevitably leads to even more exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Massive outdoor recreational events have become an excuse for
young ladies (actually, they aren't ladies) to take off their tops.
Several women with bared breasts were held aloft this spring in the
infield at Baltimore's Preakness race,for instance. This brazen act
seems to have more to do with too much beer consumption than with a
deliberate descent into sexual degradation.
</P>
<P>
   Should we worry? Hard to tell.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just America that is stripping. ``The Full Monty,'' a
funny and wise 1997 film about unemployed men who decide to raise
money by putting on a strip show, set the pace.
</P>
<P>
   This past January a club of proper British middle-aged matrons
took off all their clothes except their pearls for a discreetly
posed calendar that forever outdated ye olde bake sale and raised
$550,000 for a local charity. They were such a hit that other
groups around England _ hunters, chefs, farmers, firefighters, men
and women alike _ have also been posing in the buff for charity.
</P>
<P>
   At a Rio de Janeiro beach in February, policemen waving guns
arrested a woman sunbathing topless and jailed her for eight hours.
Going topless had been banned for 70 years, but the law had never
before been enforced.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest prompted days of protests, during which men donned
bikini tops. Legal bikinis are so miniscule they are called, in
Portuguese, ``dental floss.'' Rio officials gave up and lifted the
ban.
</P>
<P>
   Even stodgy Russia has caught the nudity virus. A new television
current affairs show, appropriately titled ``The Naked Truth,''
features interviewers who hug microphones to their bare breasts,
newsreaders who undress as they deliver the news and a female
weather reporter who does a strip-tease. The show is reportedly
popular with those who want to keep abreast of the news. (No
complaints, please, for this corny pun; I lifted it from a London
newspaper.)
</P>
<P>
   The sports world is an energetic participant in the movement to
cut away cumbersome clothing and show lots of female flesh.
Near-nudity sells. TV cameras consistently shoot attractive young
soccer, volleyball and tennis players from angles that best capture
thighs, buttocks and breasts. Their outfits, sometimes mandated by
the sport organizers, are as skimpy as the law will allow. The
Australian women's Olympic soccer team posed for a calendar last
year displaying full frontal nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this is just for fun, some for commercial exploitation.
Some, of course, is for sex. Does it mean anything dire for
society? Moral purists will disagree, but I don't think shedding
our inhibitions, within limits, means society is doomed. It may,
however, mean an uncovered world will soon catch a collective cold.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
