<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5298 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-MISSILES-0606     06-05 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MISSILES-0606-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW U.S. MISSILE DEFENSE SYSTEM WOULD NOT THREATEN RUSSIA,
CLINTON SAYS
 &HT;    700&AMP;add
 &HT;    With story slugged CLINTON
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Clinton took his case for a controversial new
U.S. missile defense system directly to the Russian people and
their elected officials on Monday, telling them the proposed weapon
poses no threat to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   He also said it was ``inconceivable'' that the United States
would deploy such a system without working closely with Moscow to
keep from renewing an arms race between the world's two largest
nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find any future apart from cooperation with you in the
nuclear area inconceivable,'' Clinton said in nationally-televised
remarks before the Russian parliament. ``The real question is a
debate over what the impact of this will be, because of the
capacity of the technology involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks capped a three-day visit to Moscow centered on tough
talks with Russian President Vladimir Putin over missile defense
and nuclear weapons reductions.
</P>
<P>
   The first American president ever to address Russia's
parliament, Clinton left Moscow afterwards and flew to Kiev.
Clinton was scheduled to return to Washington late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   During some eight hours of face-to-face summitry, Putin stood
firm in his objections to a new U.S. weapon system being developed
to defend the country from a missile attack by a rogue state or
terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made a pitch for Russian acceptance of the system in a
joint speech before the 450-member Duma, the key legislative body,
and the 178-member Federation Council. Not all members were in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called national missile defense, or NMD, system is aimed
at protecting the United States from the threat that a rogue state,
such as North Korea, or a terrorist group, such as the followers of
Osama Bin Laden, might one day attempt to attack the country with a
nuclear weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Putin told Clinton the risk of such attack was being exaggerated
by NMD advocates and that deploying an NMD system could cause more
harm than good by upsetting the balance of power between the United
States and Russia, which together possess more than 80 percent of
the world's nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pleaded with Russians to think carefully about how
quickly global security is being changed by the wide availability
of new technology and information that will soon make it possible
for many new actors to acquire weapons that only a few large
countries now possess.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be realistic,'' said Clinton. ``Despite our best
efforts, the possibility exists that nuclear and other deadly
weapons will fall into dangerous hands, into hands that could
threaten us both.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton, ``the technology required to launch missiles
capable of delivering them over long distances, unfortunately, is
still spreading across the world. The question is, what is the best
way to deal with it?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to decide this fall whether to deploy the
NMD system, currently being tested by the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made his comments during a 45-minute speech meant to be
a grand survey of U.S.-Russian relations at a time of social and
economic turmoil within the former superpower. He urged the Russian
people to press ahead in their difficult journey from Communist
autocracy to free-market democracy and stressed the need to build
the elements of a civil society based on the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   Russian parliamentarians showed little emotion during the
speech, never interrupting it for applause. Some could be seen
fidgeting in their chairs or otherwise expressing signs of tedium,
as Clinton poured over the litany of tasks the United States wants
Russian to accomplish: clean up its corrupt government, put in
place an effective tax code, create legal protections for foreign
investors, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's message ran into particularly heavy weather in the
form of parliament member Vladimir Zhirinovsky, the
ultra-nationalist who has built a political career by decrying the
collapse of the former Soviet Union and the subsequent decline of
living standards across the Russian motherland.
</P>
<P>
   Seated 14 rows away from Clinton, Zhirinovsky grumbled loudly
when the president was introduced. As applause filled the chamber
at the end of the speech, he hollered out to colleagues, ``Why are
you applauding for him? He destroyed our country.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Zhirinovsky led several dozen protesters _ some chanting
``Yankee go home,'' and ``U.S. out of Serbia _ outside of the Duma
building, while others waved red Soviet-era flags with the hammer
and sickle motif.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has poured money into Russia, and after
eight years, what has happened? It has brought to power a KGB
colonel, those whom the United States was fighting against on the
dollars of U.S. taxpayers,'' said parliament member Alexei
Mitrofanov, the number two man in Zhirinovsky's ultranationalist
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is worse for most Russians after ten years of reform,''
Mitrofanov told American reporters traveling with the president.
``Clinton understands nothing of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Kiev, Clinton rounded out his Moscow summit
almost certainly his final trip to the Russian capital as president
with a brief stop at the dacha of former Russian President Boris
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin looked good today,'' Clinton told reporters after the
social call with the man who was his Russian counterpart for seven
years. ``He's in good spirits, happy, he's got a beautiful place.''
</P>
<P>
   In a reference to Yeltsin's propensity toward alcohol, a
reporter asked which spirits, exactly, Clinton had referenced.
</P>
<P>
   ``No spirits,'' Clinton laughed. ``He and his wife and his
daughter were there. We all just had a nice visit. It was like old
times. But he's in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans can be e-mailed at: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
