<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5299 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-TEXAS-DEMOCRATS-HNS &LR;      06-05 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEMOCRATS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS DEMOCRATS ACCENTUATE THE POSITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For all the ground they have lost to the
Republicans in recent years, Texas Democrats might be forgiven for
wanting to cry as they head for the state party convention later
this week.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic officials are optimistic, even in a year when
some party faithful might vote for a favorite son presidential
candidate, Republican Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you gain anything by crying,'' said Betty
Flores, a Democrat who is the mayor of Laredo. ``I think a long
time ago those wounds, if you want to call them that, were healed
and people tended to them. Now I think it's just, `Let's go get
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   But, Flores added, ``First you've got to know what `it' is.''
</P>
<P>
   To Flores _ who volunteered that she crossed party lines to vote
for Bush when he ran for re-election in 1998 and has voted for
Republican Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison _ it is a matter of attracting
good, credible candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mixture of getting the right people to come back into
politics, and I don't think we're there yet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm said the
convention, which begins Thursday, would reflect the party's
efforts to expand its majorities in the state House and the state's
delegation to Congress, and win back the Texas Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will give everyone an opportunity to see why we are
confident of accomplishing those goals,'' she said. ``Our
convention will be diverse and inclusive and show how people from
all walks of life can unite and work together for the good of all
the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Polinard, a political scientist at the University of Texas
Pan American, had a gloomier assessment of the convention, which he
described as ``a useful device to circle the wagons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a little bit more exciting than a wake,'' he said.
``The party is close to being in desperate straits.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of Democratic heavyweights are not planning to join the
crowd at the convention, which is expected to draw 7,000 delegates
and alternates to draft a state platform, pick a state leadership
team and choose state delegates to the national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the party's presumptive presidential
nominee, is expected to skip the event.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Mayor Ron Kirk will be out of state, according to his
office. Austin Mayor Kirk Watson, another rising Democratic star,
plans to attend the U.S. Conference of Mayors in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Former Lt. Gov. Ben Barnes, garnering new attention after a
speech in which he warned that Texas is ``drifting toward
mediocrity,'' may attend a convention kickoff reception Thursday
for Energy Secretary Bill Richardson. But that's about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have got a lot of commitments next week I just made really
without being aware when the convention was,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Barnes is planning an Austin event to raise money
for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee that is
anticipating a bigger name than any appearing at the convention _
President Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
