<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5306 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MICROSOFT06-COX     06-05 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOVERNMENT SPURNS MICROSOFT'S ANTITRUST FORMULA
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department asked a federal judge Monday
to spurn nearly all of the changes Microsoft Corp. wants in the
government's plan to break up the giant software maker.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing with U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson,
the antitrust team submitted a revised version of their breakup
plan that makes 19 fairly minor changes to its prior draft. But
Justice Department and 17 states largely stood behind their plan,
rejecting all the company's substantive suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   The government brief argued that Microsoft got its way, its
proposals ``would create loopholes and permit Microsoft to continue
to engage in anti-competitive practices or otherwise frustrate or
undermine the purposes'' of the proposed remedy decree.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is primed to issue that landmark order, perhaps as soon
as this week, after he receives Microsoft's final rebuttal
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The company, for its part, has acceded to Jackson's request that
it devise a remedy formula on its own. But it still regards that
plan, which the government disdains, as totally unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like putting lipstick on a pig,'' said Michael Murray, a
Microsoft spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who has found that Microsoft illegally leveraged its
Windows monopoly for operating software, shows every sign of
approving government plan to divide the company into two firms. One
would make Windows, while the other would make such applications as
Office.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson is certain to stay his breakup order pending the
outcome of an appeal, which could take several years.
</P>
<P>
   The latest government brief urged the judge to move quickly. It
argued that ``it is in the public interest that the remedy
contemplated by the final judgment be implemented as soon as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The government also held that Jackson should ignore the
company's request to be given a year, instead of four months, to
devise a full reorganization plan. It also urged that he reject a
request to limit to four years the period under which Microsoft
must operate with a full set of curbs in force, instead of 10 years
prescribed by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has had a dominant position in the operating-systems
business for at least a decade, and under the circumstances there
is no sound justification for entering a decree of shorter
duration,'' the government said in its filing.
</P>
<P>
   In citing an earlier deposition by Bill Gates, the company's
chairman, that ``I delete 98 percent of my e-mails,'' the
government further said there was ``no sound reason'' to lift a
proposed requirement that Microsoft preserve electronic mail
written by officers, directors and managers involved in software
development for at least four years.
</P>
<P>
   In assailing the limited ``cosmetic changes'' made by the
government, another Microsoft spokesman, Jim Cullinan, said: ``We
have tried to avoid the ambiguity and vagueness inherent in the
government's proposal and the government refuses to be specific
about the issues it is trying to address. The result is going to be
bad for consumers and bad for the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.usdoj.gov/atr/cases/ms(underscore)index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
