<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5314 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT &LR;      06-05 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFIN OUTLASTS PIOLINE TO REACH FRENCH OPEN QUARTERFINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ For the first time in history, two Russian men are in
the quarterfinals of a Grand Slam event.
</P>
<P>
   Through drizzle and delays on another rainy day at Roland
Garros, Marat Safin, a 20-year-old with a whippet's frame, a huge
serve and one of the most explosive two-handed backhands in
history, eliminated Cedric Pioline, 6-4, 1-6, 6-3, 7-5, to reach
the final eight in a grand slam event for the first time in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Safin's occasional mentor Yevgeny Kafelnikov reached the final
eight on Sunday and will face Gustavo Kuerten in his quarterfinal.
But the happiest Russian right now appears to be Andrei Chesnokov,
Safin's coach, who was grinning and flashing the thumbs-up signal
to his young pupil as he sauntered off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Safin _ who has won 23 of his last 26 matches, winning
tournaments in Barcelona and Majorca _ parted ways with his
longtime Spanish coach Rafael Menusa and hired his fellow Russian
Chesnokov on a trial basis during the Barcelona tournament. At that
stage, Safin was 5-11.
</P>
<P>
   Chesnokov, a French Open semifinalist in 1989, has helped Safin
regain his appetite for the game. He had never coached anyone
formally, but Safin's enormous gift for the game and for handling
the big occasion has been clear since he qualified here as a
teen-ager in 1998 and beat the future champion Andre Agassi and
Kuerten, the defending champion, on his way to the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that Safin would soon reach the top of the sport,
but he also has a temper and a tendency to overhit instead of
overanalyze. Chesnokov has helped him regain a measure of control
and helped talk him through the two-hour rain delay Monday that
interrupted the third set. But Safin is still no stoic.
</P>
<P>
   Serving in the mist at 4-5 in the fourth set with the French
crowd cheering Pioline's every flourish, Safin missed a forehand
passing shot to fall behind by 0-40 and then wheeled and smashed
his racket onto the clay. ``I was already thinking about the fifth
set,'' Safin said.
</P>
<P>
   But he would proceed to win the next three points as Pioline,
who had attacked earlier in the game, suddenly stopped pushing
forward. In all, Safin saved four set points before knocking away a
backhand volley to get back to 5-5. Visibly deflated, Pioline lost
his serve in the next game on a double fault and then failed to
capitalize on Safin's inability to get his own first serve in play
in the final game. Magnus Norman joined Safin in the final eight by
defeating last year's surprise finalist Andrei Medvedev, 6-0, 6-4,
6-2. The day's two other fourth-round matches were suspended due to
darkness with Argentina's Franco Squillari leading Morocco's Younes
el-Aynaoui by 6-4, 6-1, 3-3 and Spain's Albert Costa leading
Australia's Lleyton Hewitt, 6-3, 4-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
