<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5316 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-05 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FISHING IN THE LAP OF PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDDING, Calif. _ The lake was glass, the oars leaving little
swirls with each stroke, and so quiet you could almost hear the
flowers bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, 10 feet off the shore of a small, nearby island, a
raucous splash and squawk on the surface snapped me to attention. I
turned and spotted a washtub-sized swirl on the lake surface,
apparently from a giant bass, leaving a five-foot ring, which then
expanded across the surface like dissipating sound waves.
</P>
<P>
   On the nearby shore, a family of Canada geese seemed to be going
crazy, the adults charging around the perimeter of their young,
rounding them up, occasionally craning their necks to stare at me,
as if to ward me off. There was one less among them, it turned out,
because it had just been eaten.
</P>
<P>
   As I made my first cast toward the island, it felt like a bass
drum was pounding in my chest. I'd been told there were giant bass
here, and now one was feeding, eating anything within range, like
even baby geese. I peered around. There was nobody else here. I had
the entire place, Steiner Lake, to myself.
</P>
<P>
   With a fly rod, reel filled with floating line, and a bass
popper, I delivered the popper on the edge of the island, then
twitched and popped it, at times just letting it sit there.
Nothing. After a dozen casts, I switched to a variation of a
Matuka, a streamer that looks like a minnow if you strip-retrieve
it in a series of short, quick yanks. But again, nothing. Relaxed
now _ the big bass was apparently done feeding _ I played staredown
with the geese as I cast, quacking at them, and suddenly, while
paying no attention, had a strike, an instinctive set, and a fish.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that gosling-eating bass, but it was a fun little
tussle, the nine-foot fly rod curved like a giant hoop; about a
2-pound bass, I figured. But to my surprise, as the fish first
appeared near the boat, it was not a bass at all, but a 15 1/2-inch
crappie, huge for that species, and a personal life-best. It turns
out that this pond not only had some of the biggest bass around,
but some of the biggest crappie as well.
</P>
<P>
   Then it hit me. This is why people will pay to fish at Steiner
Lake. Same with several other catch-and-release private ponds and
lakes in Northern California, where there are big trout, bass,
crappie and bluegill, often good numbers of them, and where access
is sharply limited to keep the fish rested, big and in attack mode.
</P>
<P>
   This new opportunity, that is, paying for access to fish private
ponds, is drawing special appeal to those new to fishing who want
action and a chance at giant fish right off, as well as for anglers
who just plain don't have the time to explore and find their own
secret spots. The cost at Steiner Lake is $85 a day; prices at most
private lakes range from $75 to $150, with lodging packages
available.
</P>
<P>
   Although something of an anomaly, the idea of fishing a private
pond has turned into the newest dimension of fishing. After all,
California has enough lakes, streams and coast to fish a different
spot every weekend for 22 years, for free. But all you need in
fishing is hope, and these private lakes lure that in front of
anglers like an intoxicant.
</P>
<P>
   Steiner Lake is located on the outskirts of Redding, about a
10-minute drive from Interstate 5. Initially I downplayed this
adventure as I headed to Redding, after all, hey, pay to fish? But
at the lake, as I sat down in the row boat (included with the fee)
and started tying up, I found myself suddenly excited and eager,
then pulse quickened as I heard and then saw the circles across the
lake from rising fish. I brought three rods, a bass rod with a
level-wind that I rigged with a Zipper Lizard, a spinning rod set
up with a spinner bait, and my fly rod with a popper.
</P>
<P>
   My first surprise was the size of the pond, bigger and deeper
than expected, covering some 30 acres with spots 20 feet deep, with
a series of sheltered, tule-lined coves along the far shore that is
quiet and protected from wind. Before heading out, I'd been told
that someone had hooked a monster back there, but couldn't handle
the fish and never even saw it.
</P>
<P>
   After catching and releasing about a dozen big crappie and bass
in the 15-inch class, alternating gear, I had worked my way to this
spot, and took bass in 3 of 12 casts, all about 3-pounders, then
paddled around a tule point for another cast. I'm not the greatest
flycaster around, but this time delivered a gentle touch, plopping
that popper just inches away from a tule berm.
</P>
<P>
   I let that popper sit there for 10 seconds, then twitched it
once, with tiny ripples emerging around it. In the next second,
what looked like Moby Bass detonated the surface in full attack,
and before I knew it, the fish was hooked and charging off. The
first run was short and powerful, what bass anglers call ``a
freight train.'' I leaned back hard on the rod, and for a minute or
so, played give and take, and then in turn, the fish then came to
surface at an angle about 30 feet out, and I got a full-on look:
About 30 inches long, a foot across from back to stomach, a
12-pounder, maybe bigger.
</P>
<P>
   In the next two seconds, Moby Bass powered straight down to the
bottom, and while I tried to contain the fish, it burrowed into the
weed-covered bottom like a gopher, and just kept going. Suddenly I
was at a complete standstill. At one point, with the rod still
arched, I opened a Pepsi and tried to figure out what to do. After
10 minutes, it became obvious there was nothing I could do. The
fish had buried himself in the weeds, and there was no way I could
get him out.
</P>
<P>
   Late that afternoon, as I rowed back to the dock, I kept
thinking about Moby Bass, and that he's still down there. Next
time, I bring a heavier rod, an 8-weight, I figured, and maybe a
duck lure. As I stepped out of the boat, I looked over at the
island, and noted the family of geese was still ashore, staying
clear of the water. They also learned their lesson for the day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For information on Steiner Lake, phone 800-669-3474.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
