u i BC-JAPAN-SUICIDE-NYT &LR;      06-05 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-SUICIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAIN COMPANIES IN JAPAN LOOK FOR WAYS TO CURTAIL GROWING NUMBER OF
SUICIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUNITACHI CITY, Japan _ With its rows of cherry trees casting
soothing pools of shade at midday and mothers ferrying babies on
the backs of bicycles across the tracks, there is hardly anything
sinister about the railroad crossing at the edge of this town.
</P>
<P>
   But with trains speeding by every three to five minutes, and
relative discretion guaranteed by its bucolic setting, this simple
railroad crossing has emerged as a favorite spot for ending one's
life. And the booming number of deaths on this rail line has given
it the reputation of being Japan's suicide express.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live on the second floor of that green house, and there seem
to be suicides here all the time'' said Yukari Omoto, a 30-year-old
mother who was ferrying her toddler daughter to town in a bicycle
seat. ``When I hear the noise I look out the window to see. By
coincidence, once I saw the whole thing take place.''
</P>
<P>
   In just a few minutes of interviews, Omoto's gory description
was matched by tales of death on the tracks by many others whose
daily commutes take them past this spot, a reflection of just how
banal the events have become. ``At the beauty parlor I heard that
people walk with their backs to the trains and jump on the track at
the last moment,'' said Yoshiko Hatori, a 44-year-old
archaeologists' assistant. ``It seems that they're coming in
bunches.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, rail suicides have come in such bunches lately that the
operator of this line, the East Japan Railway Co., or JR East, has
begun to treat them as nothing less than a companywide disaster.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1990s, suicide deaths skyrocketed on JR East's
network of lines, increasing to 212 last year, from 81 at the start
of the decade and far outstripping the 50 percent increase in the
number of suicides nationally during that period. And year in and
year out, the 80 miles of the company's Chuo Rapid, a heavily
traveled commuter express to the bedroom communities west of the
capital bears the largest concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are suffering major losses from suicide,'' said Masaki
Ogata, general manager for transport safety of JR East. ``We've
been studying the problem for 13 years now. There are various
measures that we can take to reduce suicides, but in the end, man
is the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The train company will not say exactly what the suicides have
cost it.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, a suicide causes an hourlong delay in train service,
which begins with a sudden stop, and then the dreaded announcement
over the loudspeaker that there has been a ``human incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Train companies charge the families of suicide victims for
damages caused by the suicides. JR East is just one of several
train and subway companies operating in the Tokyo area, but it is
widely rumored that JR East became the most popular line for
suicides because it charged the bereaved families the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a delicate matter,'' said a rail official, who
declined to give information on damage claims by the company.
``Naturally, we would not like to encourage people.'' Other rail
companies, for that matter, would not even release suicide
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   JR East's latest efforts to discourage suicide include painting
crossings like these in a green so bright it could have sprung from
The Wizard of Oz. The thinking behind this, based on psychologists'
studies, is that the dazzling color will alter the state of mind of
would-be suicides. The company has also increased the number of
remote surveillance cameras along its route and trimmed back tree
branches to deny people a sense of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   At enclosed stations, where 46 percent of the deaths occurred
last year, JR East has begun installing mirrors across the tracks
from passenger platforms, with the idea that the sight of oneself
could give a jumper pause.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts say, though, that efforts like these are likely to
prove futile. Psychologists speak of Japan's suicide problem as an
economic crisis and social crisis all wrapped up in one.
</P>
<P>
   The decadelong rash of suicides has coincided with an economic
stagnation that is unequaled in modern Japanese history. In a
society where much is driven by shame, record-high levels of
unemployment have turned many men into despondent daytime wanderers
who pretend to have gainful occupations by staying away from home
all day.
</P>
<P>
   Many people here say that as a nation, too, Japan seems to have
lost its purpose. For decades, the goal was to catch up with the
West economically. Since attaining that goal in the 1980s, the
country has been adrift.
</P>
<P>
   When he set up a telephone hot line last year to help suicidal
people, with financial sponsorship from JR East, Dr. Yukio Saito,
received 1,300 calls a week from people _ mostly men _ who said
they were ashamed of their failings and were considering ending
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic crisis has created quite a lot of anxiety at the
turn of the century,'' said Saito. ``There is a lack of hope.
People have no dreams for the future, and everything seems to be
declining.'' In such a setting, he said, ``suicide has become sort
of epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Kunitachi City, as she crossed the tracks aboard her
plain black bicycle, a 68-year-old woman who has long lived in this
town and who would give her name only as Sato said much the same
thing, only in simpler terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seem to be more people doing it all the time,'' she said
about the railway suicides. ``There was a time when the only people
you would hear about dying here were junior high school students
fooling around on the tracks. But that was before the economy went
bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
