<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 11)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TWO SLEEK HOTELS FOR NEW ORLEANS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two renovations have brought a bold postmodern twist to New
Orleans' upscale hotel scene, where furnishings tend to be antique,
real or fake, fabrics are often flowery, and charm has long been
mandatory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The more visible of the hotels is the W New Orleans in the
Central Business District, formerly a Sheraton Four Points and a
neighbor of Harrah's new casino. Nearby, the W New Orleans-French
Quarter is a dramatic remake of the Hotel de la Poste.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But neither of the hotels, both of which opened officially on
May 11, is without a trace of Louisiana culture. Beyond the
striking red and gold velvets, black leather and oversize chrome
tick-tack-toe games in the small reception area of the W in the
French Quarter, there are voodoo dolls for sale in the guest rooms'
snack bars, for $7 each. The same is true of the W in the Central
Business District, where there is a marble-and-glass staircase and
a backgammon set made of cloth, and chaises longues sit legless in
the playfully decorated lobby. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As in other W properties, both the 98-unit French Quarter hotel
and its sibling, which has 400 guest rooms and 23 suites, are
furnished with beds outfitted with pillow-topped mattresses and
down comforters. The rooms' 27-inch television sets are equipped
with wireless keyboards offering fast Internet access.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the downtown W, the signature restaurant is Zoe Bistrot,
where the cuisine is French. In a room off the lobby, Whiskey Blue
is a relative of cocktail lounges in Manhattan and elsewhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the French Quarter W, an Italian-style restaurant, Bacco, run
by the Brennan family, who run Commander's Palace, is a holdover
from the Hotel de la Poste. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rates at the W New Orleans-French Quarter, 316 Chartres Street,
(504) 581-1200, fax (504) 522-3208, start at $139; in high season
(roughly fall, winter and early spring), $199 to $339.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the W New Orleans, 333 Poydras Street, (504) 525-9444, fax
(504) 581-7179, rates start at $129; in high season, $179 to $339.
Both hotels have pools; the W New Orleans has a fitness center. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --FRANCES FRANK MARCUS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUS LINK TO YOSEMITE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to reduce the number of cars in Yosemite, a public
bus system is now making scheduled runs into the national park from
three surrounding counties.
</P>
<P>
   The Yosemite Area Regional Transportation System (Yarts) is
providing service to Yosemite Valley along Highway 140 from a
terminus in Merced, west of the park; passengers can catch a bus at
a number of points along the route, and buses make several stops in
Yosemite. There will be about 14 daily departures during the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is weekend service from Coulterville, also
west of the park, and there are daily trips from the valley floor
to Wawona inside Yosemite's southern entrance. Weekend service from
Mammoth Lakes, southeast of Yosemite, started Memorial Day weekend
</P>
<P>
   The new service, which connects with Yosemite's existing shuttle
system, will run all year, although departures will be far more
frequent in summer. Most trips are made with large touring buses,
and fares vary depending on distance. The trip from Merced to the
valley visitors center takes about two and three-quarters hours one
way and costs $15 round trip, $14 for ages 4 to 12 and seniors;
from El Portal, just west of Yosemite, the trip takes about an hour
and costs $7 round trip, $6 for children. The park entry fee ($20 a
vehicle for up to seven days) is included in the fare. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information: (877) 989-2787 or (209) 372-4487 or
www.yosemite.com/yarts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --CHRISTOPHER HALL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITE TRACKS AIRPORT CONDITIONS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Federal Aviation Administration's effort to reduce
air traffic delays this summer is to do a better job of putting
together a picture of air traffic delays around the country and
sharing it with its own personnel, the airlines and anyone else who
needs to know. As a result, the agency has established a reasonably
consumer-friendly Web site for travelers, www.atcscc .faa.gov,
giving a window on its Air Traffic Control Strategic Command
Center.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The main page shows a map of the contiguous 48 states and the
major airports; clicking on one shows the delays. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there is not much to say. But on May 10, a day of
widespread thunderstorms in the east, clicking on ORD (better known
as O'Hare) got this response:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to SUPPORT SWAP, departure traffic destined to New York
City's La Guardia Airport is currently experiencing delays
averaging 413 minutes, with some flights receiving as much as 500
minutes delay.'' The glossary explained that SWAP is Severe Weather
Avoidance Program; SUPPORT is undefined. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Newark, it said the numbers were 337 minutes and 500
minutes. Other entries said ``Due to intense TSTMS, departure
traffic destined to ZBW airport will not be allowed to depart until
at or after 5 P.M. CDT.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The terminology is a little rough. A glossary notes that ZBW is
the Boston Air Route Traffic Control Center, which is not an
airport at all but a control center in Nashua, N.H., that handles
traffic to and from Boston, Hartford and other New England
airports. ZNY Airport means the traffic center that covers New
York's major airports. TSTMS is thunderstorms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Calling up La Guardia Airport produced an advisory that gate
hold and taxi delays were ``between 255 and 269 minutes in length
and increasing.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SUMMER HOUSE, REINVENTED IN ENGLAND  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who wants to find out what a sitooterie is should head
for Belsay Hall in northeast England this summer. Scattered around
the 30-acre landscaped garden of this grand house built in Greek
revival style by Sir Charles Monck in 1817 are 12 sitooteries, the
Scottish colloquialism for a structure to sit ``oot'' in. Twelve
leading architects, including Sir Norman Foster, Claudio
Silverstrin and Julian Opie, have designed contemporary
interpretations of the traditional summer house and pavilion, which
will be exhibited through Sept. 30 at Belsay Hall in
Northumberland. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nick Crosbie, of Inflate, has reinvented the bandstand, with a
movable molded plastic canopy, and his entry, positioned near the
front hall, is the first image visitors will see. FAT (Fashion,
Architecture, Taste) has designed a miniature Romanesque church
along the woodland walk; Julian Opie's sitooterie is open to
interpretation: it could be a garage, a customs barrier or a Greek
temple. Perched on an arched ha-ha, Thomas Heatherwick Studio's
sitooterie has more than 5,000 protruding ash batons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sitooteries are part of English Heritage's Year of Public
Sculpture, a countrywide program of exhibitions, festivals and
workshops devoted to sculpture. A free leaflet is available from
English Heritage, (44-207) 973-3434, as is ``A User's Guide to
Public Sculpture,'' a guide to the public monuments and sculptures,
which highlights nine sculpture walks in regional cities ($12 plus
postage). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sitooteries exhibition is open daily from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.
Admission is $5.70, children $2.85. Belsay Hall is 10 miles from
Morpeth station in Northumberland, 285 miles from London; telephone
(44-1661) 881636. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
