<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5319 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-GRANDPARENTS06     06-05 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GRANDPARENTS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRANDPARENTS' RIGHT TO VISIT CHILDREN LIMITED BY HIGH COURT
 &HT;    670&AMP;insert.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dealing a setback to grandparents, a divided U.S.
Supreme Court ruled Monday that they do not have a constitutional
right to visit their grandchildren against parents' wishes.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 decision grew out of a case from Washington state, which
has one of the nation's most liberal visitation laws. The ruling's
impact on the 50 different state visitation laws is likely to vary.
</P>
<P>
   In reaching its decision, the high court weighed the rights of
families to raise their children without government interference
against laws giving grandparents visitation rights in an era when
divorce and out-of-wedlock births have blurred the rights of the
extended family. The court ruled in favor of parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a presumption that fit parents act in the best
interest of their children,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor wrote for
the court's majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as a parent adequately cares for his or her children
... there will normally be no reason for the state to inject itself
into the private realm of the family to further question the
ability of that parent to make the best decisions concerning the
rearing of that parent's children.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice John Paul Stevens, writing in dissent, argued that the
Constitution ``leaves room for states to consider the impact on a
child of possibly arbitrary parental decisions that neither serve
nor are motivated by the best interests of the child.''
</P>
<P>
   In a complicated ruling, the court issued six separate opinions:
the majority 6-3 ruling by O'Connor, two concurring opinions and
three dissenting opinions.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the ruling may be limited, because O'Connor
focused on the application of the Washington state law, rather than
on the constitutionality of grandparent visitation laws in general,
said Jan LaRue, senior director of legal studies for the Family
Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agree with Justice (David) Souter that the Supreme Court
should have affirmed the Washington Supreme Court's decision that
the law was unconstitutional 'on it's face,' and not just as
applied,'' LaRue said. ``Parental rights are a fundamental
constitutional right and deserve the utmost protection in the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, parents groups hailed the decision while AARP, the
nation's largest elder organization, said it would work with other
states to improve their visitation laws to comply with the court's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dodge, a spokesman for the Coalition for the Restoration of
Parental Rights, an organization at the forefront of opposition to
legislated grandparents' rights, said his group was pleased with
the court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't look at this as a defeat for grandparents, we look at
this as a significant step toward supporting families,'' Dodge
said, noting that nearly all disputes between grandparents and
adult children are handled out of court. ``It's a defeat for
grandparents who want to litigate rather than cooperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Entmacher, vice president of the National Women's Law
Center, said Washington state's law _ which allowed ``any person''
to seek court-ordered visitations ``at any time'' _ went too far in
interfering with parental rights concerning care, custody and
control of their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``States cannot simply substitute their judgments for a parent's
simply because a state judge believes a 'better' decision could be
made,'' Entmacher said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Matheis, AARP's director of state legislation, said the
case before the high court ``was never about giving grandparents
the right to usurp parents' control in raising their children,'' it
was about giving grandparents access to their grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Matheis said the ruling leaves room for grandparents ``in states
with more narrowly drawn or applied statutes (to) continue to
petition the courts for visitation which is in the best interest of
the child.''
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   In her opinion, O'Connor noted that roughly 28 percent of the
children in America live in one-parent homes rather than the more
traditional two-parent households. Such changes have sparked laws
in every state giving grandparents some degree of contact with
their grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extension of statutory rights in this area to persons
other than a child's parents, however, comes with an obvious
cost,'' O'Connor wrote. ``For example, the state's recognition of
an independent third party interest in a child can place a
substantial burden on the traditional parent-child relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington state case grew out of a relationship between
Tommie Granville and Brad Troxel, who never married but produced
two daughters before ending their relationship in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   After Troxel committed suicide in 1993, his parents continued to
see their granddaughters until Granville attempted to limit their
visits to one short visit per month.
</P>
<P>
   The Troxels filed suit seeking more extended visitation rights,
including one weekend per month and a week in the summer. A state
court found in favor of the grandparents, but an appeals court
dismissed their claim and the Washington state supreme court upheld
that decision. The U.S. Supreme Court affirmed the state supreme
court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Supreme Court: www.supremecourtus.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition for the Restoration of Partental Rights:
www.parentsrights.org/
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
