<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5328 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-COCKFIGHTS-2TAKES(TRI     06-05 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCKFIGHTS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE CRITICS, COCKFIGHTING THRIVES ACROSS RURAL AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Okla., N.M., La., Texas, Ohio, Ariz., Ala., Mo.)   By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KELLYVILLE, Okla. _ In a carnival atmosphere on Friday night,
200 people gathered at the local cockfighting club to watch
roosters tear each other apart and to bet on their fates.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, the scene was being repeated across the country,
from seedy pits in urban areas like the Bronx to private clubs in
rural communities like this one, where the blood sport of
cockfighting remains entrenched.
</P>
<P>
   Cockfighting classes, instructional videos and books,
newsletters and magazines help fuel a subculture and sustain a
variety of enterprises nationwide. More than half of the 170 pages
of the May issue of Gamecock, a 62-year-old monthly magazine that
claims 16,000 subscribers, were advertisements aimed at
cockfighters. Breeders from Connecticut to California raise birds
for sale at home and abroad, offering proven winners for $1,000,
untested cocks for $75 to $300, and a dozen eggs of winners' mother
hens for $100 to $200. Farm-supply companies sell trainloads of
food for the birds.
</P>
<P>
   The magazines also run ads for drugs. One labeled Strychly Speed
is the stimulant strychine, which, the ad says ``speeds up the
bird's reflexes, making him quick on the draw.'' Another, called
Pure Aggression, can ``put an end to the fear of shock in those
long, hard fights.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the ads and feed stores, a score of manufacturers sell
gaffs and a wide variety of curved, razor-sharp knives, up to 3
inches long, for mounting on legs. The knives, costing up to $100,
tend to kill faster than cheaper gaffs because they rip as well as
pierce. The weapons simply deal a quick death to cocks that would
die in much longer bouts with natural spurs, the breeders maintain.
</P>
<P>
   Cockfighting endures legally in New Mexico, Louisiana and
Oklahoma, which is home to more than 40 established backroad pits,
and illegally in many other states. While betting is a misdemeanor,
it is routine at the pits and ignored by most county sheriffs.
</P>
<P>
   All states allow breeding the birds, which the breeders sell in
states where fighting is legal, in the Philippines, Guam, Mexico
and other countries where the sport is popular, or in the woods and
urban back alleys.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few years though, cockfighting has become a target
of the advocates of animal protection. They call it barbaric and
unambiguously cruel, the only sport since the prohibition of dog
fighting decades ago in which animals are bred solely to kill one
another.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the Humane Society of the United States, based in
Washington, helped opponents in Arizona and Missouri win ballot
initiatives that outlawed it. Early this year, the Oklahoma
Coalition Against Cockfighting, largely with $100,000 from the
society, gathered more than 100,000 signatures for a referendum,
possibly in November, that would ban cockfighting and punish
violators with fines of up to $25,000 and jail terms of up to 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, more than 180 House members and more than 40
senators have sponsored bills to prohibit the interstate shipment
of fighting cocks.
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma, only the small silhouette sign of a rooster marks
the turn off Route 66 in Kellyville up a dirt road to the
corrugated metal home of the Kellyville Game Club. There, in the
club's glass-enclosed pit, a man in a red baseball cap and another
in a gray T-shirt step onto the dirt floor from opposite corners.
Under one arm, each cradles a fidgeting two-year-old rooster with
alert orange eyes.
</P>
<P>
   These are strikingly majestic birds, one of the Hatch breed, the
other a Roundhead, with shimmering manes of orange hackle feathers
and arching black tail feathers. But their heads, shorn of wattles
and haughty combs, have become bobbing red knobs. Bound like thorns
to the nubs of each of their severed spurs, they wear a curved,
2-inch long steel gaff that can puncture hearts, brains and lungs
with the thrust of a heel.
</P>
<P>
   The birds are two of the 150, paired by weapons and weight, that
will fight at the regular Friday night derby starting at 10
o'clock.
</P>
<P>
   Admission, restricted to members of the breeders' association
and their families, costs $11. The 39 men who have entered the
required four cocks in the derby pay participation fees of $50 or
$75. The fees go into the purse, sometimes up to $5,000, that is
awarded to those whose four cocks win.
</P>
<P>
   In the pit now, the men with the Hatch and the Roundhead begin
the pre-combat ritual of thrusting their birds back and forth, beak
to beak. The betting starts. ``Ten on the red hat,'' shouts one of
200 patrons in the six tiers of seats surrounding the pit. ``Twenty
on the gray shirt,'' shouts another, and another.
</P>
<P>
   The referee shouts, ``Ready, pit!'' The birds explode from their
handlers' grasp and collide breast-to-breast, a foot off the
ground. Beak grabbing beak, hackles flaring like porcupine quills,
the cocks bounce apart and collide, again and again.
</P>
<P>
   The Hatch takes command. The Roundhead rolls over, then revives.
He pounds the Hatch with a foot, spearing a lung. The Hatch fades,
hunkering down and refusing to budge. Coughing up drops of blood,
his breathing sounds like footsteps on gravel. The Roundhead,
fatigued but intact, wins. The Hatch is carried off, most likely to
die.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows the full dimensions of this business. Sandy C.
Johnson, a breeder in Ohio and director of administration of the
United Gamefowl Breeders Association, with affiliates in 33 states,
declined to disclose figures. She said cockfighting generates
hundreds of millions of dollars a year in sales of birds,
medicines, feed and breeding and fighting gear.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama is probably the biggest producer, just ahead of Texas,
Johnson said. ``We estimate that Alabama has 11,545 farms'' that
raise fighting cocks, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Urbanowsky, president of Blue Bonnet Feeds in Ardmore,
Okla. said he and his competitors sell $25 million to $30 million a
year in fighting cock feed to stores in Oklahoma alone. John
Wilson, manager of Midway Feeds, a store in Gans near the Arkansas
border in east central Oklahoma, said cockfighters account for a
third of his sales.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Among the industry's customers is Jeffrey Pearce, 43, who has a
30-acre fighting cock farm on the outskirts of Sallisaw, near
Arkansas. Pearce moved to Oklahoma eight years ago from Oregon,
where he and his father also raised cocks. His father-in-law is a
prominent breeder in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce raises Hatches, known for power, and Blacks, known for
speed, and continually crosses them. He has all but sold out this
year's production of 200 two-year-olds, for $150 to $175 each,
largely to the Philippines and Guam.
</P>
<P>
   Pearce said that starting at puberty, at six or eight months
old, each male bird, a stag until its first molt at two years old,
is dispatched to its own two-sided, 4-foot tall metal A-frame hut
and tethered by a 9-foot cord to keep him off the turf of
neighboring males.
</P>
<P>
   Across Pearce's closely groomed field of huts, 200 stags
strutted and crowed one day, pecking at the grass and their feed.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike inexpert breeders, Pearce said, he does not drug the
birds. He said good care produces the toughest, healthiest
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't make them fight,'' he said. ``Their sole purpose in
life is to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Oliver, attorney for the 7,000-member Oklahoma Gamefowl
Breeders Association, said of the birds, ``They just don't like
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Cockfighting also survives in urban areas. This weekend, the
police in New York City raided a rundown movie house in the Bronx
and arrested 190 people just as a night of betting and bloody
fighting was getting started.
</P>
<P>
   Spectators had paid $25 to sit under low-hanging fluorescent
lights in a squalid auditorium and wager $200 to $500 on the
roosters. The theater was the scene of a similar raid in March
1995, when the police stopped what they said was a national
championship cockfight. Nearly 300 people were arrested or ticketed
that night.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   George R. Day, who raises 100 cocks in Arkansas, said the
opponents of cockfighting do not understand what the sport means in
many rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people who have never lived a rural lifestyle trying
to impress their values on us,'' Day said. ``It doesn't mean
they're right. It just means there are more of them.''
</P>
<P>
   To the humane society and the state's anti-cockfighting
coalition, the sport is beyond justification, unlike killing for
food.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this as a top priority,'' Wayne Pacelle, senior vice
president of the Humane Society, said of the group's opposition to
the sport.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Seeing their traditions and livelihoods under attack, Oklahoma's
breeders formed a lobbying group that is attempting to stall the
referendum with legal challenges for at least a year, allowing time
to eventually kill it.
</P>
<P>
   It could succeed because cockfighting has become a dicey
political issue. Breeders and supporters contribute to political
campaigns, and like most state politicians, Gov. Frank Keating, a
Republican, has been staying out of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really has not taken a position,'' said John Cox, a
spokesman for Keating. ``He's for people deciding the issue. I
don't think he sees a lot of merit in cockfighting, but there are a
lot of business interests in the state that have to be adhered to a
little bit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
