<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-BUICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT WOODS, BUICK CLASSIC IS A TUNEUP FOR THE OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ Instead of resting before next week's U.S.
Open, many of the world's top golfers have come to New York.
</P>
<P>
   That is good news for the Buick Classic, which begins Thursday
at Westchester Country Club. Six of the top 10 players in the world
ranking will compete in the Buick Classic _ David Duval, Davis Love
III, Phil Mickelson, Vijay Singh, Ernie Els and Jesper Parnevik _
giving the tournament one of its strongest fields ever. Other
recognizable names in the field include Tom Lehman, Jim Furyk,
Sergio Garcia, Paul Azinger, Fred Couples, Steve Elkington, Greg
Norman, Jose Maria Olazabal, Craig Stadler, Bob Tway and the
defending champion Duffy Waldorf.
</P>
<P>
   But golf's most renowned player will be missing: Tiger Woods,
the world's No. 1 player, is following his usual routine of taking
the week off before a major championship. With the U.S. Open
beginning June 15 in Pebble Beach, Calif., players had an
interesting decision to make. Should they skip the Buick Classic
this week, practice at home, then head to Pebble Beach early to
prepare for the Open? Or should they play the Buick Classic, a
tournament played on a challenging, traditional course, hoping for
a strong week that would build confidence and momentum heading into
the Open?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Buick Classic, many top players decided to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good golf course, and I'm sure they'll try to get the
greens firm, the way we'll probably see them next week at Pebble
Beach,'' said Olazabal, who spent part of Monday practicing on the
putting green with Garcia and Miguel Angel Jimenez. ``This is a
good way to prepare for the Open, but I'm not thinking about next
week yet. I'm concentrating on playing well this week.''
</P>
<P>
   For Europeans like Olazabal, who is from Spain, stopping in New
York was a nice way to break up the long trip to the West Coast.
Other players, like Duval, simply enjoy coming to Westchester
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the golf course, and having to travel out to Pebble
Beach after it's over won't be a problem,'' Duval said recently.
``Most guys will still get out to California by Sunday night. And
you don't want to over practice once you get out to the Open
anyway. If you play 18 holes for three or four days at Pebble
Beach, you might be worn out before the tournament starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Buick Classic, held the week after the United States
Open in Pinehurst, N.C., did not attract a field as strong as the
one this year. This will be Mickelson's first appearance at
Westchester since 1993. Norman has not played Westchester since
1996. Neither Garcia, Love nor Parnevik played last year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the absence of Woods, who has not played the Buick
Classic since 1997, the field this year will not lack marquee
names.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field is strong, and I'm looking forward to a good week,''
Olazabal said. ``You'll need to bring every part of your game to
win here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
