<HEADER>
A5338 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      06-05 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, June 6. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EUROPE (Moscow) _ Roundup: President Leonid Kuchma of
Ukraine used the occasion of a brief visit by President Clinton to
announce that the Chernobyl nuclear power station will be closed by
Dec. 15. Kuchma made his announcement after the two leaders met in
the white-and-gilded splendor of the Mariinsky presidential palace.
On the six-hour stopover in Kiev, the last leg of Clinton's last
trip to Europe as president, he also delivered a speech to tens of
thousands of Ukrainians. By Elaine Sciolino and Michael R. Gordon.
(Eds.: an early version of this story has moved; the
1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   ATT-MEDIAONE (Washington) _ Clearing the final significant
regulatory obstacle to a corporate merger that will create the
nation's largest cable television, telephone and high speed
Internet company, the Federal Communications Commission approves
AT&AMP;T's acquisition of MediaOne after the companies agreed to the
sale of some of their assets. By Stephen Labaton. (Eds.: an early
version of this story has moved; the 1stLd-Writethru is scheduled
to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-GRANDPARENTS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court strikes
down a Washington state law that had allowed not only grandparents
but also non-relatives to petition for the right to visit children.
The 6-3 decision overturned the Washington law as ``breathtakingly
broad.'' But the justices leave open the possibility that less
extreme laws upholding the rights of grandparents might withstand
their scrutiny. By Linda Greenhouse. (Eds.: an early version of
this story has moved; the 1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9
p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   NJ-CENSUS (Washington) _ The New Jersey Assembly approves a bill
requiring that the state only use census data derived by
traditional counting methods when it redraws congressional and
state legislative lines after the 2000 Census. The measure is the
latest example of how the battle over the use of statistical
sampling to augment the census count has quietly shifted from
Washington to state capitals. By Steven A. Holmes. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-BAPTISTS (Winston-Salem, N.C.) _ A deep rift has
developed within the nation's largest Protestant denomination, the
Southern Baptist Convention, in which many in the moderate minority
have created a separate existence, without actually breaking away.
Reluctant to accept conservatives' insistence that the Bible be
interpreted literally and that women be barred from serving as
pastors, moderates have set up seminaries, sent out missionaries
and created church networks, like the Cooperative Baptist
Fellowship, which counts 1,800 congregations as contributors to its
budget. By Gustav Niebuhr. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   COCKFIGHTS (Kellyville, Okla.) _ Cockfighting furtively survives
in squalid dives in urban America, but in rural communities around
the country it remains entrenched. Its advocates claim it generates
hundreds of millions of dollars for breeders and suppliers. While
it is legal in New Mexico, Louisiana and Oklahoma, it has become a
target of the advocates of animal protection. Bills in the House
and Senate would prohibit the interstate shipment of fighting cocks
_ breeding is legal in all states. We visit a cockfight in the
Kellyville Game Club along Route 66. By Peter T. Kilborn.
(Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ITALY (Rome) _ Russian President Vladimir Putin called on
the European Union and NATO on Monday to join forces with Moscow
and set up a joint anti-missile shield, after talks here with
Italian Prime Minister Giuliano Amato. ``This will avoid creating
problems linked to a imbalance in the equilibrium of forces and
ensure 100 percent the security of all European countries, with the
obvious involvement of our American partners,'' Putin told a press
conference. By Alessandra Stanley. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m.
ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   UKRAINE-ECON (Kharkiv, Ukraine) _ Nearly a decade after
independence, Ukraine's decision to go along with the United States
and break a deal with Russia over an Iranian power station is
emblematic of a lament frequently expressed in this city: that
Ukraine's agenda for growth and economic development in the
post-Soviet era never seems to be as important as the strategic
objectives of the United States and its Western allies. By Patrick
E. Tyler. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY (Undated) _ Is the reform party splitting at the
seams or is Pat Buchanan solidifying his grip? By Michael Janofsky.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN-WOMEN (Undated) _ A federal agency has determined that
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. systematically discriminated
against women working in one of its divisions, opening the door for
lawsuits, and possibly a class action, against the firm. By Patrick
McGeehan. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GRAND-CANYON (Undated) _ This summer more than one million
tourists will venture to the rim of the Grand Canyon and are likely
to feel their jaws drop as they gaze upon the world famous
spectacle: a vast wilderness of rocks, deep gorges and a mighty
river lost below cliffs, buttes and pinnacles festooned in pastel
shades of purple, orange, pink and green. Inevitably, some of these
visitors will turn to a park ranger and ask: ``How did the Grand
Canyon get formed? Why did this happen here and nowhere else?'' The
honest answer is that nobody knows. By Sandra Blakeslee. (The story
has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3, and a graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
