<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5340 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GORE-REAX-COX1STLEDE     06-05 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-REAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 1STLEDE &HT;    Eds. RUNS WITH GORE-NC
 &HT;    Fixes graduating class numbers; date of father's death
 &HT;    By Viola Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TARBORO, N.C. _ Surrounded by members of Al Gore's Secret
Service unit, Gerald Perry bid the Tarboro High School Class of
2000 farewell.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, 18, vice president of the 136-member graduating class,
became the man of his house at an early age, after the death of his
father, James, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son had to grow up a little faster than I hoped,'' his
mother, Dorothy Perry, said. ``He's been the man of the house since
his father died, and his sister and I will definitely miss him when
he goes off to school. But for now, we're just proud of the young
man he has become.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a leader on the THS football team. He will attend Fork
Union Military Academy near Richmond, Va., in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In his farewell address, Perry said, ``As we depart from this
educational institution, we move forward to a fast-paced society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to prepare for the future, and that future is now. We
must find an antidote to help us cope and make us better as people.
Today the antidote I present to you is faith. Faith is a precious
commodity to us. We won't realize how important it is right now,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said he was proud to be a part of the class that had Vice
President Al Gore as its commencement speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were first told about changing the date so he could
come, we didn't really like it,'' Perry said. ``I think it brought
national attention to our area. I'm glad he came.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior class President Casey Collins, who introduced Gore, said
she practiced her introduction for hours Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of family here today, which made me very happy,''
Collins said. ``I was happy about shaking his hand. Not very many
people can say they did that, except for the Class of 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Graduate Trevin Parker won't soon forget the first few days of
June. He became not only a high-school graduate, but also a father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really sure how I feel right now,'' Parker said.
``I've kind of changed my plans for the immediate future. I'm going
to take the first semester off and spend time with my child. But I
do plan to attend Fayetteville State second semester. It's been an
exciting week.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Monteiro Brito, a Brazilian exchange student, participated
in the graduation exercises, although she only attended the school
for 10 months. She was hosted by Cindy Smith and her family and
says she will return to Brazil next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoyed today,'' Brito said. ``I've enjoyed being in
Tarboro, because all of the people have treated me so well. I've
made some true friends.''
</P>
<P>
   When Brito returns home, she plans to attend college, and says
she will study to be a food engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Wizikowski, 18, said he will attend Oral Roberts University
in the fall to study computer arts and music. Until then, he said,
``As far as what I'm doing this summer, I will be installing
heating and air-conditioning units.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he and the rest of the class had to be patted down by
the Secret Service, Wizikowski said it was worth it to have Gore as
the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to take our cap and gown off as well as our socks and
shoes,'' Wizikowski said. ``It was wild. We had to empty our
pockets and were patted down. But it was worth it. This is
something we will always remember about the Class of 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Wizikowski and friends had to wait until after the ceremony to
spray each other with canned foam or bounce a beach ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't sneak any of those things in with us,'' Wizikowski
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Coker is headed to Georgia for six and half months as
part of her National Guard training.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will remember the Class of 2000,'' Coker said. ``We
were the best.''
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of the members of the graduating class had plans
to further their education, while the rest will join the workforce
or military. Approximately $500,000 in scholarships have been
awarded to THS graduates. Four graduates are N.C. Teaching Fellows;
they will get $26,000 toward a college education to be repaid with
four years of teaching in North Carolina public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
