<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CLINTON (Moscow) _ William Jefferson Clinton's legacy
looked secure in Ukraine with 30,000 adoring people greeting him.
But just hours earlier, Russia's parliament sat stony faced as he
lectured it. The truth is, Clinton's last lap here shows just how
ambiguous he has been to this land. By David Filipov and Brian
Whitmore. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-ANALYSIS (Belfast) _ Northern Ireland Assembly gets back
together after several months, but the sounds of discord bode ill
for the rocky marching season ahead. By Kevin Cullen. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COURT-GRANDPARENTS (Undated) _ Supreme Court affirms the primacy
of parents in decisions about their children's lives, in a ruling
that advocates for children, grandparents, and homosexuals hailed
as a milestone in legal recognition of the changing composition of
American families. By Adam Pertman. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   TERRORISM-REPORT (Washington) _ A suggestion by a congressional
panel on terrorism that federal immigration officials surveil
foreign students' study programs prompts criticism from academics.
By Anne E. Kornblut. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NERVES (Undated) _ A new biomaterial made up of tiny
molecules that assemble themselves like ``smart Legos'' can act as
a scaffold for nerve cells and could make possible a new era of
spinal cord repairs, MIT scientists say. By Richard Saltus. 800
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATT-MEDIAONE (Undated) _ FCC approves AT&AMP;T's proposed $54
billion bid for MediaOne Group. But there are conditions. The FCC
is the last major regulatory hurdle to completing the buy of the
cable TV company, but the acquisition still faces shareholder
approval. By Peter Howe. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   THOMSON-PRIMARK (Undated) _ Thomson Corp. will buy
financial-information provider Primark Corp. for $1.08 billion in
cash and assumed debt as the Canadian company sheds its newspapers
to focus on distributing information electronically. By Beth Healy.
700 words.
</P>
