<HEADLINE>
AN OPEN E-BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will e-books be a hit? No one knows. But as publishers and
computer companies gamble on success, they should abide by the
principle of openness.
</P>
<P>
   The future seems promising. Publishers are cranking out e-books.
Companies sell e-reading software and hardware. Authors love the
idea of reaching new audiences. And e-books can be bought on
bookselling Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, deals cut by Microsoft with Random House and
Simon &AMP; Schuster raised fears about monopolies and limited consumer
access. Want to read the electronic version of Michael Crichton's
book ``Timeline'' for free? You can, but only with Microsoft Reader
software.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out this isn't a conspiracy, just a limited- time offer to
create marketing buzz. Hundreds of other e-books are available in
many electronic formats. As officials at Random House and Simon &AMP;
Schuster point out, publishers make money by offering lots of
options _ conventional books, audio books, and different electronic
versions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Simon &AMP; Schuster does plan to announce the release of a
book that will only be published electronically. This is not an
information blackout, but it is bad news for some _ including the
blind, teenagers whose families can't afford computers, those whose
eyes or temperaments can't tolerate computer text, and others not
on line.
</P>
<P>
   A Simon &AMP; Schuster official says the company needs freedom to
experiment with such releases. It's an argument with some merit, if
the experiment leads to productive discoveries. In general, though,
e-books ought to create possibilities, not limit them. Simple
mercies include loading e-reading devices with textbooks for
students who would otherwise be crushed by the weight of their book
bags. Consumer opportunities might include electronic travel books
that would be easy to access and update. Commuters with hand-held
devices might no longer have to wrestle newspapers into submission
on crowded subway cars.
</P>
<P>
   Part of literacy's great history, e-books have to uphold a
tradition of making human thought infinitely more accessible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
