<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MOSCOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S HANDICAP IN MOSCOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Displaying his fabled empathy, President Clinton acknowledged
Monday to Russia's parliament that many Russians suspect ``America
does not wish you well.'' Clinton assured the legislators this was
a misconception. Calling on his uncanny knack for telling an
audience what it wishes to hear, Clinton said: ``The United States
wants a strong Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   As ever, the president's performance in Moscow was suffused with
an acute feel for the political psychology of his hosts. Russians
across the political spectrum do resent the way Washington seems to
treat their country. An egregious example of the Russian tilt
toward a paranoid view of the United States was the boorish
behavior of Vladimir Zhirinovsky. As Clinton concluded his speech
to the Duma, the nationalist member of parliament screamed at his
colleagues for applauding their guest.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Zhirinovsky said of the remarks he had directed at
Clinton: ``I told him in English: Lift the blockade on Iraq,
withdraw troops from Yugoslavia, and do not intervene in Russian
affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, few take Zhirinovsky seriously anymore. Nonetheless,
his ranting may reverberate in the Russian psyche. Criticism of
Russian massacres of civilians in Chechnya is considered
intervention in Russian affairs even by sober officials in the
Kremlin. The NATO bombing of Serbia by US planes is perceived by
many Russians as unwarranted aggression against a sovereign state.
There are even some Russians, like Zhirinovsky, who believe that
the mass murderer Saddam Hussein is an undeserving victim of US
hegemonism.
</P>
<P>
   So Clinton had the right idea when he tried to talk Russians out
of their suspicions. But his mission was foredoomed by the great
burden he brought to Moscow _ a national missile defense scheme
that is not technologically feasible at present and that confirms
Russian fears of an arrogant America willing to plunge Russia back
into a bankrupting nuclear arms race. Washington has enough
disputes with Moscow over Chechnya, money laundering, weapons
proliferation, Caspian oil, and NATO expansion. The mirage of a
national missile defense should not be allowed to cause chronic
enmity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
