<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-MEDIAONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC PUTS CONDITIONS, SEAL OF APPROVAL ON ATT-MEDIAONE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the key federal approval in hand, AT&AMP;T Corp. says it hopes
to complete its acquisition of MediaOne Group &UR;  &LR; by August.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission approved the $58 billion
takeover Monday, but imposed conditions aimed at preventing the
telephone giant from achieving excessive control over the US cable
market.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the FCC approval, within a year AT&AMP;T must unload
either 40 percent of the combined companies' cable subscribers, or
MediaOne's 25.5 percent stake in Time Warner Entertainment, or
multibillion-dollar television programming interests including
Liberty Media.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T had no immediate comment on which option it will pursue. In
a conference call with reporters, AT&AMP;T general counsel James
Cicconi indicated the company thinks it could comply with the FCC
by selling fewer than the reported 9.7 million subscribers or
taking a step short of an outright sale of Liberty Media and other
programming companies.
</P>
<P>
   Greater Boston, along with Chicago and San Francisco, is one of
three ``super clusters'' that each have over 1.5 million AT&AMP;T and
MediaOne subscribers where the companies see huge opportunities in
marketing local telephone and Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   With MediaOne, AT&AMP;T would own outright systems serving 16
million cable subscribers nationally, and own interests in systems
serving nearly 17 million more, most of them through MediaOne's
minority stake in Time Warner Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   RoadRunner Internet subscribers may be moved to AT&AMP;T-controlled
Excite(at)Home in the next two years, under a consent decree
reached last month with Justice Department antitrust prosecutors
who reviwed the MediaOne deal.
</P>
<P>
   But otherwise, MediaOne customers should expect little immediate
change in service offerings, aside from probably new reduced-price
package deals to get telephone service as well as TV and Net
access, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us at AT&AMP;T are delighted by the FCC's decision,''
Cicconi said.
</P>
<P>
   The move also apparently pleased Wall Street, where MediaOne
shares rose $2.3125 to $69.3125 and AT&AMP;T, the nation's third most
widely owned stock, rose $1.125 to $36.25.
</P>
<P>
   As initially announced last year, the deal values MediaOne
shares at $85 each in AT&AMP;T stock and cash. Unless AT&AMP;T stock
returns to levels over $50, where it traded for much of the last
year, the phone giant may have to come up with billions of dollars
more cash for MediaOne owners to close the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission approval represents a key
leap for AT&AMP;T's bet-the-company gamble on acquiring cable systems
to provide phone service and Net access to millions of US homes
through upgraded cable TV systems.
</P>
<P>
   The MediaOne deal is part of a $120 billion move by AT&AMP;T, which
has also bought cable provide TCI Inc., to move out of the dying
long-distance phone market and compete with companies such as Bell
Atlantic for local phone and Net customers.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T would have to unload cable interests to comply with federal
rules forbidding any one company from controlling more than 30
percent of the multichannel TV market, defined to include cable and
satellite-dish systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision strikes the appropriate balance between
promoting competition in local telephone service and protecting
competition in cable and high-speed Internet service,'' FCC
chairman William E. Kennard said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the three divestiture options offered by the FCC is
especially appealing for AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Dumping the interest in Time Warner could remove AT&AMP;T's leverage
in its negotiations to sell local phone service over Time Warner
systems. Selling Liberty Media could lead to a multibillion-dollar
tax bill for capital gains. And unloading 9 million cable
subscribers undercuts AT&AMP;T's goal of becoming a nearly nationwide
alternative to local phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Cicconi said the company is ``confident that we can comply''
with the FCC conditions, but repeatedly suggested the company
thinks it can get away with a modified version of one of the FCC
plans. ``I am certainly not ruling out any of the options,''
Cicconi said. ``We've got time to assess them and make (a)
determination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
