<SLUG> BC-JBAKER-BREAKOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
J. BAKER SEES BREAKOUT YEAR AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a new e-commerce and catalog strategy partly borrowed from
a recent acquisition, J. Baker Inc. thinks it's finally ready for a
breakout year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the best kept secret in Boston,'' said Alan I.
Weinstein, chief executive of a Canton, Mass. apparel and shoe
retailer with about 650 stores and sales last year of $665.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, J. Baker bought an apparel chain called Repp Ltd. Aside
from 135 stores, Repp also had a catalog and e-commerce operation,
something lacking in J. Baker's biggest clothing chain, Casual Male
Big &AMP; Tall.
</P>
<P>
   By expanding Repp's Georgia call center and fulfillment
warehouse and by making them do double-duty for both the Repp and
Casual Male chains, J. Baker has the potential to swell annual
sales by an additional $100 million to $150 million over the next
three to five years, Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Casual Male sent out its first catalog in March, and a retail
Web site, www.Casualmale.com, just went live, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been disappointed by upbeat forecasts from J.
Baker before. After sustaining big losses in the mid-1990s, the
company has rebounded to modest profitability, though its stock
price has generally languished in the $6 to $7 range.
</P>
<P>
   For most of its history, the name J. Baker has been synonymous
with shoes. But during the mid-90s, the shoe business became
fiercely competitive, and J. Baker suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, it had branched out with stores that sell clothing
to big and tall men. Gradually, the sideline eclipsed the mainstay,
and some of the shoe business was sold as J. Baker sought to become
the go-to clothing brand for big men.
</P>
<P>
   With about 400 stores, Casual Male has the muscle to be an
important force in a $5.6 billion US market for big men's clothes,
according to investment bank Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   While other big shots in big clothes include Sears, Roebuck and
Co. and J.C. Penney Co., nearly half the dollars that men spend on
outsized duds are rung up by mom-and-pop stores; those bit players
are vulnerable to having sales taken away by the much bigger J.
Baker, according to a recent Bear Stearns report.
</P>
<P>
   J. Baker also operates Work 'n Gear, a chain that sells clothes
nurses and construction workers might wear on the job.
</P>
<P>
   J. Baker also runs shoe departments in stores owned by other
retailers such as Bradlees Inc. and Ames Department Stores Inc.
Shoes accounted for 38 percent of J. Baker's sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   Like Casual Male, Repp aims at the 15 percent of the US adult
male population that requires outsized clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Though Repp and Casual Male target the same male market, the two
chains segment it by income levels.
</P>
<P>
   Casual Male and Repp represent the better and best parts of a
``good, better, best'' strategy. If Repp sells to large, upscale
men and Casual Male sells to large, middle-income men, then J.
Baker's outlet stores, in the process of being renamed B&AMP;T Factory
Stores, aim at large men of more modest means.
</P>
<P>
   J. Baker operates about 50 B&AMP;T stores, and Weinstein thinks that
number can triple.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Repp offered J. Baker an added bonus _ a
blueprint for taking Casual Male into catalogs and onto the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of starting e-commerce and catalog businesses from
scratch, J. Baker could draw on Repp's expertise and infrastructure
to expand Casual Male into new sales channels.
</P>
<P>
   J. Baker recently issued first-quarter results. Sales were up 32
percent to $170 million, partly due to the Repp acquisition. Net
income rose 58 percent to $1.5 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
