<SLUG> BC-TONY-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEERS FOR TONY BROADCAST, DESPITE A DROP IN THE RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: a list of winners appears at end of story.) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite the return of Rosie O'Donnell as host, the
competition may have been just too much for the Tony Awards on
Sunday night. The show was up against ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' the season premiere of ``Sex and the City,'' and the
Lakers-Trail Blazers game.
</P>
<P>
   The fast national rating for the two-hour CBS broadcast _
meaning an early tally _ was the lowest ever: 6.1, down from 7.0
last year. The ratings have been steadily declining, from 8.4 in
1998 and 9.6 in 1997. Each rating point represents just over a
million homes.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, within the theater industry the consensus was that
this year's ceremony was a great improvement over last year's. In
addition to what many considered a misguided effort to honor
straight plays with a montage of lines, last year's show at the
last minute dropped the number from one of the nominated musicals,
``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'' because of time constraints.
</P>
<P>
   This year the show ended early, all the musical numbers were
performed, and most people in the industry agreed that the
broadcast made Broadway look exciting.
</P>
<P>
   There were those who came away disappointed, like the creators
of ``The Wild Party,'' which won no awards and, with flagging
ticket sales, was in need of a boost. George C. Wolfe, the
director, co-writer and co-producer of the show, said that there
were no plans yet to close it.
</P>
<P>
   Other shows shut out of the awards included Susan Stroman's
revival of ``Music Man,'' Matthew Warchus' acclaimed production of
Sam Shepard's ``True West,'' and ``Dirty Blonde,'' Claudia Shear's
homage to Mae West.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HONORS ON BROADWAY: THIS YEAR'S TONY AWARDS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are this year's winners of the Tony Awards, presented
Sunday at Radio City Music Hall:
</P>
<P>
   Play: ``Copenhagen''
</P>
<P>
   Musical: ``Contact''
</P>
<P>
   Book of a Musical: ``James Joyce's `The Dead,''' Richard Nelson
</P>
<P>
