<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore calls Tarboro graduates 'heroes'
 &HT;    By Gene Metrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TARBORO _ Vice President Al Gore on Monday told the members of
the Tarboro High School Class of 2000 they were ``American heroes''
for the part they played in helping their community recover from
the 1999 flood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world witnessed your bravery, your dignity, your
generosity and your grace under pressure,'' Gore said during his
12-minute commencement address. ``After what you've been through,
with what you have already overcome, there's nothing in this world
that you cannot do.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before a crowd of more than 2,400 people who filled the
stands at the school's football stadium, Gore told the 136
graduating seniors to always remember the ``quiet acts of courage
and simple acts of caring'' that united the community as it
struggled to overcome the devastation wrought by Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rising tide of floodwater was followed by a mighty wave of
compassion and concern for others,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore recounted how some of the students had been dropped off by
helicopters ``on this very field'' after losing practically all of
their possessions to the flood. With the high school gym turned
into an emergency shelter for homeless flood victims, many of the
students - some left homeless themselves _ chipped in to help
distribute food, clothing, drinking water and other supplies and
support to the victims, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are an outstanding success by any measure,'' he said.
``You have faced tremendous obstacles and you have endured. We're
all proud of you.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president urged the students to view the graduation
ceremony as a ``vantage point'' from which to chart their future
successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The values that we stand for when we are at our best are the
same values you embodied and lived when you were helping others in
a time of challenge and need,'' he said. ``You have changed your
town for the better - now, you have the same power to change
America for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore made no mention of politics or the 2000 presidential
campaign, but said he was ready to go on the record with a
``controversial statement'' about the Lady Vikings basketball
team's final game in the state regional tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the closing seconds of the game against St. Paul's,
Marquetta was fouled,'' he said, referring to Marquetta Dickens'
final shot attempt in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. John Edwards and U.S. Rep. Eva Clayton, D-1st
District, attended the ceremony with Gore. Edwards said that Gore's
father, the late Sen. Albert Gore, ``taught his son heroic life
lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for a model of what a good life can do, you
need look no further than the vice president of the United States,
Al Gore,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   In closing, Gore encouraged the graduates to continue to find
meaning in their lives in their relationships with other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say exactly where the 21st century will take us, but
I believe with all my heart that it can be the greatest time in all
of history,'' he said. ``I have great faith in you, the Tarboro
Class of 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
