u i BC-IRELAND-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      06-05 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD ARGUMENTS, OLD CONFRONTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As the power-sharing Northern Ireland Assembly
reconvened Monday for the first time in four months, onlookers
could be forgiven for thinking they had seen it all before.
</P>
<P>
   There was the Big Man, the Rev. Ian Paisley, flailing his arms
in the East Belfast assembly, protesting how disgraceful it was
that Irish republicans refuse to fly the Union Jack over the
government buildings they now control.
</P>
<P>
   With Irish republicans, once sworn to destroy the state and now
part of the establishment, it is a new Northern Ireland, but the
arguments are old. Paisley, a fundamentalist
preacher-turned-politician, came to prominence in the 1960s by
challenging the right of Catholic nationalists to fly the Irish
tricolor anywhere in Northern Ireland. It was treason, he fumed
then.
</P>
<P>
   It's treason now, he fumed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The resumption of sessions in the ornate parliamentary chambers
at Stormont was a culmination of the compromise that saw the Irish
Republican Army vow to allow international inspectors to check its
arms dumps, and the Ulster Unionist Party, which represents most
Protestants, to put aside its demands that the IRA begin disarming
before it would resume a power-sharing government with Sinn Fein,
the IRA's political wing.
</P>
<P>
   It was a promising return to democracy, but no one should be
under any illusions about the difficulties that lie ahead. The most
obvious is the vow by Paisley and his Democratic Unionists to make
the power-sharing government unworkable by filibustering, having
their two Cabinet ministers resign regularly to disrupt its
workings, and putting forward purposely disruptive motions like the
one Monday that demanded the 108-member assembly expel Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   But dissident Irish republicans are as determined as Paisley to
wreck the assembly in particular and the peace process in general.
They put a bomb on Hammersmith Bridge in London last week and have
vowed to mount an offensive in the British capital.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, meanwhile, the annual marching season peaks, as
Protestant groups demand to march through Catholic neighborhoods
where they are not wanted. The Protestants say they are expressing
their heritage; Catholics see it as bigoted triumphalism dressed up
as parades.
</P>
<P>
   While policing and security matters are still the domain of the
British government, the power-sharing assembly in Belfast will
debate and try to find a compromise on the vexing issue of parades.
And as it did Monday, the assembly will continue to debate and try
to resolve the dispute over symbols, such as flags and the badges
for and name of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the 90
percent-Protestant police force that most Catholics want
drastically reformed and which most Protestants want to remain as
is.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists of all stripes are outraged that the Sinn Fein Cabinet
members, Education Minister Martin McGuinness and Health Minister
Bairbre de Brun, refuse to fly the Union Jack over the buildings
that house their offices. In an interview, McGuinness said he would
authorize the flying of the Union Jack beside an Irish tricolor. He
said he is not trying to deny the right of British people to see
their flag, only to secure the same right for Irish people.
</P>
<P>
   Paisley, not surprisingly, was apoplectic at the prospect of
McGuinness, a former IRA chief of staff, unilaterally deciding not
to fly what Paisley called ``the national flag.''
</P>
<P>
   While Paisley ranted, de Brun and first minister David Trimble,
the Ulster Unionist leader, tried to make sure the health budget
wasn't cut.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein leader, seemed almost plaintive when
he spoke to reporters at Stormont Monday, saying, ``All sensible
people will want to see these institutions functioning not just
around the big emotive issues, but on the crucially important
issues which affect people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But as he quietly tries to mollify rejectionists in his own
camp, Gerry Adams knows better than most that not all of the people
in Northern Ireland are sensible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
