<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMSON-PRIMARK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMSON AGREES TO BUY PRIMARK FOR $1.08 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomson Corp., owner of Boston's Thomson Financial, has agreed
to buy Primark Corp., a Waltham, Mass. provider of financial and
economic data, for $1.08 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Thomson will pay $38 a share for Primark, a 31
percent premium over Friday's close. The Toronto-based publisher
and financial information company, which is in the process of
selling its 130 North American newspapers, will assume $235 million
of Primark's debt as part of the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will bolster Thomson's roster of financial data units
that sell information and software to professional investors. And,
in a move that will affect investors who closely watch Wall Street
analysts' earnings estimates, Thomson's First Call and Primark's
IBES International Inc. _ the two biggest providers of earnings
estimates _ would be combined under one company.
</P>
<P>
   Primark shares rose $8.25 Monday, to $37.25, while some
investors wondered if a rival bidder might surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a little low,'' Michael Kupinski, an analyst with
A.G. Edwards in St. Louis said of the purchase price. ``The
question now is, could there be room for a sweetened offer or the
emergence of a competing bidder?''
</P>
<P>
   Primark has been looking for a buyer for more than two years.
Thomson took a look at that time, as did an array of companies,
including McGraw-Hill Cos., which is said to have offered around
$50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Both Thomson and Primark have changed significantly since.
Thomson has been refashioning itself into an ``e-information and
solutions'' company, with a focus on business clients. In addition
to selling its newspapers, Thomson since 1989 has sold its oil and
gas operation and a travel business in the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Richard J. Harrington, the chief executive of Thomson, said,
``We're much further along in our own strategy.'' He said Primark's
international reach, with 55 percent of its business overseas,
would enhance Thomson's business: ``It gives us increased scale and
resources to serve our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Primark, for its part, last month sold its Yankee Group unit, a
Boston high-tech consulting and research firm, for $72.5 million to
Reuters Group, the London news service and information company.
Reuters is a rival of Thomson. Primark had revenue of $495 million
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson Financial employs about 3,000 people at a downtown
campus and focuses on selling information and services to mutual
fund companies and brokerages. Under the deal, Primark would become
part of Thomson Financial. Primark's chief executive, Joseph E.
Kasputys, would become chairman of Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said there would be some overlap in administrative
employees at the companies, which could result in job cuts. For the
most part, he said, ``There's probably not much redundancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomson said the purchase would eat into earnings in 2000 and
2001. Thomson shares dipped $1.80 (Canadian) to $49.20.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
