<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5374 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-R-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-AR     06-05 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: WHAT COULD BE GOOD ABOUT MORNING SICKNESS?
PLENTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Evolution has not always come up with things people consider
wonderful. Note mosquitoes, sickle cell anemia and the killer
instinct. But according to evolutionary theory, there is a reason
for everything that has evolved. However obnoxious it may seem,
somehow it enhances survival.
</P>
<P>
   And so it seems that survival is the likely reason for morning
sickness, survival not just of the unborn child but also of the
pregnant woman who must bear the burden of its prenatal
development. That is the conclusion of two Cornell University
evolutionary biologists after examining the results of nearly
80,000 successful and unsuccessful pregnancies, correlating their
findings with the incidence of morning sickness and the development
during early pregnancy of food aversions and cravings.
</P>
<P>
   MOTHER AND BABY BENEFIT _ Samuel Flaxman, a graduate student,
and Dr. Paul Sherman, a professor of neurobiology and behavior,
report in the current issue of the Quarterly Review of Biology that
nausea and vomiting in pregnancy, which they call NVP, helps to
protect both mother and fetus from exposure to infectious organisms
and toxic chemicals that could result in fetal damage, miscarriage
or even, in primitive societies at least, maternal death.
</P>
<P>
   Morning sickness, these researchers note, is a misnomer. It can
occur at any time of the day (though not at night while a woman is
asleep) and, they insist, it is not a sickness. It is a 100 percent
normal characteristic of early pregnancy that is associated with a
reduced risk of miscarriage and a greater chance that the pregnancy
will have a healthy outcome. All nine studies that have explored
this relationship in about 20,000 pregnancies showed that women who
experienced the condition were significantly less likely to
miscarry.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than morning sickness, NVP should be called ``wellness
insurance,'' Sherman said. Worldwide and in the United States,
two-thirds of pregnant women acquire this free insurance to varying
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that a pregnant woman afflicted with nausea and
vomiting will be unlikely to consume certain foods that may be
damaging to her fetus at a time when its major organ systems are
developing. Organ development takes place during the first three
months of pregnancy, which is when morning sickness is most
prominent. ``There is an obvious _ indeed striking _ correspondence
between the sensitive periods in embryonic organogenesis and the
peak occurrence of NVP,'' the scientists wrote.
</P>
<P>
   At this time, too, the Cornell biologists noted, a pregnant
woman's immune system is naturally suppressed to keep her from
rejecting the fetus as a foreign tissue. But immune suppression
renders her more susceptible to food-borne parasites and
microorganisms and the toxins they produce, so NVP would protect
her, too.
</P>
<P>
   THE MAIN PROBLEM _ While other theorists, like Dr. Margie Profet
of the University of California at Berkeley, have suggested that
morning sickness evolved to protect the embryo and young fetus from
exposure to natural dietary toxins in vegetables, spices and some
fruits that might cause malformations, the Cornell researchers'
exhaustive analysis of all existing evidence gathered since 1940
has indicated that meat, poultry, fish and eggs are far more
important sources of possible pregnancy problems. Until
refrigeration, these foods were most likely to harbor infectious
and toxic organisms that could sicken a pregnant woman, damage her
fetus or cause an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Cornell report found, the meat category leads the
list of food aversions that develop during pregnancy; nonalcoholic
beverages like coffee come second, and vegetables a distant third.
Having completely lost my appetite for meat and coffee during my
own pregnancy, I am inclined to think the Cornell biologists are
right on target. For most women suffering from NVP, bland
carbohydrate foods like bread, cereal and grains have the greatest
appeal, though cravings for fruit and fruit juice, desserts, ice
cream and sometimes unusual foods are commonplace. Studies have
shown that very few pregnant women crave alcohol, which is a cause
of fetal malformations.
</P>
<P>
   In further support of their theory, the Cornell team examined
dietary patterns in seven nonindustrial societies where pregnant
women never or rarely experience morning sickness and compared the
results with 20 similar societies in which NVP occurs. Those
societies without NVP ``were significantly less likely to have meat
as a dietary staple'' and were ``significantly more likely to have
corn as a dietary staple,'' the scientists wrote.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Also intriguing are the different rates of NVP in industrialized
societies that have different dietary habits. The highest frequency
for a single country was in Japan, a nation fond of eating raw
fish, where 84 percent of the pregnant women in one study reported
experiencing nausea and vomiting. Raw fish, a dietary no-no during
pregnancy in this country, can carry parasites that could harm a
fetus in addition to making the pregnant woman quite ill. Likewise,
undercooked meat, popular in many Western countries where NVP
frequencies are high, can carry a parasite called toxoplasma that
causes serious congenital defects.
</P>
<P>
   But even cooked meat that is not spoiled can be a problem,
Sherman said. If the meat sat around unrefrigerated for a while, it
could become contaminated with pathogens like E. coli even though
it looks and smells fine, he explained. His evolution-based
conclusion: ``A pregnant woman's body responds to the smell and
taste of meat because this category of food in general can be
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cornell biologists do not dispute the role that the hormones
of pregnancy are known to play in touching off morning sickness.
Rather, Sherman said, ``the hormones explain how this happens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking why it happens,'' he said. ``Why do the hormones
cause these particular symptoms of nausea and vomiting and food
aversions? Why not headaches or backaches?'' Their answer is that
nausea and vomiting in early pregnancy is protective; it helps to
guarantee the next generation will be healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Studies suggest that morning sickness has a genetic component.
Women are much more likely to experience it if their mothers or
sisters also had NVP Forms of morning sickness have also been
observed in domestic dogs and captive rhesus monkeys and
chimpanzees.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SHOULD A WOMAN DO? _ Women who do not experience morning
sickness should not fret, Sherman said, if they live in
industrialized countries where the food supply is safe. But neither
should heroic measures be taken to prevent ``normal'' NVP. The best
way to alleviate the problem is to always have some food in one's
stomach. Hence, the common advice to keep crackers on the night
table and to eat several before getting out of bed in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said he saw ``no reason to believe that suppressing the
symptoms of NVP would improve the outcome of a pregnancy'' unless a
woman developed hyperemesis, continual vomiting that occurs in only
half of 1 percent of pregnancies and which requires hospital
treatment. Ordinary morning sickness, he said, ``is a phenomenon
that is adaptive, not pathological. It's not a symptom of a failing
female body. It's a temporary condition that occurs early in
pregnancy when fetal demands are small and would not be a major
drain on a woman's resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman also sees no reason to force a pregnant woman to consume
any foods to which she has developed an aversion. In most women,
aversions that start in the first trimester dissipate during the
second along with a waning of NVP.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all pregnant women should be taking daily prenatal
vitamin-mineral supplements, which help compensate for any
nutrients missing while suffering from NVP. Most important in the
first months of pregnancy is folic acid (or folate), which has been
shown to greatly reduce the risk that the baby will suffer a spinal
defect when consumed at a level of 400 micrograms a day. Since
January 1998, flour and grain products (foods that are unlikely to
be on a pregnant woman's list of aversions) have been fortified
with folic acid.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
