<SLUG> BC-HOMEPLUG-STANDARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP AGREES ON HOME-WIRING ELECTRONICS STANDARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leading technology companies have taken another step toward the
development of plug-and-play computer networks that would run over
a home's electrical wiring.
</P>
<P>
   The HomePlug Powerline Alliance, a group of more than three
dozen high-tech firms, Monday settled on a framework for an
industry-wide powerline networking standard. The standard will be
based on technology developed by Ocala, Fla.-based Intellon Inc.
The Intellon system will be refined and should be adopted as a
final standard by the fourth quarter of 2000. Retail products using
the standard should be available in about a year.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the alliance, which includes chipmaker Intel Corp.
and networking hardware maker Cisco Systems Inc., is the creation
of computers and other electronic devices that will be able to talk
to each other through the same electrical outlets that provide them
with power.
</P>
<P>
   Most computer networks now employ a technology called Ethernet,
which uses special cables that must be connected to every machine
on the network. These wired networks are common in businesses, and
many new homes have such wiring built into them as well. But it's
difficult and costly to install new wiring in millions of existing
homes.
</P>
<P>
   But every home has electrical wiring. Alberto Mantovani,
president of HomePlug, says it makes sense to turn the socket into
a data port. ``You have to be connected,'' said Mantovani. ``Why
not get access to the Internet and the home network through that
connection?''
</P>
<P>
   The products planned by HomePlug will be able to transmit data
over electrical wiring at a rate of 10 million bits per second _
the same speed found on many corporate computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   There are already a number of products that use electrical
wiring to transmit data, but there's been no standard way of doing
it. Any reliable system must be carefully designed to filter out
electronic noise common on electrical networks. For example,
turning on a hair dryer in another part of the house could garble
data on the network unless this noise is filtered out.
</P>
<P>
   HomePlug officials think the Intellon system offers the best
solution to such problems.
</P>
<P>
   Mantovani said early HomePlug products will be used not to
deliver Internet access but solely to connect multiple computers
inside the home. A user who wants high-speed Internet access will
still need a cable modem or DSL telephone modem. But later versions
of the HomePlug technology might enable the delivery of high-speed
Internet services directly through the electrical wires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
