A5379 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURT-GRANDPARENTS-HN     06-05 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-GRANDPARENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT LIMITS GRANDPARENTS' RIGHT TO VISIT GRANDCHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wading into the complexities of modern American
families, the Supreme Court ruled Monday that parents generally
have the right to decide whom their children may visit, including
the time spent with grandparents and other relatives.
</P>
<P>
   In a 6-3 decision, the court struck down a Washington state
judge's order under a law that allowed ``any person'' _ a
non-relative as well as a grandparent _ to seek visitation rights
with children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington's breathtakingly broad statute effectively permits
a court to disregard and overturn any decision by a fit custodial
parent concerning visitation based solely on the judge's
determination of the child's best interest,'' Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor wrote in the court's main opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ruling did not strike down the Washington statute,
it could threaten visitation orders previously won under the law by
grandparents in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The complicated decision yielded six opinions from the
nine-member court, but no one opinion attracted a majority of five.
</P>
<P>
   Although giving a slight boost to parental rights, the ruling
stopped well short of answering all questions that state courts
face daily in visitation battles over children. In particular, the
high court did not give parents absolute veto power over who gets
to visit their children. Nor did it give grandparents nationwide
any special status in visitation cases.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Monday's decision said nothing to directly endanger
grandparent-visitation laws in the other 49 states.
</P>
<P>
   Such laws are most frequently invoked when parents divorce or
die. Some state statutes require proof of a close relationship
between children and grandparents before visits can be ordered.
Still others insist that courts consider the effect of such visits
on parent-child relationships.
</P>
<P>
   All states require that judges must determine, before they
permit visits between children and their grandparents, whether such
visits are in the children's best interests.The American
Association of Retired Persons (AARP) praised the court for not
striking down the state law, saying that ``grandparents play an
important role'' in the lives of their grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The National Women's Law Center, a Washington-based legal
watchdog organization, called the decision a ``victory'' for
parents. ``States cannot simply substitute their judgments for a
parent's, simply because a state judge believes a `better' decision
could be made,'' said Joan Entmacher, the law center's vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington state dispute arose from Gary and Jenifer
Troxel's efforts to see their two granddaughters, now 10 and 8,
over the objections of the girls' mother. The mother, Tommie
Granville, had not married the girls' father, the Troxels' son
Brad. The girls were regular visitors at the elder Troxels' home
while their son was alive.
</P>
<P>
   After Brad Troxel's suicide in 1993, Granville married Kelly
Wynn, who adopted the girls. She sought to limit the girls' visits
with the Troxels to one day a month so her new blended family,
which includes six other children, could bond, she said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1993, the dispute had moved into the courts, with
the Troxels arguing that the bond between them and their
grandchildren was a positive experience for children that should be
legally protected.
</P>
<P>
   The trial judge ruled in 1995 that the Troxels could have one
visit a month, from Saturday afternoon through Sunday afternoon,
plus one week during the summer and four hours on each
granddaughter's birthday. But in 1997, a state appeals court
reversed that decision. Then, in December 1998, in a resounding
victory for Tommie Wynn, the Washington Supreme Court voted 5-4 to
invalidate the state's visitation statute, saying it violated
parents' constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, while declining to strike down the law, the U.S.
Supreme Court partially affirmed the state high court decision by
ruling that the trial judge had violated the parent's Fourteenth
Amendment right to due process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visitation order (by the trial court) was an
unconstitutional infringement on Granville's fundamental right to
make decisions concerning the care, custody and control of her two
daughters,'' O'Connor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Joining O'Connor were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Justices David H. Souter and Clarence Thomas wrote concurring
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   In his concurrence, Thomas said he agreed with O'Connor ``that
this court's recognition of a fundamental right of parents to
direct the upbringing of their children resolves this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Souter said the state law ``sweeps too broadly in allowing
anyone at any time to request visitation rights'' and therefore
gives state courts ``too much discretion in every case.''
</P>
<P>
   Justices John Paul Stevens, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M.
Kennedy each wrote dissenting opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said that the Washington statute ``merely gives an
individual _ with whom a child may have an established relationship
_ the procedural right to ask the state to act as arbiter, through
the entirely well-known best-interests standard, between the
parent's protected interests and the child's.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixty million Americans are grandparents, including six of the
court's members: O'Connor, Rehnquist, Stevens, Scalia, Kennedy and
Ginsburg. Thomas was raised by his grandparents. The Granville case
was one of the most closely watched of the term and prompted
friend-of-the-court briefs from numerous organizations and more
than a dozen states.
</P>
<P>
   Among the groups monitoring the case were gay and lesbian
organizations, which argued that ``de facto'' parents who are not
biologically related to the children they are raising should be
given deference in visitation cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay parents sometimes must defend themselves from legal
challenges by meddling third parties who disapprove of the parents'
sexual orientation, while non-biological parents can be shut out of
their children's lives entirely,'' said Ruth E. Harlow, deputy
legal director for Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund, a New
York City-based gay-rights group.
</P>
<P>
   Among the groups weighing in for the grandparents were the AARP
and the National Conference of State Legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   A survey released in January by AARP found about one in nine
American grandparents above the age of 50 helps care for at least
one grandchild. The survey showed that 8 percent provide day care
regularly and 3 percent actually rear a grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   Of the grandparents who don't live with their grandchildren or
provide day care, 44 percent see them once a week.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INDONESIA-ECON-NYT &LR;      06-05 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA   AND IMF REJECT MEASURES TO PROP UP CURRENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ In a move that seems likely to snuff out
Indonesia's latest flirtation with currency controls, the new
managing director of the International Monetary Fund declared
Monday that closing off Indonesia's capital markets would hinder
the nation's fragile economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF's chief, Horst Kohler, emerged from a breakfast meeting
with President Abdurrahman Wahid and briskly dispelled speculation
that the IMF would agree to an Indonesian effort to defend its
faltering currency, the rupiah, by placing controls on the
currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and I fully agreed that the introduction of
capital controls would be counterproductive,'' said Kohler, who was
making his first visit to Jakarta as IMF director. ``He feels that
it would be the wrong decision, and I agree, because such a
decision would deter foreign investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, a senior economic adviser to President Wahid,
Sofyan Wanandi, said: ``It's over. It's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Indonesian officials said they were considering some
type of controls to stabilize the rupiah, which has dropped 18
percent in value since the beginning of the year because of fears
of renewed political unrest. Indonesia considered setting a fixed
rate for the rupiah in early 1998, after a far more serious slide,
but backed off under intense pressure from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Although the economy has crept back from the abyss of 1998, it
still depends on billions of dollars in loans from the fund to bail
out debt-ridden banks and corporations. Last week, the IMF approved
a $372 million loan that had been delayed because officials at the
fund were unhappy with the fitful pace of economic restructuring
under President Wahid.
</P>
<P>
   Kohler made it clear Monday that Indonesia's future lay in
strictly adhering to the IMF's program. He urged the Indonesian
Bank Restructuring Authority to accelerate the sale of assets of
insolvent banks and companies. Failure to do so, he said, ``would
lead to a deterioration in the asset values.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohler's predecessor, Michel Camdessus, aroused resentment in
1998 when he stood watching with arms folded, as Indonesia's
longtime president, Suharto, reluctantly signed a loan agreement
with the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Though Kohler did not mince words Monday, he took pains not to
sound imperious. ``We are here to help and support, not to lecture
and impose,'' he said. ``But of course we offer frank advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's markets responded quickly to Kohler. The rupiah,
which had been rallying in recent days on speculation that it might
be stabilized, slipped to a rate of 8,460 to the United States
dollar from 8,400. But the stock market welcomed the news, jumping
2.14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Capital controls have gained some credibility in Asia in the
last two years, since Malaysia imposed controls on its currency and
embarked on a powerful recovery. Analysts here said that officials
were focusing less on a fixed exchange rate than on measures to
keep rupiah in the country, like requiring exporters to repatriate
and convert their foreign-exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But Indonesia is not Malaysia, which has disciplined officials
to police the flow of currencies in and out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't work here,'' said Umar Juoro, a former adviser to
Wahid's immediate predecessor, B.J. Habibie. ``We don't have the
capacity to do it. All it would do is to discourage foreign capital
from coming back to Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   The decline in the rupiah has rattled officials because they
remember that Suharto was ultimately swept out of power by violent
unrest ignited by a weak currency. But some analysts said the
impact of a weaker rupiah would not be as great this time because
it hurts companies with debt denominated in dollars. And most of
those companies are already bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the weak rupiah has bolstered Indonesian exports, which
jumped 29 percent in April compared with April 1999. For Indonesia
to achieve Wahid's personal goal of 5 percent-plus economic growth
this year, it will need continued strength in exports.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest drawback of controls may be political, according to
James W. Castle, an American consultant. Since Indonesia fell into
crisis, the rupiah has been a reliable barometer of public
confidence in the government. The recent decline was precipitated
by Mr. Wahid's decision to dismiss two of his most respected
cabinet ministers and replace them with people regarded as cronies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lesson to the government that there is a price to
pay,'' Mr. Castle said. ``The danger is that it would lose that
feedback mechanism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
