<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMANDMENTS-JUDGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Controversial judge vies for Alabama Supreme Court
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alabama judge Roy Moore is riding the wave of his ``hang ten''
notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   After his 1992 appointment as Etowah County Circuit Judge in
northern Alabama, Moore surveyed his long, narrow Court Room No. 2.
His bench stood three steps off the ground in the left corner of
the room. Except for the portrait of a former judge, the white
acoustic wall tiles were bare.
</P>
<P>
   As Moore explained, ``I wanted something to hang on the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Baptist construction worker picked a redwood tablet
of the Ten Commandments he had carved more than a decade earlier.
He raised the ire of the American Civil Liberties Union, among
others, and was sued.
</P>
<P>
   From the resulting legal battles, the 53-year-old former
Australian ranch hand constructed a formidable soapbox among
Alabama's social conservatives and cultivated a nationwide hero
status among like-minded Christian activists.
</P>
<P>
   The name recognition comes in handy during today's Republican
primary. Moore faces three opponents in the race for chief justice
of the Alabama Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of the battle over the homemade plaque in
Gadsden, more than half the respondents in a February poll had
heard of Moore _ an astounding number for a judicial race. That has
translated into other surveys predicting Moore will land in a
runoff against state Supreme Court Associate Justice Harold See.
</P>
<P>
   The winner faces Democratic civil appeals court Judge Sharon
Yates in November's general elections. Yates has no primary
opposition. Republican Perry Hooper Sr., 74, is retiring as chief
justice.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Johnson, who heads polling for the Alabama Education
Association, says his survey Thursday night of 228 registered
voters who said they'll vote today in the Republican primary shows
Moore winning 33 percent of the vote compared to 28 percent for
See, the favorite of business leaders. The small sample size
generates a margin of error of 6.5 percent, though other larger
polls reveal similar results.
</P>
<P>
   In an April poll, Moore led See 40 percent to 14 percent. See's
aggressive television advertising has helped him cut the gap. In
one ad, See talks about his faith and how he defended Moore's right
to hang the Ten Commandments _ though he doesn't mention his
opponent by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't want to alienate religious voters in this
state,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The undecided bloc of voters is nearly one-quarter of the
respondents. Johnson predicts Moore could win between 40 percent
and 45 percent of today's anticipated small turnout.
</P>
<P>
   The Ten Commandments are an issue to fewer than one of every
five voters, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the broader issue is that the voters do not know the
candidates,'' he said. ``That means they're looking for cues how to
vote. Just the fact that they've heard the name of a judge
contributes to his name recognition... If it's a legislator or
president or a governor, you develop issues. Judicial races are for
the most part devoid of issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, after the ACLU challenged Moore's Ten Commandments
display, Moore ignored a state judge's order to remove the tablet
and stop opening his court session with a prayer. Gov. Fob James,
an evangelical Christian activist in his own right, threatened to
protect Moore's display by calling in the National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Moore is out of town nearly every weekend preaching about the
Ten Commandments, telling the faithful that school shootings would
diminish with more prayer. He decries judges whom he says deny the
religious underpinnings of the country's government.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've taken something away from us that is the most valuable
thing our forefathers held dear _ the freedom to worship God
publicly and privately in the manner we choose,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar crusades by James helped cost the Republican governor
re-election in 1998 and deepened a backwoods notion of the state
that caused business leaders to cringe. Just like James' primary
race two years ago against business-favored Winton Blount, Moore's
contest illustrates the tug of war for the Alabama GOP between
fiscal and social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say Moore is cut from the same philosophical cloth
as James, who once said the Bill of Rights didn't pertain to
Alabama. The former governor often invoked Moore's name during
campaign appearances.
</P>
<P>
   That's why two powerful commerce groups _ the Business Council
of Alabama and the Alabama Farmers Federation _ have endorsed See.
The groups have helped See raise $1.1 million in campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our support is for Judge See and not against any of the other
candidates,'' said Bill O'Connor, president of the Business
Council, tantamount to a state chamber of commerce. ``All we ask
for is impartiality. That's all anybody wants at any station of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Business groups helped convince See to give up his associate
justice seat on the court to run for chief justice. In a state
where business has battled for tort reform, See has developed a
track record for trimming big jury verdicts during his four years
on the state Supreme Court, said University of Alabama political
science professor William Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   But now business leaders face the risk of losing the 5-4
Republican majority on the court if See loses, since Gov. Don
Siegelman likely would appoint a fellow Democrat to fill the
vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows how much business interests value that (chief
justice) seat,'' Stewart said, ``for them to give up (See's) seat
in exchange for a Democratic governor to appoint someone.''
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA SUPREME COURT
</P>
<P>
   Etowah County Circuit Judge Roy Moore hugs his nine-year-old son
Caleb as he attends a civic club luncheon in Montgomery, Ala., on
Monday, June 5, 2000. Moore crisscrossed the state Monday, calling
for a moral revival. But the other candidates seeking the
Republican nomination for chief justice took a lower profile on the
eve of the primary election. Justice Harold See worked in his
Supreme Court office, leaving his ads to carry his message. Circuit
Judge Wayne Thorn telephoned supporters. And criminalappeals court
Judge Pam Baschab appeared on talk radio. (AP Photo/Dave Martin)
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court Justice Harold See works in the library of the
State Judicial Building in Montgomery, Ala., on Monday, June 5,
2000. See is seeking the Republican nomination for Supreme Court
Chief Justice in the election on Tuesday but chose to work in his
office on the state holiday instead of campaigning. (AP Photo/Dave
Martin)
</P>
