<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEPATITIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Public awareness crucial for detection of hepatitis C
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When someone is achy and tired but the doctors can't say why,
it's a good idea to get tested for hepatitis C. More than 2.7
million of the nearly 4 million Americans infected with the viral
liver disease don't know they have it, according to estimates by
the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).
</P>
<P>
   ``In more than 90 percent of the cases, the symptoms are mild or
none at all,'' says Greg Carter, the registered nurse who directs
infection control at Kettering Medical Center. ``Those individuals
that may have chronic fatigue and don't know why should get tested.
So should those who have flulike symptoms that come and go
frequently.''
</P>
<P>
   The most vulnerable are those who received blood transfusions or
dialysis before July 1992, when testing donated blood for the virus
became mandatory. Infected needles are the most common source of
transmission now.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam veterans are at particular risk of the disease because
U.S. military field hospitals performed about 365,000 blood
transfusions there just from 1967 through 1969, according to
Veterans Aimed Toward Awareness. A study last year of 26,000
patients in Department of Veterans Affairs facilities found that
nearly 8 percent had tested positive for hepatitis C, and estimates
for Vietnam vets alone range from 16 percent to 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the past two years did federal officials start notifying
people who received suspect blood that they were at risk for
hepatitis C, which can go undetected for 20 to 30 years. It was
believed the disadvantages of a possible health scare outweighed
the advantages of detecting people for whom treatment was
expensive, debilitating and largely ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of antiviral and alpha-interferon drugs now
achieve long-lasting remission in 40 percent of patients, the CDC
says, up from
</P>
<P>
   25 percent in 1997 as therapy has extended from six months to
12. ``They're more effective if they're given early,'' Carter says.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the drug treatment doesn't help, a diagnosis also lets
patients know they should avoid alcohol and medications that might
damage their livers, and be more careful not to spread the virus.
</P>
<P>
   The public health concern was the main reason behind hepatitis C
awareness campaigns in the last few years, Carter says. ``The
numbers we were seeing were frightening, and the hope was that
bringing awareness might help prevent people from spreading the
disease and maybe save somebody's life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Hepatitis C Coalition was created last month in order
to identify the estimated 200,000 Ohioans with the virus and also
to encourage more research into a cure and a vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Greater awareness has translated into more diagnoses. The number
in Montgomery County rose from 160 in 1996 to 561 last year. The
public announcement Friday that county courts clerk Craig Zimmers
has hepatitis C will shine further light on the disease, Carter
says. ``That was very brave of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The disease is still widely confused with its less deadly
cousins. Hepatitis A, transmitted mostly by contaminated food and
water, can cause a short bout of severe fever, nausea and jaundice,
but not chronic liver disease. Hepatitis B, blood-borne like
hepatitis C, is less likely to cause chronic disease and also can
be prevented through vaccination. Hepatitis C leads to chronic
liver disease in 7 out of 10 people it infects.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis C's death rate of 5 percent is much lower than the
more prominent blood-borne viral infection, HIV and AIDS, but the
CDC estimates it is four times more prevalent. For both infections,
the CDC says more than half the cases are undiagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   Although confirmed U.S. deaths from AIDS fell from 21,000 in
1997 to 10,200 last year, it's an indication of the infections'
relative statuses that the CDC's latest death figures for hepatitis
C show about 10,000 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also want to raise awareness in the legislature and
Congress,'' says Carter, a coalition member. ``They fund the
research.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are working on enzyme inhibitors that would keep the
virus from reproducing. The U.S. Food and Drug Administration is
considering approval of Schering-Plough's more convenient
once-a-week alpha-interferon drug, which was approved in Europe
last week. But aside from the interferon and the antiviral
ribavirin, a liver transplant is the only fall-back option.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly because of hepatitis C, the waiting list for liver donors
has more than tripled in five years to 15,409, adding about 45
names per week since 1998. While the waiting list was only 11
percent higher than the number of liver transplants in 1994, it was
more than three times higher last year.
</P>
<P>
   The recent use of living donors, giving one lobe of their
livers, could shorten the list. Harold and Ian Kaplan of
Beavercreek underwent only the 66th such transplant surgery with an
adult recipient in October. But that number will increase, said Dr.
Douglas Hanto, the Kaplans' University Hospital surgeon in
Cincinnati, ``as we gain experience with it and as long as people
are dying on the waiting list.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Kevin Lamb by e-mail at kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
