</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-GRANDPARENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT AFFIRMS PARENTS' CONTROL IN VISITATION RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US Supreme Court, limiting government intrusion into ``the
private realm of the family,'' affirmed Monday the primacy of
parents in decisions about their children's lives.
</P>
<P>
   On a 6-3 vote, the justices struck down as overly broad a
Washington State law that gave anyone, related or unrelated,
extensive rights to seek court-ordered visitation with children
over their parents' objections.
</P>
<P>
   The case was brought by two grandparents who had wanted to spend
more time with their two granddaughters than the girls' mother
would allow. Grandparent-rights groups nevertheless lauded Monday's
ruling because it left narrower visitation statutes in the other 49
states intact, and because they agreed the Washington law was too
sweeping.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the grandparent-rights groups joined advocates for
children and homosexuals in viewing the high-court ruling _ which
included a section explicitly acknowledging the proliferation of
nontraditional parents _ as a milestone in legal recognition of the
changing composition of US families.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as a parent adequately cares for his or her children
... there will normally be no reason for the state to inject itself
into the private realm of the family to further question the
ability of that parent to make the best decisions concerning the
rearing of that parent's children,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor
wrote in the majority opinion.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, along with several of the five justices who wrote
concurring and dissenting opinions, said the states could still
specify conditions under which people other than parents may ask a
judge to order visitation. But the justices notably did not try to
define what relationships those people needed to have with the
children involved, or what constituted a parent.
</P>
<P>
   Legal analysts said those omissions, whether deliberate or not,
underscored the authority of state politicians and judges to take
bold actions such as the precedent-setting Massachusetts Supreme
Judicial Court ruling last June that granted visitation rights to
the former partner of a lesbian mother.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts said the Supreme Court decision also appeared to
bolster the legal standing of other nontraditional care-givers,
including adoptive parents, foster parents, and grandparents. About
3 percent of America's 60 million grandparents raise grandchildren
and another 8 percent assist in the process, according to the
American Association of Retired Persons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best thing that could have happened to
grandparents,'' said Richard Victor, executive director of the
Grandparents Rights Organization. He added that he was ``relieved''
the court gave the states wide discretion rather than setting any
guidelines, even though its decision provided grandparents with no
special status for seeking visitation.
</P>
<P>
   Ethel Dunn, president of the National Coalition of Grandparents,
said her only concern was that some grandparents would incorrectly
think that their rights had been limited because this had been
widely billed as a pivotal ``grandparents' rights'' case. ``This
affects only the law in Washington, which was far too broad; for
grandparents everywhere else, and for all sorts of nontraditional
families, this is a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The case grew out of a complaint from Gary and Jenifer Troxel, a
couple in Anacortes, Wash., whose daughter-in-law limited their
visits with their two grandaughters after their son died. So the
Troxels asked a state court to award them more time, which it did
in 1995: one weekend a month, a week each summer, and four hours on
the girls' birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor pointed out that neither the Troxels nor any court had
accused the mother, Tommie Granville Wynn, of being an unfit
parent. As a result, the justice asserted, it was wrong to impose
on Wynn the burden of proving that seeing the Troxels would not be
in her children's ``best interests'' _ the standard used in most
states to determine visitation rights.
</P>
<P>
   The state-court order in the Troxels' favor was therefore an
unconstitutional infringement on the mother's right to make
decisions regarding the rearing of her children, O'Connor said. She
denounced the ``sweeping breadth'' of the Washington law on which
the Troxels had based their claim, which she said had been an
``application of that broad, unlimited power.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor pointedly wrote that she was making her decision at a
time when the old notion of a nuclear family _ two married parents
living with their biological children _ was quickly being replaced
by a wide variety of situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demographic changes of the past century make it difficult
to speak of an average American family,'' O'Connor said. ``The
composition of families varies greatly from household to
household.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining O'Connor in the majority were Chief Justice William
Rehnquist and Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen Breyer,
while Justices David Souter and Clarence Thomas wrote separate
concurring opinions. Justices John Paul Stevens, Antonin Scalia and
Anthony Kennedy each wrote dissenting opinions.
</P>
<P>
   The case had long been perceived as a major test of
grandparents' rights. But the extraordinarily broad language in the
Washington State statute evidently turned it into a barometer of
parental and state responsibilities instead.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of those two often-controversial issues led to
the unusual coalition of the left, right, and center in Monday's
court majority. And it explained the equally uncommon spectrum of
support for the justices' decision, with praise coming from groups
as diverse as the American Civil Liberties Union and the
conservative Institute for Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredibly important ruling ... as much for what it
doesn't say as what it does,'' said Joan Hollinger, director of the
child-advocacy program at the University of California Law School
at Berkeley and author of a friend-of-the-court brief in this case
for the National Association of Counsel for Children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Washington State law declared open season on parents, and
that couldn't stand. But, by leaving the door open to the states to
do whatever they choose, while explicitly pointing out the changing
nature of American families, this opinion also has far greater
implications.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Logue, an attorney who also wrote a brief in the case
for the Lambda Legal Defense Fund, a gay-rights organization,
echoed Hollinger's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The justices ... basically are letting the states experiment
with how to balance constitutional rights and the reality of
changing families,'' she said. ``They don't presume that there's
just one way to do this, and that's very important for gay and
lesbian families.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
