u f BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-N     06-05 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT REJECTS BIG CHANGES IN ITS BREAKUP PLAN FOR
MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Responding in detail to Microsoft's criticisms, the
Justice Department Monday rejected any substantive changes in its
plan to break up the company.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the company's proposed revisions ``would undermine or
frustrate the purpose and effectiveness'' of the remedy proposal,
the government said in a brief filed with the judge in the
long-running antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   After Microsoft filed its proposal last week to water down the
government plan _ while still disputing its very premise _ the
Justice Department and 19 state governments that are partners in
the antitrust suit asked for a chance to respond. As a result,
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson postponed his final ruling, expected
at the end of last week, and scheduled two additional filings,
including the government document issued Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft now has until Wednesday to respond, and Jackson will
probably rule late this week. He is widely expected to accept the
government's breakup plan.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Cullinan, a Microsoft spokesman, said the government brief
makes ``only cosmetic changes'' and therefore remains ``vague and
ambiguous as well as excessive and harmful to consumers and the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The government filing Monday notes that Microsoft had asked
Jackson in court on May 24 for an opportunity to comment on ``the
form'' of the government's remedy proposal. But ``many of
Microsoft's comments go beyond merely addressing the proposed
form'' and ``make arguments about the merits that Microsoft has
previously raised and that plaintiffs have addressed in their prior
filings,'' the brief says.
</P>
<P>
   It also notes that Microsoft, in its proposed revisions,
repeatedly tried to reargue the facts of the case, even though
Jackson issued a final ruling on April 3 declaring Microsoft in
wide violation of state and federal antitrust laws. ``Microsoft's
effort to reargue its position should be rejected,'' the brief
says.
</P>
<P>
   The document lists the few Microsoft revisions the government is
willing to accept. Most deal with punctuation or semantics. For
example, Microsoft heatedly objected to the government's
characterization of the breakup plan as a ``reorganization.'' A
Microsoft spokesman, Mark Murray, said, ``That's like saying, when
a tornado hits a house, it's a spring cleaning.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the government agreed to call the breakup a
``divestiture.'' The other changes are of about the same magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest of Microsoft's proposed changes, the government
argues that they ``would create loopholes and permit Microsoft to
continue to engage in anti-competitive practices.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the company had objected to the date when its
intellectual property holdings would be considered allocated to
specific divisions for purposes of any breakup. The government had
set the date at April 27, the day before its remedy proposal was
published, to prevent Microsoft from changing its plans once it
knew the specifics of the government's proposal. Microsoft wanted
to move the date forward. But Monday's brief says: ``Microsoft's
proposal would allow the company to shift assets before the plan of
divestiture is implemented to frustrate the effectiveness of the
final judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the company, in its revision, struck out a provision
requiring Microsoft to inform computer manufacturers _ known as
``original equipment manufacturers,'' or OEMs _ of future plans for
Microsoft products. Monday the government said: ``The proposed
change would allow Microsoft to withhold critical information about
its future plans from certain OEMs in retaliation for their
supporting non-Microsoft products, an OEM concern that was
expressed at trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft tried to write the state attorneys general out of the
case during enforcement of the remedy. The government rejected
that.
</P>
<P>
   The government also turned back Microsoft's proposal to delay
preparation of a plan for implementation of the breakup for a year
instead of four months, as the plaintiffs had proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in the public interest that the remedy contemplated by
the final judgment be implemented as soon as possible,'' the
government said, ``and the time periods proposed by plaintiffs are
adequate to perform the specified tasks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
