<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dot-com magazines grow with Internet
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dot-com bubble may not be limited to the stock market.
Fortune (June 12) sees a good-sized bubble in the proliferation of
dot-com magazines devoted to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Net magazines have great buzz, are loaded with ads, and seem
indispensable guides to the `new economy,''' says Fortune, which
now devotes a big part of its magazine to the dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   The new genre includes Business 2.0, Fast Company, Upside, The
Industry Standard and Red Herring. They are so full of ads they
choke mailboxes _ 418 pages for Fast Company.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies spent $687 million advertising in these
magazines last year, up 347 percent from 1998. The dot-com
companies like them not so much to reach customers as potential
investors _ venture capitalists, Fortune says.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by this success, several of the magazines, including Red
Herring, The Standard and Upside, indicate they may go public with
a stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   While we're at it, here's a rundown of what's in some of these
Net magazines for June:
</P>
<P>
   _Business 2.0 looks at five companies that it says understand
the Internet's potential, and five that do not.
</P>
<P>
   _Upside looks at the future of Microsoft, which it says is
permeated by ``big company'' thinking in a changing industry.
</P>
<P>
   _Yahoo Internet Life says hotels, airlines and cruise companies
will have to wire up on the Internet ``or pack it in.''
</P>
<P>
   _Fast Company looks behind the scenes at CNBC, which it calls
``a window into a nation obsessed with Wall Street and the Net.''
</P>
<P>
   Unbiased arbitration
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a decade of complaints, investors who feel they
have been cheated by a broker can bring their gripe to an
independent arbitrator, says Barron's (June 5).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big change from the old system where the foxes
guarded the chicken coop: Disputes were decided in arbitration
hearings run by the brokerage industry's self-regulatory bodies,''
Barron's says.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for investors, Barron's says the new system will
cost more to log a complaint because it is not subsidized by the
brokers, as the previous self-regulatory arbitrators were.
</P>
<P>
   In the cards after Microsoft
</P>
<P>
   Flush with (apparent) success against software giant Microsoft,
the Justice Department's next big antitrust campaign will be Visa
and MasterCard, the leading credit card companies, Business Week
(June 12) reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice will try to use its witnesses to tell the story of how
Visa and MasterCard, which jointly control 75 percent of the
business, have worked together to bully competitors and harm the
American public,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   But Visa and MasterCard already are waging a wide-ranging
counterattack. They claim that Justice is simply bailing out a
group of rivals that couldn't win in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Business Week notes that the annual percentage rate
on many credit cards has broken the 30 percent barrier, despite the
low introductory offers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
