<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5388 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-PSI-NET-COX     06-05 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSI-NET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PSiNet to open Internet hosting center in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PSINet today will anounce opening of a huge Internet hosting
center in Atlanta, part of the Virginia company's plans to dominate
the expected boom in global communications.
</P>
<P>
   By year's end, Atlanta with about 50 employees will be one of
more than 20 such hosting centers, including Amsterdam, Los
Angeles, London, New York and Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   According to William Schrader, founder, chairman and chief
executive of PSINet, the multibillion dollar expansion is designed
to catch the swelling Internet wave, with more centers being
completed as the demand grows for Net-based communications.
</P>
<P>
   The plain-spoken Schrader thinks it will be a tsunami.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts predict that up to 10 percent of the world's
economy will be dependent on the Internet within five years.
Schrader thinks that is too conservative by far. He predicts that
80 percent of the economy will ride on the Internet within four
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may either think I am nuts or you won't believe me. But I
don't care what you think, because I am right. I think if you don't
have a good Internet infrastructure you won't have an economy. You
won't be able to buy light bulbs.''
</P>
<P>
   With 88,000 square feet at 40 Perimeter Center East, the new
PSINet center will provide e-commerce services for companies around
the Southeast. Included in that is consulting help for companies
with their Web sites and an offer of high-speed services like the
streaming of video, audio and animation. Customers will be offered
speeds up to 2.4 gigabits per second.
</P>
<P>
   PSINet's biggest competition is WorldCom and its MCI and UUNet
subsidiaries. With revenue of $37 billion and a range of services
that includes local phone service and long-distance, WorldCom has
far more muscle and a longer list of products. By comparison,
PSINet hopes to end the year with revenue coming in at a rate of $2
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom leads in serving the world's biggest companies, at
least those seeking one provider for all their telecommunications
services, Schrader said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they are trying to be all things to all people,'' Schrader
said. ``I have said before that WorldCom has an advantage over
PSINet with Fortune 1000 companies that are focused on price.''
</P>
<P>
   PSINet, by contrast, does most of its businesses with smaller
companies, usually of fewer than 2,000 employees and often spending
no more than $5,000 per month on telecommunications. What PSINet
customers do have is presence in more than one place, usually
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet can connect those offices, and the better the
technology, the more that can be done with that link.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader says he has what he needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are focused only on the Internet and the surrounds of the
Internet such as Web hosting. We are nothing but Net.''
</P>
<P>
   PSINet, which several years ago sold its consumer access
business to MindSpring Enterprises, owns more than 1 million miles
of high-speed fiber lines, much of it obtained in its 70
acquisitions. But it also has bought and is building the hosting
centers that tie together the network. Having both gives it greater
control over what the customer is using.
</P>
<P>
   His customers ``have a Web and Internet presence and they want
it to work. They don't care what the reason is _ they want it to
work. You can call it control, but I call it customer service. And
if you own your own fiber, you have the lowest cost.''
</P>
<P>
   PSINet has not made a profit yet. Schrader won't say when he
expects one. But he said the major capital investments are already
made and the company is waiting to fill the lines and servers.
Moreover, PSINet has several billion dollars in cash.
</P>
<P>
   That money is a comfort in a time when the stock market frowns
on efforts of high-tech companies to issue stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would call it a borderline crisis,'' he said. ``The ability
of smaller and medium companies to raise cash is zero. We have a
lot of cash, and we are hoarding cash. I like cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
