<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5389 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WORLDCOM-COX     06-05 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WorldCom sees Net as `ubiquitous'
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a lot riding on the spectacular rise of the Internet and
wireless technology _ like the future of WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi-based telecommunications giant has pegged its
strategy on the belief global transmission of data will make the
Net ``ubiquitous,'' creating an array of new ways to use it, said
John Sidgmore, WorldCom's vice chairman and chief operating
officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, wireless data is really the key to this
puzzle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking during the first day of the Supercomm trade show at the
Georgia World Congress Center, Sidgmore said WorldCom's many
acquisitions _ including the pending purchase of Sprint _ are meant
to build networks that will carry a customer's data from ``end to
end.''
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged off naysayers who believe WorldCom and other
providers of high-speed lines will soon produce a glut. Yes, there
has been a huge increase in supply of the lines. But consumers and
businesses will fill that bandwidth with things like full-motion
video, Sidgmore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that there is no way that Internet bandwidth demand
is going to slow down,'' he said. ``I think demand is going to
speed up. Within the next three to five years, we are going to see
innovation like nothing we've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidgmore showed a series of graphs about the wireless and Net
industries that portrayed factors like revenues, users and market
capitalization. All looked the same _ a long, slow start followed
by a rocketlike ascent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the reality is dwarfed by potential, he said: About 250
million people in the world use the Internet, including less than
one-third of U.S. families, he said. ``Hardly anyone is really on
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   And wireless is the way to bring the Net everywhere. Sidgmore
held aloft a Net-ready phone from Sprint and joked, ``I paid $130
billion for this phone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for WorldCom, that phone is not quite bought.
Regulators are rumored to be skeptical about the acquisition.
Monday, Sidgmore rejected the report in a British paper that
WorldCom was thinking of spinning off its UUNet subsidiary to win
regulatory approval of the company's pending merger with Sprint.
The deal faces roadblocks both in the United States and Europe.
UUNet, the company's Web management and data transmission business,
could be jettisoned as the price of doing the deal.
</P>
<P>
   UUNet is the main competitor to PSINet, which today announces
opening of an Atlanta-based Web-hosting center.
</P>
<P>
   Supercomm, which is expected to draw up to 50,000, runs through
Thursday. A ticket for most events cost $100.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
