<HEADER>
A5391 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-POLITICS-630&AMP;A     06-05 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-POLITICS-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIRAC URGES FRENCH TO SHORTEN PRESIDENTIAL TERM TO FIVE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ President Jacques Chirac proposed on Monday that
France's presidential term be shortened from seven years to five, a
move that could profoundly change the nature of French politics and
help him in the next elections.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac had long opposed such a change, saying that the country's
42-year-old constitution worked just fine as it is. Only last July,
he called the idea ``a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a televised interview Monday evening, the 67-year-old
president said he believes that cutting the presidential term is
necessary to modernize France's democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear it's a long time, '' Chirac said of the seven-year
term. ``Probably too long, in view of the demands of a modern
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls indicate that more than 75 percent of the French
population support such a change. A shorter term has been proposed
by most of the presidential candidates in the last three decades,
but their enthusiasm has always dwindled once they were in office.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, however, Chirac could gain from the shorter term. He
will turn 70 in 2002, when the next elections are scheduled. If the
presidential term is only five years long, his age may be less of a
factor in the voting.
</P>
<P>
   However, Chirac seemed annoyed when interviewers suggested that
to him, saying that if he were concerned about his age as a factor,
he would have acted sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find these reflections curious,'' Chirac said. ``I have
known all along what my age is. If this were the case I would have
acted long ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Chirac also refuted interviewers' contentions that he had
``changed his mind'' on the issue. He said that he had always been
in favor of a shorter term but did not want to open the door to
extensive changes to the constitution that was crafted by Charles
de Gaulle.
</P>
<P>
   He said he could now support the measure because he had
concluded that changing the presidential term alone would not
significantly effect the ``institutions'' of the French government.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is vehemently opposed to any other constitutional
changes, such as limiting the number of terms a president can serve
or strengthening the Parliament's powers. Such measures had been
suggested by former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing, but not
until he was long out of office. He recently brought the issue of a
shorter presidency to the top of the political agenda by proposing
a bill on constitutional reform in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac, a Gaullist, said he would use his presidential powers to
stop any measure if amendments were tacked onto the bill during the
approval process in the legislature, which is largely controlled by
France's Socialist prime minister, Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac is likely to face Jospin in the next elections. Some
political analysts believe that Chirac acted Monday in part to keep
his rival, who has often called for a shorter presidential term,
from using the issue against Chirac in 2002
</P>
<P>
   A change in the length of the presidential term could have a
far-reaching impact on French politics. Many hope that putting the
presidency and the legislators on a matching 5-year cycle would
help reduce the awkward periods of ``cohabitation,'' such as the
one France is experiencing now, when the president and the prime
minister belong to different parties.
</P>
<P>
   At least three times in the last 15 years, the French have
elected a president and then a few years later changed course and
elected a majority of legislators from another party. If the
elections were held simultaneously, this would be far less likely
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The periods of cohabitation are often tense, as the president
tends to lose much of his power and lines of authority between the
two executives are not clearly drawn.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both Chirac and Jospin, 62, are extremely popular, with approval
ratings of more than 50 percent. But the constant maneuvering for
political advantage between them is evident at almost every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Even on this reform, both men are jockeying for position.
Quickly responding to Giscard d'Estaing's proposal, Jospin urged
Chirac to move without delay.
</P>
<P>
   If he did not move fast enough, Jospin warned, he would bypass
the president and use Parliament to get the ball rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac took his time answering. Some analysts have said they
expected the president to try to prolong a debate on the proposal
so that an early decision on a shorter term could not be used to
pressure him into resigning early to call for new elections. Chirac
made clear during the interview that he had every intention of
finishing his seven year term and that any changes would apply to
presidents elected in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   He gave no details about when he would take action on his
proposal, which would require approval in Parliament and a
referendum to take effect. Some officials expect it will be debated
in the National Assembly and Senate in the coming weeks. A
referendum could be held as early as October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
