<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5399 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SKINS-DEION-COX     06-05 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SKINS-DEION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sanders added to 'Skins talent grab
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Redskins continued to make prime additions to their roster
on Monday, signing former Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders to a
seven-year, $55 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, 32, was waived by Dallas in a cost-cutting move only
three days earlier. The eight-time Pro Bowl player received an $8
million signing bonus from the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Since losing to the Buccaneers in the NFC divisional playoffs in
January, the Redskins already had added former Bills defensive end
Bruce Smith, Vikings quarterback Jeff George, Cardinals running
back Adrian Murrell and Lions safety Mark Carrier.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins also had two of the first three picks in April's
draft, which they used to select Penn State linebacker LaVar
Arrington and Alabama offensive tackle Chris Samuels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely the `Who's Who' of the NFL now,'' Redskins
receiver Irving Fryar said. ``We've got a lot of great names who
carry a lot of great talent with them. Yeah, on paper, we're the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, the former Falcon who won Super Bowls with the 49ers
and Cowboys, was cut by Dallas because the team would have owed him
a guaranteed $23.5 million the next two years, including a $10
million roster bonus due prior to this season.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders arrived in Washington on Saturday night and had dinner
with Redskins owner Daniel Snyder, director of player personnel
Vinny Cerrato and cornerback Darrell Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have the same goal here,'' Sanders said. ``There's a
lot of teams in the NFL who only play because they put a football
on the field. But Washington has prepared to go to the Super Bowl
and that's what I love.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who has 44 career interceptions, joins a secondary that
includes Green and second-year pro Champ Bailey, a former Georgia
star who was drafted in the first round in 1999. Green, 40, signed
a new five-year contract last week, but will likely lose his
starting job for the first time in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
