<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5409 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-NAMES-GREENFIELD     06-05 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-NAMES-GREENFIELD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIM. THEM. US. VOTE. 
</HEADLINE>
  (New York Times OpEd for use Tuesday, June 6, and thereafter.) 
ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By JEFF GREENFIELD    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore. George Bush. Two candidates. Four syllables. That's the
choice. Coincidence? Uh-uh. Those four syllables speak volumes. Not
about them. About us. About what's happened. What's happened to our
politics. What's happened to our attention span.
</P>
<P>
   Once it took more than four guttural grunts to list America's
choices. In 1900, Americans chose among William Jennings Bryan,
William McKinley and Eugene Victor Debs. The names rolled slowly
off the tongue, lingered for a moment in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the days when we wrote lengthy epistles to each
other, not e-mails spattered with acronyms. It was a more
reflective time, a time when we had the patience to pause and
listen to the name of a multisyllabic officeseeker. And so it was
through most of the century: indeed, a high point was reached in
1952, when Dwight Eisenhower defeated Adlai Stevenson _ a
10-syllable battle, even without middle initials. (Eisenhower also
holds the distinction of having the most unusual last name of any
president, thus proving that if you win a world war, you need hold
neither previous political office nor an easily accessible name).
</P>
<P>
   By the century's close, the inexorable erosion of the American
attention span had slammed full force into our political campaigns.
The half-hour speeches had long since been replaced by the
30-second commercial. The network news had cut the average sound
bites of the major candidates from about 50 seconds in 1968 to
barely nine in 1988. (Had Franklin Roosevelt been running that
year, his most famous utterance would have been reported: ``The
only thing we have to fear is fuhhhh ...'') It was only a matter of
time before the candidates themselves would be judged, however
subconsciously, on how quickly the voters could absorb their names.
</P>
<P>
   Once Michael Dukakis crashed and burned in '88 _ ``I don't even
know how to say his name!'' one of George Bush's country-western
singer supporters had declared that year _ the die was cast. In
1992, Bill Clinton, Bob Dole and Ross Perot combined had a shorter
syllable count than Adlai and Ike. In 1996, with Perot shunted to
the sidelines, Clinton and Dole produced a grand total of five.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is even more dramatic when we fold in the running
mates. In 1844, Henry Clay could choose a running mate so
syllabically endowed that their campaign song became a classic:
``Hurray! Hurray! The country is a-rising! Hurray! Hurray! For Clay
and Freylinghausen!'' And in that landmark year of 1952, Stevenson
had no qualms about running with Estes Kefauver.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, what have we been offered in recent tickets? In
1992, Clinton-Gore defeated Bush-Quayle. Four years ago,
Clinton-Gore beat Dole-Kemp. And this year, some of the likeliest
possibilities sound more like a series of Cro-Magnon grunts than a
ticket: Bush-Ridge; Gore-Graham; Bush-Dole. (Memo to Pataki and
Lieberman: Don't hold your breath).
</P>
<P>
   The next step? Since it's widely believed that politics is
mostly show business, let future candidates take their clue from
that universe: single-name candidates. In fact, short-single-name
candidates. We're not talking Coolio or Madonna. We're not even
talking Donahue or Oprah. We're talking Cher. We're talking Prince.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Greenfield, a senior analyst at CNN, is author of the
forthcoming novel ``Jackpot.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the OPED
package and other features.
</P>
