<HEADER>
A5412 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SOUTHERN-BAPTISTS-2TA     06-05 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-BAPTISTS-2TAKES(1160)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERATE BAPTISTS REBEL AGAINST CONSERVATIVE LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. _ A deep division within the nation's
largest Protestant denomination, the Southern Baptist Convention,
has developed to the point that a significant moderate minority has
been creating a separate existence from the denomination's
increasingly conservative leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctant to accept the conservatives' insistence that the Bible
be interpreted literally and that women submit to their husbands
and be barred from serving as pastors, the moderates have set up
seminaries and a religious publishing house.
</P>
<P>
   They have also sent out their own missionaries and created
separate associations of congregations, like the Cooperative
Baptist Fellowship, which by itself counts 1,800 churches as
contributors to its budget.
</P>
<P>
   One of those is First Baptist Church, which covers a city block
here and whose members, over the last century, have donated
considerable time and money to the convention's causes, said its
pastor, the Rev. David Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, Hughes likens the relationship between church
and denomination to a marriage gone sour. The two are like a couple
that ``still live under one roof, but they have very little to do
with each other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the Southern Baptist Convention, the Rev. Paige
Patterson, acknowledged that moderates had ``formed a denomination
within the denomination.'' Patterson said he would not be surprised
if 1,500 or more moderate congregations were to leave the
convention in the coming years out of the more than 40,000 total
congregations that belong.
</P>
<P>
   But they would quickly be replaced, he said, adding that the
denomination started 1,479 new churches in 1999 and that its
increasingly conservative stance had been attracting established
congregations as new members, like the Thomas Road Baptist Church
in Lynchburg, Va., where the Rev. Jerry Falwell is pastor. ``We're
gaining, not losing,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' he added, ``is anytime you take a stand and
define yourself very clearly _ and in this case, returning to the
faith of our fathers _ there are people who want to be part of that
and join you. And there are people who don't want to part of it,
and are going to use their chute and rip cord.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without the moderates' participation, the convention
remains formidable. It operates six seminaries, fields more than
6,000 missionaries and runs one of the world's largest church
literature publishing houses. When Southern Baptist leaders speak,
politicians and the news media take notice.
</P>
<P>
   Academic authorities are reluctant to call the rift among
Southern Baptists a formal split because no clean break has yet
taken place, and many moderates still regard themselves as members
of the convention. But the differences are serious and
long-lasting, and many on both sides have suggested they could lead
to the creation of a separate denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Should that happen, the Southern Baptists would be finally
confirmed in a staunchly conservative identity.
</P>
<P>
   What the rift also shows is how difficult it can be, at a time
when many Protestant church members' loyalties to denominations
have weakened, to hold together big church bodies amid divisive
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is particularly acute among Southern Baptists
because of how their convention works. Its member churches across
the country are autonomous, owning their own property and hiring
their own pastors, but collaborating for missionary purposes,
sending men and women around the world to try to convert people to
faith in Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   The formula has been so successful that the denomination long
ago spilled outside its home region, the Southeast, and is nearly
twice the size of the next-largest Protestant body, the United
Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Leonard, a church historian who is dean of Wake Forest
Divinity School, an institution recently established by moderates
in Winston-Salem, said the convention was undergoing a
fragmentation, particularly since the appearance of rival Baptist
organizations in Texas and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   But part of the challenge, Leonard said, arises from a growing
tendency among younger Protestants to think of themselves as
nondenominational.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't emphasize enough that among this generation of college
students and seminary students, conservative and liberal, their
sense of denominational identity is much smaller than previous
generations,'' he said, meaning that they think of themselves as
Christians, rather than specifically as Baptists or Methodists or
Presbyterians.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy T. Ammerman, a sociologist of religion at Hartford
Seminary in Connecticut, said she saw ``an increasing diversity''
within Southern Baptist ranks as different groups found homes
inside ``alternative organizations,'' like the Cooperative Baptist
Fellowship and a smaller group, the Alliance of Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   Examples of such sentiments can be found among members in a
congregation like First Baptist Church in Winston-Salem, affiliated
with the Cooperative Baptist Fellowship. Phyllis Lile-King, 35, a
civil rights lawyer, simply calls herself ``an authentic Baptist,''
and says she and others she knows are past feeling the need to
actively oppose the conservatives' rule.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara R. Blackburn, 38, a university professor, said that
whenever she moved, she sought out congregations affiliated with
the Cooperative Baptist Fellowship, like First Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptist leaders have been taking increasingly
conservative positions for years. But in May, a committee of
leaders proposed revising the denomination's core statement of
beliefs at the annual meeting, on June 12 in Orlando, Fla. The
revisions, if adopted at the meeting, would call on Christians to
oppose abortion, homosexuality and pornography.
</P>
<P>
   One clause, among the most controversial, would also firmly
state that the Bible does not allow women to be pastors, a largely
symbolic move in a denomination where few congregations have hired
women for that office. ``While both men and women are gifted for
service in the church,'' the proposed revision states, ``the office
of pastor is limited to men as qualified by Scripture.''
</P>
<P>
   One does not have to search far in North Carolina to find
Baptist women who concur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I subscribe to that,'' said Cheri Jimenez, 31, a former
communications director for the conservative organization Concerned
Women for America.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very controversial and there is enormous complexity to
this issue,'' said Jimenez, a Raleigh resident who helps to run a
Christian ministry to women. ``But I just have to stand on
Scripture and the authority of that, even though that is not
popular at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Eckerd, 33, a physical therapist in Winston-Salem, agreed.
Eckerd said she saw no Scriptural ban on a woman being a political
or business leader. ``If that's where God's directing her, sure,''
she said. ``But I think within the church, within spiritual
leadership, it needs to be a man.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptists became a separate denomination in 1845, when
Baptists nationwide split along North-South lines over slavery.
Today, Baptists in the United States are divided among several
denominations, with Southern Baptists the largest.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last century and a half, Southern Baptist churches
coalesced and flourished in their region, developing a religious
way of life as all-encompassing as anything in American
Protestantism. Church members could attend services three times a
week, belong to church organizations as children, adolescents and
adults, study Baptist Sunday School material and choose among
colleges and seminaries affiliated with the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a total system that connected people to the
denomination from birth to death,'' said Leonard, the Wake Forest
dean.
</P>
<P>
   The denomination thrived, through Reconstruction, the Scopes
trial and the Depression, he said, supported by its members'
loyalty and the atmosphere of a distinct Southern culture.
</P>
<P>
   The cultural support began to crumble in 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the breakup of the Old South _ the civil rights
movement, the immigration of Yankees in and Southerners out,'' said
Ammerman, the sociologist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, a group whose leaders included Patterson, the current
president, succeeded in electing one of their own as the
denomination's president, gaining an office whose powers included
appointing trustees to oversee the Southern Baptist seminaries,
missionary agencies and other boards. The conservatives have
preached that the standard of Baptist belief is that the Bible is
``inerrant'' _ literally true in all matters _ and have said that
those who serve the denomination ought to subscribe to that.
</P>
<P>
   After unsuccessfully trying for a decade to wrest control of the
presidency away from conservatives at the annual convention, the
moderates began founding their own seminaries and ministerial
programs in the 1990s. One is the Baptist Studies Program at
Candler School of Theology at Emory University in Atlanta, whose
graduates include the Rev. Stacey Simpson, 28.
</P>
<P>
   Baptized in a Southern Baptist congregation, Simpson attended
Furman University in Greenville, S.C., when that institution took
steps to distance itself from South Carolina's Baptist
organization, dominated by conservatives. At Candler, she was
ordained in a liberal-leaning congregation that was eventually
expelled from the Baptists' Georgia organization.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson serves as pastor of Fellowship Baptist Church, a
five-year-old congregation in Edison, Ga., affiliated with the
Cooperative Baptist Fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call myself a Baptist,'' she said, ``and I kind of have to
add a bunch of clarifiers after that, when people ask.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
