<SLUG> BC-THOMSON-PRIMARK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMSON AGREES TO BUY PRIMARK FOR $842 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Thomson Corp., which is selling most of its
newspapers to focus on the electronic distribution of legal and
financial information, agreed Monday to buy the Primark Corp. for
$842 million.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson will pay $38 a share for Primark, a rival provider of
financial data based in Waltham, Mass., a 31 percent premium to
Primark's share price of $29 on Friday. Thomson will also assume
$235 million in debt. Shares of Primark rose $8.25, to $37.25,
Monday on the New York Stock Exchange. Thomson fell 1.80 Canadian
dollars, to 49.20, on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Thomson has spent more than $2 billion to buy
database publishers. Its largest division is legal and regulatory,
which includes West Group and its Westlaw online research service,
followed by Thomson Financial. Two other divisions provide research
for professionals in the scientific and health care fields and
education.
</P>
<P>
   Like Thomson, Primark has been focusing on electronic services
and just completed the sale of a subsidiary, Yankee Research Group,
to Reuters Group PLC for $72.2 million in cash. The company said
proceeds would be used to reduce debt and expand in electronic
services.
</P>
<P>
   With the most recent deal, Thomson will add Primark's IBES
International Inc. unit, which compiles analysts' forecasts, to its
First Call/Thomson Financial unit, which does similar work. Thomson
Financial's other services are used by securities dealers and
institutional investors for research, trading and settling
transactions. It owns Securities Data, the Electronic Settlements
Group and American Banker. The combined Thomson Financial and
Primark, which will also bolster Thomson's presence in Europe, will
have about $2 billion a year in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Kasputys, the chairman and chief executive of Primark,
will become chairman of Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   The boards of both companies have approved the acquisition,
which is conditional on at least 51 percent of Primark's shares
being tendered. Thomson said the purchase, which is expected to
close in the second half of the year, would weaken its earnings per
share this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   Although Thomson had its beginning in newspapers and radio
stations in Canada in the 1930s and continues to publish newspapers
and specialized periodicals, its business in electronic databases
and related services contributed half of its $5.8 billion in
revenue last year. The company's chairman, Kenneth Thomson, said
recently that electronic data sales should reach 80 percent of the
company's total revenue within five years, and half of that could
be Internet-related.
</P>
<P>
   A chain of 130 newspapers in Canada and the United States, with
combined annual revenue of $800 million, has been for sale since
February, and could be sold before the end of the year. Analysts
think the newspapers could sell for as much as $2.5 billion.
Thomson is keeping its flagship Toronto paper, The Globe and Mail.
</P>
<P>
   The market has become cluttered, however, because in late April
Conrad Black's Hollinger Inc. of Toronto put a for-sale sign on all
but the biggest of its 77 daily newspapers and 302 other
publications in Canada and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   While Thomson's head office is in Toronto, its executive offices
are in Stamford, Conn., and four-fifths of its revenue comes from
doing business is in the United States. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
