A5418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-LEWIS-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      06-05 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEWIS-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER AND ASSAULT CHARGES ARE DROPPED AGAINST LEWIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Murder and assault charges against Ray Lewis, the Baltimore
Ravens' star linebacker, were dropped in an Atlanta courtroom
Monday after he pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor charge of
obstructing justice and agreed to testify against two
co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who had faced the possibility of life in prison if
convicted of murder, received one year of probation. He cannot
drink alcohol or use drugs for one year under the terms of his
probation, which falls under the Georgia first-offender act.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to testify Tuesday and could be back with the
Baltimore Ravens in their minicamp next week.
</P>
<P>
   Art Modell, the Ravens' owner, said Lewis would probably have a
news conference Friday at the Ravens' complex near Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the National Football League said Lewis would not
be suspended but could be fined.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 25, and two friends, Reginald Oakley and Joseph Sweeting,
were charged with murder, felony murder and aggravated assault in
the stabbings of Richard Lollar and Jacinth Baker in the early
hours of Jan. 31 on a street outside of an Atlanta nightclub. The
killings occurred a few hours after the Super Bowl XXXIV game at
the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had alleged that Lewis, Oakley and Sweeting killed
the men in a street brawl outside of the nightclub and then jumped
into a stretch limousine that Lewis had rented from Baltimore.
Duane Fassett, the limousine driver, was expected to testify that
he saw all three defendants fighting and that Oakley and Sweeting
admitted stabbing the men.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Sparks, who was riding in the limousine, had said she saw
another passenger dump a white hotel laundry bag into a garbage
bin. Prosecutors say the bag contained Lewis' white suit and
alleged it had blood on it. But the suit was never found and
prosecutor's witnesses changed their testimony from their original
statements. None of them could place Lewis at the scene with a
knife in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   The police and friends testified that Lewis tried to cover up
his role in the deaths, having told the co-defendants to ``Keep
your mouth shut,'' and that he gave incomplete statements to the
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fully acknowledges his responsibility for those acts,'' Ed
Garland, another attorney for Lewis, told Judge Alice Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Paul Howard, while acknowledging
disappointment in many witnesses whose testimony differed from
earlier statements, said he did not regret prosecuting Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``A trial is an instrument to reach the truth, and I think that
in many respects it has been shielded,'' Howard said. ``We are
continuing to try to bring the truth forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my nearly 40 years of ownership, I have had previous
incidents involving our players but this one was especially brutal
because of the nature of the crime,'' said Modell, the Ravens'
owner. ``It has been brutal for all involved but especially for the
family and friends of the people slain. I would not have testified
at Ray's bond hearing if I didn't think that Ray was innocent of
the serious charges. He is a good guy and a great football player
and we welcome him back with open arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL has its heroes on the field every week and we owe a
responsibility to the fans in deed and in conduct. I intend to have
a long talk with Ray about that. And I hope this has a sobering
effect on all of our players throughout the league and especially
on Ray.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The serious charges were dropped and he was entirely cleared
of those charges,'' said an NFL spokesman, Joe Browne. ``We don't
know at this time if there will be a fine that would fall under the
conduct detrimental to the league policy because we are going to
review the case once his involvement has concluded, including him
testifying on Tuesday. We are going to continue to work as hard as
we can to see that National Football League players will not be
involved in these tough and tragic situations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good day for Ray,'' said one of his defense attorneys,
Don Samuel. ``In effect, the district attorney is saying that Ray
Lewis is not guilty of murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting's lawyer, Steven Sadow, said: ``No matter what Ray
Lewis says, the jury will not find Joseph guilty. It may have an
effect on our overall strategy but then again we have to hear what
Ray says.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Harvey, a lawyer for Oakley, said: ``The state just
finished proving with several detectives that Lewis is a liar. He
was a liar when he was a defendant. I guess now he's the state's
liar.''
</P>
<P>
   David Wolfe, another attorney for Oakley, suggested there was no
reason for Lewis to plead guilty since prosecutors had a weak case.
</P>
<P>
   Thomasaina Threatt, an aunt of Lollar, one of the victims, told
The Associated Press outside the courtroom Monday: ``You let a
guilty man go free. Where's the justice in that?''
</P>
<P>
   The Lewis case unfolded following the arrest of the former
Carolina Panthers receiver Rae Carruth in January on murder charges
in the shooting of his pregnant girlfriend. Critics have said the
two cases show that NFL players' off-field conduct may be out of
control and at the least requires more serious counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Tagliabue, the NFL commissioner, said: ``If anyone in the
NFL needed a reminder that high-profile professional athletes need
to be extraordinarily careful in their associates and activities,
Ray Lewis' experience provides that reminder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
