<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-WOMEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EEOC SAYS A MORGAN STANLEY DIVISION DISCRIMINATED AGAINST WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal agency determined Monday that Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. discriminated against women working in
one of its divisions, opening the door for lawsuits, and possibly a
class action, against the firm.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the first investigations into pay and promotion
practices at a big Wall Street investment bank, the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission said it had seen evidence of ``a
pattern and practice'' of discrimination against women employed in
Morgan Stanley's institutional stocks division. The case stems from
a complaint filed with the commission in 1998 by Allison K.
Schieffelin, a trader of convertible bonds, who said she repeatedly
had been denied a promotion because of her sex.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said the evidence it had gathered supported
Schieffelin's contention that less-deserving men had been promoted
to the top rank of managing director while she remained a
principal. The commission also said it found that the firm
retaliated against Schieffelin for making her complaints.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Morgan Stanley, Ray O'Rourke, said: ``We
emphatically disagree with the findings of the commission. We do
not practice or condone employment discrimination of any kind. We
think the commission can only have misinterpreted the data that we
gave them because the information shows no pattern of
discrimination whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   The determination signals that the commission may sue Morgan
Stanley if the firm does not agree to a settlement. Litigation is a
last resort for the commission: Last year, it received 77,444
complaints and filed just 465 suits against employers.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has filed suit against some brokerage firms and
some major corporations, such as the Mitsubishi Motors Corp. and
drugmaker Astra U.S.A. in recent years. But it has not disclosed
any actions against major Wall Street firms in about a decade.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998. Mitsubishi agreed to pay $34 million to hundreds of
women who worked in its auto factory in central Illinois and agreed
to outside monitoring of complaints of harassment and
discrimination. That settlement was easily the biggest of its kind,
supplanting one the commission reached earlier that year with
Astra, in which Astra agreed to pay $10 million, to admit that it
had fostered a hostile work environment for women and to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what sort of settlement the commission would try
to elicit from Morgan Stanley but a monetary settlement could be
substantial because employees in the division are highly paid.
Managing directors at the firm can earn several million dollars a
year and they can hold those jobs for 10 years or more.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. consented to the commission's
monitoring of its hiring of women and minorities in its brokerage
business. Recent high-profile sex harassment and discrimination
suits against Merrill Lynch and the Salomon Smith Barney unit of
Citigroup were filed in federal court without intervention by the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the commission demanded that Morgan Stanley turn
over comprehensive records on hiring, pay and promotions in its
institutional stocks division, in which Schieffelin has worked
during her 14-year career. Neither the commission nor O'Rourke
would describe the information the firm turned over.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Outten, a lawyer in Manhattan who represents Schieffelin,
said he had not seen the data but he believed the commission
received profiles of the division's employees going back 15 years.
He said there were other facts that supported Schieffelin's
complaint, including that only three of 50 managing directors in
the division are women and that senior executives of the firm
condoned and participated in firm-sponsored events from which women
were excluded.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffelin is a golfer but was not invited on golf outings with
clients, he said. She also contended in her complaint that the firm
paid for the entertainment of clients and strip clubs. But in its
response to the commission, Morgan Stanley said ``entertainment at
topless bars was at most infrequent.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission also based its decision on information supplied
by several other women who have worked at Morgan Stanley. Two women
who worked in the same division as Schieffelin and now work at
other investment banks corroborated her contentions in sworn
statements, Outten said. He would not identify those women.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffelin filed her complaint with the commission after she
was passed over for promotion to managing director in 1997. Since
then, she has been passed over twice more, Outten said. He said her
year-end bonus for 1999 was substantial but ``we believe that her
bonus could have and should have been higher'' and ``was adversely
affected by the fact that she's a woman and she filed this
charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Outten said going public with her complaint has had a harsh
effect on Schieffelin's relationship with the firm and her
co-workers. She has felt shunned and has been excluded from some
extra-curricular roles, including recruiting prospective employees
and helping develop an online system for marketing new securities,
known as an electronic roadshow.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffelin, 39, has declined to comment on her case because
Morgan Stanley's lawyers have warned that she could be disciplined
or fired for talking to the press without permission, Outten said.
O'Rourke confirmed that Schieffelin would be violating firm policy
if she talked about her case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5420 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-NYT &LR;      06-05 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH MAY SCOFF AT POLLS, BUT AIDES CALL THEM RELIABLE PREDICTOR OF
VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ You could buy a Texas ranch with a dollar for
every time that Gov. George W. Bush has dismissed polls by saying
that the only meaningful one is on election day. But his aides seem
plenty attuned to the growing number of voter surveys that
anticipate that moment.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, they invited reporters to the campaign's headquarters
here and, with charts, graphs and a multicolored map of the
electoral college, they made the case that Bush's lead over Vice
President Al Gore in most polls over the past several months is no
fluke. To the contrary, they said, it is a compelling verdict on
the Texas governor's sturdy appeal.
</P>
<P>
   What about the two national polls released over the last week
that showed Gore only a point behind? Possible anomalies, they
responded, crying out for context and statistical confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Or the analogy of 1988, when the challenger, Michael S. Dukakis,
saw a late spring and early summer advantage over the sitting vice
president, George H.W. Bush, collapse and come to naught? A poor
indicator, for any number of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One senior adviser drew reporters' attention to a simple,
overarching reality: Bush, from the time that polls began pitting
him against Gore, has frequently hit or surpassed 50 percent of
voters' support, while Gore has not. In the two recent polls in
which the candidates were neck-and-neck, Gore's support was below
45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about that,'' the adviser said. ``There are 182 polls.
He is the vice president of the United States, with name ID well
into the 90s, an incumbent administration of peace and prosperity,
job approval ratings in the 50s and 60s, and this guy can get
himself to 49 percent one time, and to 46-plus five times, whereas
the guy on the other side can get himself to 50 percent 117
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its value as an engrossing reading and rearranging of
political tea leaves, the briefing by Bush's advisers _ the second
of its kind in less than two months _ suggested an investment in
portraying Gore as a persistently unappealing loser whose
retoolings have failed to reinvigorate his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This explains why they're going through their latest
reinvention,'' the adviser said, citing the Gore campaign's
abandonment of attack mode. ``They fundamentally gave it their best
shot, and it didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for the Gore campaign, said he could
not, off the top of his head, even confirm or dispute the Bush
campaign's figures and interpretations, because the vice president
``does not waste his time and resources by analyzing polls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a sure sign of a campaign that's starting to get
very, very nervous when they have to resort to pointing to polls
that support their candidacy,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   He nonetheless argued that polls now as opposed to five or six
months ago made a case for Gore coming on strong and showed that
Gore had eaten into Bush's once-whopping lead by 15 or more
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   And another Gore adviser subsequently called and said that
Dukakis was 12 points ahead at this point in 1988, while Bush was
only 1 point up in the two recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   According to materials handed out Monday by the Bush campaign,
Bush led Gore in 46 of 52 national public polls since early March.
The Bush campaign also used what officials said were the latest
public polls in individual states to draw a map that showed Bush in
a position to garner 266 electoral votes, Gore in line to get 136
and another 136 up for grabs. It takes 270 electoral votes to win.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers repeatedly rejected the model of 1988. And just
last week the candidate himself offered an alternative comparison:
1960, when the vice president, Richard Nixon, was defeated by the
challenger, John F. Kennedy. It was a telling metaphor, implying
that Bush sees himself as the charismatic, fresh alternative to a
perpetually striving, charm-challenged pol.
</P>
<P>
   ``He followed a pretty successful administration,'' Bush said of
Kennedy. ``His message was, `Let's soar higher.' And that's what my
message is going to be, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
