<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5421 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-DEAL06-COX     06-05 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-DEAL06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis to take the stand in Atlanta murder case
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When NFL All-Pro linebacker Ray Lewis takes the stand
today, prosecutors hope they finally have the star witness that has
eluded them in the Buckhead stabbings trial.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview Sunday with Fulton County prosecutors, Lewis
continued to maintain he had nothing to do with the street fight
that left Jacinth Baker, 21, and Richard Lollar, 24, of Decatur,
Ga., dead of stab wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he didn't touch a person,'' Lewis attorney Ed Garland
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is now expected to testify against his former
co-defendants Joseph Sweeting, 34, of Miami, and Reginald Oakley,
31, of Baltimore, after prosecutors dropped murder charges against
the 25-year-old football star Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis also implicated Carlos Stafford, a passenger in his
limousine the night of the killings. Lewis told prosecutors he saw
Stafford kicking a victim and that Stafford told him later that he
had hit Baker with a champagne bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford's feet ``may have inadvertently hit one of the people
fighting,'' his lawyer, Dwight Thomas, said. ``It was not
intentional. He was acting as a peacemaker. He surely didn't hit
anyone with a bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Paul Howard said he is considering charges
against another individual, whom he declined to identify.
</P>
<P>
   In a videotaped statement, Lewis said he saw Oakley and Sweeting
punching the victims in the body. Prosecutors contend the attackers
hid knives in their fists.
</P>
<P>
   While Lewis said he did not see anyone with a knife during the
fight, he told prosecutors Sweeting had a knife minutes afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he saw a knife in Sweeting's hand when he asked what
had happened. Sweeting said that every time he got hit, he hit
back, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis attorney Don Samuel said the testimony should support a
self-defense argument, noting Lewis said his group was confronted
by six men after leaving a nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis corroborated accounts of Oakley being hit over the head
with a champagne bottle and said he saw Sweeting attacked by two
larger men, Samuel said. Former DeKalb District Attorney Bob Wilson
said the impact of Lewis' testimony remains to be seen. ``What you
have to remember is that the jurors will be listening to a guy who
a couple of weeks ago the D.A. said was part of the homicide,'' he
said. ``But now the prosecution will be saying he's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
