A5423 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DEATH-COX     06-05 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another knock on Texas' death penalty
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Nine Texas death row inmates were condemned to die
after jurors heard testimony that the defendants are more likely to
become repeat offenders because they are Hispanic or black,
according to the state attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   The review of the cases was sparked by a Collin County death
sentence that was overturned Monday by the U.S. Supreme Court
because of race-tinged testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Quijano, a former chief psychologist for the state prison
system, used 24 factors in testifying about whether Victor Hugo
Saldano would commit future acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Quijano's calculation included the fact that blacks and
Hispanics are over-represented in prison as compared to their
proportion of the overall population. The fact that Saldano, 27, is
Hispanic ``was a factor weighing in favor of future
dangerousness,'' Quijano testified.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Court of Criminal Appeals affirmed the death sentence,
ruling there was no ``fundamental error'' in admitting the
race-based testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. Supreme Court, at the urging of Texas Attorney
General John Cornyn, ruled Monday that Saldano is entitled to a new
punishment hearing. His guilt is not in question.
</P>
<P>
   The court did not reverse Saldano's conviction in the November
1995 slaying of Paul King during a Collin County robbery.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief filed with the Supreme Court, Cornyn said the state
could not defend the death sentence in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the fact that sufficient proper evidence was submitted
to the jury to justify the finding of Saldano's future
dangerousness, the infusion of race as a factor for the jury to
weigh in making its determination violated his constitutional right
to be sentenced without regard to the color of his skin,'' Cornyn
told the justices.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said his staff has found eight other death row cases in
which similar testimony was offered. A decision on how to proceed
on those cases will be announced this week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn spokesman Mark Heckmann declined to release the names of
the defendants in the other cases. All of the cases are now on
appeal in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Collin County prosecutors opposed Cornyn's effort to seek a new
punishment hearing for Saldano.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it was a miniscule part of the punishment evidence
that had no bearing on the punishment verdict and it was harmless
error,'' said Assistant District Attorney John Schomburger.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling comes as Texas' busiest-in-the-nation execution
chamber gets close scrutiny as a result of Gov. George W. Bush's
bid for the presidency. Last week, for the first time since he took
office in 1995, Bush granted a 30-day reprieve in a death row case.
Bush said the condemned man, Ricky Nolen McGinn, was entitled to
more time to pursue DNA testing that could exonerate him in the
rape-slaying of his 12-year-old stepdaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has said he has no doubt about the guilt of any of
the 131 people executed during his administration.
</P>
<P>
   Saldano's guilt is not in question. His appeal included only a
challenge of the death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Stanley Schneider, representing Saldano on
appeal, said it is rare for the state to ``confess'' error in a
death penalty case before the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now know that are some people who believe race can be an
issue, and that is shocking,'' he said of the psychologist's
testimony. ``Race has no bearing in a criminal trial, ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Quijano was unavailable for comment Monday. But his associate,
Roger Saunders, defended the use of the statistical data concerning
Hispanic inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Quijano was not suggesting that by virtue of the fact
alone that the defendant was a Hispanic was the factor in
determining that he was a future danger,'' said Saunders. ``He was
referring to the fact that he fell into a group which is known to
have a higher-than-average rate of arrest and conviction and
incarceration.''
</P>
<P>
   But Quijano's testimony brought international protest. Saldano
is backed by the government of his country, Argentina, as well as
the governments of by Brazil, Chile, Ecuador, Honduras, Mexico,
Panama, Paraguay, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   ``Argentina finds it intrinsically offensive for anyone to
suggest that any Hispanic is more dangerous _ and therefore more
deserving of the death penalty _ simply because he is Hispanic,''
lawyers for Argentina told the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
