<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1000&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON LAST DAY OF CLINTON TRIP, UKRAINE ANNOUNCES CHERNOBYL PLANT WILL
CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for complete rewrite to restructure and fold in earlier
story, CLINTON-EUROPE-UKRAINE, to create a ledeall on Clinton's
day. Pls. note reversed byline.) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO with MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine _ President Leonid Kuchma of Ukraine used the
occasion of a brief visit by President Clinton on Monday to
announce that the Chernobyl nuclear power station, site of the
worst radiation accident in history, would be closed by Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchma made the announcement after the two leaders met in the
white-and-gilded splendor of the Mariinsky presidential palace.
``This is a hopeful moment,'' Clinton said. ``It is also a moment
when we remember those who suffered as a result of the accident
there.''
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, the six-hour visit to Ukraine was the last stop on
his last trip to Europe as president.
</P>
<P>
   He began the day in Moscow with an address to both chambers of
the Russian parliament, in which he acknowledged that ``Americans
have to overcome the temptation to think that we have all the
answers.'' He then urged the Russians not to reject Washington's
proposal for a limited national missile defense and to make the
changes needed to achieve full participation in global trade.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier conversations with President Vladimir Putin, Clinton
failed to shake the Kremlin's staunch opposition to Washington's
proposal for a new missile defense plan _ an opposition shared by
China and much of Europe on the ground that it could spur a new
arms race. The United States argues that it would construct
defenses only against the chance of missiles being launched by
``rogue states.''
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine has been under pressure from the United States and
Europe to shut down the last working reactor at the Chernobyl
plant, where a fire in 1986 spewed radiation over vast stretches of
northeastern Europe and caused untold thousands of deaths and
illnesses. Kuchma had previously said he was prepared to shut down
the plant if major industrialized nations would contribute toward
the $1.2 billion Ukraine needs to built two new nuclear power
plants.
</P>
<P>
   In his announcement Monday, Kuchma said Clinton had agreed to
solicit the Group of Eight industrialized countries for help in
meeting the costs. Clinton also pledged $78 million in new U.S. aid
to help Ukraine repair and strengthen the concrete ``sarcophagus''
over the damaged reactor, $2 million to improve security at other
Ukrainian nuclear plants, and an unspecified amount to assist the
tens of thousands of Ukrainians whose livelihoods come from
Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The aim of this decision is to reduce nuclear risks in the
world,'' Kuchma said, adding that it ``was not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the many Ukrainians who depend on the plant for
jobs, Ukraine faces an acute energy crisis. The country also needs
to spend an estimated $750 million to reconstruct and stabilize the
hastily built concrete and steel structure that encases the
shattered No. 4 reactor hall and the nearly 200 tons of radioactive
fuel inside; the structure is riddled with leaks and threatening to
crack open.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his talks with Kuchma, Clinton went outdoors to
address tens of thousands of Ukrainians packed into St. Michael's
Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the oppressors are gone,'' he said. ``Stalin is gone.
The Nazis are gone. But you, the people of Ukraine, you are still
here, stronger than ever! You must build a free and prosperous
Ukraine. Do not give up. Keep on fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the speech, administration officials said, was to
give a strong show of support for Ukraine's independence, which
came with the collapse of communism nine years ago after three
centuries of rule by Moscow, but has run up against severe economic
hardship and rampant corruption. Ukraine is the third-largest
recipient of U.S. aid, after Israel and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was also a brilliant photo opportunity that Clinton seized to
the fullest. He stood atop a dais and waved to the crowd against a
backdrop of the gold-domed, Wedgwood-blue Monastery of Saint
Michael and a city square decked with huge Ukrainian and U.S.
flags.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, concluding his two-day visit to Moscow,
Clinton had taken a defensive line in his speech to Parliament.
``Many Russians still suspect that America does not wish you
well,'' he said. ``The United States wants a strong Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The reception to that speech, however, was muted. Some deputies
skipped the session, partly because they were confused about when
it was supposed to start. For many of them, NATO's expansion, the
Western alliance's war with Yugoslavia and, more recently, the
administration's plans to build a limited missile defense have
created the impression that Washington revels in its role as the
world's only superpower and is determined to thwart the emergence
of new powers, including Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia's future is very important to others, because it is
among the most important journeys the world will witness in my
lifetime,'' Clinton declared from the lectern.
</P>
<P>
   On security issues, he insisted that his administration's plan
for a limited missile defense was not a drive for military
superiority, and he stressed that he wanted to preserve the
principles of nuclear deterrence. On the economy, Clinton backed
Russia's bid to join the World Trade Organization, a bid that still
requires Moscow to change some of its economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia should not be the only major industrialized country
standing outside this global trading system,'' he said. ``We will
support you, but you must know the decision to join the WTO
requires difficult choices that only you can make.''
</P>
<P>
   On the political front, he criticized the Russian prosecution of
the war in Chechnya. ``My question on Chechnya was an honest one,
the question of a friend,'' he said. ``And that is whether any war
can be won that requires large numbers of civilian casualties and
has no political component bringing about a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   More generally, Clinton insisted that he had not come to Moscow
to preach to Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will choose what your interests clearly demand and what
your people democratically embrace.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some reviews of the speech were generally positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a clever lecture,'' said Andrei Kokoshin, a legislator
in the Fatherland-All Russia party and a national security adviser
when Boris Yeltsin was president. ``I think Clinton is still
important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a full hall'' said Nikolai Kharitonov, the leader
of an agrarian faction that generally supports Putin. ``But it was
not a bad speech. Let's hope it is realized constructively.''
</P>
<P>
   Communists and nationalists in parliament were predictably
critical. The Communists held up signs that read ``Clinton Go
Home'' and ``Defense Missile System Is a Threat to the Word.'' They
chanted, ``Soviet Union! Soviet Union!'' over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Zhirinovsky, a legislator who plays the part of an
ardent nationalist but who is seen by many Russians as a kind of
clown on the political fringe, created a row during Clinton's
speech, screaming ``Shame! Shame!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is he teaching how to live?,'' Zhirinovsky yelled. ``It's
profane! We are not going to do what America commands!''
</P>
<P>
   After addressing parliament, Clinton received the warmer welcome
he was more accustomed to during his previous four trips here as
president when he called on Yeltsin at his residence outside
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Yeltsin had a sense of comradery that was clearly
lacking in the president's businesslike meetings with Putin. And
Clinton seemed to look back on the old meetings wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all just had a nice visit, just like old days,'' Clinton
said. ``He's got a beautiful place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
