<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AIDE SAYS CLINTON-PUTIN MEETING WAS VALUABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story does not carry a byline.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Gov. George W. Bush,
said that the Clinton-Putin meeting had been valuable in advancing
relations between the United States and Russia. Bush welcomed
agreements on disposal of nuclear materials and establishment of a
joint center to monitor missile launchings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Fleischer said, the two leaders did not sign
any binding pledges that would limit action by the next president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is pleased the agreements they reached do not tie
the hands of President Clinton's successor so that we can have a
defense policy that reflects post-Cold War thinking,'' Fleischer
said. ``Nothing that was done will hinder that process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5426 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ALBRIGHT-MIDEAST-NYT &LR;      06-05 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-MIDEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT IN MIDEAST, TRYING TO PUSH ISRAELI-PALESTINIAN TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arrived here
Monday for her first visit in six months, seeking to inject a sense
of urgency into the long-running Israeli-Palestinian negotiations
and to lay the foundation for a three-way retreat-style summit
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment of truth is fast approaching in the pursuit of the
Israeli-Palestinian peace,'' Albright said Monday night. ``If the
Israelis and the Palestinians are willing to accept that neither
can get 100 percent of what they want, and that each side must
address the other in a spirit of partnership, then they will
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with President Clinton's eagerness to propel the
parties toward a final peace accord during his waning months in
office, Albright, who began her visit by meeting with Prime
Minister Ehud Barak of Israel, hopes to imbue both sides with a
spirit of compromise realistic enough to get them to the endgame of
a century-long conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the Israelis and the Palestinians, who remain far
apart on every crucial issue, can come together on any of them
quickly enough remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat have not yet made clear if they are willing to
stare down domestic opponents and make deep concessions on
emotional issues like the fate of Jerusalem and the Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, American officials say, it comes down to whether
Barak and Arafat consider the constellation of their determination,
their political strength and their chemistry sufficient to seize
what all are calling a historic opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Albright is scheduled to meet with Arafat on Tuesday in the West
Bank city of Ramallah, and to return to Barak in the evening.
Arafat is then supposed to travel to Washington to see President
Clinton, who emerged from a meeting with Barak in Lisbon last week
with the optimistic pronouncement that an agreement was ``within
view.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the Oslo interim peace agreement of 1993, the
negotiations on final peace terms were supposed to take three
years. But because of repeated breakdowns in the
Israeli-Palestinian relationship, the talks began in earnest just
six months ago and delved deeply into the substantive issues only
in the last several weeks during back-channel talks in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   Now, American mediators are trying to parse each side's demands
and determine ``what really is critical to them as opposed to what
may be desirable,'' a senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   After her visit here, Albright is to go to Cairo on Wednesday
for talks with Syrian's foreign minister, Farouk al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the first high-level Syrian-American meeting since
President Clinton's failed meeting with President Hafez Assad in
Geneva in March, and it raises the prospect that the moribund
Israeli-Syrian peace track could be resuscitated.
</P>
<P>
   That would be bad news for Arafat. Last December, during
Albright's last trip here, Clinton announced the revival of
Israeli-Syrian talks, which effectively shut down Israel's talks
with the Palestinians for months, until the negotiations with Syria
derailed.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel there is the palpable sense _ an anxiety for the right
wing _ that the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations are about to enter
the final round. Many of Barak's ministers sent him a letter Monday
night demanding that he convene an urgent meeting of the security
cabinet to let them know what was really happening in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   And before he met with Albright Monday night in his office and
then over dinner at his residence, Barak survived the latest in a
series of parliamentary no-confidence resolutions, this one based
on the concessions he is presumed to be making to the Palestinians.
The resolution was voted down, 38 to 33, with 13 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
   Even the doves in Barak's cabinet disagree about how to approach
the months ahead. In one camp are those like Haim Ramon, a
government minister who oversees Jerusalem affairs, who say the
thorniest issues should be deferred. And in the other are those
like Justice Minister Yossi Beilin who say those issues, like
Jerusalem and refugees, will never get any easier.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Clinton administration officials say the goal of the
talks is to reach a full deal. ``If they can achieve it, what they
have agreed on is that it should be an end-of-the-conflict
agreement,'' a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
   And like Beilin, several experts say Barak will find it easier
to win broad public backing in a referendum if a peace deal is
comprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Barak, yielding much of the West Bank is the price for a
deal,'' said David Makovsky, a senior fellow at the Washington
Institute for Near East Policy. ``But the prize of the deal is the
end once and for all of the conflict. To pay the price without
winning the prize will be seen as undermining the entire rationale
of the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
