<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5427 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBN-ROCKER-DEMOTION-N     06-05 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-DEMOTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES DEMOTE ROCKER AND FINE HIM $5,000 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faced with a relief pitcher wild in two ways, the Atlanta Braves
demoted John Rocker to the minor leagues and fined him $5,000
Monday. If Rocker's stay at Richmond of the International League
lasts four weeks, he will miss the Braves' four-game series against
the Mets at Shea Stadium starting June 29.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' action came a day after Rocker verbally attacked a
magazine reporter for the article that quoted Rocker as denigrating
large segments of society. His comments in the Sports Illustrated
interview earned Rocker a fine and suspension and have made him a
controversial focus of attention of fans and players alike.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates had seemed to tolerate him, hoping he would
maintain a low profile and not cause further disruption in their
clubhouse. But his confrontation with the writer, Jeff Pearlman,
near the clubhouse in Atlanta on Sunday appeared to eradicate their
patience.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves said they optioned Rocker to Richmond not for his
behavior off the field but his performance on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As has been fairly evident watching him pitch, he has not been
able to demonstrate the ability to command or control his stuff and
it has gotten him and our team in considerable hot water,'' General
Manager John Schuerholz said by telephone from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz said he, Manager Bobby Cox and Leo Mazzone, the
pitching coach, had been discussing the best way to try to get
Rocker straightened out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environment to do that doesn't exist here,'' Schuerholz
said. ``We don't have the luxury for guys to work their way through
tough times. We decided he needs to pitch consistently to do that.
We think he will do that and be as good as he was last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who last year gained 38 saves, has been one of the most
erratic relievers in the National League this season. He had 10
saves, but he also averaged 2.4 runners per inning. He walked 25
and gave up 18 hits in 18 1/3 innings. Of the 41 NL pitchers who
had walked 25 or more before Monday night's games, most had pitched
far more innings than Rocker. The closest pitcher to him was Scott
Sauerbeck, a Pittsburgh reliever, who had walked 31 in 29 1/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz said the problem had reached the point where Cox
``had to have a shadow closer behind the closer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That wears on the bullpen,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Braves wanted to remove Rocker from the team quickly
for disciplinary reasons, his wildness gave them good cover for
their move. The Braves don't have to give a reason for optioning
Rocker, but the players association could question whether it was
disciplinary action. Gene Orza, the union's associate general
counsel, was traveling Monday and could not be reached for comment
on the option.
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz readily acknowledged that the fine was a disciplinary
measure for Rocker's tirade against Pearlman, who quoted the
pitcher as telling him, ``Do you know what I can do to you?'' and
``This isn't over between us.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig said in a statement that he was
``saddened by the regrettable incident'' that took place in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major League Baseball is monitoring the situation closely,''
he added, ``and I have been in contact with Braves president Stan
Kasten throughout the day. While Major League baseball is
conducting its own investigation, I am satisfied that the Braves
have moved expeditiously and have treated the matter with the
seriousness it deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig, acting on Rocker's magazine comments, initially fined
Rocker $20,000 and suspended him for all of spring training and the
first four weeks of the season. However, the union challenged the
action as excessive and baseball's impartial arbitrator reduced the
fine to $500 and the suspension to the first two weeks of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   An optioned player must remain in the minors for 10 days unless
another player on the major league roster is injured. But a
four-week stay would ease a problem Major League Baseball has
dreaded _ his appearance at Shea for the first time since the N.L.
championship series last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the security issue becomes less of a concern if he is
not with the team,'' Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager,
said Monday. ``I think we'll be prepared either way. It's something
we always have to be aware of when a team like the Braves is in.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said he could understand why the Braves sent Rocker to
the minors. ``It becomes a disruption,'' he said. ``You've read the
players' comments plus he hasn't been performing well.''
</P>
<P>
   To take Rocker's place on the roster, the Braves promoted Jason
Marquis, a pitcher, from Class AA Greenville.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
