<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5428 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NJ-CENSUS-NYT &LR;      06-05 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CENSUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS WAR SHIFTS TO STATES, WHERE COUNTING HEADS WINS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Ariz., Colo., Kan., Va., La., Utah, Mich., Pa.)  By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Congress and the Clinton administration in a
stalemate over whether or not to rely solely on traditional
counting methods in the 2000 census, Republicans have quietly moved
the battle over the decennial head count from Washington to state
capitals.
</P>
<P>
   At the prompting of state party leaders, the
Republican-controlled New Jersey Assembly approved a bill Monday
night mandating that the state only use census data derived from
mailed-in census forms, door-to-door canvassers or other
traditional means when it redraws congressional and state
legislative lines. The measure passed 42-34, with Republicans and
Democrats voting along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau and Democrats argue that such traditional
counting methods should be supplemented by data obtained from a
randomly selected national sample of 314,000 households. The
information gleaned from these households would be used to adjust
population totals and, Census Bureau officials say, make the census
more accurate.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey bill, which both Republicans and Democrats expect
also to pass in the state Senate would, if signed by Gov. Christie
Whitman, make New Jersey the sixth state to ban the use of census
data that is adjusted using sampling in the redrawing of
congressional and legislative district lines. The other states are
Alaska, Arizona, Colorado, Kansas and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Similar measures have been passed in at least one legislative
chamber in Louisiana, Utah and Michigan, and the Pennsylvania
Senate has passed a nonbinding resolution that also prohibits the
use of adjusted data in redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   All the bills have been introduced by Republican state
legislators and votes have followed party lines.
</P>
<P>
   The movement of the fight over statistical sampling to the
states is a deliberate strategy on the part of national leaders of
the Republican Party who felt their prospects of blocking sampling
in Washington were small.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years President Clinton has vetoed bills that would
have prevented the Census Bureau from conducting a census that was
supplemented by statistical sampling.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court gave opponents of sampling only a partial
victory when it ruled in that the method could not be used in
determining population counts used in allocating seats in the House
of Representatives among the states, but was silent on whether
sampling could be used to draw lines for legislative districts.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the Supreme Court decision, the Census Bureau
announced that it would produce two sets of population figures. One
would be used to apportion seats in the House of Representatives
among the states. The other set of numbers could, if the states so
choose, be used to draw congressional and state legislative
districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Supreme Court decision, it was decided the prospects
of achieving much more in Washington had basically disappeared,''
said a Republican official who was familiar with the strategy but
who asked not to be identified. He added: ``It was a definite
strategy that once all the progress that could be made in
Washington was done, the idea was to turn it over to the states.''
</P>
<P>
   By adjusting the population counts using numbers from the
national sample, the Census Bureau hopes to avoid a repeat of the
1990 Census when more than 8 million people, mainly minorities,
were missed, and another 4 million people, mainly whites, were
counted twice.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's plans, however, have become the subject of an
intense partisan debate. Republicans fear, and Democrats hope that
adjusting the census count will increase the number of people
living in traditionally Democratic areas. As a result, these areas
may gain seats in state legislatures at the expense of white
suburban or rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey Monday familiar arguments over the legality of
statistical sampling and whether it produces more or less accurate
population figures for small geographic areas _ debating points
that filled the air in Washington in recent years _ echoed in the
halls of the state legislature in Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   ``An argument can be made that statistical sampling can be more
accurate on a universal level, say for getting the population of
New Jersey,'' said Michael Patrick Carroll, a Republican from
Morris County who is the chief sponsor of the bill. ``But when
you're trying to get the population of Grove Street in Morristown,
then statistical sampling has a huge margin of error, something
along the lines of 35 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Census officials acknowledge that in some tests that were
conducted before the actual census, population figures derived by
using numbers from a national sample were off by about 35 percent
in some small geographic areas. But these officials say often
figures obtained by traditional counting methods are equally
inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, a group of black ministers and African-American and
Hispanic legislators called on Whitman to veto Carroll's measure
when it reaches her desk.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference, the Rev. Reginald Jackson, executive
director of the Black Ministers' Council, called the bill
``divisive'' and added that ``it dilutes, lessens and, in fact,
negates the votes of Latinos, African Americans and other
minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter McDonough, a spokesman for Whitman said that the governor
has yet to decide whether she will sign the measure or veto it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not formed an opinion on the bill yet,'' McDonough
said. ``We are waiting to hear more of the debate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
