<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5429 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-05 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: FLAG DEBATE
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Ireland Assembly met for the first time since home
rule was suspended by Britain in February and spent the day
debating whether the Union Jack, the Irish tricolor, both flags or
no flag should fly over official buildings. The Rev. Ian Paisley,
head of the hardline Ulster Democratic Party that has vowed to
disrupt the power-sharing government, protested the refusal of two
ministers from Sinn Fein, political ally of the Irish Republican
Army, to raise the British flag at their offices.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: THOUSANDS PROTEST KILLING
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people held silent vigils across the country to
protest the death of Jesus Maria Pedrosa, a town councilor in the
Basque city of Durango shot to death by suspected Basque rebels.
Pedrosa was a member of Spain's ruling center-right Popular Party
and had received threats from radical Basque separatists. The armed
Basque group ETA has reportedly killed five people since ending a
cease-fire last December.
</P>
<P>
   EASTERN EUROPE: RESTORING DANUBE DELTA
</P>
<P>
   Romania, Bulgaria, Ukraine, and Moldova signed an agreement to
enlarge the protected part of the Danube River delta to more than
2.5 million acres of marshes and flood plains. The river, whose
tributaries drain 11 countries on the way to the Black Sea, has
been heavily polluted over the last century by industrialization
and mining on its banks.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA: U.N. HOSTAGES FREED
</P>
<P>
   Four hostages involved in United Nations work in the rebellious
Abkhazia region of Georgia were freed after being held for five
days by gunmen. Two were United Nations observers from Denmark, one
a British mine-clearing expert and the fourth an Abkhazian
interpreter. Although the abductors, part of a group that does not
recognize Abkhazia's independence declaration, demanded a ransom,
none was apparently paid. The United Nations has about 100
cease-fire monitors in Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE: U.S. REPORT CONDEMNED
</P>
<P>
   The government dismissed as an ``anti-Hellenic concoction'' a
U.S. congressional report suggesting sanctions against Greece
because of its ``passive response'' to terrorism. Defending Greece
as a safe and secure country, a government spokesman, Dimitris
Reppas, said the report ``presented a false picture of Greece.''
The report came a month after the State Department ranked Greece
second to Colombia in anti-American terrorist attacks in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: FOX SLIPS
</P>
<P>
   Four weeks before the July 2 presidential balloting, Francisco
Labastida of the governing party has again edged ahead of Vicente
Fox, the leading opposition contender, according to a poll by the
newspaper Reforma. The survey of 1,543 voters found Labastida
favored by 42 percent of voters and Fox by 38 percent. Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas, the leftist candidate, was backed by 17 percent. The
margin of error was plus or minus 2.5 percent. A poll in early May
showed Fox leading Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: TAX PROTEST CONTINUES
</P>
<P>
   The police in Peshawar fired tear gas at merchants and beat up
some of those who demonstrated against the government's efforts to
catch tax evaders and impose a 15 percent sales tax. Chanting
shopkeepers marched in defiance of a ban on protests on the eighth
day of a partial strike against the new measures.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: MAHATHIR RULING
</P>
<P>
   An appeals court refused to overturn a ruling that Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad will not be required to testify at the
sexual misconduct trial of his former deputy, Anwar Ibrahim.
Ibrahim contends the case against him was manufactured by the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: SUHARTO QUIZZED
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors questioned former President Suharto in a continuing
attempt to build a case against him for corruption and abuse of
power. It was the first questioning since he was placed under house
arrest a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON, GERMANY: ASYLUM OFFER
</P>
<P>
   Germany is prepared to offer political asylum to as many as 400
members of the Israeli-backed South Lebanese militia that disbanded
when Israel withdrew from southern Lebanon. About 6,000 Lebanese
fled to Israel; of those, some want to stay, some seek to return
and some aspire to be resettled abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
