<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5431 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-05 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PANNING FOR GOLD IN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's one heck of a lot of money sloshing around the political
troughs these days. According to a report in Monday's New York
Times by William Glaberson, one race for the Ohio Supreme Court
this year is going to cost up to $12 million. We have candidates
spending a couple of million dollars to become state legislator, a
job that generally carries less prestige than that of nightclub
bouncer. At this rate, the next bunch of people stranded on a
desert island with a TV crew is going to demand a whole lot more
than a lousy million dollars for the effort. (Coming soon: ``Who
Wants to Be a Political Consultant?'')
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to the primary Tuesday in New Jersey, where a
former Wall Street honcho named Jon Corzine has spent close to $35
million trying to win the Democratic nomination for U.S. Senate
against former Gov. Jim Florio, whose entire budget is
approximately what Corzine will be spending on fax machines and
commemorative potholders.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine is in many ways a fascinating story, although the
fascinating part does not seem to follow him onto the campaign
trail. Despite the very best coaching money can buy and a
dramatically left-wing agenda, he makes Steve Forbes look like
Franklin Delano Roosevelt. (In a recent debate, Corzine delivered
this defense for his largess: ``I have not been a politician and
spent 30 million and over 30 years building name recognition and
establishing the perspectives people might have. I needed to
communicate.'')
</P>
<P>
   According to one of his associates, Corzine entered the race
envisioning a $10 million primary, a plan that went awry somewhere
between his decision to hire Robert Shrum, the man who gave us Al
Checchi's failed $38 million campaign for governor of California,
and the moment he started opening his checkbook for the local
Democratic organizations. Corzine used to be famous for his
munificent federal campaign contributions. But he assured New
Jersey party officials that his newfound interest in state politics
would naturally be reflected by a shift in his gift-giving. This
had the approximate effect of tossing a chunk of hamburger into a
tank of piranhas. ``Word got out there was this pot there, and
things got out of control,'' conceded one campaign official.
</P>
<P>
   One of the comforting things about American election campaigns
is the way the monetary playing field keeps leveling. You come into
the game like George W. Bush with a big fat financial cushion and
slurp, it vanishes. Nature may abhor a vacuum, but political
campaigns can create one in a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always that pressure _ to donate to the local parties,
hire the local potentates' daughters. You end up not saying no to
anything,'' recalled John Weaver, who has run presidential
campaigns for candidates with too little cash (John McCain) and too
much (Phil Gramm). ``Gramm went through the money pretty quickly,''
he recalled. ``We had about 25 opposition research people. We
probably needed one.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no way that Corzine could go through his entire
$400 million fortune running for Senate _ potentates have only just
so many unemployed relatives and you can only run so many ads on TV
before the viewer throws a shoe through the screen. Even as it is,
Corzine may have overdone it. He seems to have made people feel a
little sorry for Florio, a feat most New Jersey residents might
have hitherto regarded as impossible. Corzine not only spent about
20 times as much as his opponent, he also managed to make Florio,
whose household income last year was more than $500,000, look
underprivileged.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has already broken the record for spending in a U.S.
Senate race, set by Michael Huffington in California in 1994. But
that was for the entire election, against an incumbent. It takes a
lot of money to overcome those odds, especially when your candidate
seems both shy and dimwitted. Corzine is running for a vacant seat,
against a primary opponent who is best known for having raised
taxes by $2.8 billion. He does not seem to lack aggression. His
friends say he is smart, and they rave about his generosity.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if all the stories about his beneficence are true,
every single person who put a Corzine sign on the front lawn this
week should expect to be rewarded with a paid-off mortgage or, at
minimum, a reshingled roof. When the money starts sloshing, the
wise man goes for a pail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
