<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A DAY OF READING AND ROLE MODELS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What a great scene. A splendid afternoon in New York,
250 elementary students sitting in Central Park's Rumsey Playfield
to help the New York Public Library kick off another summer reading
club membership drive.
</P>
<P>
   There was a fresh twist to this year's Reading Rally:
professional athletes _ Major League Baseball players _ the Mets'
Al Leiter, the veteran pitcher; Todd Zeile, the first baseman; the
reserve infielder Matt Franco and Manager Bobby Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   The kids sat in bleachers and, on Valentine's cue, chanted,
``Let's Go Mets.'' Then they settled down to listen to the players.
Franco began by reading ``Where the Wild Things Are.'' Zeile read
``Giraffe and a Half'' as Valentine pantomimed each new layer of
the story: ``a giraffe and a half _ with a rat in his hat _ looking
cute in his suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Leiter read ``The Great Kapok Tree.'' He prefaced the
reading with a caveat about his own elementary school days when he
didn't love to read as much as he should have.
</P>
<P>
   This was a good day, though for the young students a confusing
day of sports news that defines their lives.
</P>
<P>
   They learned that Ray Lewis, a talented linebacker for the
Baltimore Ravens on trial for murder and aggravated assault, got
the break of his young life: Probation, no prison time in exchange
for his testimony against two co-defendants. The students learned
that John Rocker, Atlanta's volatile relief pitcher who made news
for ugly comments about gays, minorities and New Yorkers in
general, blasted the reporter who wrote the story. By day's end the
students learned that Rocker had been demoted to the minors and
fined $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   What a collage: baseball players reading books to kids on a
sunny afternoon; a football player paying dearly for bad judgment
and a pitcher on the brink of ruining his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more than just a story,'' Leiter said. ``It's almost
like a book you can write on professional sports being a microcosm
of society in the year 2000. What I see, even outside my teammates
is that it's a very loose, liberal environment. There a lot of
people who have very little concern for discipline. I think our
society has gotten to a point where freedom of this and freedom of
that is more important of maybe knowing what's right and wrong and
having somebody to let you know what's right and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter broke in with the Yankees in 1987. When the subject of
athletes and responsibility is raised, Leiter's lament is similar
to the lament of veteran athletes in all sports and older workers
in all professions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in when Ron Guidry would look at me a certain way and I
knew I had to shut up,'' he said. ``Or Dave Righetti. If he saw
that I sat too far in the back of the plane he'd just go like
this.'' Leiter motioned with his index finger, as if to say, `Come
here.' ``I didn't curse or say, `Who do you think you are?',''
Leiter said. ``I turned around. I understood the fraternity of it,
I respected him as a person and as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, the older guys stood their ground and made a stink
of it. We, as older guys, we don't hold our ground; we'll let an
idiot young player get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter said the reason older players may not chastise younger
ones as readily _ or as rigorously as before _ is the perceived
volatility of youth. He recalled the old days when you fought and
the fight ended and was over. ``Now you're worried someone might
have a gun. You think of stuff like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Does Leiter really think younger players would respond violently
to being corrected. ``Maybe they would,'' he said. ``There was a
guy, Jackie Gutierez a few years ago, winter ball. A guy made him
mad; he went home, got a gun and came back: Forget that. I don't
know what kind of unstable mind some of these guys have.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is Rocker thinking? What's he thinking? I don't know. I
don't want to make him mad. Plus he's a big guy; probably kick my
behind. So you know what? You turn your head and say, `Forget it.'
If the people upstairs don't see this and don't take care of it,
just because he throws 97 miles per hour ... I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The answers came out right Monday: Atlanta made John Rocker the
minor leaguer he's always been. Lewis, as it turned out, was stupid
but not guilty. And the Mets? The Mets made 250 elementary school
students associate sports with all the good stuff: sunny days,
baseball and ``Giraffes and a Half.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
