<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poll: Fan split on what todo with Rocker
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marion Hammond wore her John Rocker jersey to Turner Field
Monday night and was disappointed that the real No. 49 wouldn't be
in a Braves uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farther in trouble he gets, the better I like him, because
he stands up for what he believes in,'' said Hammond, 47, of
Sylacauga, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was sent down to Richmond a day after he confronted
Sports Illustrated writer Jeff Pearlman at the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're punishing him for what he said,'' Hammond
said, ``plus he hasn't been throwing good anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Other fans said that Rocker's lack of control in his conduct _
not to mention his throwing _ justified sending him to the minors
to work on his game.
</P>
<P>
   In an online vote conducted on ajc.com, which began before the
demotion, 58 percent of the first 11,000 respondents voted to keep
Rocker on the team and 42 percent wanted to get rid of him. But
during the game, the next 5,000 voters had swung the poll toward
booting rocker 50 percent to 49 percent, with 1 percent voting to
``give him one last chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Demuth, 26, of Charleston, S.C., believes sending Rocker
to Richmond was the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's to get his wits about him,'' Demuth said. ``He
has to rethink his career.''
</P>
<P>
   And Demuth thinks Rocker's absence will improve morale. ``You
don't want to have someone in your clubhouse who's giving a
negative feeling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But like many fans, Demuth wants to see a new, improved Rocker
back in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He adds to the game,'' he said. ``I hope he's a little smarter
and has his mouth under control a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   And his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Brown, of Rome, Ga., agreed that the 25-year-old closer
needed to find his strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``And maybe he needs to regroup his thoughts about what he said
and what he's done,'' said Brown, 54, who wore a 1995 World Series
shirt. ``Maybe he hasn't gotten over it, and he needs to.''
</P>
<P>
   She wants to see him back, too, ``but not like he was. He
doesn't fit the typical profile of a Brave. The image I have of a
Brave is of a gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's husband, Randle, 57, a Braves fan since the team arrived
in Atlanta, thinks the Braves can use Rocker, ``but he's got a head
problem right now. It's affecting his skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Wells of Sheridan, Wyo., who has followed the team since
they were the Milwaukee Braves in 1957, was making his first trip
to Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking forward to the excitement when he came sprinting
in from the bullpen tonight,'' said Wells, 52.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks Rocker was sent packing because of his outburst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're going to be counseling Rocker on how to deal
with the media over the issues from his statements,'' Wells said,
``and I think they want to emphasize to him that what he did
yesterday is not acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wells thinks the Braves can't win it all without Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the Braves to win the World Series,'' he said.
``Rocker's a part of that and I think the Braves know that. I don't
think the Braves are going to deal him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
