<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newsweek speculates on Ted, George on the politics of beauty
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fathers will have their day on June 18, and now they have their
own magazine. A new bimonthly publication, dads ($2.99), debuts
today with a cover story on Cal Ripken and articles aimed at
helping men be parents. Features include notes on fatherhood from
Ben Stein, Frank McCourt and Boomer Esiason, advice on how parents
can connect with their sons, and tips on what gifts fathers really
want.
</P>
<P>
   Editor Eric Garland, a new father, says the magazine fills a
niche that traditional magazines have ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our proposition is simple,'' Garland says. ``Men are
different. We are different from our fathers' generation, and
different from our wives. ... We want to be more committed, more
connected.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine is packed with helpful, if somewhat bland, service
articles. What it needs are more entertaining essays such as Debra
Goldman's column on how fathers are portrayed on television. Even
the new show ``Once and Again'' gets it wrong, she notes: The
divorced-dad character, Rick, is ``the perfect dad, the perfect
lover _ and, alas, the perfect bore.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  All about Ted: In a report on CNN's 20th-anniversary bash and
the pending AOL-Time Warner merger, Newsweek ($3.50) recaps the
events in Ted Turner's private life and speculates about the media
mogul's future without any clear-cut duties. Telling Newsweek
correspondent Johnnie L. Roberts that ``change is always difficult
for older people,'' Turner then hints that he might try to buy a
television network. But AOL's Steve Case says the network deal is
not happening: ``This is not the right time to be thinking of other
acquisitions.'' (Rob come out a winner.
</P>
<P>
   If this light is on, your vehicle's emissions are out of
control. Scheduled maintenance may help, but sometimes these items
simply deteriorate over time.
</P>
<P>
   The first on my list is the oxygen sensor, thurn the extra fuel
completely. Instead of getting carbon dioxide (a harmless gas that
trees recycle into oxygen), you end up with carbon monoxide (a
poisonous gas that kills people and animals). This is called a
fuel-rich mixture.
</P>
<P>
   The other side of the coin is too much oxygen and not enough
fuel. Although this would seem to be OK because extra oxygen
shouldn't hurt anything, the fuel molecules are moved further apart
from each other, becoming difficult to ignite. The combustion
process is incomplete. This is called a lean mixture.
</P>
<P>
   The byproduct is hydrocarbons (the stinky part of exhaust) and
extra oxygen. In addition, extra oxygen causes a hotter burning,
which creates another gas called oxides of nitrogen, or NOX.
Hydrocarbons and NOX contribute to ground-level ozone.
</P>
<P>
   The oxygen sensor is called that because it senses oxygen by
comparing the amount of oxygen in the air with the amount of oxygen
contained in the exhaust gasses. If there is too little oxygen, it
sends the signal back to the computer that the fuel is rich, so it
cuts the fuel supply to the engine.
</P>
<P>
   Now the exhaust gas will contain more oxygen. The O2 sensor
sends the signal back to the computer, which interprets a lean
condition, so it supplies more fuel to the engine. This seesaw
effect happens in milliseconds. As long as it switches back and
forth at this rapid pace, proper fuel control is taking place,
resulting in complete combustion. Years of starting, warming up,
idling, and miles of driving take its toll. The sensor becomes
lethargic, reacting slowly to the change in oxygen. The signal to
the computer slows down, and fuel control is affected, increasing
tailpipe emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter is an automotive instructor and an ASE master
automobile technician/L1. Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
