<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5448 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REFORM-PARTY-(TRIMS)-     06-05 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEROT IS UNLIKELY TO CHALLENGE BUCHANAN, HIS AIDE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mass., Minn., Colo., Del., Md., Alaska, Wyo., R.I.,
Calif.)   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite his distaste for Pat Buchanan's conservative views on
social issues, Ross Perot, the founder of the Reform Party and it
two-time presidential candidate, has all but ruled out running
against Buchanan for the party nomination this year, a spokesman
for Perot said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way someone could get in now and compete for the
presidential nomination,'' said Russell J. Verney, a former
national chairman of the Reform Party who remains close to Perot
and often conveys his political sentiments. Verney added that Perot
had no plans to engineer an 11th-hour campaign to put himself in
contention for the nomination through a balloting process that
begins next month and ends on the eve of the party convention in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Verney's statement seems to remove the last bit of uncertainty
over whether Buchanan will win the third-party nomination and the
$12.5 million in federal campaign funds that go with it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Verney emphasized that staying out of the race did not
necessarily reflect Perot's support for Buchanan, even though it
was largely at Perot's invitation that Buchanan left the Republican
party last year to join the Reform movement.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Verney expressed concern that Buchanan was ultimately
less interested in winning the White House than in presiding over
an ``ideologically pure right-wing party'' that reflected his
deeply held beliefs on social issues like abortion and
homosexuality, which the Reform Party platform has ignored for the
sake of party unity.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, a former White House speech writer and political
pundit, deflected the accusation in an interview Monday with
Political Points, the Web cast of The New York Times and ABC News.
``I'm criticized on the one hand by social conservatives,'' he
said. ``They say, `You've abandoned right-to-life, Pat, and you're
not talking about the social issues.' On the other hand, there are
Reform Party opposition folks who say, `All you're talking about is
right-to-life and the social issues.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of the matter is I've never abandoned my views and
philosophy. I am pro-life. I indicated to that in my opening
announcement running for the Reform Party nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the concern about Buchanan's intentions focuses on what
he and his allies could do with the Reform platform. While the
popular vote determines the nominee _ virtually any registered
voter can cast a ballot _ a nominee supported by two-thirds of the
delegates has the right to rewrite the party platform and its
preamble, both of which are currently silent on social issues.
Party rules also provide for a two-thirds vote of the delegates to
overturn the popular choice of presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   No one from Buchanan's campaign has said unequivocally that he
would not alter the platform or preamble if he were nominated. Paul
Truax, who serves as the party's southwest regional representative,
said Monday that Buchanan officials ``have told us repeatedly they
would not make a change this year. But we just don't know. Are we
supposed to be satisfied for just this year? We don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   To win a place on the Reform primary ballot, a candidate has to
demonstrate, through signature petitions, sufficient support around
the country to become a viable challenger to the likely major party
nominees, Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Buchanan has helped get the Reform Party on the ballot
in almost 30 states, and he was well on his way to securing the
delegates he would need if he wanted to alter the party platform.
After state reform party conventions last weekend in Iowa,
California and Rhode Island, he estimated that he has won the
support of almost half of the 596 national convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're really marching toward the nomination,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, opposition remains.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of Perot, some Reform leaders are backing John
Hagelin of the nascent Natural Law party. Reform Party officials
opposed to Buchanan have been helping the Hagelin campaign generate
support among Reform members who feel more comfortable with the
party platform as it was written with Perot at the helm. Those
issues focus on government reform as the party's major thrust,
positions that the Natural Law party embraces in a variety of
areas, like education, health care and the environment. Like the
current Reform Party platform, the Natural Law party takes no
official position on abortion or other social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin, a research physicist from Connecticut who now lives in
Iowa, predicted that he would win the popular vote over Buchanan
because his politics appeal to a broader base of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely positive about our chances,'' Hagelin said in an
interview. ``And I'm quite confident we are going to win the public
plebiscite.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Opponents to Buchanan are also trying to ease his
ever-tightening grip on the party infrastructure. In addition to
collecting signatures and wooing delegates, Buchanan has also
enjoyed widespread success in helping place supporters in key state
party positions. In at least three states _ Wyoming, Delaware and
Maryland _ the state party chairman, who is ostensibly supposed to
project neutrality, is also the Buchanan campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   And two members of the national convention credentials
committee, which controls who gets seated, are Buchanan chairmen in
their states, Alaska and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some Buchanan supporters say the efforts to derail him _
especially any by Perot supporters _ are simply sour grapes because
they have lost control of the party. David Goldman, a senior party
official in Florida who was once a staunch Perot and Verney
loyalist, said he has broken with them to support Buchanan over
what he described as ``fraudulent behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   As examples, he cited Dick Lamm, the former Colorado governor,
Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota and Buchanan as people they invited
to join the party and help expand its base, only to turn on them
when they began to generate support.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would rather blow up the party than allow people like
Ventura and Buchanan to have control,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Buchanan, he added, ``They're trying to destroying their
own creation, but he has been strong enough to resist their efforts
to drive him out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
