<HEADER>
A5453 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TERRORISM-STUDENTS-BO     06-05 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORISM-STUDENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US PLANS TO MONITOR FOREIGN STUDENTS ALARMS SOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Terrorism-Report)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If a foreign student enrolls in a US university to
pursue a literature degree then switches to study nuclear physics,
should the move be monitored by school and immigration officials?
</P>
<P>
   Such changes are already kept on file at individual
universities. But when a congressional panel on terrorism Monday
suggested that the Immigration and Naturalization Service should
also be notified about a student's study program, it drew immediate
criticism, even though plans for tracking foreign students more
closely have been under way for years.
</P>
<P>
   Some school officials, and one former CIA anti-terrorism chief,
expressed alarm at a suggestion in the report by the National
Commission on Terrorism that a new immigration system might
``record a student's change in major from English literature to
nuclear physics.'' Sharon Ladd, director of Harvard University's
International Office, said she ``sort of shuddered'' when she heard
about the report on the news. She cited how controversial the
monitoring of student visas has been historically.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my colleagues are very concerned about (the program)
being intrusive,'' she said. ``I think a lot of it is the way it's
being portrayed. Is this the INS trying to provide a service for
schools, or is it that we're trying to track terrorists?''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's recommendation came as part of a 47-page report, titled
``Countering the Changing Threat of Terrorism,'' mandated by
Congress after the US embassy bombings in East Africa two years
ago. The recommendations included reclassifying Greece and Pakistan
as countries ``not cooperating fully'' with anti-terrorism efforts,
as well as devoting greater resources to collecting
counterintelligence information. In general, the commission found
that the US government should prepare more fully for a terrorist
attack.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more unusual proposals was one to limit the ability
of federal law enforcement officials to keep ``secret evidence''
when prosecuting foreign terrorism suspects. Juliette N. Kayyem,
one of the 10 members of the commission and an associate at the
Kennedy School of Government at Harvard University, said the
recommendation marked a victory for civil rights advocates because
it recognized that in hiding evidence from a defendant, Americans
had ``gone too far.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first national security commission which has been
known to ask for less,'' Kayyem said.
</P>
<P>
   But that measure was greatly overshadowed by the single line in
the report recommending the monitoring of student degree programs,
in part because the rules governing an estimated 250,000 foreign
students are still in flux.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the 1993 bombing of the World Trade Center, when
immigration officials were unable to locate a suspect who entered
the country on a student visa and stayed after it expired, the INS
has been under pressure to map a new strategy for monitoring
foreign students. Efforts have thus far mostly centered on an
obvious first step: putting all student visa information onto a
computer network instead of relying on paperwork that takes months
to process.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of Monday's report said they were not proposing any
expansion of INS powers. The chairman of the blue ribbon panel,
former ambassador L. Paul Bremmer, said there would be ``no change
in procedure or in the scope of it,'' saying the chief
recommendation was that the INS streamline its paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   The written recommendation was worded extremely cautiously:
``The President and Congress should work together to create an
effective system for monitoring the status of foreign students
nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview, Bremmer outlined a program that went beyond
the one INS officials describe as their current practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presumably, if you had a student from a terrorist state
switching majors from humanities into molecular biology or nuclear
physics, it should at least send up a red flag at INS to ask
questions about the guy,'' said Brenner, a former
ambassador-at-large for counter-terrorism. ``Presumably, you could
have the INS call him in for an interview.''
</P>
<P>
   In developing its new strategy for monitoring foreign students
over the last four years, the INS has moved relatively cautiously,
beginning with a pilot program known as the Coordinated Interagency
Partnership Regulating International Students, or CIPRIS.
</P>
<P>
   Comprised of 20 schools in Southern states, CIPRIS is described
by immigration officials as simply a computerized version of the
current paper system _ and a welcome advance at the often outdated
immigration agency, according to officials at several schools.
</P>
<P>
   But despite assurances by the report's authors that the panel
was not suggesting any expansion of authority, an INS official
Monday night said the new INS pilot program does not include
monitoring which degree a student is pursuing. Eyleen Schmidt, an
INS spokeswoman, said it was ``not included as part of the original
CIPRIS pilot, and at this point, there are not plans to include
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said the panel had, in its recommendation, interpreted
immigration law differently from the INS. One of the elements the
INS tracks is the ``current academic status'' of a student, which
it defines as whether a student is in school full-time. The panel,
she said, would redefine that term to include which program a
student was enrolled in.
</P>
<P>
   But in doing so, said Vince Cannistraro, former head of the CIA
counter-terrorism unit, the commission was addressing ``a problem
that may not exist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's intrusive,'' Cannistraro said of the commission's
proposal. ``I don't think it's necessary. The FBI already has all
the authority they need to follow people who are up to no good. If
you put on them the additional burden of tracking every foreign
student in the United States, you run a significant risk of civil
liberties infringements.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5454 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PERU-ELECTION-NYT &LR;      06-05 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS DENOUNCE FREE TRADE AS OAS DELEGATES DEBATE PERU 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario _ Inside the annual meeting of the Organization
of American States, delegates debated Monday Peru's flawed
presidential vote. But outside, free trade was the issue that
brought 2,500 protesters surging around the 10-foot steel mesh
fence protecting the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can say they are talking about poverty, and dealing with
issues like Peru and so on,'' said Maude Barlow, chairwoman of the
Council of Canadians, a nationalist group. ``But the OAS is the
political institution moving forward the agenda of Free Trade Area
of the Americas.''
</P>
<P>
   Although trade is not on the agenda of the three-day meeting,
which ends on Wednesday, some Canadian and American demonstrators
against free trade had vowed to shut it down.
</P>
<P>
   With almost one police officer on duty here for each protester,
Canada decided to follow the example of Washington, D.C., last
April in pre-empting protesters before they could cause the chaos
that disrupted the World Trade Organization meeting last November
in Seattle. The protests here have been the largest in memory at an
OAS gathering.
</P>
<P>
   In the four days leading up to Sunday's protest, Canadian
immigration officials at the bridge and tunnel crossings from
Detroit refused admittance to 560 Americans, a much higher rate
than the normal rate of refusal of 1,000 a month. Ken Lawrence, a
spokesman for the immigration service, said many of ``the
individuals were coming in to protest.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny Yen, a Canadian customs spokesman, said that during the
same time at the Detroit crossing, customs officials had
confiscated, from about 200 Americans, hundreds of items that could
have been used in protests, including tear gas canisters, gas
masks, eye goggles, bleach, pepper spray, pipes, bats, flares and
spray-paint cans.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, 41 protesters were arrested outside the riverfront
convention center here, 35 for blocking a bus that carried
delegates and several more for attempting to scale the security
fence. Sgt. David Rossell of the Windsor police said that officers
used pepper spray after protesters hiding behind an anti-free-trade
banner had thrown smoke bombs and unknown liquids at them.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, about 400 people in downtown Detroit, across
the river here, paraded with Shut Down OAS banners, chanting
``Clean up this mess, stop the OAS.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, police officers removed scores of demonstrators who
had linked arms and sat in the rain to block delegates in three
buses from arriving at an official luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that by moving aggressively, they had
headed off the kind of disorder that cost $10 million in damage in
Seattle and led to 525 arrests. In Washington, D.C., there were
1,300 arrests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
