<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5457 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-EDDY-LIBRARY-BOS &LR;      06-05 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDDY-LIBRARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LIBRARY TO MAKE AVAILABLE MARY BAKER EDDY PAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Christian Science Church plans to announce Tuesday
a plan to build a $50 million research library to house more than
500,000 documents and artifacts of church founder Mary Baker Eddy.
</P>
<P>
   The documents, many of which have not been available to scholars
or the public, are expected to make the Mary Baker Eddy Library for
the Betterment of Humanity the largest library devoted to the work
of an American woman.
</P>
<P>
   The library, which is being modeled after presidential
libraries, with a mix of exhibits for tourists, archives for
researchers, and meeting spaces for conferences, will be housed in
the 68-year-old Publication Society Building, in the church's
landmark Back Bay headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Leading religion and US history specialists said the library
would provide invaluable resources on the history of gender, faith,
and journalism in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was quite fascinated by the comprehensiveness of the
collection,'' said Don W. Wilson, who has worked on numerous
presidential libraries, including the George Bush presidential
library in Houston, and is one of several non-Christian Science
scholars on a panel that will oversee the Eddy Library.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a 19th century woman leader who was ahead of her
time, and the collection shows the multifaceted nature of her
interests, in journalism, in healing, in a whole variety of
issues,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to construct the library comes as the Christian
Science church is increasingly seeking to promote public interest
in Eddy as an early advocate of spiritual healing and an early
example of women's rights in action. The church, which does not
release estimates of the size of its membership, says it will not
use the library to recruit new members.
</P>
<P>
   ``These papers are probably the largest single collection by a
woman leader of the 19th century that remained unavailable through
the 20th century. . . . I suspect (they) will be widely used in
many areas,'' said historian Allen Weinstein, president of the
Washington-based Center for Democracy. The former Smith College and
Boston University professor has been granted access to the archives
and is working on a book of Eddy's letters.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Science Church, founded by Eddy in 1867, has often
been controversial, largely because many members refuse the medical
care of doctors because of their belief that disease can be cured
through prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Eddy, a native of Bow, N.H., who lived part of her adulthood in
and around Boston, enjoyed a long life _ from 1821 to 1910 _ and
she was an extraordinarily prolific writer and a dedicated saver of
documents. The collection includes her diaries, scrapbooks, poems,
sermons, and notes, as well as correspondence to and from everyone
from her grandchildren to suffragist Susan B. Anthony, publisher
William Randolph Hearst, and first lady Ida S. McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   Her collection, which church officials started saving before she
died, has been supplemented by donations and purchases over the
last century, and is now stored in vaults in and around Boston.
Church archivists believe they have 500,000 documents, 14,000
photographs and 7,000 objects associated with Eddy, but specialists
say estimates of collections of this size are often low.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials say they hope to open the library in 2002, and
a satellite facility in Seneca Falls, N.Y., in 2003. Seneca Falls
is the site of the first women's rights convention in 1848.
</P>
<P>
   The church also owns three houses that Eddy lived in, as well as
her artworks, her personal library, her jewelry, and the eight
carriages in which she traveled around Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Among the documents, now being catalogued by 20 church
archivists, are an 1862 letter to Eddy from her second husband,
written from a Confederate jail during the Civil War, and the 1875
printer's bill for the publication of Eddy's book, ``Science and
Health.'' That volume, and the Bible, are the basic texts of the
Christian Science religion.
</P>
<P>
   The documents also include the 47-word missive with which Eddy
ordered her students in 1908 to establish the Christian Science
Monitor _ an order they honored within months and which led to the
creation of a highly respected newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials said the materials are likely to enrich
history's view of Eddy, but not dramatically alter it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are any surprises, it's just that the scope of this
material is so broad,'' said Virginia S. Harris, who as chairman of
the Christian Science board of directors is the church's top
official. The church has no clergy. ``It's not just religious. . .
. It will speak to women scholars and to (19th century) historians,
of journalism, of medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   The library, covering 75,000 square feet, is intended to become
the main tourist attraction on the Christian Science campus,
providing access to the Mapparium, a 30-foot-high, walk-in, stained
glass globe depicting the world in 1985 which had been attracting
250,000 visitors a year before being closed in 1998 to allow
building renovations to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars say that the decision to make Eddy's documents public
reflects a maturation of the denomination, its leaders now secure
enough to eliminate some of the secrecy that characterized a group
of adherents once fearful of persecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a movement that has had somewhat tense relations
with American society in general now feeling comfortable to come
forward and completely open the papers of their founder to the
public and the scholarly world,'' said Ann Braude, a women's
religious history specialist at Harvard Divinity School who has
agreed to advise the library project. ``What is most significant is
that they now feel they can let the light of day shine on their
most private documents.''
</P>
<P>
   Although best known for her advocacy of healing through faith,
Eddy was also an early advocate of what she called a
``father/mother God,'' a deity who is not necessarily male.
</P>
<P>
   In 1907, Human Life magazine called Eddy ``the most famous,
interesting, and powerful woman in America, if not in the world,
today. No woman was ever so rich, who actually earned the money
herself; no woman was ever so influential, for in her church she
has more authority than the Pope; and no other woman in history was
ever the means of erecting such beautiful and costly edifices, or
of promulgating a faith that had 80,000 faithful followers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
