<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-MEDIAONE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC APPROVES AT&AMP;T'S ACQUISITION OF MEDIAONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Updates throughout with quotes, details, background; no
pickup.) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Communications Commission approved
AT&AMP;T's acquisition of MediaOne on Monday after ordering the
companies to sell some of their assets, clearing the final obstacle
to a merger that will create the nation's largest provider of cable
television, long-distance telephone service and high-speed Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is a prime example of the consolidation that began in
the telecommunications market after it was deregulated in 1996,
which has promised to blur and redefine the nation's phone, cable
and broadcast industries.
</P>
<P>
   C. Michael Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's chairman and chief executive since
1997, has been trying to move his company away from a stagnant
business _ long-distance telephone service _ so it can take
advantage of the revolution in digital communications. He has
committed billions of dollars to offer consumers a basket of
services: television; the Internet; and local, long-distance and
wireless telephone access.
</P>
<P>
   But there are limits. The FCC gave the companies a choice of
which programming and cable subsidiaries and investments to sell to
comply with a rule that forbids a corporation from having interests
in more than 30 percent of the nation's cable and satellite
television market, or nearly 25 million subscribers. Officials
estimate that, without any divestitures, AT&AMP;T and MediaOne would
control more than 40 percent of that market, reaching more than 34
million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The decision angered some consumer groups, who had asked the
commission to force AT&AMP;T to sell the cable systems the company
co-owns with Time Warner, its next biggest rival, which is being
acquired by America Online. The groups had also asked the agency to
force AT&AMP;T to open its Internet network to competing service
providers without requiring consumers to pay additional fees.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Consumers Union said they were so troubled by the
decision that they would file a lawsuit in federal court to
overturn the commission's action and would ask Congress to adopt a
new law that would narrow the agency's authority to review mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than use its merger authority to protect the public
against an expanding monopoly, the commission has allowed AT&AMP;T to
extend the reach of its cable and broadband Internet service
monopolies and extended the time during which it can abuse
consumers and harm potential competitors,'' said Gene Kimmelman,
co-director of Consumers Union's Washington office. ``This decision
is so inconsistent with the commission's own factual depiction of
AT&AMP;T's market dominance that it defies logic.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimmelman added that the decision ``smacks of political
favoritism for one company.''
</P>
<P>
   But federal regulators said the order struck a delicate balance
by encouraging AT&AMP;T and MediaOne to continue investing billions of
dollars to upgrade the nation's cable system for high-speed
Internet access and entering local telephone markets to challenge
the regional Bell companies. At the same time, they said, the order
prevents the company from monopolizing the cable market and
creating inappropriate bottlenecks for rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T's application, as originally filed, was inconsistent with
the public interest and presented significant diversity and
competition concerns,'' said William E. Kennard, chairman of the
FCC. ``But the merger we approve today looks very different from
the application initially presented to us. This decision strikes
the appropriate balance between promoting competition in local
telephone service and protecting competition in cable and
high-speed Internet service.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said he had also relied on AT&AMP;T's nonbinding commitment
not to block rivals' access to its system, as Time Warner did
briefly during a recent contract dispute with ABC, which is owned
by Disney.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T executives were thrilled by Monday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger will mean a real choice and lower prices in local
phone service, faster Internet access and better cable TV,''
Armstrong said. ``For consumers, that's a home run in any ball
park.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger was valued at $58 billion when it was
announced a year ago during a wave of consolidation in the
telecommunications and high-speed Internet markets.
</P>
<P>
   Those deals have posed a particular challenge for antitrust
regulators because of the complex interlocking ownership interests
between cable operators, programmers and high-speed Internet
service providers. In many ways, the blurring of lines between
content providers and distributors mirrors the technical
convergence that is occurring as it is becoming more difficult to
distinguish between a telephone service, a television network and
an Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   Both AT&AMP;T and Time Warner, which will be the nation's
second-largest cable operator, have shared interests in the same
high-speed Internet and programming companies. But two weeks ago
the Justice Department's antitrust division approved the AT&AMP;T
merger after the companies agreed to sell their interest in Road
Runner, the nation's second-largest cable Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the FCC went further, ordering another round of
divestitures to comply with a law that says the agency will approve
mergers that are only found to be in the public interest.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC decided to give AT&AMP;T and MediaOne a year to choose from
three options to meet the 30 percent limit. They can sell their
interest in the Liberty Media Group and Rainbow Holdings,
programming companies that AT&AMP;T acquired interests in when it
acquired Tele-Communications Inc. last year. They can sell
MediaOne's 25 percent interest in Time Warner Entertainment, a
programming and cable operating company that serves 12.6 million
cable subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Or AT&AMP;T and MediaOne, which together have interests in 41.8
percent of the cable and satellite television markets, could shed
11.8 percent, or about 9.7 million subscribers, to lower their
share of the market to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The order gives the companies until May 19, 2001, to complete
the divestitures. The date is the one-year anniversary of a
decision by a federal appeals court here upholding the
constitutionality of the cable ownership limits. The agency also
ordered AT&AMP;T to report on what companies they intend to sell within
six months of the date of the closing of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   James Cicconi, AT&AMP;T's general counsel, said the company had not
decided what it would sell but that it had had no intention of
spinning off its interest in Liberty Media. That unit's largest
shareholder, John C. Malone, is also AT&AMP;T's largest shareholder and
a member of its board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not prepared to pick an option today,'' Cicconi said.
``We're confident we can comply.'' He said AT&AMP;T planned to close
the deal by the first week in August.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer groups and rivals said that once the deal closed,
it would solidify AT&AMP;T's position as the dominant cable player.
They said the FCC appeared to have caved in to special interests
and that the regulators should have used the deal to force the
companies to open their Internet network to competing service
providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In its approval, the FCC indicates that it will continue to
monitor AT&AMP;T's promise to provide open access in the future,'' said
Greg Simon, co-director of the Open Net Coalition, a group of
consumer organizations, Internet providers and other telephone
companies critical of AT&AMP;T's refusal to provide them with equal
access to its high-speed service. ``However, by the time the FCC
determines if AT&AMP;T has fulfilled its vague voluntary commitments on
open access, it may be too late to offer customers meaningful
choices for cable Internet services.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
