<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POST-COLD WAR SUMMIT A BIT CHILLY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (editors: Haass is cq) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As President Clinton finished his historic appearance
before the Russian Parliament Monday, Vladimir Zhirinovsky, the
ultranationalist, leaped up to scream: ``It was a waste of time.
There was no need to invite him.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the polite applause from less caustic legislators, by
the end of his three-day visit to the Russian capital, Clinton
himself may have been wondering about the wisdom of tacking the
summit with President Vladimir Putin onto his frequently amended
European itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Putin clearly did not establish the warm
relationship that grew up almost immediately between the U.S.
leader and former Russian President Boris Yeltsin _ two
larger-than-life, natural-born politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there a major breakthrough on the agenda-topping issue
of the prospective U.S. anti-missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   In the not-too-distant days of Cold War summitry, that could
have been a dire, world-shaking, market-moving disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But in the current geopolitical scheme of things, the equivocal
outcome of the first major Clinton-Putin sit-down was not even
necessarily a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong in moving slowly on the anti-missile
front, in the view of a number of U.S. and European defense
specialists, especially given the Clinton administration's strong
advocacy of the Alaska-only siting of the system. Analysts believe
alternative siting proposals, including a sea-based system, have
been given extraordinarily short shrift.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would have welcomed a more substantive outcome, but
Western analysts had cautioned against make-work deals with Putin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a moment for great accomplishments,'' said Richard
Haass, director of foreign policy studies at the Brookings
Institution in Washington. ``Rather, it's part of a continuing
dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just meeting to stay in touch,'' said John Hulsman,
senior policy analyst at the Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   It was a point the Clinton administration, facing a summit with
minimal results, had virtually conceded before leaving home. Sandy
Berger, Clinton's national security adviser, said Clinton's
entourage was seeking ``some greater degree of understanding'' with
the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton has all but banned the word ``legacy'' from the
White House, there is little doubt he has his eyes on the history
books. And he is on his way to becoming the first U.S. president
since Gerald Ford not to complete a bilateral arms-control deal
with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Haass, pointing out that Clinton is ``15/16ths'' through his
term, warned that ``this is not a time for great legacy-building''
based on last-minute deals.
</P>
<P>
   More conservative analysts, such as the Heritage Foundation's
Kim Holmes, question even the continuing emphasis on U.S.-Russian
summitry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole strategic relationship is, in some ways, a relic of
the Cold War,'' Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was having none of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find any future apart from cooperation with you in the
nuclear area inconceivable,'' Clinton, the first U.S. president to
address the Russian Parliament, told legislators Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's said his message was that it was not for the United
States to tell Russia how to run itself, but he spent much of his
45-minute address doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered the lawmakers what has become boiler-plate
advice in remarks to foreign parliaments, urging nations to work
together to solve the challenges of economic globalization, wider
democratization and environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
   For Russia, he particularized the message to call for passage of
an equitable tax code and guarantees on private property to attract
outside investment, which he said the nation needed more than aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must have a sense of responsibility for the future,''
Clinton said. ``We are not destined to be adversaries, but it is
not guaranteed that we will be allies. For us there is no fate
waiting to be revealed, only a future waiting to be created, by the
actions we take, the choices we make and the genuine views we have
of one another and of our future.''
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Clinton made a quick trip to the Kremlin to
bid farewell to Putin _ he is to see him at least three more times
this year _ and then visited Yeltsin at his home outside Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in good spirits,'' Clinton said of his long-time
interlocutor. When a reporter, referring to Yeltsin's well-known
drinking, asked ``Which spirits exactly?'' Clinton laughing
replied, ``No spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Yeltsin often met without a major agreement to sign,
and the American, earlier in his weeklong European tour, spoke out
against saving summits until a big deal was ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't only do these trips and these dialogues when we
know we've got a guaranteed outcome,'' Clinton said in Lisbon,
Portugal. ``Sometimes it's most important to be talking when
there's still unresolved differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton found Putin ``frank and open.'' In translation, at
least, the new Russian leader seemed largely devoid of the musty
obfuscations that encrusted the discourse of many leaders who grew
up in the Soviet era.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin also lacked the back-slapping bonhomie of Yeltsin, who
picked the 47-year-old ex-spy out of the Kremlin chorus line of
bureaucrats and thrust him into the nation's top job with an early
retirement last New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Any White House fixation on personal relations between the two
presidents has long been criticized by analysts. Holmes called it
``one of the mistakes'' of the Clinton years ``to personalize our
relationship with Russia through the support for the president in
power _ more or less equating that president with democracy by
saying the alternatives are worse, therefore, we have no choice but
to support him.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the traffic tie-ups as motorcades zip around central
Moscow, ordinary Russians have become blase about summitry.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction outside the Parliament building near Red Square was
muted. A couple of old-line communists waved hammer-and-sickle
flags of the Soviet Union, and there were a couple of rude signs.
One retro soul shouted: ``Yankee, go home!''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential schedulers possibly should re-examine the wisdom of
putting the most important part of a trip at the end of the
itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was clearly weary as he delivered his speech to the
Russian legislators.
</P>
<P>
   At least one Duma member was struck by Clinton's almost wistful,
nostalgic tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a farewell address to Russia,'' said Andrei
Kokoshin, a centrist parliamentarian.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
