<SLUG> BC-BESTFOODS-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: A HIGHER BID FROM UNILEVER PUTS PRESSURE ON
BESTFOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: ``Advisors'' in 7th graf is cq.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS and ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The board of Bestfoods met Monday night to discuss a
sweetened takeover offer of about $20 billion, or $72 a share, from
Unilever amid increasing pressure from shareholders to sell the
company.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bestfoods was pursuing a $15 billion purchase
of the Campbell Soup Co., the beleaguered maker of canned soups
that has been struggling to expand its business over the last
several years. One person involved in the talks said the company
would also discuss its options with Campbell at the board meeting,
which may resume Tuesday. Representatives of Campbell and of
Bestfoods refused to comment on the reports.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever increased its bid by $6 a share, to $72, Sunday night,
executives said. That offer for the maker of Skippy peanut butter,
Thomas' English muffins, Entenmann's baked goods and Knorr soups
was up from the $61 to $64 originally offered in April. At the
time, the board of Bestfoods unanimously rejected the plan, saying
the price was inadequate and that it did not think it was
``opportune to consider a sale of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Niall FitzGerald and Antony Burgmans, the co-chairmen of
Unilever, arrived in New York on Friday and have been waiting
anxiously for breakthroughs in their bid to acquire Bestfoods.
``They look very tired,'' said a person close to the talks. ``This
is gamesmanship. It's three-dimensional chess, with humans.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last month, Burgmans said his company was
surprised that the $66-a-share offer had not brought Bestfoods
executives to the negotiating table. ``What puzzles and amazes
us,'' he said, ``is that at that price, a premium of 34 percent
over what the stock was trading at, they haven't come up to talk to
us.'' The company has seemed unwilling to bid higher, without a
real competitor other than Bestfoods' reluctance.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether the latest increase will be enough to
make the board budge from its position, although several large
investors said they thought Unilever was headed in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think Bestfoods will end up selling at a price anywhere
from $72 to $75,'' said Alexi Makkas, a principal equity analyst
for State Street Global Advisors in Boston, which, with 5.7 million
shares, is the fourth-largest shareholder of Bestfoods.
``Bestfoods' management team are rational people and they
understand they are not going to be able to get this sort of value
on their own. They have been adamant the entire time about doing
the best thing for shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Unilever in New York said the company would be
making no statements Monday on its attempt to buy Bestfoods.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the talks said that Unilever, whose brands
include Dove, Lipton and Good Humor, had raised its bid for
Bestfoods from $66, first offered in April, to about $72 a share
over the weekend. The actual price had not been fixed, executives
said, because Unilever wanted to first determine whether there were
additional cost savings that might be realized through the merger.
Unilever said it anticipated $500 million in such savings, but in
talks with investors, Bestfoods has asserted that closer to $1
billion could be saved through a merger.
</P>
<P>
   The offer was made in a letter delivered to Bestfoods on Sunday
night, according to a person close to the talks. The letter was
accompanied by a draft contract intended to be a starting point for
negotiations, the person said, adding that top executives from
Unilever and Bestfoods met informally on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bestfoods' bankers have been discussing merger
possibilities with their counterparts for Campbell. Investors
seemed highly disapproving of any union with Campbell, and drove
down Bestfood's share price Monday in response to reports that the
company was considering such a move. Shares of Bestfoods closed at
$63 Monday, down $2.125.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bestfoods has been scrambling for alternatives for the last
month, but I don't see how buying Campbell's is a defense against a
$70-plus all-cash bid,'' said John R. McMillin, an analyst for
Prudential Securities. With a board considered independent, and not
dominated by company insiders, many expect Bestfoods to make a
decision that will provide the biggest payout to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Another shareholder, Barry Goggins of David L. Babson &AMP; Co.,
said a Campbell-Bestfoods union would not play well with investors.
``The Street obviously thinks Bestfoods is ready to do something
defensive,'' he said. ``But with Campbell's problems, I'm wondering
how they can compare this and make it shareholder-friendly,
relative to the Unilever offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Makkus of State Street said that a serious move in the direction
of a Campbell acquisition would be devastating for shareholders,
and for the company. ``If they go out and buy Campbell, the stock
gets crushed and management loses all credibility,'' he said.
``After that, there's no way the stock gets back up to $72.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent increased bid from Unilever does not necessarily
represent a capitulation, said one person close to the talks. ``It
could be interpreted as bidding against yourself, or it could be
interpreted as paying more for more synergies,'' the person said.
``Unilever on this occasion is more likely to walk away than to
engage in further debate on the subject.''
</P>
</TEXT>
