<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GRANDPARRENTS-CAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SEVEN YEARS, A COUPLE FACES DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With SCOTUS-GRANDPARENTS) 
 By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT VERNON, Wash. _ For seven years, through three tiers of
the court system, Gary and Jenifer Troxel have been trying to win
the legal right to have extended visits with their grandchildren.
Monday, after a divided United States Supreme Court ruled against
them, the Troxels were left with little but an emotional appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one afternoon a month is what we get, we'll be happy with
that,'' Mrs. Troxel. ``We miss them. They're still a part of our
family.''
</P>
<P>
   But a few hours a month _ which was the original offer of the
parents that set the Troxels off on a legal trek that galvanized
retirement groups on their side and parents' rights organizations
on the other _ may not even be in the offing now, the parents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a huge waste of time, money and emotion,'' said
Tommie Wynn, the mother of the two children at the center of this
case. ``I'm relieved we finally won. It's a victory for every
parent in the country. But I'm just not sure what we'll do as far
as their request for visits.''
</P>
<P>
   The case that pitted a pair of 60-year-old grandparents, one of
whom claims an asterisk in rock 'n' roll history, against the
mother who was never legally tied to the Troxel family, dates to
1993 when Brad Troxel, father of the two children, committed
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Troxel and the children's mother, then known as Tommie
Granville, were never married; Brad lived at home with his parents.
After the suicide, when the mother tried to limit the time the
grandparents could spend with their two children, the Troxels went
to court and were granted visits one weekend a month and for one
week during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Troxels have been married 35 years, and have three other
children and 10 grandchildren. Gary Troxel, a longshoreman, was a
founding member of the rock band the Fleetwoods, which recorded
hits like ``Come Softly to Me'' and ``Mr. Blue.'' In his house in
the Skagit Valley north of Seattle are two gold records for the
songs, and he still performs with the group on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary was quite well known in the music world, and these girls
have a right to know him,'' said Mrs. Troxel. The grandchildren,
both girls, are 8 and 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute was not about whether the grandparents had the right
to visit but rather boiled down to exactly how much time they could
have with their grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   When Tommie Granville married, she tried to limit the visits.
She offered them one afternoon a month, both sides said. But the
Troxels wanted overnight stays. They were backed by a Washington
state law that allows ``any person'' the right to visit when it
serves a child's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wynn said there never would have been a problem if the
Troxels had not insisted on extended visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were never denied visitation,'' she said. ``It was a
control decision. These people became like the Elian Gonzalez
relatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wynn has eight children, six of whom live at home with her
in Anacortes, just a few miles from the Troxels.
</P>
<P>
   The court, in its ruling Monday, said the Washington law
allowing third-party visits was ``breathtakingly broad.'' The
Washington State Supreme Court also ruled against the Troxels, and
it was the grandparents' appeal of the latest Washington state
ruling that led to Monday's high-court decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Troxels' lawyer, Mark D. Olson, said he was ``heartened by
the decision'' because it did not throw out laws that allow
grandparents the right to visit, but only knocked out the
foundation of the Washington statute.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said the grandparents did not have a new legal
strategy for enforcing visits. ``Frankly, the Troxels will take any
time they can get,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
