<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-IMPACT-COX     06-05 1544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-IMPACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis accepts misdemeanor, gets probation
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    and Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard paused in a hallway
to sum up why he decided to cut murder defendant Ray Lewis loose on
misdemeanor charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``A trial is about getting to the truth,'' he said. ``Sometimes
it comes in strange ways.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the understatement of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Criticized roundly by many for rushing to ``overcharge'' Lewis
and trying a case fraught with flip-flopping witnesses and scant
direct evidence, Howard had to shore up his flagging case. After
two weeks of testimony, courtroom observers had been on somewhat of
a death watch of the Lewis prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   A directed verdict _ where the judge throws out the charges
before the case reaches the jury _ would have been a huge
embarrassment to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case was going down the tubes,'' said prominent criminal
defense attorney Jerry Froelich, who has closely watched the trial.
``They should have cut this deal a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard said election-year political pressure did not cause him
to back off Lewis. ``I thought about the two dead boys'' in
deciding to cut a deal with Lewis, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Howard insists those who criticize him for indicting the case
too quickly were ``dead wrong.'' He credits the quick indictment,
and the ensuing speedy trial, with bringing the issue to a head.
And those factors ultimately may help solve the case, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Howard admitted he had been ``disappointed''
with and ``surprised'' by the changing testimony of some of the
prosecution witnesses he called to the stand.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Harvey, attorney for former co-defendant Reginald Oakley,
said Lewis, the prosecution's new star witness, has zero
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state just finished proving he's a liar; now they're
saying, `He's our liar,''' Harvey said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor charge of obstruction of
justice and will be sentenced to 12 months' probation and pay
one-third of the court costs of his prosecution. Lewis' lawyers
said that could total $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis also will be sentenced under the First Offender Act, where
his charges will be expunged if he stays out of trouble during his
probation. ``It was as if it never happened,'' said Lewis' attorney
Ed Garland.
</P>
<P>
   The obstruction charge stems from Lewis' telling his limo
passengers to keep their mouths shut and giving an ``incomplete''
statement to police, Garland said.
</P>
<P>
   The murder and aggravated
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) Please see LEWIS, B4
</P>
<P>
   assault charges against Lewis were dropped in exchange for him
testifying as to what he saw Jan. 31 when Jacinth Baker, 21, and
Richard Lollar, 24, both of Decatur, were stabbed to death. The men
died after a night of post-Super Bowl partying when they brawled
with the passengers in Lewis' rented Lincoln Navigator limousine.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is expected to say he saw his co-defendants fighting, as
well as another unidicted limo passenger, Carlos Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Thomas, Stafford's attorney, said he has heard that Lewis
has told investigators that Stafford was involved in the deadly
melee. Thomas said his client may have inadvertently kicked a
victim but was acting as a peacemaker. He denied his client hit
Baker with a champagne bottle, something Lewis has allegedly told
prosecutors. Howard said the victims' families were split in their
reaction to the deal. ``One family understood, the other had some
reservations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charita Lollar, a cousin of one of the victims, was angered by
the decision. ``In Atlanta if you have money. . . you'll walk out
of here and play football,'' she said. Howard said he took the case
to the grand jury based on statements made to him by limo driver
Duane Fassett, who failed to deliver expected key testimony two
weeks ago. Fassett backed off a statement that he saw Lewis hit a
victim and that he overheard co-defendants Oakley, 31, of Baltmore,
and Joseph Sweeting, 34, of Miami, admit to stabbing the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised by the way they testified,'' said Howard,
describing Fassett and other witnesses. ``We would have acted
differently'' in pursuing the murder indictment against Lewis, had
he knew Fassett would waver.
</P>
<P>
   Howard said he had made a pre-trial trip to Baltimore where he
sat down and looked Fassett ``eye to eye'' to gauge his
credibility. Howard said he will not continue to pursue Fassett to
force him to testify again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Lewis is not guilty of murder, then the system ultimately
worked, (although) it may not be pretty,'' said J. Tom Morgan,
district attorney of DeKalb County. ``Prosecutors all the time cut
deals with those who are the least culpable to get those most
culpable. Usually it's not in the middle of a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland said he had fielded other offers from Howard to cut a
deal, refusing them until the latest deal came.
</P>
<P>
   Before the trial, Howard offered Lewis a chance to plead guilty
to aggravated assault with a recommended sentence of three years in
prison plus seven more on probation, Garland said.
</P>
<P>
   But Garland flatly rejected that deal because Lewis was never
going to admit he played any role in the fight. ``It didn't matter
what they offered in exchange for aggravated assault,'' Garland
said. ``He was not going to admit having anything to do with
injuring people.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland said he was driving to the office Sunday morning when
Howard called saying he wanted to talk. Garland returned home to
his Buckhead mansion where he and co-counsel Don Samuel met Howard
and Assistant District Attorney Clint Rucker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredibly relaxed,'' Samuel recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was made and later that day a call was put into
Superior Court Judge Alice D. Bonner, who tentatively approved it.
Lewis then gave a videotaped statement.
</P>
<P>
   The offer of reducing two murder charges to a misdemeanor with
no time to serve was too good to pass up, even though Garland was
convinced his client would be acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is sure what a jury will do,'' Garland said. ``But with
this deal, we can't do any better.''
</P>
<P>
   While Garland praised Howard's ``courage'' for making the deal,
he also contended the whole matter could have been avoided.
</P>
<P>
   The dealings between Lewis' camp and prosecutors have been rough
from the start.
</P>
<P>
   The lines were drawn even between Garland and Atlanta police
after Lewis was arrested and jailed for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Garland had held news conferences proclaiming his client's
innocence, accusing authorities of a rush to judgment and saying
police didn't know the whole story. He said he'd called the
district attorney's office to offer information on Lewis' behalf
but couldn't get his calls returned.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on Feb. 8, Atlanta Police Sgt. Keith Meadows called
Garland, asking the lawyer to identify passengers in the limousine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I need to have some dialogue with you and someone from
the D.A.'s Office,'' Garland said, according to Meadow's account
turned over to the defense in pre-trial discovery. ``If you want
these names we all need to discuss a bond for my client or some
kind of deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Meadows said he was investigating a homicide and would not
take part in discussing deals or bonds. Garland became ``irate,''
Meadows wrote in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I guess you have your case and that's it, you're not
interested in these witnesses,'' Garland said, according to
Meadows. ``If we can't sit down and have some dialogue I'll just
bring my witnesses to court.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Lewis was indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Splits in the defense camps were evident last week, especially
when Lewis' attorneys fought successfully against the introduction
of a witness statement that called Oakley ``a fall guy'' who needed
to worry because ``Lewis has the money and resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey complained to the judge when jurors heard testimony from
a detective who said Lewis told him he was ``with the wrong
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the remaining defendants differed Monday when asked
by Superior Court Judge Alice D. Bonner if they wanted to trial to
continue right away.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey, wanted a continuance to Tuesday to assess Lewis'
statement and to ready themselves to cross examine him.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting's attorney, Steve Sadow, wanted Lewis to testify right
away. To continue the case, even for a day, ``gives the state a
little more time to get it's case together.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonner sent the jury home Monday morning without hearing any
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Sadow believed his client, Sweeting, was close to getting his
charges dropped on a directed verdict from the judge or at least
was on his way to an acquital. Harvey is expected to argue his
client was knocked semi-conscious by the bottle and dropped a knife
at the scene. Jessica Robertson, a limo passenger who has spent
much of the week with Lewis, told police she overheard Oakley say
he dropped a knife during the fight.
</P>
<P>
   A knife was found at the scene with no blood on it. Harvey will
argue that his client may have been involved in the fight but
stabbed nobody and will argue that one of the other limo passengers
did so.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
