<HEADLINE>
CHRISTOPHER REEVE TRIES THERAPY TO ENABLE BREATHING WITHOUT
VENTILATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By DORIS CHANDLER   
 The Gainesville Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ University of Florida rehabilitation experts
are consulting with paralyzed actor Christopher Reeve and his
medical team on therapy designed to help him spend less time on a
ventilator and more time breathing on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Reeve has followed a training program for six months that has
been used in the past four years to successfully wean certain
long-term ventilator patients off the machine or to decrease their
dependency on it.
</P>
<P>
   Reeve uses a small spring-loaded device that provides, in
practical terms, weight training for the breathing muscles, said
Danny Martin, associate professor of physical therapy with the
university's College of Health Professions.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Paul Davenport, professor of physiological sciences
and a specialist in respiratory physiology at the College of
Veterinary Medicine, met with Reeve in his Bedford, N.Y., home in
December to discuss the program. Since then, Martin and Davenport
have consulted regularly by telephone with Reeve and his pulmonary
medical team, which oversees the training exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not originate this idea of training patients that are
on ventilators. We modified a program that had been in use a decade
ago,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   The device is placed on the tracheotomy breathing tube in
Reeve's throat, and he has to breathe, generating sufficient
pressure to open the spring and take in air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set the pressures at appropriate levels to build up his
strength, and then couple that with increasing periods of time
where he is breathing on his own, without any ventilator support
whatsoever,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeve is progressing, albeit slowly, since beginning the
muscle-strengthening exercises, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeve was the first patient with a spinal cord injury to
participate in this training.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can generate spontaneous breath, otherwise he couldn't
train, so there obviously was a sufficient sparing of his spinal
cord,'' said Davenport. Apparently enough descending nerve fibers
were still intact after the injury to allow Reeve to breathe on his
own, Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So our goal, then, with any patient that has that kind of
sparing is to increase the power of what's there. Part of his
muscle weakness is disuse. Part of it is a loss of conductions from
the place _ the brain stem _ that produces the signal to breath and
the actual nerves that make the muscles contract,'' Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   The driving force behind breathing is the brain stem, which
sends signals through connections in the spinal cord to the nerve
cells that drive the pump that makes us breathe, Davenport said.
The body breathes in oxygen, which is metabolized and the
by-product _ carbon dioxide _ is exhaled.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take a patient off the ventilator and they are not
breathing, their carbon dioxide is going up and their oxygen level
will fall until that stimulates the brain stem to say, `We've got
work to do,' and then they will start breathing. That will kick the
system in and rev the engine up, and away the pumping goes,''
Davenport explained.
</P>
<P>
   It will be many months, possibly a year or more at Reeve's
current rate of progress to reach a level where he experiences real
functional breathing off the ventilator, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's coming slowly, and really, from the very first meeting,
we told him we didn't know how far he was going to advance or if he
was going to advance at all,'' Martin said. ``He reassesses on a
regular basis whether or not he wants to continue, so we're six
months into the process and he still feels like he's making
sufficient progress to continue. We agree with his assessment of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every patient on a ventilator is a candidate for this type
of rehabilitation therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term ventilator subjects like coma patients, patients who
have progressive diseases like Lou Gehrig's disease, or patients in
the advanced stages of multiple sclerosis and certain other
neurological diseases would not be candidates for this type of
program, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
