<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5473 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-REACT-COX     06-05 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-REACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis a hero back home in Baltimore
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the sports Webs to the radio stations, the crab houses to
the fan clubs, Baltimore welcomed Monday the imminent return of
football hero Ray Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   There was a sigh of civic relief from some, and a collective
urge to put behind this sorry southern affair which sullied more
than just a newly native son. There was also a palpable
``I-told-you-so'' current of public opinion which castigated
official Atlanta's rush to judgment when, it turns out, the
evidence against Lewis was as weak as Monday's rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy for him. I don't think he did it,'' said Ange
Jordan, who works at the Windsor Inn Crab House west of downtown
Baltimore. ``Your (officials) followed the letter of the law too
seriously. This situation seemed a little too vague for the letter
of the law. But I'm not a lawyer. I'm just a barkeep.''
</P>
<P>
   It was to a private dining room at the Windsor Inn that Lewis
and fellow Raven football players would retire Monday evenings for
Baltimore's trademark crab cakes and cold beer. But the NFL's best
linebacker isn't expected to soon return to the favored haunt. Fans
predict he'll opt instead for a quiet life beyond the media
spotlight in his Owings Mills mansion.
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't keeping staunch supporters from planning a
homecoming of sorts. Larry Young, a popular radio host and former
Maryland state legislator, hopes to hold a community prayer service
for Lewis this Saturday at the New Shiloh Baptist Church in west
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   To Young, Lewis represents more than just the latest in a long
line of Baltimore sports icons which runs from Babe Ruth through
Johnny Unitas to Cal Ripken. Lewis is black, and, Young points out,
he beat a criminal justice system too often allied against people
of color.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that a majority of whites thought Ray was
innocent, but certainly a majority of blacks in the community
did,'' said Young, whose morning radio show followed closely the
Buckhead murder trial. ``Some hope that Ray will be mindful that
(blacks) have stood with him. I proudly said to them that I don't
expect that to be a problem. ... We said he's innocent and the case
bore us out. That gives the Afro-American community bragging
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lewis' return isn't without tarnish. He pled guilty Monday
to a misdemeanor charge of obstruction of justice for lying and
misleading Atlanta police and prosecutors investigating the murders
of Jacinth Baker and Richard Lollar. Today, as part of his plea
bargain, Lewis is expected to testify against former friends and
co-defendants Reginald Oakley and Joseph Sweeting.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore will be watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of folks will be saying, `Well, he's a snitch, a
turncoat,' '' said Doug Phillips, president of the Ravens Nest Fan
Club who has proudly owned season tickets to the Ravens and former
Colts since 1975. ``But he kept his mouth shut at the beginning, I
guess, because he was scared. Now, he realizes he better do some
talking or else he could get in some real trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of fans spun ``Ray-is-vindicated'' messages on Phillips'
Web site Monday. One missive, from ``bigravensfan'' read: ``May the
guilty be punished and may we all move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Not yet. While team officials welcome Lewis' return to a
voluntary practice next week, the NFL might impose a fine and/or a
suspension on Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
