<P>
   Our report today also includes:
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) DBARWA REFUGEE CAMP, Eritrea -- June 5, 2000 --
ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-2 -- A truck of Eritrean refugees arrives at the
Dbarwa refugee camp, Monday. Thousands of the displaced are living
in tents and whatever other sheler is available. With fighting
between Ethiopia and Eritrea shifting to the port of Assab, some
refugees are leaving the camp while others continue to arrive by
the truckload. (Tyler Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) DBARWA REFUGEE CAMP, Eritrea -- June 5, 2000 --
ETHIOPIA-ERITREA -- A young Eritrean refugee at the Dbarwa camp
washes up, Monday. Thousands of the displaced are living in tents
and whatever other sheler is available. With fighting between
Ethiopia and Eritrea shifting to the port of Assab, some refugees
are leaving the camp while others continue to arrive by the
truckload. (Tyler Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BISHAN, China -- June 5, 2000 -- CHINA-FACTORY -- As
China applies for entry into the World Trade Organization,
international concern has been directed at the sometimes unpleasant
or dangerous working conditions in the country's export industries.
Workers apply pungent glue to shoes in a small factory. (Erik
Eckholm/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- June 5, 2000 -- OBIT-BASKIN -- Sculptor
Leonard Baskin, whose works depicted the suffering of the Holocaust
and the common people mourning Franklin Delano Roosevelt, has died.
He was 77. Baskin was one of several artists commissioned to create
various parts of the FDR memorial in Washington, which was
dedicated in 1997. For the memorial, Baskin, a longtime FDR
admirer, created a 30-foot-long bas relief of the president's
funeral procession with the coffin on a caisson followed by people
with heads bowed and hands reaching for each other in search of
comfort. (R. Michelson Galleries/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- June 5, 2000 -- FASHION-BRIEFS -- While many
women may have a hard time seeing pregnancy as a chance to take
hold of new fashion opportunities, the British model Stella Tennant
felt no such limitations. Tennant, a granddaughter of the Duke and
Duchess of Devonshire, has modeled for Burberry, the unstoppably
trendy label of her homeland, since 1997. Now, Tennant, seven
months pregnant, will be seen in this Burberry ad that will appear
this September. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- June 5, 2000 -- DAHL-WOLFE-FASHION -- On June
12, the Museum of the Fashion Institute of Technology will present
the first full-scale retrospective of Louise Dahl-Wolfe's work as a
fashion photographer. Out of the studio: a 1948 shot taken by
Dahl-Wolfe in the California desert. (Fashion Institute of
Technology/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- June 5, 2000 -- DAHL-WOLFE-FASHION-1 -- On
June 12, the Museum of the Fashion Institute of Technology will
present the first full-scale retrospective of Louise Dahl-Wolfe's
work as a fashion photographer. A 1950's Harper's Bazaar cover in
the saturated color that was Dahl-Wolfe's trademark. (Fashion
Institute of Technology/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LONDON -- June 5, 2000 -- LONDON-ARTSCENE -- To be in
London these days is to be endlessly entertained by art, by the
museums that show it, the multiplying galleries that sell it and
the masses who have become weirdly fascinated by it. A visitor
looks at Damien Hirst's ``Hymn'', at The Saatchi Gallery on St.
John's Woods street in London. (Saatchi Gallery/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LONDON -- June 5, 2000 -- BESTFOODS -- The board of
Bestfoods met Monday night to discuss a sweetened offer from
Unilever under increasing pressure from shareholders to sell the
company. At the same time, reports continued to swirl that
Bestfoods was pursuing a merger with the Campbell Soup Company, the
beleaguered maker of canned soups that has been struggling to grow
its business over the last several years. Niall Fitzgerald,
chairman of Unilever, at the company's headquarters in London.
(Jonathan Player/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- June 5, 2000 -- MORGAN-WOMEN -- A federal
agency has determined that Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Company
systematically disriminated against women working in one of its
divisions, opening the door for lawsuits, and possibly a class
action, against the firm. Allison K. Schieffelin, a convertible
bond trader, filed a complaint with the commission last year
claiming she had been denied a promotion because she was a woman.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) KHARKIV, Ukraine -- June 5, 2000 -- UKRAINE-ECON --
Though there are signs that the Ukrainian economy is beginning a
recovery after a decade of unceasing contraction, the Kharkiv
Initiative, as payback for what Ukraine has sacrificed at
Washington's insistence, has failed to generate a single contract
for any industry in this city. Indeed, it has taken two years for
the State Department to open an office here, which is now staffed
by a single contract employee. Anatoly Myalitsa general director of
Kharkiv's aircraft plant. (Patrick Tyler/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) GREENFIELD, Mass. -- June 5, 2000 -- -AUTHOR-GRENOBLE-BOS
-- Move over J. K. Rowling, author of the best-selling Harry Potter
series. Out in the bucolic hinterland of Western Massachusetts,
right down the road from Butynsky's Farm Stand, lives a
freckle-faced sixth-grader who is so adept at putting the fruits of
a gifted imagination into words that she recently won a national
writing contest for young authors. Nicole Grenoble at home during a
recent interview. (Suzanne Kreiter/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BOSTON, Mass. -- June 5, 2000 -- BORING-COMMENCEMENTS-BOS
-- Commencement speeches have long been the realm of inspiration,
including exhortations for graduates to fulfill their potential,
advice on the dos and dont's of adulthood, and other wisdom to chew
on as students depart the shelter of ivory towers. But not every
student is graced by such rousing rhetoric. Graduates at the
University of Massachusetts-Boston seem unimpressed by the
commencement speech. (John Tlumacki/The Boston Globe) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ATLANTA -- June 5, 2000 -- FBN-LEWIS-TRIAL-2 -- NFL star
Ray Lewis pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor on Monday under an
agreement that drops murder charges in the stabbing deaths of two
men outside a Super Bowl party. Lewis and two friends, Joseph
Sweeting and Reginald Oakley, were charged with murder, felony
murder and aggravated assault in the stabbings of Richard Lollar
and Jacinth Baker. Oakley, right, looks towards Ray Lewis (not
shown), as Lewis plead to lesser charges in court Monday. Oakley's
attorney, Bruce Harvey, is at left. (Kimberly Smith/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ATLANTA -- June 5, 2000 -- FBN-LEWIS-TRIAL -- NFL star
Ray Lewis pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor on Monday under an
agreement that drops murder charges in the stabbing deaths of two
men outside a Super Bowl party. Lewis, center, flanked by his
defense attorneys, Ed Garland, left, and Don Samuel, right, look
over at a probation officer in court, Monday. (Kimberly Smith/The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) GREENFIELD, Mass. -- June 5, 2000 --
MONEY-INVESTING-DOGS-BOS -- While surfing Web investing sites a
couple of years ago, Stephen Lepley came across some investing
strategies promising to beat the Dow Jones industrial average, with
the offbeat names Dogs of the Dow and the Foolish Four. Lepley and
his wife Karen check their investments while at home. (The Bill
Greene/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) KINGMAN, Ariz. -- June 5, 2000 -- SCI-GRAND-CANYON -- The
mysteries of Grand Canyon's formation continue to amaze geologists.
This week more than 80 of them will gather in Grand Canyon Village
to compare notes and work toward a unified theory of how and when
the canyon formed. This is the largest area of the Grand Canyon,
the Parashant National Monument, which covers a million acres and
is filled with vegetation, minerals, and Paleozoic rock. (Bureau of
Land Management/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BALTIMORE -- June 5, 2000 -- SCI-SAILING-YOUTH -- The
sport of sailing is now being used to help youths facing abuse,
violence, and crime. Organizations like the Living Classroom
Foundation in Baltimore are using sailing to help teach
responsibility and control to troubled teen-agers. (Marty Katz/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 5, 2000 -- SCI-ORBACH-DIANA -- Dr. Susie
Orbach, the therapist who treated Diana, Princess of Wales, for her
eating disorders, is the founder of the Women's Therapy Center of
London. In her latest book, ``The Impossibility of Sex: Stories of
the Intimate Relationship Between Therapist and Patient,'' Orbach
says that psychotherapists must develop responses that fit the
various emotional invitations they receive from their patients.
(Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
