<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5476 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      06-05 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FCC Approves Purchase of Cable Giant by AT&AMP;T
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission approved AT&AMP;T's
acquisition of MediaOne after ordering the companies to sell some
of their assets, clearing the final obstacle to a merger that will
create the nation's largest provider of cable television,
long-distance telephone service and high-speed Internet access. The
FCC gave the companies a choice of which programming and cable
subsidiaries and investments to sell to comply with a rule that
forbids a corporation from having interests in more than 30 percent
of the nation's cable and satellite television market. Officials
estimate that, without any divestitures, AT&AMP;T and MediaOne would
control more than 40 percent of that market.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson to Purchase Primark
</P>
<P>
   Thomson, which is selling most of its newspapers to focus on the
electronic distribution of legal and financial information, agreed
to buy Primark for $842 million. Thomson will pay $38 a share for
Primark, a 31 percent premium to Primark's stock price of $29 on
Friday. Shares of Primark, based in Waltham, Mass., rose $8.25, to
$37.25, while Thomson fell 1.80 Canadian dollars, to 49.20.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch in Talks to Buy Market Maker
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch is in discussions to buy Herzog Heine Geduld for
nearly $1 billion, according to people close to the companies. The
deal, which could be announced as soon as today, would give Merrill
a much larger role in trading on the Nasdaq stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Mixed in Lackluster Session
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices were mixed as investors paused after last week's
big advance. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 20.54 points, to
10,815.30, but the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 9.63
points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,467.63. The Nasdaq composite index,
which rose a record 19 percent last week, rallied during the last
hour of trading and closed at 3,821.76, up 8.38 points, or 0.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   SEC Tackles Variable Annuities
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a federal examination of the sale of variable
annuities, a fast-growing and controversial combination of mutual
funds and insurance, a senior Securities and Exchange Commission
official issued a stern warning that misleading tactics and
incomplete disclosure would not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   Start-Up Seeks Copyright Ruling
</P>
<P>
   In a case experts say may have broad implications for whether
automated Internet search engines can be held liable for linking to
pirated material, an Internet start-up, MP3Board.com, has asked a
federal judge to find that it is not abetting copyright
infringement simply by linking to MP3 music files.
</P>
<P>
   IMF Chief Advises Indonesia
</P>
<P>
   The new managing director of the International Monetary Fund
said that closing off Indonesian capital markets would hinder the
nation's fragile economic recovery. The IMF's chief, Horst Koehler
emerged from a breakfast meeting with President Abdurrahman Wahid
and briskly dispelled speculation that the IMF would agree to an
Indonesian effort to defend its faltering currency, the rupiah, by
placing controls on the currency.
</P>
<P>
   Health and Safety Concerns in China
</P>
<P>
   As China applies to join the World Trade Organization,
international concern has been directed at the sometimes unpleasant
or dangerous working conditions in the country's export industries,
especially those owned by foreign companies. But health and safety
conditions are generally far worse, Chinese and foreign experts
say, in the many smaller factories and mines that have sprung up
during the economic reforms of the last two decades, mainly
producing goods for the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi Quietly Introduces Juice Drink
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi-Cola, which is known for big-league marketing tactics, is
introducing FruitWorks, a line of juice-based noncarbonated drinks
that will compete with Snapple and Fruitopia, with comparatively _
but deliberately _ little fanfare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
