<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ENVISIONS A GOVERNMENT WITH ALL ITS SERVICES ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ In a populist spirit, Vice President Al Gore on
Monday proposed putting nearly all federal services online so that
citizens do not have to wait in line or at their mail boxes to do
things such as receive their Social Security benefits, apply for a
federal home loan or report a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous activities are now possible online, such as applying
for student loans and paying taxes. Gore would expand those
services, so that, for example, the six million companies that now
file quarterly Social Security payments through the United States
mail on behalf of their workers could do so online.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the plan could go into effect by 2003. It would cost
$100 million, but Gore aides said it would more than pay for itself
with savings in paperwork. And as part of his plan to bring the
government up to Internet speed, Gore proposed giving everyone an
encrypted ``digital certificate'' to gain access to their own
information and ensure their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The virtual town square that Gore envisions would also allow the
government to make its vast purchases on the Internet and to
auction off surplus equipment, using a site called ``g-bay,'' a
play on the concept of ``eBay'' that drew chuckles from his
audience of about 100 people at North Carolina State University's
Centennial Campus, part of the 7,000-acre Research Triangle Park.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal fit with the campaign's recent strategy, in which
Gore is putting forth positive ideas and avoiding the negative
attacks against his rival, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, that have
marked much of his post-primary period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concentrating on my own vision of America's future and
what we can do together,'' he told reporters after his speech as he
flew on his airplane to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at the Supper Club in midtown Manhattan, Gore joined a
bevy of Democrats to celebrate the 70th birthday of Rep. Charles
Rangel of Harlem. The evening raised $2.6 million for the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The money came from two events _ a reception with 70 people, who
paid up to $1,000 apiece, at the Supper Club, and a dinner with 250
people who paid $5,000 apiece at the union headquarters of the
Service Employees International Union.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 200 people applauded Gore, Hillary Rodham Clinton,
the Democratic Senate candidate; Rep. Dick Gephardt, minority
leader; Rep. Patrick Kennedy, chairman of the House Democratic
re-election campaign; and Dennis Rivera, president of the local
service employees union, one of the most powerful in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton paid homage to Rangel, who has been stumping across the
country for House Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to the days when her Senate candidacy seemed an
improbable rumor, Clinton noted: ``Maybe earlier than many, I began
to just do whatever Charlie told me to.'' She added: ``And so when
people said, ``Well, you know, gee, are you going to run for the
Senate in New York?' I said, well, Charlie told me I should, so
here I am, and I'm very happy I am because I'm having the time of
my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
