<SLUG> BC-SOFT-MONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN SOFT MONEY ENRICHING DEMOCRATS, REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats and Republicans have almost doubled their
soft-money totals raised four years ago, and House and Senate
candidates set records in the 15 months that ended March 31, the
Federal Election Commission reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee and the party's Senate and
House campaign committees raised $86.4 million in soft money _ the
large, unregulated donations from corporations, unions and wealthy
individuals _ compared with $44.7 million in the 1995-96 period.
For their Democratic counterparts, the total was $77 million
compared with $39.7 million in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
   For both parties, the sharpest increases came for their
congressional fund-raising committees. While the Republican
National Committee's total of $41.2 million in soft money was up 38
percent, the National Republican Senatorial Committee's $17.6
million was up 101 percent, and the National Republican
Congressional Committee's $27.5 million was a 183 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   But no Republican Committee approached the growth rate of the
Democratic Senate and House committees, which are aggressively
raising unrestricted donations in a drive to regain control of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Senate Campaign Committee raised $16.5 million in
soft money, up 1,037 percent since 1995-96. The Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee's take rose only half as fast, up
540 percent to $21.9 million. In contrast, the $39.9 million raised
by the Democratic National Committee was only a 14 percent increase
in four years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, rising soft-money contributions to the political
parties sparked controversy. The Democratic National Committee
returned millions of dollars in suspect soft money that came from
overseas donors or from individuals who may not have contributed
their own money. Both parties used soft money for issue advertising
to promote their presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money is already an issue for elections this year:
Democrats have blasted Republicans for contributions from tobacco
companies and the National Rifle Association, while Republicans
have criticized Democrats for donations from trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In ``hard money'' donations to party organizations, which are
limited to $20,000 in a calendar year from individuals and $15,000
from political action committees, there were only modest changes
from 1995-96. The three Democratic committees raised $104 million,
up 1 percent. The Republicans raised $179.3 million, down 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties were also about even in hard cash on hand, an
important detail because soft money cannot be used by itself but
must be combined with varying fractions of of hard money in
different states to buy television advertisements, its main use
these days. Republicans had $32.2 million on hand, Democrats had
$31.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came to individual candidates in House races,
especially races where no incumbent is running and seats are most
likely to change parties, Republicans held an important advantage.
In open seats, their candidates had raised an average of $165,775.
Democrats in those seats had raised an average of $75,820.
</P>
<P>
   Of the top 30 fund-raisers among Senate candidates, 19 were
Republicans. The overall leader was Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New
York City, a Republican who withdrew from the race last month. He
reported raising $19.3 million, compared with $12.8 million for
Hillary Rodham Clinton, the New York Democratic nominee. She was
second. U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio, the Long Island Republican who became
his party's nominee after Giuliani dropped out, but who was still a
House candidate on March 31, was sixth among House candidates, with
$2.1 million raised, but first in cash on hand, with $3.5 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
