<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5494 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-ROCKER-MAIN-COX     06-05 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RBy Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Braves made John Rocker go away Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't very happy,'' general manager John Schuerholz said,
``but nobody who's sent down ever is.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely not the combustible Atlanta closer, who closed out a
tumultuous two weeks by being optioned to the club's Class AAA
affiliate in Richmond. In another determination the team maintains
is not related, the Braves also fined Rocker $5,000 for his his
threatening exchange with Sports Illustrated writer Jeff Pearlman
at Turner Field Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's going to say this is related to the incident that
happened in the tunnel,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``It's absolutely
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker has 72 hours to report to the Richmond Braves, or face a
fine. In a midafternoon meeting in a conference room off the Braves
clubhouse, he did not imply he would not report but first wanted to
consult with his agents, the Houston-based team of Randal and Alan
Hendricks.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker left the stadium without speaking with reporters. Before
he departed, he did make an obscene comment to an Atlanta
Journal-Constitution photographer who attempted to snap his picture
in the same tunnel where the pitcher encountered Pearlman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a pact he would calm down and not get in any
trouble,'' right fielder Brian Jordan said of the fine. ``And he
made another boo-boo, another mistake. He forced their hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Under baseball rules, Rocker must remain in Richmond for at
least 10 days and will be paid under the terms of his $290,000
contract and not a minor-league salary. The timing makes him
available to return to the team in time for the much-anticipated
four-game series with the New York Mets June 29-July 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys are measuring it by the trip to New York. We're
not,'' Schuerholz said. ``When he's ready to pitch for us and able
to pitch for us, he'll be here, whenever that is, whenever we think
he's ready to help. We didn't even think about New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball began an investigation into the Pearlman
incident, with executive director of security Kevin Hallinan
interviewing witnesses to the Sunday morning tirade. Sports
Illustrated spokesman Joe Assad said the magazine would not pursue
any possible charges for the episode.
</P>
<P>
   In a released statement, commissioner Bud Selig said, ``I am
saddened by the regrettable incident that took place.... Major
League Baseball is monitoring the situation closely and I have been
in contact with Braves president Stan Kasten throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Major League Baseball is conducting its own
investigation, I am satisfied that the Braves have moved
expeditiously and have treated the matter with the seriousness it
deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig attempted to fine Rocker $20,000 and suspend him for a
month for his racially charged statements in a December Sports
Illustrated article. An arbitrator later reduced the sanctions to
two weeks and $500.
</P>
<P>
   WAGA Channel 5 sportscaster Jeff Hullinger said he had not be
interviewed by MLB officials, though he says Rocker twice engaged
him in heated exchanges. The second incident some three weeks ago,
Hullinger alleged Rocker threatened his life and said sports
psychologist Jack Llewelyn had to separate them.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker had become the least reliable pitcher in the bullpen,
allowing 12 of the last 18 hitters he faced to reach base. He has
issued 25 walks in 18 1/3 innings and loaded the bases in three of
his last four appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks he's pitching good,'' Cox said. ``My opinion was,
he's not pitching good, not the way he can pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker will be working with Richmond pitching coach Mike
Alvarez, who recently replaced legendary coach Bill Fischer after
he was hired in April by the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we had been thinking about since our last road
trip in Houston,'' said Cox. ``At that time, Greg McMichael came up
with a sore (shoulder) and we couldn't do it. We thought maybe this
could be a repreve for him and he can get it going again. But he
hasn't got it going again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play so many tough games with this ball club and they're
always close. When you bring in a guy in the seventh, eighth or
ninth inning, you got to have strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Rocker left them no indication he would not report to
Richmond, the Braves fully expect him not only to report by return
to Atlanta soon, even if he left the clubhouse glumly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn to ignore what guys say when they're optioned,''
assistant general manager Frank Wren said
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
