u a BC-NY-FLOWER-DOG-NYT &LR;      06-05 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FLOWER-DOG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WALKING, JUST WATERING FOR THIS PUPPY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Switzerland, Germany, Spain)   By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last year, the art world was abuzz about elephant
dung and a shark in formaldehyde at the Brooklyn Museum of Art.
This year, animals are once again capturing artistic attention: a
parade of artist-designed cows are posing throughout the city this
month, and Monday, the artist Jeff Koons unveiled a 43-foot puppy
sculpture carpeted with living flowers in Rockefeller Center.
</P>
<P>
   Like the cows, which were a hit in Zurich and Chicago, Koons'
West Highland white terrier is a tried and true crowd pleaser.
Koons first exhibited the sculpture, called ``Puppy,'' during an
international art show in 1992 in Germany. The artist had not been
invited to participate in the exhibition, ``Documenta IX,'' but
``Puppy'' nonetheless stole the show, and was shown again in Sydney
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Puppy' is one of the most significant sculptures of the 20th
century,'' Susan Freedman, the president of the Public Art Fund,
told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   But however bland and friendly its demeanor, ``Puppy'' may not
have been, strictly speaking, a safer choice than a shark or
elephant dung. In 1997 in Spain, where a second version of the
sculpture stands guard outside the Guggenheim Bilbao, two
terrorists were caught trying to plant bombs inside the artwork,
and a police officer died in the ensuing gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Monday marked the first time ``Puppy'' has been seen in the
United States. It will be on view in Rockefeller Plaza, where the
Christmas tree stands during the holiday season, until Labor Day.
Rockefeller Center paid for the display but refused to disclose the
cost, saying it was a gift to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Koons is famous for borrowing American kitsch and transforming
it into art. In the '80s, his porcelain portrait of Michael Jackson
with his pet chimp, Bubbles, was priced at $250,000. More recently,
a 1988 sculpture brought $1.8 million at an auction at Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven stainless-steel sections, each holding 12 inches of dirt,
fit together to form the armature of the verdant canine. An
internal irrigation system nourishes a varicolored carpet of 60,000
flowering plants, including marigolds, begonias, impatiens,
lobelias and 50 kinds of petunias from nurseries on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's controlled random,'' Koons said of the pattern created by
the flowers, which will be allowed to grow out naturally. ``It's
such a pleasant experience to give up control, to let nature take
its course.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5509 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AFRICA-PIPELINE-ART-N     06-05 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-PIPELINE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$3.5 BILLION AFRICA PIPELINE EXPECTED TO BE APPROVED BY WORLD BANK
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With U.S. support, the World Bank is expected to
approve on Tuesday a $3.5 billion project to develop an oil
pipeline in Chad and Cameroon in West Africa, despite widespread
concerns about the potential for corruption and environmental
damage.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration will vote in favor of World Bank
sponsorship after specifying an unusually detailed list of
safeguards that officials hope will earmark the oil revenues for
development projects and ward off abuse, a senior U.S. official
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the project does not have united European support, the
United States, as the major shareholder in World Bank, is confident
that there will be enough votes for a loan to pass, the official
said. Exxon Mobil is the lead company that is seeking the loan. The
World Bank is generally expected to contribute $90 million to $200
million.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed 663-mile pipeline, which would link oil fields in
landlocked Chad to the Atlantic Coast of Cameroon, has stirred an
outcry among environmentalists and anti-poverty crusaders. They say
the project will provide a boon to corrupt African officials,
dislocate indigenous peoples and harm ecologically sensitive areas.
</P>
<P>
   The senior U.S. official said critics had ``very legitimate
concerns.'' But after more than two years working with the oil
companies, he said, officials and independent figures in both
countries, planners have come ``a very long way'' in addressing
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a project with substantial development potential,''
the official said. ``I'm confident that it will be approved.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups contend that the companies have failed to
set aside adequate money to clean up an oil spill, allocating less
than $1 million, despite Dutch researchers' citing a need for $28
million.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline, the critics add, will threaten the livelihoods of
hundreds of Bagueli people, or pygmies, and endanger the habitats
of endangered black rhinos, gorillas and chimpanzees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you lay a pipeline, you're basically building a road
for loggers and poachers,'' said Alejandro Queral, associate
Washington representative of the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics say the World Bank will effectively be lining the
pockets of a corrupt government in Chad that the State Department
says brutally persecutes its enemies. Nearly every region of Chad,
a nation 2 1/2 times the size of France, has erupted in
ethnically-based unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Providing oil revenues to the central government is ``like
adding more fuel to the fire,'' asserted Korrina Horta, a senior
economist at Environmental Defense in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very dangerous situation,'' Horta added.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil has insisted on World Bank participation as a hedge
against instability, Horta said. She referred to the bank's role,
which represents less than 10 percent of the project, as
``political risk insurance'' for investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make the World Bank a shareholder in the project, and no
government is ever going to nationalize it,'' Horta said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the support clears the way for Exxon Mobil, Chevron
and Petronas to seek additional financing before investing $3
billion of their own, she said, adding, ``It's the Good
Housekeeping Seal of Approval.''
</P>
<P>
   In tandem with its support for the loan, the administration has
insisted on a framework to be monitored by the World Bank that
would reduce the risk of corruption or mismanagement. That
structure would include an escrow account for oil revenues that
would set aside most of the income for health, education and
development and allow for monitoring by nongovernmental groups in
Chad.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-backed strictures also require that money be set aside
to create national parks, compensate displaced people and respond
to oil spills.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline would be one of the largest that involves direct
foreign investment in Africa in decades, officials said. Experts
expect it to generate $80 million to $100 million a year for Chad
and $20 million in transfer fees for Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials acknowledged that the project would be something
of a test for the World Bank. Last week, the bank released a report
in which it faulted itself and the International Monetary Fund for
making Africa poorer through failed lending policies over 40 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
