<HEADLINE>
SHARE PRICES MIXED AS INVESTORS PAUSE FOR RECENT GAINS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (CORRECTS fractions of stock prices in 19th, 22nd grafs)  
(Eds.: ``Advisors'' in last graf is cq) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices were mixed Monday, as investors paused
to consider the landscape after last week's big advance.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said they were encouraged by the price action. Monday's
activity stood in stark contrast to the eruptions seen for much of
the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in April and May you would get a 150-point to 200-point
rally and give it all back the next day,'' said Ned Collins, head
trader at Daiwa Securities America.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I am concerned,'' he added, ``it is good that we are
treading water. We had such a big move last week that we need to
consolidate some.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by Hewlett-Packard, the Dow Jones industrial average rose
20.54 points, or 0.2 percent, to 10,815.30. But the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index fell 9.63 points, or 0.7 percent, to
1,467.63, attributed in part to declines in General Electric, Cisco
Systems and Wells Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which rose a record 19 percent last
week, rallied during the last hour of trading Monday and closed at
3,821.76, up 8.38 points, or 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And the Russell 2000 index of small company stocks also managed
to eke out a small gain, rising 0.27 points to 513.30.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks jumped last week on reports that showed the economy might
be losing some of its momentum, an indication that efforts by the
Federal Reserve Board to achieve that end might be working.
</P>
<P>
   Since last June, the Fed has raised short-term interest rates
six times to cool the economy and dampen inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   However, the only report of any note this week is the Producer
Price Index for May on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, analysts said stock prices were expected to
remain in a trading range for this week, and possibly a good deal
longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``To stay in a trading range is probably the best thing that can
happen to the market,'' said Kenneth M. Sheinberg, head of listed
trading at SG Cowen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives the people the chance to get into stocks they want to
get into, and to sell others at levels they want,'' he said.
``There is no need to panic one way or the other. That is probably
helpful, because the market needs to be a little calmer.''
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume was light, but not abnormally so for a Monday in
what Wall Street considers the summer season.
</P>
<P>
   Some 838 million shares changed hands on the New York Stock
Exchange. Volume on the Nasdaq stock market was 1.4 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard was the Dow's biggest gainer, rising 9], to 120
5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and IBM also helped to move the Dow higher.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft rose 9/16, to 66~, after it said it would spend $2
billion to speed adoption of its new Internet-based software.
</P>
<P>
   IBM rose four, to 112 7/16 after a Merrill Lynch analyst
expressed optimism about its prospects for the second half of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   But Intel slumped 1|, to 132 9/16, as investors took some
profits following last week's big advance. Intel's shares gained 14
percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bank stocks, which have rallied strongly in recent weeks on
hopes that an end to interest rate increases by the Fed is near,
retreated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo, a S&AMP;P 500 component, lost 2 3/8, to 45[. Bank of
America slid 1}, to 59\. Chase Manhattan lost 1 3/16, to 79]. And
Bank of New York shed 1}, to 46~.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology stocks, which posted very good gains last week,
continued to advance.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech was the biggest winner, rising 19~, to 129, after the
drugmaker won approval from the Food and Drug Administration for
TNKase, a next-generation version of Activase, a clot-busting drug
for heart-attack patients.
</P>
<P>
   Human Genome Sciences rose 7 9/16, to 113{. And PE Corp Celera
jumped 22{, to 91.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was expecting some retrenchment in the biotech sector, and
it didn't happen,'' said Mike Weiner, a managing director at
BancOne Investment Advisors in Columbus, Ohio. ``The follow-through
in those stocks surprised me, and it probably masked some weakness
in the Nasdaq.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
