<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INDONESIA-ECON-1STLD-     06-05 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ECON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA AND IMF REJECT MEASURES TO PROP UP CURRENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs to correct spelling for IMF's Koehler throughout) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ In a move that seems likely to snuff out
Indonesia's latest flirtation with currency controls, the new
managing director of the International Monetary Fund declared on
Monday that closing off Indonesia's capital markets would hinder
the nation's fragile economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF's chief, Horst Koehler, emerged from a breakfast meeting
with President Abdurrahman Wahid and briskly dispelled speculation
that the IMF would agree to an Indonesian effort to defend its
faltering currency, the rupiah, by placing controls on the
currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and I fully agreed that the introduction of
capital controls would be counterproductive,'' said Koehler, who
was making his first visit to Jakarta as IMF director. ``He feels
that it would be the wrong decision, and I agree, because such a
decision would deter foreign investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, a senior economic adviser to Wahid, Sofyan
Wanandi, said: ``It's over. It's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Indonesian officials said they were considering some
type of controls to stabilize the rupiah, which has dropped 18
percent in value since the beginning of the year because of fears
of renewed political unrest. Indonesia considered setting a fixed
rate for the rupiah in early 1998, after a far more serious slide,
but backed off under intense pressure from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Although the economy has crept back from the abyss of 1998, it
still depends on billions of dollars in loans from the fund to bail
out debt-ridden banks and corporations. Last week, the IMF approved
a $372 million loan that had been delayed because officials at the
fund were unhappy with the fitful pace of economic restructuring
under Wahid.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler made it clear Monday that Indonesia's future lay in
strictly adhering to the IMF's program. He urged the Indonesian
Bank Restructuring Authority to accelerate the sale of assets of
insolvent banks and companies. Failure to do so, he said, ``would
lead to a deterioration in the asset values.''
</P>
<P>
   Koehler's predecessor, Michel Camdessus, aroused resentment in
1998 when he stood watching with arms folded, as Indonesia's
longtime president, Suharto, reluctantly signed a loan agreement
with the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Though Koehler did not mince words Monday, he took pains not to
sound imperious. ``We are here to help and support, not to lecture
and impose,'' he said. ``But of course we offer frank advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's markets responded quickly to Koehler. The rupiah,
which had been rallying in recent days on speculation that it might
be stabilized, slipped to a rate of 8,460 to the United States
dollar from 8,400. But the stock market welcomed the news, jumping
2.14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Capital controls have gained some credibility in Asia in the
last two years, since Malaysia imposed controls on its currency and
embarked on a powerful recovery. Analysts here said that officials
were focusing less on a fixed exchange rate than on measures to
keep rupiah in the country, like requiring exporters to repatriate
and convert their foreign-exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But Indonesia is not Malaysia, which has disciplined officials
to police the flow of currencies in and out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't work here,'' said Umar Juoro, a former adviser to
Wahid's immediate predecessor, B.J. Habibie. ``We don't have the
capacity to do it. All it would do is to discourage foreign capital
from coming back to Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   The decline in the rupiah has rattled officials because they
remember that Suharto was ultimately swept out of power by violent
unrest ignited by a weak currency. But some analysts said the
impact of a weaker rupiah would not be as great this time because
it hurts companies with debt denominated in dollars. And most of
those companies are already bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the weak rupiah has bolstered Indonesian exports, which
jumped 29 percent in April compared with April 1999. For Indonesia
to achieve Wahid's personal goal of 5 percent-plus economic growth
this year, it will need continued strength in exports.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest drawback of controls may be political, according to
James W. Castle, an American consultant. Since Indonesia fell into
crisis, the rupiah has been a reliable barometer of public
confidence in the government. The recent decline was precipitated
by Wahid's decision to dismiss two of his most respected cabinet
ministers and replace them with people regarded as cronies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lesson to the government that there is a price to
pay,'' Castle said. ``The danger is that it would lose that
feedback mechanism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
