<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CT-PARISH-EGAN-2TAKES     06-05 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-PARISH-EGAN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATING A BISHOP'S MOVE: FISCALLY WISE OR COLD AND BIASED? 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ In his dozen years as head of the diocese of
Bridgeport, Bishop Edward Egan has had his leadership tested
repeatedly by a long-running, uncommonly public dispute with the
parish of Our Lady of Montserrat, a fast-growing congregation of
Hispanic immigrants here that in many ways represents the future of
Roman Catholic America.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy has centered on the simple fact that Our Lady of
Montserrat, despite vibrant growth, has never had its own suitably
sized building. Parishioners yearned to build a new church. Egan
decided that the parish could not afford it. In 1997, relations
with the bishop became so bitter that the church's pastor, the Rev.
Bernardo Rodriguez, resigned in protest.
</P>
<P>
   This month, both Our Lady of Montserrat and Egan move on. Last
Friday, under the bishop's order, the parish will leave its cramped
building to merge with the parish of St. Benedict, half a mile
south in the Cove section. Ten days later, Egan will be installed
as the new archbishop of New York.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepares to take the most visible Catholic pulpit in the
nation, both Egan's most devoted supporters and his harshest
critics have pointed to his handling of the Our Lady of Montserrat
situation as an indication of how he will take control of an
unwieldy archdiocese with 10 counties, 2.4 million worshipers and
complex financial concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, diocesan officials close to Egan have
characterized the merger of the two churches as the latest example
of his deep commitment to meeting the needs of immigrants, which
they saw fit to emphasize as he moved to New York, where there are
nearly 900,000 Hispanic Catholics, more than double the number of
all parishioners in the diocese of Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   It could also be seen, they said, as evidence of his management
skill in consolidating to cut costs and of a willingness to make
tough decisions in the face of public outcry. These qualities, they
said, would be essential in New York, where many financially
struggling schools and parishes need to be consolidated or closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a public dispute with respect to the bishop's
leadership regarding Our Lady of Montserrat,'' said Tom Drohan, a
spokesman for the Bridgeport diocese. ``As the leader of the
diocese, he has responsibility for the health of each parish, the
spiritual health and the financial health.''
</P>
<P>
   But some parishioners at Montserrat view the merger as the
latest blunder in a long dispute in which Egan and his predecessor,
Bishop Walter Curtis, failed to help the parish build its own
permanent house of worship. It is evidence, they say, of an
autocratic, unyielding style less concerned with people than with
finances.
</P>
<P>
   Some parishioners say they not only feel betrayed by Egan, but
are doubly stung by the lavish praise heaped upon him after his
appointment to succeed Cardinal John J. O'Connor. Some described
Egan as not just unconcerned with immigrants, but as anti-Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the impression that the people here have of him,'' said
the Rev. Leonard Paskus, who has been the administrator of
Montserrat for a year and a half. Paskus said he disagreed with the
negative view of Egan, but he invited parishioners to vent their
anger at a meeting shortly after the merger with St. Benedict was
announced in March. About 60 people attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's injustice,'' said Maurizio Ahumada at the
meeting. ``It's discrimination. He has been described as a
brilliant fund-raiser, but he never did anything to help this
parish.'
</P>
<P>
   Ahumada recalled a meeting with Egan in September 1997. It
began, he said, not with a prayer or a call for healing, but with a
warning. ``You will not bend me,'' Ahumada recalled the bishop's
saying. ``I have been in this business for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Aniceto Villamide, the vicar for Hispanic ministry,
dismissed the criticism, saying Hispanics had flourished under
Egan. The bishop learned Spanish when he arrived in Bridgeport, and
frequently worshiped in Spanish, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bishop Egan was very supportive of Hispanics,'' Villamide
said. ``The numbers speak for themselves. When he came here 11
years ago, there were only three Spanish-speaking priests from
Hispanic countries. Right now, when he leaves, there are 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Egan, Villamide said, the diocese began a weekly radio
program in Spanish and added a page in Spanish to the diocesan
newspaper. ``He was the one to take the initiative to create
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this has swayed the Montserrat parishioners. It may
be telling that when he went to the church to announce the merger,
Egan was accompanied not by Villamide but by Michael Dolan, the
diocese's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the bitterness stems from the thwarted efforts of
parishioners to undertake a renovation and expansion of
Montserrat's building on Hope Street. An architect's rendering
showed a white Spanish Colonial building with a red-tiled roof,
arched windows and a bell tower.
</P>
<P>
   The parish, which has more than 1,500 members, raised $500,000
by summer 1997 to meet goals set by Egan. Current and former
parishioners said they kept their end of the deal. All they needed,
they said, was the bishop's help to get a loan for the balance.
</P>
<P>
   But, Drohan said, the church never met a diocesan requirement
that any parish wishing to undertake a building project must have
enough money to cover at least half of the cost. By the time the
parish raised $500,000, the projected expansion cost had increased
from $1 million to more than $1.5 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   So in July 1997, Egan decided against giving the parish its
loan. Angry parishioners held a rally with signs questioning the
bishop's faith. Father Rodriguez, their beloved pastor, quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some feel if we were an Anglo community,'' Paskus said, ``we
would have been given permission to build.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Villamide said Egan's decisions reflected a trend among Catholic
leaders to prefer territorial parishes that served parishioners
within a geographic area to parishes intended for an ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   He said Egan was tending to a growing community of Haitian
Catholics in Stamford, which would get the building occupied by
Montserrat as a community center. Several parishioners there said
they suspected that the diocese planned to sell the property, a
valuable parcel surrounded by condominium buildings. Drohan denied
any intention to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriela Rivera was among those shocked by the merger. ``After
an hour and a half with the bishop, you are wondering what are you
here for,'' she said. ``You are here just to listen and obey.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than 15 years, the parishioners of Montserrat have been
Catholic nomads, going from one building to another. By 1984, their
original home, a small wood-frame building in downtown Stamford,
could no longer hold them. Curtis proposed a merger with St.
Benedict.
</P>
<P>
   That merger was abandoned after protests from hundreds of
parishioners at St. Benedict and pleas from Montserrat worshipers
who hoped to build their own church.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Montserrat bought a building on Hope Street, knowing it
would not be big enough for its growing needs. That December, Egan,
who had been vicar of education in New York, was installed as head
of the Bridgeport diocese.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived to find a diocese deeply in debt. Many of its urban
churches and schools, once filled with European immigrants, were
impoverished. Alongside the old congregations were equally poor new
ones filled with immigrants from Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
   The new bishop closed some schools and initiated a fund-raising
campaign. It was not a time to talk about building anything. In
1995, with the Montserrat parishioners asking for more space, Egan
sought to add a Spanish Mass at St. Mary's, one of Stamford's
largest churches.
</P>
<P>
   Parishioners at St. Mary's, mostly of Irish or Italian descent,
suspected a possible merger and rebelled. ``Why does Montserrat
need to have its own church?'' one St. Mary's worshiper wrote to
The Advocate of Stamford. ``Why should it take ours? If most of the
parishioners there consist of illegal aliens and the like, why
should they have the right to such a voice in selecting the church
they'd like to own?''
</P>
<P>
   Any idea of joining the churches was dropped, and Egan swiftly
removed the pastor of St. Mary's. Lay leaders said they thought
their priest had been punished for their opposition to a merger
with Montserrat.
</P>
<P>
   The Montserrat parishioners continued to hope for their own
church. After the fight with St. Mary's, planning began in earnest
for expanding Montserrat. Financial and architectural plans were
drawn up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parishioners of Our Lady did everything they were supposed
to do in good faith, but in the end we were told we couldn't do it
for reasons that were not justified,'' said Alex Martinez, a former
parishioner who was the parish's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Since his resignation, Montserrat has not had an official
pastor, but an administrator. Seeking to underscore that the merger
with St. Benedict would be an equal one, Egan announced Father
Paskus and the Rev. Vincent Veich of St. Benedict would be
co-pastors of the new St. Benedict-Our Lady of Montserrat.
</P>
<P>
   The diocesan newspaper applauded the merger as providing new
lifeblood for the older congregation and a new home for the younger
one, a Tudor-style stone church with stained glass and a separate
social hall. Its mission would be to serve new Americans, whether
from Eastern Europe or Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   Veich attended the meeting at Montserrat to listen to complaints
and offer calming words. Parishioners at St. Benedict are
apprehensive about parking, but have have responded favorably to
the tripling of their congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Veich said the merger guaranteed that St. Benedict, built to
serve Slovak Catholics, would remain strong. He said it was fitting
that a parish that served one immigrant group at the start of the
20th century would serve another at the start of the 21st.
</P>
<P>
   The church secretary, Cathy Romano, has prepared the first joint
newsletter, in English and Spanish. Some parishioners are
contemplating new culinary traditions. ``I don't know about
kielbasa anymore at the picnics,'' said Ronnie Florio. Her husband,
Tony, disagreed. ``We'll mix it with the enchiladas,'' he said.
``We'll have a variety of food.''
</P>
<P>
   Drohan said things would work out. ``Part of what goes with the
bishop's role is the loneliness of command,'' he said. ``But a
decision isn't made in a vacuum. It's measured against facts. It's
measured against the future and future needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it an unpopular decision?'' he said of the merger.
``Clearly it was in certain quarters. Was it the correct decision?
We're very confident that the parishioners and the community will
see that it was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
