<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-STAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELMONT IS LOOKING FOR A FEW GOOD HORSES
</HEADLINE>
  By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After three years of Triple Crown suspense, Belmont
Park was trying to pick up the pieces from its shattered cast for
the Belmont Stakes Monday. But it was finding few signs of a
stampede by quality horses to replace the departed winners of the
Kentucky Derby and Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   It was also having trouble finding words to express its dismay
at not having a horse with a shot at the Triple Crown this year
after three straight blockbuster years when a horse did, before
crowds that reached a record of 85,818 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like anybody, we are disappointed with the turn of events that
have cost us the Derby and Preakness winners,'' said Terry Meyocks,
president of the New York Racing Association. ``But the well-being
of the horses comes first. However, our expectations are still
high. The Belmont Stakes is a New York event.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks after the withdrawal of Red Bullet, who won
the Preakness, the race was dealt a kind of coup de grace on Sunday
by the withdrawal of Fusaichi Pegasus, who won the Derby and ran
second in the Preakness. It lost Red Bullet when his owner decided
the colt needed more time between races. Then Fusaichi Pegasus was
withdrawn by his trainer, Neil Drysdale, after the colt sustained a
small cut on his right front hoof in his stall. Neither horse had a
shot at the Triple Crown, of course, but a rematch would have at
least made the Belmont highly anticipated. And now, some of that
anticipation is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the trainers at Belmont Park reacted diplomatically to
the double blow, but Carl Nafzger announced from Churchill Downs
that Unshaded, who ran second to Postponed in the Peter Pan, would
now be entered in the Belmont. Not only that, but the horse's
owner, James Tafel, will also pay the $100,000 supplemental fee
required because the colt was not nominated to the Triple Crown.
Earlier, Nafzger had said that Unshaded would not run unless the
race ``fell apart.''
</P>
<P>
   The trainer announced the switch in plans after Unshaded was
timed in one minute flat for five furlongs in a workout at
Churchill Downs, with Nafzger terming it ``a very professional
work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, when Fusaichi Pegasus came out of the race,'' he
said, ``that had something to do with it. But it was the work that
made the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Another horse at Churchill Downs was committed to the Belmont
after a solid workout. D.Wayne Lukas, who had listed Commendable as
a possible starter, made it definite after the colt worked six
furlongs in 1:13 4/5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an excellent work,'' Lukas said from his barn at Santa
Anita. ``We were leaning toward running anyway, but we wanted to
get that last work into him.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the defection of two top players would be an open
invitation to lesser horses to enter a major race. But it was
difficult to find horses who could run a 1 1/2 miles and who were
ready to try it this Saturday. Entries must be filed by Wednesday,
so it appeared likely that the absence of Fusaichi Pegasus and Red
Bullet would favor the contenders already committed to the race. A
field of 12 is expected.
</P>
<P>
   John Kimmel, the trainer of Wheelaway, who ran fifth in the
Derby, skipped the Preakness and is now set for the Belmont,
reacted with something of an understatement, saying, ``I look at it
as one less horse to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Scotty Schulhofer, the trainer of Postponed, acknowledged some
sense of relief that Fusaichi Pegasus would not be running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very bad for Neil Drysdale,'' he said. ``But I'm not
going to say that I'm not happy the horse isn't running, because I
am. It makes the race easier for the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Did the handlers of Red Bullet have second thoughts now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Fusaichi Pegasus had nothing to do with it,'' said Joe Orseno,
who trains Red Bullet for Frank Stronach. ``We weren't going in the
Belmont before, and we're not going after.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though New York may have been spoiled by three straight
years when the Triple Crown was within the grasp of a 3-year-old
colt running in the Belmont, racing officials were hoping that
there might be some carry-over effect and that the public would
show up in force this Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the decade of the '90s, in the years before the Triple
Crown went on the line, we had crowds of 37,171 on Belmont Day in
1995 and 40,797 on Belmont day in 1996,'' said Bill Nader, NYRA's
director of broadcast communications and promotions. ``Then,
suddenly, we had three years in a row when a horse came in here
after winning the Kentucky Derby and Preakness, and the crowds
doubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if Pegasus had come in here after winning the Derby
and Preakness, and for the fourth straight year, racing history
went on the line. We might have had 90,000 people at the track next
Saturday, maybe even 100,000.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
