<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-GREGSON-OBIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREGSON'S DEATH LEAVES RACING WORLD IN SHOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The suicide of Eddie Gregson, trainer of 1982 Kentucky Derby
winner Gato del Sol, left the California racetrack world in shock
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Gregson, 61, shot himself in his South Pasadena
office and was found dead at 9:45 p.m. Sunday night by his wife
after he failed to come home or answer the phone.
</P>
<P>
   He had saddled horses in two races at Hollywood Park earlier in
the day. Crows finished third and Street Cat finished seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Mark Miller said Gail Gregson told police her husband faced
personal problems unrelated to racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, these things are just an awful blow to you,''
said Noble Threewitt, the veteran trainer who gave Gregson his
start as a horseman in the late 1960s. ``I visited with Eddie
almost every day. I visited with him (Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   Threewitt said Gregson didn't indicate anything was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, Gregson was president of California
Thoroughbred Trainers and an officer of the California Thoroughbred
Breeders Association. His life had been unusually eclectic for the
insular horse-racing world.
</P>
<P>
   Born Edwin Janss Gregson in Los Angeles on Aug. 7, 1938, the
nephew of real-estate developer Edwin Janss Jr., he graduated from
Stanford with a degree in European history and did post-graduate
work at Cal. He worked as an actor under contract to Warner Bros.
and 20th Century Fox, appearing in ``The Naked and the Dead''
(1958), in which his character was bitten by a snake, requiring him
to foam at the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (New York Times) review said the snake-bite scene was the
most exciting thing in the movie,'' Gregson told the Daily News in
1985. ``Unfortunately, that wasn't enough to further my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregson quit Hollywood and divorced actress May Britt after a
two-year marriage, went to work on a ranch and speculated in
Mexican cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Threewitt, who had trained for Ed Janss, recalled the uncle
saying, ``Eddie can't seem to find anything he wants to do. Now he
wants to train horses. Can you help him out?''
</P>
<P>
   After learning from Hall of Fame trainer Woody Stephens in New
York and Threewitt in California, Gregson opened his own stable in
1974. He will be remembered best for Gato del Sol, who won the
Derby at 21-1, and Super Diamond, the 1986 Hollywood Gold Cup
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Financially comfortable, his reputation established, Gregson had
the luxury of walking away from owners who disagreed with his
methods. He didn't saddle many horses in later years and won only
13 races in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Gregson made news in recent months by speaking out against the
racing industry's permissiveness on equine medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good horseman. He was very, very intelligent. He was
very honest,'' Threewitt said. ``I don't think you can say too many
good things about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregson is survived by Gail, his third wife, and daughters
Brooke and Esme. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
