<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, JUNE 6
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-TRADE-PROTESTS-NYT (moved on Saturday, June 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent Saturday, June 3,
about plans for protests in Detroit and in Windsor, Ontario,
against an inter-American trade meeting being held in Windsor
through today referred incorrectly to the protests last November at
the World Trade Organization meeting in Seattle. The Seattle
protests were primarily peaceful. The authorities said any objects
thrown were aimed at property, not people. No protesters were
accused of throwing objects, including rocks and Molotov cocktails,
at delegates or the police.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-READING-TEST-NYT (moved on Thursday, June 1)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, June 1,
about fourth graders' performance on a statewide reading test
misidentified the New York City district in which scores rose most
sharply. It was District 33, a citywide unit with 3 elementary
schools and 10 middle schools reporting to the chancellor rather
than to a community school board; it was not District 31 on Staten
Island.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ECON-REPORT-NYT (moved on Friday, June 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, June 2,
about the Labor Department's employment report for May misstated
the period for a forecast of economic growth made by Macroeconomic
Advisers, a consulting firm in St. Louis. In predicting growth
closer to 3 percent than to the 4.5 percent originally forecast, it
referred to the second half of the year, not the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TONY-AWARDS-NYT (moved on Sunday, June 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, June 4,
misstated the surname of a winner, for best book of a musical. As
shown in the related article, the winner, for ``James Joyce's `The
Dead,''' was Richard Nelson, not Wilson.
</P>
</TEXT>
