<SLUG> BC-PERU-ELECTION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEMISPHERE GROUP PLANS TO SEND A MISSION TO PERU TO STUDY CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Subs for writethru.) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario _ Responding to the unopposed election of
Alberto Fujimori to a third term as president of Peru, foreign
ministers of the Americas agreed here Monday night to send a
mission to Lima to explore options for strengthening democracy in
Peru.
</P>
<P>
   The team is to be led by two critics of the May 28 voting in
Peru, Canada's foreign minister, Lloyd Axworthy, and Cesar Gaviria,
secretary general of the Organization of the American States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidential vote in Peru is a matter of deep concern to
us all,'' Axworthy said Monday morning before the vote. ``Left
unexamined, it will certainly diminish the credibility of this
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Opening the conference here on Sunday, Gaviria, a former
president of Colombia, cited attempted military coups in Ecuador
and Paraguay and the election problems in Peru, describing this as
``a year of trials, threats, and stumbling blocks for democracy in
the Americas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to face the fact that democracy can no longer be
considered an absolute certainty,'' Gaviria continued.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the election in Peru, he said bluntly, ``There were
irregularities, defects, inconsistencies and inequities in both
rounds of elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution left it up to the mission to decide on a
timetable for the mission and a forum for its reporting. Many
diplomats agreed that the mission would have most impact if it went
to Lima well before Fujimori's planned inauguration date, July 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a loss for the OAS if this becomes a high-level
fact-finding mission; we are beyond fact finding,'' said Eduardo
Stein, the former Guatemalan foreign minister who pulled his OAS
observer mission out of Peru two days before the May 28 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Calling for an election administration that is independent of
Fujimori, a ban on the use of state resources for official
candidates, and full press access to all candidates, Stein said of
the new mission: ``Their role should be promoter and negotiator of
these changes _ as fast as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights and Peruvian opposition legislators who gathered
here Monday called for new elections, and, failing that, concerted
pressure on Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to tell Fujimori that we have you under the
microscope here, your case is not under a done deal,'' said Jose
Miguel Vivanco, a Chilean lawyer who is executive director of the
Americas division of Human Rights Watch, a Washington-based
organization.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If the OAS does not take these minimal steps, the
message is the OAS will only react to confront bloody, unpopular
coups.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
