<SLUG> BC-JOHN-BODIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE NAME SUSPECT IN WOMEN'S DEATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO, RICHARD ESPINOZA and TANYANIKA SAMUELS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Prosecutors Monday
named the suspect in the killings of two women found buried in
barrels in a Kansas field, and authorities found three more barrels
in the man's Raymore storage locker.
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Edward Robinson Sr., 56, was being held Monday in the
Johnson County, Kan., Jail. Bond was $5 million _ the largest ever
set in the county.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he is charged with sexually assaulting two women after
meeting them for sadomasochistic encounters at hotels in Lenexa and
Overland Park, both in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County prosecutors said that Robinson, who has a
criminal record of fraud and theft charges dating to the 1960s,
would be facing homicide charges within a few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Robinson is a suspect in the deaths of the two women found
in the barrels in Linn County,'' District Attorney Paul Morrison
said. He said he did not expect anyone else to be charged in the
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the two women, who authorities think have been
dead for weeks, if not months, were found Saturday on land near La
Cygne, Kan., that Robinson bought in September.
</P>
<P>
   In Cass County, police Monday found three 55-gallon drums in the
locker at Stor-Mor For Less, 711 E. Missouri 58, Raymore Police
Chief Kris Turnbow said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County authorities learned last weekend that Robinson
had been renting the locker for about five years.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the barrels were sealed, but one was partly open.
</P>
<P>
   After looking inside that barrel, police sent all three of them
and other evidence to the Jackson County medical examiner's office
and the Kansas City police regional crime lab for analysis, Turnbow
said. He would not say what police saw in the open barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators remained at the storage facility into the night,
itemizing the contents.
</P>
<P>
   Cass County Prosecutor Chris Koster was to hold a news
conference at 1:30 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   In Linn County, Kan., investigators said they would continue to
search Robinson's property, where police dogs helped them find the
two drums on the west edge of the land. About 20 investigators,
including some from the FBI and the Kansas Bureau of Investigation,
were working on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ground-searching every bit of the land involved, and
there is also a pond involved,'' said Linn County Sheriff Marvin
Stites. ``There's a possibility we may drain that pond.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of the bodies resulted from a three-month
investigation. Robinson was arrested Friday at an Olathe mobile
home community where his wife works as a manager.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said Monday that one of the bodies found Saturday was
thought to be that of a woman who was reported missing March 1. The
woman lived in another state that Morrison declined to identify.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities did not know who the second victim was, but Morrison
said he thought she would be identified in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsies were being conducted, and investigators said they had
a good idea how the women died, although they would not discuss the
causes of death.
</P>
<P>
   At least one of the women Robinson was charged with sexually
assaulting traveled from Texas to have a sexual encounter with him
in April. The residence of the other woman, who met with Robinson
in May, was unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson allegedly developed relationships on the Internet with
women interested in sadomasochistic encounters. He was known to use
the screen name ``slavemaster'' in his computer correspondence and
sometimes called himself James Turner in person, Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case has to do with the suspect having numerous contacts
throughout the United States who share similar interests, over,
among other things, the Internet,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were looking for other women who had been in
contact Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Both women involved in the criminal charges told police that
they voluntarily agreed to act as ``sex slaves'' for Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   They said they objected to his photographing them during the
encounters, and both said he brutalized them in a way that went
beyond what they intended.
</P>
<P>
   The woman from Texas also reported that Robinson stole more than
$700 worth of whips, paddles, riding crops, rattan canes and other
sex toys from her.
</P>
<P>
   When she asked for her property back, he allegedly threatened to
reveal a signed ``slave contract'' to licensing authorities in
Texas, where she is a licensed psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson appeared in court Monday on the charges of aggravated
sexual battery and felony theft.
</P>
<P>
   He asked for a court-appointed attorney, and District Judge
William Cleaver appointed the public defender's office.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver also increased Robinson's bond from the $250,000 set
Friday to the $5 million requested Monday by Ted Baird, assistant
district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Baird said prosecutors considered Robinson an ``extreme flight
risk'' with previous felony convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials in Kansas and Missouri said Robinson had been
incarcerated in both states in the 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Court records in Clay and Johnson counties show convictions for
theft, stealing and fraud-related charges.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors in Olathe said they had no idea of Robinson's criminal
past.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Timmons, who lives next to Robinson at the Santa Barbara
mobile home park, described him as a cordial neighbor who put out
yard decorations on holidays and seemed to keep to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Timmons said he was surprised when police arrested Robinson and
searched his trailer, which is on a fenced lot with an enclosed
patio. Timmons saw investigators pull coolers, large popcorn tins
and a toolbox from Robinson's garden shed. Later, he said, police
towed away Robinson's pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has another trailer on his property in Linn County,
which he bought Sept. 28, 1999, according to county records.
Records show that the 16.5 acres and the trailer, which included a
deck, were valued at $36,670.
</P>
<P>
   The property is about two miles north of a high school and is
surrounded by farmland near La Cygne.
</P>
<P>
   Corn and soybeans grow in fields around Robinson's land. Several
duck hunting clubs are near the property.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie McGuire, 61, lives near Robinson's land but had not met
him. She and her husband, Tom, moved to the area in recent years
from Mission Hills and built a house.
</P>
<P>
   McGuire said she occasionally saw a pickup truck outside
Robinson's trailer but had seen nothing suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``You move to the country and you don't expect anything like
this to happen,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
