<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE LAKERS' BRIDGE TO PROMISING FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Inside their locker room Sunday, Shaquille O'Neal
and Kobe Bryant quietly sat with their Laker teammates and listened
to Coach Phil Jackson's final instructions for Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe 20 yards away in a corridor of the Staples Center, Magic
Johnson held court before the deciding game of the Western
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of playoff frustration, Johnson was wondering the
same as everyone who has watched O'Neal and Bryant grow and mature
the past four seasons: Were they ready to fuse the Lakers' magical
past with its promising future?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it means to Shaq,'' said Johnson, who led the
Lakers to their last finals in 1990. ``He wants to get that loser's
tag off his back. I know how much this means to him. It means a lot
to those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest fourth-quarter comeback in NBA history was still a
few hours away, the night the Lakers came back from 15 points down
in the final 10 minutes 28 seconds and shocked the Portland Trail
Blazers, 89-84, before the most raucous and unlaid-back L.A. crowd
anyone could remember.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had not yet scored 9 of his 18 points in the final
period, shelving his frustration at being mobbed by Blazers
underneath the basket so that he could find open teammates on the
perimeter with the game in the balance. It was long before he would
calmly collect on 8 of 12 free throws, including two with 2:44 left
that tied the score at 77-77.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant had yet to put up an eye-opening line of 25 points, 11
rebounds, 7 assists and 4 blocked shots. He had not yet broken a
tie with a scintillating jump shot left of the free-throw line with
1:34 left or thrown that impossible lob pass to the right of the
rim with 41.3 seconds remaining that O'Neal threw down, the most
pressurized alley-oop dunk of any playoff series, ever.
</P>
<P>
   Before their heroics, O'Neal and Bryant were merely two young
all-stars trying to find their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long, Kobe and Shaq and all of us were in a mode of not
being able to prove ourselves when it mattered,'' Rick Fox said.
``After a while, that wears on you. I'm still processing all of it.
You come so far and you lose your way, and then you have to work so
hard to get back to where you were. We found our way. And we kept
going.''
</P>
<P>
   It took nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Since the last vestige of Showtime left the Fabulous Forum and
the Magic stopped in 1990 many have tried to pass this franchise
off as a passable imitation. The Lakers of Shaq and Kobe were a
team of marketable faces, flair, the only consistent ratings
grabber after Michael Jordan retired.
</P>
<P>
   But they had this awful habit of wilting as the postseason wore
on. Whether Utah swept the Lakers in the 1998 conference finals or
San Antonio accomplished the feat in the second round of the 1999
playoffs, they always managed to die hard.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much that they lost but the way they lost that gave
the appearance of little character and resolve. How could a team
with the most awesome physical presence in the game and one of the
most exciting young players come apart at the hinges so easily? Why
weren't they more durable and resilient?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we doubted ourselves after every season,''
O'Neal said. ``But after a while, you read the newspapers and
listen to what people are saying about you. You can't help but let
that either get you down or motivate you to change people's
perceptions. That's what we did, changed people's perceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared to happen in a blink, but the legwork was already
there on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Though they fell behind early, Bryant was collaring rebounds in
the first half as if he were a power forward, swinging his elbows
to clear space among the Redwood Blazers. For all his talent and
highlight reels, he went after Bonzi Wells, Scottie Pippen and
Steve Smith on the defensive end as if only playing that end of the
floor mattered.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal took a while to find a rhythm and didn't lose his temper
against Arvydas Sabonis and the rest of Portland's front line, who
grabbed, fronted and bumped him to no end. He, too, worked hard on
both ends, at one point diving into the third row of seats to hunt
down a loose ball.
</P>
<P>
   As the comeback began and their shots started to fall, there
would be no more meltdowns. It was just two veterans determined to
let a season of accomplishment slip away on their home floor. They
would go onto to face the Indiana Pacers in Game 1 of the finals
Wednesday night at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   In one quarter, the old issues died and they suddenly became
prohibitive favorites to win the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, when you get here, you've got to win it,''
Jackson said. ``We may have learned enough at this point to know
how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, pumping his fist and smiling, was almost as ecstatic as
O'Neal and Bryant after the improbable Game 7 victory that most of
Los Angeles is still buzzing about Sunday, the night the Lakers'
magical past fused seamlessly together with its promising future. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
