<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5533 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-BASKIN-NYT &LR;      06-05 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BASKIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCULPTOR LEONARD BASKIN, 77, DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leonard Baskin, a figurative sculptor and graphic artist whose
work varied from a Holocaust memorial to a prize-winning children's
book but dealt mostly with the human condition in angst-ridden
terms, died on Saturday in Northampton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin was 77 and lived in Northampton. He had been treated for
kidney problems for several months, said Richard Michelson, his
primary representative since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   In an art world given to changing styles and continually updated
aesthetic agendas centering on abstraction, Baskin remained
steadfast in his belief in the superiority of figurative art and
the importance of mortality as a theme. His convictions brought him
honors and important commissions, including those for the bas
relief of a funeral cortege that he created for the Franklin Delano
Roosevelt Memorial in Washington and an anguished, heavily draped
seated cast-bronze figure, 7 feet tall, for the Ann Arbor Holocaust
Memorial in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Widely read and articulate, Baskin could be acidly funny,
referring to Pop Art, for example, as ``the inedible raised to the
level of the unspeakable.'' Or he could pontificate in biblical
sonorities, as in a frequently quoted statement published in Time
magazine: ``Our human frame, our gutted mansion, our enveloping
sack of beef and ash is yet a glory. Glorious in defining our
universal sodality and glorious in defining our utter uniqueness.
The human figure is the image of all men and of one man. It
contains all and can express all.''
</P>
<P>
   Baskin's art did its best to keep up with this sense of urgency
and drama. In sculptures of wood, limestone or bronze, and the
large-scale wood block prints that may be his most lasting
achievement, his figures often had scabrous surfaces, appeared
bloated or malformed, and sometimes merged with animals. His
favorite figure was the owl, whose predatory habits fascinated him.
</P>
<P>
   If Baskin's figures did not appear to be actively suffering or
simply dead, they often appeared to be in numbed, introspective
states.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin was born in New Brunswick, N.J., the son of a rabbi who
moved his family to New York seven years later. By age 14 he knew
he wanted to be a sculptor; at 15 he began a two-year
apprenticeship to the sculptor Maurice Glickman. At 18 he won an
honorable mention for the Prix de Rome.
</P>
<P>
   He studied art at New York University's School of Architecture
and Applied Arts, and, on scholarship, at Yale University from 1941
to 1943. He discovered the illustrated books of William Blake in a
library at Yale, an encounter that inspired him both to teach
himself printing and, in 1942, to found the Gehenna Press, which
became noted for its fine typography and superbly illustrated
limited-edition books. Its first publication was a small book of
Baskin's own poems, titled ``On a Pyre of Withered Roses.''
</P>
<P>
   After serving in the U.S. Navy in the Pacific during the final
years of World War II and working for a period in the Merchant
Marine, Baskin returned to New York and earned his bachelor's
degree at the New School for Social Research in 1949. He then spent
a year studying at the Academie de la Grade Chaumiere in Paris, and
another year at the Accademia di Belle Arti in Florence, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Europe on a Guggenheim Fellowship in 1953, Baskin
found himself attracted to a variety of figurative sculpture,
including the effigy tomb sculpture of the Middle Ages, the early
Renaissance carving of Giovanni Pisano and the 19th- and
20th-century work of Rodin, Manzu and especially the German
Expressionist sculptor Ernst Barlach.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin had his first solo show in New York at the Grace
Borgenicht Gallery in 1953, exhibiting regularly there and with the
Boris Mirski Gallery in Boston throughout the 1950s and '60s. His
work figured prominently in the ``New Images of Man'' exhibition at
the Museum of Modern Art in New York and was included in the
biannual exhibitions in Sao Paulo in 1961 and Venice in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin taught sculpture and printmaking at Smith College in
Northampton, Mass., from 1953 until 1974 and at Hampshire College
in nearby Amherst from 1984 to 1994. He and his family lived in
England during the intervening decade.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin's most recent solo show was at the Salander O'Reilly
Galleries in Manhattan in 1997. His work is represented in public
collections across the country and has been the subject of numerous
retrospectives.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin was a lifelong collector of prints and old and rare
books, calling collecting ``the only activity I know of that
involves every one of the seven deadly sins, even sloth.'' His
obsession with books was more actively expressed in the dozens he
designed or illustrated. For the Gehenna Press, which published
more than 100 books and was still operating at the time of his
death, these included editions of Blake's ``Augeries of
Innocence,'' Euripedes' ``Hippolytos,'' and Ted Hughes' ``Primer of
Birds.''
</P>
<P>
   The books Baskin illustrated for other publishers included
several more collections of Hughes' poetry, as well as works by
Dante, Homer, Conrad, Swift, Tennyson, and by his first wife,
Esther Tane Baskin, who died in 1967. His illustrated children's
book ``Hosie's Alphabet'' won the Caldecott Medal in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin is survived by his wife, Lisa Unger Baskin; a son from
his first marriage, Tobias Baskin, of Columbia, Mo.; two children
from his second marriage, Hosea Baskin and Lucretia Baskin, of
Northampton, Mass.; a brother, Rabbi Bernard Baskin, of Hamilton,
Ontario; a sister, Pearl Rabinowitz, of Massapequa, N.Y., and three
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the broad range of his work, Baskin disdained color,
saying, ``Black and White is all I need.''
</P>
<P>
   He also did not depict women. ``The female form is useful for
some ideas,'' he said in 1964, ``but the colossal male is better
suited to the ghoulish ones I try to portray.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
