<SLUG> BC-BBO-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARLINS TAKE FIRST BASEMAN WITH FIRST PICK IN DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For anyone with professional baseball as his goal, the San Diego
area is apparently the place to live. Holding their annual draft of
amateur players Monday, major league teams selected six players
from that area, including two from the same high school, in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Gonzalez, a left-handed-hitting first baseman, was the
No. 1 pick in the draft, chosen by the Florida Marlins, and the
first of the five San Diego players taken.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who batted .645 and drove in 34 runs in 76 at-bats
this season, was given a $3 million signing bonus. Some baseball
people speculated that the Marlins had planned to take Scott Heard,
a catcher from Rancho Bernardo High School in San Diego, but that
Heard rejected their bonus offer.
</P>
<P>
   Al Avila, the club's scouting director, denied that economics
played a role in the decision. John Boggs, a San Diego area agent
who advised the Gonzalez family in the negotiations with the
Marlins, said the Marlins also denied that Heard had turned down $4
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they came to us,'' Boggs said by telephone from Miami,
``they said they had a figure, and if it was something we weren't
going to be comfortable with, they had other options. Adrian's real
focus was to get his career started. He made the ultimate decision.
He didn't want a protracted negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Heard went much lower in the first round than had been expected.
The Texas Rangers made him the 25th player selected. His
batterymate, Matt Wheatland, a right-hander, was the eighth player
drafted, going to the Detroit Tigers. Their selection marked only
the third time in the 35-year history of the draft that high school
teammates were selected in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel kind of blessed that I've had two kids like that
on the team,'' Sam Blalock, the Rancho Bernardo baseball coach,
said by telephone from San Diego. ``It's so nice to see such poised
and mature baseball players.''
</P>
<P>
   Also selected in the first round were Adam Johnson, a
right-handed pitcher from San Diego and California State University
at Fullerton, taken as the second pick by Minnesota; Shaun Boyd, a
high school second baseman from a San Diego suburb, taken as the
13th player by St. Louis; and Robert Stiehl, a catcher, chosen as
the 27th player by Houston. Stiehl attends El Camino Junior College
in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Wheatland, Heard and Boyd competed against each other this
season in the Palomar League of the North County Conference. Also
on a team in that league was Anthony Gwynn, son of the Padres' Tony
Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, whose high school is in the southern part of the
county, said having so many good players and teams in the area was
beneficial to him. ``You always look in paper to see how they're
doing, and you want to do better than them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our league is one of the toughest in the nation year
in and year out,'' said Blalock, whose team won the section title
for the second successive season. Yet another of his players, David
Giorgis, the right fielder, was selected by the Padres in the
eighth round.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' first-round selection, David Parrish, son of Lance,
the former Detroit catcher, was one of several sons of former major
leaguers drafted. The group also included shortstop Aaron Herr, son
of Tom, by Atlanta in the ``sandwich'' free-agent compensation
round between the first and second rounds; third baseman Lance
Niekro, son of Joe, by San Francisco in the second round; pitcher
Kyle Gross, son of Wayne, by the Giants in the fifth round; and
pitcher Jason Fingers, son of Rollie, by Kansas City in the 10th
round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
