<HEADER>
A5535 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-05 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   ENDORSEMENTS WITHDRAWN
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters union has withdrawn its endorsement of two
Democratic House members _ Lois Capps of California and Tom Sawyer
of Ohio _ because they supported the China trade bill. The move
could undercut labor's push to help Democrats regain control of the
House. But Bret Caldwell, a Teamsters spokesman, said the
1.4-million-member union, one of the largest in the AFL-CIO, was
more concerned about ``whether members of Congress will stand up
when it counts for working families.'' The endorsement withdrawals
were part of a reassessment of all 73 House Democrats who backed
the China bill. Other House Democrats who face a strong chance of
losing the Teamsters' endorsement, Caldwell said, include Martin T.
Meehan and Richard E. Neal of Massachusetts, Tom Allen of Maine,
Sander M. Levin of Michigan and Dennis Moore of Kansas. The
Teamsters and the Auto Workers, which also opposed the trade deal,
are by far the strongest unions in Moore's district, which he won
by a razor-thin margin in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   THE STATES
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARIES IN 5 STATES
</P>
<P>
   Five states hold the last of the presidential primaries Tuesday,
their role about as useful to politics as the appendix is to
people, thanks to the big rush this year by many states to hold
early primaries. The five states are Alabama, Montana, New Jersey,
New Mexico and South Dakota. While some contests, notably the
Senate primaries in New Jersey, are expected to draw voters, there
is not likely to be a lot of enthusiasm for casting a Bush or Gore
vote. That was the case two weeks ago in the Kentucky primary,
where the turnout was just 14 percent of enrolled Democrats and 11
percent of Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   GORE BYPASSES TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas decided to skip his
state's Republican convention because he is so far ahead in
presidential preference polls there. Now Vice President Al Gore
most likely will bypass the Texas Democratic Party's state
convention for, well, the same reason. Texas is going to be
``difficult'' for Gore in the fall, so he probably will not show
for the June 9-10 gathering, the state's Democratic leader, Molly
Beth Malcolm, told the Dallas Morning News recently. ``It makes
more sense,'' she said, ``that he would go to one of those states
where possibly he has a real shot at winning.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   HITTING GORE WHERE HE LIVES
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and officials with the Bush campaign have an
insatiable appetite for making fun of Vice President Al Gore's
retoolings, restylings and resolves to make sure that voters get to
know him better, and Monday they bit into some fresh meat. A Bush
campaign official, speaking to reporters in Austin, Tex., said that
one of the states in which the Democratic National Committee had
investigated the cost and availability of air time for biographical
television commercials about Gore was Tennessee. There's a certain
poetry to this, the official said. They're going to put a bio ad on
in Tennessee to reintroduce him to all of those hometown people who
have grown distant to him over the years. The official conceded
that some states on the list may be there to divert attention from
the real targets, and Jenny Backus, a spokeswoman for the DNC, said
the committee had not made ``a final decision about if we'll go up,
when we'll go up, what we'll go up with and where we'll go up with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   THE GREEN PARTY
</P>
<P>
   NADER CHOOSES RUNNING MATE
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader said over the weekend that if he wins the
presidential nomination of the Green Party, as is expected, he
wanted an American Indian activist, Winona LaDuke, on the ballot as
the party's candidate for vice president. LaDuke is a Harvard
graduate from the White Earth Indian Reservation in northwestern
Minnesota, where she farms and writes. She was Nader's running mate
four years ago. Ten years ago, she started the White Earth Land
Recovery Project, an effort to win back lands taken from
Minnesota's Objibwa tribe. Nader, who is running on a promise to
end corporate influence in government and put more power in the
hands of citizens, called LaDuke ``a very accomplished person.''
The Green Party holds its convention later this month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES &QL; 
GEORGE W. BUSH _ Augusta, Ga. &QL; 
AL GORE _ New York &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
