<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-GRANDPARENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT'S VISITATION RULING GOES AGAINST GRANDPARENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) The U.S. Supreme Court on Monday struck down as
``breathtakingly broad'' a Washington state law that allows anyone
_ including grandparents _ to petition for visitation rights to
children against their parents' wishes.
</P>
<P>
   The high court stressed that parents have a constitutional right
to raise their children free from government interference. But the
court did not strike down the other grandparent visitation laws
that exist in some variation in all 50 states, or set standards for
how those laws should protect the rights of parents. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Legal analysts said the 6-3 ruling will likely prompt state
legislatures and courts to examine whether the laws sufficiently
narrow a court's discretion in granting grandparents visitation
over a parent's objections.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling leaves Seattle-area grandparents Gary and
Jenifer Troxel without any legal claim to visitation with their two
granddaughters. They filed suit demanding overnight visitation with
the girls after their son Brad Troxel &UR;  &LR; killed himself &UR;  &LR;  in 1993 and
the girls' mother, Tommie Granville Wynn, began limiting _ but not
denying _ the grandparents' visits.
</P>
<P>
   The Troxels were granted visitation by a Washington superior
court judge, but Granville appealed the decision. The case
ultimately reached the Washington Supreme Court, which ruled that
the state's third-party visitation statute unconstitutionally
interferes with the fundamental rights of parents to raise their
children.
</P>
<P>
   The broad Washington state law allows anyone, at any time, to
sue for court-ordered visits with other people's children. The law
does not require previous custody or any familial relationship, and
leaves the determination of the ``best interest of the child''
solely to the presiding judge. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The Troxels' attorney, Mark Olson, said Monday that his clients
would now approach the girls' mother for the one afternoon a month
of visitation she had originally offered before they sued.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Cheryl Matheis, director of state legislation for the
AARP, said there may be room to debate the Supreme Court's wording,
but that she believes the court struck down the Washington law on
its face, and as applied in the &UR;  &LR; Troxel case. AARP attorneys helped
write most of the grandparent visitation laws across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Supreme Court is saying to the legislatures is, if
you're going to write a third-party visitation statute, write
something with some standards defined,'' said Sanford Ain, a
Washington, D.C., family law attorney who wrote a brief in this
case for the American Association of Matrimonial Lawyers. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Tommie Granville Wynn was delighted with the decision, said
attorney Howard Goodfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision affirms what she has stated all along _ that fit
parents are the persons who get to make the decisions about when
and where their children visit with other people,'' Goodfriend
said. ``Even though it's an opinion on only one statute, it's going
to have some precedential effect on other statues.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, who wrote the controlling opinion,
noted that the ``demographic changes of the past century make it
difficult to speak of an average American family.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide enactment of nonparental visitation statutes is due
in part to states' recognition of the changing realities of the
American family, she wrote, because grandparents and other
relatives take on the duties of a parental nature in many
households. The U.S. Census Bureau reports that more than 2.5
million grandparents are raising their children's children.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Connor stressed that the 14th Amendment due process clause
preserves the interest of parents in the ``care, custody and
control of their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as a parent adequately cares for his or her children
... there will normally be no reason for the state to inject itself
into the private realm of the family to further question the
ability of that parent to make the best decisions concerning the
rearing of that parent's children,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Troxels did not claim that Granville was an unfit parent,
O'Connor wrote. It was wrong to ask the mother to prove that
grandparent visitation would not be in her children's best
interest, she said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; O'Connor said the court was basing its decision on the
``sweeping breadth'' of Washington's law, and not on the conclusion
of the Washington Supreme Court that a visitation statute must
require proof of harm to a child if visitation is not granted.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's opinion was joined by Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist, Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer,
while Justices David H. Souter and Clarence Thomas
wrote &UR;  &LR; concurring opinions generally agreeing with O'Connor. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Justices John Paul Stevens, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M.
Kennedy each wrote dissenting opinions.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, Rehnquist, Stevens, Scalia, Kennedy and Ginsburg are
grandparents. Thomas was raised by his grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
