<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-HERZOG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL SAID TO BE IN TALKS TO PURCHASE HERZOG HEINE
</HEADLINE>
  By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seeking to play a much bigger role in trading on the
Nasdaq stock market, Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. is in serious discussions
to buy Herzog Heine Geduld Inc. for nearly $1 billion, according to
people close to the companies.
</P>
<P>
   In a deal that could be announced as soon as Tuesday, Merrill is
negotiating to use its stock to buy Herzog, a private company based
in Jersey City that serves as an intermediary, or market maker,
between buyers and sellers of Nasdaq stocks. Herzog is the
third-biggest market maker in Nasdaq stocks and Merrill has been
plotting lately to expand its market-making business.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Merrill and of Herzog declined to comment on
the matter after it was reported Monday by the Dow Jones Newswires.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Knight Trading Group, the No. 1 market maker with
18 percent of Nasdaq trades, fell 13 percent Monday, to $30.9375,
on concerns that an aggressive move by Merrill would divert some of
the flow of trades that go from Merrill and other brokerage firms
to Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Herzog, which handles about 9 percent of Nasdaq trades,
would represent a reversal for Merrill in a couple of ways: the
firm has sharply cut back its Nasdaq trading business in the last
few years and its executives have been reluctant to make any big
acquisitions after its last buying binge depressed its stock price.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq market, many firms can make a market in a
particular stock, by standing ready to buy shares from willing
sellers or sell shares to buyers. Market makers keep the difference
between what they pay sellers and what they receive from buyers, a
difference known as the spread.
</P>
<P>
   Spreads on Nasdaq trading shrank after the National Association
of Securities Dealers, which runs the Nasdaq market, put in place
new rules in the wake of lawsuits that contended that market makers
colluded to keep spreads unjustifiably high. The investigation
caused by those suits culminated in a $1 billion settlement paid by
dozens of Wall Street firms, including Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   With their trading profits drying up, some big firms chose to
make markets only in the most popular Nasdaq stocks, leaving
thousands of others to traditional market-making firms like Herzog.
Some technology-based newcomers, like Knight, formerly
Knight-Trimark, stepped in to the void and showed that market
making remained a profitable business. In recent weeks, Merrill,
the No. 6 market maker, has been telling traders that it planned to
quadruple the number of stocks in which it makes a market to about
2,000 from about 550. Merrill had planned to set up a Nasdaq
trading site in Jersey City that would serve as its beefed-up
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were divided on whether buying Herzog was a smart move
for Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``When better to buy a Nasdaq market maker than after a Nasdaq
crash?'' said Richard Strauss, an analyst at Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   He said Merrill appeared to be copying a model that has worked
well for its rival discount brokerage firm, Charles Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab routes many of its customers' Nasdaq stock trades to its
own Jersey City-based market-making operation in a practice known
as internalization that is becoming a buzzword on Wall Street.
Keeping trades in-house gives the firm more information about which
way stock prices are headed, data that it can use to trade for its
own account.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab, the No. 2 market maker with 12 percent of Nasdaq trades,
has been a notable dissenter to proposals to create a central book
of all existing orders to buy and sell Nasdaq stocks. Merrill and
other big Wall Street firms had supported such a change, but lately
that support has been weakening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Merrill has a clear idea of where market reform is
going,'' Strauss said.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Butte, a Bear, Stearns analyst, said that buying Herzog
would make Merrill a big market maker quickly. ``In making this
acquisition, they would look a lot more like Schwab,'' she said.
But, she added, market makers' profits are threatened again by the
Securities and Exchange Commission's plan to change the structure
of the U.S. stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   For several months, Butte has recommended against buying Knight
stock, in part, because she believes that the profits of pure
market makers are likely to be squeezed. Based on the price Herzog
reportedly would fetch, she said, Knight's stock price is much too
high.
</P>
</TEXT>
