<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DRAFT-LOCAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRINGTON LEADS LOCAL CONTINGENT ON DRAFT'S FIRST DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ His pitching prowess never in question, Matt
Harrington's prize for his stellar Palmdale High career and golden
right arm is being drafted by the Colorado Rockies _ where stellar
careers and golden arms go flying out of Coors Field along with
home runs.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm freaking relieved. I'm thrilled,'' Harrington said after
being chosen seventh overall in Monday's Major League Baseball
First-Year Player Draft. ``I don't have concerns. Maybe it'll make
me a better pitcher. I've got to make the same pitches, whether I'm
in Dodger Stadium or in Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington was the first local player taken and one of four
selected in the first round. Camarillo graduate Joe Borchard, a
Stanford outfielder, went 12th to the Chicago White Sox; UCLA
second baseman Chase Utley went to Philadelphia with the 15th pick
and the Mets took Loyola Marymount pitcher Billy Traber at No.16.
</P>
<P>
   Five other local college players, including Pepperdine catcher
Dane Sardinha (second round, 46th overall to Cincinnati) were
drafted before the next area high schooler, Highland of Palmdale
pitcher Matt Parris, taken in the sixth round (No.168 overall) by
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The first 20 rounds were Monday and the final 30 rounds are
today.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington had been featured on the cover of Baseball America
and mentioned in Sports Illustrated. There had been talk he would
go in the first five picks, so some might be surprised he was
available when Colorado drafted.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: On Sunday, Minnesota, owner of the second pick,
called Harrington and offered him about $3 million to sign.
Baseball America reported online that Florida agreed to close to
that same amount with San Diego first baseman Adrian Gonzalez, who
the Marlins made the No.1 pick.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington's parents, Bill and Sue, thought the Twins' offer was
fair but left the decision to their son. On advice from advisors
Tommy Tanzer and Jeff Kahn, Harrington declined.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies, meanwhile, also called and told Harrington they
would pay him what he was worth, not basing his signing bonus on
the amounts other draft picks received. Harrington was satisfied
and went to school hoping he would be available when Colorado
picked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rockies are a better fit,'' Harrington said. ``The Twins
wanted to slot me and pay me less than No.1. In a lot of people's
opinion, he (Gonzalez) is not the No.1 guy. A lot of people thought
I was, so Tommy thought I should be paid (appropriately).''
</P>
<P>
   Borchard had a different dilemma: baseball or football?
</P>
<P>
   He could return to Stanford and be the Cardinal starting
quarterback this fall. Or he could sign for seven figures and play
for the White Sox. Or he could try and do both: Play a short summer
with Chicago and return to school for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to entertain that option,'' Borchard said in a
conference call, ``but I'm not sure what the White Sox feel about
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough decision, considering how much time I've devoted
to football. It's hard to give something like that up when you get
to take the reins, so to speak. When I play football, I miss summer
and fall (ball). From the end of June to Jan. 2, I don't pick up a
bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Borchard knows his future lies in baseball, unlike another
famous Stanford alum who chose football _ John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm about as signable as anyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Borchard, like Traber, didn't find out from the team that
drafted him. Traber knew the Internet carried the draft live, so he
logged on, only to find a blank page.
</P>
<P>
   Then he got a call from LMU coach Frank Cruz congratulating him.
Then he got calls from five friends who saw it on the Internet.
Then the Mets called. Then Traber couldn't reach his parents
because he didn't know their work numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a weird draft,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Utley agreed. He knew the Phillies were interested, but he also
knew teammate Bill Scott could be the first Bruin taken.
</P>
<P>
   Scott went in the sixth round, to Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get myself up in case I was disappointed,'' Utley
said. ``I was hoping for the best and it worked out great.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
