u i BC-CHERNOBYL-CLOSING-HNS     06-05 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHERNOBYL-CLOSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHERNOBYL PLANT WILL SHUT DOWN, UKRAINE LEADER TELLS CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine _ The crippled Chernobyl power plant, site of the
worst nuclear accident in history, will be closed permanently on
Dec. 15, President Leonid Kuchma announced Monday during a brief
visit by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The move means that the fourth and final functioning reactor at
the plant, about 60 miles north of Kiev, will be taken off line and
shut. One reactor was destroyed in the catastrophic meltdown and
explosion in April 1986, a second burned in 1991 and a third was
closed in 1996 near the end of its safe operating lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 15,000 people have died in the intervening 14 years
as a result of the radiation that spewed into the atmosphere, a
toxic dose some scientists believe was equivalent to about 500
times that of the atomic bomb the United States dropped on
Hiroshima, Japan, in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred thirty-five thousand people were evacuated. Sharply
higher radiation levels were recorded across much of northern and
eastern Europe, and less severe increases were noted as far away as
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a hopeful moment,'' Clinton said after he and Kuchma
toasted the Chernobyl announcement with champagne. ``It is also a
moment when we remember those who suffered as a result of the
accident there.''
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, Clinton spoke to tens of thousands of
Ukrainians in a plaza at St. Michael's Monastery but did not
mention the Chernobyl accident or Kuchma's new closure pledge.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. government source indicated the Chernobyl announcement
was more for international consumption, saying that Clinton omitted
comments on the upcoming closure from his remarks because the
reactor incident is a politically and personally sensitive issue in
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of people got sick and died,'' the source said. ``There's
a pain in many Ukrainian hearts today.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, ending a week-long European trip, then flew to
Washington. He is to remain in the U.S. capital only a day before
heading off for a quick Wednesday-Thursday trip to Japan for a
memorial service for former Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   En route from Moscow to Kiev, the Ukrainian capital, Air Force
One flew within sight of Chernobyl, its massive cooling towers
reflecting in the afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchma had promised several years ago to close the fourth
reactor but reneged when wealthier nations did not make good on
pledges to help finance construction of new reactors. The reactor
destroyed in 1986 was quickly encased in a steel and concrete
``sarcophagus'' that is considered an inadequate final measure and
which some scientists believe could crack.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced a new U.S. aid package of $78 million for new
containment projects at Chernobyl and $2 million for safety
measures at other nuclear power plants in Ukraine. Forty percent of
the electrical power generated in Ukraine is from nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchma said Clinton agreed to make certain that donations from
the other leading industrial democracies, known as the G7
countries, are forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this will take place,'' Kuchma said. ``The aim of
this decision is to reduce nuclear risks in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   A so-called ``pledging conference'' to raise funds for a second
Chernobyl sarcophagus will be held at Berlin in July.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said that G7 nations have worked since 1995 to
``mobilize'' about $2 billion through energy sector loans from
international financial institutions such as the World Bank. An
additional $1 billion in grants for Chernobyl site safety projects
has been provided by G7 nations
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the United States, the G7 nations are Britain,
Canada, France, Germany, Italy and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton's visit approaching, Kuchma said Sunday that
Chernobyl ``must be stopped from all points of view, and first of
all from the point of view of security. I have no doubts about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
