A5542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MOSCOW-TALKS-NYT     06-05 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MOSCOW-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MODEST GAINS IN MOSCOW 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 6:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Little progress on arms control was expected from Bill
Clinton's weekend visit to Moscow, and little occurred. President
Vladimir Putin of Russia acknowledged that there might soon be a
need to counter nuclear threats from unpredictable powers like
North Korea. But he did not soften his opposition to U.S. plans for
a national missile defense. Clinton agreed that there should be
significant new reductions in offensive missiles as part of a deal
that would also amend the 1972 Antiballistic Missile Treaty to
allow a limited defensive shield. But Clinton held back from
steeper cuts that Russia favors and the Pentagon resists.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, prospects for reaching agreement on these issues
during the remainder of Clinton's term do not look good. But with
more than seven months and at least three further meetings with
Putin before Clinton leaves office, both sides should keep working.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings saw some modest but important arms control
achievements. The United States and Russia agreed to safely dispose
of 34 metric tons of military plutonium each, enough for thousands
of nuclear warheads if smuggled to countries like Libya or Iraq. In
addition, an early warning station will be established in Moscow
staffed jointly by Russian and U.S. personnel to share information
on missile and space launches, reducing the danger of misreading
peaceful launches as surprise attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The most important disagreement is over U.S. plans for a
national missile defense. The Clinton administration favors a
strictly limited system usable only against smaller states. Russia
fears that such a system could later be upgraded to blunt some of
its own strategic missile force. If Russia's fears about missile
defense can be eased, Moscow would be eager to cut the number of
both sides' offensive missiles to 1,500 or lower. The Pentagon,
however, wants no fewer than 2,000 to 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is understandably reluctant to press military leaders on
this issue during an election campaign. But a reasonable case can
be made that the United States can safely meet all of its military
goals with somewhat fewer missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the administration should not rush to meet its own
artificial deadline for deciding whether to go ahead with building
such a system later this year. The technology has not yet been
adequately tested nor have the possibilities for diplomatic
agreement been exhausted. Clinton should not risk unraveling
existing treaties by moving too hastily to decide on missile
defenses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
