<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-DELAY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GLITCHES CAUSE INTEL TO DELAY RELEASE OF THRIFTY PROCESSOR  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the latest embarrassment related to its
attempt to move the PC world to a new type of memory, Intel on
Monday postponed the release of a new ultra-low-cost PC processor
from this summer to the first quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   The new chip, code-named Timna, is intended for consumer PCs
priced below $600. Until yesterday's disclosure, it was expected to
ship in time to go into new models for this year's back-to-school
and holiday seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major slip, but it's not going to hurt Intel's business
much,'' said Linley Gwennap, principal analyst at the Linley Group,
a Mountain View market-research company. ``They can continue to
supply the market segment Timna was aimed at with their Celeron
processors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What they may be losing,'' he added, ``is the first-mover
advantage _ the opportunity to jump in first with a fully
integrated chip.''
</P>
<P>
   Timna is supposed to reduce the overall cost of building a PC
because it incorporates several features that have previously
required separate chips, including circuitry to generate screen
graphics and to control the exchange of data with the computer's
memory. Via, a Taiwanese chipmaker that offers low-end
Intel-compatible processors, is planning similar integrated chips
for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Intel is that Timna was designed to use a new
type of memory called RDRAM, instead of the SDRAM used in most PCs
today. Intel expected the new format to become the industry
standard by now, but adoption has been slower than expected. RDRAM
remains more expensive than SDRAM, which has made it a poor choice
for low-cost PCs.
</P>
<P>
   So Intel designed a new companion chip called a Memory
Translation Hub, or MTH, to enable Timna and other products
designed for RDRAM to work instead with the older, cheaper SDRAM
format.
</P>
<P>
   The MTH, however, has been plagued with technical glitches. Last
month, for example, Intel was forced to launch a
multimillion-dollar program to recall PC logic boards because of
crashes and freezes caused by the MTH.
</P>
<P>
   Intel had hoped to solve the problem by making quick changes to
the MTH. But yesterday, spokesman Mike Sullivan said the company
has now determined that the chip ``isn't going to meet our quality
standards.'' Instead, engineers will design a new part from the
ground up to perform the same tasks _ a process that will take
months.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5677 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDICARE-DRUGBILL-SFC     06-05 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGBILL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 COMPROMISE MEDICARE DRUG BILL TO BE INTRODUCED  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hoping to break a Capitol Hill deadlock, Rep.
Anna Eshoo will introduce legislation Tuesday to give Medicare
beneficiaries a prescription drug benefit, positioning the
Atherton, Calif., Democrat's bill as a compromise between current
Democratic and Republican proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting drug expenses for seniors is an election year priority
for both parties, with Republicans fearful they'll alienate older
voters if they don't act, while Democrats want to retain control of
an issue that has been a potent political weapon for their party.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no consensus has jelled around any of the several
proposals floated by President Clinton and lawmakers from both
parties. Political observers believe that, although it may be too
late to pass a Medicare drug bill before Congress recesses, Eshoo's
bill has a chance of instigating a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe Anna's bill could be the platform for a
compromise,'' said Walter Moore, a lobbyist for Genentech Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Moore explained that Eshoo, whose Silicon Valley district
includes hundreds of biotech firms, is one of 60 so-called ``New
Democrats'' _ lawmakers who tend to side with business on economic
issues. With only a few weeks left to build a majority, Eshoo could
offer Republicans a palatable proposal, Moore said, plus enough
Democratic votes to inoculate the measure against a presidential
veto.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of the Medicare drug issue begin with the fact that
a third of the nation's 39 million Medicare beneficiaries lack any
prescription drug coverage. Democrats have seized on the issue and
have crafted a series of proposals to placate seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Allen, D-Maine, and Rep. Pete Stark, D-Fremont, Calif.,
have proposed legislation to let Medicare beneficiaries buy drugs
at the price paid by the Veteran's Administration, which would
amount to a discount of at least 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical industry has opposed that approach as a form
of price controls, and the bill will probably go nowhere _ except
into campaign literature aimed at winning votes for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle have
taken a different approach. They want to add a Part D drug benefit
to Medicare. To get the benefit, seniors would pay a
still-to-be-defined premium. In return, Medicare would eventually
pay one-half of their drug expenses up to $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the Clinton and Daschle approaches differ.
Clinton would offer no benefit above $5,000. Daschle's bill would
include what is called a stop-loss provision: Above $5,000,
Medicare would pay all of a Medicare beneficiary's drug expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Eshoo's bill builds on the Clinton and Daschle plans. It
includes the 50-50 coverage up to $5,000 as in the Clinton proposal
and also the stop-loss provision in the Daschle plan.
</P>
<P>
   To this Eshoo adds a feature designed to hold down the benefit's
overall cost, which has been estimated at as much as $200 billion
by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Eshoo would encourage several drug providers to compete in the
Medicare Part D market in each region of the country. Clinton and
Daschle would have just one Medicare drug provider per region. The
difference is subtle but critical, political and industry observers
say.
</P>
<P>
   Drug plans typically try to control costs by developing
formularies, or lists of preferred drugs. Whenever there are two or
more drugs that treat the same condition, drug plan managers go to
each manufacturer and demand a deep discount for choosing that
company's product.
</P>
<P>
   Eshoo's plan would preserve this competitive behavior, whereas
Daschle's and Clinton's single providers would carry all brands and
rely on purchasing power to hold down costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volume purchasing won't work,'' said one biotech industry
lobbyist, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``The only way to get
price breaks is to threaten drug manufacturers with loss of market
share by excluding them from the formulary.''
</P>
<P>
   Eshoo said she added the competitive feature out of concern that
if Congress enacts a Medicare drug benefit and program costs soar,
lawmakers would only come back and institute price controls on
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be disastrous,'' she said. ``It would choke off the
supply of capital for research and development.''
</P>
<P>
   But Eshoo's approach also has drawbacks for Medicare
beneficiaries. What happens if a patient _ accustomed to a certain
manufacturer's drug _ joins a Part D plan that opts for a different
brand of pills?
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of older people have chronic medical conditions for
which they need to take daily medications, and they usually know
which medications work best,'' said John Rother, legislative
director of the American Association of Retired Persons (AARP), in
Washington, D.C. ``Which (brands of) medications end up being
covered by a Medicare drug plan becomes very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course Eshoo's bill won't go far unless it appeals to
Republican lawmakers, who are in a bind over the whole Medicare
drug issue. Until recently, they've backed legislation that would
encourage seniors to join Medicare HMOs, which generally offer some
drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But with more insurers dropping Medicare, Republicans have had
to abandon that position and pledge to come up with a Medicare drug
benefit bill of their own. So far, however, they have not proposed
specific legislation. In any event, they would need Democratic
support and a deal with the Clinton administration to avoid a veto.
</P>
<P>
   The key Republican on the Medicare issue, Rep. Bill Thomas of
Bakersfield, is aware of Eshoo's proposal, but declined to comment
on it until she formally introduces the bill, which is expected to
happen tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Eshoo, meanwhile, is lining up Democratic co-sponsors like Texas
Rep. Martin Frost, the third-ranking member of the House democratic
leadership. Rother, the AARP lobbyist, said Eshoo must show House
Republicans she can deliver enough Democratic support to pass a
bill and get Clinton's signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``A compromise could happen,'' Rother said, ``but we're running
out of time.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
