<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MONEYBAG: SUIT CLAIMS PENNY FOOLISH  &HT;     By ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Q: As an active investor, I have received a fair
number of shareholder class-action notices over the years. Usually,
these come with many words printed in small type that tire the eyes
and brain.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever I bother to fill out and send back these tedious forms
_ with lots of personal information _ I never hear further. I've
never received a check of any size. Should I just throw these
notices in the trash?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: If you never fill out a class-action form again, chances are you
won't lose much. These cases usually are settled _ after
interminable delays _ for only pennies per share. (You may yet get
a response to some of the forms you already have filed.)
</P>
<P>
   The suits serve mainly to enrich class-action lawyers, who stand
to receive perhaps a quarter of the entire settlement. In the case
of large companies, that can add up to hundreds of thousands and
even millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   It's really a question of what you think your time is worth.
Often, the class-action forms require you to dig up and make copies
of ancient brokerage slips that confirm your stock ownership. If
you are willing to do that in hopes of getting back a few bucks
during the second administration of Al Gore or George W. Bush, go
ahead. But I get the impression that you aren't.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Stock Exchange
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: We recently unearthed a stock certificate for American Royalty
Trust dated June 7, 1985. I have been unable to find any
information regarding this company in my Web searches. Do you know
of it, or could you offer any ideas on how I could search for
information?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: According to documents found in the Dow Jones Interactive
database, American Royalty Trust of Houston, which earned royalties
from oil and gas production, was absorbed by Freeport-McMoRan Oil
and Gas Royalty Trust in a series of tender offers ending in 1988.
American Royalty holders received Freeport-McMoRan units rather
than cash.
</P>
<P>
   You should still be able to exchange your certificate with
Freeport-McMoRan. Try writing its shareholder relations department
at 712 Main St., Houston, TX 77002. Or call its transfer agent,
Chase Mellon, at (800) 635-9270.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Credit Conundrum
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I have a credit card with a 13 percent interest charge, and a
total balance of about $30,000. I am tired of paying so much
interest and am considering selling my $18,000 stock portfolio _
which includes $11,000 in capital gains _ to liquidate part of the
debt. Does this make sense?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: It depends on how good an investor you are. If your stock
portfolio is going to increase in value by significantly more than
13 percent annually, then it wouldn't make sense to take money out
of the portfolio to stop the credit-card drain.
</P>
<P>
   You don't say, but I'll assume that your capital gains are all
long term and that your tax bracket is high enough so that you must
pay the maximum 20 percent federal tax on long-term capital gains.
In that case, if you liquidate your $18,000 worth of stocks, you
will be left with roughly $15,000 after federal and state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   If you then use the proceeds to pay off $15,000 worth of your
credit-card debt, you will reduce your annual interest payments by
$1,950.
</P>
<P>
   If, instead, you leave the stocks untouched and they gain in
value by 15 percent during the next 12 months, that will add $2,700
to the value of your portfolio. Even allowing for a combined 25
percent federal and state tax bite on these additional gains, you
will do better under this scenario than you would if you sell your
stocks and pay off debt.
</P>
<P>
   Also keep in mind that you won't ever have to pay capital-gains
taxes if you never sell the stocks _ and instead pass the portfolio
along to your heirs. Their cost basis for tax purposes will be the
value of the stocks on the day you die, rather than your own cost
basis. That's another good reason not to sell the stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The catch here is that you must produce exceptionally strong
investment returns to offset the credit-card interest. Over the
long run, most investors earn less than 13 percent annually on
their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Arthur M. Louis at  &LR; moneybag(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
