<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5681 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DAYTRADE-GAMBLE-SFCHR     06-05 1556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTRADE-GAMBLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DAY TADING TAKES GUTS, QUICK FINGERS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Todd Beardsly doesn't like gambling. During a
recent trip to Las Vegas, he didn't make a single wager, spending
his time instead watching shows and cruising the Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Beardsly related this as he rapidly purchased hundreds of shares
of Ciena Corp., watched the company's stock price move a little
higher and then just as quickly sold off his holding for a tidy
profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a gambler,'' he said, his eyes drifting over four
computer screens providing a constant flow of market data. ``It
just doesn't appeal to me.''
</P>
<P>
   What does appeal to Beardsly is the notion of turning a fast
buck by getting into and out of stocks at warp speed _ an activity
that the former San Jose house builder expects to earn him more
than $1 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Beardsly and the relatively few other successful day traders
like him are definitely the exception. Studies show that the vast
majority will lose their shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite such grim statistics, and despite a market that now
lacks much of the momentum of past years, would-be masters of the
universe continue flocking to join the ranks of day traders.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 100,000 of the approximately 8 million North
Americans who buy and sell stocks online are believed to be at
least part-time day traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``When individuals hear that they can make a lot of money doing
this, they go for it,'' said Brett Trueman, a professor at the
University of California at Berkeley's Haas School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to believe that anyone who day trades will
do well,'' he said. uncx ``But people still tend to focus on the
success stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Las Vegas,'' Trueman added. ``You might hear from
friends who made some money at the casinos, but you seldom hear
from all the rest who didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Casinos are an apt metaphor for day trading. While some gamblers
may have systems or the self-discipline to beat the odds, just
about everyone else who takes a seat at the green-felt tables will
end up being separated from his or her cash over the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   The North American Securities Administrators Association
determined in a recent report that 70 percent of day traders ``will
not only lose, but will almost certainly lose everything they
invest.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Securities and Exchange Commission has warned
that ``most individual investors do not have the wealth, the time
or the temperament to make money and to sustain the devastating
losses that day trading can bring.''
</P>
<P>
   And still they come, lured by hopes of market riches and easy
living.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very risky,'' admitted Jimmy Hsu, manager of the Silicon
Valley branch of ProTrader, which operates a chain of 19
day-trading offices nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you talk to a guy who consistently pulls money out of the
market, and you can see that something is clicking _ they have
it,'' he said. ``It may seem like gambling to those who don't
understand, but not to those who do.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, when asked to arrange access to a day trader
in his shop, Hsu picked Beardsly, who has been with ProTrader for
just six months.
</P>
<P>
   Beardsly, as Hsu would say, has it. After a couple of months of
steady losses, he estimates he now makes an average $5,000 a day.
He is the Bay Area poster boy for day trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never work for a living again after doing this,''
Beardsly said during a brief lull in the action. ``Why would I?''
</P>
<P>
   Overhead, CNBC's market commentary blared from a TV. Other
traders tapped away at keyboards at other workstations. They joked
among themselves, occasionally cursing when a trade went sour.
</P>
<P>
   Beardsly likes the clubhouse atmosphere of the ProTrader office,
where each member puts up at least $50,000 to open a trading
account. He said being surrounded by fellow day traders provides a
support group when things are rough as well as an opportunity to
learn from others.
</P>
<P>
   At Beardsly's side sat his wife, Inna, who is learning the
ropes. She has been trading shares of Applied Materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it does,'' Inna said, clicking on a
description of the company. ``Semiconductors? I didn't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   This is hardly unusual. Most day traders tend not to have a clue
about the stocks they trade, knowing only that certain ticker
symbols can be relied on to post wide swings in value, which is how
a day trader makes money.
</P>
<P>
   Beardsly has been trading Ciena's shares almost since day one.
On a typical day, he might move as many as 30,000 shares in and out
of his account.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know anything about it,'' he said. ``I know
they make communications equipment. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, he entered a typo on his trading screen and instead
of buying Ciena, he mistakenly purchased shares in another company.
Beardsly quickly sold off the mystery company, pocketing a few
hundred dollars in accidental profit.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Not for Amateurs
</P>
<P>
   He makes it look so easy.
</P>
<P>
   And that's part of the danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally fun,'' said Joey Anuff, producer of the online
humor site Suck.com and author of the book ``Dumb Money: Adventures
of a Day Trader.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the more I day traded, the less money I had,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anuff doesn't day trade any more and said he wouldn't advise
others to get into the game. ``It's just too intense for most
amateurs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Split-second financial decisions will make me rich or ruin my
life,'' Anuff writes in his book. ``Can you grasp the agony? True
humiliation is knowing you missed a chance at effortless riches not
a year or a month ago, but five seconds ago.''
</P>
<P>
   A Lonely Profession
</P>
<P>
   That risk of humiliation was what kept Anuff from doing his
thing in a day-trading office. He preferred to wage his own
personal crusade for easy money from the privacy of his San
Francisco apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a deeply personal voyage,'' Anuff observed. ``Who
wants to do that in front of strangers?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most day traders feel the same way. According to the
Electronic Traders Association, an organization of day traders, up
to 10,000 day traders go at it on a full-time basis, usually at a
day-trading shop.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 90,000 others day trade on a part-time basis, often
from home, almost always alone. These are the ones who tend to go
bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are huge distinctions between the people who do this
full time _ the professionals _ and the ones who do it part time,''
said Randy Dale, branch manager of a day-trading office in Santa
Rosa called Market Wise. ``You cannot expect to succeed at this
part-time.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Anuff learned is that a day trader is not, as Beardsly
and others professed, merely ``taking money out of the market.''
Generally speaking, Anuff said, a day trader is going toe to toe
with other online traders, with the race going to the one with the
fastest connection and typing speed.
</P>
<P>
   Speed Does Matter
</P>
<P>
   As such, he noted that day traders who subscribe to services
providing real-time market access _ and pay between $9 and $19 in
commissions per trade _ are always out in front of active traders
using services like E-Trade, Schwab and Fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   Anuff refers to these people as ``E-Tards,'' and expresses
gratitude to them in his book for always being there, one or two
steps behind, ready to snap up whatever the faster day traders are
ready to unload.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speed that day traders have places them at the top of the
food chain,'' said Market Wise's Dale. ``There are a lot of people
attempting to day trade with online brokerage accounts. That's a
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet many people appear to be doing just that. According a
report from investment firm U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray, a record
2.5 million new online brokerage accounts were opened in the first
quarter, and online trading volume surged 69 percent from the
previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   At the biggest online broker, San Francisco's Charles Schwab,
its online customers alone made nearly 300,000 trades per day in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder, then, that Dale sees day traders as being the most
ferocious predators in an increasingly crowded jungle. And these
predators will continue to prey on those who lack the speed to
outrun them.
</P>
<P>
   David and Goliath
</P>
<P>
   ``You could look at it like that,'' Beardsly said. ``But I don't
think of myself as playing against anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he sees himself as being in a constant struggle with
the institutional heavyweights that are buying and offering shares
on a second-by-second basis.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers ticked by on Beardsly's screen almost too fast to
follow. He stared intently, watching for opportunities before him
as quickly as his fingers could strike the keys.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the closing bell rang and trading came to an abrupt
halt. Surveying his performance for the day, Beardsly announced
that he had made $8,366 trading about 115,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   An impressive performance, and one that ProTrader employees
readily concede cannot be easily imitated by others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people calling themselves day traders who
shouldn't call themselves day traders,'' said Hsu, the branch
manager. ``But still they keep trading. Why? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
