<SLUG> BC-SCHWABSIDE-TRADING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 U.S. EMBRACED `INSANE' TRADING IDEA  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the mid-1980s, Philip Berber was a marketing
executive for a British software company doing hush-hush work for
the United Kingdom defense ministry when he experienced what he
calls ``a eureka moment.''
</P>
<P>
   His company had a contract to do submarine spotting, using
advanced technology that bounced signals off the ocean floor. The
company's artificial-intelligence software looked for patterns in
the squiggly lines generated by those signals, repetitions that
could distinguish a menacing enemy craft from, say, a big rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, what if that line were a stock price?,'' recalled
the 41-year-old Berber. ``It was one of those moments that changed
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Berber tried to interest Britain's brokerage firms in the
technology. What he got were some not-very-polite turndowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to one blue-blood firm in the City (London's Wall
Street) and I remember the gentleman's exact words: `Mr. Berber,'
he said, `We would much prefer to use our natural intelligence to
your artificial intelligence.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Discouraged by the reaction, the Dublin-born Berber moved to the
United States, where a small community of like-minded
entrepreneurs, known colloquially as ``quants,'' was pushing the
outer limits of computer technology and finance. Their goal: to
design computer programs that recognized patterns in the price
movements of securities or currency that could predict where those
prices would be at some future moment.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Berber started his first company, Financia, to sell
computer programs based on that idea to money managers. Three years
later, he sold the company to a Texas financial software firm.
</P>
<P>
   After several years working as a quant at a money management
firm, Berber had another eureka moment.
</P>
<P>
   He was invited in 1995 to one of the first day-trading shops,
located in a Houston shopping mall. In those days, no stock
brokerage offered price-scanning software that could also carry out
trades.
</P>
<P>
   At the Houston firm, a customer checked moving stock prices on a
computer. If the customer wanted to trade, he shouted out the order
to a registered stockbroker sitting across the table.
</P>
<P>
   Berber decided to start a company, named CyBerCorp, that would
combine brokerage operations with price-scanning software, allowing
customers to directly access the market.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, where few imagined that computers could predict
prices in financial markets, ``I felt insane,'' Berber confided.
But here Berber turned his edge-of-the-envelope insights into
moneymaking businesses. In the United States, he said, ``I was no
longer insane.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0482 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5686 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SCHWAB-DIRECT-SFCHRON     06-05 1459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-DIRECT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ORDINARY INVESTORS MAY GET DIRECT MARKET ACCESS  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Philip Berber stares at a PC screen filled with
an array of color-coded flashing lights. Stock prices pop up, then
disappear, next to the names of dozens of wholesale brokers trying
to buy or sell shares. Charts monitoring the market move at
dizzying speed.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like a computer game for 14-year-olds with short
attention spans. It's actually a popular stock-trading program for
active traders, full-time stock jockeys who buy and sell dozens of
times a day. Market experts say it represents the future of online
trading for ordinary investors.
</P>
<P>
   To Berber, founder and chairman of CyBerCorp, the Austin, Texas,
electronic brokerage that offers the program to investors, the
software is nothing less than a weapon of war.
</P>
<P>
   He sees the stock market as a bloody pit where the naive are
mauled and only the strong survive. He has designed CyBerCorp's
program to turn a computer into the control panel of a finely tuned
fighting machine that scans the entire market for the best prices,
grabbing trades before the market big boys step in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are like a Jedi warrior,'' said Berber, an intense,
bearded Irishman turned Texan. ``This enables you to fight for your
own stock order in among the professional traders.''
</P>
<P>
   CyBerCorp and a handful of rival online brokers are unraveling
the tangled web that is the stock market - where hundreds of
wholesale brokers and computerized networks quote a continually
changing stream of prices.
</P>
<P>
   By creating a unified, more-efficient market, their technology
promises to make it easier in the not-too-distant future for
average investors to trade shares at the prices they want, while
making it tougher for market pros to fleece the little guys.
</P>
<P>
   What firms like CyBerCorp are doing is bringing to individual
investors an advantage that only professionals sitting on Wall
Street trading desks previously enjoyed _ the ability to see the
prices every market participant is quoting at any point in time,
nimbly darting in and out to trade.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, such ``direct-access`` technology is only of interest
to a small group of full-time speculators, the so-called day
traders of popular lore, who may pay several hundred dollars a
month to get this kind of market data.
</P>
<P>
   For such traders, who sometimes hold on to stocks for just a few
minutes, price differences of a few pennies per share could mean
the difference between profit and loss. They have fueled the growth
of small brokers that offer advanced price-scanning technology,
such as CyBerCorp, Tradescape and Tradecast.
</P>
<P>
   Now, market experts say, that technology is about to move into
the mainstream. Big-name online brokers are looking closely at
direct access and advanced market-scanning programs, trying to
figure out how to adapt them to the mass market. That interest was
highlighted earlier this year when Charles Schwab Corp., the No. 1
online broker, bought CyBerCorp for $487 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hyperactive traders are defining the future of the
marketplace,'' said Rob Hegerty, analyst with Massachusetts
consulting firm TowerGroup. ``As day traders force the market to be
more efficient, down the road, that will affect the average
investor.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this does not mean millions of online investors will
suddenly want to know what a wholesale dealer in Chicago or an
electronic network in New York are selling Microsoft for. Quite the
contrary, most customers will be content to specify the price they
are willing to pay to buy shares, or willing to accept to sell
shares, and let their brokers do the hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not going to be a huge outcry of demand for this,''
said Credit Suiss First Boston analyst James Marks.
</P>
<P>
   But mainstream brokers are likely to use CyBerCorp-style
software in ways customers never see to ensure orders are executed
at the best possible price. ``It will be transparent, (but) they
will benefit,'' said Jim Hackley, a Schwab official who was
recently named CyBerCorp's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, CyBerCorp and its rivals use ``intelligent
order-routing'' software that not only scans prices throughout the
market, but also instantaneously figures out which broker is most
likely to fill the order. ``It should provide better execution,''
said TowerGroup's Hegerty.
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate the advantage of the software, it's important to
understand the current chaotic state of the stock market. Right
now, when a customer clicks in a trade, an online broker routes the
order to any of hundreds of destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Orders for popular Nasdaq stocks at set prices _ so-called limit
orders _ generally go to computerized networks called ECNs. Orders
involving thinly traded or New York Stock Exchange shares, as well
as ``market'' orders with no set price, usually go to wholesale
brokerages called specialists or marketmakers.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, under Security and Exchange Commission rules,
computerized networks and wholesale brokers are supposed to use
computer links to scan the entire market to find the best prices
for customers.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't always work out that way. Bottlenecks in the
system and the vagaries of broker behavior mean that customers
don't always get the best deal.
</P>
<P>
   For example, brokers are required to fill orders on a
first-come, first-served basis. But the SEC says some brokers
ignore the rule in order to take care of their best customers
first.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, retail online brokers have sweetheart arrangements
with specific wholesale dealers to which they give preferential
treatment. For example, Schwab, which owns the nation's
second-largest market-making firm, sends the bulk of market orders
from its customers to that subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   In a practice that is legal, but arguably corrupt, market-making
dealers pay retail brokers a kickback to send market orders their
way.
</P>
<P>
   Marketmakers earn their living from the gap between what they
pay for shares and what they sell them for, so an order that can be
executed at whatever price they set is valuable to them. Needless
to say, there is little incentive to pass the order off if a better
price turns up elsewhere in the market.
</P>
<P>
   For online brokerage customers, the current system often
produces unfilled limit orders that could have been executed and
trades that get done at less-than-optimal prices.
</P>
<P>
   On the limit-order side, federal officials have considered
cutting through the chaos by routing all orders through a single
computer network, nicknamed CLOB for central limit order book. But
some market pros maintain that CyBerCorp-style order routing
software accomplishes the same task by collating price information
from all market participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have a virtual central limit order book,'' said
Matt Andresen, president of Island, the No. 2 ECN. ``And there will
constantly be better and better versions.``
</P>
<P>
   The issue now is how quickly online brokers will adopt
CyBerCorp-style order-routing technology instead of directing
orders to traditional partners. ``That would end the conflict of
interest between the broker and investor'' inherent in the broker's
relationship with marketmakers, said Gary Craft, an analyst at
Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab bought CyBerCorp to get its hands on technology demanded
by active traders, one of the most profitable customer segments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, market watchers point out that Schwab and its rivals
benefit hugely from the current system. Schwab in particular could
lose tens of millions in profit at its market-making subsidiary if
CyBerCorp-style technology became the norm for less-active
investors as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Integrating CyBerCorp technology would direct order flow away
from Schwab's (marketmaker),'' Craft said. ``Schwab has everything
to lose. It could cannibalize the existing preferential
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab now finds itself in the awkward situation of controlling
a technology that directly threatens its profits. Company officials
say only that they intend to keep all order-handling systems in
place for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Schwab wanted to, though, no one thinks it could
successfully limit CyBerCorp technology to the active trader
community while keeping the old system in place for the masses.
Rivals will soon get their own hands on the technology, which is
likely to spread throughout the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Craft, for one, thinks the wisest course is to use the
technology to attract customers. ``I think a marketing strategy
will soon surround it. I can see someone advertising `We use
technology to get the best price for you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
