<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO FAILS TO GET SUPPORT OF INDEPENDENCE PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With REFORM-PARTY) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, the Republican Senate nominee, failed Monday
night to win the nomination of the Independence Party, the New York
state wing of the Reform Party. The development could cost him
votes by splitting support among the candidates opposed to Hillary
Rodham Clinton, the Democratic nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Two candidates within the Independence Party received the most
votes Monday at its nominating convention in Albany, N.Y., and the
party authorized a primary on Sept. 12 to determine which one would
be listed on its ballot. The party is torn by the kind of
infighting and factionalism that its national organization is
facing.
</P>
<P>
   The top vote-getter, Jeff Graham, a radio talk show host who was
mayor of Watertown for two terms, said he decided to run only after
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani dropped out of the race last month. Graham,
who said he believed that Giuliani would have been a sure bet for
the Independence Party nomination, received 63 percent of the vote
from the party's 266 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   In the runoff, he faces Jeff Beller of Westerlo, near Albany,
the president of an advocacy group for alternative fuels, who
received 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a tight race, the third-party lines in New York state are
considered crucial. The Independence line can draw more than
100,000 voters. Lazio also won the Conservative Party endorsement
and Clinton the Liberal Party endorsement last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In the week since his nomination as the Republican candidate,
Lazio has faced sticky questions about a possible association with
the Independence Party because Pat Buchanan, who has been accused
of making anti-Semitic remarks, stands a good chance of winning the
presidential nomination of the Reform Party. That means Lazio's
name would have been on the same ticket, had he received the
nomination Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who had said that Buchanan was divisive, insisted late
last month that he would still accept the nomination while
expressing clear support for George W. Bush, the Republican
candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in an appearance before the Independence Party last
month, denounced Buchanan and refused any support from the party.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for the Lazio campaign noted the presence of a number
of Democratic Party operatives at the Independence Party
convention, leading some to conclude that Clinton's surrogates had
helped engineer Lazio's loss to divide her opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, Clinton's campaign spokesman, acknowledged that
aides were present at the Independence convention but would not
comment on what, if any, active role they played. ``They were
observing,'' he said. ``They were watching democracy in action.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham said he believed that Lazio's poor showing had less to do
with his comments about Buchanan than his association with Jack
Essenberg, the Independence Party's former chairman, who gave up
his position last week after a court fight resulted in Lenora
Fulani, an avowed Marxist, and Frank M. MacKay wresting control of
the party. The two have aligned themselves with Buchanan. Graham,
who is backed by MacKay, said there was a perception among
delegates that Lazio was cultivating support from Essenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lazio was negotiating through Essenberg, and that didn't play
well with the state committee,'' said Sarah Lyons, a party
spokeswoman. ``He didn't have the sense to realize he was dealing
with the wrong person.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Flood, a spokesman for Lazio, said he was not aware of
contacts Lazio made with the party. ``He respects the party's
process,'' Flood said. ``It was the delegates' decision, and what
they decide to do is not have any major-party involvement. We
respect that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lazio finished fourth, with 1.3 percent of the vote, behind Abe
Hirschfeld, the eccentric Manhattan real estate developer and
perennial candidate for public office, who won 3 percent of the
delegates' votes.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides played down the turn of events Monday, saying he
had not aggressively sought the nomination, though he would have
welcomed it. Sen. Charles Schumer, a Democrat who also ran on the
Independence Party line in 1998, received 109,000 votes from the
party in his 10 percentage point victory over Alfonse D'Amato in
1998. There are about 170,000 people enrolled in the Independence
Party.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to running against Lazio and a candidate from the
Independence Party, Clinton, viewed as the front-runner, is also
expected to face opposition from the Right to Life Party. The party
is holding a primary on Sept. 12 between Louis Wein, its candidate
for governor in 1990, and John Adofope, a telephone company
engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Independence Party officials said their candidate would campaign
on a platform similar to that of the national Reform Party, which
supports changes intended to make politics more accessible to
everyday people, like same-day voter registration and a ban on
unregulated financial contributions to political parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
