<HEADER>
A5689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-YANKS-EXPOS-NYT &LR;      06-05 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE IS FAR FROM PERFECT IN MONTREAL
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Making the final out in David Cone's perfect game
last year ranked among the greatest moments of his career, Orlando
Cabrera said at the time. But slamming a game-winning homer off
Cone Monday night probably ranks a little higher on his personal
scale.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on short notice after shoulder stiffness sidelined
Ramiro Mendoza, Cone was pounded for six runs in six innings,
including Cabrera's tiebreaking three-run homer in the sixth, as
Montreal dumped the Yankees, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 30-23, Montreal 31-23.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch was unable to play because of the recurring
problem in his left forearm. His status will be evaluated day to
day.
</P>
<P>
   Cone briefly considered a career in journalism before opting for
a more lucrative profession. But he served in the role of reporter
Monday afternoon, after accompanying Mendoza on the team bus to
Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza is reserved, but what Cone ascertained in their
conversation was that his teammate's right shoulder felt stiff.
Cone walked into the office of manager Joe Torre, delivered the
news about Mendoza and volunteered to pitch in his place. ``Strap
it on and go,'' Cone said minutes later, walking through the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos hit him immediately. With Montreal down by 2-0 in the
bottom of the first, Rondell White doubled before Cone hung a
slider to Vladimir Guerrero. Montreal's right fielder attacked the
ball with ferocity, seemingly rising out of his shoes as he swung
viciously. Estimated distance: 436 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Cone fell behind in the count continually, throwing a ball with
his first pitch to 14 of the first 19 batters, and the count was
2-0 when Lee Stevens singled in the third to score Guerrero, who
had doubled.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied at that point, 3-3, only because of a
base-running gaffe by the Yankees and their serial failures with
runners on base. Ricky Ledee opened the game with a home run and
the Yankees scored another run in the inning, but they should have
had two more. Scott Brosius hit a two-out single with the bases
loaded, Bernie Williams trotting home with one run, Tino Martinez
rounding third. But center fielder Peter Bergeron threw to third
base to nail Jorge Posada _ and the tag was applied an instant
before Martinez ambled across home, meaning the inning was over
before Martinez stepped on the plate.
</P>
<P>
   That was the first of many scoring chances blown by the Yankees,
who stranded 35 runners in three games over the weekend in Atlanta.
They loaded the bases in the third and couldn't score, left one
runner in scoring position in the fourth and stranded two more in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Cone surrendered a single and hit a batter with a pitch with one
out in the sixth inning, and Cabrera came to bat. He had no chance
against Cone's swerving slider last July, something he has probably
been reminded of dozens of times, if he watches television. There
is that recurrent image of Cabrera popping up toward third and Cone
dropping to his knees as Brosius makes the final catch.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone's slider is not sharp these days, and when he fell
behind in the count, 2-0, to Cabrera in the sixth inning Monday
night, his pitch selection was limited. He threw a fastball,
Cabrera crushed it and paused as he watched the flight of the ball,
his eyes darting for an instant in Cone's direction. Redemption.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 23rd hit against Cone with runners in scoring
position this year; he surrendered 34 during the entire 1999
season. Cone said early in the season that he was searching for
answers, and now he is 1-6 after 12 starts and the search goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said the Yankees' trainers did not think Mendoza's injury
was serious, that he might miss the next few days and then return.
Mendoza has been a versatile pitcher for the Yankees, bouncing from
the rotation to the bullpen, but he has been unavailable to pitch
several times in the last few years because of stiffness in his
shoulder _ something that will undoubtedly be noted, along with his
record of success, by teams considering making a deal for him.
Teams looking at possible trades for Mendoza have been trailing the
right-hander, including the Kansas City Royals (Johnny Damon),
Cincinnati Reds (Dmitri Young) and the Houston Astros (Moises
Alou).
</P>
<P>
   The change will jumble the Yankees' pitching rotation. Cone was
supposed to pitch Tuesday, and must be replaced. Ted Lilly, one of
the pitchers acquired from Montreal in the Hideki Irabu deal, was
scratched from his scheduled start Monday evening in Ottawa, where
he was to pitch for Triple-A Columbus; the Yankees could opt to
promote him, or perhaps start the veteran Mike Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez is scheduled to pitch here Wednesday, which
means that Roger Clemens, Andy Pettitte and Cone could be in line
to start against the Mets at Yankee Stadium this weekend. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
