<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES' 3-RUN SEVENTH ENDS HAMPTON'S WINNING STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Hampton had dirt caked on his left knee, more
dirt on his right knee as he stomped around the mound like an angry
pitcher in the seventh inning Monday night. He had tamed the
Baltimore Orioles all evening, but things suddenly had changed and
Hampton was desperately trying to keep the Mets ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But Hampton failed. The Orioles blitzed the left-hander for
three runs in the seventh and defeated the Mets, 4-2, on a blustery
night at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton had throttled Baltimore on one run and five hits and
seemed to be cruising toward his fifth consecutive victory, but he
crumbled and could not hold a one-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   See him pitch, see him hit and see him run. That is the Hampton
the Mets always wanted, the feisty pitcher who refuses to give in
to hitters, who plays like a shortstop and who forces anyone
watching the game to stare right at him. That is where the action
will usually be when Hampton is pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The action was all around Hampton in the seventh Monday night
and he could not stop it from turning a game that was his into a
game that became Mike Mussina's, ending Hampton's winning streak as
well as Baltimore's five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton trudged to the mound in the seventh within nine outs of
another victory, but he never made it out of the inning. It started
with B.J. Surhoff's booming homer to left center field off an 0-1
fastball that tied the score, 2-2. The blast caused Hampton to
drift off the mound, turn toward center and cringe.
</P>
<P>
   After a single and a force out, Hampton walked Rich Amaral to
put runners on first and second. Hampton wound up tumbling to the
dirt after Ball 4 because he thought Mike Piazza might have to
unleash a throw to second to possibly get the runner, Mussina, who
was going on the 3-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   When Mike Bordick punched a single to center that knocked in
pinch-runner Delino DeShields to put the Orioles in front, 3-2,
Hampton was aggravated about surrendering the lead and he caught
Piazza's return throw with his bare left hand.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton struck out Jeff Conine for the second out and jammed
Albert Belle with a fastball for what could have been the third
out. But Belle was strong enough to bloop the ball over first base
for a run-scoring double that made it, 4-2, and ended Hampton's
night.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who had been 4-0 with a 1.17 earned run average in his
past five starts, gave up four earned runs and nine hits in 6 2/3
innings. Mussina yielded two runs and three hits in the second, but
tamed the Mets on three hits over his other five innings in winning
for only the third time in 13 starts.
</P>
<P>
   The game had started well for Hampton. With two out and no one
on in the second, Melvin Mora bunted along the third-base line. Cal
Ripken Jr. made a nice barehanded pickup and an accurate
off-balance throw, but Mora beat it for a single. Normally, it
would be foolish for a No. 8 batter to attempt to bunt for a hit.
Not when Hampton is batting ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton is not like other pitchers because he is not an
automatic out. He smacked a grounder that nicked off a diving
Ripken's glove and trickled into left-center field, allowing Mora
to breeze into third and extending Hampton's hitting streak to five
games. He is 11 for 31 (.355) this season.
</P>
<P>
   Next up was the rookie Jason Tyner who had raved about Mussina
and reminded himself not to get psyched out when batting against
the outstanding right-hander he was used to seeing on television.
Mussina jumped ahead of Tyner with two quick strikes, but Tyner
sliced the next pitch to left field for a single that put the Mets
ahead, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Mussina was the one who was psyched out because he walked
Derek Bell on four pitches to load the bases and then fell behind
Edgardo Alfonzo, 3-0. Mussina threw a strike and Alfonzo fouled off
two pitches as the count hung at 3-2, but Mussina unleashed another
ball to force in a run and make it, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles, who botched a bases-loaded chance in the first when
Charles Johnson hit into an inning-ending double play, countered
against Hampton in the third. Amaral singled, stole second and
eventually scored on Belle's two-out single to right. But Hampton
stranded two more runners and maintained a 2-1 lead by retiring
Johnson. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
