<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREESERVE-T-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS REPORTED ON GERMAN BID FOR BRITISH INTERNET SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain's largest Internet service provider, Freeserve
PLC, is in talks to be acquired by Deutsche Telekom's Internet arm,
T-Online International, according to executives close to the
discussions. Freeserve, not yet two years old, was the first in
Britain to market an Internet service with no online charges, a
business model that has been widely imitated.
</P>
<P>
   Freeserve and its parent, the Dixons Group PLC, a British
electronics retailer, have held preliminary talks with other
interested parties, including Terra Networks, the Internet unit of
Telefonica, along with the British cable company NTL Inc. and
British Telecommunications PLC, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   While the executives stressed that a deal was not yet imminent,
they said T-Online had expressed the most interest in Freeserve.
The two companies have discussed how much T-Online might pay for
Freeserve, but have yet to reach any agreement over price, the
executives said. Freeserve's current market capitalization is
almost $8 billion. The executives also cautioned that the companies
could decide to abandon the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Dixons, which owns 80 percent of Freeserve, formed it about a
year and half ago as a side bet to get into the Internet business.
It stunned competitors by quickly becoming Britain's most heavily
used Internet access provider, displacing AOL U.K., a unit of AOL
Europe, then a joint venture of America Online and the German media
giant Bertelsmann.
</P>
<P>
   Freeserve's main innovation was to attract customers by not
charging a monthly subscription fee. In contrast to the United
States, where Internet access over a telephone line is relatively
inexpensive, users in Britain, as in most other European countries,
pay by the minute for local phone calls, in addition to the charge
from the Internet access provider.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of charging a subscription fee, Freeserve makes money by
sharing a percentage of the revenue generated by the cost of a
user's telephone call with the phone company. Freeserve also
derives revenue from advertising and electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   A deal with Freeserve would be a major boon for T-Online as it
tries to create a company that reaches beyond Germany to compete
with the likes of Terra Networks, which just acquired the
U.S.-based Internet company Lycos and also has operations in Latin
America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5696 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-JACKSON-AUDIT-KAN &LR;      06-05 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-AUDIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAIL ANNEX OVERRUNS, PRISONER RELEASE PROGRAM CRITICIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLENN E. RICE and MARK MORRIS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Jackson County's
legislative auditor on Monday harshly criticized millions of
dollars in cost overruns for construction of the new jail annex,
and the methods used to determine release of inmates to prevent
crowding.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among its other findings, the information criticized County
Executive Katheryn Shields, saying she had failed to include $3.4
million in her initial budget for furnishing the facility, buying
new information systems and relocating the Kansas City Board of
Election Commissioners, which was moved to make way for the annex.
</P>
<P>
   Shields' critics called for audits of the cost overruns and
release programs last year. They said Monday that the findings
showed a pattern of financial mismanagement and inattention to
public safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many dangerous criminals are released from the new jail
annex because of incompetence and mismanagement of the Shields
administration,'' said Victor Callahan, chairman of the county
Legislature. ``Another truth is that after the expenditure of $24.2
million dollars, the new jail is seriously over budget and
dangerously operated under capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Callahan said the Legislature would review the audits and press
Shields to make reforms. As for the cost overruns, he said the
Legislature would have to appropriate additional money if needed.
</P>
<P>
   The jail annex, which opened in July, was built to comply with
federal court orders to ease crowding. The project, which was
planned to add 196 beds, initially was budgeted at $18.7 million.
But the jail annex opened several months behind schedule and nearly
$6 million over budget.
</P>
<P>
   Before the audits were released Monday, Shields emphasized that
the jail annex had cost less than a $30 million version proposed by
her predecessor and had saved taxpayers millions in construction
and operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you read this (the audit) fairly, this is not a negative
audit,'' Shields said. ``They brought up some good points, but they
were not earthshaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Shields laid some of the blame for budget problems on the
Legislature and suggested the audits were politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative Auditor Kelly Markham Stegall, a lawyer and
certified public accountant, works for the Legislature and not the
county executive. And over Shields' objections, Missouri Auditor
Claire McCaskill's office assisted Stegall in the study of cost
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, the county should ensure that the budgets for
large construction projects are prepared in a detailed manner
during the planning phase of the project,'' Stegall wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Though the county's jail construction fund has about $800,000
left to meet outstanding bills, Stegall noted those could exceed $3
million. They include claims from an architect and a construction
company.
</P>
<P>
   Stegall also criticized $510,000 paid to contractors with
handwritten checks that would not have been recorded in the
county's electronic accounting system had she not found them last
August.
</P>
<P>
   Shields agreed that the checks should have been posted to the
electronic system on the day they were issued, and that steps were
being taken to correct that situation.
</P>
<P>
   Though the jail is under a federal court order to limit
crowding, Stegall said administrators should consider operating
nearer its 800-bed capacity, rather than its current limit of 725
inmates. By working with the higher limit, administrators would
have to make fewer choices about which inmates to release, Stegall
said.
</P>
<P>
   She also urged Shields to institute a stronger case-by-case
review of inmates before release to ensure public safety. Stegall
pointed to the case of an accused methamphetamine manufacturer who,
despite several arrests for drug possession and failing to appear
in court, was released.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current...system results in individuals being released
that have been judged to be a potential threat to the safety of the
community,'' Stegall wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Pam Taylor, the jail's population control
coordinator, noted that the system Stegall reviewed was seldom used
but had been accepted by the federal judge overseeing the jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is intended as a rarely used last resort, not a daily
administrative tool,'' Taylor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The system used on a daily basis allows for a detailed review of
each prisoner before release, Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan urged Taylor to keep better records on the number of
inmates who failed to make court appearances after release. Stegall
had noted that the county kept no such records.
</P>
<P>
   ``The county needs to start keeping track of the
failure-to-appear rate,'' Callahan said. ``How many more headlines
do we have to read? How many more victims have to be killed?''
</P>
<P>
   Shields said the courts, not her office, were responsible for
keeping those statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does a great disservice for the chairman (Callahan) to
paint a picture of danger when it is inaccurate,'' Shields said.
``It is very unfortunate and frustrating that he would choose to do
that.'' ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
