u k BC-EDIT-PARENTAL-RIGHTS-     06-05 0258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PARENTAL-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PROTECTING PARENTAL RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 6:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has wisely affirmed a ruling by the Washington
state Supreme Court that a state statute goes too far in permitting
courts to grant grandparents visiting rights over a parent's
objections. The case, Troxel vs. Granville, raises the question of
whether and when states can intrude on parental rights to recognize
other family ties. It has been closely watched because family
structures are changing, and grandparents and other adults are
taking on parental roles.
</P>
<P>
   All 50 states allow for grandparent visitation in some form. But
the Washington law, as Justice Sandra Day O'Connor noted in her
plurality opinion, is ``breathtakingly broad'' in that it allowed
``any person'' at ``any time'' to get visitation rights if the
court decided that visitation would ``serve the best interest of
the child.'' The court found that the law as applied in this case
unconstitutionally infringed on the fundamental parental rights of
a mother named Tommie Granville. A state judge ordered that
Granville's daughters be required to visit their paternal
grandparents without giving ``special weight'' to Granville's
views. The judge in effect substituted his judgment for hers.
</P>
<P>
   The court did not set a fixed rule for determining the
constitutionality of all visitation statutes. O'Connor said,
cautiously, that constitutionality turns on how any standard is
applied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
