<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5699 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-ESCAPE-FORD-KAN &LR;      06-05 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESCAPE-FORD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD, CLAYCOMO PLANT ARE EXPECTING ESCAPE TO BE A WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ At Kansas City's auto
show earlier this year, an older man who was a Buick loyalist was
checking out the Ford Escape, the automaker's new small
sport-utility vehicle being built at the Claycomo, Mo., plant.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He confessed he had been planning to buy another passenger car,
but the new SUV had him reconsidering.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. is banking on that type of thinking as it
prepares to launch the latest in its strong line of SUVs. The
Escape will represent Ford's entry into small SUVs, a niche of the
market that has been dominated by Honda, followed far behind by
DaimlerChrysler and Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   Honda is the perennial leader in small-SUV sales. Last year it
sold more than 120,000 CRVs. But early consumer reaction to the
Escape has analysts predicting that Ford eventually could overtake
Honda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect the Escape to become the segment sales leader, taking
the top spot away from the CRV,'' said Tad Malesh, director of
North American sales forecasting for J.D. Power and Associates, an
automotive consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the Escape's entry into the market could be
better. Gasoline prices are reaching record highs around the
country, interest rates are on the rise, consumer confidence is
slipping and sales of the huge SUVs are off. The effect of these
factors on overall SUV sales, however, remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   SUV sales surpassed 3 million last year. Bigger SUVs are not
selling as well through the first part of 2000. However, the Ford
Explorer, the country's top-selling SUV, continues to outpace last
year's sales levels.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ford has been building Escapes at Claycomo for the past
several weeks, its official launch has not occurred and it
continues to receive fine-tuning on quality issues.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has said Escape will have a late spring or early summer
launch and will show up in dealer showrooms in August and
September. Union officials have indicated the launch could be as
early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   When Ford rolls out the Escape, it will culminate a two-year
process that began when Ford Chief Executive Jac Nasser announced
in July 1998 that the Escape would be built at Claycomo.
</P>
<P>
   Ford reportedly invested as much as $750 million in the Claycomo
facility in preparation for the Escape, adding 122,000 square feet
to the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Although union officers contend that the Escape has resulted in
the addition of several hundred production jobs, Ford officials
insist there has been little net gain of jobs at the plant. The
plant employs about 5,200 people, including 4,900 hourly employees.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Missouri aided Ford in its decision to bring the
new SUV to Claycomo. An enterprise zone was expanded that provided
a $16.6 million tax break, according to a spokeswoman with the
Missouri Department of Economic Development. In addition, Missouri
gave Ford training funds totaling $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ford already builds the top-selling F-series pickup at Claycomo,
where workers put in overtime as a way of life just to keep up with
demand. But Claycomo's passenger-car line that the Escape is
replacing has not been as busy during the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring the reliable-but-generic Tempo-Topaz models, Ford
launched the much-ballyhooed Ford Contour and Mercury Mystique in
1994 at Claycomo. After an extended period of hype proclaiming
Contour to be the ``world'' car with a $6 billion price-tag to
develop it, Ford saw Contour sales fall far short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   While the Contour received solid reviews for its quality,
critics said it was too similar, particularly in price, to the
popular Ford Taurus. The Contour suffered as Ford car buyers either
chose the Escort or Taurus, leaving Contour without a solid market
niche.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Contour-Mystique line was introduced during a
period in which Americans increasingly were turning away from
passenger cars and flocking to pickups and SUVs. The result was
that Ford's employees who built the Contour-Mystique spent several
weeks of the year off the job.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ford is replacing its passenger-car line at Claycomo with
the Escape and its Japanese version, the Mazda Tribute. Is Ford
making the same mistake again at Claycomo, producing another SUV as
the SUV market matures and gas prices surge? And is the Escape too
similar to the popular Explorer?
</P>
<P>
   Auto industry analysts and observers say no on both counts,
applauding Ford's entry into the small SUV market, and say they
consider the timing to be right.
</P>
<P>
   The more than 3 million SUVs sold last year represented a 15
percent jump from 1998. The American appetite for SUVs seemingly
has been insatiable the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ford said last month that it would cut production of
the Excursion, its biggest SUV, by 25 percent. That had some
observers predicting that with the rise in gas prices, the SUV
market had peaked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to see everybody look at (the Excursion) as an
indication that consumers no longer want SUVs'' said Malesh of J.D.
Power in Agoura Hills, Calif. ``There are some signs that the SUV
market is maturing, but there remain pockets of growth and pockets
where there's a slowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Malesh said there initially was a pent-up demand for the
Excursion when it was introduced late last year. People who could
afford it wanted the latest and biggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's somewhat of a faddish segment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Malesh said rising gas prices are making the
biggest SUVs less attractive.
</P>
<P>
   All the better, he said, for the Escape, a small SUV that gets
24 miles per gallon on the highway. Meanwhile, the sale of small
SUVs continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hot part of the market is what Ford is moving into with
the Escape,'' he said. ``There's no question that this vehicle has
a tremendous future in the long-term picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford also is upgrading the Explorer, adding a third row of
seats. That will provide some separation from the Escape in terms
of features and pricing, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Explorer is going where the Dodge Durango is,'' said David
Cole, director of the Office for the Study of Automotive
Transportation at the University of Michigan. ``Ford certainly
doesn't want the Escape buyer to be somebody leaving the Explorer
or Expedition. They've done their internal analysis. Based on
Ford's historical success with SUVs, the Escape is going to be a
strong product.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford estimates that 70 percent of Escape buyers will be people
who previously owned passenger cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think a significant majority will be new customers,'' said
Stu Smith, the Escape brand manager for Ford. ``It's really going
to fill a need for people who have not purchased an SUV yet because
vehicles like the Explorer are too large.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Ford's selling points for the Escape will be that it is
being built on a car platform, giving it the driving
characteristics of an automobile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to handle like a car, and it's going to be more
fuel-efficient than most SUVs,'' said George Magliano, director of
research for the WEFA Group in New York. ``It's got the best of
both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sight, co-owner of Bob Sight Ford in Lee's Summit, said he
has seven of his 10 Escapes already sold in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The Escape will come in both front-wheel and four-wheel drive
models, but the car dealers expect the front-wheel version to be
very popular in this region.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get all the advantages of the front-wheel drive without
paying extra for the 4x4,'' said Mike Gerlt, new-car manager at Bob
Sight Ford. ``You get maybe one major snowfall a year here, so
people are looking for the front-wheel drive. It really fits this
environment and this area.''
</P>
<P>
   The Escape's front-wheel drive model begins at $18,160, and the
four-wheel drive begins at $19,785.
</P>
<P>
   Malesh of J.D. Power said Ford has priced the product
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Power is estimating that Ford will produce about 235,000
Escapes and Tributes in calendar year 2001. If the consulting firm
is accurate, the days of downtime for Ford's second line at
Claycomo may be a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reaction from consumers from the auto-show circuit was very
positive,'' said Jeff Schuster, J.D. Power's senior manager of
forecasting in Troy, Mich. ``We're expecting good (production)
volumes out of this program.'' ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
