<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LUXEMBOURG-MASQUERADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A DANGEROUS MASQUERADE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 6:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone watching the hostage crisis in Luxembourg last week would
applaud the release of nursery school children and their caregivers
after a crazed gunman was shot by local police. But by using a
camera crew as camouflage for their gun and by shooting the suspect
who thought he was getting ready to give a television interview,
the Luxembourg police have now made it more dangerous for other
journalists to do their jobs and thus harder for them to get news
of critical importance.
</P>
<P>
   The agonizing 30-hour incident began when a man described as
psychologically troubled by Luxembourg police stormed into a
village day care center, taking 37 children and three teachers
hostage. When the gunman demanded time on television to air his
grievances about losing custody of his children, police borrowed
equipment from Radio Television Luxemburg to use as cover. They
then shot and disabled the gunman as he approached the mock crew
for his appointed ``interview.''
</P>
<P>
   While police celebrated the happy outcome, many experienced
journalists were understandably horrified at the way they went
about it. In their business of gathering information, journalists
must be armed only with the tools of their reporting trade, and
their sole task is to transmit as much truth and reality as
possible to their public audience. The singularity of that mission
is what makes it crucial that journalists are solely journalists,
not secret government agents or undercover police. Any confusion,
even for a good cause, can expand into more danger in the future
for people who already range across some of the most dangerous
territory in the world _ trying to convince rebel armies, for
example, that a press badge is a sign of neutrality, the camera is
not a threat and the reporter is not armed. Any erosion of
journalistic neutrality could limit the wide range of news and
information we have learned to expect from the international media.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
