<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS TAKE A 3-1 ADVANTAGE OVER TIRED AND DEMORALIZED STARS  

</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Rookies are supposed to bide their time in the Stanley
Cup playoffs, settling for little ice time and minor roles. The
pressure of the championship round, especially, is supposed to be
for battle-tested veterans who are proven through years of
experience.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have plenty of veterans, and they played well again
Monday night. But two significant goals were scored by rookies,
John Madden and Brian Rafalski. Both contributed to a 3-1 victory
that left the Devils one victory from the Stanley Cup. In the
four-of-seven games series, they lead the defending champions by 3
games to 1. The other goal, the first of a stunning comeback, was
scored by Sergei Brylin.
</P>
<P>
   The teams will not play Game 5 until Thursday night in
Continental Arena. By that time, the Devils should have a better
sense of the condition of Jason Arnott, their best forward in this
tournament. Late in the game, while the Devils were on a power
play, Arnott was hit in the face by Derian Hatcher, the big Dallas
defenseman and captain who is known for rough play.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott, walking unsteadily, had to be helped to the locker room
after Hatcher's hit Arnott in the head. Although it was difficult
to immediately ascertain the point of contact, it appeared that
both Hatcher's hands and the butt end of his stick came up to meet
Arnott. Curiously, although the incident occurred in full few of a
capacity crowd, no penalty was called by either referee, Kerry
Fraser or Bill McCreary.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' domination in the third period was thorough and
breathtaking. They outshot the Stars by 31-17 in the game and by
15-4 in the third period. The Stars, an older team, looked
exhausted and demoralized, despite having opened the third period
with a 1-0 lead. But the Devils surged ahead with three goals in a
span of 3 minutes and 41 seconds by Brylin, Madden and Rafalski.
</P>
<P>
   Brylin scored at 2:27 on a rebound, finishing a Russian
combination with Alexander Mogilny and Vladimir Malakhov. Playing
one of his best games since joining the Devils in the second half
of the regular season, Malakhov took a pass from Mogilny, burst
into the Dallas zone, and passed back to Mogilny, whose shot was
stopped by Dallas goalie Ed Belfour. Brylin stabbed successfully at
the rebound to tie the score at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Madden, a rookie center and defensive specialist, scored while
shorthanded at 4:51 to give the Devils a 2-1 lead. During the
regular season, he had six shorthanded goals to lead the National
Hockey League. On this particular penalty-killing shift, it was his
second short-handed chance. After Ken Daneyko chipped the puck to
Sergei Nemchinov, Madden took the next pass and rushed down the ice
to beat the goalie with a wrist shot.
</P>
<P>
   Rafalski, another of the Devils four rookies who play regularly,
gave New Jersey a 3-1 lead at 6:08 after streaking in on Belfour
after a neutral zone turnover by Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The tight play and low scoring over the first two periods were
no surprise. Although the Devils won the first game by the flukey
score of 7-3, the next two games both ended at 2-1, with the Stars
winning Game 2 and the Devils winning Game 3. &UR;  &LR;  Back in the lineup
for Dallas was Jamie Langenbrunner, a right wing who had missed the
previous five games with a knee sprain. Langenbrunner was re-united
with his center, Nieuwendyk, who had been slumping, without a goal
or an assist this series.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks Monday morning, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock discussed
Nieuwendyk, who won the Conn Smythe trophy last season as the most
valuable player in the tournament as the Stars won the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody focuses on the goal-scoring,'' Hitchcock said.
``That wasn't the reason he won the Conn Smythe. He was an
emotional leader. He played out of character for two months. He was
physical. He fought. He was a gritty guy in the real critical
areas. If Nieuwendyk wades in, plays out of character again, then
we have got ourselves a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   In the scoreless first period, neither Langebrunner nor
Nieuwendyk had a shot on goal. The teams exchanged lengthy spurts
of dominance, first the Devils, then the Stars, then the Devils
again. New Jersey failed to score on two consecutive power-play
attempts, the best chance being Randy McKay's short push from the
crease.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull, the Dallas sniper, had good scoring chances in the
first minute of the period and again in the final minute. Skating
impressively for the Devils was Scott Niedermayer, who led rushes
from his defensive position.
</P>
<P>
   Derian Hatcher, the Dallas defenseman, also joined the attack
for his side, moving deep into New Jersey ice, albeit at a slower
rate of speed.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars got a great scoring chance when four Devils converged
on Hull at the New Jersey blue line and he worked the puck low to
his linemate, Mike Modano. But as Modano moved in toward the net,
Brodeur forced the play by charging from his crease for a poke
check that left Modano tumbling to ice.
</P>
<P>
   At the first intermission, Nieuwendyk was asked in a television
interview about having Langenbrunner back. ``We had a lot of jump
that first period,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``He's an impact player. He
plays with a lot of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk scored the only goal of the second period, on a power
play, and the Stars carried a 1-0 lead into the third period. The
Devils had the best of play in the middle period, keeping the Stars
from even shooting on goal for more than 10 minutes, a span that
included two Dallas power plays.
</P>
<P>
   But when Vladimir Malakhov of the Devils went off for
cross-checking at 16:38, the Stars mounted a concentrated attack.
The scored when Nieuwendyk planted himself in Brodeur's crease and
stayed there while Darryl Sydor fired the puck from the left point.
It caromed around Brodeur's skates and Nieuwendyk finished the play
by pushing the puck over the line at 18:02.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
