<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEE-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE WITHDRAWS FROM NUCLEAR SECRETS TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal judge who was to oversee the trial of a scientist
accused of mishandling nuclear weapons secrets from the Los Alamos
National Laboratory announced Monday that he is excusing himself
from the case to assume senior status.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge John Edwards Conway of federal District
Court in Albuquerque, N.M., was scheduled to preside over the trial
of Wen Ho Lee, a Los Alamos National Laboratory physicist who is
accused of having illegally downloaded a mountain of highly
sensitive nuclear secrets with the intention of passing them to a
foreign power.
</P>
<P>
   Conway, 66, had earlier set Wednesday as the date for arguments
on a defense motion to suppress the warrant the government had
obtained to search Lee's home last year. He had also scheduled for
Monday a pivotal hearing on the defense motion that all the
classified information Lee is accused of downloading be admissible
in open court.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has vigorously denied the charges and has maintained that
nearly all the data he downloaded was already publicly available.
</P>
<P>
   Conway said in a statement that he had decided to take what is
known as senior status, a kind of semi-retirement which allows him
to decrease his case load and that he had chosen to drop out of the
Lee case. An experienced judge, Conway was appointed to the bench
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there and done that,'' Conway said of his decision.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was scheduled for Nov. 6, but that date has also been
canceled and the new date will be up to U.S. District Judge James
A. Parker, who as been assigned to replace Conway . Parker is
familiar with the case, having presided over a series of bail
hearings in January when Lee was denied bail because of the
government's contentions that he posed a threat to national
security.
</P>
<P>
   The change in judges came several weeks after the government's
unexpected announcement that it was replacing the lead prosecutor
in the case. Bob Gorence, an assistant U.S. attorney in
Albuquerque, had been in charge, but was replaced without
explanation with George Stamboulidis, an experienced organized
crime prosecutor from Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to move as quickly as possible for an expedited
trial and hope to exonerate Lee,'' said Mark Holscher, one of Lee's
defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Attorney's office in Albuquerque said simply that the
announcement ``speaks for itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-05-00 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000605.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-05 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5706 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-LAD     06-05 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PACERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS EVOLVING INTO CHAMPIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Some changes are too subtle for the naked eye to
detect. The long-awaited transformation of the Lakers from fatally
unsound to finals-bound, could not be seen with a casual glance in
mid-January or even with a more pointed examination in April.
</P>
<P>
   The uniforms, still purple and gold. The faces, mostly the same.
More wins but no shortage of disappointments along the way _ always
another reminder that for the last decade, high expectations
usually were followed by disaster.
</P>
<P>
   A change was nevertheless taking place, even if there was no
obvious signal, nothing to scream, ``Champions in the making.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's Game 7 victory in the Western Conference finals now
stands as the defining moment for this Lakers team. One
fourth-quarter comeback from 15 points down stands as one of the
greatest wins in Lakers history and as tangible evidence that this
group has indeed evolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've slowly taken another step,'' said fourth-year guard
Derek Fisher, ``in terms of establishing consistency, in terms of
establishing a tradition everybody wants to see us establish. And I
think (the victory) is another example of us growing into that
basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher knows about what Los Angeles and a franchise with a proud
history was waiting to see. He arrived as a rookie in the summer of
1996, along with rookie Kobe Bryant and free-agent signee Shaquille
O'Neal. The expectations accompanied that banner offseason.
</P>
<P>
   They have never been closer to fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of times we were thrusted into being the team
that we're supposed to be but really weren't quite ready to be that
team,'' Fisher said. ``But (Sunday), we took another step. And the
final step has not been taken yet, but this definitely helps us
going into the next round.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be the finals step.
</P>
<P>
   As coach Phil Jackson noted with a quickly scrawled ``4 TO GO''
on the locker room dry-erase board, the Lakers are not yet
champions. But the overwhelming feeling is they have already passed
their greatest test. It seems unlikely that the Indiana Pacers _ or
any team, for that matter _ could push, pull, prod, fluster and
flummox the Lakers for seven games the way the Portland Trail
Blazers just did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope not,'' Rick Fox said with a laugh. ``No lack of respect
for the Pacers. You'd like to not have to deal with those ups and
downs like we did. But no one's going to give it to us. We're going
to have to go out and take it. We went out and took it (Sunday).''
</P>
<P>
   It was, Fox agreed, the most poise under pressure this team has
displayed ``since I've been here, even this year.''
</P>
<P>
   And that subtle change in the Lakers was at last revealed in
their facial expressions _ from Shaquille O'Neal's crazy-eyed,
mouth-gaping exuberance after his fourth-quarter slam dunk, to the
exhausted, dazed look of Fox, sitting at his locker, still in
uniform, 30 minutes after the 89-84 win was over.
</P>
<P>
   And in the joyous, boyish glee on the face of 21-year-old star
Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited,'' Bryant said. ``I'm extremely excited. I'm
playing for the whole thing, going to the big dance. It's something
I dreamed about all my 21 years. The moment is finally here, so I'm
just going to enjoy it. We're going to give it all we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be anticlimactic from here. The Pacers don't have the
personnel to swarm O'Neal the way the Blazers did, nor are they as
deep and athletic as Portland.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers know better now than to underestimate anyone. And
the championship has yet to be awarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one remembers who finishes second 10 years down the road,''
said Jackson, seeking his seventh ring to go with six Chicago Bulls
championships. ``The reality is when you get here, you've got to
win it. And we may have learned enough at this point to know how to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But both of us, Indiana and us, are coming into this finals,
neither team having been in the finals. ... And I think it carries
some weight that Shaq has been in the finals and knows the
experience, and Brian Shaw also. And (Robert) Horry, of course
(Ron) Harper. So we have a little bit of experience as individuals
but not as a team. We have to build on what we did (Sunday) to be
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox was so emotionally and physically spent Sunday evening in
the wake of the win, he said he couldn't even remember things that
happened an hour before. He didn't mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only hope I feel this way a week and a half from now,
again,'' he said. ``I'm sure ... winning a championship, the level
of adrenaline and exhaustion will be even greater, but I'll take
it. I'll deal with it. I'll learn how to deal with it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
