<SLUG> BC-BKW-SPARKS-MCCRIMMON-LADN </SLUG>
 
SPARKS' McCRIMMON FINDS HER NICHE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nikki McCrimmon honed her skills as a quick, defensive, flashy
guard on the school yards in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   It was her defensive intensity minus the flash that gave her the
nod as the Sparks backup point guard.
</P>
<P>
   McCrimmon was the Sparks fourth-round draft pick, but she beat
out Nicole Kubik, the first-round draft pick, and Felecity Willis,
who was picked up in the Sparks invitational tryout, for the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Nikki since the Say No Classic,'' Sparks coach
Michael Cooper said. ``I was going to give her a shot. She's a
gamer. She's defensive-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   In two games, McCrimmon have shown she can provide an offesive
boost, as well. She has 11 points with 3 of 4 attempts made from
the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can shot the ball. She just has to understand when to take
her shot,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   It's been two years since the former USC guard played
professionally. She started her pro career with the American
Basketball League's Long Beach StingRays before she was traded to
Atlanta. After the grass roots league folded in 1998 McCrimmon
supported herself by substitute teaching in Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   But she never gave up on basketball. She trained on her own and
played pickup games to tune up her game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I waited for a long time and nothing was given to me,''
McCrimmon said. ``Just because Lisa (Leslie) is here and I played
with Lisa and Coach (Marianne) Stanley is here that had no bearing
on me making the team. I just went out there and played hard.''
</P>
<P>
   That McCrimmon is playing in the league today is a tribute to
her persistence. With no agent, she made several requests to Renee
Brown, WNBA director of player personnel, about getting an
invitation to the combine in April. Eventually her pop calls paid
off.
</P>
<P>
   McCrimmon has shown a lot of maturity since her days in the ABL.
She's learned to be a role player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a lot of mistakes playing in the ABL, things that I
needed to work on. Things that I didn't know that I know now as far
as attitude, being mentally tough. I'm older now. I learned from
the best and that's something that's going to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   No one's more aware of McCrimmon's progress than Sparks
assistant coach Marianne Stanley, who coached the wiry guard at
USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a maturity step for her,'' Stanley said. ``At least on
this team our needs are to have stability, quality play at the
point, taking care of the basketball, and making good decisions
here. That's what we need our point guards here to do. We don't
need her to be Allan Iverson. We have some tremendous talent in a
number of different positions. We need someone whose like the glue
that runs the engine that keeps in all together.''
</P>
<P>
   McCrimmon can't wait for the road trip to her New York when the
Sparks play the Liberty on June 25. As the youngest of eight,
she'll get a chance to visit her seven siblings and, time
permitting, go by the famous Ruckers Park in Harlem, where NBA
legends like Julius Erving have played.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be grounded there. I need that street ball, to play out
there and talk to them, step away from being a professional athlete
and just be Nikki,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And when it's time to play New York, there will be a personal
cheering section reserved just for McCrimmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole of Harlem will be at Madison Square Garden.''
</P>
<P>
   SPARKS NOTES: The Sparks are 2-0 after defeating Minnesota 82-75
Saturday. ... Portland Fire, one of four expansion teams, is 1-1.
They extended three-time defending champion Houston to
double-overtime before losing 93-89 in their season opener. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
