u s BC-HKN-STARS-NYT &LR;      06-05 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIEUWENDYK SCORES, BUT IT IS NOT ENOUGH TO OVERCOME DEVILS 
</HEADLINE>
  By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ If Brett Hull doesn't score, the Dallas Stars don't
win, not even when Joe Nieuwendyk scores a point. It has been that
simple in the Stanley Cup finals thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Three times in four games, Hull _ the leading scorer in the
playoffs this season _ has been held without a goal. The Stars have
lost all three times.
</P>
<P>
   In a pivotal Game 4, Hull went scoreless Monday night. And the
New Jersey Devils shook off Nieuwendyk's first goal of the finals
to score three goals in the first 6 minutes 8 seconds of the final
period and rally for a 3-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils took a 3-1 lead in the best-of-7 series and can
capture the second Stanley Cup championship in their history when
the series resumes at Continental Arena on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he scored the Stars' only goal, the biggest Dallas
shot of the evening did not belong to Nieuwendyk. Nor did it come
from Hull, whose two goals in Game 2 paced the Stars to their only
victory. Instead, it was a cheap shot that emanated from the
forearms of defenseman Derian Hatcher, who knocked Jason Arnott out
of the game with 7 1/2 minutes left in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had come into the game 7-0 in these playoffs when
Nieuwendyk scored a point. The 30-year-old center, the most
valuable player of the playoffs last season, scored his first goal
of this season's finals here Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk's first point of the finals came with 1 minute 52
seconds remaining in the second period. He scored it on the power
play, from behind Martin Brodeur in the crease, with a backhanded
sweep of a loose puck behind Brodeur's legs.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was Nieuwendyk's seventh of the playoffs this spring,
but it was also his first in six games. Nieuwendyk's resurgence
just happened to coincide with the return of his favorite linemate,
left wing Jamie Langenbrunner. The mere presence of Langenbrunner,
who had missed the last five games _ including the first three
games of the finals _ with a knee injury, seemed to light a fire
under Nieuwendyk Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But had the Stars not lost two of the first three games of the
finals, Langenbrunner never would have been playing Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock was gambling that Langenbrunner's
presence, even if it were at less than full strength, would give
the Stars a second line that the Devils must take seriously. The
Devils hadn't needed to take any line, other than Mike Modano's top
line, seriously thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk scored his goal on the power play, with Modano and
Hull as his linemates. Still, Nieuwendyk did have more life Monday
night. With Langenbrunner on his wing, he was definitely more
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of jump,'' Nieuwendyk admitted between periods.
``We spent a lot of time in their own end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an impact player,'' he said Langenbrunner. ``He plays
with a lot of energy. He's great to have in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were hoping that Langenbrunner, who has been out since
Game 5 of the Western Conference finals, could help dig Nieuwendyk
out of his funk. Nieuwendyk had not scored a point since
Langenbrunner injured his knee. The two teamed for 21 goals during
last season's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says he adds goal scoring,'' Hitchcock said Monday
morning, when asked what Langenbrunner's return brings to his team.
``He's got one so far. Hopefully he can add to that. He's a gritty
guy. This is a gritty series.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the first three games of the series, the Stars were a
one-line team. But even that line, with Modano centering for Hull
and Jere Lehtinen, had been no match for the Devils' top line of
Arnott centering for Patrik Elias and Petr Sykora for two of the
first three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, Jamie can bring back some chemistry and some
continuity,'' Hitchcock had said Monday morning. ``That was a very
good line when it played together. Unfortunately, we've had some
injured people on it. But it has always given us a big boost. If
Jamie is able, it could really help us.''
</P>
<P>
   It did for two periods. But, unfortunately for Dallas, it was
not enough. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
